<SLUG> BC-BKN-WILT-YOUTH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG, OLD RECALL BIG WILT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jon Harris wore a Kobe Bryant jersey. Hassan
Shamir had the familiar No. 23 of a guy named Jordan. They braved
the heat for some one-on-one at Reseda Recreational Park, unaware
one of the basketball's giants, literally and figuratively, died a
few hours before.
</P>
<P>
   Wilt Chamberlain, who won two NBA championships, including one
with the Lakers, was found dead at his Bel-Air home Tuesday. He was
63.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, neither of the teen-age cagers knew much about
Chamberlain, though they were acutely aware of his standing as one
of the few athletes who shaped a sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always on the highlights,'' Harris, 16, said. ``I
remember every time they showed him he was wearing a headband. I
know he played for the Lakers and they won a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   On basketball courts across the San Fernando Valley _ whether in
Reseda or Encino or Northridge or Woodland Hills _ most of the
players knew of Chamberlain, of his star magnitude, of his prowess,
and his now infamous proclamation of having slept with thousands of
women.
</P>
<P>
   However, the generation that monopolizes the playing time at
area courts know more about Jordan and Larry Bird and Magic
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilt particulars are lost on the younger generations who
were either not born or too young to remember Chamberlain, who
concluded his career in 1973. Leave that to some of the elders,
like Zacharia Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the strongest man I've ever seen play,'' said
Cambridge, 65, a longtime Lakers fan. ``I hear this talk about (the
Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal), but Wilt was pure strength. They had to
change the game because of him. Him and Bill Russell. I'll tell
you, there was nothing like those two.
</P>
<P>
   ``These players today, all those guys, they couldn't play with
either of those guys. Not for my money.''
</P>
<P>
   Sal Magliotti, 73, of Calabassas said he lived in suburban
Philadelphia when Chamberlain was playing for the Philadelphia
Warriors. Magliotti, ironically, grew up a Boston Celtics fan and
said he would take Russell over Chamberlain in the inevitable
``who's better'' argument but gave Chamberlain his due.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times teams couldn't stop him,'' Magliotti said
while sitting on a bench at Balboa Sports Complex park. ``He was a
physical specimen. I can't believe (he died). Teams would
double-team him. Sometimes triple-team him. They did it all the
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew, from the first time I saw him ... you knew he was
going to be great. Magic Johnson, Larry Bird, Michael Jordan? I
think it was Russell and Chamberlain that really got (the NBA)
going.''
</P>
<P>
   As word of Chamberlain's passing spread throughout the Valley,
the feeling was of disbelief and shock.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain, who played with four NBA teams and set a record in
averaging an 50.4 points and 25.7 rebounds a game during the
1961-62 season, was always regarded as one of the most
well-conditioned athletes in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he advanced into his 50s, debate raged as to whether
Chamberlain, given a few weeks to work himself into better shape,
could play in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the younger kids see Michael Jordan, what he's done
to elevate the game,'' Leonard Symorsky said. ``Wilt Chamberlain
did the same thing when he was playing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
