<HEADLINE>
CYBERTALK PRODUCER WANTS YOU TO BE A STAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ron Diorio has all the tools to make ``you'' a cybersports radio
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   From his home in New York, Diorio has been making cybertalk-show
stars out of Internet-savvy sports junkies for the past year on his
site, the Sports News Network (www.sportsnewsnetwork.com).
</P>
<P>
   His site is a portal for real-audio talk shows created by
everyday sports fans who talk about or interview sports figures on
subjects ranging from college football rankings to general sports
news.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the pioneering steps toward practical use of
broadband technology, which Diorio recognizes as the next big step
for multimedia capabilities on the 'Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe that the next set of celebrities is coming
from the Internet,'' said Diorio, who evaluates cybertalk
candidates before granting them a show. ``I haven't found the next
Merv Griffin, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   Diorio has found Daryl Fein, who talks about college athletics
and professional baseball on the ``Fein Line.'' Fein brings the
kind of attitude that Diorio wants in his shows. Diorio doesn't
want radio shock talk, but a blend of information mixed with
personality.
</P>
<P>
   Said Fein: ``I like to present my work as I would like to hear
it if I were listening _ nothing too drawn out and too formal _ but
like you'd hear while sitting on a bar stool with the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Another believer is Steve Kyler, who operates BskBall's
Hoopsworld (www.bskball.com), a fan-based site about the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the style of information that we present as a group,''
Kyler said. ``I think we represent the next generation of sports
commentary.''
</P>
<P>
   Diorio said he wants his cybercasters to already have a
following. That is why he approached Ross Fleege, whose site, The
Frozen Tundra (www.thefrozentundra.com), is one of the more popular
stops for Green Bay Packers fans.
</P>
<P>
   Fleege said the bigger companies, such as ESPN.com and CBS
SportsLine, have the resources to dominate sports information on
the Internet. Diorio's site gives the smaller companies a chance to
be heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Online radio is the next big thing on the Internet, and I
think Sports News Network does a good job of capitalizing on the
potential of real-audio technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Diorio has all the hardware to make this concept work. It's not
been profitable, so far, but Diorio said he hopes to ride the
momentum to bigger things with broadband applications with this
niche.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I'm ESPN,'' he said. ``On my site, you can just
hear different points of view. Our guys may not necessarily be Jim
Rome, just someone who's really knowledgeable about sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Diorio, a New York University film-school dropout, dabbled with
audio distribution in radio in 1995, but soon found the Internet to
be the best outlet for his work.
</P>
<P>
   Diorio, who also produces audio projects about medical and law
topics, said he's finding ``tons of creative people all waiting to
be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe someone out of this group becomes a big star _ that's
great,'' he said. ``The site's success is not about me, but more
about people who put their effort into it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
