<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WASTED OPPORTUNITY SENDS THE WRONG MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The No. 1 question entering the National League
Championship Series was how the New York Mets could possibly beat
Atlanta after the Braves had manhandled them during the season;
worse, in the last three weeks. In trying to answer that question
objectively, members of the Braves looked at other factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In these types of games, it's about execution, the least
amount of mistakes,'' Don Baylor, the Braves' hitting coach, said.
``The mistakes you make during the season, missing the cutoff man,
being thrown out at home, are magnified now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozzie Guillen, a veteran utility infielder, said he didn't
expect pitching to decide the outcome because both teams could
pitch. ``Whoever puts the bunt better, whoever moves the guy over
better or plays better defense is going to be the winner,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning of Tuesday night's Game 1, the Mets had
Roger Cedeno at third base with no one out. The Braves had scored a
run in the first inning after only two batters, but now the Mets
had the perfect opportunity to match the Braves' run.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux, the pre-eminent pitcher of the 90s working for the
pre-eminent team of the 90s, had easily retired the first six Mets
batters, needing only 21 pitches to breeze through them. But when
Cedeno led off the third inning, he drilled a line drive into the
gap in left-center field and scooted to second for a double. But
when the throw back to the infield from Gerald Williams, the left
fielder, skipped past third base, Cedeno hurriedly took the extra
base.
</P>
<P>
   Runner at third, no one out. Except for a ball hit into the
stands, this was the best opportunity the Mets could ask for to tie
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Rey Ordonez was the batter who had the first chance to make it
1-1. The shortstop, however, swung mightily at a Maddux pitch and
beat the ball into the ground. It was the type of ball that usually
rolls foul, so Ordonez strayed only a few feet up the first-base
line. The ball did not go foul; instead, it spun slowly a few feet
up the third-base line. It veered slightly, from the right side of
the chalky foul line to the left, but it stayed on the chalk.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Perez, the catcher, did not give the ball a chance to veer
any more to the left. He pounced on it, took a quick glance toward
third to make sure Cedeno wasn't going anywhere and fired to first,
easily beating the stationary Ordonez. Perez then motioned to Ryan
Klesko, the first baseman, to watch Cedeno to make sure he was not
planning a belated and sneaky charge to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Masato Yoshii was the next candidate to produce the tying run.
As pitchers go, Yoshii had executed his share of sacrifice bunts
during the season. His six ranked third among the Mets' pitchers.
So it didn't seem as if it would be an impossible task for him to
put the ball on the ground when Bruce Benedict, the substitute
third-base coach, flashed the sign for a suicide squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   With two balls and no strikes, Maddux went into his motion and
delivered the pitch. Cedeno scampered down the line. Yoshii turned
in the batter's box to get into position to bunt. The ball arrived
at the plate. Yoshii bunted at it. Oops. Bat did not meet ball.
Ball eluded bat and went instead into Perez's glove. Oops. Cedeno
was caught naked on the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   Perez ran at Cedeno, and the runner retreated to third. But
Cedeno was in no man's land, certainly where no base runner should
be with one out in a 1-0 game, and Perez tagged him for the second
out. Suddenly, a promising rally was not so promising. Yoshii
slapped a bouncer to Maddux at the mound, the pitcher flipped to
first and, just like that, with no batted ball traveling more than
57 feet, the Mets had lost the opportunity to pull even with the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   They would eventually do that, scoring a run in the fourth
inning after Edgardo Alfonzo cracked a double that was not wasted.
But when Maddux, or any of the Braves' starters, for that matter,
is pitching, no team can afford to squander the kind of gift the
errant throw on Cedeno's double gave the Mets. It was almost gift
wrapped; only the bow was missing. But the Mets couldn't tie the
bow _ or the game.
</P>
<P>
   They went on to lose it, 4-2, leaving them wondering whether
they really had the ingredients necessary to beat the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been fortunate to beat them,'' Tom Glavine, Maddux's
fellow starter, said before the game. ``We found ways to win close
games. I anticipate a lot of close games and whoever figures out
how to win will win.''
</P>
<P>
   However either team won, Brian Jordan had said, the first game
was critical. ``You definitely want to send a message the first
game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets didn't like the loss; they didn't like the message.
According to Baylor, a veteran of post-season appearances as a
player, they won't like what could come either.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the season,'' the coach said, ``you can get over a
defeat pretty quickly and go on to the next day. In a series like
this, it just grabs you and hangs onto you more than 24 hours
sometimes. Plus you can ride out a victory a lot longer if you do
well. The next day you believe things are going to happen for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets may start believing, too _ believing that they can't
beat the Braves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
