<SLUG> BC-BROKER-EARNINGS-385&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 BIG BROKERAGE FIRMS' EARNINGS BEAT EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three big securities firms reported
better-than-expected third-quarter earnings Tuesday, reflecting a
strong rebound from a disastrous comparable quarter last year but a
decline from a strong first half.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. reported the most remarkable turnaround from
a year ago, when it recorded a quarterly loss of $163 million,
after taking an after-tax charge of $288 million to restructure its
bond businesses. Despite a slight decline in its biggest source of
revenue, trading commissions, Merrill had its most profitable third
quarter, earning $572 million, or $1.34 a diluted share.
</P>
<P>
   Paine Webber Group, another firm with a national network of
brokers who sell stocks and bonds to individual investors, reported
a 67 percent increase in net income to $138.2 million, or 86 cents
a share. Paine Webber also said it was pleased with response to a
brokerage account it was introducing to compete with a new offering
from Merrill Lynch that allows customers to make unlimited trades
for a pre-set annual fee.
</P>
<P>
   A third firm, Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Inc., weathered a
rocky market for the junk bonds it underwrites and trades to post
net income of $122.2 million, or 85 cents a share. That total,
depressed by heavy advertising spending for the firm's DLJdirect
electronic-brokerage service, nearly quadrupled the $25.7 million
the firm earned a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the results were several cents a share more than
analysts had forecast. Investors reacted most favorably to
Donaldson, Lufkin's results, pushing its stock up $2.1875 a share,
to $42.50. Merrill's shares were down 75 cents at $67, and Paine
Webber slipped 68.75 cents, to $35, partly reflecting a broad
decline in the overall market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in what's feared to be a transitional stage for the
full-service brokerage business,'' said Guy Moszkowski, an analyst
at Citigroup's Salomon Smith Barney unit. The industry is grappling
with Internet-based competitors, he said, and investors will remain
wary of brokerage stocks until they get a better sense of how the
competition will affect their earnings.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, investors are watching for the impact of the
firms' shift to letting customers pay annual fees for brokerage
services instead of commissions on every transaction.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Merrill rolled out a new account this summer that, for a minimum
fee of $1,500 a year, allows customers to make as many trades of
stocks, bonds and mutual funds as they want, either online or
through a broker. That move was a response to the growing
popularity of low-cost, electronic trading offered by younger
companies like Charles Schwab and Etrade Group.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors think Merrill has priced its new account too
aggressively and fear that the firm's return on customers' assets
will continue to decline. ``My reading of it is they're going to
execute a Schwab-killer strategy,'' said Steve Galbraith, an
analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Paine Webber chief executive Donald Marron on Tuesday emphasized
that the firm's 7,500 brokers have more ``flexibility'' in setting
the fees that different customers will pay for its brand-new
account, which it calls Insight One. Marron said Paine Webber kept
slightly less than $1 of every $100 of customer assets invested
with it and that he does not expect the firm's cut, which has
declined steadily over the years, to drop significantly because of
the new account structure.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill chief financial officer E. Stanley O'Neal said the firm
was pleasantly surprised by the effect the change had had so far on
its overall return on assets. But he added that the cost of
compensating brokers for switching their clients to lower-priced
accounts was the primary reason that Merrill's compensation costs
rose in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For most Wall Street firms, the cost of paying employees moves
up and down in line with revenue. But Merrill's compensation
expenses edged up last quarter, while its net revenue _ total
revenue minus interest expense _ declined 3.2 percent, to $5.27
billion. Moszkowski estimated that much of that difference could
comprise one-time payments of $50 million or more to its 14,000
brokers, who stand to earn less from the new fee-based accounts.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal said he expected Merrill's ratio of compensation costs to
net revenue to move back toward 50 percent from 52 percent last
quarter. But, he said, Merrill's marketing costs will rise sharply
starting this quarter as it funds an ad blitz.
</P>
<P>
   On the investment-banking side of its business, Merrill had ``a
solid quarter, despite the difficult environment,'' O'Neal said.
During a volatile market for certain types of bonds late in the
quarter, the firm fared much better than it had last year when a
default by the Russian government roiled financial markets around
the world and caught Merrill holding a huge inventory of risky
bonds. Merrill also had strong gains in revenue from underwriting
stocks and bonds and from advising on mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   At Paine Webber, investment-banking revenue was up 12 percent
from a year earlier to $134.2 million, but was flat for the first
nine months of 1999. The firm's total revenue increased just 3
percent, to $1.86 billion, from $1.8 billion in the third quarter
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Like Paine Webber, Donaldson, Lufkin said its third quarter was
so much stronger this year that it had already earned more in 1999
than in any full year. The biggest gains came from underwriting and
fees for advising companies on mergers. Overall, Donaldson,
Lufkin's revenue jumped 59 percent, to $1.7 billion, from $1.07
billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In the junk-bond business, Donaldson, Lufkin's market share
jumped to 25 percent in the quarter and 20 percent for the year in
a market that has been upset by rising rates. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
