</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DANGEROUS COUP IN PAKISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Oct. 13:
</P>
<P>
   The military coup in Pakistan is cause for alarm in South Asia
and the rest of the world. A nation newly armed with nuclear
weapons, and with a volatile history of wars and internal
upheavals, has been seized by generals who may be inclined to favor
a more confrontational approach with India. Suddenly, after fitful
steps toward India-Pakistan rapprochement, the subcontinent is once
again one of the most dangerous places on earth. Gen. Pervez
Musharraf, the army chief of staff who ``dismissed'' Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif, acted only after Sharif tried to oust him earlier in
the day. But the United States and other nations must demand that
the generals ensure Sharif's safety, restore him to power and
respect Pakistani liberties.
</P>
<P>
   Coups have been a sadly regular feature of Pakistan's history.
But in the 11 years since the death of the last coup plotter, Gen.
Mohammad Zia ul-Haq, the country has stumbled through a succession
of civilian governments controlled by either Sharif or his main
rival, Benazir Bhutto.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the military has always lurked in the background as a
power, and civilian Pakistani leaders have understood that there
were limits on how much they could challenge the top generals.
Sharif may have forgotten that lesson when he tried to oust
Musharraf. He had also angered the democratic opposition in
Pakistan by his consolidation of power and trampling on the rights
of others. But such excesses cannot excuse the military's action.
</P>
<P>
   The train of events leading up to the coup may never be
completely known. But it can almost certainly be traced to the
military's ill-advised decision last spring to send soldiers and
militants into Indian territory to take up positions in the
mountains of the disputed region of Kashmir. Indian artillery and
air attacks pushed the invaders back, and the United States
intervened to get Sharif to agree to their withdrawal. Pakistan's
generals were angry at the retreat, even though Sharif got a
commitment from President Clinton to take more of an interest in
the Kashmir conflict. Word spread in Pakistan that Sharif had sold
out his nation.
</P>
<P>
   The discontent with Sharif has led to rumors of a coup in the
last few weeks, but the generals acted only after the prime
minister tried to oust his chief of staff. Clinton administration
officials are suggesting that they tried to warn Sharif not to
overplay his hand, but that the advice was rejected. The United
States does not have much leverage with which to press Pakistan to
return to civilian government. Economic and military relations were
already frozen after Pakistan exploded a nuclear bomb last year,
although a few sanctions were eased by the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund when Sharif took steps to defuse
tensions with India.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Pakistan's history as a ``front-line state'' against
the former Soviet Union, the United States has maintained
relationships with Pakistani generals. Washington must now work
with two other important Pakistani allies, China and Saudi Arabia,
to see that the generals do not even consider trying to solve their
problems with India by military force. They must be made to
understand that the only way Pakistan can win international support
for its conflicts with India is by adhering to its civilian
tradition. In India, Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee has won
re-election and promised to try to resolve problems with Pakistan
peacefully. Pakistani leaders must also realize that military coups
or not, there are no military solutions to Pakistan's problems. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
