<SLUG> BC-GM-DEALERSHIPS-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT IS PROMISED OVER GM PLAN TO BUY DEALERSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The president of the National Automobile Dealers
Association, one of the nation's wealthiest and most powerful
business lobbying groups, on Tuesday bitterly criticized General
Motors Corp. for its plan to buy 5 percent to 10 percent of its
dealerships and operate them itself. He hinted that dealers might
try to use their political influence to stop the company.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism set the stage not only for a fight over how
automobiles are sold in the United States but also over the
development of electronic commerce and the Internet. GM and other
automakers have been trying to market vehicles over the Internet,
but dealers have been blocking many of those initiatives, using
state franchise laws that require that all vehicles be sold through
dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   GM could get around those laws by owning dealerships. The
company's policies are important because of GM's size. Optimistic
predictions of sales to consumers over the Internet by all
industries run as high as $100 billion in 2003; GM alone already
sells that much in automobiles each year in North America, so
Internet commerce could grow much faster if it included direct
sales to consumers by automakers.
</P>
<P>
   James Willingham, the president of the dealers association, said
he and other dealers planned to meet Wednesday with GM chairman and
chief executive John Smith to ask him to abandon or significantly
modify the plan to buy dealerships, which was announced Sept. 28.
``It's an unprecedented attack on the dealer franchise system,''
Willingham said in a speech at an Automotive Press Association
luncheon in Detroit on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   If Smith refuses to back down, the nation's auto dealers will
consider several possible responses, including an attempt to win
state or federal legislation blocking GM's plans, Willingham said.
He noted that there was an average of 52 new-car dealers in the
district of each United States representative.``Some dealers went
to school with that guy,'' he added, ``or worked on his campaign,
so we have some grass-roots clout and we're going to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   GM spokesman Terry Sullivan declined to respond to the specifics
of Willingham's remarks but noted that the automaker planned to buy
only a minority of its dealerships. ``We're indicating 5 to 10
percent _ that means another 90 percent out there'' will remain
independent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But GM has also said that it is most interested in buying large
dealerships in the nation's 130 largest metropolitan areas over the
next decade. Because a fifth of the nation's dealerships account
for four-fifths of the vehicles sold, GM could end up selling a
huge number of vehicles itself. GM has about 7,700 dealerships in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers have traditionally beaten automakers in political
showdowns because of the dealers' presence in every congressional
district, and in practically every state lawmaker's district, too.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has experimented with buying stakes in dealerships in five
midsize cities, starting in Tulsa, Okla., late last year. Dealers
have already responded by persuading state legislatures in Texas,
Arkansas, Illinois, Indiana, Georgia, North Carolina and Montana to
pass legislation this year tightening state laws against
automakers' ownership of dealerships. GM officials have not
disclosed how, if at all, they plan to get around these laws.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ford decided in late September to temporarily halt dealership
acquisitions while reviewing its strategy. Willingham said Tuesday
that Ford's approach bothered him less than GM's because Ford is
taking minority stakes in dealerships, leaving dealers in control,
while GM plans to buy them outright.
</P>
<P>
   GM and Ford have insisted that they will not favor factory-owned
dealerships, but Willingham questioned whether impartial treatment
was possible. ``If there are two babies crying, one of them is
yours, which are you going to pick up?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler AG and foreign automakers are trying a different
strategy of working more closely with their dealers. Many dealers
these days have franchises from several automakers and can steer
customers to favored brands, making it difficult for automakers to
change dealership policies.
</P>
<P>
   Willingham, a Buick dealer in California for 39 years and the
owner of dealerships that sell seven other brands of automobiles,
said that with auto sales at their highest level ever in the 1999
model year, the current dealership system must be working. Citing a
recent survey paid for by dealers that showed high customer
satisfaction with dealerships, he said that, ``We're kind of
asking, if it ain't broke, why mess with it?''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
