<SLUG> BC-CONFERENCE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: AT ANNUAL MEETING, BIG MARKETERS FOCUS ON E-BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   C.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMELIA ISLAND, Fla. _ Begging your pardon, Irving Berlin. The
contention of the closing general session of the 1999 annual
conference of the Association of National Advertisers was that
there's no business like e-business.
</P>
<P>
   E-business _ as in electronic commerce, interactive advertising,
electronic retailing, the new media and online marketing _ was the
sole focus of the concluding session of the conference Tuesday at
the Ritz-Carlton Hotel here. The session, lasting more than three
and a half hours, was notable for two reasons.
</P>
<P>
   One was that, according to those attending who work for
interactive advertising agencies, the audience of large national
advertisers seemed completely comfortable with the technical
terminology that the speakers used, everything from ``streaming
media'' and ``channel conflict'' to ``data mining'' and
``first-mover advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The second was that the session included no sponsored segments,
unlike the general sessions Sunday and Monday. The sponsorships,
bought by the Conde Nast Publications unit of Advance Publications,
and five national radio networks, drew complaints from many
attendees for huckster-like sales pitches from the stage.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the media sponsorships _ unique among ad industry
annual conferences _ were the inspiration for jokes during an
awards dinner Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are, sponsors,'' said Myer Berlow, president for
interactive marketing at America Online Inc., whose company
co-sponsored the awards with the trade publication Advertising Age,
``and we don't have a commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to hear Rush Limbaugh talk about something he
knew about,'' Berlow continued, referring to the talk show host's
speech during the presentation sponsored by the radio networks,
``his rate card.''
</P>
<P>
   How e-business rates with advertisers proved to be compelling
content at the closing general session, which had as its moderator
a newly minted ``e-trepreneur'': Lou Dobbs, the former CNN business
news anchor who is chairman and chief executive of a fledgling Web
site company, Space.com.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs should not worry about his enterprise, according to the
opening speaker, Robert Herbold, executive vice president and chief
operating officer of Microsoft Corp., because ``aggressive
newcomers have created the buzz'' in e-business while ``incumbency
has never been worth less.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason, Herbold said, is that the goal of many new
e-commerce sites is ``to `clean up the value chain' and get it
direct from the source to the consumer.'' He cited Proflowers.com,
which ships products to customers not from florist shops but from
growers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web is a distribution system, a medium and a
marketplace,'' Herbold said, adding that Internet advertising will
``become absolutely gargantuan'' and far more creative than it is
now.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he suggested that marketers selling packaged-goods
products of ``low interest'' to consumers could ``revisit the
marketing of the '40s and '50s when brands were sponsors of
something important to people'' and ``become sponsors of Web sites
with information of value.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Beindorf, chief operating officer of Planetrx.com, an
online drugstore, offered rules to ``contend with the `futurity' of
what is already happening today'' in E-business.
</P>
<P>
   While ``brands continue to matter,'' Beindorf said, ``you will
have to move much faster'' to ``put a stake in the ground and
create a positioning'' that will differentiate brands from one
another in the minds of computer users, a benefit he described as
the ``first-mover advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The ability to measure sales more quickly and more precisely
with online advertising means that ``marketers will become
accountable for expenditures and results,'' Beindorf said, ``maybe
for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Accountability was the subject of a panel on channel conflict,
though not the kind facing viewers torn between watching ``Will and
Grace'' or ``Dharma and Greg.'' Rather, the term refers to the
problems confronted by marketers whose products can be sold online
as well as by brick-and-mortar retailers, who may resent the
powerful new competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 95 percent of our products, it doesn't make sense'' to
sell ``directly to the consumer,'' Vivienne Bechtold, interactive
marketing director at the Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., said. ``But certain
products that go to specific targets, like Pampers Preemie and
coffees, there's an opportunity to sell them maybe more effectively
online, maybe through a retailer.''
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G is planning to start a Web site, Reflect.com, that will sell
customized beauty products directly to consumers. ``We'll be using
online media and offline media to drive online awareness'' of the
site, Ms. Bechtold said.
</P>
<P>
   At First Union Corp., which signed the millionth user of its
financial Web site Oct. 1, ``we're getting away from the
mass-marketing mindset of `one size fits all,''' said James
Garrity, senior vice president for marketing. Instead, he said, the
company is embracing ``tailored solutions differentiating consumers
based on who are our most loyal, profitable customers.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ford Motor Co. is grappling with the ``huge impact'' of
``disintermediaries,'' independent Web sites that act as sales
channels for new and used vehicles, according to David Ropes,
Ford's director for corporate advertising and integrated marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is ``spending $20 million in retraining our dealers,'' he
said, ``getting connected not only through their own Web sites but
through the main company site.'' By the end of the year, he added,
85 percent of Ford's dealers will be online.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There was also business without an ``e'' prefix at the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The advertiser association formally mothballed a much-disputed
proposal, made at the annual conference last year, to invite
advertising agencies to join as members. The proposal drew
castigation from officials of the agency trade group, the American
Association of Advertising Agencies.
</P>
<P>
   John Sarsen, president and chief executive of the advertiser
association, and O. Burtch Drake, president and chief executive of
the agency association, said separately that officials of both
groups would meet sometime early next year to discuss cooperation
on two long-divisive issues: How marketers review advertising
accounts and the ways marketers compensate their agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's happy with that,'' Drake said.
</P>
<P>
   And attendees breathed a loud sigh of relief as the conference,
which began Saturday afternoon, ended last night. When the
advertiser association held its annual conference here in October
1996, a rare Florida northeaster washed out all outdoor activities,
confining attendees inside. This time, by contrast, the weather was
as sunny as, well, the outlook for e-business.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
