<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-ROGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROGERS BATTLING THROUGH POSTSEASON WOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The postseason struggles of New York Mets left-hander
Kenny Rogers remain unexplained.
</P>
<P>
   Theories abound, but none should question the pitcher's
intestinal fortitude, Mets manager Bobby Valentine said Tuesday
before Game 1 of this National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``His makeup is fine. What he needs is his pitches,'' said
Valentine, who plans to start Rogers against the Braves this
afternoon in Game 2 at Turner Field in Atlanta. ``I think he'll
have his pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers must or can expect to hear more questions regarding his
inability to perform during October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to prepare the same way,'' said Rogers, who is 0-1
with an 11.92 earned-run average for his five postseason
appearances. ``Like I said, I'm going to take this game just like
it's a regular-season game because that's the way I think I'll be
most successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get caught up in all of the other distractions and the
magnitude of it, it will take your focus away from what you want to
do out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers took the loss during the Mets' lone blemish in their
best-of-five Division Series against the Arizona Diamondbacks.
Rogers surrendered four runs on five hits and two walks during the
Mets' 7-1 loss in Game 2 before being replaced by right-hander Pat
Mahomes after 41/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, though, is not alone in his pursuit of postseason
excellence. Yankees right-hander Roger Clemens and Braves
right-hander Greg Maddux have endured similar questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to know that guys of that caliber can go out there
and struggle once in awhile, too,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Rogers could carry a slight edge to the mound for this
afternoon's start. Rogers, whom the Mets acquired July 23 from the
Athletics, did not pitch against the Braves this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he makes his pitches, it will be a definite advantage,''
Valentine said. ``There might be an at-bat or two that he gets away
with because they don't know how sharp his breaking ball is or
don't realize he pitches inside or what kind of sink he has on his
fastball or changeup.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's a distinct advantage,'' Rogers said. ``I'll take
any advantage I can get, but good hitters are going to hit good
pitches sometimes. So, you have to just keep continually making
good pitches against their hitters.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
