<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCKER GETS GAME 1 START FOR BOSTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Left-hander Kent Mercker, who pitched only 1 2/3
innings against the Cleveland Indians in Game 4 of the Division
Series on Sunday, was named by Red Sox manager Jimy Williams as the
starting pitcher for Game 1. Orlando Hernandez will pitch for the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker, who missed two weeks in September with a strained
ribcage, allowed two runs on three hits and three walks Sunday
before being yanked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just felt he was the right one to start this particular
game,'' Williams said. ``Maybe \RSunday\S was more of a side
session for him. His command wasn't what it should be. Hopefully,
he'll locate the ball better and get out in front of hitters
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox's choices were limited. Bret Saberhagen and Pedro
Martinez both pitched Monday, and Ramon Martinez, who will start
Game 2, went 52/3 innings Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Knuckleballer Tim Wakefield was considered another candidate,
but both he and John Wasdin were dropped from the roster for Pat
Rapp and Bryce Florie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I get the start by default,'' Mercker said. ``I'm
looking forward to it. But I don't think Jimy did it out of
necessity because nobody else could pitch. I think he has
confidence in me.''
Clemens vs. Martinez Both managers announced their rotations for
the first four games of the series. Boston's Ramon Martinez will
face David Cone in Game 2, but the big matchup everybody is looking
forward to is Game 3 between Pedro Martinez for the Red Sox and
Roger Clemens for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens pitched with the Red Sox from 1984-96 before leaving as
a free agent. He won three of his five Cy Young Awards while with
the Red Sox. Martinez won the National League Cy Young Award in
1997 while with Montreal, and a record of 23-4 with a 2.40 ERA
makes him a lock to win it this year in the AL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a lot of fun,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre
said. ``Obviously, what Roger has meant to that organization and
that ballpark for a number of years and of course what Pedro has
done this year, it ought to be interesting.'' Hunter family honored
Helen Hunter, widow of Hall of Fame pitcher Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter,
and his children Todd, Paul and Kim Hunter-Layne, are scheduled to
throw out the ceremonial first pitch for Game 1 tonight. This is
the family's first appearance since Hunter died of amyotrophic
lateral sclerosis (Lou Gehrig's disease) on Sept. 9. Davis on
Martinez Red Sox ace Pedro Martinez is considered the best pitcher
in baseball, but Yankees designated hitter Chili Davis isn't
exactly in awe of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get impressed with much,'' Davis said. ``I give my
respect to Pedro, but I'm not impressed. I faced guys like Nolan
\RRyan\S and Dwight \RGooden\S in their prime, and they were just
as good.'' O'Neill expected to play Yankees right fielder Paul
O'Neill said he expects to play tonight even though he's suffering
from a broken rib in his right side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better today obviously than it was a few days ago,''
O'Neill said after the Yankees' workout yesterday. ``I went through
everything today, and I'm looking forward to playing. Unless I wake
up and have a big setback, then everything is a go at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill injured himself running into a wall at Tropicana Field
in Tampa Bay, Fla., on the final Saturday of the season. He played
in the first two games against the Rangers but sat out Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm worried about how I feel, instead of playing, then I
shouldn't be out there,'' O'Neill said. ``Right now I went out,
went through everything and felt pretty good.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
