<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WILT-RIVALRY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILT, KAREEM RIVALRY STRAINED OVER TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was an odd relationship _ filled with times of
great friendship and also long periods of animosity.
</P>
<P>
   The strange bond between Wilt Chamberlain and Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar is, and always will be, hard to understand, surpassing
in puzzlement the fragile relationship between Chamberlain and Bill
Russell.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Russell and Chamberlain were contemporaries, rivals
who consistently played against each other in the NBA Finals. It
was inevitable their bond would be strained.
</P>
<P>
   The Chamberlain-and-Abdul-Jabbar feud was more confusing. They
played against each other only four years. In addition, it was
Chamberlain, then an NBA superstar, who befriended Abdul-Jabbar
when he was a high school star in New York City. For a time, he was
Kareem's mentor.
</P>
<P>
   The animosity came mostly from Chamberlain, who spent a lot of
time sniping at Abdul-Jabbar in the press once Kareem turned
professional.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, long after Chamberlain retired, he belittled
Abdul-Jabbar's rebounding, and even urged him to retire a few
times. He summed up those feelings in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for Kareem,'' Chamberlain said. ``One thing for
sure _ he was blessed with a magnificent body and magnificent
talent. Not to say he loafed, but he never pushed himself to the
limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here to chastise Kareem. He was the greatest offensive
force I ever faced on the basketball court _ by far. The only time
I ever saw him push himself was against me.''
</P>
<P>
   During his career, Abdul-Jabbar stayed above the fray. But he
did respond in his post-career book, ``My Turn,'' published in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   In a segment sub-titled ``An Open Letter to Wilt Chumberlame,''
Abdul-Jabbar lashed out at the man he once idolized.
</P>
<P>
   He ended the letter by writing: ``So, now that I have left, one
thing will be part of my legacy: People will remember that I worked
with my teammates and helped us win. You will be remembered as a
whining crybaby and a quitter, stats and all.''
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Jabbar later said he wrote the letter against the wishes
of the book's publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the one who wanted to do it,'' Abdul-Jabbar said. ``As a
matter of fact, Mignon (McCarthy, the co-author) said, `Don't do
it, don't do it, it's like getting into a mud-slinging contest.' I
told her I was already covered with mud....
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilt had his say for a long time, and I've never really
responded to it, never told my side of it. I just figured I'd have
some fun with it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Abdul-Jabbar released this statement: ``Wilt was one
of the greatest players ever, and we will never see another one
like him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5057 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     10-13 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE TODAY'S STARS, CHAMBERLAIN LED THE WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The only thing small about Wilt Chamberlain was
the audience he reached. Because he came into his own long before
cable-TV sports came of age, there actually are people who call
themselves rabid NBA fans who will tell you with a straight face
that Kareem Abdul Jabbar or Patrick Ewing or _ God forbid _
Shaquille O'Neal redefined the center position.
</P>
<P>
   These people ought to be convicted of blasphemy and sentenced to
13 months of studying grainy basketball films from the 1960s and
early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame the image of the silky 7-foot-1 Chamberlain
blocking a shot or leading the fast break or finger-rolling the
ball into the basket isn't as easily retrieved from the mind's
archives as Michael Jordan's wagging tongue or fadeaway jumper.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Chamberlain, who was found dead in his Bel-Air
home Tuesday, revolutionized the game as surely as did Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of his death at age 63 is sadly ironic, coming the
day before the Los Angeles Lakers were to open their exhibition
season and unveil the same triangle offense that showcased
Chamberlain's array of skills and cemented his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the posies and platitudes stands O'Neal, who is in the
best position to honor Chamberlain's memory. The 7-foot-1 center
can pay homage to the Hall of Famer by losing himself in the
triangle offense and leading his team to the NBA title this season,
his eighth in the league, same as Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   After all, imitation is the sincerest form of flattery.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain, who played the final five years of his career in
L.A., and Celtics center Bill Russell were the Magic Johnson and
Larry Bird of their day. Their rivalry was the thrust that elevated
not only their individual games but lifted the league into a
different stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Russell and Chamberlain challenged the casting of the center as
a sort of human glacier, in the middle of the action but not
central to it.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't plodding, they weren't loggerheads, they didn't
move as though they had escaped from Baron von Frankenstein's
laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   In one game, Chamberlain used his 50-inch vertical leap to block
the first 10 shots taken by Walt Bellamy, himself no slouch. In
another he scored 100 points, a total most teams in the league
today can't muster.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain averaged 50.4 points his third year in the league
and led the league in assists in his ninth, averaging 8.6 a game.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1959 and 1973, he won 11 rebounding titles. In five of
those seasons, he also captured the scoring title, a double-double
nobody has done since.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain was as multi-faceted as a diamond. His value
extended well beyond scoring, though those 118 games of 50-or-more
points had a way of blinding people.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966-67, Philadelphia coach Alex Hannum _ a college teammate
of Tex Winter's at USC _ installed a triple-post offense he had
borrowed from Trojans coach Sam Barry. It wasn't easy but Hannum
managed to convince Chamberlain his rebounding and passing _ even
more than his prodigious scoring _ were paramount to the system's
success.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain, tired of getting beaten up by the critics who
derided him as a big basketball player but not a great one, placed
his ego in Hannum's hands. He didn't lead the NBA in scoring that
season but finished tops in the league in rebounding and shooting
percentage and was third in assists.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, Philadelphia finished second to none. Where
there was Wilt there was a way; Philadelphia defeated San Francisco
in six games in the NBA Finals and Chamberlain shed the loser label
that, he later wrote, had ``stuck on me like some big, ugly scar
from an operation I never had.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain again subjugated his scoring for the good of the
team in 1971-72. Bill Sharman, the Lakers' coach, also had been
weaned on basketball, Sam Barry style, and so it was Chamberlain
concentrated on his rebounding and passing and left the scoring
largely to guards Gail Goodrich and Jerry West.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich led the Lakers in scoring that season, averaging 25.9
points. Chamberlain averaged 19.2 rebounds and 14.8 points.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven years later Chamberlain is gone. But there's no
reason his example can't live on.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have two proven scorers in Kobe Bryant and Glen Rice.
They've got a big man with more scoring titles than NBA
championship rings.
</P>
<P>
   If O'Neal commits to passing, rebounding and shot-blocking it
could be yesterday once more. And wouldn't that be a eulogy worth
waiting for?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 0054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5058 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-CHAMBLERLAIN-REME     10-13 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CHAMBLERLAIN-REMEMBERED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS OF BASKETBALL MOURN LOSS OF BIGGEST GIANT OF ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (With OBIT-CHAMBERLAIN, which moved in ``a'' category) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tommy Heinsohn remembered when he purposely threw a basketball
off the backboard because he was convinced Wilt Chamberlain would
block his shot.
</P>
<P>
   Willis Reed was happy to have been outscored by Chamberlain by
56-32 in their first encounter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have doubled my points if he made his free throws,''
Reed joked.
</P>
<P>
   Red Auerbach called him ``a giant of giants,'' and affectionatly
remembered their first meeting. ``He was an 18-year-old bellhop at
the Kutsher's Country Club in Monticello, N.Y.,'' the Celtics'
patriarch said. ``You could tell even then he was headed toward 7
feet tall and greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   The day Chamberlain died at his Bel Air, Calif., home at age 63,
the people who played with and against the game's most indomitable
center remembered him.
</P>
<P>
   Heinsohn, the former Celtic who played and coached against
Chamberlain, last saw him in May during a tribute to Bill Russell
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went out till 3 in the morning and told war stories,''
Heinsohn said. ``I told him that he took a handful of my jersey and
ripped it out his rookie year.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinsohn added: ``Wilt brought two things to the NBA. First of
all, because of Wilt Chamberlain, people started thinking of
basketball players as the world's greatest athletes. Before him,
you supposedly played the game because you were tall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, he was such a dominating individual. And yet, he showed
basketball was a team sport, that the talent around you meant more.
He helped create the Boston Celtics. In turn those two elements
helped create the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Cunningham, a teammate of Chamberlain's for three seasons
in Philadelphia, was stunned by the news. Cunningham was not there
for Chamberlain's 100-point game against the Knicks, but said: ``I
played with several guys who were there. Everybody denied that they
played him that night or they'd say, `I only had to guard him for a
minute.' I'd always ask them, `Then who in the hell did he score
all those points on?' It was a running joke in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how many charities he's helped in his life,''
Cunningham said. ``He's a very caring person, especially when he
was away from the camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerning his reputation in the league, Cunningham added: ``He
was Goliath. He was the bad guy. No matter what he did, what he
achieved, they always booed him. That was just what Wilt had to
deal with. Some of that was because he was the first athlete that I
can remember who was outspoken about issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would say, `The guy can't play,' after a game. Say it like
it is. At the time, the public was not ready to deal with that kind
of honesty. I'm sure that fed into the persona people had about
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West, the Lakers' president who was a teammate of
Chamberlain's and won the 1972 championship in Los Angeles with the
big center, said: ``Wilt would sometimes say to me, `I can never
understand why they always boo me and they always cheer you. I told
him, `No one roots for Goliath.' We always laughed about that.''
</P>
<P>
   West added: ``His ability to come into a situation, look at the
people around him and try to make us a better team always amazed me
at the point in his career. He wanted to win. When I first started,
he helped make me a better player. We seemed to have a real good
feel together. He was one of those fabulous players that kind of
defined sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listen to players now and then, saying he couldn't play
today. `Sure, sure,' I always tell them. Let me tell you, they
wouldn't want to play against him.''
</P>
<P>
   As one of Chamberlain's greatest rivals, the Knicks had many
fond memories of the Big Dipper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just remember he was dominating, a scoring machine,
unstoppable,'' Walt Frazier, the Knicks' Hall of Famer, said. ``The
guy looked indestructible. He was such a physical specimen, I never
thought something like this would happen to him at 63.
</P>
<P>
   ``His legacy is comical. When you read about his records, it
makes you laugh. He has records that are just remarkable. I don't
care if he was 10 feet tall, the things that he did. I think the
season he averaged 50, he averaged almost 30 rebounds, something
incredible like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed, another Knick Hall of Famer and currently the Nets'
57-year-old senior vice president, said: ``Going from offense to
defense, he would always run back and stand right in front of the
basket, so you weren't going to get any layups. That was out. I
used to score against him by playing outside. I wouldn't go in. I
used to try to go in and get cute and he would block all of that
stuff. He was a tremendous athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Russell-Chamberlain rivalry, Reed added: ``Bill used to
tell me that when he used to play Wilt, they'd get in town the
night before and he would always call him up and take him out to
dinner and be real nice to him so he'd feel sorry for him the next
night. Over my first couple of years in the league, they called me
`Rookie.' I called them Mr. Chamberlain and Mr. Russell. They were
the league. Those two guys were the two standout players.''
</P>
<P>
   The news of his death caught many in the game by surprise,
especially the people that had recently spent time with
Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it because they had a tribute to Russell in
June in Boston,'' Reed said. ``I was there and Wilt was there and I
had a chance to talk with him. I saw him then and in Cleveland when
they had the NBA 50. His knees were bothering him a bit, but other
than that he looked great.''
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Wilkens, the Atlanta Hawks' coach, said: ``It's a huge
loss because he was one of the great ambassadors for the NBA. He
was a very congenial guy. He had a great sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to love to run in New York. He had an apartment up
there and he used to run through Central Park with two dobermans
and we used to always joke that no one's going to try to rob him in
Central Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Casey, the Nets' coach, added: ``His persona in the league
was something that maybe some of us didn't understand in the
beginning. When he held out for money because he felt he was
underpaid, he probably knew more than most of us that the game was
a big entertainment business.''
</P>
<P>
   NBA commissioner David Stern said in a prepared statement:
``We've lost a giant of man in every sense of the word. The shadow
of accomplishment he cast over our game is unlikely ever to be
matched. We're gratified that in the last few years, the NBA family
has had the opportunity to tell him how much his contributions have
meant to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham added: ``I heard the news while I was driving down
the street and had to pull over. I couldn't drive the car for a
minute. I don't look at it as losing a basketball player. I look at
it as the loss of a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember '67, my first season,'' Frazier said. ``I saw this
guy. He did everything, blocked shots, led the league in assists,
and he wasn't even scoring a lot, but he was doing all the
accessory things to make them a formidable team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd just stare at him, and call him Chamberlain. If he spoke
to you, it was like, `Oh man.' You'd tell your buddies, `Hey, Wilt
knew my name.' '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
