<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5060 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      10-13 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILT CHAMBERLAIN: GIANT CONTRADICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ To the generation of basketball fans who have grown up
since Wilt Chamberlain retired: You have no idea.
</P>
<P>
   Not just about the the enormity of the man, who was then dwarfed
by his staggering accomplishments. But about the contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   The only player to lead the NBA in scoring, rebounds and assists
could not execute consistently a basketball action often mastered
by 12-year-olds: The free throw.
</P>
<P>
   When the nation in 1968 was shaken by a civil rights movement
seeking long-denied justice, Chamberlain, who along with Muhammad
Ali may have been the world's most prominent black athletes,
endorsed Richard Nixon for president.
</P>
<P>
   The man who once averaged 48.5 minutes in a season for a
48-minute game (he played overtimes too) was sometimes criticized
for lacking competitive heart.
</P>
<P>
   For a player who remade basketball for all future big men, who
forced the rules writers to rejigger the game, who was the
7-foot-1, 275-pound acme of basketball's majestic power, his most
frequent contact with the game in his retirement was as a spectator
at Los Angeles Clippers' contests, where he was a pal of the club's
vile owner, Donald Sterling.
</P>
<P>
   For all his imagery as an invincible titan, he was probably too
soft, fearful of his power to injure. Said longtime rival and
friend Bill Russell of Chamberlain's famous 1970 Finals showdown
with gimpy-legged Willis Reed, who led the Knicks to victory over
the Lakers partly because Chamberlain seemed to back off:
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm the one playing Willis when he comes out limping, it
would only have emphasized my goal to beat them that much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the behemoth Lothario who claimed to have bedded 20,000
women died Tuesday at home in bed, alone, never married.
</P>
<P>
   A man bigger than nearly all men and nearly all description,
Chamberlain's contradictions make him that much richer a character,
and so much more than a great ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his ballplaying greatness has somehow been warped, not only
with time but through the green filter of Russell, his nemesis,
rival and friend whose unmatched career seemed fated to compromise
the game's most powerful, agile giant.
</P>
<P>
   As the pair locked up in a goateed grind in the low post
throughout the 1960s, it was Russell's Celtics who almost always
were superior to Chamberlain's Warriors, 76ers and Lakers teams.
Watching the NBA evolve on fuzzy black-and-white TVs, it seemed
that every winter Sunday was incomplete without at least a few
minutes spent watching Russell barely outmaneuver his formidable
adversary.
</P>
<P>
   Sports theater was rarely better. To witness two such skilled,
intelligent, dramatic rivals directly pitted against each other for
most of a decade was a national privilege, made all the more rare
by sports' failure to produce its like again.
</P>
<P>
   Russell's teams won 11 championships in 13 years, and he was
recently selected Sports Illustrated's greatest team player of all
time. Chamberlain's Philadelphia team of 1966-67 and his Laker team
of 1971-72 won titles, but it was never enough, even though those
teams may have been the best in league history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all judged by the championships we win,'' said forlorn
Laker president Jerry West Tuesday, talking about his former
teammate and fellow 40-year hoop icon. ``Unfortunately, he only won
two.''
</P>
<P>
   Only won two.
</P>
<P>
   Think about that. Consider how many NBA greats, particularly in
the Michael Jordan era, never won a single one. But Chamberlain
seems forever consigned to secondary status because his foil had so
many more.
</P>
<P>
   The heat of their battle long since faded to cold embers,
Russell articulated, during the NBA All-Star game in 1997 that
featured the selection of its 50 greatest players, the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody seems to appreciate what an incredible player Wilt
was,'' he said. ``He was the best player of all time because he
dominated the floor like nobody else ever could. To be that big and
athletic was special.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be blasphemous in the recently concluded era of Jordan.
Comparisons between eras are always murky, as well as comparisons
between different positions. But there is one fact that usually
escapes consideration in the argument.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA of Chamberlain's time had about 100 players. The NBA
when Jordan dominated swelled to more than 300, meaning he came up
against nowhere near the caliber of competition Chamberlain took on
every night. Whether it was Russell or Reed, or Nate Thurmond, Walt
Bellamy or Wes Unseld, Chamberlain almost always ran into a quality
foe.
</P>
<P>
   He crushed 'em all.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the freakish, 100-point game. Those 50-point, 28-rebound
games that he (begin italic) averaged (end italic) didn't come
against Jim McIlvaine or Greg Ostertag. While 30 years of gene-pool
splashings may have improved the caliber of the average NBA
athlete, 30 years of expansion have spread those athletes around
much more broadly.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain in his prime today would be even more dominant than
in his day, because of the flatness of the surrounding territory.
And owing to growth of the NBA's popularity and the increase in
media coverage, his blunt, sometimes reckless personality would be
even more immense.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a Dennis Rodman with brains, sophistication and
multidimensional talent.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1983 biography ``Giant Steps,'' Kareem Abdul-Jabbar wrote
about his hero worship as a kid of Chamberlain, his brief playing
rivalry as their careers crossed in the early 1970s, and of his
later contempt for his personal politics.
</P>
<P>
   But the game's giants eventually patched things up. And although
the book is filled with Abdul-Jabbar's belief of his superiority
over Chamberlain, he knew that in psychological as well as physical
stature, there was no one in the public mind quite like
Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Jabbar wrote: ``In airplanes and subways, on movie lines
or in the street, all big black guys were asked not, `Are you Bill
Russell?' but `Are you Wilt?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In his greatness, his contradictions and his foibles,
Chamberlain was a magnificent American original _ outsized, all
ways.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
