<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5076 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-WILT-DEATH-2ndTAKE-LA     10-13 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILT-DEATH-2ndTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY STEVE CARNEY 
</HEADLINE>
 
LOS ANGELES: Player awards. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  and JASON KANDEL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1972, Chamberlain helped the Lakers win their first
championship since moving to Los Angeles 12 years earlier from
Minneapolis, when he scored 24 points with a sprained wrist in the
decisive Game 5 against the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Even 18 years after his retirement, Chamberlain said he could
still play in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a hard thing to fathom,'' he said in a 1991
interview. ``I know what I'm capable of doing. It wouldn't be what
I was doing in the '60s, but I could go out and get 10, 11 rebounds
today. Those are league-leading numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to be playing today to get some of that money,'' said
Chamberlain, who earned $450,000 in his final season, 1972-1973.
``They couldn't afford me today. I helped make the league what it
is. I brought in a lot of fans.''
</P>
<P>
   His sister saw another side of him, she said Tuesday, eyes
rimmed in red and holding hands with her husband, Elzie, and
brothers Oliver and Wilbert.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always one of our favorite, favorite people,'' Barbara
Lewis said. ``He was a truly family-oriented person, but he was a
private person. He liked to crack a good joke, though.''
</P>
<P>
   He showed an example of his offbeat sense of humor in his
autobiography. He wrote that after he died, he wanted to be
cremated and placed in a jar inscribed: ``I bet you wonder how all
of me got into this little jar. Well, the same way I got into those
little cars when I was alive. Where there's a Wilt, there's a
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg said he and Chamberlain's family ask that fans and
friends alike pray for the fallen star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to all the millions and millions of fans Wilt had all
over the world,'' he said. ``He's been a famous athlete since high
school. He has so many fans and so many friends -- to this day he
receives fan mail by the hundreds every month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a giant among giants,'' Goldberg said, ``and let's hope
he rests in peace now.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain's longtime groundskeeper saw him in the bedroom of
his hilltop home about 10 a.m., and thought he was dozing, Los
Angeles police Cmdr. David Kalish said. When he saw Chamberlain
still hadn't moved at 12:30 p.m., groundskeeper Joe Mendoza
checked, found he wasn't breathing and called 911.
</P>
<P>
   Paramedics arrived and pronounced Chamberlain dead at 12:41
p.m., Kalish said. He said the cause of death was natural. An
autopsy is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg said Chamberlain had experienced heart problems off and
on.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, his sister, said she last spoke to Chamberlain on
Saturday, and said he was complaining of extreme pain from surgery
Thursday to remove two teeth knocked back in his playing days. She
said he was on medication and had lost several pounds during the
ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just not doing too well,'' she said, adding that he
rarely complained.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 he was hospitalized after experiencing an abnormal heart
rhythm during a Lakers game at the Forum. The following day his
doctor said Chamberlain still had the slight arrhythmia, but was in
excellent condition at Centinela Hospital Medical Center in
Inglewood.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
