<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5077 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-WILT-DEATH-2TAKES-LAD     10-13 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILT-DEATH-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA ICON FOUND AT HIS BEL-AIR HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 and JASON KANDEL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Wilt Chamberlain, who dominated basketball for the
Los Angeles Lakers and other teams through his size, agility and
demeanor, was found dead Tuesday at his home in Bel-Air. He was 63.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain, hospitalized with an irregular heart beat in 1992,
apparently died of a heart attack, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``Wilt the Stilt'' and ``The Big Dipper,'' the
7-foot-1, 275-pound center moved the game into a new era with
overpowering offensive skills that included the first monster
dunks, and which eventually convinced the league to widen the
free-throw lane to keep him farther from the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring a record 100 points in a single game, Chamberlain's size
and speed set the standard for power centers, a role now held by
7-1, 315-pound Shaquille O'Neal of the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers executive vice president Jerry West said Chamberlain
created a new era in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we acquired Wilt, he rejuvenated my enthusiasm for
playing the game, and was one of the people who helped all of us
achieve our dream of winning an NBA championship,'' West said.
``I'm sure that basketball fans from all over the world are
saddened by the passing of this truly great icon.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain generated adulation for his astonishing exploits and
criticism for his bravado, whether he was mulling a comeback long
after his 1973 retirement from the NBA, or boasting of his sexual
exploits.
</P>
<P>
   But his prowess on the court gave him grounds to boast.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain scored 31,419 points while playing in the National
Basketball Association, a record that stood until longtime rival
Kareem Abdul-Jabbar broke it in 1984. Chamberlain never fouled out
in his 1,205 regular-season and playoff games, and he still holds
the record for career rebounds with 23,924.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilt was one of the greatest ever, and we will never see
another one like him,'' Abdul-Jabbar said.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain helped win two NBA championships -- including the
first for the Lakers in Los Angeles -- and earned four Most
Valuable Player awards.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, the outspoken Chamberlain made news
again when he claimed in his 1991 autobiography, ``A View From
Above,'' that he'd had sex with 20,000 women.
</P>
<P>
   The sensational statement only added to the hype that followed
Chamberlain through his life. But family and friends said that
Chamberlain was a modest, thoughtful man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the brightest, most intelligent guys I've ever
known,'' said Chamberlain's attorney and friend for 40 years,
Seymour Goldberg of Marina del Rey.
</P>
<P>
   He called the star ``a giant among giants.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain had recently taken up the saxophone, was writing a
screenplay about his life and enjoyed late-night philosophy
discussions. ``He was really a man for all seasons,'' Goldberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia native began his basketball career at Overbrook
High School, where at 6 feet, 11 inches he already loomed large
over his teen-age opponents.
</P>
<P>
   After playing two years at the University of Kansas and one for
the Harlem Globetrotters in 1958, he joined the NBA's Philadelphia
Warriors in 1959, and moved with the team when it relocated to San
Francisco in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to Philadelphia in 1964 when he was traded to the
76ers, then came to Los Angeles in 1968 in a blockbuster trade to
the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain also won MVP awards from 1966 through 1968, led the
league in scoring for seven straight seasons and in rebounding for
14.
</P>
<P>
   When asked Tuesday if Chamberlain was the greatest player ever,
Goldberg replied: ``He thought so, and I thought so, so that's two
of us.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the quip, he remarked that Chamberlain was offended by
attempts to compare players of different eras. And though he didn't
elaborate, Goldberg added that Chamberlain ``wasn't very happy with
the way he thought the league was going.''
</P>
<P>
   The big man's play at the University of Kansas and his NBA
career that spanned 1959-1973 were marked by opponents' extreme
attempts to contain him, including double-, triple- and even
quadruple-teaming him. His frustration with opponents and referees
made him consider quitting the NBA after his rookie year.
</P>
<P>
   He played a summer with the Harlem Globetrotters, but
reconsidered and returned to the Warriors that winter.
</P>
<P>
   Born Aug. 21, 1936, Wilton Norman Chamberlain was not only one
of the greatest NBA players of all time, but earlier this year,
ESPN named him one of the 20 greatest athletes of the 20th century.
In spite of his obvious talents, however, others labeled him
arrogant and selfish.
</P>
<P>
   To prove their respective points, critics of his ethic and
worshippers of his talent often cite the same game -- March, 2,
1962, when Chamberlain became the only player in NBA history to
score 100 points in a single contest.
</P>
<P>
   During that extraordinary display, Chamberlain and his
Philadelphia Warriors teammates beat the New York Knicks 169-147
before a crowd of only about 4,000 in Hershey, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   But Chamberlain was a sensation long before that game.
</P>
<P>
   In only his first year, he exploded onto the league, setting
all-time single-season records for points scored, rebounds and
points-per-game average, as well as five other marks. He naturally
won the league's Rookie of the Year and Most Valuable Player
awards.
</P>
<P>
   (2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
