<HEADLINE>
METS' PIAZZA SET FOR RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Mets regained the services of catcher Mike Piazza
for Game 1 of the National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine learned before noon that Piazza's
swollen left thumb would not prevent his catcher from playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was even a little better than it was \RMonday\S, and
\RMonday\S was good enough to play,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza did not play during the Mets' final two victories against
the Diamondbacks in the Division Series. Piazza's replacement, Todd
Pratt, hit the 10th-inning, game-winning home run in Game 4 that
eliminated the Diamondbacks. Weiss in, Hernandez out Braves
shortstop Jose Hernandez struggled offensively against the Astros
during the Division Series, so manager Bobby Cox turned to veteran
Walt Weiss for Game 1 of the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss emerged as one of the heroes of the Division Series with
his diving stop of Tony Eusebio's 10th-inning ground ball in Game
3. That helped the Braves escape a bases-loaded jam unscathed, and
Atlanta went on to win that contest, 5-3, in 12 innings. Weiss also
appears more comfortable at the plate through his work with hitting
coach Don Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked good down in Houston when he came in, and Don's got
him swinging a lot better right now,'' Cox said. ``He's a great
defensive shortstop, and I thought I'd go that way for tonight's
game anyway.'' Baylor, Cubs meet The Cubs interviewed Baylor for
their vacant managerial position Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor met with Cubs general manager Ed Lynch and president Andy
MacPhail for three hours after the Braves' workout. Baylor
interviewed with the Angels three weeks ago, but that was before
the resignation of general manager Bill Bavasi.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers have also contacted Baylor, but he has not been
interviewed for their managerial opening. Cox takes high road Bobby
Valentine suggested this week that the Mets do not receive the
proper respect from the Braves. Bobby Cox, though, attempted to
downplay the animosity between the two ballclubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a real classy ballclub over there,'' Cox said. ``I
like a lot of their guys. There's always a few players in the
league that you would rather not have on your team, but I couldn't
name you one on that team.'' Cox wants best-of-seven It would mean
the reduction of the regular season's 162-game schedule, but Cox
prefers that the Division Series be expanded to a best-of-seven
format like the LCS and World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think you play all year long to get knocked out
in three games,'' Cox said. ``It's not quite fair \Rto someone\S
like Texas.'' He said it ``Well, speaking from experience ... I
haven't had any, so I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mets manager Bobby Valentine, on the differences between
managing a five- or seven-game series
nn
