<HEADLINE>
STARS' NEEDS ARE FILLED WITH CONTRACT EXTENSIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ |When the Stars signed center Joe Nieuwendyk and
goalie Ed Belfour this month, they signed two of their three
players scheduled to become unrestricted free agents next summer.
</P>
<P>
   They also pretty much took themselves out of the free-agent
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, what this does is we've signed our free agents for
next summer,'' Stars assistant general manager Doug Armstrong said.
``We won't, more than likely, be in that market because there is
not a need. We have our core center icemen, wingers, goalie and
defensemen taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that Armstrong gets the summer off.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have a number of restricted free agents' contracts
coming up this summer, including wingers Jere Lehtinen, Jamie
Langenbrunner and Blake Sloan and defenseman Sergei Zubov. On the
rise The Stars have one of the best top lines in the NHL in Mike
Modano, Jere Lehtinen and Brett Hull. Tonight, they face a line of
Owen Nolan, Vincent Damphousse and Jeff Friesen for San Jose that's
angling to get put in that category.
</P>
<P>
   They have combined for 10 goals and 13 assists in their first
five games, and the Stars realize slowing them down is going to be
tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so fast. You just got to keep them to the outside and
not give them the middle of the ice,'' Stars defenseman Richard
Matvichuk said. ``Obviously, you have to be physical when you can
with that line.'' Expecting more from Modano Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said he expects center Mike Modano to come back stronger
than ever from the injuries, both physical and mental, he
suffered.MDNM/ in an Oct. 2 game against Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   He also expects him to come back smarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could call it a wake-up call, I think the wake up for
Mike is teams are going to take advantage of anybody on our team
that puts themselves in a vulnerable position,'' Hitchcock said.
``I think the hardest part will be moving onto that area of the ice
again. I think during warmups someone is going to have to smack him
into that area of the ice.'' Marshall to play
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Grant Marshall (groin) said he felt better and
would play tonight.
nn
</P>
