<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-RIVALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGTIME RIVALS ADD ALCS TWIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Baseball has only three rivalries of enduring
significance.
</P>
<P>
   There is the Los Angeles Dodgers and the San Francisco Giants, a
rivalry born in New York and kept alive with their joint move to
California in 1958. There is the Chicago Cubs and St. Louis
Cardinals, a heated Midwest affair brought back to life by Sammy
Sosa and Mark McGwire in their chase for the home run record.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the New York Yankees and the Boston Red Sox, as
fierce a rivalry as found in any sport. Their fates have been tied
together since the Red Sox sold Babe Ruth to the Yankees in 1919.
The teams take center stage again tonight when they meet at Yankee
Stadium for Game 1 of the American League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question it's going to be something special,''
Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``As far as playing them, there's
no speech I could make that could get them excited more than
knowing they are going to Fenway Park and the Red Sox are coming
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are coming off a three-game sweep of the Rangers in
the Division Series in which their pitchers held one of the best
offenses in baseball to one run in three games. The Red Sox, after
losing the first two games of their series to the Cleveland
Indians, advanced by rallying to win the final three games. They
did so with an offense that scored 44 runs in those three games,
finishing the job with a 12-8 victory in Game 5 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You savor the moment when you accomplish something like
that,'' Red Sox manager Jimy Williams said. ``We felt our team did.
But we know we have a hard task ahead of us here with this
ballclub. We are trying our best to prepare for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have dominated the rivalry from the moment Red Sox
owner Harry Frazee sold Ruth to the Yankees for $100,000 plus a
$300,000 loan. The Yankees have won 35 pennants and 24 World Series
since, while the Red Sox have won only four pennants. They haven't
won a World Series since 1918, when Ruth was the best left-handed
pitcher in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The two years remembered most in the rivalry are 1949, when the
Yankees beat the Red Sox on the final two days of the season to win
the pennant by one game, and 1978, when New York prevailed in the
one-game East Division playoff on Bucky Dent's famous three-run
homer off Mike Torrez.
</P>
<P>
   The wild-card format, introduced in 1994, allows the two teams
to meet in postseason for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a student of history, you have to be excited,''
Yankees pitcher David Cone said. ``It's great for baseball and it's
great for New England. It's a tremendous opportunity for Boston
fans; they've been waiting for this a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Red Sox-Yankees rivalry particularly intense is
the cities are only 200 miles apart and both teams are usually
well-represented in the stands no matter if it is at Fenway Park or
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're really going to see the excitement in the stands,''
Yankees designated hitter Darryl Strawberry said. ``Obviously, we
have to play the game on the field; but you go up to Boston, their
fans and the New York fans are always at each other's throats.''
</P>
<P>
   Tradition and a regular-season record of 98-64, best in the
American League, would seem to make the Yankees the favorites. They
have a deep pitching staff _ well-rested after the sweep of the
Rangers while the Red Sox are scrambling to set their pitching
staff after the grueling five-game series against the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Sox took eight of 12 from the Yankees during the
regular season, including a three-game sweep Sept. 10-12 at Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 25 guys who play hard and leave it out on the field,''
said Red Sox pitcher Kent Mercker, who is starting tonight. ``Being
an underdog is not a bad situation for us. When everybody expects
you to lose, it can be a source of motivation trying to prove them
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question for the Red Sox is if they have anything
left after their emotional victory over Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not tired,'' Williams declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the Yankees think we're emotionally spent,'' Red Sox
right fielder Trot Nixon said. ``No way. We're a bunch of battlers.
There's nothing but gamers in here.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
