<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COX, BRAVES PLAY A WINNING HUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bobby Cox played a hunch in Game 1 of this National
League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' playoff-tested manager inserted a 35-year-old
reserve into his lineup at shortstop, and that would be the
catalyst that propelled Atlanta to a 4-2 victory over the New York
Mets on Tuesday night at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss, who served primarily as a reserve after Atlanta
acquired shortstop Jose Hernandez from the Chicago Cubs on July 31,
ignited the Braves' offense. Weiss went 3-for-4 with a run-scoring,
eighth-inning single, but it was his fifth-inning double that
allowed him to score what proved to be the game-winning run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a storybook performance for Walt,'' said Cox,
who decided to start Weiss for his defensive skills with
right-hander Greg Maddux on the mound. ``He didn't have a whole lot
plays in the field, but we all know he can catch the ball. It was
just a terrific performance. He's only played sporadically for the
last month and a half, but this came at a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox wanted Weiss in the lineup because of the number of ground
balls Maddux induces with his sinking, two-seam fastball. Maddux,
who surrendered only one run during his seven-inning appearance for
the victory, induced 12 ground-ball outs.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss' value, though, came at the plate after the Mets tied the
game with a fourth-inning run on a groundout by catcher Mike
Piazza. Weiss led off the fifth inning with a double against
right-hander Masato Yoshii and advanced to third on Maddux's
sacrifice bunt. Weiss scored on the ensuing single by left fielder
Gerald Williams, and the Braves never looked back after taking a
2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gerald Williams is the guy who really got the club moving,''
Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Maddux continued to mow down the Mets in typical
fashion. Maddux, who entered this contest 8-2 with a 2.28
earned-run average his career against the Mets, needed only 86
pitches to complete seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, he's Greg Maddux,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said.
``He doesn't have all those trophies because he's lucky. He's a
terrific pitcher, and he made good pitches when he had to. He
worked both sides of the plate, threw some curveballs early in the
game and did a good job. He did a very good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii took the loss, but the right-hander almost matched Maddux
inning for inning before departing during the fifth after spraining
his ankle while fielding Maddux's sacrifice bunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Yoshii pitched his butt off,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves got an insurance run with the sixth-inning home run
by catcher Eddie Perez, who hit only seven during the regular
season after replacing the injured Javier Lopez as the starter.
</P>
<P>
   Braves closer John Rocker allowed an unearned run in the ninth
inning after a two-out error by third baseman Chipper Jones, but
the left-hander recorded the final four outs for the save.
</P>
<P>
   The victory marked the Braves' 10th this season in 13 games
against the Mets, who must win Wednesday afternoon or return to
Shea Stadium in New York trailing this best-of-seven series, 2-0.
The winner of Game 1 has won every NLCS since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always better to win the first game,'' Cox said. ``I'd
rather win it than lose it. That's for sure.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
