<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' IRVIN WANTS FAST RETURN TO THE FIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Those mind-racing fears normally associated with
spinal injuries had subsided by the time injured Cowboys wide
receiver Michael Irvin spoke with coach Chan Gailey on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's ready to play. He wants to play,'' Gailey said yesterday.
``One of the first questions I got from him was, `What kind of
coverage did \RPhiladelphia\S play the rest of the game?'''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin could be out as many as six to eight weeks, which is more
a reality check, one source says, than it is a medical opinion at
this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in really good spirits,'' said Gailey, who found some
personal relief in Irvin's upbeat nature less than two days after
his big scare.
</P>
<P>
   So Irvin already is itching to play; he's eager to get back on
the field, and he is curious to see how opposing defenses choose to
play in the meantime against Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail and the other
Cowboys receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who knows Michaels knows that's him,'' Gailey said,
referring to Irvin's desire to get back. In fact, Gailey wants
Irvin to stay as close to the team as possible, even travel with
the Cowboys if he can.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Andrew Dossett, who has treated Daryl Johnston's neck
injuries since administering 1997 surgery, is scheduled to examine
Irvin today to determine what procedures, if any, need to be done,
and possibly how long he will be out.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston, who learned Sept. 14 that his season was over, has
spent the past month working as something of a coach with Tim
Lester and Robert Thomas at the fullback position. But Gailey said
that Irvin won't be expected to assume a similar role with the
receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Said Gailey: ``D.J. has the mind-set that he isn't going to play
this year, so he wants to know, `How can I help?' Michael's
mind-set is, `How fast can I get back?' I think they are different
mind-sets, totally.''
</P>
<P>
   Surgery for Irvin has not been entertained or ruled out because
the diagnosis is in the early stages, Cowboys trainer Jim Maurer
said. There also still is swelling and fluid in the spinal region
three vertebrae down from the skull.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin's place will be taken by veteran Ernie Mills and rookie
Wane McGarity, who are expected to split time although not
necessarily 50-50. McGarity was inactive the past two games because
of his limited contributions to special teams once Deion Sanders
came back to return punts.
</P>
<P>
   McGarity, who is looking for his first NFL regular-season catch
after having two drops in the Atlanta game Sept. 20, admittedly has
been ``frustrated'' by being inactive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want a guy who wouldn't get frustrated by not
playing,'' said Gailey, who went to McGarity and advised him on
Friday before each of the past two games that he would not be
activated on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   McGarity watched the Cowboys' upset loss to the Eagles on TV
from his home in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey recalled McGarity's reactions each time he has told him
that he wouldn't be suiting up, that he was still on the 53-man
roster but not the game-day 45-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first game \Rvs. Arizona\S, he nodded his head but he
didn't know what it meant,'' Gailey said. ``Then last week \Rvs.
Philadelphia\S, he said, `Explain this to me,' so we went through
the whole scenario again.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills, who has eight receptions for 81 yards and no touchdowns
this season, is coming off a game in which he had as many drops as
catches _ two.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey has no plan sign an experienced receiver. He would rather
set up auditions for the young receivers, McGarity, Jeff Ogden,
Jason Tucker and Chris Brazzell.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, we want to see how it goes with Michael \Rrecovery and
rehab\N,'' Gailey said. ``Another thing we're taking into
consideration is that we want to see how well these young guys can
perform, and if they can reach expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   And how quickly they can do it. \Nsubheds:Briefly. Left tackle
Flozell Adams' play Sunday in his fourth career NFL start at left
tackle earned praise yesterday from Gailey, who said, ``Flo played
very well this past week. I don't use this word often, but I
thought he was especially dominant with his run-blocking. We're
very pleased with his progress in becoming a solid left tackle for
us for a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback-punt returner Deion Sanders is ``real close ... 90
percent or above'' in getting back to where he was before his toe
injury in November, Gailey said. Sanders will make his third start
of the season, but his first prime-time appearance, when the
Cowboys face the New York Giants at the Meadowlands on Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Kevin Smith came out of Sunday's game with a tight
hamstring. It was Smith's first game action since Aug. 9. His back
(a bulging disk that sidelined him eight weeks) held up fine,
Cowboys trainer Jim Maurer said.
</P>
<P>
   Right guard Everett McIver (strained right hamstring) said he
hopes to resume practice full-go this week. If both McIver and
center Mark Stepnoski (lower back contusion) can start Monday night
against the Giants, it will mark the first time since the Sept. 12
season opener that the Cowboys have their starting offensive line
on the field together.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
