<HEADLINE>
WAC ATHLETIC DIRECTORS READY TO DEBATE EXPANSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Western Athletic Conference commissioner Karl Benson
has read all the news reports, seen the film clips, even conducted
a teleconference. He remains puzzled on one point, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's not important,'' he said, ``but I haven't actually
received any notification from TCU that they are leaving. I mean,
it's not a big deal; just thought I'd mention it.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the news reports are not an elaborate hoax, WAC
athletic directors will begin discussing expansion scenarios
Wednesday. Benson said he hopes to ``get a feel for their thinking,
and convey that to the presidents when they meet Sunday. It might
be nine schools, 10 or 12, or nothing. I personally feel that a
12-team league with two divisions is the best model, but I
understand the concerns about adding that many schools.''
</P>
<P>
   As for TCU's departure, Rice AD Bobby May said, ``I hate to lose
a conference member, and old Southwest Conference compadre. But
they're doing what they feel is best for them, and I can't fault
them for that. More than anything else, we lose a long relationship
with that school, and that's sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think that they'll be better off. Now it's our job
to do all we can to prove that they made the wrong decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa AD Judy MacLeod said, ``I'm disappointed that TCU is
leaving ... but I'm ecstatic that SMU is staying. I was really
afraid they would both go, and we would be cut off from the Dallas
area completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having that connection is very important to us and our fans,
and I'm glad it's not just us and Rice left over here in this
region.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii basketball coach Riley Wallace said, ``I don't really
feel that we lost a lot. Dallas is a good city, and SMU is a great
school with a program that's coming up. I would like to see us have
some stability, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson said he felt that under the circumstances, the WAC came
out lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we caught a break,'' he said. ``I wouldn't feel that
way if we had lost both of them, but I'm certainly happy with the
one that's left in the WAC.
</P>
<P>
   ``SMU delivers Dallas, and I don't know that TCU necessarily
does. SMU is connected politically and media-wise to Dallas, and
that's important. I checked that out before I took this job, and I
was told that TCU alone cannot deliver it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we need to convince the marketplace that we are a
valuable product regardless of whether one team leaves or not. As
for SMU going through a `healing process,' as has been suggested, I
think it will be brief, because president (Gerald) Turner and
(athletic director) Jim Copeland have gone out of their way to make
sure they didn't lose the respect of their peers.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Copeland attended the day's meeting, TCU was
represented by associate AD Jack Hesselbrock, prompting a question
to Benson about whether the presence of TCU AD Eric Hyman would
have caused added strain in the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't answer that,'' Benson said, ``but I think Jim Copeland
would have been here today even if they were leaving.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
