<HEADLINE>
AS LAME DUCK, TCU MIGHT FEEL WAC BACKLASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The timing of Monday's announcement that TCU
would join Conference USA in the 2001-2002 academic year was both
good and bad, Horned Frogs football coach Dennis Franchione said.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione preferred that TCU players hear it from coaches.
Instead, the players read about it in newspapers and watched it on
television. There was no practice Monday, and Franchione said it
would have been too difficult to round up that many people. He
discussed it with the team for the first time yesterday. He told
them life might not be fun as a lame-duck member of the Western
Athletic Conference for the rest of this season and next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The juniors and the seniors probably don't have much interest
because it won't affect them,'' Franchione said. ``But they need to
understand that as big as the bull's eye was on us, it might have
got a little bigger, if that's possible. It's something we'll deal
with. Some people might use this for motivation, I suppose.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing was good, however, because of Saturday's 6:05 p.m.
game against Tulsa (1-4, 0-2 in the WAC) at Amon Carter Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs (2-3, 1-1) will have 75-100 potential recruits at the
game.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, a move from the WAC to Conference USA will come up in
the sales pitch. The WAC has a tie with one bowl game next season,
and C-USA has contracts with three bowls. The WAC's television
contract guarantees seven football broadcasts, compared with the
current C-USA contract of 25 TV games per season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids want to know about television and bowls,'' Franchione
said. ``Conference USA has a nice, well-thought-out package that
I'm sure will grow. There is also some name identity. Conference
USA just seems to be doing a great job of creating a very good
image of itself.'' \Nsubheds:Not a bad week TCU junior running back
LaDainian Tomlinson said it's turning out to be a pretty good week
for the Frogs. Tomlinson's 300-yard performance Saturday made him
the leading rusher in NCAA Division I-A with an average of 176.4
yards per game. Two days later, TCU is invited to join a new
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all recognition for TCU, so it's all a good thing,''
Tomlinson said. ``It is kind of weird to look in the stats and see
my name up there. It's a tribute to everybody. Now, we have to keep
it going.''
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, Tomlinson's two best rushing days came
against Tulsa. He ran for 165 yards against the Golden Hurricane in
1998. He rushed for 180 yards and two touchdowns against Tulsa in
1997. \Nsubheds:Plays for Batteaux Dennis Franchione said the
coaching staff is thinking of ways to get senior quarterback
Patrick Batteaux more playing time, which might result in some
plays at wide receiver. It will not happen Saturday against Tulsa,
however.
</P>
<P>
   But in two weeks, when the Frogs play Rice, they could have
starting freshman quarterback Casey Printers and Batteaux in the
game at the same time. Batteaux, who is recovering from a ligament
injury in his left hand, would remain the team's backup
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still need him at quarterback, but I know he wants to be in
the game,'' Franchione said. ``He's always played, and even though
he would never complain about his current situation, I know this is
hard for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Batteaux entered Saturday's 42-0 victory against San Jose State
in the third quarter at quarterback.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
