<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIEUWENDYK SIGNS CONTRACT EXTENSION; CHAMBERS SIDELINED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Stars playmaker Joe Nieuwendyk wasn't born in
Texas, but he got here as fast as he could.
</P>
<P>
   Now, four years after getting traded from Calgary, he's staying.
Nieuwendyk, last season's Stanley Cup most valuable player, signed
a three-year, $15 million contract extension that ensures he will
be in a Stars uniform through the 2002-2003, likely the end of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I see myself playing too many years behind it
but you never know,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``I have a little time to
worry about that. I just think the team is committed too, to having
a good team here. I think I'd be crazy not to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were in need of some good news Tuesday after
arthroscopic surgery on defenseman Shawn Chambers brought bad news.
What started out as exploratory surgery on his right knee turned
into surgery to remove pieces of cartilage and repair cartilage in
the socket which had been worn thin.
</P>
<P>
   He will be on crutches for six weeks, begin rehabbing after that
and will be out until at least mid-January. Until then, the Stars
will rely on Brad Lukowich and Alan Letang to absorb Chambers'
20-plus minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn's injury, probably for the team out of what could've
transpired, is a worst-case scenario,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said. ``From our standpoint, we've got to look at this as a real
opportunity for the younger guys. It is going to give us an
opportunity to have a long-term look at Lukowich and Letang.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Stars get Mike Modano (concussion) and Darryl Sydor
(fractured left eye socket) back from injured reserve for Wednesday
night's game against San Jose at Reunion Arena, Chambers goes out.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Hitchcock has shuffled his usually staid
defensive pairs to compensate. Last year, the Stars' defense
remained as unchanged as CBC hockey commentator Don Cherry's
wardrobe remains bright.
</P>
<P>
   He has Sydor playing with Jamie Pushor, a chance to get him
extended playing time. Sydor's usual partner, Sergei Zubov, has
been paired with Derian Hatcher, turning that into a shutdown
tandem with skill. Richard Matvichuk will be playing with Lukowich
and Letang.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't see us playing in three groups of two,''
Hitchcock said. ``I see us with six defensemen. I don't see us as
definitive this year as we were last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher and Matvichuk were like an old married couple, always
together as the No. 1 defensive pair. Likewise for Zubov and Sydor.
Only they were the skilled pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changes for Zubov because he takes additional minutes in a
defensive role, but I think he's ready for that challenge,''
Hitchcock said. ``It changes for Syd because he is going to have to
kill more penalties than he did.''
</P>
<P>
   While adjustment was the short-term theme around StarCenter
Tuesday, stability was the long-term theme. With Nieuwendyk's
extension, the Stars now have the core of the team that won the
Stanley Cup tied up for the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars already had Sydor (three years), Matvichuk (four
years), Hatcher (four years), Modano (five years) and goalie Ed
Belfour (three years) locked up in long-term deals.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour signed a two-year, $11.5 million extension on Oct. 1,
and at that time contract talks with Nieuwendyk looked to be tabled
until next spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance to sit down one more time and Joe said he'd
like to work something out,'' Stars assistant general manager Doug
Armstrong said. ``So we went back to work and over the last week on
the last road trip we had a chance to spend some time together to
work on an extension that keeps the core of our team in so next
year we won't lose any players to free agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk acted as his own agent, negotiating his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call myself Arliss,'' Nieuwendyk said, referring to
a fictional sports agent on the HBO show Arli$$.
</P>
<P>
   Just a Texan. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
