<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-WORRIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGGIES' OFFENSIVE LINE, RUN DEFENSE WORRY SLOCUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum offered
some sobering words yesterday to fans who consider the 13th-ranked
Aggies back on the inside track toward a third consecutive Big 12
South Division title after a 45-13 rout of Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still not a championship-caliber team,'' Slocum said.
``We've got a couple of areas we need to shore up if we're going to
stay in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Heading the list of concerns as A&AMP;M (4-1, 1-1) prepares for
Saturday's 11:30 a.m. meeting with Kansas (2-4, 0-2) at Kyle Field
is his offensive line. Andy Vincent, the Aggies' starting right
tackle, suffered a concussion against Baylor and is not expected to
play against Kansas. Michael Mahan, a redshirt freshman who has
started the past two games at left tackle, worked at right tackle
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Tango McCauley, slowed the past two weeks because of a sprained
ankle, is expected to make his first start at left tackle against
Kansas. But McCauley, a converted defensive lineman, has been slow
in responding to treatment. If McCauley can't play, Slocum said he
is unsure where he would turn for a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M's tackle ranks were depleted when starter Shea Holder
suffered a season-ending knee injury Sept. 25 against Southern
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said he also wonders about a run defense that ranks sixth
in the nation (67.8 yards per game) but ``hasn't really been
tested'' except during a 21-19 loss to Texas Tech, when Red Raiders
fullback Sammy Morris rolled for 170 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Each of Kansas' top three tailbacks averages at least 4.6 yards
per carry, with Mitch Bowles coming off a career-high 101 yards
against Kansas State and starter David Winbush (55 carries, 255
yards) slated to return to the lineup after missing last week with
knee and ankle ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the prospect of playing without tailback Dante Hall
(back) and fullback D'Andre Hardeman (groin) against the Jayhawks,
Slocum said he is encouraged by A&AMP;M's depth at running back.
Reserve tailbacks Eric Bernard and Joe Weber combined to rush for
131 yards and two touchdowns against Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got more depth this year,'' Slocum said. ``If we get
down to two available backs, we still have capable people.''
\Nsubheds:Warren's cast removed Defensive end Ty Warren, one of the
most celebrated members of A&AMP;M's 1999 freshman class, had a cast
removed yesterday that protected a broken left thumb. Warren
(6-foot-4, 277 pounds) suffered the injury Aug. 18 and has seen
limited playing time. He has yet to record a tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said that should change now that Warren can use both
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to getting him on the field,'' Slocum said. ``I
think he would've helped before now if not for that injury.''
\Nsubheds:On the sideline Outside linebacker Jason Glenn, limping
yesterday because of a sprained ankle, said he ``definitely'' will
play against Kansas. Slocum disagreed, saying, ``We can't afford
... to risk losing him for another two weeks if he reinjures
himself because he's not 100 percent.'' Glenn leads A&AMP;M in tackles
for losses (nine for minus-39 yards).
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
