<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-BLACKMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS TO HONOR BLACKMAN BY RETIRING NO. 22 JERSEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Three years after he retired from basketball, Rolando
Blackman will receive an honored place in the Mavericks'
organization.
</P>
<P>
   In a show of family unity, the Mavericks plan to retire
Blackman's No. 22 jersey during halftime of the team's March 11
home game against the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tremendous, great feeling for me,'' Blackman said
Tuesday. ``I'm very happy and very proud, and it'll be a special
day.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other jersey the Mavericks have retired in the team's
19-year history is Brad Davis' No. 15. Davis is ecstatic about his
jersey hanging in the Reunion Arena rafters with Blackman's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was getting lonely up there,'' Davis said. ``It's good for
Ro, and I'm glad to see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really a professional _ the way he practiced and the
way he played. He practiced hard, he played hard, he played hurt,
and he always seemed to make big shots when we needed them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks president and CEO Terdema Ussery notified Blackman
about the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rolando's one of the greatest players to ever play for the
Mavericks franchise,'' Ussery said. ``And he, just as importantly,
conducted himself on and off the court in a way that made everybody
in this city proud.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to honor him and to show him how much we appreciate
what he did for the organization, and what he continues to do in
terms of how he represents the Mavericks and the city of Dallas in
his business pursuits.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if plans are in the works to retire the jerseys of two
other prominent players who also helped lay the foundation for this
franchise, Derek Harper and Mark Aguirre, Ussery said: ``One at a
time. This is about Ro, and that's what we're focused on right now,
just trying to make sure that he has a day and a night to
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackman, 40, played for the Mavericks from 1981-92, averaging
19.2 points and shooting 49.7 percent from the field. The 6-foot-6
shooting guard was selected to All-Star teams in 1985-87 and 1990
and played in all 48 of the Mavericks' playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   When Blackman was the ninth pick of the 1981 draft from Kansas
State, he said he only had one mission on his mind at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to beat out Elston Turner to get a chance to
get some playing time,'' Blackman said. ``Then, all of a sudden, my
career blossomed, and I became one of the best.''
</P>
<P>
   After playing 11 years with the Mavericks, Blackman was traded
to the New York Knicks on June 24, 1992, for a first-round draft
pick. He played two years for the Knicks _ they lost to Houston in
the 1994 NBA Finals _ and finished his pro career in 1996 after
playing one season in Athens, Greece, and one year in Milan, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks forward Cedric Ceballos said Blackman should have had
his jersey retired ``a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a history buff, and Rolando was always a calm, clutch
player,'' Ceballos said. ``I think it's a good move by the
organization to honor such a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   A Brooklyn native, Blackman and the Mavericks were one game away
from reaching the 1988 NBA Finals. They lost a seven-game series to
the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Blackman, who lives in Frisco, is a college-basketball analyst
for ESPN. He also has a video voice and data company and works with
Aguirre on a website called lifecast.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a fantastic career,'' Blackman said. ``But this
retirement ceremony should be a glowing situation not only for me
but also for all of the people who helped me become the person that
I am today.'' STRONG DEBUT FOR WALKER
</P>
<P>
   Did anyone catch Samaki Walker's opening act for the San Antonio
Spurs over the weekend? Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson
heard about it. So did many players and front-office employees.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who spent a lion's share of last season in Nelson's
doghouse after turning down the team's four-year, $20 million
contract extension, scored the winning basket as the Spurs opened
preseason play with a 98-97 victory at Philadelphia. In victory,
Walker was phenomenal.
</P>
<P>
   The third-year power forward converted 7-of-12 shots, made
9-of-9 free throws, grabbed seven rebounds, recorded two blocks and
scored 23 points off the bench. Nelson didn't sound surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect him to do well,'' he said. ``He's a good player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did try to keep him here. We offered more money than (the
Spurs) did. He wanted to move.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurs coach Gregg Popovich is more than happy to have Walker as
a part of his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Walker has come to camp, we've made him an outside guy
instead of an inside guy,'' Popovich said. ``It just seemed
apparent that he's real comfortable facing the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that we're right. It looks like we might be.'' WILLIAMS
GETS INJECTION
</P>
<P>
   Backup center John ``Hot Rod'' Williams received the first of
three weekly steroid injections of Epidual on Tuesday, and will
likely start the regular season on the injured list.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who has yet to practice this season because of chronic
back spasms, will not be available for any basketball activities
for at least three weeks. The season opener is Nov. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit of a setback for him,'' Don Nelson said.
``But there's nothing we can do about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is being treated by Dr. Andrew Dossett, a back and
spine specialist who also works with Cowboys and Rangers players.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
