<SLUG> BC-FBN-HILL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRVIN'S FIRE WILL BE MISSED AS MUCH AS HIS OUTPUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has never been a shortage of opinions on Cowboys receiver
Michael Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   More proof came during ugly proceedings Sunday at Veterans
Stadium. As Irvin lay motionless on the turf with head and neck
trauma after being hit by Eagles safety Tim Mauck, Eagles fans
cheered, while Eagles players waved their hands to quiet the crowd
in a show of respect for a worthy adversary.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin escaped serious injury. But it is uncertain when he will
play again.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, who quietly believe Irvin's absence could be six to
eight weeks, must find a way to play on without him.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be an easy task, no matter the opinion of him.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Irvin put the ``c'' in controversial and has been equally
glorified and despised for much of his 11-year career.
</P>
<P>
   His trash-talking, showboating style made him a villain on the
field long before his off-field troubles turned him into the NFL's
marquee bad boy.
</P>
<P>
   His playmaking output, which has him ranked among the top 10
receivers in NFL history to go along with three Super Bowl titles,
has him poised as a shoo-in for the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that both his apologists and detractors can agree on
is that the fiery Irvin has also always been a consummate warrior.
He has long been the heart and soul of Cowboys, who fed off his
boundless energy during the Super Bowl title seasons in 1992, 1993
and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Never considered the most talented player, Irvin is a superstar
player because of his unparalleled intensity, competitiveness and
work ethic. Irvin, 33, has not missed a game due to injury since
1990, when he missed the first four recovering from knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   That's 139 straight, excluding the five he missed in 1996 for
violating the NFL's substance-abuse policy.
</P>
<P>
   That same work ethic is the reason many believe Irvin will be
back as good as ever before the season is over and maybe before the
doctors anticipate. Irvin, who openly talked about the Super Bowl
last week, is real excited about what the Cowboys can do this
season and will likely ``break his neck'' to get back on the field.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, the Cowboys, who are considering not re-signing
Irvin next season because of his age and declining output, will get
a free glimpse of life without Irvin's continual chatter on the
field and the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   The view didn't look so good in the final three quarters Sunday.
As more than not having someone to step up and make a play
offensively, the Cowboys also lacked emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about Irvin's finger-pointing, body-shaking
maneuvers, they often charged his teammates into a frenzy and
spurred scoring drives. Cowboys coach Chan Gailey's play-calling,
Raghib Ismail's speed and Troy Aikman's leadership all had the
impact of a funeral procession against the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Backup receivers Ernie Mills and Wane McGarity have been charged
with trying to pick up Irvin's on-field production in the interim.
But the facts are if somebody doesn't replace his act-a-fool
passion, he will return just in time for another burial _ the
Cowboys' season.
INSIDE THE LOCKER ROOM
</P>
<P>
   There has been some talk about the Cowboys' signing a veteran
receiver to replace Irvin. But there's just one problem. Any
receiver that could help the Cowboys is already on somebody's
roster. There is a reason guys are unemployed five weeks into the
season. But for you hard-headed folks, here is a short list of
available choices _ unemployed, flawed veterans Michael Jackson,
Randal Hill and Alvin Harper.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is problem two _ Chan Gailey's intricate offense. Any
newcomer would be hardpressed to learn the offense well enough to
become a factor at this point in the season. Very little teaching
is done during the season. Teams work on plays and game plans.
Taking time away to catch one person up to speed retards the
offensive process for the team as a whole.
YARDSTICKS: HOW FAR DO THE COWBOYS HAVE TO GO?
PASSING DOWN
</P>
<P>
   With seven interceptions through four games, the Cowboys are on
pace for 28, which would be their highest total in 13 years. The
Cowboys mustered just 21 pickoffs the past two years combined,
including a paltry seven in 1997.
IN THE `RED' ZONE
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' offense is tied for first in the NFL in red-zone
touchdown efficiency. They have nine touchdowns and one field goal
on 12 trips inside their opponent's 20-yard line. The problem is
that they are 20th in number of trips in the red zone. They were
there just once against the Eagles.
FOURTH DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Last season the Cowboys' special teams units were among the
league's elite _ ranking first in kickoff coverage, third in punt
coverage, fourth in punt-return average and 12th in kickoff return
average. So far in 1999, they are third, 25th, 19th and 14th in the
same categories, respectively. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
