<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5100 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-ART-1     10-13 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES WIN NLCS OPENER, 4-2 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There was a prominent skid mark on the third-base line
of Turner Field, a glaring reminder in full view of the New York
Mets' dugout of their stumbles on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Steve Phillips tested an analogy the other day,
suggesting that the last time the Mets had faced the Braves, they
were sliding down a slippery slope and now, reinvigorated by their
rush into the National League Championship Series, they were
climbing the mountain wearing spiked boots. But when Roger Cedeno
sprayed white chalk on the infield grass in his frantic attempt to
get back to third base after Masato Yoshii failed to squeeze him
home in the third inning, it was clear that the crampons were
failing.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, in a renewal of the late-season failure to get timely
hits that nearly doomed their bid to make the playoffs, lost their
grip on a closely played game and lost 4-2 to the Braves to drop
the first opener of their four-of-seven-game League Championship
Series.
</P>
<P>
   If the third-base line was too oblique a symbol for the Mets'
continuing woes against the Braves, who dominated them in their
regular-season series, then the sight of Melvin Mora, standing on
third base while the Braves reliever John Rocker, who got the save,
zipped fastball after fastball by John Olerud to end an
eighth-inning threat, and Rey Ordonez grounding out to end a
ninth-inning rally that had already scored one run were more
direct.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who were sent into a nearly fatal funk by Braves
pitching just three weeks ago _ Rocker saved all three of those
games, too _ had provided entertaining theater in getting back to
Atlanta. But from the looks of this game, they hadn't gained much
ground on the decade's premier National League team. This loss,
which sends the Mets into a hole with Kevin Millwood starting
Wednesday for the Braves, was, despite the drama of the last 10
days, eerily similar to the five late-season losses to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the good news,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said. ``You
can only have so many of these in a year. I think we're going to be
able to play these games and play for the break.''
</P>
<P>
   But these kinds of games against the Braves are mounting, and
now, with a World Series slot on the line, there is little time for
the Mets to wait for a break. A few of the daunting figures: Rickey
Henderson, 0 for 4; Mike Piazza, his timing off a bit from the two
games he missed with a swollen thumb, 0 for 4; Robin Ventura, who
hit just .174 against the Braves in the final six games, 0 for 3,
with a strikeout looking for the second out in the ninth inning;
Darryl Hamilton, 0 for 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does not have all those trophies because he's lucky,''
Valentine said of Greg Maddux, who held the Mets to one run on five
hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   The bad omens started to pile up for the Mets before the first
inning ended. Maddux, whom the Mets had somehow managed to hammer
for their only victory of their six games against the Braves in the
last 10 days of the season, retired the side in the first inning on
just nine pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The next chilling sign came in the form of Orel Hershiser, the
starter sent to the bullpen for long relief in the playoffs,
already warming up after Masato Yoshii had faced just three
batters.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii had none of the control early in the game that had made
him the Mets' most consistent starter since August, and Gerald
Williams smacked Yoshii's first pitch of the game up the middle for
a single. Williams stole second and scored when Bret Boone reached
up to slug a full-count, shoulder-high pitch for a chopper up the
middle to give the Braves a 1-0 lead, which looms when Maddux is on
the mound.
</P>
<P>
   But in the top of the third came the strongest signal yet that
the pixie dust that had glistened on the Mets for the last 10 days
had worn off a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno doubled to lead off the inning, the first hit the Mets
got off Maddux. Cedeno's shot went into left field and Williams,
the left fielder, threw the ball in to second baseman Boone, the
cut-off man. But Boone had to travel 30 feet to even get close to
the ball, which he missed. As the ball rolled away, Cedeno went to
third base on the error.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a fiasco that, should the Mets not advance, may go
down as one of the crucial lost chances of this series. Ordonez
topped a pitch that rolled along the third-base line. He stood
still watching it. But the Braves' catcher, Eddie Perez, astutely
picked up the ball, which had remained fair, and threw to first
base, getting Ordonez out without even having to check third to
make sure Cedeno was not moving.
</P>
<P>
   Worse was what came next. On a 2-0 count, Yoshii had received
the sign to bunt, to start a suicide squeeze to bring Cedeno home.
But Yoshii missed the ball entirely and Cedeno was caught in
no-man's land, already more than halfway home. Perez ran him down,
and the mark Cedeno made was symbolic of the Mets' mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the time it was a really big play,'' Valentine said. ``We
had a chance to tie it up, and we missed the squeeze.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets finally scored in the fourth inning to tie the game
when Edgardo Alfonzo smashed a double into left-center and later
came home on a Piazza groundout. But Yoshii, who had allowed just
one base runner since the first inning, encountered trouble again
in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss, whom Atlanta Manager Bobby Cox had put into the
lineup at shortstop because of the defensive skill that may have
saved the Braves' season during the division series against
Houston, smacked a leadoff double into right field, one of his
three hits. Maddux bunted back to the mound to move Weiss to third,
but Yoshii came off awkwardly and turned his left ankle before
throwing Maddux out.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' trainer, Fred Hina, and Valentine came out to check on
Yoshii, and in his warm-up pitches, he seemed to hop a little on
the left foot. But he remained in the game to face Williams. It was
a bad decision.
</P>
<P>
   Jumping on Yoshii's first pitch again, Williams hit a single to
left field. Henderson overran the ball and, while Weiss scored to
give the Braves a 2-1 lead, Williams went to second base. But the
Braves again failed to batter the Mets. Cedeno made a
full-extension diving catch of a Boone fly ball for the second out
and, after Chipper Jones was intentionally walked and after Yoshii
was removed for Pat Mahomes, Jordan flied out to end the inning.
Yoshii, bothered by his ankle, had been chased after allowing the
Braves two runs in four and two-thirds innings
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' failure to pile up runs might have had more impact
on the game if the Mets could have made something of their at-bats.
In addition to the suicide-squeeze debacle, the Mets stranded
runners in scoring position in the fourth, sixth and eighth
innings. The Braves added two more runs, one on a home run by
Perez. By the time the Mets failed to add more than just one run in
the ninth _ Hamilton came in on Todd Pratt's pinch-hit single _ it
felt as if the Braves had beaten the Mets more thoroughly than the
score indicated and pushed the recent upstart just a bit farther
down the hill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
