<HEADER>
A5102 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     10-13 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILT'S LEGACY ASSURED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wilt Chamberlain played his last official game of basketball in
1973. But every time I saw him, I wondered why he ever retired.
</P>
<P>
   He quit the game at 37 after 14 NBA seasons, which seems
premature by today's standards. After dragging the likes of Clyde
Lovellette, Tommy Heinsohn, Walt Bellamy, Nate Thurmond and Bill
Russell up and down the court for 14 seasons, he certainly deserved
a rest.
</P>
<P>
   But this man was never out of shape. In the '70s and '80s, he
was a regular on the local track and volleyball scene. On one
particular Saturday, after watching a UCLA dual meet at Drake
Stadium, Chamberlain, a high jumper at Kansas, went down to the
field to talk to some of the jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   With maybe a dozen people still in the facility, most of them
athletes or writers, Wilt, shoeless, loped up to the high jump bar
and, using the old split jumping style, cleared a height estimated
at seven feet. He was around 45 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, he showed up on a sports talk show and said
with aplomb that he could still play in the NBA. He was in his 50s
by now. Some critics scoffed, but only those who harped on the
drain of an 82-game schedule.
</P>
<P>
   In a one-on-one situation, no one doubted he could handle the
modern NBA post man. I certainly didn't. Neither did Jerry West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust me,'' said Lakers General Manager Jerry West, ``today's
players wouldn't want to play him.''
</P>
<P>
   No one ever handled Chamberlain during his 14-year NBA career,
with the obvious exception of his nemesis, Boston's Bill Russell.
And even then, it wasn't a matter of Russell handling Chamberlain
as much as containing him and having the good fortune to play on
superior teams.
</P>
<P>
   During the NBA's 50th anniversary party two years ago, Russell
chuckled at those who said he got the better of Chamberlain because
he won ten titles compared to Chamberlain's two. Russell won the
titles, but Chamberlain always attended. His teams made it to the
finals or conference finals in 12 of 14 seasons, and he lost a Game
7 to the Celtics by four points or less four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Celtics were the greatest franchise of all time,'' Russell
said. ``But each time we played for the title, Wilt always stood in
my way. I took great pride in my defense, yet he had so many great
games against me. I remember a game when someone congratulated me
for holding Wilt to 55 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilt was a very intelligent player. I could not play him the
same waymes in a row, and there were a lot of guys I never
ever had to change the way I played. There are things Wilt did that
no one will ever come close to doing -- 100 points in a game, 55
rebounds in a game, averaging 27 rebounds and 50 points a game for
a full season.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the many NBA records Chamberlain still holds is the 55
rebounds he posted in one game. Considering the opponent that
night, Russell and the Celtics, it might be a more meaningful
record than his 100-point game against the Knicks in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain led the league in scoring his first seven seasons,
with a low of 33.5 (1966) and a high of 50.4 (1962), and in
rebounding 11 of 14 seasons. This was during an era of the NBA when
every team had a center with guile, strength or both.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six years after retiring, Chamberlain still holds NBA
records for career rebounds (23,924), highest single game shooting
percentage (100 percent, done three times in 1967), fewest
disqualifications (he did not foul out once in 1,045 games) and
most games with 50 or more points (118).
</P>
<P>
   He undoubtedly would hold the record for blocked shots, too, if
the league had taken the time to keep the stats during his career.
There were also subtle shifts in league rules (lane, goaltending)
that were a direct result of Chamberlain's presence.
</P>
<P>
   But fitting his reputation as a renaissance man off the court,
Chamberlain showed great diversity on it. After leading the league
in scoring seven straight seasons, Chamberlain changed his game
with the Philadelphia 76ers and won three straight MVP awards.
</P>
<P>
   He turned his attention to setting up others rather than just
scoring. In 1967, he averaged 7.8 assists a game and led the 76ers
to the NBA title. In '68, he led the league in assists (702, 8.6 a
game).
</P>
<P>
   And when he came to the Lakers for the 1968-69 season, he
subjugated his game even further in deference to West, Baylor and
Gail Goodrich. Defense became his forte; in the last two seasons of
his career, he was named to the league's all-defense team.
</P>
<P>
   As gawdy as his statistics were with Philadelphia and San
Francisco, his first four seasons with the Lakers might have been
his most rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, he lifted the Lakers to the finals against the Celtics,
only losing Game 7 by two points because Lakers coach Bill van
Breda Kolff inexplicably kept Chamberlain on the bench down the
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The 1970 season is remembered for Willis Reed's Game 7 miracle
in the Knicks finals win over the Lakers. What's forgotten is that
Chamberlain missed all but 12 games of the regular season with a
knee ligament injury, and he was not at top shape during the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, Chamberlain personally carried the Lakers to the NBA
finals when injuries sidelined West and Baylor for the playoffs. In
the finals, Milwaukee and a young center named Kareem Abdul-Jabbar
beat Wilt and the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1972, Chamberlain and the Lakers had the greatest season
in NBA history a 69-13 record, the best in league history (since
broken by Michael Jordan's 1996 Bulls at 72-10); a 33-game winning
streak that still stands as the longest winning streak in pro
sports; revenge against Kareem's Bucks in the Western Conference
finals; and a NBA title in five games over the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain still holds more than a dozen Laker records. Most
notably, he had 30 or more rebounds in 14 games with the Lakers.
Kareem Abdul-Jabbar had 30 or more rebounds just twice. Shaquille
O'Neal is still looking for his first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 0139EDT &QL; 
