<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-100POINTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NIGHT HE HIT 100
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There are no television highlights to look at, and
only 4,000 fans were said to have been in the arena that night 37
years ago when Wilt Chamberlain scored 100 points in one game.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain, who died Tuesday of an apparent heart attack at 63,
was playing for the Philadelphia Warriors. The date was March 2,
1962. The opponent was the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, the single most dominant performance in basketball
history didn't take place in either city.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it happened in Hershey, Pa., home of the famous
chocolate bar and an overwhelmingly Amish area.
</P>
<P>
   Given the lack of coverage, the unlikely site, and the fact
that, to this day, there are disputes over how Chamberlain scored
the basket to give him 100 points, some people consider it all a
hoax.
</P>
<P>
   That's how unbelievable Chamberlain's 100-point game was.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people don't know,'' Chamberlain said in 1997, ``is that
for the six or seven games right before the 100-point game, I was
averaging over 70 points. Some people said it was inevitable that
I'd score 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain averaged 50.4 points that year, and more than 25
rebounds while averaging 48.5 minutes per game. He played all but
eight minutes of every game the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   ``During that time he was just that much better than everybody
else,'' said Cleve Buckner, a rookie forward with the Knicks that
year. Buckner, 61, is a former basketball coach at Blair High in
Pasadena. ``The whole league knew he was going to score that (many
points) some night.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain thought he scored the final basket on a dunk.
Darrall Imhoff, who was guarding him, says it was on a finger roll.
</P>
<P>
   Some players remembered the game ending moments after
Chamberlain scored the last basket, when fans stormed the court
with about 50 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, recalled Imoff. Joe Rulick came in for Wilt and
finished the game.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Chamberlain tried an arcade shooting game
and beat the record score on the machine by almost 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps that was an omen,'' Chamberlain said.
</P>
<P>
   It helped that New York was without starting center Phil Jordan,
who was ill. In his place was the 6-10, 225-pound Imhoff, who was
20 pounds heavier than Jordan but still much smaller than the 7-1,
275-pound Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain had 23 points in the first quarter, and was 9 of 9
from the free-throw line. His career free-throw percentage was 51.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all mental,'' Chamberlain said. ``Free throws were the
most embarrassing and frustrating part of my career. In practice
I'd make them, in the game....''
</P>
<P>
   By the half, Chamberlain had 41 points, which was normal for him
that season. At that point, he was 13 of 14 from the line.
</P>
<P>
   The league-scoring record at the time was 78 _ held by
Chamberlain from earlier that season _ but that was in a triple
overtime game against the Lakers. Chamberlain also had the
regulation mark, 73, set two months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the third quarter in Hershey, Chamberlain had 69,
including 21 of 22 from the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   ``After he got it going, and they were feeding him, you knew is
was going to be hard to stop him,'' Buckner said. ``We were doing
everything _ double-teaming, triple-teaming, five men on him. He
was just hot that night, he made everything. That game he made all
his free throws. He only missed four.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckner also enjoyed a big night, scoring 33 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those nights,'' Buckner said. ``Bad night
to pick for my high game.''
</P>
<P>
   Not if you were Wilt Chamberlain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
