<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5112 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     10-13 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ Through early May, he was more bowwow than his normal
wow. Through early May, Greg Maddux deserved to answer to
``Doggie.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suddenly, the best pitcher of the decade was all bark and no
bite.
</P>
<P>
   People blamed, or credited, the umpires. They said Maddux
finally was being made to throw the ball over the plate for strikes
to be called. Given how he always had ``shaded'' the corners, or at
least been given the benefit of the doubt regarding same, it was
feared in Atlanta the Maddux magic had been exposed. The master
illusionist, whose 88-mph fastball could tie a batter in knots, was
a mortal after all.
</P>
<P>
   On May 4, when the Cardinals hammered him for a worst-ever eight
earned runs, his ERA was well above 5.00 and his opponents' batting
average surpassed .350, unprecedented in the '90s. Everybody here
was worried sick. He had to be hurt _ or washed up.
</P>
<P>
   He issued denials on both counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's execution,'' he said. ``That's it, nothing else. I'm just
getting hit. I'm making 20 mistakes a game, instead of 10 to 15.
But I feel fine. Really.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux persevered. His reservoir of confidence gave him more
resilience than ordinary arms possess. Although the umps stayed
tough on him, keeping the strike zone straight and narrow, he
adapted.
</P>
<P>
   By season's end, he had won 19 games and his ERA was down to
3.57, a more-than-respectable number for 99 percent of the pitchers
in the majors today. He wouldn't beat the Astros in the Division
Series opener last week, but seven subsequent days of rest _ he
pitched to one additional Astros batter, walking Craig Biggio, in
relief in Game 3 _ left Maddux ready for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Who, it seems, weren't quite ready for Maddux despite having
rocked him pretty good in their most recent encounter.
</P>
<P>
   This was only the Mets' fifth playoff game of the '90s. It was
his 20th. Different season, October.
</P>
<P>
   The Greg Maddux who gave up but five hits and one run over seven
throwback innings Tuesday night was pretty darn close to the same
Greg Maddux who went 126-49 with a 2.05 ERA over 1,636 innings from
late in the 1991 season through mid-August last year, a
historically remarkable span that included his winning an
unprecedented four Cy Young Awards successively.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux's mastery of the Mets, easily the most significant aspect
of Atlanta's 4-2 National League Championship Series-opening
victory, was a beautiful thing to observe. Unless you were a Met.
He left the Amazins amazed.
</P>
<P>
   A pity so many Atlantans missed it. The paid gate of 44,172 was
about 6,000 shy of a sellout. Maddux and his teammates clearly have
spoiled the locals by making the NLCS a virtual extension of their
regular season since '91. Why fork over $45 for the ``cheap''
seats, which were $11 for the first round, when the Braves go this
far every year?
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, that's why. Wouldn't you pay $45 to watch Monet or
Picasso paint? Genius is always worth the price of admission.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't own all those trophies because he's lucky,'' Mets
manager Bobby Valentine said. ``He made good pitches when he had
to. He did a good job, a very good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Among modern pitchers, only lefthander Sandy Koufax owns
statistics that arguably surpass Maddux's. Among righthanders, it's
universally agreed you have to go back to the early part of the
century, to Walter Johnson, to find an equal. Maddux made himself
such an anomaly in our gopher-ball age that his travails in May _
he went 0-3 with a 6.10 ERA _ were downright shocking.
</P>
<P>
   He was roughed up for 10 or more hits in five consecutive starts
after not giving up that many even back-to-back over 351 outings.
His 37 runs allowed in his first nine starts were only two fewer
than he yielded in 28 starts in 1995, his fourth Cy Young season.
</P>
<P>
   He looked 33 going on 43. But then, just like that, he righted
himself. Buoyed by a stretch of 20 scoreless innings in late June
through early July, he finished by going 14-5 with a 2.86 ERA.
Still, his 258 hits allowed were the most of his 13-year career and
marked the first time he has given up more than one per inning
since 1990, when he called Wrigley Field home.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux has nothing left to prove, but he might feel the need to
prove it anyway. His oft-desultory performances in the NLCS (3-6,
3.96 before Tuesday) never have measured up to his remarkable
regular-season successes, but he appears to be nicely on track to
change that.
</P>
<P>
   Although, honestly, he hopes his next start will come in the
World Series, where he has posted a 1.99 ERA. Now, because of him,
the Braves find themselves one-fourth of the way there after a
disappointing two-year absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maddux really had a great night,'' his skipper, Bobby Cox,
said. ``If Chipper (Jones) doesn't bobble the ball (in the fourth)
when (Mike) Piazza broke his bat on that ground ball, he doesn't
give up any runs. It's always good to get the first game.''
</P>
<P>
   Doggie got it, all right. The canine has his canines back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
