<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5118 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-NLCS-HNS &LR;      10-13 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ It was a fairly telling sign when he retired the first
six batters he faced. The fact he was massaging the corners of the
plate with ease was another tip-off. But when he blindly stabbed a
hard-hit liner up the middle, it was pretty clear.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was Greg Maddux's night, and there wasn't much the New York
Mets could do about it.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux pitched seven strong innings and made contributions in
the field and at the plate to lead the Atlanta Braves to a 4-2
victory in Game 1 of the National League Championship Series on
Tuesday night at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have all of those trophies because he's lucky,''
Mets manager Bobby Valentine said of the Braves' four-time Cy Young
Award winner. ``He's a terrific pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux allowed only six baserunners, made a few nice plays in
the field and perfectly executed a sacrifice bunt that led to a
run. The Mets finished with just six hits in the game _ five off
Maddux, who threw 65 percent of his pitches for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   It was a typical performance for Maddux, who is 3-1 with a 1.18
ERA in the first game of playoff series during his career.
Lefthanded reliever Mike Remlinger pitched two-thirds of a
scoreless inning, and closer John Rocker finished the game,
notching his second save of the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams spent the days leading to Tuesday trying to downplay
how the Braves manhandled the Mets during the regular season,
winning nine of 12 games. Obviously, it's not a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who haven't reached the World Series since 1996,
have history on their side. The Game 1 winner of the NLCS has
advanced to the World Series 19 out of 29 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, the Padres won the first game last year, and
they won (the NLCS),'' Braves catcher Eddie Perez said. ``Two years
ago, the Marlins won the first game, and they won everything.
Winning the first game is important. We've got our best pitcher
going tomorrow, so we'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The best-of-seven series resumes this afternoon at 3:09 p.m.
Kevin Millwood, who pitched a one-hitter against the Astros in the
Division Series, will start for the Braves. Lefthander Kenny Rogers
gets the nod for New York.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons the Mets struggled to beat the Braves
during the regular season is because they couldn't contain Chipper
Jones. On Tuesday, they found their best option was simply to avoid
him. Jones walked three times, and his lineup protection _ Brian
Jordan and Ryan Klesko _ was a combined 0-for-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves dug a little deeper for their offense, all the way to
the seventh and eighth spots in their order, where Perez and Walt
Weiss did most of the damage. Leadoff hitter Gerald Williams also
proved to be a problem for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely trio combined for seven of the Braves' eight hits
and three of the four RBIs and runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   Mets starter Masato Yoshii pitched admirably for 4 innings, but
he was pitching on borrowed time after he sprained his left ankle
fielding a bunt in the fifth inning. Yoshii, who won his final five
decisions of the regular season, allowed two runs on five hits and
a pair of walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Yoshii) pitched his butt off,'' Valentine said. ``He made
super pitches and pitched out of jams. He was matching Greg inning
for inning.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did so often during the second half of the season,
Williams ignited the Braves' offense with a leadoff single in the
first. He stole second and scored on Bret Boone's base hit up the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to set an offensive rhythm for my
teammates,'' said Williams, who was 2-for-5 with an RBI and a run.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets tied the score in the fourth on Mike Piazza's
broken-bat groundout, which scored Edgardo Alfonzo from third. The
Braves took the lead for good on Williams' RBI single in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii faced three batters after injuring his ankle but
eventually was replaced by righthanded reliever Pat Mahomes, who
served up a solo homer to Perez in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hanging slider, and I hit it pretty good,'' said
Perez, who became the Braves' primary catcher after Javy Lopez's
season-ending injury. ``I hit it with the good part of the bat. I
knew it was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss' RBI single gave the Braves an insurance run in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a storybook night for Weiss,'' said Braves
manager Bobby Cox, who has managed in more League Championship
Series (nine) than any manager in major-league history. ``He only
played sporadically during the regular season, but he had a big
night tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, who lost his starting job when the Braves acquired Jose
Hernandez from the Cubs at the trading deadline, was a surprise
starter Tuesday. Asked if Weiss would be in the starting lineup
today, Cox said: ``I'll make out the lineup tomorrow; I'm not going
to make it out tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets didn't go down without a fight. Pinch hitter Todd
Pratt's RBI single tightened the score in the ninth, and the Mets
had the potential tying run at the plate with an out remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker won a hard-fought battle with light-hitting shortstop Rey
Ordonez, who ended the game with a ground ball to Jones.
Coincidentally, it was Jones' error that prolonged the inning for
Pratt's clutch single.
</P>
<P>
   ``We battled them to the last out,'' Valentine said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
