<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5128 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBA-ALCS-HNS &LR;      10-13 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ As baseball lore goes, the Boston Red Sox have
supposedly been cursed for the last 80 or so years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But they have a chance to bury the past, beginning tonight when
the Red Sox and Yankees resume their storied rivalry in Game 1 of
the American League Championship Series at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't have a better scenario to close out the
millennium than the Red Sox against the Yankees for the pennant,''
said New York's Jim Leyritz, who has also played for Boston during
his career.
</P>
<P>
   Boston hasn't won a World Series title since 1918. In 1920, the
Red Sox sold star pitcher/outfielder Babe Ruth _ who would only
turn out to be the greatest player ever _ to the Yankees for a
reported $100,000. Is there really a Curse of the Bambino? Well, 24
Yankees World Series titles later, the Red Sox are still reminded
of the mistake that has arguably left them baseball's most haunted
team.
</P>
<P>
   The most punishing occurrence of the last 15 years came in 1986.
The Red Sox shocked the Mets by winning the first two games of the
World Series at Shea Stadium and were one victory away from
clinching the title. But despite Boston's holding a two-run lead in
the 10th inning of Game 6, the Mets rallied and won when Mookie
Wilson poked a slow roller through the legs of Bill Buckner at
first base for an improbable 6-5 victory. The Mets won the seventh
and deciding game.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, the Yankees overcame a 14-game Red Sox lead in July and
forced a one-game playoff at Fenway Park for the AL East title.
Bucky Dent hit a three-run homer over the Green Monster in left
field to secure the victory for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no greater rivalry in the '70s,'' said Yankees bench
coach Don Zimmer, who once managed the Red Sox. ``Those players
hated each other. I don't think that's the feeling of today.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter that they are playing their most traditional rival for
the right to go to the World Series, the Red Sox are savoring what
has already been some surprising postseason success. Having reached
the playoffs as the AL wild-card team, Boston completed a stunning
turnaround Monday with a 12-8 victory over Cleveland, becoming the
fifth team ever to rally from an 0-2 deficit to win a best-of-five
series.
</P>
<P>
   Boston won the final three games of its Division Series with the
Indians by scores of 9-3, 23-7 and 12-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ought to be playing the Jets or somebody, the way they're
scoring,'' Yankees outfielder Paul O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   New York, however, is a clear favorite to win its third AL
pennant in four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a source of motivation to try to prove everybody wrong.
It is obvious we are an underdog,'' said Red Sox pitcher Kent
Mercker, who will start Game 1 of the ALCS against New York's
Orlando Hernandez. ``We were an underdog against Cleveland.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre doesn't think his club will need any
extra motivation as its biggest rivalry goes to the postseason
stage for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no speech that I could make that could get them
excited more than knowing they are going to Fenway Park and that
the Red Sox are coming here,'' Torre said. ``It has been a rivalry
back before me and before them. But I think even if they don't know
the ancient history that has these two clubs involved, I think they
have seen Bucky Dent's home run on that scoreboard more than they
wanted to, especially with my bench coach being the manager of the
Red Sox at the time. There is no question that you feel that this
is going to be something special.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
