<HEADLINE>
DAVIS, CALIF.: `THE WEIRDEST CENTER OF THE WORLD'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: California)   (This 775-word ``separate buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIS, CALIF. _ Things have been pretty weird around the city of
Davis ever since the local branch of the University of California
developed square tomatoes back in the 1980s. (The round ones, they
said, wasted too much space in the packing boxes).
</P>
<P>
   And lately, things have just been getting weirder. Owls have
been cited by police for noise pollution, while toads are lavished
with every kindness, notably being offered the benefits of a
custom-built tunnel to take them safely across the six-lane freeway
that cuts through the city.
</P>
<P>
   Late-night partying is frowned upon, even in student
neighborhoods; nightbirds are encouraged instead to look up into
the sky with the help of specially modified street lights that
prevent glare from interfering with the view of the stars.
</P>
<P>
   Smokers are looked down upon with a disdain usually reserved for
common criminals, while ruts and potholes are viewed by the mayor
as rather quaint. She has lobbied, so far unsuccessfully, for them
to go unrepaired to add texture to Davis's ``historic'' downtown.
</P>
<P>
   And that is not to mention some of the curious ideas still on
the drawing board. Like planting fruit trees along select downtown
streets so that the poor and the hungry would always have something
to eat. Or building a new police headquarters out of straw.
</P>
<P>
   A Midwestern newspaper once called Davis ``the weirdness center
of the world,'' but residents bristle somewhat at that definition.
Generally, the word they prefer is quirky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quirky'' is how the city is sold to students attending UC
Davis, one of the prime agricultural research centers in the world,
who might otherwise think twice about spending the prime of their
youth stuck in California's dusty Central Valley.
</P>
<P>
   But even ``quirky'' sounds too dismissive to the ears of Mayor
Julie Partansky, originator of many of the city's stranger
ordinances and bylaws, and a true believer in the values of
environmentalism, manageable growth and general wonder at the power
of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Davis should be known as a progressive, intellectual
and caring community,'' she told students at the start of the new
academic year last month. ``Does having a strong smoking ordinance
make us quirky? Does having a toad tunnel so that toads can live
make us quirky? I think it's thoughtful.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Partansky, who is 52, herself graduated from UC Davis in
1970 and never left. Having been active in Green Party politics,
she was elected to the city council in 1992 and immediately began
lobbying for her most celebrated achievement, the toad tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   It was completed a couple of years ago along with a hotel and
brew pub for the little creatures to look forward to once they have
crossed Interstate 80.
</P>
<P>
   The toads, it must be said, have not shown a great deal of
interest, and continue to get squished above ground at pretty much
the same rate as before. That's gratitude for you.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Councilwoman Partansky _ she became mayor just last
year _ continued her crusade to keep shopping malls and chain
stores out of Davis, along with skateboards and smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Even by California's draconian standards, Davis is tough on
tobacco, imposing a smoking ban both inside and within 20 feet of
shops, bars, restaurants and office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   But that is nothing compared with the city's attitude to noise.
Five years ago, a woman was fined for snoring too loudly and
disturbing her neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Other offenders have since included owners of barking dogs,
fraternity boys out on the town and, last month, the proprietors of
a tree house used by local owls for late-night hooting sessions.
</P>
<P>
   A ban on gas-powered leaf blowers is in the offing, as is
after-hours scratching on university blackboards.
</P>
<P>
   It's not all thou-shalt-nots, however. Davis has commissioned
some funky sculpture, including a pair of joggers sitting in front
of the police station, and a man with eyes in his buttocks who
greets customers at an ice-cream parlor.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is justly proud of its broad array of cafes, cheap
eateries, bookshops and offbeat curiosity shops, which beat just
about anything else in the Central Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Partansky has also encouraged skaters and cyclists,
introducing special traffic lights for two-wheelers that clear the
roadways and effectively put them on an equal footing with cars.
</P>
<P>
   For her next trick, she has come up with a very British idea.
</P>
<P>
   Believing the U.S. system of four-way stop signs to be confusing
and dangerous, she wants to be the first person to introduce the
New World to the wonderful world of roundabouts. Now that's quirky
for you. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 775-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
