<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PELOSI-WHIP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 REP. PELOSI AIMS TO BECOME TOP WOMAN IN THE HOUSE  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Convinced that Democrats are on the verge of
winning control of the House of Representatives, San Francisco Rep.
Nancy Pelosi is aggressively pursuing a post that would make her
the most powerful woman in the history of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi, who has represented San Francisco since 1987, has her
sights set on the job of majority whip, the third-highest post in
the House after speaker and majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, Pelosi will reach a leadership level never before
attained by a woman in Congress and will be on a trajectory that
many believe could someday lead to being speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come. The opportunity is there,'' Pelosi said
during an hourlong conversation in her Capitol Hill office. ``I
have been a slugger and a fighter and an advocate. ... Being in
leadership strengthens your hand in every issue you are involved
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi has been a party stalwart since 1977, when she was
Northern California chair of the state Democratic Party. As a
member of the House, she has championed causes ranging from
increasing AIDS funds and human rights in China to turning the
Presidio from an Army base into a national park.
</P>
<P>
   In scores of dinners, conversations and written exchanges over
the past few months, the 59-year-old Baltimore native has made a
vigorous appeal to her Democratic colleagues, touting her decades
of service to the party, her fund-raising prowess and her belief
that California must be represented at the highest levels.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats traditionally choose their leaders in the weeks
following the general election. Two other Democrats _ Steny Hoyer,
D-Md., and John Lewis, D-Ga. _ have indicated their intention to
seek the post. With election day still more than a year away,
Pelosi's aggressive campaign has prompted complaints that internal
fighting among Democrats might distract them from their larger goal
of retaking the House.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the early campaign seems to be paying dividends
for Pelosi _ apparently freezing the field at three and propelling
her to the head of the pack. So far, Pelosi said she has spoken to
about two-thirds of the 211 Democrats in the Congress. Although she
would not disclose how many had  &LR; promised to support her, she was
extraordinarily upbeat about her chances of winning, a view
supported by numerous independent observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anyone would agree that I am far and away the
front-runner,'' Pelosi said. ``If the vote were taken today for
whip, I would win.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi's political roots run deep. Her father, Thomas
D'Alesandro Jr., was a House member for the first six years of her
life, representing the city of Baltimore, where he would later
become mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Although her voting record places her on the party's liberal
edge, she has spent considerable time helping Democrats of all
political stripes raise money and win elections. In the last
campaign, Pelosi distributed more than $300,000 _ mostly raised in
the Bay Area _ to help fellow Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Northern California has been without a voice in the House
leadership since last year's retirement of Rep. Vic Fazio,
D-Sacramento, who served as chairman of the democratic caucus, the
party's No. 4 post. In 1976, San Francisco Rep. Phil Burton came
within a vote of becoming House Majority Leader, but was topped by
Texas' Jim Wright, who went on to become speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi's push is contingent on Democrats winning a majority of
the House in the 2000 election. Were that to happen, Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., would likely be elected speaker,
Minority Whip David Bonior, D-Mich., would presumedly move up to
majority leader, and the position of whip would be up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   To boost the chance that Democrats regain control of the House,
Pelosi has created a new political action committee she calls ``PAC
to the Future,'' which will distribute money in key races next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The whip's official duty is to count and deliver votes, the name
drawn from the image of using a whip to keep members in line. Over
the years, the position has evolved into a high profile platform,
used as a bully pulpit by occupants ranging from Newt Gingrich, the
retired Georgia Republican, to Tom DeLay, R-Texas, who currently
occupies the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a tremendously powerful position,'' said Jack Pitney, a
professor of government at the Claremont McKenna School of
Government in Los Angeles, and the author of several books on
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Pitney said it would be a ``a great advantage'' for her San
Francisco constituents. ``A member can use it as leverage. Nobody
will ignore her phone calls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My voice would be amplified,'' Pelosi quickly acknowledges.
``You are more than a member. Anything you are interested in
becomes more important. Anything you say is important. ... You help
establish the priorities for the caucus. Your hand is greatly
strengthened.''
</P>
<P>
   Leadership posts are so limited that openings are typically the
subject of intense power struggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take the opportunity when it opens,'' Pitney said.
``The stars align just right only once in many years.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi's pitch begins with lending a geographical balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is, in my view, almost unthinkable that California would
not have somebody in top leadership of the Congress,'' said Pelosi,
who said she never considered the move until Fazio retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go home (to California) every week, and I come back here and
it's like going into a time warp,'' Pelosi said. ``We're pioneers.
It's that whole entrepreneurial spirit that is needed (in
Washington).''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said she is not pushing her status as the only woman in
the race, but she hears a lot about it from people around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a real asset to say to people in our country,
whether they are men or women, that when the Democrats win, a woman
will be one of the top leaders of the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of Pelosi's competitors has his own niche.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who represents Atlanta, is a civil rights legend, bearing
scars from beatings he suffered during protests including the famed
march alongside Martin Luther King, Jr., from Selma to Montgomery
in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   His voting record, like Pelosi's, is among the most liberal in
the House. Lewis touts his long record of social activism, his
impeccable reputation for integrity, his good relations with
liberals and conservatives alike, and the need for a minority face
among the party's leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leadership should be a reflection of the makeup and the
Democratic Party and the country,'' Lewis said in an interview.
``Right now, the ... leadership is all white.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoyer, whose Maryland district stretches from the Washington
suburbs to Chesapeake Bay, served as chairman of the Democratic
Caucus _ the House's fourth-highest position _ and has long been
regarded as a rising star within the party. Hoyer was defeated by
Bonior in a race for whip in 1991. Hoyer's voting record is not as
liberal as Pelosi or Lewis, making him more appealing to some of
the party's more conservative members.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever prevails will immediately be thought of as a potential
future speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you are whip, you have a clear shot at being
speaker,'' said Rep. Bob Matsui, D-Sacramento, who along with most
of the 28 Democrats from the state is in Pelosi's camp.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said she would never challenge Gephardt or Bonior, for
whom she has ``complete respect.''
</P>
<P>
   But were an opening for speaker available down the road, Pelosi
sees no reason to impose limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't rule it out,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
