<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VEGETARIAN NEW YEAR'S?
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Surf 'n' turf meets Y2K.
<P>
   As you prepare for the new millennium, fellow survivalists,
along with flashlights and water and ammo, better stock up on filet
mignon and lobster.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, the wholesale price-per-pound of filet mignon
has jumped from $7 to $11.40, and Australian lobster tail has leapt
from $18.50 to $30. Leapin' lobsters!
</P>
<P>
   The leading theory: Giant Las Vegas casinos and many large
hotels are stockpiling the best eats for their Millennium New
Year's high-roller megabashes, driving filet mignon and lobster
prices up.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to blame them. Let's say you're signed on for the Mark
Hopkins Hotel's top New Year's package _ $16,100 for three nights
in a Garden Suite. You're probably expecting more than a Happy Meal
and fish stix.
</P>
<P>
   The rising prices probably aren't due to a shortage of cattle,
since other meat prices aren't skyrocketing. But there are only two
filets per animal and apparently they're being squirreled away in
hotel freezers for the big event.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, many restaurants are either raising prices or taking
lobster and filet mignon off their menus.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, some places refuse to be cowed, so to speak. At
John's Grill in San Francisco, the menu is set and they won't drop
the top stuff or jack up the prices.
</P>
<P>
   You get new-millennium meat at old-millennium prices.
</P>
<P>
   USE A HAMMOCK, go to jail?
</P>
<P>
   That almost became the law in Richmond last night, when the City
Council met to consider adopting the most sweeping anti-homeless
law in the Bay Area. In the face of strong arguments from homeless
advocates, the council tabled the issue for further study.
</P>
<P>
   It's called a no-camping ordinance, but it's not aimed at Boy
Scouts. The proposed law says that from 10 p.m. to 6:30 a.m., you
can't sleep in cars or motorhomes, or under overpasses.
</P>
<P>
   Also illegal: Sleeping overnight in a hammock. Apparently the
City Council wants to protect citizens from the danger of falling
coconuts.
</P>
<P>
   It's OK to be homeless in Richmond, as long as you don't sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond is the city that turned down the free use of a large
building as a temporary homeless shelter because (one reason) it
didn't meet city seismic building codes, although the city doesn't
have seismic building codes.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed ordinance, which calls for jail time or fines of up
to $2,000, is backed by Richmond Mayor Rosemary Corbin. So
naturally opponents of the measure are calling it Rosemary's Baby.
</P>
<P>
   HOW BADLY do you want tickets for Opening Day of the Giants' new
ballpark next April?
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' ticket people tell me the demand is huge, and some
fans are already phoning with personal pleas. One man has a family
history of dads taking sons to Giants' openers at the Polo Grounds,
Seals Stadium and Candlestick and wants to keep the tradition
alive.
</P>
<P>
   So far, no dying-wish-type requests, but it's early.
</P>
<P>
   Tom McDonald, head of ticket sales, says the Giants could
probably sell out 41,000-seat Pac Bell Park four times for opening
day, and wouldn't that be comfy? All 81 home games might be
sellouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants aren't soliciting hardship stories for Opening Day
tix, and if you do have a heart-rending plea to lay on 'em, be
aware that they've heard a lot and the bar is high.
</P>
<P>
   NATURE NEWZ: It has been reported here that birds around the Bay
Area are learning to mimic the sounds of car alarms and cell
phones. Well, the birds continue to assimilate themselves into
modern civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday a crowd of people gathered on Treasure Island to watch
the Blue Angels fly. During the program, a squadron of about 100
ducks appeared in the sky above the island, honking up a storm and
performing, for three or four minutes, a series of precision flying
stunts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cheered 'em,'' says Jan Faulkner.
</P>
<P>
   P-P-PLAY B-B-BALL: Game 7 of the World Series, if it's needed,
is scheduled for Halloween. If there's a rainout, we could be
watching baseball into November.
</P>
<P>
   Boys of Summer, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   CELL-U-LITES, the users of cell phones, aren't necessarily bad
people, despite what you may have read in this column.
</P>
<P>
   But can they control their habit, or do they need help? Mark
McGuire in Redwood City says he's noticing a lot of Peninsula cops
cruising in patrol cars, yakking on cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are the police radio systems so archaic that they have to use
cell phones?'' McGuire wonders. ``Are they calling their brokers?
Are they bored?''
</P>
<P>
   This could be one of the more visible manifestations of a
growing problem: Employees cell-phoning on company time. I saw a
garbage-truck driver the other day, parked, talking on a cell. On a
legit break, maybe. But maybe talking trash when he's supposed to
be collecting it.
</P>
<P>
   A small San Francisco ad agency named Red Ball Tiger has fired a
volley in the cell wars. Cell phone use is prohibited on company
grounds by any agency employee or visitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has just gotten out of hand,'' says Greg Wilson, agency
founder.
</P>
<P>
   The rule at Red Ball: Check your phone at the front door. In a
pinch, employees and clients are allowed to step outside for a cell
break, so workers inside are not exposed to secondhand chit-chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule was tough at first on our clients,'' says managing
director Bob Ravaiso, ``but then an amazing thing started to
happen. You would see them relax and calm down as it would sink in
that they were no longer tethered to that damn phone. Meetings
became more productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Some try to sneak cell calls in the rest rooms, but if caught,
they face loss of vacation time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
