<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5266 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-TECH-EUROPE-$ADV17-CO     10-13 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-EUROPE-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EUROPEAN TECH SECTOR VIBRANT, BUT HAMPERED BY HABIT AND RULES
 &HT;    720&AMP;add. Moving in (i) international and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, Oct. 17.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUNICH, Germany _ In the 45 years since Allied bombers and
Soviet artillery flattened its sprawling Berlin complex, Siemens AG
has emerged as a global electronics powerhouse, behind only General
Electric and IBM in overall revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Siemens and Finland's Nokia, the high-tech sector of the
European economy is showing that is ready to compete with _ and in
some cases surpass _ its American rivals. But analysts say the
surge is being held back by excessive regulation, chronic high
unemployment and reluctance to abandon outdated business practices.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens executives have aggressively courted customers abroad,
to the point that 70 per cent of its business is international. The
company's stock has doubled in value since last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 152 years in business, we're in the process of
drastically changing our corporate culture,'' said Karl-Hermann
Baumann, who chairs Siemens' supervisory board. ``We're becoming a
lot less bureaucratic and a lot more entrepreneurial. And we're
focusing our core business increasingly on information and
communications technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Often powered by Siemens switches, Europe's 320 million people
are fast being wired up for the next millennium. Nearly a dozen
firms are laying fiber-optic networks from the Atlantic to the
Urals to offer a broader communications backbone for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   These new networks have already had an impact on the European
market. The cost of a 10-year lease on a jumbo 155-megabit data
circuit between London and Paris has fallen from $12 million two
years ago to $2 million today.
</P>
<P>
   The new competitive wave has led in turn to declining
long-distance charges. In Germany, they have fallen to less than 10
cents a minute, comparable to the prevailing rates in the United
States. Wired customers are increasingly using price rankings
posted on the Internet to find the cheapest providers. And TV sets
in German hotel rooms now widely offer metered Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans are 10 years behind us in mobile technology,''
declared Erkki Liikanen(cq), the commissioner of the 15-nation
European Union (EU) who is responsible for competitiveness,
innovation and the information society.
</P>
<P>
   However, Liikanen, a Finn, acknowledged in an interview at the
EU's Brussels headquarters that ``we're behind in software and on
the Internet because our entrepreneurial environment is much more
restricted and our capacity to create small enterprises is more
limited.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, he said, it takes 11 weeks in Europe for a start-up
firm, where much of high-tech growth is occurring, to open its
doors for business, compared with a week and a half in North
America.
</P>
<P>
   The mixed picture drawn by Liikanen's analysis is borne out in a
recent market survey of more than 2,000 top European companies and
500 local government units commissioned by Cisco Systems Inc., the
computer network equipment maker, and Oracle Corp. Both U.S. firms
are both striving to expand their European sales.
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ In contrast to the U.S. scene, fully two-fifths of top
European companies do not believe it will be necessary for them to
do business over the Internet within the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some 55 percent of their key employees lack access to E-mail,
and 60 percent do not have access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than 30 percent of top-level executives have never had a
technology briefing at their companies, and nearly 30 percent say
they never intend to have one.
</P>
<P>
   Britain and the Scandinavian lands were among the most advanced
in adapting to the Internet, with Germany also doing well, while
France, Belgium and Italy were behind. Italian firms, however,
showed the fastest growth of the 10 nations in the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the advantages of a single market _ and, for 11 EU
members, a single currency _ e-commerce across European frontiers
still lags well behind the U.S. pace. One reason is that most
European telecommunications firms charge their customers by the
minute, thereby cutting incentives for leisurely Internet trolling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're missing a wonderful opportunity to make the single
market a reality,'' said Diana Wallis, a British member of the
European Parliament. ``Things are not moving fast enough.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite America' pre-eminence in much of the high-tech world,
Europe appears primed to retain its lead in mobile phone systems
for many years to come.
</P>
<P>
   A critical reason: In the early 1980s, the EU set a common
standard for all its members, known as the Global System for Mobile
Communications or GSM. Today, GSM is used in 118 countries, serving
more than 150 million subscribers, some 40 percent of all mobile
users. Notably absent from the consortium: The United States, which
still adheres to four different standards, including GSM, and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Finland's Nokia passed Motorola to emerge as the
world's biggest manufacturer of mobile phones, producing 41 million
of 163 million phones sold around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Finland became the first country to license third-wave
operators, who offer mobile subscribers an express connection to
the Internet as well as digital high-quality secure voice lines.
Germany, Britain, Austria and the Netherlands are also preparing to
award licenses. Even with their slower second-generation
Internet-capable phones, Europeans now transmit as many as one
billion brief data messages each month.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in Europe, unlike in North America, every mobile
number has a different area code from landline numbers, thereby
making it easier for people to know where their call is being
routed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all starting to come together,'' said Baumann, the
Siemens chairman, as he stowed his tiny company-made phone and
invited his guests to lunch. ``And one reason it's working is
because we're offering our people lifetime employability instead of
lifetime employment.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
