<HEADER>
A5278 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-SMART-GUNS-ART-NYTSF &LR;      10-13 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMART-GUNS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMART GUNS DON'T KILL KIDS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    THREE COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 By JOSEPH D'AGNESE  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   A handgun is remarkably simple to operate. You pick it up, point
it and squeeze the trigger. The gun does the rest of the job. The
hammer cocks and then crashes down on the firing pin, sparking a
tiny gunpowder explosion that expels the bullet from its cartridge.
</P>
<P>
   From a technological standpoint, the process is child's play.
That's the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Children frequently handle guns, with deadly results. According
to the National Safety Council, 220 kids under the age of 14 died
in 1997 as a result of playing with guns.
</P>
<P>
   For other kids, the game of point and shoot has become an outlet
for personal rage. Ever since the shooting massacre at Columbine
High in Littleton, Colo., last spring left 14 students and one
teacher dead, many national and state legislators have confronted
gunmakers with a challenge: In a safety-conscious culture rife with
air bags and childproof medicine bottles, why can't someone design
a gun that kids can't operate?
</P>
<P>
   Congress is pressuring manufacturers to create safer guns,
childproof guns _ smart guns that fire only when an authorized user
pulls the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine: A criminal grabs a cop's gun. A child finds Daddy's
weapon in the bedroom. Neither can shoot because they don't have
the specially designed ring, bracelet or pin that electronically or
magnetically unlocks the firearm.
</P>
<P>
   Another weapon, seemingly lifted from the works of Ian Fleming,
won't fire unless the microchip sensor recognizes the user's
fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   Such guns are not a futuristic fantasy. Make no mistake: The
technology is very much here and now and no more complicated than
popping open the garage door with a remote device.
</P>
<P>
   All engineers have to do is shrink the necessary circuitry to
fit into a gun _ and keep it working flawlessly. That's the tough
job.
</P>
<P>
   To understand why, consider dropping your cell phone or
electronic notebook out the window.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a laptop inside of your firearm,'' says
Jonathan Mossberg, vice president of 0.F. Mossberg &AMP; Sons, the
world's largest maker of pump-action shotguns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know firearms, there's an amazing amount of stresses
that go on when you pull a trigger,'' explains Mossberg, who is
developing a smart shotgun. ``It's like hitting something with a
sledgehammer every time you fire it.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the percussion, there's also smoke, heat and accumulated
residue of gun oil and gunpowder. Altogether, a gun is a most
inhospitable home for a silicon chip.
</P>
<P>
   But engineers are working around the problem. They're tucking
critical processors into insulated gun grips, away from the line of
fire.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of a semiautomatic pistol, that space normally
houses a magazine clip full of bullets. So the chips must be
miniaturized to fit under a gun grip's thin decorative plate _ and
still be cost-effective.
</P>
<P>
   As for power, one maker experimented with NiCad rechargeable
batteries but switched to 10-year lithiums, figuring customers
would balk charging their guns like electric shavers. No wonder one
engineer grumbles, ``Building a smart gun is a bitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer smart guns are probably still about two to four years
away _ plenty of time to work out the kinks.
</P>
<P>
   And there are a few. Though several companies are rumored to be
working on the project, only a handful have gone public with their
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Colt's Manufacturing Company of Connecticut, best known for the
Colt .45, has toiled for three years on a smart gun intended for
law enforcement, but not home use.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the foibles of making smart guns were on full display
when the company demonstrated its radio wristlet device. The weapon
jammed as a reporter looked on but subsequently fired a hundred
rounds flawlessly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not perfect yet,'' a company spokesman admits. ``When the
processors get hot, it doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   The folks who may be the first to rely on silicon to defend
their lives _ cops and other law enforcement workers _ are watching
all of these developments closely. But there is still plenty of
skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has really worked this out,'' says Magna-Trigger's Rick
Devoid, also a New Hampshire police officer and firearms
instructor. ``Nobody wants to rely on a battery. If a battery
fails, you're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Americans are accustomed to glitches in their everyday
electronics. When it comes to guns, however, inconsistent behavior
won't do; performance must be foolproof.
</P>
<P>
   An engineer shaping a gun of the future offers this disparity:
``If your computer doesn't let you log on, you're inconvenienced.
If your smart gun doesn't shoot when you need it, you're dead. If
it fires when it shouldn't, your child could be too.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Joseph D'Agnese is a regular contributor to Discover magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
