<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5314 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MINOR-COLUMN14-COX     10-13 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big Guy vs. Little Guy
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The highlight of the week came on a
Wednesday when my husband rushed, not strolled, in the front door
pronouncing. ``Honey, I found cereal!'' The 8-year-old and I danced
in the kitchen. Then we sat down to spread the last of the peanut
butter on the last of the Pepperidge Farm Toasting bread and pour
the last of the milk over our new breakfast cereal .
</P>
<P>
   Trix. Not my first choice, but I'll take it. At this point, I'll
take anything.
</P>
<P>
   I know. What kind of woman am I to give my family multicolored
fruit-shaped puffs for dinner? But _ hello out there! _ that is not
the point. The point is this:
</P>
<P>
   For one week, my family did not set foot in one nationally owned
corporate mega-chain conglomerate superstore. No Eckerds. No Home
Depot. No Texaco gas.
</P>
<P>
   Allow me to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   No Blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   No Hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   No Publix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?'' asked some guy I work with.
</P>
<P>
   Seven days later, I'm not so sure myself.
</P>
<P>
   The little guy. That's who Denny Grady likes to buy from. Grady
is director of the Chamber of Commerce of the Palm Beaches, and he
tries to shop at locally-owned stores. Not just to be politically
correct. That's part of it. It would be bad form to see your local
chamber guy dropping big bucks at the Big K. After all, what kind
of commerce is that promoting?
</P>
<P>
   But Grady likes the intimacy of the small stores. The clerks
know his name. If he wants his shirts folded, they'll fold them. If
he wants them on hangers, they'll do that, too. They smile. They
take his check without looking at his driver license. They trust
him.
</P>
<P>
   And he trusts them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll say, 'Dennis, you can always get it cheaper someplace
else, but I won't sell you anything bad. I'm going to take care of
you,' '' Grady says. And he likes that.
</P>
<P>
   That's what I wanted to experience for a week. Sure, the clerk
at Publix knows who I am. Sometimes. The guy at the gas station
smiles. Sometimes. But I wanted to buy from those whose blood,
sweat and tears make their business.
</P>
<P>
   According to David Morris, vice president of the Institute for
Local Self-Reliance in Minneapolis, the demise of small business is
scary. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   _ Community pharmacies have been closing their doors at a rate
of about 1,000 per year for the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1972, independent bookstores sold 58 percent of the
nation's books. Today, it's down to 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Almost 5 percent of the nation's retail spending belongs to
just one company: Sam Walton's Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   This gives me strength as the week progresses, and we run out of
paper towels, waffle fries, frozen chicken nuggets, Shredded Wheat
cereal, Goody barrettes and Clorox.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a small-town girl. When I was growing up, I bought my dolls
from Kurtz Five &AMP; Dime in Columbiana, Ohio. My dad bought his
cigarettes at Ryan's Newsstand, and my mom bought her Wedgwood blue
paint at Keller's Hardware. We got our ice-cream cones from Ray
Candle at the Dairy Queen and bought our Ford automobiles from John
Koch's dad. We supported local business, mainly because we had no
choice.
</P>
<P>
   But today, we've got choices. Lots of them.
</P>
<P>
   If I wanted to, I could get my eyeglasses, my insulin and my Red
Delicious apples from the very same store. I could put pool toys in
my shopping cart, then a New York Times bestseller and then my
meat. And I could do all this at 3 a.m. if I wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Oct. 4., my husband and I sat at the breakfast table
with our very shopping-savvy son to explain that for one week, we
would go only into stores owned by a local person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't go to Publix,'' I told him.
</P>
<P>
   He raised his eyebrows slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or Walgreens.''
</P>
<P>
   He ate another spoonful of Shredded Wheat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or Blockbuster, which means no Nintendo games.''
</P>
<P>
   He fainted on the floor in his best impression yet of a young
boy whose life has been ruined by his newspaper-columnist mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll just sleep all week and save my energy since we
won't have any food,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I told him that was fine but to be sure and dream about the
Little Guy.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, I realized I'd made a huge mistake.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't planned this right at all. I should have gone to some
place like Costco, the giant of mega-chain superstores, the night
before this started. I should have stocked up, because by Day Two
we needed apples, bread, milk, breakfast waffles and a birthday
card for Uncle Phil. Suddenly, I had an overwhelming urge to
surround myself in the white light of Bed, Bath &AMP; Beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, I needed new cotton sheets? No dice.
</P>
<P>
   I got out the Yellow Pages and looked under Grocers, an
interesting exercise in social responsibility. All the little
markets near me are on streets I wrote about when I covered crime
10 years ago. I threw my liberal leanings out the window and opted
for yuppie. Jerry and Joe's Marketplace in Palm Beach Gardens. Easy
to get to. And they sell fresh flowers, too.
</P>
<P>
   I spent $71.52 at Jerry and Joe's in 24 minutes. This is the
kind of place people flock to for star fruit, designer coffee and
strawberries off season. This is not the kind of place you buy
juice boxes, Oreo cookies and Ragu spaghetti sauce.
</P>
<P>
   I went crazy. After all, I'd been deprived of all buying
pleasure for practically 48 hours. I bought apples, milk, pasta,
spaghetti sauce. I bought fresh juice and good bread. I bought
bruschetta topping, and I'm not even sure why. Isn't bruschetta
simply stale bread?
</P>
<P>
   But there were some comfort items missing from my grocery bags,
which I lugged to my truck by myself. No mosquito coils. No frozen
waffles. No Popsicles. No Maybelline lipstick. No decent breakfast
cereal. And the milk is that stuff that's ultra-pasteurized. It
doesn't go bad until the year 2001 or thereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the best part. I paid $10.09 for a jar of spaghetti
sauce. That is not a typo. It's from Rao's, a famous restaurant in
New York City. ``It's pricey,'' owner Jerry Scalisi acknowledged.
``But it's good.''
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't know. I'm afraid to open the jar, let alone eat it.
What could be in it, for crying out loud? Streisand tickets for New
Year's Eve?
</P>
<P>
   We lasted seven days, but we were not total purists. We watched
cable television. We got our videos from a small store that isn't
owned by a corporation but is owned by some guy who lives out of
state. We bought our gas from a locally owned Chevron franchise. We
made a birthday card on the computer, but we used a Microsoft
program. You can't get any more Big Guy than that.
</P>
<P>
   But we went in little markets run by husbands and wives. We
ordered our takeout from the local pizzeria. We avoided 7-Eleven
and Blockbuster and Walgreens. We went for seven days without a
Nintendo 64 game. And, all the while, we taught a certain
8-year-old a valuable lesson: Trix cereal is really gross, even
when you wash it down with yuppie milk.
</P>
<P>
   Emily J. Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: emilyminor(AT)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
