<SLUG> BC-OHIO-GROUPHOME14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Couple plan to make farm refuge for the mentally ill
 &HT;    By Tom Beyerlein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROTWOOD, Ohio _ Margaret Gerkin has been an outspoken advocate
for the mentally ill since her son was diagnosed with paranoid
schizophrenia 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's taking her activism to another level: She and her
husband, Jim, have ``hocked everything we own'' to purchase an
1860s farmhouse on 40 acres, and plan to use it for a special kind
of group home for the severely mentally ill and handicapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just heaven,'' Gerkin, 68, said of the place she calls
St. Dymphna's Farm, named for the Catholic patron saint of the
mentally ill. ``It's not going to be so much group home as
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerkin said the farm, on Basore Road near Hara Arena, will
provide what many formerly institutionalized mental patients need
most: a ``controlled'' but ``comfortable and loving environment.''
She said the residents will be closely supervised by trained
workers and required to take any prescribed psychotropic
medication.
</P>
<P>
   She plans to set up a trust fund so the farm can continue its
work after the she and her husband die.
</P>
<P>
   Gerkin hopes to launch the project with two residents in
December and work up to the eight allowed in the existing
3,500-square-foot house, but envisions eventually adding buildings
and housing about 50. The Gerkins are still in the process of
getting a group home license from the state. Their Community
Educational Resources for the Mentally Retarded and the Mentally
Ill has already gotten non-profit status from the Internal Revenue
Service. They mortgaged their Trotwood home to help buy the
$240,000 farm.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Hibbs, a spokesman for the Ohio Department of Mental Health,
said Gerkin shouldn't have any problems with state approval, even
for an expanded 50-patient facility, as long as the farm meets
health standards and has adequate staff.
</P>
<P>
   Trotwood's zoning code requires Gerkin to get a conditional use
permit from the Board of Zoning Appeals, said planning and zoning
administrator Steve Olmsted. But he said he'll check with
Trotwood's law director to make sure the rule doesn't conflict with
anti-discrimination laws. ``We don't want to be too restrictive or
discriminate or do anything that wouldn't stand up to a
challenge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trotwood planning and zoning Director Michael Lucking said
neighbors of the farm probably aren't yet aware of Gerkin's plan,
but ``to be honest with you, I can't imagine they would be real
thrilled about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerkin said she'll plant trees as a buffer between the farm and
some adjacent homes, and the 40 acres will buffer the farm from
most of the nearby neighbors. ``We're not going to be in anybody's
face,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a very controlled situation,'' Gerkin
said. ``They're not going to be out wandering the streets, they're
not even going to be able to walk the grounds without supervision.
I hate to use the word 'control,' but at the same time, there has
to be control in just about everything in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents would be referred to the farm by Eastway and Places
Inc., local gatekeepers for mental health services. The Gerkins
hope their non-profit group will be able to tap federal sources for
funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some people, this (farm) is going to be a dream come true,
an ideal setting,'' said Joseph Szoke, executive director of the
local mental health board. ``It's one more piece of this mosaic (of
housing opportunities) we need to have. And, God love her, she's
doing it on her own with no federal help or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Miller, a board member of Advocates for the Mentally
Ill, said the Gerkins are taking on a task that should be the
responsibility of the Ohio Department of Mental Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's trying to do what the state should have done out at Twin
Valley (Psychiatric System, formerly Dayton Mental Health
Center),'' Miller said. ``She's really putting her entire financial
life on the line here, and I admire her greatly for it. There
aren't many people who would do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The state doesn't want to build an intermediate care facility at
Twin Valley, Hibbs said, because of state law and policies aimed at
moving patients from hospitals to the community.
</P>
<P>
   The Gerkins _ she's a homemaker and he's a retired liquor store
worker and jazz musician _ didn't know much about mental illness
until their son fell ill when he was 20, 13 years ago. He is their
only surviving child _ Gerkin had seven miscarriages, and an older
son, David, was stabbed to death on July 4, 1974.
</P>
<P>
   The surviving son has been in and out of hospitals and jail over
the years, and has been committed to the Dayton state mental
hospital since 1994, when he nearly ran over a mounted police
officer, then led police on a wild chase through downtown Dayton.
His mother said he's now stable and could be conditionally released
soon. After his release, he'll live on the farm.
</P>
<P>
   Gerkin hopes to hire experienced staff members who have been
laid off from the downsized state mental health department. She
plans to provide physical and psychological therapy, supervised
outings, and activities like swimming, arts and crafts, soccer,
softball and a pool table.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of them feel like they're not worth a whole lot,''
Gerkin said. ``I want to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Beyerlein writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
