<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's being widely reported that the world's population is now
6 billion. Can you give us some historical context for world
population growth?
</P>
<P>
   A: Statistics vary according to different sources, but World
Book Encyclopedia and World Almanac (1999) provide some insight. In
2000 B.C., the world's population was an estimated 108 million; in
1000 B.C., 120 million. In A.D. 1, it was an estimated 138 million
(World Book Encyclopedia) or 200 million (World Almanac). In A.D.
1000, it was 275 million. In 1650, 500 million (World Almanac) or
550 million (World Book). By 1850, it was 1 billion; 1930, 2
billion; 1975, 4 billion; 1998, 5.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   While growth has slowed from highs of nearly 100 million people
annually, the U.N. Foundation, which tracks statistics, says global
population continues to increase rapidly _ by 77 million a year, a
rate roughly equivalent to adding a city the size of San Francisco
every three days.
</P>
<P>
   As reported, the 6 billion figure can't be definitively pinned
down to an exact date, but U.N. experts picked Oct. 12, 1999,
because it falls halfway between their predicted dates based on
low-end and high-end population estimates. Other sources say the 6
billion figure was passed in June or July.
</P>
<P>
   Information about the United Nations Foundation's population
statistics can be found online at its Web site:
www.unfoundation.org/
</P>
<P>
   Q: We often hear about the best-selling rock album, the
best-selling country music album and so on. What is the
best-selling classical music album?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``The Three Tenors in Concert'' holds the title, according to
the Guinness Book of Records (1999). Recorded by Jose Carreras,
Placido Domingo and Luciano Pavarotti for the 1990 Soccer World Cup
finals, it has sold about 13 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Announcers on televised football games frequently use the
somewhat irreverent expression ``Hail Mary'' to describe a long
forward pass. How did this come about?
</P>
<P>
   A: Our resources don't identify the first person to use the
phrase, but they offer some information of interest. One of the
earliest times it appeared in print was in 1982, in Tim Considine's
book ``The Language of Sport.'' It defined a ``Hail Mary'' as a
low-percentage pass, one that would require a great deal of luck or
the intercession of a ``higher power'' for completion. In its Aug.
13, 1990, issue, Time magazine expressed it in a different, but
easily understandable, way: ``With time running out and 80 yards to
go . . . you throw the long one and pray.''
</P>
<P>
   The phrase is sometimes used in basketball games, too, to
describe the type of shot whose only chance to go in the basket is
accompanied by devout prayer. The expression also was used in a
very different context in a 1991 press briefing by Gen. Norman
Schwarzkopf, who compared a flanking maneuver in the Persian Gulf
War to the ``desperation (football) Hail Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Presidential pardons are back in the news with former
President Carter asking President Clinton to pardon Patty Hearst,
the kidnapped heiress, and Clinton pardoning some convicted Puerto
Rican terrorists. How does the pardon prodecure work? To whom does
one apply?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Office of the Pardon Attorney, the Justice Department
office responsible for processing pardon petitions on behalf of the
president, receives and reviews petitions for executive clemency,
initiates the necessary investigations, and recommends to the
president which form of executive clemency _ including pardon,
commutation of sentence, remission of fine, and reprieve _ it finds
appropriate in certain cases.
</P>
<P>
   A pardon petition is addressed to the president, but submitted
to the pardon attorney, said Chris Watney of the Justice
Department. Forms can be obtained from Office of the Pardon
Attorney, Justice Department, 4th Floor, 500 First St. NW,
Washington, DC 20530-0001) or from the wardens of any federal penal
institution. The forms explain what documentation is required.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently reported on Rock City Gardens, the tourist
attraction on Lookout Mountain near Chattanooga, Tenn., which says
seven states are visible from there. The claim about South
Carolina, Kentucky and Virginia seems highly suspect, even on the
clearest day, for a mountain that barely rises 2,000 feet above sea
level. Can you check on this again?
</P>
<P>
   A: Officials at See Rock City have backed away from the claim,
but they do offer an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question about the ability to see Tennessee, Georgia
and Alabama. North Carolina is only 50 miles away and the Smoky
Mountains ``are fairly easy to see,'' said Lydia Thompson,
spokeswoman for the attraction. South Carolina is 80 miles away and
Mount Pinnacle, on the Virginia-Kentucky border, is 120 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   But she added: ``We cannot prove that we can see these last
three states from Lover's Leap. The truth is, we don't really know
beyond a shadow of a doubt whether all seven can be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``See Seven States'' finds its roots in a journal
entry by a Union soldier during the Civil War, Thompson said. The
soldier wrote that when he and some fellow soldiers went to the top
of Lookout Mountain, they could see seven states. And thus the
slogan _ true or not _ was born.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I frequently read and hear references to Jane's Fighting
Ships, always cited as an authority on military vessels. Where does
the ``Jane'' come from?
</P>
<P>
   A: It comes from Fred T. Jane, founder of a company in England
that, since 1897, has been publishing books about ships in the
world's navies and about military and civilian aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There's been a lot in the news about a pay raise for people
in the military. Will retirees also get a raise?
</P>
<P>
   A: The ``99 percent answer'' for current, non-disabled military
retirees is that the legislation signed by President Clinton on
Tuesday will have no effect, said Defenfe Department spokesman Lt.
Col. Tom Begines. A ``handful'' of people with disability
retirements may get an increase, he added, but that would fall
under a system already in effect that involves increases pegged to
the Consumer Price Index. Such an increase is automatic and does
not require legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The $289 billion in defense spending authorized by the current
legislation is for fiscal 2000. The act includes a 4.8 percent pay
increase _ largest since 1981 _ for the 1.4 million men and women
in the military. Currently, starting pay for an enlisted recruit is
$889 a month, increased to $959 after four months.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In response to a question about President Carter having
awarded the Presidential Medal to Freedom to Roger Baldwin, founder
of the American Civil Liberties Union, Q&AMP;A listed the date of the
award as Jan. 16, 1981. I thought Carter was out of office by then.
Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: Carter's term ended Jan. 20, 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My brother was killed on the battleship St. Paul off the
coast of Korea in April 1952. Do you know if this ship is still in
service? If not, what happened to it?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was a cruiser, hull number CA 73 _ CA designating heavy
cruiser _ and not a battleship, said John Reilly of the Navy
Historical Center. Cruisers traditionally were named after cities.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Paul was involved in a series of bombardment and other
missions off Korea and suffered a powder explosion in its forward
turret on April 21, 1952, with about 30 people killed, Reilly said.
Your brother apparently was a victim of that accident. On Jan. 28,
1980, the St. Paul was sold for scrapping to the National Metal and
Steel Corp. of Terminal Island, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said you can find information about this particular
vessel, and many others, in the Dictionary of American Naval
Fighting Ships, a set of books published by the Navy Historical
Center. Most libraries have it, he said. Information about the St.
Paul can be found in volume 6. Information also can be found online
at www.uss-salem.org/danfs/cruisers/ and at www.history.navy.mil
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
