 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take two of 2 takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: The new state quarters have gotten lots of publicity. Are the
old eagle quarters still being produced?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. The U.S. Mint reports that the only quarters minted for
the next decade (1999-2008) will be the 50 state quarters. But the
eagle quarters obviously will continue to be in circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why does the Ku Klux Klan use crosses? Why are crosses
burned?
</P>
<P>
   A: A cross stands in every Klan den ``as a constant reminder
that Jesus Christ is our criterion of character and his teachings
our life blood, bought holy, sanctified and sublime,'' according to
the Klan Web page (www.kkk.com). It adds that the burning of a
cross is not an act of desecration, but is ``a symbol of truth,
light and obedience to God.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross-burning, of course, also is a means of intimidating ethnic
and racial minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many American survivors of the Bataan Death March are
still living?
</P>
<P>
   A: About 1,000 survivors are still alive, said Army Maj. Richard
Gordon (ret.), spokesman for a Bataan survivors organization.
However, he points out that no records were maintained on the
infamous march on the Bataan peninsula of western Luzon in the
Philippines, and no one knows for sure even who made it. It can
only be assumed from the units who were on Bataan at its fall,
Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   About 715 Americans died on the march, actually a series of
marches lasting from five to nine days after the surrender of the
Bataan defenders to the Japanese in April 1942. The distance a
captive had to march was determined by where on the trail the
captive began. The basic trail started with a 55-mile march from
Mariveles, Bataan, to San Fernando, Pangpanga. At San Fernando, the
prisoners were placed into train cars and were taken to Capas,
Tarlac, a distance of about 24 miles. Those who survived were
marched another 6 miles to their final destination, Camp O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   About 9,300 American prisoners reached O'Donnell, Gordon said.
There were just over 12,000 Americans on Bataan before its
surrender to Japanese forces.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Warren Buffett, listed by Forbes magazine as the
third-richest American with $31 billion, is about the same age as I
am. Can you trace his career for me? Did he ever serve in the
military?
</P>
<P>
   A: Buffett, who was born Aug. 30, 1930, in Omaha, Neb.,
developed his interest in making money at an early age. At 11, he
started playing the stock market with one of his two sisters.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't in the military. After graduating from the University
of Nebraska with a B.S. in 1950, and from Columbia University in
1951 with his M.B.A, Buffet worked as an investment salesman with
Buffett, Falk and Co., his father's investment firm in Omaha, from
1951-54, and he was a security analyst under Benjamin Graham _ a
pioneer in the ``value,'' as opposed to ``growth,'' approach to
portfolio management _ at the Graham-Newman Corp. in New York from
1954-56.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Buffett returned to Omaha and formed the Buffett
Partnership, an investment firm that he managed for 13 years. He
then turned his attention to building up Berkshire Hathaway, a
Massachusetts textile firm he had bought control of in 1965. By the
time the textile business failed and was closed in 1985, Buffett
had developed Berkshire Hathaway into a profitable holding company.
You know the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Airline passengers hear a message advising that, in an
emergency, oxygen masks would be released above the seats and
adults should put theirs on before putting one on a child. If only
one mask is provided per seat, what about an infant held by an
adult?
</P>
<P>
   A: On most aircraft there's an extra mask that would be released
for the use of someone with a ``lap child,'' or in case one of the
other masks wasn't functioning, said Kathleen Bergen, spokeswoman
for the Federal Aviation Administration. In a row of five seats,
for example, there would be six masks; in a row of three seats,
four masks; in a row of two seats, three masks. And as Delta
spokesman John Kennedy explained, airlines don't seat more than one
lap child in any row.
</P>
<P>
   Only infants younger than 2 can be a lap child, by the way.
Rules require that anyone 2 or older must be in a seat.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there some way I can track down a former Army buddy?
</P>
<P>
   A: Army Public Affairs says the Privacy Act of 1974 prohibits
releasing the last known address of former Army members without
their written consent. But there's a procedure you can follow that
will assist your search by forwarding your letter to the service
member's last known address.
</P>
<P>
   First, write your letter to your buddy. Place it in a sealed and
stamped envelope, with your full name and return address. Write a
second letter to the National Personnel Records Center requesting
its assistance. Include the service member's name, serial number
and/or Social Security number, and date of birth, if available.
Place both letters in one envelope and address it to: National
Personnel Records Center, 9700 Page Blvd., St. Louis, MO
63132-5200.
</P>
<P>
   If the record center cannot identify the service member, or if
the person is known to have died, your letter will be returned.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can fans send mail to Oprah Winfrey? She is such an
inspiration to so many of us.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write her in care of the Oprah Winfrey Show, Harpo
Productions, P.O. Box 909715, Chicago, IL 60607.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A fellow Toyota driver told me that our cars actually should
be called Toyodas, because that was the name of the man who founded
the car company. Can you confirm?
</P>
<P>
   A: Toyoda is the last name of the man who, in 1926, founded
Toyoda Automatic Loom Works in central Japan (his first name:
Sakichi). Before he died in 1930, Sakichi Toyoda sold the rights to
the loom he invented, and gave the proceeds, to his son, Kiichiro
Toyoda, to begin an auto business. It was the son who, after
splitting offthe car department from the loom works, took it
public in 1937 and changed its name to Toyota for clarity in spoken
Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some of us were wondering if ``Chipper'' is the real first
name of Atlanta Braves star Chipper Jones. Do you know?
</P>
<P>
   A: He was named Larry Wayne Jones Jr. when he was born on April
24, 1972, in DeLand, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some time ago, the newspaper reported on two boys, members of
an Indian tribe in Alaska, who held up a pizza delivery person. The
elders of the tribe exiled them to some remote islands. What was
the outcome?
</P>
<P>
   A: The case involved Simon Roberts and Adrian Guthrie, members
of the Tlingit tribe of southeastern Alaska. Convicted of robbing
and severely beating pizza deliveryman Tim Whittlesey in Everett,
Wash., in 1993, the two initially were permitted by Superior Court
Judge James Allendoerfer to participate in what tribal judges said
was ``traditional rehabilitation'': banishment to uninhabited
islands for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   But the experiment in cross-cultural justice wasn't entirely
successful. Because of problems supervising the youths, along with
unauthorized visits and infighting among members of their Tlingit
tribe, Allendoerfer stopped the experiment and sent the two to
prison: 55 months for Roberts, who struck Whittlesey with a
baseball bat, and 31 months for Guthrie. They also were ordered to
pay $43,000 in restitution.
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie was released in August 1996 and Roberts was released
last December. At last report, Whittlesey, the victim, remained
partially deaf and still was suffering from memory problems.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A reported recently on the difference between typhoons and
hurricanes. There was no mention of such storms occurring in the
South Atlantic or South Pacific oceans. Do they not have them?
</P>
<P>
   A: We've learned never to say ``never'' about anything, but it
would be abnormal if such storms occurred in the areas you mention.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Encyclopedia of Hurricanes, Typhoons and
Cyclones, hurricanes typically originate over the warm (84-86
degree) waters of the North Atlantic Ocean, including the Caribbean
Sea and Gulf of Mexico, and the eastern North Pacific Ocean (north
of the equator and east of the international date line).
</P>
<P>
   During the early part of the June-to-November season, hurricanes
form principally between latitudes 6 and 10 degrees north.
Late-season hurricanes primarily develop north of latitude 10
degrees north.
</P>
<P>
   (ENDIT.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
