<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5322 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-COOKING-CARDIOLOGIST1     10-13 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKING-CARDIOLOGIST14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cardiologist prescribes a diet low on fat but high in excitement
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ He's the only chef in America with a
whisk-o-scope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wear it to remind people that the fight against heart
disease starts in your kitchen,'' says Dr. Richard Collins, ``the
cooking cardiologist.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins came up with the idea of combining a kitchen whisk and
stethoscope and uses his homemade gadget in cooking lectures and
demonstrations. He comes to Dayton on Thursday on behalf of
Franciscan Medical Center's Cardiac Rehabilitation Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll try to show people how they can change recipes into
something heart-healthy,'' says Collins, 55, who directs the
Alegent Heart Disease Reversal and Wellness Program at Alegent
Health Heart Institute in Omaha, Neb. He is also author of a
cookbook, The Cooking Cardiologist (Advanced Research Press,
$21.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make my favorite breakfast pudding, show people how to
use tofu, saute without oil and I'll make a fabulous lemon cream
broulee,'' says Collins, who creates recipes designed to lower
cholesterol, reduce the risk of heart disease and control weight.
</P>
<P>
   Collins admits he was raised on Midwest staples of meat and
potatoes and didn't always enjoy spending time at the stove. That
all changed six years ago when he became involved with the Dean
Ornish heart program and its strict vegetarian diet. (``If it has a
mother, you can't eat it,'' he quips.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd had a number of patients with heart disease who were
running out of options,'' Collins says. ``One had had three bypass
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   To put himself in his patients' shoes, Collins decided to try
the Ornish diet and began experimenting in his kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost 15 pounds and I gained a lot of energy,'' he says. ``If
you have heart disease and want to stop it, it takes a major leap
(like the Ornish diet), and doing just a little bit doesn't help.
But as I started to work with the foods, I realized that if you
don't have heart disease, you don't have to give up everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food is an art,'' Collins says. ``Our problem in America is
that we don't love our food enough. We don't eat with awareness, we
just shove it in. If you look at Mediterranean people, they spend
more time with their food.''
</P>
<P>
   A low-fat vegetarian diet is one ingredient in a heart-healthy
lifestyle, says Collins. Others are exercise, stress reduction and
group support.
</P>
<P>
   That exercise, he adds, can be as simple as a brisk walk three
times a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept in America is that if one pill is good, two is
even better,'' Collins says. ``People think if they run another
mile they are going to live longer, but studies have shown moderate
exercise is sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that stress reduction is most important. The more you
practice stress management _ yoga, relaxation, meditation _ the
better your arteries get. The mind's control over the body is
pretty spectacular.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes cooking can be an excellent form of stress
reduction. ``When you put love and energy into food, it seems to
carry over to other people. Feeding one another is like loving one
another, it's about attachment, attention.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggests kids be involved in the cooking process, too. ``I
don't think we're teaching our children the nourishment they need
to know,'' Collins says. ``Start introducing different flavors and
textures.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Collins is most often in the kitchen with Donna, his
wife of 33 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's refreshing to have something different to eat and have
someone help you,'' she says, adding that her husband is a lot more
creative than she is.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really experiments in the kitchen, he makes good pasta
dishes and is very creative with tofu, which we'd never eaten
before. Our cooking is very spontaneous, never planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins says he finds creative ways to eat at restaurants, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Wendy's, I get the salad bar and make my own strawberry
vinaigrette salad dressing with vinegar, a dash of pepper, some
strawberries and onions,'' he says. ``I'll add salsa and broccoli
to a baked potato.''
</P>
<P>
   Dee Schrimpf, a dietitian who works with the Ornish program
locally, says she met Collins at the Ohio Dietetic Association's
statewide meeting in Dayton six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a wonderful repartee with the audience, a great sense
of humor and gives wonderful low-fat cooking tips,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Collins notes, however, that the cooking cardiologist has
one flaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't clean up,'' she confides. ``Guess who does that?''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith Moss writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: meredithmoss(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
