 Wednesday, Oct. 13, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6320.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BIONIC-LEG (Albany, N.Y.) _ Mike Tallman, 36, lost his right leg
in a motorcycle accident on a curvy Louisiana road. He is now the
first person in the United States to be fitted with a computerized
knee joint that can practically anticipate his every move.
Developed in Germany, the C-Leg relies on a microprocessor and
sensors to adjust to changes in Tallman's gait. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-SUPERINTENDENTS (San Francisco) _ Although women make up
nearly 80 percent of the nation's teachers, they account for just
10 percent of the superintendents leading public school systems _
virtually no improvement since the turn of the century. By JULIAN
GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   SF-HOMELESS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown,
facing a firestorm of criticism for a plan to seize shopping carts
from the homeless three weeks before a mayoral election, told his
staff to postpone the effort, but publicly denied such a plan
existed. By ILENE LELCHUK.
</P>
<P>
   QUAKE-ANNIVERSARY (San Francisco) _ Just last week, a worried
homeowner called Eliza Chan in the federal government's San
Francisco disaster office, to report a basement crack that the
caller susepect was caused by the Loma Prieta earthquake. Such
calls aren't uncommon, Chan said, even though it's been 10 years
since the 7.1 quake unleashed its lethal force on the Bay Area. By
CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEW-CAULFIELD (Undated) _ Conventional wisdom in TV Land
says the cop genre is dead. But Fox, which either loves to go
against the grain or just doesn't have much common sense, is
launching a new cop show called ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One.'' By
TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-HOTEL (Manitou Springs, Colo.) _ The Cliff House at
Pikes Peak reopened July 15 to great fanfare in the quaint town of
Manitou Springs, nestled against the Rocky Mountains near Colorado
Springs. With the theme ``Luxury Becomes a Landmark,'' the hotel
hopes to attract the same clientele that frequents the Broadmoor in
Denver _ on a far smaller scale. By JULIE COOPER. (Photo available
on the Wieck database.)
</P>
<P>
   CONCORDE (Undated) _ Except for a handful of astronauts and
military pilots, we Concorde passengers are flying higher and
faster than any other humans in history. We are literally moving
faster than a speeding bullet. By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-RATTO-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ ``Bigger than life'' means
whatever the user of the phrase wants it to mean. For me, it was
Wilt Chamberlain. His passing Tuesday of what is being called a
heart attack caught most people unprepared because he seemed too
big to die. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
