<P>
   1. THE BIZARRE WORLD OF MATTHEW BARNEY When Matthew Barney came
onto the world art scene in 1991 with his surreal sculptures and
videos, he was instantly successful. Since then, his work has only
got better and stranger. He has mostly been making a series of
increasingly elaborate films, called ``Cremaster.'' Now 32, Barney
is the most important American artist of his generation. By Michael
Kimmelman. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (5,100
words) + edited article available.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
NEW JAMES BOND FILM -- ``THE WORLD IS NOT ENOUGH'' + PHOTOS Iain
Johnstone was the only journalist invited to be on the set and
locations for the duration of the shooting of the latest James Bond
film ``The World Is Not Enough.'' Here are 3 intriguing articles
with the inside story. (Not available in the U.K.)
</P>
<P>
   (a) PIERCE BROSNAN Profile of Pierce Brosnan, who plays secret
agent 007 in the new (19th) James Bond film ``The World Is Not
Enough.'' Iain Johnstone talked to Brosnan and watched him at work
for six months. He explains why this actor has become the most
successful of the five men to play Bond. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   (b) THE BOND GIRLS Bond Girls have been an integral part of the
series since Ursula Andress strolled out of the sea in her white
bikini in 1962. Beauty is adroitly combined with brains in the new
Bond film which features six actresses : Sophie Marceau, Judi
Dench, Denise Richards, Samantha Bond, Serena Scott Thomas and
Maria Grazia Cucinotta. Their nationalities range from English to
French to Italian to American and their ages from 27 to 64. 2,000
words.
</P>
<P>
   (c) Q'S FIRST FAREWELL PERFORMANCE The latest James Bond film
could well be the last one to feature Desmond Llewelyn as 'Q,'' the
``gadget wizard.'' He is the longest serving Bond actor, in 17 out
of the 19 films in the series and first appeared in 'From Russia
With Love,' 36 years ago. Now 85, Llewelyn is a little over the age
for service in MI6, but popular demand has kept him in the job.
John Cleese was recruited to play his assistant in the new film.
2,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   3. PIANO MANIAC ``I am an excellent pianist,'' writes Irving
Wardle. ``The only snag is that I don't play very well. The answer
is to practice every day .... once I've salvaged the wreck of my
adolescent technique, I may yet find employment at a white baby
grand in a piano bar.'' Being a 65-year-old piano student made him
feel like a freak, but he signed up anyway for a piano summer
school in France. From Prospect Magazine. 1,500 words. (N/A U.K.)
Irving Wardle is a former theatre critic.
