<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Online computer shopping rated
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As we ease into another holiday season, the analysts
are guessing that more and more people will be doing some of their
shopping from Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   But which sites are the easiest to use? Who has the best
customer service?
</P>
<P>
   Gomez Advisors, a market research firm, looked at the best Web
sites for buying a computer. Gomez broke the results down into the
best sites for first-time buyers, bargain hunters and serious
shoppers. The results are at Gomez's Web site, www.gomez.com.
</P>
<P>
   Buy.com ranked first. Gomez said the Web site had the lowest
prices and offers 30-day toll-free customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Buy.com offers a strong variety of products, order tracking and
easy access to manufacturers with technical support links,
according to the review. The site was flagged for its ``spotty''
product descriptions and for the online delays for customer service
help.
</P>
<P>
   For bargain hunters, www.buy.com, www.computers4sure.com, www
</P>
<P>
   .onsale.com and www.outpost
</P>
<P>
   .com were the top-ranked sites.
</P>
<P>
   For first-time buyers, www.buy.com, www.pcmall.com,
www.outpost.com and necxdirect.necx.com rated high. First-time
buyers are defined as people interested in sites that are easy to
navigate and have accessible customer service.
</P>
<P>
   For ``serious shoppers,'' Gomez.com ranked www.cdw.com,
www.pcmall.com, www
</P>
<P>
   .buy.com and www.computers4sure.com highly.
</P>
<P>
   Serious shoppers are defined as those who tend to make purchases
for their business. The buyer is drawn to sites that offer the best
selection, detailed account information and a chance for volume
discounts or leasing options.
</P>
<P>
   FEMALE CEO FINDS IT'S A LONELY ROAD
</P>
<P>
   What's it like to be young, attractive, female and the head of a
Silicon Valley technology company?
</P>
<P>
   Kim Polese, chief executive of Marimba, talks about what it's
like to walk that fairly deserted street in the October issue of
Upside magazine. Upside is the print version of
www.upsidetoday.com, a Web magazine devoted to the technology
industry's personalities, companies and money.
</P>
<P>
   Polese was part of the product management group responsible for
spreading the word about Java, the programming language in which
many Internet applications are written. She left Sun Microsystems
and helped form Marimba, a company that builds and sells software
that allows software updates to be delivered to networked PCs.
After a good bit of hype, most of which focused on the novel idea
of a young, female CEO, the company went public in April _ but not
before a slight change in direction, from a ``push'' technology
firm to one that delivers software over the Internet and networks.
</P>
<P>
   The woman-as-CEO attention was important and valuable for a new
technology company, but when the company changed direction, Polese
took the heat. Magazine and newspaper stories questioned whether
the company was more hype than reality, and since the hype centered
on her gender, Upside questions whether the criticism was sexist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sexism was in the mix,'' Polese said in the article,
``but my reaction when I saw that was not concern about sexism but
disappointment on behalf of my company, my co-founders and our
customers. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a reaction to the oddity and the novelty of a woman
CEO. But it didn't really bother me at the end of the day because I
knew we were going to execute, I knew we were going to be
successful, and I knew we were going to kick butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Some urban legends aren't false after all
</P>
<P>
   Have you heard the one about the guy who kills himself trying to
get a can out of a soft drink machine? Unlike most so-called urban
legends, this one apparently is true.
</P>
<P>
   The Nov. 11 issue of the Journal of the American Medical
Association documents 15 cases of a soda machine falling on someone
trying to retrieve a can. Of those, 12 people were injured and
required hospitalization, and three were crushed to death.
</P>
<P>
   A Web site devoted to urban legends, www.urbanlegends
</P>
<P>
   .com, looks at some of the more interesting, intriguing and
mostly false stories making the rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
