<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-NETWATCH12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Web pioneer follows the money
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASPEN, Colo. _ Jim Clark is a bona fide ``been there, done that,
have the T-shirt'' member of the Silicon Valley boys club.
</P>
<P>
   First, he started Silicon Graphics, then hooked up with
University of Illinois wunderkind Marc Andreessen to found
Netscape. Clark took home a bundle after Netscape went public, then
moved on to Healtheon, the medical benefits information company
that was later acquired by Atlanta-based WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   So who better to give the keynote address to the Internet
insiders, players and pretenders at the Industry Standards'
NetReturns 2000 conference at the St. Regis Hotel? The 400-plus
attendees all turned their cell phones off and put down their
PalmPilots long enough to listen to Clark describe his personal and
extremely profitable trip down the fast lane of the information
superhighway.
</P>
<P>
   His advice to the assembled industry players was simple: Follow
your gut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every entrepreneur knows there's one thing you need to succeed
... follow a strong gut instinct that tells you what you know can
bring about a company that sells something people will want to
buy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the so-called dot-com start-ups are fortunate
because they don't have what he calls the ``Barnes &AMP; Noble
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are encumbered by the current way of doing things,'' he
said. ``The great thing about a start-up is that you are not
encumbered. Your goal, of course, is to become encumbered.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Clark's ventures have all been wildly successful,
he's not afraid to admit where things went wrong. Maybe it's OK to
admit where you've messed up when you have a cool billion to show
for it.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about Netscape, he said, ``After three months of talking
to Marc, I got it and I got it big,'' he said. Clark said
Netscape's ultimate failure was its focus on business customers:
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to convince newspapers and media companies and direct
marketers that the Web could be a vehicle for electronic commerce.
But it was a little early. And we threw away our portal
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark admits where he went astray with Healtheon. ``The biggest
market I could think of was health care,'' he said. ``We built the
world's best benefits enrollment system, but not a lot of people
wanted it at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with wildly successful, if slightly flawed, Web ventures
behind him, Clark isn't about to call it a day. He is still
traveling the highways and byways of Silicon Valley with a new
venture called My CFO (www.mycfo.com).
</P>
<P>
   The venture is built upon Clark's own problems managing the
millions he has amassed as a Web pioneer. As it happens, Clark has
an awful lot of money scattered around in an awful lot of places,
and he's having just the darndest time trying to keep track of it
all.
</P>
<P>
   Clark decided to go with his gut again and form a Web-based
company _ his fourth start-up. The year-old company is targeted at
an audience that Clark calls ``high-net-worth individuals with
complex financial lives.''
</P>
<P>
   My CFO's users are worth a million or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``A business wouldn't consider operating without a CFO,
controller and accountant. We're doing for the individual what
businesses have to do,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   The list of investors and users of My CFO reads like a who's who
of Silicon Valley with a roster of old-money superstars including
Cisco Systems Chief Executive Officer John Chambers. And just for
being Jim Clark, he's already got backing from big-time venture
capitalists such as Kleiner Perkins and Excite At Home Chairman Tom
Jermoluk.
</P>
<P>
   Clark talked of how these high-income individuals have trouble
keeping their financial houses in order, especially when it comes
to money earned from what he termed ``wealth-generating events''
like an initial public stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Clark's enviable track record, My CFO seems to share
some of the flaws of Clark's other ventures. He's overlooked the
little people again and has underestimated the big ones. If you
have a million dollars, why can't you just hire your own
flesh-and-blood financial managers and pay for it with the cash
generated from all these ``wealth-generating events'' that seem to
happen to Silicon Valley millionaires almost daily?
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to Clark's new venture was mixed. ``I think Clark needs
to volunteer at a soup kitchen,'' cracked one attendee milling
around in the lobby during a break. ``He's been down in the Valley
pricing Ferraris, oceanfront property and sports teams too long.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Does hitting the video poker in South Carolina count as a
wealth-generating event?'' muttered one of the conference speakers.
``I don't understand what he's trying to do. It's not a Web site,
it's an intranet investment banking firm for Clark and his
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   My CFO became one of the hottest topics at the four-day
conference. It seems to have everything a turn-of-the-century Web
start-up should have: Big-time backers, super-rich users, and the
envy and resentment of every Web player who didn't think of it and
will never be rich enough to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the public relations people tried to put the best
spin on My CFO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, he's Jim Clark,'' said one of the conference organizers.
``He's done it all, and he's just having fun now. Why shouldn't
he?''
</P>
<P>
   He's just following his gut _ and following the money.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-11-99 1103EDT &QL;
</P>
