<SLUG> BC-CPT-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING SMALL BUSINESSES' INTERNET DREAMS INTO REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Companies hoping to do business on the Web are being bombarded
with more ``solutions'' than ever _ all promising to provide
services that address the problem of how to set up shop online.
</P>
<P>
   And within the e-commerce sphere, the segment that ``solutions
providers'' seem to think needs the most help is the small-business
category. In fact, they may be right. According to the U.S. Small
Business Administration, only 30 percent of the nation's 24 million
small businesses accept orders on the Web, and far fewer can
process credit card transactions.
</P>
<P>
   But as more of those companies develop a full-scale Internet
presence _ and as everyone who ever had a lemonade stand decides to
sell something on the Web _e-commerce software and service
providers are competing more furiously for market share.
</P>
<P>
   One increasingly popular approach is to offer ``all-in-one''
e-commerce packages, in which merchants pay a nominal monthly fee
for software that enables them to build a site that is then hosted
by a third party _ sparing the client the cost of Web servers and
fast Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say such services generally fall short of providing
everything businesses need to succeed on the Web, which is, of
course, what many promise to do. Still, all-in-one packages have
proved to be a good way to test the Internet waters, according to
many business people who have used them. And as more competitors
enter the market, analysts say, the quality of low-priced
e-commerce services should improve.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Simon, for one, can attest to the wide array of low-cost
e-commerce packages available. Last year, Ms. Simon decided to
build a Web site, www.blindsdepot.com, to extend the reach of her
window-treatments business, which she had previously run by herself
selling door to door.
</P>
<P>
   A technology neophyte, Ms. Simon looked first at one of the
market leaders in one-stop e-commerce setup, Yahoo Stores. As with
other companies, Yahoo enables users to build a Web site in minutes
by filling out a series of forms online. For $100 a month, digital
entrepreneurs can post their store on Yahoo's site and offer as
many as 50 products for sale. The more products offered for sale,
the higher Yahoo's monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   Like its competitors, which range from established companies
like IBM to Internet service providers like Hiway Technologies and
other portal sites, Yahoo offers a host of additional features. It
aggregates orders and sends them via fax to the store owner for
processing, encrypts credit card numbers during processing and
offers a shopping cart feature, so customers can pay for multiple
products at once.
</P>
<P>
   What Ms. Simon could not get from Yahoo _ or any e-commerce
provider, for that matter _ was placement high up on the results
pages of search engines. Seeking more shoppers, Ms. Simon opted for
an all-in-one package provided by iMall, which guarantees placement
on its shopping site, www.imall.com. When that also failed to
generate sales, she built a store using software provided by
Concentric Network, an Internet service provider that hosted the
site for $50 a month, and she set about learning how to manipulate
the search engines for better placement.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Concentric software tools were somewhat limited for
her purposes, Ms. Simon said, so she spent about $500 to build a
more sophisticated site with ShopSite software, from Open Market.
With the help of a consultant, she also learned how to increase her
site's visibility on search engines. The payoff, at last, came in
March, when sales started to roll. ``I'm making much more than
before,'' Ms. Simon said, though she would not disclose specific
numbers. ``And I'm working much less.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Staff, chief economist with Zona Research, a unit of
Intelliquest, said that ``there are literally dozens of features
that are needed to make an e-commerce site work well'' beyond those
offered by the one-stop e-commerce companies. Among other things,
Staff said, small businesses need technologies to analyze customer
activity on the site, gauge the effectiveness of advertisements,
personalize the site for each visitor, build incentive programs,
offer coupons and instant discounts, confirm orders and returns and
automate e-mail responses. ``And then the real issue becomes how to
get well known with consumers,'' Staff said.
</P>
<P>
   In this regard at least, e-commerce service providers feel their
customers' pain. According to Andrew Beebe, chief executive of
Bigstep.com, which provides e-commerce services to businesses,
profitability and visibility are difficult to achieve in this
category. ``There are a lot of people doing this,'' he said, ``and
they're making a lot of noise.''
</P>
<P>
   As for profitability, Beebe said his company, which began
operations last month, ``is not making any money at all right
now.'' The plan, at least, is to provide free help to small
businesses starting e-commerce sites, then sell them more advanced
technology services along the lines of what Staff, of Zona,
described. With 20,000 small businesses currently signed up and
hundreds more being added daily, Beebe said he can negotiate
discounts from e-commerce technology providers and extract a margin
with every sale to his customers. ``But this really is going to be
a tight-margin game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That is especially likely if his competitors keep driving the
price of services down. ``Every time someone else thinks they're
going to sell something, we're going to give it away,'' said Serge
Wilson, chief executive of Freemerchant.com, which provides
e-commerce services completely free of charge. Wilson, whose
company has signed up 20,000 merchants, earns money by offering
suppliers like the Office Max retail chain access to Freemerchant
store owners.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson sees his service as an ideal entree for people who are
not sure they want to commit thousands of dollars to an Internet
business. ``A certain percentage of our merchants will never sell
successfully,'' he said. ``It takes the right product, and time and
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   It also takes more expertise in a given category than many
e-commerce newbies are willing to develop, said Larry Erlich,
founder of Domainregistry.com, who provides consulting services to
small businesses. ``Almost without fail, the people who try to
start an e-commerce site try something they have absolutely no
expertise in,'' he said. ``They're usually involved in a business
they could probably make some money with on the Web, but they want
to do something else. It's clicks and wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-10-99 1848EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
