u a BC-CPT-NETAID-MUSIC-REVI     10-13 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-NETAID-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP REVIEW: THE STARS GIVE A PARTY FOR A GLOBAL WEB SITE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (nk) 
 By JON PARELES c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When is a benefit not a benefit? When it's a start-up party for
a Web site. Three all-star concerts were given on Saturday for
www.netaid.org, a Web site intended to take on not just one cause
on one occasion but long-term work on five major global issues:
poverty, the environment, human rights, refugees and poor
countries' debt. It was a way for stars to demonstrate concern
about everything from malnutrition in Bolivia to toxic oil-refinery
waste in Lake Charles, La.
</P>
<P>
   Net Aid was modeled on Live Aid, the shows in England and the
United States that raised $200 million for African famine relief in
1985. While donations were accepted (to be used for refugee relief
efforts in Kosovo and in Africa), the goal of Net Aid was primarily
to publicize the Web site. Net Aid, supervised by the U.N.
Development Program, is a clearinghouse for volunteer efforts,
donations, information on agriculture and business development and
Internet-style organizing, including an e-mail petition urging
developed countries to forgive $371 billion in third-world debt.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. concert, Net Aid New York, took place at Giants Stadium
in East Rutherford, N.J.. The nearly eight-hour show began and
ended with Wyclef Jean and Bono. They had collaborated on a song
for Net Aid, ``New Day,'' which touches on problems from
unemployment to crime to homelessness but promises, ``Sun got the
darkness on the run.'' The lineup also included Puff Daddy, Sting,
Jewel, Mary J. Blige, Busta Rhymes, Sheryl Crow, the Black Crowes,
Counting Crows, Jimmy Page, the Algerian singer Cheb Mami and the
Italian rocker Zucchero. Although nearly all the performers have
sold at least a million albums each, the scattered lineup didn't
fill the stadium; the top tier was empty, as were expanses of the
lower tiers and the field.
</P>
<P>
   Between sets, the audience at Giants Stadium saw video clips
from the two other Net Aid concerts: a packed performance at
Wembley Stadium near London, with a lineup including David Bowie,
the reunited Eurythmics, George Michael, Bush, Bryan Adams, the
Corrs and Robbie Williams, and an invitation-only event at the
Palais des Nations in Geneva with Bryan Ferry and Des'ree, which
was attended by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan. The concerts
were broadcast on radio stations in 132 countries and shown on VH1
and MTV in the United States and on the BBC. A two-hour show of
excerpts is scheduled for Wednesday night at 8 on the TNT cable
network.
</P>
<P>
   With television cameras transmitting to an international
audience, the musicians didn't stint on production values. They
brought full bands, choirs, string orchestras and, for Puff Daddy,
pyrotechnics. They also refrained from profanity.
</P>
<P>
   Some stars brought out their most earnest, idealistic anthems.
Bono _ dressed in a quasi-military uniform and wearing a cap from
Jubilee 2000, an organization pressing for debt forgiveness _ sang
``One'' with a string orchestra conducted by Quincy Jones,
insisting, ``We got to carry each other.'' Jewel declaimed like a
gospel preacher in ``Life Uncommon,'' which grows militant: ``There
is a new army coming and we are armed with faith/To live, we must
give.''
</P>
<P>
   Others just treated their short sets as condensed versions of a
regular show. The guitarist Jimmy Page rocked the stadium with
time-tested arena fare when he played his old Led Zeppelin songs
while Chris Robinson, of the Black Crowes, sang as much as he could
like Robert Plant; Robinson, a Southerner, was imitating an
Englishman who emulated Southern blues singers. Mary J. Blige
lavished her voice on songs about romantic strife, as her vows and
pleas gave way to wordless, virtuosic swoops, blending the cutting
tone of Dinah Washington with the gutsiness of Gladys Knight. Busta
Rhymes set off one party chant after another, machine-gunning
syllables and racing around the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Net Aid is touted as the largest Web site to date, showing off
technology from Cisco Systems, which contributed more than $10
million to the site; it claims the ability to handle one million
connections a minute. The concerts were shown on the Internet,
through an electronic network 10 times larger than the previous
largest Webcasts (for Victoria's Secret and the opening of the 1998
Olympics), able to send out 125,000 video streams simultaneously.
But on a home computer with a 56K modem, sound and video quality
were still murky, and network traffic made connections difficult in
some areas. Douglas Graham, who oversaw the design and software of
the Web site for KPMG, ascribed the problems to local Internet
providers and high Internet use on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Even more than Live Aid, the Net Aid concert drove home stark
contrasts between the haves, onstage and in the audience, and the
have-nots. Puff Daddy's songs celebrated material success _ the
Mercedes, the cell phones _ but then, in a burst of piousness,
insisted there's more to life than a platinum Rolex. He was the
concert's prime showman, with a white piano, a white-robed gospel
choir, puffs of flame and two guest hard-rock guitarists to show
he's keeping up with the metal-rap trend: Slash of Guns 'n' Roses
and Page, who let Puff Daddy turn Led Zeppelin's ``Kashmir'' into a
wounded lover's rant.
</P>
<P>
   Video clips, shown during equipment changes, detailed harrowing
situations and statistics: arms hacked off during Sierra Leone's
civil war, 22 million refugees, 800 million people chronically
undernourished, 1.3 billion people in extreme poverty. They made
for some bizarre juxtapositions. Immediately after a segment on
teen-age prostitution and drug addiction in Russia, a video clip of
the Corrs at Wembley was shown. ``It really doesn't matter if we
don't eat/It really doesn't matter if we never sleep,'' they sang,
`` 'Cause we are so young now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly absent from the concerts was any music from the countries
that Net Aid is intended to help most. Sting made an effort by
turning over a song (and his band) to Cheb Mami, an Algerian rai
singer with an expressive, fine-pointed voice. And Jean,
over-reaching his limited skills on guitar, tried to cover the
United States (with rap, rockabilly and blues) and the Caribbean
(with ``Guantanamera'' and a version of ``Hot, Hot, Hot'' that
turned the original soca into a Haitian compas). As cyberspace is
now, Net Aid was a sphere of the affluent, but one that envisions
affecting the whole world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-10-99 1751EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1225EDT &QL; 
