<SLUG> BC-CPT-DIGICOM-COLUMN-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL COMMERCE: TAKING TECHNOLOGY TO AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (lb) 
 By DENISE CARUSO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The technology sector's financial success in the last three
years has been largely a North American phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   But some forward-thinking investors have been moving offshore
toward untapped markets and investments, often pushing
communication technologies into underdeveloped countries in Latin
America and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   On foreign soil, U.S. investment often looks _ and acts _
remarkably like invasion. And it is sometimes treated accordingly,
as cellular-telephone providers discovered last year when the
Chinese government abruptly terminated a number of successful joint
ventures with vendors like Motorola and Ericsson in favor of its
own technologies.
</P>
<P>
   So how will U.S. investors, particularly those drunk on their
recent good fortune and feeling perhaps a little invincible,
henceforth enter these raw new markets? The answer to that question
may determine which nations are pulled into the global market and
which are left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Some areas, notably much of Africa, might even welcome an
invasion of foreign technology investment.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly 800 million people in nearly 50 countries speaking
hundreds of dialects and often in conflict with one another, Africa
has attracted almost no technology investment. Add to those
problems the continent's relatively high levels of poverty and
illiteracy, and the risk-reward ratio is not exactly compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Yet people like Noah Samara are willing, and even eager, to take
the risk.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years of planning and development, Samara, the
Ethiopian-born founder and chairman of Worldspace Corp. in
Washington, began broadcasting digital radio programming from his
company's Afristar satellite on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Afristar, the first of three Worldspace satellites (two more
serving Asia and Latin America are to be launched in 2000), is the
first satellite to deliver simultaneous programming to the entire
African continent.
</P>
<P>
   If all three satellites are in orbit by the end of next year,
Worldspace's potential audience will be more than 4.8 billion
people.
</P>
<P>
   Worldspace was conceived when, while practicing law in
Washington, Samara saw the AIDS epidemic ravaging Africa. People
desperately needed information to stem the spread of the virus, he
realized, but distributing printed materials was expensive and
impractical in a continent with so many remote areas and such
illiteracy, and television sets were rare and were too expensive
for most Africans.
</P>
<P>
   Samara's answer was the world's first portable satellite media
receiver: a digital radio that connects with various power sources,
including solar panels for poor, rural areas, as well as to PCs and
printers.
</P>
<P>
   The receivers, manufactured by Matsushita's Panasonic and JVC
subsidiaries, Hitachi and Sanyo, cost about $250 today, Samara
said. That seems prohibitively expensive, but he said that ``once
you start introducing new products and services, people start
working harder to make sure they can benefit from the
conveniences.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've calculated the number of families in our coverage area
that can afford receivers at these prices,'' he added. ``We
designed the African satellite's footprint to cover the more
affluent Middle East, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Why radios and not the Internet? Digital radio was the only
solution that made sense, he insisted, because it was the cheapest,
most efficient way to reach the widest population, from poor,
illiterate rural villages to more affluent urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the most adaptable, he said, because the digital
radios could also receive data, like documents and static Web
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Worldspace, with $1.2 billion of investments, primarily from
Saudi backers, hopes to make money by selling time on the
satellites to various broadcasters, and by offering pay services of
its own.
</P>
<P>
   Today, these include Time Warner's CNN International and
Bloomberg Financial News as well as national and indigenous
broadcasts from countries like Egypt, Ghana, Senegal and South
Africa. But more interesting than its commercial services is its
goal of creating markets by fighting poverty.
</P>
<P>
   A central part of Samara's strategy was setting aside 5 percent
of his satellites' capacity for a nonprofit organization called
Equal Access, which Worldspace started with Solaria, a solar-energy
equipment provider and the State of the World Forum
(www.worldforum.org), a nonprofit global leadership and education
organization formed by Mikhail Gorbachev in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Equal Access aspires to provide free digital radios and a rich
flow of basic information, including educational and health
programming, to the poorest African villages, at a net cost of $10
a user.
</P>
<P>
   Its strategy is to get money directly from organizations like
UNESCO and the World Bank, which have millions of dollars earmarked
for poverty-eradication programs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An early project will be a Pan-African, noncommercial news
program, in the tradition of National Public Radio. Samara calls it
``the voice of Africa talking to the people of Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   And because the Worldspace radio receiver can also connect with
a PC and a printer, even remote villages would be able to receive
multimedia data for distance learning and health programs as well
as school curriculums in multiple languages.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most critical project for Equal Access, says Tom
Rautenberg, director of strategy and program development for State
of the World Forum, is a broadcasting service for women and
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned from World Bank studies that the education of
women and girls is probably the most critical variable in
sustainable development,'' Rautenberg says. ``Their status and
economic potential is a leading indicator of how that community is
doing and its potential for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Samara is dedicated to changing the lives of Africans
and others in developing countries, he argues that the strategy
makes business sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought a lot about how to subsidize the development of the
poorest part of the market,'' he said. ``People need so many things
in these areas _ information on hygiene, how to be better
entrepreneurs, a whole range of issues. If we can do that, we will
help them break through some of the hardest barriers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-10-99 1747EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-INTERNET-PRIVACY-     10-13 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-PRIVACY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
UNDATED: Infrastructure Project.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The industry has financed independent privacy monitoring
organizations, like eTrust and BBB Online. Even so, enforcement
remains an issue for privacy groups and in negotiations between the
United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   To date, much of the development of privacy practices online has
been by the marketplace, responding to complaints, often by the
thousands. In 1997, for example, when word spread that America
Online planned to pass along customers' telephone numbers to
telemarketers and other direct-sales merchants, the big Internet
service provider heard a consumer outcry _ and quickly dropped the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Likewise Amazon.com, the big online bookstore, ran into a
backlash last month when it posted ``purchase circles,'' which
showed the book buying habits of users from selected companies and
universities. Some users found this a breach of privacy without
consent and asked to be removed. After asking employees for their
reaction, IBM Chairman Louis V. Gerstner Jr. received 5,000 e-mail
responses within hours. More than 90 percent objected to having
their book-buying habits as a group disclosed online.
</P>
<P>
   IBM was removed from the book-purchase circles. Later, Gerstner
wrote to Jeff Bezos, chief executive of Amazon.com, saying, ``I'm
certainly not going to tell you how to run your business, but I do
urge you to view this as an enormously important issue.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some online privacy issues have surfaced case by case. Last
year, for example, a customer service representative at America
Online told a Navy investigator the real name of a naval officer
who had identified himself by the screen name ``Tim'' and listed
his marital status as ``gay.'' Later, America Online reached an
out-of-court settlement with the officer and adopted new policies
to protect the privacy of its customers. America Online's thousands
of customer service representatives are now given special
``scenario training'' to insure that they do not give out private
information about users without the users' consent or a court
order.
</P>
<P>
   This trial-and-error, market-driven approach to privacy,
Internet executives note, has often resulted in stricter practices
than those, for example, of the credit card and catalog industries.
Besides, they add, a rapid response system for customers is built
into the Internet, where e-mail complaining and chat room
organizing can punish companies more quickly and more severely than
government regulations can.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, good privacy policy is good business
for us,'' said Robert Pittman, president of America Online. ``It's
very important to our members. We've learned that anything you do,
you have to think through the prism of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not always perfect,'' Pittman added. ``But if we miss
something, our members tell us in one big hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Most online consumers, apparently, are willing to fend for
themselves on the increasingly commercial Internet. A survey by
Privacy and American Business, a research firm, found that 86
percent of 460 adult Internet users questioned earlier this year
said they wanted to be able to essentially ``trade'' their own
personal information with Web sites _ as long as they were properly
informed about how their data were used and were offered benefits
for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky, the FTC chairman, points to those survey results as
the reason he is ``willing to be patient to see if self-regulation
works.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Yet many people argue that some basic legislation to protect
individual privacy on the Internet is inevitable _ and that it
could both benefit consumers and stimulate the growth of e-commerce
by fostering greater public trust in doing business on line. Such
sentiments extend well beyond the traditional champions of
government intervention like privacy advocates and consumer groups.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Berners-Lee, the British physicist who created the basic
software for the Web, is the director of the World Wide Web
Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. His
consortium is working on privacy-enhancing technology, software
that holds a person's privacy preferences and can communicate and
bargain on an individual's behalf over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Berners-Lee said: ``On privacy, I don't think that
self-regulation is enough. In America, I believe that the lack of
regulation means that the corporate marketers have too much
power.''
</P>
<P>
   That power seems certain to increase in the near future. The
spread of Internet technology will result in a data collection
network of previously unimagined reach as telephones, televisions,
cars and appliances _ not just personal computers _ are connected
to the global digital network before long. And the rapidly
developing fields of data-mining and profiling software will enable
corporations to increasingly slice and search through this ocean of
data to identify personal patterns of buying and behavior _ and
make inferences, accurate or not, about a person's likely behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The unnerving prospect, according to Paul Saffo, a director for
the Institute for the Future, is that ``we will all be players in
what could be a fairly inaccurate virtual Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   At stake, technologists say, is far more than who gets which
Internet marketing pitches. Profiling, they say, could be employed
to determine who gets _ and who is excluded from _ all kinds of
opportunities like jobs, housing and education.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC is also studying the use and potential abuse of
increasingly powerful Internet software. The commission has
scheduled a public workshop on ``online profiling'' in November.
</P>
<P>
   Digital red-lining, Ms. Varney says, is an evocative term and a
troubling concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that this technology could be hugely
invasive,'' she said. ``But it could also be enormously empowering
by allowing individuals to make their own choices and by saving us
all time and money. Particularly in the future, we will face more
difficult decisions and trade-offs. But I think that argues for
leaving those decisions to the marketplace for privacy as much as
we can.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-10-99 1611EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
