<HEADER>
A5424 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-APPLE-SOFTWARE-RE     10-13 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-APPLE-SOFTWARE-RESURGENCE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 CUPERTINO, Calif.: from Microsoft. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bud Tribble, now a Sun Microsystems executive, was a manager at
Next when Tevanian came aboard in 1988, fresh from Carnegie Mellon
with a Ph.D. in computer science. He recalls Tevanian as being
``self-confident and bright'' and quickly rising to run Next's
software operating system group.
</P>
<P>
   ``A key quality, shared by many who successfully work for Steve
Jobs, is that he could definitely hold his own with Steve,''
Tribble said. ``I think Steve admires that, as long as it is clear
that the person really knows what they are talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tevanian's friends say that for many years, during which Next's
software received high technical marks but failed to catch hold in
the PC marketplace, Tevanian would often speak wistfully about the
large number of Microsoft stock options he had forgone by signing
on with Next. But Tevanian's patience has been vindicated. In 1997,
when he left Next to come to Apple, he received almost 400,000
Apple stock options, potentially worth $27 million at the stock's
current price.
</P>
<P>
   But then it is Tevanian's role in bringing new rigor to Apple's
software operation that has had much to do with the company's
improved financial standing. Apple's operating system strategy,
which is based on shipping a major release each year and a minor
upgrade six months later, is already contributing significantly to
the company's profitability. Although the numbers are not reported
separately in Apple's annual report, Jobs said last week that Mac
OS was now contributing $50 million a year in profit to the
computer maker, which had $300 million in total profit in 1998.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Turning Apple's decade-and-a-half-old operating system into a
cash cow has been one of Jobs' cleverest accomplishments since
returning to Apple. When he sold Next to Apple in late 1996, many
people in the computer industry expected that Apple would simply
replace its aging Mac OS with Nextstep, the elegant but
commercially unsuccessful operating system developed by Tevanian.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Jobs has chosen an approach of gradually trickling the
Next technology into the Mac OS, while continually pushing back the
introduction of a completely new operating system, now known within
the company as Mac OS X.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs said in a recent interview that customer test versions of
Mac OS X would appear early next year, but that a final version
would not reach the market until later in 2000 _ a significant
delay, compared with the original timetable, which called for the
new system to appear by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Several former and present Macintosh software engineers, who
would speak only if they were not identified, said the company
still had an imposingly large amount of work left to finish on the
project. That would suggest that Jobs and Tevanian, for all their
success in updating the current Mac OS, may have simply succeeded
in delaying the same crucial transition that the company failed to
make nearly three years ago, when it canceled its ambitious but
troubled Copland project.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than merely delaying a potentially wrenching
transition, Jobs contends that he realized there was still plenty
of potential growth in the existing Mac OS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that we were the owners and caretakers of one of
only two high-volume operating systems in the world, and that this
was a wonderful place to be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-10-99 1621EDT &QL;
</P>
