A5464 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-13 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GRASS ROOTS OF DEMOCRATIC POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The other afternoon, the early shift state
workers were gathering at the bus shelter at Washington Avenue and
Lark Street, one of this old city's key intersections, waiting for
a bus to ferry them home.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a dozen people milled in and around the green metal and
glass structure on the corner. It was a gentle fall day, awash in
sunlight, so the shelter wasn't needed for protection from the
elements, as it will be in January. The shelter just squatted there
on the corner, the size of a one-car garage, erected a few years
ago at a cost of _ get this, now _ $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   That was the breathtaking price for this thing. At the time,
Donna DeMaria, one of Albany's most prominent homeless activists,
was battling to squeeze about 85 cents out of the city government
so she could keep her shelter for helpless winos going. She was so
annoyed at what this structure had cost that she staged a
demonstration at the corner. The left-wing homeless activists were
picketing a bus shelter to complain, of all things, about
government waste. The point is that when government does something
_ just about anything, really _ it always costs more than it would
cost in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   Tsvi and Deborah Gold know all about that.
</P>
<P>
   They're a pleasant young couple. Tsvi (pronounced ``Svee'') just
got out of Albany Law School. He works in the Bronx for a state
legislator. Deborah is a financial planner. They have a little
house on a quiet corner maybe 40 blocks from the bus shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the Golds decorate their lawn with political signs,
generally signs for liberal, independent Democratic candidates
opposed by the city's powerful Democratic organization. Since this
is a city with about a 14-to-1 enrollment advantage for the
Democrats, primary elections are the only elections that count. The
regular Democratic organization takes primaries seriously. The
organization also takes seriously people who oppose the party's
official selections for political office.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, the Democratic Party committeeman in the
neighborhood, who lives a few doors away, told the Golds that they
don't mow their lawn often enough. The committeeman said he mowed
his lawn twice a week. He suggested that they do the same thing.
Otherwise, the city government might give them trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah and Tsvi are busy people. They said thanks for the
advice and kept on mowing twice a month. Not long afterward, they
found on their door a notice from the city ordering them to mow
their lawn. They called the city. An inspector came out. The
inspector said he saw no problem with the yard and left.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a few weeks ago, Deborah and Tsvi took a trip to the
Netherlands. Tsvi's sister was getting married there. When they
came home, they found a notice that the city had mowed their lawn
and was demanding $138.75 for the service. You pay it, or the city
imposes a lien on your house.
</P>
<P>
   This is a tiny lawn _ 30-by-120 feet in the front, 30-by-40 in
the back. A lawn service might charge $40 to mow it. The city had
done a crummy job, too. Big clumps of grass were left. Thirteen
days after the mowing, a tape measure showed those clumps to be
seven inches in height, indicating that the grass hadn't been all
that high when city workers had swooped down on the Gold's lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bruce, Albany's commissioner of general services, would not
say who had complained about the Golds' lawn. Was it the
committeeman, he was asked? Well, Bruce didn't really know, and
didn't want to talk about it. When reached, the committeeman said
it definitely wasn't he who had complained.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce did look into the matter, though. He decided that the city
had made a mistake. So, the commissioner said, Tsvi and Deborah
Gold will receive a letter telling them to forget about the
$138.75. Which, apparently, ends this little adventure in
government economics.
</P>
<P>
   Unless somebody somewhere has the political juice to get a bus
shelter erected on the Golds' corner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
