<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESSE-VENTURA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN `RIGHT' IS WRONG FOR THE REPUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE SCOTT  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALNUT CREEK, Calif. _ Open-minded people understand the
frustration with a meddling ``Christian'' right that led to
Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura's unfortunate quip about religion
being for the ``weak-minded.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the sage from St. Paul dodges jeers, we might give a
two centuries' belated cheer for the Freedom From Religion
Foundation, based in Madison, Wis. The organization, which fights
for the separation of church and state, held its convention in San
Francisco a few months ago. One more time: Our founding fathers
were not ``Christians'' but broad-minded, philosophically
omnivorous theists.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, Madison, Franklin, Jefferson, Washington and others used
``God'' as an all-encompassing, inclusive, even mystical concept
for what might be believed or not yet known. Jefferson and some of
the Virginians may have been Anglicans. But please, enough with
this Bible-appropriating, divisive Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   The historical Jesus was, by all accounts, a wandering
carpenter/philosopher with a sense of humor who enjoyed a debate.
Had he been a contemporary of and met Buddha, Mohammed, et al.,
they'd probably have broken bread together, become friends, even
traveled together awhile.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to believe in the Chevrolet-Pontiac-Buick line of
General Christianity, fine. This is your right as an American. But
it is not _ and never should be _ a requisite of citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Like any code, philosophy or belief system, Christianity has
been used to justify war, torture, land-grabbing, genocide, bigotry
_ a far cry from the gentle, inclusive invitations of a
big-hearted, visionary, traveling craftsman. A far remove from
polyester-garbed, limo-riding televangelists bilking the life
savings from ill-educated grannies and shut-ins, and the We/They
code speak of political hacks like Jesse Helms, Pat Robertson and
Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   As a white North Carolina schoolboy in the early '60s, I had
dinner at the home of a white classmate. We bowed our heads in
prayer. Within minutes, my friend's brother received only the
mildest, chuckling rebuke from his parents after telling an
astoundingly ugly n-word joke.
</P>
<P>
   In the third grade, the only way to escape the weekly Bible
teacher was to produce a note from home, which meant you spent that
time like some lonely leper in the empty school library.
</P>
<P>
   This was a public school. So you'd feign interest as some pious,
heavily rouged harpie recited the usual parables from the
much-revised King James Impala/Galaxie 500 version of the New
Testament. (None of that Old Testament weirdness in good old
Charlotte, N.C.) In the sixth grade, in another public school in a
slightly more upscale neighborhood, presumably to demonstrate a
modern, low-earth-orbit, Mercury-capsule view of our colonial past,
the teacher had each pupil announce a religious affiliation. This
exercise was to make us appreciate our ``religious freedom'' and
diversity as we approached another Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard?'' ``Baptist''; ``Charlie?'' ``Methodist''; ``Susan,
Tommy, Kathy?'' ``Baptist, Baptist, Presbyterian''; ``Virginia?``
``Episcopalian'' (this exotic departure seemed fitting since little
Virginia was a hothouse orchid often absent with rheumatic fever);
``Sammy, Bucky, Patricia?'' ``Baptist, Baptist, Lutheran.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike? `` ... uh ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike?'' ``Well, uh, my parents play tennis Sunday mornings.''
</P>
<P>
   The blistering silence suggested I'd announced we were
puppy-eatin' Martians. During recess, a couple kids sidled over to
me and admitted my answer was ``cool.'' But I was still a pagan
Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party loves the Christian right. A public
blindsided with the Ten Commandments and prayer in the classroom
won't question who's getting how much from big tobacco, gun
manufacturers, and corporate polluters.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom is an adult concept. Some people can't handle it. But
freedom is the bedrock of our nation, and our nation's defining
tract, the Constitution, which protects, but does not dictate, the
Bible, Cervantes, Mark Twain, rap, performance artists, Strom
Thurmond and the late, great Henny Youngman.
</P>
<P>
   In the texts of all the world's great religions you find the
Golden Rule. The Talmud's version is as elegantly simple as any of
them: ``What is hateful to you, do not to your fellow men. That is
the entire Law; all the rest is commentary.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want to customize that with options at your local dealer,
fine. But no advertising in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Scott, a writer from Walnut Creek, Calif., says he is a
Reformed Druid.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
