<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COPS, KIDS FIND COMMON TURF 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ In this city, when you see clusters of cops,
their car lights flashing, you usually say, ``Uh, oh. What's
wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Jerry Brown's superstardom notwithstanding, Oakland's
reputation remains that of a crime-ridden city where police actions
are commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, last week, as the early autumn sun started to set, all
those cops and their cars surrounding a seven-story downtown garage
were part of a unique street-theater piece designed to close some
of the communications gap between local law enforcement and
teen-agers. Kids and cops are usually an oil-and-water combination.
In recent years, however, some artists, community activists and
police leaders have worked to concoct a smoother blend of those
normally unmixable ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Their work culminated in the performance art piece known as Code
33, cop lingo for ``emergency _ clear the air.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is what Code 33 tried to do. Police cars and low-riders
were scheduled to enter the garage in a procession to start the
event. But several hundred supporters of Mumia Abu-Jamal, a
convicted cop killer sentenced to death in Pennsylvania,
interrupted the proceedings. Their noisy march caused Code 33
organizers to cancel the procession. The conversations between cops
and kids on the garage rooftop went on, however. In circles of
eight or 10, police officers and teen-agers of different racial
backgrounds went at it verbally for about 90 minutes, as hundreds
of ordinary Oaklanders and city officials eavesdropped. The talk
was often direct and honest.
</P>
<P>
   Cop: ``What has a bad cop done to you personally?''
</P>
<P>
   Kid: ``I got sprayed with Mace, pushed around and handcuffed. I
felt really disrespected.''
</P>
<P>
   Kid: ``Everybody stereotypes everybody else. That's why we feel
the way we feel and you feel the way you feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Kid: ``We're talking about power, and you're the ones with
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Kid: ``The police should establish friendships with kids and the
community, to build trust, so kids will stay out of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Cop: ``That's right. The most rewarding moment for me is when a
bunch of kids run up to me and call me by my name.''
</P>
<P>
   Cop: ``Some parents will call us to control their kids. We
become the bad guys. That's why people have negative attitudes
toward us.''
</P>
<P>
   Kid: ``My mom and I were passing out fliers for my mom's
business in the hills. Lots of Caucasian people live there. A
police car drove by. He kept looking at us. He drove away, then he
came back. That was not called for. Finally, he said my mom's car
lights were messed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Cop: ``What I would have done is wave and ask how you're doing
and drive away. We're not going to nitpick you. There are so many
other things we need to do. I wouldn't harass you or your mom,
unless we see something out of the ordinary. Some police officers
may be racists or prejudiced. We try to correct those feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police officers are also people. Most police officers have
experiences that most people don't have. That officer may have been
prejudiced or he may have noticed something you didn't see.''
</P>
<P>
   Kid: ``I was thrown on the hood of a police car. It was hot. I
didn't do anything. The cops didn't apologize, or nothing. I don't
trust police.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk is cheap. We know that even the most innovative methods of
getting a relatively small number of cops and kids to spend a few
hours talking honestly with one another in a non-threatening
situation aren't going to wipe out deep feelings of distrust
between members of the two groups. But an event like Code 33 is a
lot better than the usual interactions between cops and kids in
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is wongink(at)earthlink.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
