<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5487 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-COLORAD-HOTEL-ART-1ST     10-13 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLORAD-HOTEL-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RESORT FOR THE FAMOUS GETS A LUXURIOUS UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS byline, Judyth Rigler sted Julie Cooper; story stands)  
 (EDs: Photo available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDYTH RIGLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANITOU SPRINGS, Colo. _ What does it take to transform a
19th-century landmark into a 21st-century wonder? Just a guy with a
dream _ plus about two years and $9 million to make it come true.
</P>
<P>
   And while Teddy Roosevelt, Thomas Edison and Jenny Lind would no
doubt be pleased to see the old place restored to its former glory,
Bill Gates and Michael Dell would surely approve as well. That's
because the Cliff House's developer saw the potential for both a
vacationer's dream and a businessman's office on the road and made
the hotel a blend of Victorian beauty and style and 21st-century
amenities and technology.
</P>
<P>
   The Cliff House at Pikes Peak reopened July 15 to great fanfare
in the quaint town of Manitou Springs, nestled against the Rocky
Mountains near Colorado Springs. With the theme ``Luxury Becomes a
Landmark,'' the hotel hopes to attract the same clientele that
frequents the Broadmoor in Colorado Springs _ although far fewer of
them, since the Cliff House has 57 rooms to the Broadmoor's 700.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the draw, said Jeanine Piper, who provided a tour of
the Cliff House. The staff-to-guest ratio is about 40 to 100, and
guests should be able to find everything they need right on the
property. The 4 1/2-story building, which has been welcoming guests
longer than Colorado has been a state, was originally opened in
1873 as The Inn, a stagecoach stop on the route from Colorado
Springs to Leadville, and that provenance earned it a spot on the
National Register of Historic Places in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   When the gold strikes in the region began to play out, Manitou
Springs turned to another attraction: the old mineral springs
bubbling up from limestone aquifers. Edward E. Nichols, who had
come from the East seeking a cure for his tuberculosis, stayed on
in Manitou Springs as an eight-term mayor. In 1876, seeing dollar
signs in the springs, Nichols converted the inn into a luxury
resort hotel. The healing powers of the springs were touted for the
restoration of good health, and for 70 years the hotel thrived as a
prime destination for the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   The Manitou Bath House Co. across the way, with its Soda
Springs, provided healing baths and sparkling water for guests.
</P>
<P>
   After operating for some years as an apartment house, the Cliff
House was bought by California real estate developer James Morley
in 1981, who converted it to a 42-unit apartment building with the
long-term dream of obtaining financing to transform it into a
luxury hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1982, the dream became a nightmare when a fire destroyed
much of the building. The fire was blamed on a careless smoker and
the low flash point of shredded newspapers that had been used as
insulation. The burned-out shell was boarded up for 16 years while
Morley fought a depressed economy.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, construction began in earnest. The estimated $3.2
million needed for the job became $9 million, and the original plan
for a bed-and-breakfast inn was scrapped for that of a
51,000-square-foot ``boutique hotel'' with Victorian architecture
and furnishings. The original architectural detail that made the
building so striking has been restored, from ornate railings and
balustrades to hand-carved moldings and wooden filigree accents
above doors and windows.
</P>
<P>
   Guest suites ranging in price from $129 to $298 include 19
studio rooms, nine junior suites, 12 deluxe rooms and 17 celebrity
suites named after well-known figures who stayed at the hotel
during its earlier life: Henry Ford, Jenny Lind, P.T. Barnum, Clark
Gable, Teddy Roosevelt, Gen. John Pershing and Katharine Lee Bates
(author of ``America the Beautiful'').
</P>
<P>
   You might want to settle into the $5,000 cashmere mattress
donated by the Simmons Mattress Co. for the Zalmon Simmons room,
named for the company's founder. One junior suite has a turret room
with overhead paneling crafted from more than 1,800 pieces of wood.
All are distinctive and lavishly appointed, even the smaller
studios.
</P>
<P>
   A pleasing range of colors has been used for the rooms. While a
bit some of the furniture is antique, most are reproductions. ``We
tried to use local vendors for as much as we could,'' Piper said.
</P>
<P>
   Amenities include two-person spa tubs or steam showers,
310-count Egyptian cotton bed linens and towels, music systems,
lighted makeup mirrors, Turtleware robes, hair dryers,
Caswell-Massey soaps and lotions and, of course, heated toilet
seats and towel warmers _ little touches that can be pretty
important on a Colorado winter night.
</P>
<P>
   Televisions are hidden behind original works of art created for
the hotel by local artisans; open the artful cabinet, and Jay
Leno's looking out. In another thoughtful touch, rooms with
fireplaces have timers built into the bed headboard _ wouldn't want
to get the tootsies cold when it's time to turn off the gas logs
and sleep.
</P>
<P>
   On the technology front, business travelers who use computers on
the road will be delighted to find in-room two-line phones, digital
T-1 capability, Internet and local area network access with
high-speed data cabling and data ports throughout the property. The
hotel, ideally suited for meetings and conferences, offers package
rates for small groups.
</P>
<P>
   In the main floor music room, guests will gather before the
largest of three original fireplaces in the hotel, crafted by
regionally famous Van Briggle Pottery. Gas-burning facsimiles are
in most of the rooms. The grand piano is grand indeed, but it's
equipped with a CD-ROM drive to ensure a constant supply of
flawless accompaniment to the oh-so-Victorian afternoon tea, as
well as meetings and receptions to be held in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before the grand opening, the adjacent Manitou
Ballroom, designed to hold up to 200 people, had already been
booked for countless special events, including 17 wedding
receptions through December. Innkeeper and co-owner Craig Hartman,
fresh from a seven-year stint at the award-winning Clifton Country
Inn in Charlottesville, Va., is also executive chef at the Cliff
House.
</P>
<P>
   In the Cliff House Restaurant, a solariumlike room where
$180,000 in Pella windows offers diners views of the nearby peaks,
fixed price, a la carte and spa cuisine menus are served. Hartman's
emphasis is on local and regional ingredients and selections from
the 7,500-bottle wine cellar, built behind the 126-year-old safe
door that hasn't budged since its installation. Also included in
the rates are a complimentary shuttle from the Colorado Springs
Airport, complimentary valet parking, a fitness room and on-call
masseuse.
</P>
<P>
   Not many hotels have a historian serving as the concierge and
gift shop operator. But Betty Jo Cardona has been following the
hotel's history for many years and snapped up the job there. ``I'm
delighted to see how it has turned out, so it was a natural for me
to work here and keep tracking it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO: The Cliff House at Manitou Springs, 306 Canon Ave.,
Manitou Springs, CO 80829; 719-685-3000 or toll free at
888-212-7000; fax 719-685-3913; e-mail canon306(at)aol.com;
www.thecliffhouse.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
