<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5504 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-REVIEW-CAULFIELD-H     10-13 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-CAULFIELD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW COP SHOW STEPS BEYOND TRITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Conventional wisdom says the television cop
genre is dead. After all, what show is going to top the gallows
humor and intelligence of ``Homicide: Life on the Street,'' and how
do you create a better character than Dennis Franz's Sipowicz on
``NYPD Blue''?
</P>
<P>
   Yet cynics who said no one would improve on the groundbreaking
``Hill Street Blues'' also were _ well, sort of _ proven wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of launching a bunch of new cop shows, recent trends
have taken to mixing them with firefighters and paramedics or, more
successfully, with lawyers. Writers drifted away from uniformed
cops after several attempts failed miserably. So lawyers bloomed
and doctors came to life in the minds of those people responsible
for keeping us entertained. Nobody wanted to mess with ``NYPD
Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fox, which either loves to go against the grain or just
doesn't have much common sense, is launching a new police show
called ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One'' (8 p.m. Eastern, Friday). Given
the current state of Fox's new fall shows, perhaps a better title
might have been, ``Ryan Caulfield: Week One.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this show has changed titles regularly. It started as
``Ryan Caulfield.'' Then it was switched to ``The Badland'' _
singular _ because it's about a rookie cop in Philadelphia's
Badlands _ plural. At the last minute, Fox gave it the current
hopeful title.
</P>
<P>
   The network may be on to something. This show is no ``NYPD
Blue,'' it's no ``Homicide.'' But that's the point, is it not? To
revive a dead genre, you have to be a little different.
</P>
<P>
   The premise is that Ryan (Sean Maher) is a 19-year-old kid who
forgoes the college experience to become a rookie cop in Philly.
His friends don't get it. After all, when things get ugly at a frat
house party, he pulls his badge. There's a word for someone who
pulls that kind of move: narc.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that is the kind of conflict the producers are adept at
tapping in the pilot. This guy should be doing Jell-O shots and
skipping classes. Instead, on his first day at work, he rolls up on
a crime scene where six people are dead, including an undercover
cop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One'' uses a lot of voice-overs from
Maher. Although that conceit usually grows tiring, it works for
this series because it is essential to know what is going on in the
mind of a guy who is getting one serious life lesson and growing up
faster than he had ever thought.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the people responsible for ``The Negotiator'' are behind
this series, and that keeps it from becoming a really bad Fox
attempt to make a cop show and, more importantly, just the usual
blues-on-a-beat formula.
</P>
<P>
   What helps this show immensely is the wonderful acting by
Michael Rispoli as Caulfield's veteran partner. Yeah, he has to
spout some of the jaded cop cliches we know all too well from
tough-partner-rookie-cop scenarios, but Rispoli makes it work, and
his character has some new wrinkles that flesh out the familiarity.
</P>
<P>
   Also helping is Roselyn Sanchez (expect to see her in magazines
and getting a lot of ink) as Caulfield's potential love interest.
She's a cop, too. And, yes, some stereotypes can't be replaced _
she's a babe.
</P>
<P>
   Where ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One'' really takes a different turn
is that the show also focuses on his life after work. His friends _
a convenience-store-working, pop-culture-spewing porn lover (James
Roday) and a lovable dim bulb (Chad Lindberg) _ give the character
a refreshingly grounded outlook. You understand that, hey, he's
only 19.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One'' probably won't stretch the
genre, it did find a new path on which to build stories. The pilot
is solid and, at times, riveting. You can build a relationship with
the characters. Maher is believable as a coming-of-age cop and,
frankly, it's good to see cops back in business because all those
lawyers are getting tiresome.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
