<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-COUNTRY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stone a mature voice in bubble gum village
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when it looked like he was perilously close to heading the
bus to Branson, last refuge for fading country stars, middle-aged
Doug Stone comes up with an album that puts him back in action as a
player on the youth-obsessed country scene. The 43-year-old
Georgian still delivers the same menthol-smooth sound that sent him
to the top of the charts in the early '90s with sweet songs about
people who punch time clocks and live in tract houses. After a
period of commercial doldrums (and some wobbly live performances),
Stone is still paying Hallmark card homage to the simple man who
rolls his cigarettes up in his T-shirt sleeve. This time, however,
he's picked an engaging set of tunes that complements his country
crooner voice, midlife perspective and working class point of view.
Stone's Southern-drenched accent is perfect on lyrics such as
``Blue bird sangin' on a redbud buddin''' (``One Saturday''), or
the gushingly sentimental ``the beauty I see can't be bought off a
rack'' (``Deeper Than That''). An album highlight is the trio of
``Dear John'' songs that captures the unbearable pain of being
jilted _ ``Not Me,'' ``A Room Without a View,'' and the duet with
Leslie Satcher, ``The Heart Holds On.'' In quite a contrast to the
bubble gum stuck all over country charts, Stone is the world-weary
guy at the bar wondering, ``What happened?'' So are a lot of
country music fans, who will welcome Stone back on this CD with a
raised glass and a toast.
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Make Up In Love''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Stone. Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
