<HEADER>
A5507 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS14-COX     10-13 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini audio reviews
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton, Richard L. Eldgredge and Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  FUNK-ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Soundsystem''
</P>
<P>
   311. Capricorn Records. 13 tracks. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Detroit could learn a lesson or two from 311. The workmanlike
Nebraska combo has taken a cue from Henry Ford, applied it to riffs
lifted from the Red Hot Chili Peppers and produced a new musical
model: assembly-line funk. Every note on the group's fifth studio
album hums with precision tune _ it's a mild motor-booty affair for
the SUV set. Cruising on a road-tested ska/hip-hop/light metal
groove, ``Soundsystem'' runs smoother than the band's self-titled
1995 breakthrough and has more engine power than the pokey 1997 dud
``Transistor.'' With all the emotion of a voice warning system
(``lights ... are ... on''), lead singer Nick Hexum delivers an
options list of be-yourself bromides such as ``Do what you feel,
the more absurd the better,'' from the fuel-efficient rocker
``Strong All Along.'' All in all, a dependable ride, though there's
little soul in this machine.
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  DANCE/POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Temperamental''
</P>
<P>
   Everything But the Girl. Atlantic. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Equally influenced by members Ben Watt's recent stints as a
late-night club DJ and Tracey Thorn's increasing passion for house
music, this British pop duo's ninth album may be the club album of
the year. While other pop stars have tinkered with drum 'n' bass
and house dance mixes, turning them into exercises of triviality
(Cher, for example, springs to mind), ETBTG raises the bar on the
genre by trading on its 15-year pop career as intelligent,
insightful chroniclers of the human condition. The act's best
weapon, Thorn's incomparably smoky alto, never gets buried in the
beats and lends a rich human warmth to a musical genre usually
dismissed by mainstream pop fans as cold and computerized. For that
reason in nightclubs, tracks such as ``Five Fathoms'' and ``The
Future of Future'' (a collaboration with Deep Dish) easily slice
through the smoke and din to caress and affect listeners. Uniquely,
the haunting intimacies of the sometimes lovelorn-heavy lyrics
enable ``Temperamental'' to be just as effective in your car stereo
system.
</P>
<P>
   _Richard L. Eldredge
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Da Grain''
</P>
<P>
   Youngbloodz. Ghet-O-Vision. 15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Though its music is Atlanta-specific and proud of it, one big
thing new rap duo Youngbloodz has going for it is the universally
loved hook. And mostly, only, the hook. If you're not familiar with
certain parts of this city, you may not understand how ``Everybody
say ...'' becomes the slang ``Now how we do it when we do it shorty
... .'' But when the hook (and the title) follows _ ``U-Way!'' _
you not only comprehend but want to yell along. Same goes for
Sean-Paul and J-Bo's ``Shakem' Off,'' another kinetic party chant
with an eerie hollow gurgle underneath. Similarly imaginative
production on ``Down Heya (In the South)'' and ``Pop, Pop, Pop''
help pass the time between yet another verse about going to the
Gentlemen's Club or a girl's house (certain hit single ``85''). But
there are way too few songs with something more than ``U-Way'' to
say.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton, Richard L. Eldredge and Sonia Murray write for
the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
