<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MAIN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's a lot to love about `10 Things I Hate'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``10 Things I Hate About You''
</P>
<P>
   (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'm wrong, but I think you can search all 37 of
Shakespeare's plays and not find a scene with a guy drawing male
genitals on another guy's face. That's one of the early clues that
this is a very loose version of ``The Taming of the Shrew.''
</P>
<P>
   The opening minutes cram in plenty of sex jokes, including a
porn novel the school counselor is secretly writing, which gives
characters a chance to say ``engorged,'' ``bratwurst'' and other
snicker-trigger words for its targeted teen crowd. But after a
terrible beginning, the movie starts to percolate with wit and
charm, thanks largely to its Kate-and-Petruchio stand-ins, Kat
(Julia Stiles) and Patrick (Heath Ledger). She's the elder of the
Stratford sisters (groan), one of those ``question authority''
girls who reads ``The Bell Jar'' and dismisses Ernest Hemingway as
an ``abusive alcoholic misogynist.'' No wonder she's unpopular,
while her kid sis, Bianca (Larisa Oleynik), is being cruised by
teen lothario Joey (Andrew Keegan).
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, their overprotective single dad (Larry Miller) won't
let Bianca date until her sister does. But when newcomer Cameron
(Joseph Gordon-Levitt) falls for Bianca, he schemes with pal
Michael (David Krumholtz) to arrange a date for Kat. Their man for
the job: Patrick, a longhaired transfer student shadowed by rumors
of a reckless past.
</P>
<P>
   Paid for the job, Patrick starts to woo Kat. You know what
happens next, especially if you've seen ``She's All That'': our
heroine's transformation, her trip to the prom and then the crisis
when she learns her new beau's actions have ulterior motives.
</P>
<P>
   The difference here is that Stiles and Ledger are captivating.
She nails her feminazi shtick, but just as easily melts into
giggles or pulls off a slapstick drunk scene. He's equally
comfortable playing a dangerous loner or doing a goofy song and
dance to impress her. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
