<HEADER>
A5513 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP14-COX     10-13 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A casserole that's worth the mess
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Robin Flanagan of Jonesboro (Ga.) said she was
desperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You published a terrific recipe ... a Chicken Enchilada
Casserole using at least two cans of Campbell's soup,'' she wrote,
hoping we could find it in the files.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe was published in 1994 with a story about Steve
Sheppard of Snellville, who said he made it only on special
occasions because it can be messy.
</P>
<P>
   A little mess won't deter Flanagan, though, who said she made it
for her family and they liked it so much that she made another one
the next day for a ladies' brunch. Then she lost the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's a kitchen without a little mess?'' she replied when we
asked her about it. ``I didn't find this recipe to be any messier
than anything else I have ever cooked. Besides, the compliments
were well worth the time put forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Such glowing praise makes us think other readers might like to
risk a little extra cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Enchilada
</P>
<P>
   Casserole
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 generous servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour, 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   20 8-inch flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   1 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 8-ounce packages grated cheese (1 Monterey Jack, 1 sharp
cheddar, 1 mild cheddar)
</P>
<P>
   2 cans (10 3/4 ounces each) cream of chicken soup
</P>
<P>
   1 can (10 3/4 ounces) cream of mushroom soup
</P>
<P>
   2 (16 ounces each) jars taco sauce (1 mild, 1 medium)
</P>
<P>
   1 (10-ounce) can diced tomatoes and green chiles
</P>
<P>
   3 (4.5 ounces each) cans peeled and chopped green chiles
</P>
<P>
   1 quart sour cream, divided
</P>
<P>
   4 fresh tomatoes, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 head of lettuce, shredded
</P>
<P>
   1 (16-ounce) jar taco sauce for serving (mild, medium or hot)
</P>
<P>
   1 large bag tortilla chips
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a large frying pan, heat oil over medium heat. Fry each
tortilla for 5 to 8 seconds per side. Remove to a plate and
separate each tortilla with a paper towel.
</P>
<P>
   Have ready 4 mixing bowls. In the first, combine all grated
cheeses. In the second, mix the soups. In the third, mix the two
jars of taco sauce. In the fourth, mix the tomatoes and chiles.
</P>
<P>
   On a large working surface, place 1 tortilla. Along the center
line of the tortilla, place 2 tablespoons of grated cheese, 1
tablespoon soup, 1 tablespoon taco sauce and 1 tablespoon of the
tomato-chiles mixture. Roll up tortilla and place at the end of a
13 1/4-by-9 1/2-by-2 3/4-inch lasagna baking pan. Continue to roll
up the tortillas and place them in the pan, packing tightly,
forming two rows of 10. When all the tortillas are rolled, pour any
remaining soup, chiles, taco sauce and cheese over them. Bake 1
hour or until bubbly. Spread 2 cups sour cream over casserole and
return to oven for another 10 minutes. Let cool 20 minutes. Slice
and serve in squares as you would lasagna. Serve with bowls of the
remaining sour cream, chopped tomatoes, shredded lettuce, taco
sauce and chips.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with all the sour cream, taco sauce and tortilla
chips): 1,024 calories, 31 grams protein, 66 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 58), 79 grams carbohydrates, 114 milligrams
cholesterol, 2,148 milligrams sodium, 6 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe request
</P>
<P>
   Robin Smith of Marietta (Ga.) longs for a thin, crispy pizza and
wonderful sauce like those bought in the 1970s at Gino's in
Marietta, now closed. The crust is thin, but it's not the texture
of a soda cracker, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for this column should be sent to Recipe
Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
