 Wednesday, Oct. 13, 1999     
 Editors     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file the following for Thursday and
Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-AGE-DISCRIMINATION (Washington) _ The Supreme Court
appears ready to deny state workers who believe they are victims of
age discrimination the right to sue their state employers under a
federal anti-discrimination law. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-PRIVACY (Washington) _ The Supreme Court weighs how far a
state can go to protect the privacy of its residents. The court
hears arguments over a California statute that prevents state law
enforcement agencies from releasing individuals' arrest records to
businesses that use them for pre-employment background checks and
other commercial purposes. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ In his zeal to escape the stigma
of right-wing negativism, George W. Bush seems to have learned a
lesson from the defeat of Republican presidential nominee Thomas E.
Dewey in 1948. The lesson is to avoid being weighted down with the
lackluster performance of a hardline conservative Congress. (For
release Sunday, Oct. 17.)
</P>
</TEXT>
