<SLUG> BC-SPCL-AIDS-AFRICA-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos and graphics are being sent to NYT clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 For Immediate Release
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; AIDS is ravaging sub-Sahara Africa, where last year 2 million
people died of the disease and some 22.5 million people now carry
the HIV virus. In a four-part series, the Globe examines the
horrific reality of the situation, including how people are coping
with life in the land of the dead and dying. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA-I (Johannesburg) _ Two million Africans south of the
Sahara died of AIDS last year. But that is just the beginning of
the devastation to come. By Kurt Shillinger. GRAPHIC (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA-I-DYING (Johannesburg) _ Pete and Sonny Boy couldn't
stop themselves. Sex and more sex was due them, they felt. Now they
are dying. By Wil Haygood. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA-II (New Tafara, Zimbabwe) _ Across a continent beset
by wars, famine, and misfortune, the AIDS epidemic has left
something else in its wake: millions of orphans. By Wil Haygood.
PHOTOS, GRAPHIC. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA-II-RAPE (Soweto, South Africa) _ A rape occurs every
26 seconds in South Africa, the highest rate in the world. And no
one denies it's adding to the AIDS problem. By Wil Haygood. 800
words.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA-II-PROSTITUTE (Carletonville, South Africa) _ Health
offcials say prostitution is playing a key role in fueling the
AIDS. By Wil Haygood. 920 words.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA-III (Rundu, Namibia) _ AIDS kills 10 times more
Africans each year than war and poses the single biggest threat to
development, yet few leaders have anything to say about it. By Kurt
Shillinger. GRAPHIC. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA-III-COUPLE (Lusaka, Zambia) _ For most African
women, having the AIDS virus is a multiple curse. It can lead to
rejection and violence. By Kurt Shillinger. 1255 words.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA-III-LAW (Johannesburg) _ The AIDS Law Project sees
the epidemic as a litmus test of the government's commitment to the
fundamental human rights enshrined in South Africa's new
constitution. By Kurt Shillinger. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA-IV (Undated) _ Stunned by the soaring number of AIDS
deaths in Africa, American black leaders are scrambling to call
attention to the crisis. By Wil Haygood. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA-IV-OUTSIDERS (Johannesburg) _ It is the aim of
Boston minister Eugene Rivers to stir the waters rather than still
them. By Kurt Shillinger. 960 words.
</P>
<P>
   For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Roy Greene  &LR; at the Boston
Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  All stories will bear the BOS designator and
move under the International (i) category code.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
