<SLUG> BC-BIONIC-LEG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERIZED LEG MAKES AMPUTEE'S GAIT EASIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Mike Tallman finally has a right leg that can
keep up with him.
</P>
<P>
   He lost his real leg 13 years ago on a curvy road in Louisiana
when the motorcycle he was driving hit a patch of sand and flew out
from underneath him. ``I pinched my leg between a culvert and the
motorcycle, and it sheared it off on the spot,'' said Tallman, 36,
who lives in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of other above-the-knee amputees in the United
States, Tallman adjusted to life with an artificial leg. The
problem was his mechanical leg never completely adjusted to him or
those daily spontaneous moments when he needed to stop short,
navigate stairs or keep his balance on an uneven patch of pavement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when I would be walking with my children and
one would suddenly step in front of me,'' he said. ``I would need
to hop-step or stumble to avoid hitting that child. I couldn't just
change my stride.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallman has since become the first person in the United States
to be fitted with a new computerized knee joint that can
practically anticipate his every move. Developed in Germany by Otto
Bock, a company specializing in prosthetic devices, the C-Leg, as
it's called, relies on a microprocessor and sensors to adjust to
changes in Tallman's gait.
</P>
<P>
   The result is an artificial leg that can take Tallman anywhere,
including down steep inclines and stairs _ two particular
challenges for amputees. ``It's almost like having your old leg
back, except you have to put it on every morning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Approved by the Food and Drug Administration over the summer,
the C-Leg took more than six years of development and costs about
$50,000. The leg, made of the same carbon graphite used to make the
Stealth bomber and powered by a lithium battery, has been available
in Europe and Canada since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big thing for above-knee amputees,'' said Bill
Sampson of Sampson's Prosthetic &AMP; Orthotic Laboratory in
Schenectady. ``This leg kind of does the thinking for them. It can
kind of know what a patient is going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Most prosthetic legs require amputees to watch where and how
they step to avoid losing their balance. While almost all
artificial legs use hydraulics similar to the C-Leg, the latest
innovation is a microprocessor to control the leg as it swings and
stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the single greatest advancement in
prosthetics in 30 years,'' said Brad Ruhl, director of sales and
marketing for Otto Bock's Minneapolis office, where Tallman
traveled in early September to be fitted with his new leg.
</P>
<P>
   Paddy Rossbach, of the Amputee Coalition of America, is
cautiously optimistic about a leg that could give amputees more
stability and smoother motion. ``I have not actually seen it yet,''
she said from her Long Island office. ``But if it's that good, it
would be wonderful if everyone could have one.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is cost. Company officials expect the price of the
C-Leg to eventually fall to between $30,000 and $40,000, it is
still two to three times more than current artificial legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is growing by leaps and bounds, unfortunately
reimbursements are going down,'' Rossbach said.
</P>
<P>
   Tallman, an Army veteran, is still waiting to see whether the
Veterans Administration will cover the cost of his new leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's worth every penny,'' he said. ``If I had a choice
between a $40,000 car and this, I'd take the leg.'
</P>
<P>
   An avid skier and outdoorsman before his accident, Tallman is
just as active today. ``I really don't consider myself handicapped
at all until Christmastime, when I use my plates for parking,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since September, seven people in the United States have been
fitted with C-Legs. Tallman was the first patient because the
company was familiar with the work done by Sampson's Prosthetics.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Sampson has since become one of only two people certified
on the East Coast to fit the C-Leg, which must be programmed for
each individual.
</P>
<P>
   ``The knee joint has given (Tallman) the ability to do more and
think less about it,'' said Sampson, who has no financial interest
in Otto Bock.
</P>
<P>
   With two children and a full-time job, Tallman doesn't miss
worrying. ``It's definitely going to be there for you,'' he said of
the C-Leg. ``It won't buckle out.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by electronic
mail at swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
