<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARIF-BAD-GENERALS-WORSE-OPED-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS, NOT GENERALS, MUST DECIDE THE FUTURE OF PAKISTAN  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY Editorial)   (This timely 575-word ``separate buy'' editorial is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By THE EDITORIAL BOARD OF THE INDEPENDENT  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Pakistan Wednesday, there were celebrations on the streets,
and few political tears. Few will lament the end of the era of
Nawaz Sharif, who was ousted as prime minister on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Elected in 1997, he had come to be deeply distrusted by his
compatriots. He was blamed for the state of the economy, whose
foreign debt runs to $32 billion.
</P>
<P>
   He was blamed, too, for the perceived humiliation that Pakistan
suffered in its abortive confrontation with India over the disputed
territory of Kashmir earlier this year. His style was autocratic;
he cracked down sharply on newspapers that dared criticize.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, the military takeover remains more of an almost-coup
than the martial full monty. General Pervez Musharraf responded to
the official announcement of his own arrest by putting his former
boss under house arrest, or, in one of those great official
misnomers, ``protective custody.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has not (yet) dissolved parliament. Nor, unlike previous
generals, who popped up to announce that they were ready to save
the country, has he declared martial law.
</P>
<P>
   It would, however, be disastrous if the world were simply to
shrug at the news of the takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan had a politically dodgy prime minister who was widely
held to be corrupt. But the need for a new prime minister is not
the same as the need for men in uniforms. Generals have ruled
Pakistan for half of its 52 years of independence, rarely to its
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill's remark that ``democracy is the worst possible
system, except for all the others'' is appropriate. Past experience
suggests that the chances that a general can solve the country's
problems are less than nil.
</P>
<P>
   Only if the military now sets out a timetable for fresh
elections _ which, according to the constitution, must be held
within three months _ is there a chance that things will get back
on track. (As the recent example of Nigeria made clear, generals
can help to lay the groundwork for a transition to democratic rule.
)
</P>
<P>
   The prospects for democracy have considerable knock-on
implications. It is notable that huge and chaotic India has
achieved political stability _ a point reinforced by the reelection
this month of the incumbent prime minister _ accompanied by
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   There is no intrinsic reason why Pakistan, though riven by
ethnic divisions, should not achieve equal stability. If the
generals want to be remembered as patriots, they must accept that
stability cannot be a synonym for suppressing democracy.
</P>
<P>
   This is particularly important, given that the international
tensions in the region remain high.
</P>
<P>
   Both India and Pakistan have carried out nuclear tests in the
last two years; they have so far refused to sign up for the
comprehensive test ban treaty that would end all testing.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a risk of nuclear confrontation, it is here that the
danger is most acute.
</P>
<P>
   Elections sometimes produce bad results. In a democracy,
however, the voters at least have a chance to change their minds
next time. Military rulers cannot so easily be got rid of when
their promises turn sour.
</P>
<P>
   If the generals use the ousting of Nawaz Sharif as an excuse to
stay in power in the longer term, the country's problems will only
go from bad to worse.
</P>
<P>
   The message must be clear: the political and economic freeze-out
will be total, if the military tries to consolidate its long-term
hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif bad; generals worse. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this timely 575-word commentary from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please
call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1452EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5572 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-SHARIF-BAD-GENERALS-W     10-13 0814
