</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARIF-COUP-BACKGROUNDER-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTANI COUP BEARS MUSHARRAF'S SIGNATURE  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This insightful 875-word ``separate buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By PETER POPHAM  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI _ The first Indians to discover something was badly
wrong in the high, bleak Himalayan mountains above Kargil this
spring were goatherds.
</P>
<P>
   They told Indian soldiers in the valley that there were
Mujahedin up there, Islamic guerrillas, camping on the peaks, deep
inside Indian territory. An Indian army patrol was sent to
investigate: none of them ever came back.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly Indian commanders and their political bosses began to
realize that they were confronting something awesome. This was far
worse than the intermittent artillery shelling from the Pakistani
side of the cease-fire line, the Line of Control (LoC) that had
rained on Kargil for the past three summers.
</P>
<P>
   Enemy forces, taking advantage of India's lack of vigilance, had
penetrated deep into Indian territory; hardened to Himalayan
altitudes, experienced mountaineers, the soldiers had scaled peaks
and ridges along an arc 150 kms (100 miles) long, establishing
bunker-like camps on the most commanding points, with lines of
supply reaching back into Pakistan-administered Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   It was the boldest and most brilliantly executed military
campaign in the history of Indo-Pakistani warfare.
</P>
<P>
   The Mujahedin on the peaks _ most of them actually regular
Pakistani troops in disguise _ stared down at India's National
Highway 1, the ribbon of road that links Delhi with Ladakh, the
highest and remotest region in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Acting as the eyes of the Pakistani artillery stationed beyond
the LoC, they had all the traffic on the road at their mercy.
</P>
<P>
   It took two months of massive effort by up to 60,000 troops,
backed by jet fighters and bombers, for India to begin to win back
the ground it had lost.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting between the world's two newest nuclear powers was
cruel and primitive. The Indian Air Force's aging MiGs strafed and
bombed the Pakistani positions, sometimes using napalm; the Bofors
guns thundered in the valley.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Indian infantry, roped together, hauled themselves up
hundreds of feet of sheer rock, with 50kg (110 lbs) loads on their
backs, many shot like rabbits as they hung there.
</P>
<P>
   They climbed only at night, then hurled themselves at the
Pakistanis as they reached the peaks, throwing grenades, storming
across minefields, finishing the fight man to man with knives.
</P>
<P>
   Every day the Indian commanders told the media back in Delhi of
new successes, new positions captured. But as the casualties
mounted into the hundreds, real success was elusive. Neutral
experts believed it would be nearly impossible to shift the
intruders before winter set in in September.
</P>
<P>
   Only when Pakistani prime minister Nawaz Sharif, under intense
pressure from India and the United States, ordered a withdrawal,
did the fighting stop.
</P>
<P>
   The architect of this Pakistani coup _ 500 men holding back
60,000 for months on end _ was the same man who emerged as
Pakistan's new strongman on Tuesday night: General Pervez
Musharraf, former commando, battle-scarred veteran of earlier
Indo-Pakistani wars.
</P>
<P>
   Both initiatives _ Kargil and the coup d'etat _ bear his
signature: boldness of conception, painstaking planning, ruthless
execution.
</P>
<P>
   But did he act alone? Deposed prime minister Nawaz Sharif's
allies and apologists have been spreading the word, since the
climbdown from Kargil ordered by the prime minister in early July,
that Sharif was out of the loop.
</P>
<P>
   Kargil, they said, was the army's show, and Sharif, the
``statesman'' who signed the Lahore Declaration with Indian prime
minister Atal Behari Vajpayee in February, only endorsed the
operation when it was too far advanced for him to call it off.
</P>
<P>
   For Sharif's admirers, this script has the advantage of making
him look like a man of peace, though also of weakness. It was a
view that the Indian defense minister George Fernandes voiced soon
after the conflict began.
</P>
<P>
   Especially for Indians it was a useful idea to hold on to:
Sharif, the friend of India, betrayed and trapped by his rogue,
fanatically Islamic army.
</P>
<P>
   But army and intelligence sources in Islamabad, as well as
well-placed foreign diplomats there, reject this account. The
informed consensus in Pakistan's capital is that the decision to
mount the Kargil campaign was taken last autumn, soon after General
Musharraf became chief of staff, with Sharif's knowledge and
approval.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness of the plan was that, while tactically brilliant,
strategically it was going nowhere. No defense expert in either
Islamabad or Delhi claims to understand what its strategic
objective might have been.
</P>
<P>
   But Sharif took plenty of decisions during his term as prime
minister _ threatening high profile foreign investors with jail,
for example _ which show just the same mixture of impulsiveness and
myopia.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif is now out of the picture, so his character flaws may
mainly be of interest to historians. General Musharraf, however, is
of more urgent interest, as he now has the fate of 140 million
Pakistanis and the peace of the whole South Asian region in his
hands.
</P>
<P>
   So far we see courage, boldness, decisiveness, but also military
tunnel vision, blindness to larger, non-military realities.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the Pakistani people early Wednesday morning,
he showed a keen understanding of where Nawaz Sharif went wrong.
But he has yet to begin demonstrating that he is better equipped to
set things right. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
