<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5579 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV1     10-13 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV17-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ATTACK ON CONGRESS SHOWS HE'S LEARNED A LESSON FROM THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 17)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients) ,
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his zeal to escape the stigma of right-wing
negativism, George W. Bush appears to have adopted the slogan of
the anti-Vietnam protesters who rampaged across the land three
decades ago: ``We're going to tell it like it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing to be a graduate of Jesse Ventura's Academy of
Iconoclasm, the affable and often vague Texas governor has attacked
old-guard positions, firing at presumed friends on the right rather
than announced foes on the left. To Bush, that apparently
constitutes telling it ``like it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Such behavior is not characteristic of cautious mainstream
Republicans like Bush. But the governor, who describes himself as a
``compassionate conservative,'' obviously has decided that he must
break out of the confines of myopic conservatism if he is to win
the votes of independents and even Democrats in November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone in trying to put a more moderate face on his
party. Arizona Sen. John McCain has been at the task for some time,
and Elizabeth Dole is pursuing a similar course.
</P>
<P>
   But because Bush is the frontrunner, his actions have drawn the
most attention.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers can cite many reasons for his stance. But
one is a lesson he might have learned from his father: Avoid being
weighted down with the pessimism of a right-wing Congress the way
Thomas E. Dewey was in 1948. That lesson remains pertinent today.
</P>
<P>
   Dewey, the New York governor who had defeated Ohio Sen. Robert
A. Taft for the Republican presidential nomination, toured the
country mouthing banalities in his magnificent baritone voice
rather than defining policies that ran counter to those emanating
from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Harry Truman, seeking a full term in the White
House, barnstormed the nation and, in his plain midwestern twang,
gave what he called the ``do-nothing,'' Republican-controlled 80th
Congress ``hell.''
</P>
<P>
   He also summoned Congress into a special post-convention
session, urging Republicans to act on major domestic issues as
promised in their platform.
</P>
<P>
   But the session ended without congressional action, and Truman
had his campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   Dewey did nothing to distance himself from the far-right barons
of Capitol Hill. He talked primarily of restoring national unity
and ending waste and inefficiency.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted Truman to assert that Dewey had given the term GOP
``another meaning ... Grand Old Platitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Dewey's cautious generalities and his refusal to stake out
positions independent of a Congress whose actions had antagonized
farmers, organized labor and consumers helped rob him of his life's
ambition to be president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters and journalists unanimously predicted his victory over
Truman, but when the ballots were counted, Dewey trailed the
president by more than 2 million popular votes and 114 Electoral
College tallies. (Dixiecrat candidate Strom Thurmond carried four
Southern states with 39 electoral votes).
</P>
<P>
   Bush does not want to get caught in a similar situation. But
Bill Clinton, who is supporting Al Gore for president, is
determined not to let him escape so easily.
</P>
<P>
   Asked his view of Bush's assault on congressional Republicans,
Clinton noted that the governor had supported the GOP's tax cut of
nearly $800 billion, which the president vetoed, plus efforts to
privatize Social Security, dilute the patients' bill of rights and
support the National Rifle Association's opposition to gun control.
</P>
<P>
   The battle, however, is far from over. Gore and Bill Bradley
should understand that if Bush is the GOP presidential nominee next
year, it will be difficult, if not impossible, to tarnish him with
the sins of the current Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Republican orthodoxy dictates that a candidate wrap himself in
right-wing ideology while seeking the presidential nomination and
then move to the center once the party has conferred its major
prize on him.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has defied that maxim. He first distanced himself from
congressional conservatives by taking issue with the House attempt
to delay payments to the poor under the earned income tax credit.
The budget, said Bush, must not ``be balanced on the backs of the
poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Bush declared that ``too often, on social issues, my party
has painted an image of America slouching toward Gomorrah. Too
often, my party has focused on the national economy, to the
exclusion of all else, speaking a sterile language of rates and
numbers, of CBO and GNP. Too often, my party has confused the need
for limited government with a disdain for government itself.''
</P>
<P>
   To conservative ideologues, Bush probably sounded like the late
Vice President Nelson Rockefeller, who is almost even with Clinton
on their hate list. One can almost hear them grumbling that George
W. is a replica of his father, President Bush, who is also viewed
with disdain by the right wing.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Texas governor is so far ahead of his Republican
opponents in the public opinion polls, he undoubtedly felt it was
safe and even wise to move now toward the center and away from the
militant right. Conservatives on Capitol Hill are so anxious to win
the White House and so certain that Bush can achieve that goal that
they appear willing to forgive him his outbursts against their
policies.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has taken a gamble, but it appears to be a safe
gamble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1456EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5580 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SOX-RIVALRY-2ND &LR;  &UR;      10-13 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SOX-RIVALRY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 Undated:... games to play.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   All they needed to do was win one of the final two games, with
two 20-game winners _ Mel Parnell and Kinder _ on the mound and
DiMaggio still weak from pneumonia. ``If we can't win one of two,''
Yawkey mused, ``we don't deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had a 4-0 lead on Saturday, with New York starter Allie
Reynolds in the showers early and manager Casey Stengel cursing in
the dugout. They lost, 5-4, when Johnny Lindell, who hadn't hit a
homer since July, ripped one down the left-field line with two out
in the eighth. ``I think we've got 'em,'' Stengel said. ``I can
feel it in my bones.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for a first-inning triple by Phil Rizzuto, which dropped
20 feet from sun-blinded Ted Williams, Kinder shut the Yankees down
on Sunday. But when the Sox couldn't crack Vic Raschi through
seven, McCarthy pulled Kinder for a pinch hitter _ and came up with
nothing. The Yankees nailed Parnell and Tex Hughson for four more
runs, held off Boston in the ninth and went on to beat the Dodgers
in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The devastated Sox got drunk on the long train ride home and
Kinder berated McCarthy for lifting him. ``Goddammit, if the old
man had let me bat for myself that day,'' Kinder said later, ``we'd
have won the pennant.''
</P>
<P>
   For a moment in 1951, after the Sox swept the Yankees at Fenway
in early July to move ahead of them, they thought they were on the
way again. ``Hey, looks like we'll be in the World Series this
year, baby,'' clubhouse boy Johnny Orlando taunted DiMaggio, as the
Yankees walked through quietly on their way to the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long ways to go, John,'' DiMaggio advised him. ``Don't count
your money. Long ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees ended up clinching the pennant by sweeping a
doubleheader from Boston at the Stadium, with Reynolds pitching a
no-hitter, and beat the Giants in the Series. The Red Sox ended up
third.
</P>
<P>
   There was no rivalry after that, not for two decades. The
Yankees won 11 of the next 13 pennants. The Sox, a country-club
team playing sandlot ball, sank slowly toward the cellar. In 1965,
when they lost 100 games and played a home game in front of 461
people, they were blanked for three innings by ancient Satchel
Paige, who was 59 going on 65.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Boston rose from the dead with the Impossible Dream
season of 1967, the Yankees were sagging and sullen. After pitcher
Thad Tillotson knocked down Joe Foy, who'd clocked a grand slam a
day earlier, Jim Lonborg plunked Tillotson and both benches
brawled.
</P>
<P>
   That was a prelude to the feuding and febrile '70s, when Athens
and Sparta went at it annually. In 1973, the clubs scrapped after
Munson slammed into Fisk on a suicide squeeze. In 1974, after
blowing a seven-game lead in late August, Boston and New York
helped wipe each other out. The Yankees won two at Fenway in
September; the Sox took a doubleheader at Shea a week from the end,
as Yankee fans littered the diamond with tennis balls and
firecrackers and fought among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Boston took three of four in Fenway to knock New York
out of first place in late June, then shut out the Yankees in both
ends of a doubleheader at Shea Stadium in July to finish them off.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, the bad blood spilled over in Yankee Stadium in May
when Dwight Evans gunned down Lou Piniella at the plate and
Piniella bowled Fisk, knees against chest. That touched off a
brutal brawl that ended with Mickey Rivers and Graig Nettles
mugging Sox pitcher Bill Lee and dislocating his shoulder _ and
essentially ending Boston's season.
</P>
<P>
   Owner George Steinbrenner and manager Billy Martin were
``Nazis,'' Lee would charge in 1977, when the Yankees overtook the
Sox down the stretch and went to the World Series. Martin sent Lee
a fish and a note: ``Stick this in your purse, you (expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   Martin was gone in 1978 and so, it seemed, were the Yankees, 14
games out in July. Boston was 62-28 and soaring _ until the
All-Star break. By Labor Day, the Sox were unraveling quickly and
the Yankees had won 13 of 15. That set the stage for the ``Boston
Massacre,'' a stunning four-game sweep in the Fens by astounding
scores _ 15-3, 13-2, 7-0, 7-4 _ that threw the clubs into a
first-place tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' muttered dumbstruck Sox skipper
Don Zimmer.
</P>
<P>
   After New York took two of three at the Stadium a week later and
began printing ALCS tickets, Boston was shaken and bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day you sit in front of your locker,'' said shortstop
Rick Burleson, ``and ask God what the hell is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston needed to win its final eight just to get into a one-game
playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way it should be,'' declared Yankee reliever
Sparky Lyle, a Sox refugee.
</P>
<P>
   After six innings, up, 2-0, the home team sensed a pennant in
the breeze. ``RED SOX AHEAD,'' proclaimed the Globe's
late-afternoon edition, which rolled off the presses just as Dent
stepped to the plate with two on and two out.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Torrez, whom Boston had signed away from the Yankees as a
free-agent amulet, watched Dent loft a routine fly to left and
began walking off the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I looked over my shoulder on the way to the dugout and
couldn't believe it,'' Torrez said. ``Yaz is back to the wall,
popping his glove, looking up. I said, `What's this? What the . .
.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees 3, Red Sox 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goddamn,'' Torrez said to himself. ``Goddamn, how could that
happen?''
</P>
<P>
   The next thing Boston knew, Yastrzemski was popping to third and
the Yankees were spraying each other with champagne.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 163d game, 5-4, with a man on third and two out in the
ninth,'' Reggie Jackson marveled.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 21 years, but here in Athens, Yaz is still staring
up at the sky, cursed and cursing. The Spartans have won three more
rings since then and Roger Clemens is vowing to win them another.
It is the final October of the 1900s, and destiny has brought the
Yankees and Red Sox together one last time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
