<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5597 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-COWS-NAMES-BOS &LR;      10-13 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWS-NAMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CANADA, GETTING BOSSY OVER BESSIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Clover is OK, ditto for Buttercup. But Suzie or Elsie
are definite no-nos.
</P>
<P>
   Daisy is borderline, and would probably require executive
approval before it could be bestowed on a cow _ at least on a cow
at Canada's Central Experimental Farm, a federal agricultural
museum and research center in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of bovine correctness coming to the barnyard.
</P>
<P>
   Instituting a policy that has raised bellows of derision on
farms across the land, bureaucrats have ordered the center to cease
the custom of giving ``human female names'' to cows because such
names might give offense to women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are ... sensitive to finding their name on an
animal. I am, for example,'' Genevieve Ste-Marie, director of the
National Museum of Science and Technology, which oversees the farm,
told the Ottawa Citizen. ``Let's say you came in and found your
name on a cow, and you thought the cow was old and ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Ste-Marie is responsible for the directive banning feminine
names for dairy cows. Instead, new cows at the government facility
must be provided only ``non-people names,'' such as Red-Leg or
Rhubarb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Animals should have their own names,'' said Ste-Marie.
</P>
<P>
   So Maple is fine, but Mabel is forbidden. Bossy gets the nod,
but not Bessie. Names unusual for women but not unheard of _ Skye
or Jewel, say _ will get the nay or yea on a cow-by-cow basis.
</P>
<P>
   According to officials, the change was instituted after a woman
visiting the research farm was insulted to discover she shared her
name with a cow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There had been a complaint raised that a cow was called
Stephani,'' said Michelle Dondo-Tardiff, director of the farm's
Agriculture Museum. ``It was a verbal complaint from somebody named
Stephani.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, Ariel, Becky, Lucy, Meg, Rosella, Veronica,
and the other 45 milk cows at the center _ even the offending
Stephani _ can continue chewing their cuds in contentment. The
original plan to change existing names was deemed impractical. And
the names of Dapple, Ghost, and Jello were safe from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Cows aren't the only critters under scrutiny. The rule will be
applied to sheep, pigs, horses, and other animals at the facility,
which is a popular destination for school tours and family outings.
</P>
<P>
   Male names may also be consigned to the dust heap of Canadian
farm history: No more Tom Turkey, no more Gilbert Goose, and,
presumably, no more pigs called Wilbur, as in E.B. White's classic,
``Charlotte's Web.''
</P>
<P>
   The move to squash sexism on the farm has touched off a
cavalcade of calls to radio talk shows and letters to newspapers.
Most citizens seem more appalled than amused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cows are wonderful animals and give us perfect food: milk,''
wrote Mildred Beechey of Ottawa. ``I'm proud to have `Millie the
cow' in the barn at the center. . . . My advice to this woman is to
change her name and leave the cows alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there are no hard rules for naming ordinary milk cows
on private farms, most are given female names _ although non-human
monikers are common.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a `Spiffy' and we've got a `Straw,' which aren't
girl names,'' said Angela Hamelin, who runs a dairy farm near
Kingston, Ontario. ``But usually we just give them female names _
`Donna,' `Debbie,' whatever. And yes, one of ours is called
`Angie.' Why would I mind? Cows are sweet and productive animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Registered cows _ that is, cows of pure stock, such as
Holsteins, Swiss, or Jerseys, whose bloodlines can be traced for
generations _ receive three names for record-keeping: the name of
the farm, the name of the sire, and the cow's ``personal'' name,
plus a number designating the cow's matriarchal line.
</P>
<P>
   Male cattle seldom get names because most are herded off to the
slaughterhouse before reaching maturity. There isn't a lot of use
for bulls down on the modern farm; almost all dairy cows are
impregnated by artificial insemination these days.
</P>
<P>
   The fuss over cow names has spawned a spate of humorous
complaints from people whose names might be associated with farm
creatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``How would you like to be named Bill?'' demanded Bill Steele of
Nepean, Ontario, in a letter to the Ottawa Citizen. ``How about
having a duck's nose named after you? That cuts me to the quick
every time I hear it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
