A5599 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-COURT-AGE14-COX     10-13 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-AGE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COURT TO RULE ON ALLOWING FEDERAL SUITS ON STATE WORKER AGE BIAS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A skeptical Supreme Court took up the question
Wednesday of whether states can be sued by their employees in
federal court for age discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   During oral arguments involving a trio of age discrimination
cases filed against state agencies _ including the Florida Board of
Regents, the Florida Department of Corrections and a state
university in Alabama _ the justices seemed reluctant to uphold a
1974 provision of the Age Discrimination in Employment Act that
extended its reach to the states.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether Congress exceeded its authority when it said
age discrimination cases against state agencies could be heard in
federal courts. Normally, states have immunity from federal
lawsuits under the 11th Amendment to the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 case involving the Seminole Indian tribe of Florida
restricted Congress's ability to override the 11th Amendment in a
law unless the lawmakers stated they specifically intended to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor noted that the 1974 discrimination
act never mentioned that Congress was abrogating the 11th
Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   But Jerome Collins, an attorney representing 36 faculty members
at Florida State University and Florida International University
and a state Corrections Department employee who alleged age
discrimination, said Congress had the power to override the 11th
Amendment because it specifically determined that false stereotypes
regarding age were being used by government agencies to
discriminate against the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Sutton, representing the Board of Regents, argued that
Congress overstepped its bounds in usurping the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``States are saying with respect to our own employees, we are
responsible for regulating them and making sure there is no
discrimination,'' Sutton told reporters after the hearing, noting
that ``the federal government doesn't allow states to bring suits
against it in state courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the elderly worried that the Supreme Court would
continue a recent pattern of siding with states rather than
Congress in assessing state immunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get an unfavorable decision, ... then millions of state
employees are left without any federal protection from age
discrimination,'' said Laurie McCann, staff attorney for AARP, the
nation's largest organization of older Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Although most states have laws against age discrimination, their
quality and enforceability vary widely, McCann said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are just words on paper. Depending on what state you live
in, you may or may not have effective protection from age
discrimination,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The court did not indicate when it would rule in the case, known
as J. Daniel Kimel Jr. et. al. v. Florida Board of Regents et. al.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
