<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-QUABBIN-UNDERWATER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS EXPLORE DEPTHS OF RESERVOIR'S HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUABBIN RESERVOIR _ The first visitors to the village of
Greenwich in 60 years wore diving gear, drifting down through
Boston's drinking water to reach the only paved road in town. For a
few surreal minutes, they returned to Depression-era America before
the rising water of the Quabbin Reservoir drowned the entire valley
and erased Greenwich from the map.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of reluctance to let researchers swim in a public
water supply, the Metropolitan District Commission is letting
divers explore the bottom of this reservoir, an engineering marvel
that cost 2,500 people their homes.
</P>
<P>
   In their first season of research, divers from the University of
Massachusetts already have discovered that Quabbin's builders
didn't remove everything before the flood. Empty graves, stone
walls, and cellar holes all rest beneath a layer of silt along with
the residue of everyday 1930s life such as glass milk bottles and
rusty buckets.
</P>
<P>
   And, in place of people, rare animals have moved in, including a
tiny worm with tentacles on its head that is believed to live
nowhere else in New England. Without intending to, say the
researchers, the builders of the Quabbin Reservoir may have created
a deepwater lake more like those of New England 10,000 years ago
than lakes of today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real goal is to find out what's living down there, since
no one has ever investigated,'' said Ed Klekowski, the University
of Massachusetts at Amherst biologist who organized the research
group. ``It was like a big, wet black box in Western Massachusetts,
and Boston was drinking it.''
</P>
<P>
   But in looking for life, the researchers are coming face to face
with the death of four towns _ Prescott, Enfield, Dana, and
Greenwich _ whose loss is still mourned weekly by former residents
who gather for Tuesday tea at Quabbin headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes an impact on your mind doing this,'' admitted
Klekowski, who plans to write a book about the experience. ``The
most poignant thing you see is the shrubs planted around
gravestones. Somebody planted this bush, probably a lilac, and here
it is underwater.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers initially feared their work would be seen as
desecration by former Swift River Valley residents, but, if
anything, many of them are intrigued at the hope of glimpsing, even
on videotape, their long-lost communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only regret is I wish I was with them,'' said Harrison
Thresher Jr., 85, who grew up in Greenwich, a stone's throw from
where the divers explored last week.
</P>
<P>
   Thresher, the son of Greenwich's mail carrier, recognized the
exact spot where Klekowski's team dove last week, on old Route 21
in front of a hotel that had burned down. Now under 54 feet of
water, all that remains is the elegantly cut stone wall and a
hitching post with a rusted ring at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its sad birth, the creation of the Quabbin Reservoir
stands as one of the Commonwealth's greatest engineering
accomplishments, providing the Boston metropolitan area with one of
the most abundant and purest water supplies in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   After years of study, but remarkably little attention to valley
concerns, the old Metropolitan Commission methodically dismantled
the towns, buying out residents, cutting down trees, and relocating
7,500 graves to empty the land. Then, a dam built on top of
Greenwich re-routed the Swift River so that it slowly flooded the
valley, which was plugged at the southern end by the massive Winsor
Dam.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the engineers created a water body quite different
from those around it. University of Massachusetts biologist Douglas
Smith said the lake resembles the waters of southern New England
2,000 years after the last ice age ended, before human pollutants,
organic matter, and sediment had time to build up.
</P>
<P>
   Almost no plants grow in the Quabbin, and its clarity is
unparallelled, allowing divers to see up to 60 feet.
</P>
<P>
   However, since the Quabbin is only 60 years old, Smith doubted
that Klekowski and graduate student Sean Werle would find anything
unusual when they began diving, along with state troopers, two
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``My assumption was that they would get whatever the Swift River
carried,'' said Smith. ``I've been pleasantly surprised all
along.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the divers have found three rare species, including a
worm called a freshwater polychaete that hasn't been found
elsewhere in New England. The fingernail-sized specimen is a
relative of Caribbean worms that use tentacles on their heads to
catch food. In addition, they have found a sponge that grows in
deep, clear water, as well as a mussel that is more typical in
streams, which tend to be cleaner than standing water.
</P>
<P>
   Smith suspects that these creatures probably lived in the
streams and ponds of the valley, and they prospered in the
artificially clean water of the Quabbin, even as they disappear
from other parts of New England where human runoff is changing the
water chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great big experiment from a biological point of
view,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for the biologists, the human stories beneath the Quabbin
are at least as compelling as the rare animals. Thresher, for
example, was born over the general store and post office in
Greenwich, where the divers explored last week, and his father
refused to leave even as the whole town was torn down around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very determined to stay to the last minute. He carried
the mail there 30 years. His grandparents and forefathers had lived
there for many years,'' recalled Thresher.
</P>
<P>
   And Klekowski's journal describes the eerie feeling of wandering
in dead towns, especially in the old cemeteries where demolition
crews left pieces of gravestones and other stonework behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``An opening appeared under me . . . filled with rotting leaves,
covered with a gray veil of water mold. I started to remove leaves
. . . when my fin slipped into the hole,'' he writes. ``The sides
were lined with brick, the hole was six feet long and shoulder
wide: it was a grave and I had one foot in it 50 feet underwater!''
</P>
<P>
   After 30 dives, Klekowski's team is finished for the season, but
he doesn't feel the research is nearly done, and he hopes the MDC
will give them permission to dive next year. At 30 minutes per
dive, the divers say they're leaving just as they are making
interesting discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just down there long enough for a snippet. There's a
whole photographic essay to be had down there,'' said Klekowski.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
