<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
14 VOLUNTEERS ON A MISSION OF MERCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You go abroad, you make a list, and don't forget the medical
supplies:
</P>
<P>
   Ace bandages, check; hypodermic needles, check; blood pressure
cuffs, check; toothbrushes by the hundreds, check; toothpaste,
natch, and combs, soap, shampoo, check; soccer balls _ soccer
balls? _ check. That's what the little Honduran kids kick around
while they're waiting for the medical team from Boston to treat
them or their families. So, soccer balls, check. Toyota Land
Cruiser? Alas, no Land Cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   When the 14 volunteers from Brigham and Women's Hospital in
Boston and Partners in Health assemble in Honduras Saturday, their
trek into the muddy hills of the countryside will commence in
borrowed or rented vehicles. Doctors, med students, nurses,
dentists, and dental assistants _ all are taking vacation time,
volunteering to serve some of the hemisphere's poorest peasants,
and paying $950 each for the privilege plus the cost of their plane
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   This is the eighth year for the Medical Mission, and this year
there will be eight week-long brigades that staff traveling clinics
in the mountainous Yeguare Region, where 50,000 people eke out a
precarious existence scraping food out of water-starved terrain.
Too much water was the problem in Honduras, which was devastated by
40 inches of rain dumped by Hurricane Mitch last year. That
destroyed roads, bridges, crops, and water supplies in a country
that didn't have enough to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks bring their supplies with them. ``They have no
supplies,'' says Linda Jo Stern, who directs the Brigham's Southern
Jamaica Plain Health Center out of a neat, new $5 million building
on Centre Street in Boston. ``Even before Mitch, these people had
nothing.'' Now there's even less.
</P>
<P>
   Stern, a cheerful self-styled '60s radical who was once arrested
in her Wisconsin student days for antiwar protesting, has mellowed
some. Married to a music industry executive and mother to a UMass
student, she planned on legging her way through the Tufts 10K road
race Monday before flying to Tegucigalpa to set up for the brigade
scheme. Stern and Dr. Helen Burstin of the Brigham's Upham's Corner
Health Center created the medical missionary organization from
scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We complement the Honduran medical services. We keep in mind
`hands, heart, head.' It's not just `gringos getting on an
airplane.' '' The needs are complex and interwoven: ``health,
nutrition, water, sanitation, and education.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern is a veteran of community and activist networks. She once
ran a food co-op and claims some mechanical training: ``I can fix a
car. I can drive anything. I guess you could say I'm a woman of
many spare parts.'' What she really craves is a new Land Cruiser
for the rugged backcountry the brigades must negotiate to go where
the patients are. ``They're really sturdy, have high axles. We'd
want a bright color, so they could see us coming from far off, no
browns or greens, you don't want to blend in.''
</P>
<P>
   When they settle in at their base camp in Zamorano College, this
month's brigade will include Stern, a Needham resident; Dr.
Burstin, an internist and team leader; Dr. Steve Lacy of the
Cambridge (Mass.) Health Alliance and his wife, Ricki, a nurse at
Cambridge City Hospital; Dr. Jennifer Kasper, a Jamaica Plain
pediatrician with experience in Nicaragua and El Salvador; dental
hygienist Carrie Thibault of Brookline, Mass.; dentist Tom Derosier
of Falmouth, Mass.; dentist Arthur Hannigan of Falmouth and his
wife, Leslie, a dental assistant; Sandy MacPherson, a nurse-midwife
from Reading, Mass.; Dr. Diane Brockmeyer of Roslindale, Mass.; Dr.
Emily Oken of Brookline; Dr. Gitta Rohweder of Hingham, Mass; and
two Honduran medical students, Mauricio Orellana and Jairo Valle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the kinds of people who like to go on these trips,''
Stern said proudly after listing her crew. She also tossed in a
bouquet for American Airlines. ``They do a fantastic job for us.
You see all those supplies in cartons down in the basement? They
crate those up and ship them for us. Todd Smith of American, he
should get a medal.''
</P>
<P>
   But nobody's doing it for medals or recognition. You give up a
week's vacation, you get your shots, you get to Logan with your
bag, and you drive for hours over bumpy mountain tracks, and when
you arrive, you give shots, set fractures, yank teeth, counsel
mothers, inoculate babies, commiserate with those beyond help, and
generally leave Honduras a little better off for your efforts. And
did I forget you pay a grand for the privilege? Because it is a
privilege to put your skills and succor in the service of your
fellow man, woman, and child, is it not?
</P>
<P>
   With or without a Land Cruiser, they do what they can.
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
