<SLUG> BC-BENNY-LETTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETTERS SHOW JACK BENNY'S RAUNCHY SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jack Benny wrote raunchy letters. Who knew?
</P>
<P>
   The man whose deadpan remains the nonpareil of stand-up comedy
loved to write gamy missives marbled with locker-room humor and
four-letter no-nos. His fifth-grade bathroom humor comes as a shock
to those accustomed to his droll, civilized presence on radio and
television.
</P>
<P>
   To testify that the letters are awfully funny is as meaningless
as it is to say that a woman is beautiful sight unseen.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a family newspaper and not the appropriate place to
plumb Benny's riffs on enemas and sex. Suffice it to say that to
read his letters is to shatter the sepulchral silence of the rare
books and manuscripts room of the Boston Public Library. Not to
worry. Roberta Zonghi, keeper of the collections, and her staff are
used to people wiping the tears from their faces as they read
Benny's account of his visit to the Mayo Clinic or his thoughts on
an African chief who spent four years blowing a coin through a clay
pipe.
</P>
<P>
   Benny's letters arrived at the library last year, when Zonghi
purchased more than 100 of them written to Frank Remley, his old
friend and admirer, for $39,000. The acquisition was designed to
augment its Fred Allen collection as well as leaven the library's
august treasure trove. Benny and Allen knew each other as fellow
radio luminaries. Allen, one of radio's most brilliant humorists,
was born in Cambridge, the son of a onetime bookbinder at the BPL,
and was a runner at the institution while a youngster.
</P>
<P>
   Benny penned scads of letters longhand from his home in Beverly
Hills and hotels from London to Sydney. The hotel stationery
includes marvelous telephone exchanges like Balzac 3530 for the
Georges V in Paris and ELdorado 5 2800 for the Sherry Netherlands
in New York. He usually pegged his thoughts to the ``Ripley's
Believe It Or Not'' staple that ran daily in hundreds of
newspapers. He would tear off the Ripley's item and include it with
his musings on the subject of the day.
</P>
<P>
   One could do worse than to spend an hour reading Benny's
missives. They make us like him all the more. We'd love to go to a
ball game with the guy because we now know that he could be
scatologically funny, too. Besides, his stuff is free and a far
better deal than another inane $8 Hollywood offering.
</P>
<P>
   My own favorite involves Emperor Vitellius, who, according to
Ripley's, ate 1,200 oysters in one meal. My lips are sealed. Again,
this is a family newspaper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
