<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-GENETOWN-USA-BOS-ART </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY ATTRACTS HYBRID OF START-UPS, ACADEMIA, DRUG FIRMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ His research subjects are swimming in a tank
of murky green water as John Shih explains how, by manipulating a
gene or two, he can enlarge a pancreas or grow saucer eyes on a
zebra fish. As senior scientist for a biotechnology firm, Shih and
his experiments on zebra fish offer clues about how human tissues
grow.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, Jill Mesirov sits in her office overlooking Kendall
Square, gazing into a computer screen displaying a wall of A's,
T's, G's, and C's _ code used by geneticists to represent the
building blocks of the human genome, which is the set of all genes.
Mesirov, a statistician at the Whitehead Institute, hunts for
patterns buried in the code that may link a specific gene to a
specific disease.
</P>
<P>
   A block away, Colin Dykes talks of a day when prescription drugs
are matched to a patient's gene profile to improve drug efficacy or
eliminate side effects. ``We are talking about a revolution in the
future of medicine,'' he says. ``I wanted to be part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dykes wanted it so much that he left London and his job at a big
pharmaceutical company a year ago to direct genomics research for
tiny Cambridge-based Variagenics Inc. Ten months before Dykes's
trans-Atlantic move, Shih had come to Cambridge from Pasadena,
Calif. Mesirov joined the Whitehead Institute as associate director
in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Each is engaged in his or her own arcane pursuits, but Dykes,
Shih, and Mesirov are all members of a community that sprouted in
Cambridge in just a few years to explore the medical and
money-making potential of information spewing out of research on
the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   The acceleration in recent years of gene discoveries is, as
Dykes said, a medical revolution, and it will take years to play
out. But the economic benefits of this revolution are happening
right here and right now in Cambridge, Mass. In Genetown USA.
</P>
<P>
   The magnet for this economic activity is the Whitehead
Institute/Massachusetts Institute of Technology Center for Genome
Research. The Cambridge research institution is among the leaders
in the Human Genome Project, a worldwide effort to identify 100,000
human genes.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Genome Project has not had as big an impact as the
Internet on the local economy. But the quest for gene-derived
drugs, therapies, and diagnostics is having a visible impact on
Cambridge, economists and experts in the field say.
</P>
<P>
   Small biotech companies trying to develop drugs based on
pioneering gene research are popping up in Kendall Square as
rapidly as bacteria in a petri dish. Pharmaceutical companies
searching for drug leads are swarming in to collaborate with
university professors and clinical researchers working in the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Funding for gene research in Cambridge attracted $18 million in
research funds in 1998 _ up $5 million in five years _ from the
National Genome Research Institute of the National Institutes of
Health. That's more than was granted to San Francisco and Berkeley
combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Boston area,'' said Eric Lander, head of the Whitehead
genomics center and unofficial mayor of Genetown, ``is one of the
hotbeds of genetics and genomics.''
</P>
<P>
   The gene boom is centered in Cambridge because the city _ with
its universities, entrepreneurs, medical research schools, and
biotech companies _ provides a potent brew in which a ``gene
industry'' is cultivated.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists bumping into each other in Kendall Square are
engaging in a continual dialogue about the newest news about their
own or colleagues' research. The cross-pollenization that occurs,
often between academics and private industry, is an invisible force
that drives the gene industry's growth, economists and industry
executives say.
</P>
<P>
   These conversations are ``like neutrons bouncing around a
nuclear reactor,'' said Elliott Hillback Jr., senior vice president
for Genzyme Corp. ``It's hard to prove it's even happening, but you
can feel the energy.''
</P>
<P>
   And the gene field is so hot that it has suddenly become cool to
be a biologist, a profession once relegated to dank labs smelling
of formaldehyde. At MIT, about 140 students declare biology as
their major _ double their numbers a decade ago, according to MIT
professor and Nobel Prize recipient Phillip Sharp, former chairman
of the biology department.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are increasing career and commercial opportunities in
the development and application of biological sciences to the real
world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp would know: He made millions by helping to found
Cambridge-based Biogen Inc. and is among at least a dozen
``biomillionaires'' recently identified in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
