<HEADLINE>
CHINA TOPS US LIST OF RELIGIOUS INTOLERANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   China was at the top of a list of seven nations the US State
Department said are of ``particular concern'' because of their
mistreatment of religious believers.
</P>
<P>
   Under provisions of the 1998 International Religious Freedom
Act, the seven are potentially subject to a host of economic
sanctions by the White House. However, the Clinton administration
can waive all sanctions for national security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The other nations cited were Afghanistan, Burma, Iran, Iraq,
Serbia, and Sudan. The list was announced this week as a follow-up
to a State Department report that described prohibitions placed on
religious freedom in more than 190 countries and territories.
</P>
<P>
   The report accused China of ``government intolerance'' of all
religions not officially approved by Beijing, including
Christianity, Tibetan Buddhism, and Islam. The persecution consists
of long jail sentences and the closing of religious sites, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   China dismissed those charges as false, saying it only
persecutes criminals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The official newspaper of Louis Farrakhan's Nation of Islam
said the destruction and death caused by Hurricane Floyd was
``God's judgement'' against the United States for the ``past and
present evil'' done to blacks and American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd slammed the Southeast in late September, killing more than
60 people, forcing thousands to flee flooded homes, and causing
billions of dollars worth of damage.
</P>
<P>
   The Final Call, the Nation of Islam newspaper, said in an
editorial this week that additional hurricanes, earthquakes, and
snowstorms would bring the United States ``to her knees'' unless it
repents for past and present injustices committed against blacks
and native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``God is angry with America and no federal funding can change
that _ true repentance and justice are the only way out, if it's
not already too late,'' the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The families of students killed in the April shooting at
Columbine High School have sued the Jefferson County School
District in Colorado, alleging they were barred from using
religious themes in a display of memorial titles in the school's
hallways.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed this week, says the school violated the
families' First Amendment rights of freedom of religious expression
and free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the midst of extreme sufferring and grief, the school
district's hostility to the religious beliefs that have sustained
these families is disturbing,'' said John W. Whitehead, president
of the Rutherford Institute, a conservative civil liberties group
based in Charlottesville, Va., that is representing the families.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego Ribadeneira,
Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
