<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITT REVEALS LITTLE; NEW YORKER'S UP-AND-COMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH CARNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As gimmicks go, the image of Brad Pitt lounging in a T-shirt
mini dress and shaved head on the cover of Rolling Stone is pretty
tame. An inside photo spread shows the actor flexing his biceps on
the beach wearing a strappy sequined number.
</P>
<P>
   What the accompanying profile fails to explain is why the
famously pretty star, now promoting his macho guy movie ``The Fight
Club,'' chose to pose in drag. Aside from acknowledging it was his
idea, Pitt has little to say about the attempt at
attention-grabbing (``There's nothing to talk about.'') He's
similarly tightlipped about having the caps on his front teeth
filed down for the role (``Not talking about it.'') and gets
animated only when arguing with interviewer Chris Heath about
whether it's fair to ask him if he plays up a dumb-blond image.
(Pitt thinks not). The piece's most articulate comments, in fact,
come from ``Fight Club'' co-star Edward Norton, who stands up for
Pitt: ``I think it's a shame if politeness and humility are
perceived as a kind of rube-ish disengenuousness.''
</P>
<P>
   More revealing is the magazine's profile of 18-year-old singer
Christina Aguilera, one in the stable of former cast members of
``The New Mickey Mouse Show'' (think Britney Spears, 'N Sync's
Justin Timberlake, and ``Felicity's'' Keri Russell) working their
way into the ranks of teen stardom, in Aguilera's case with a
rumored $1 million backing from RCA Records. When not cruising to
McDonald's in a stretch limousine, ordering around reporter Anthony
Bozza, and complaining about the back-stabbing in her high school's
cheerleader clique, the young singer apparently exhibits some real
talent. ``Christina threw me at first, because she could sing so
well,'' says David Frank, who co-wrote her current hit ``Genie in a
Bottle.'' ``In the teen-pop world, I've found myself in a room a
few times where no one could sing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Young up-and-comers are the core of The New Yorker's double
``Next Generation'' theme issue. Fifteen-year-old Concord novelist
Amelia Atwater-Rhodes, 17-year-old Def Jam Records' rapper Shanell
Jones (a.k.a. Lady Luck), 33-year-old Harvard economist Caroline
Minter Hoxby, and 8-year-old chess prodigy David Howell are among
the many precocious talents getting ink. One of the most absorbing
pieces, however, is 29-year-old New York writer/professional
personal essayist Meghan Daum's story about how she slipped into
$75,000 worth of debt while working as, by many measures, a
successful freelance writer in the most expensive city in the
United States. Daum's story is familiar to many of her peers: Her
debt can be traced to student loans she took out to finance a
graduate degree, dental work she paid out of pocket because she
couldn't afford insurance, and to the ``certain ephemeral
luxuries'' seen as necessities by her 20-something college-educated
urban demographic, like Starbucks coffee breaks and sushi lunches
and casual long-distance phone calls. In addition to illustrating
an increasingly common American predicament, the piece offers
insight to those of us who have followed Daum's regular column in
Self magazine and wondered why an obviously talented writer would
continue to turn her most trivial experiences into published
personal essays; she really needed the money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. magazine features a special report on Thailand's sex trade
and its effect on the girls and young women who support their
families by working as prostitutes. Betty Rogers describes how the
business has grown in the past 30 years to an estimated $4
billion-a-year industry employing several million workers. Rogers
visits the famous nightclubs targeting international tourists in
the Patpong district of Bangkok, and interviews teenage
prostitutes, many of whom work essentially as indentured servants.
Parents borrow money from club recruiters and hand their daughters
over to pay off the debt. As the economic collapse limits these
young women's career options further, Rogers finds that the
recruiting techniques have also changed; now more and more girls _
including undocumented immigrants fleeing nearby countries like
Burma, Cambodia, and Vietnam _ enter the trade voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spin magazine seems to have lost some of its wacky irreverance
since the firing of editor in chief Michael Hirschorn earlier this
year, but it still can be relied upon for informative, amusing
takes on various subcultures. In the November issue, Mike Romano
offers a story on the future of computer hacking as a means of
political protest, or ``hacktivism.'' The chief debate is whether
individualistic hackers are using their technological skills for
meaningful protest or simple vandalism. One of the more successful
hacks, a computer science student who goes by the name Bronc
Buster, managed to infiltrate the Chinese goverment's Web site and
replace it with a diatribe asserting the country's leaders were
``thugs and bullies.'' In retrospect, Bronc tells Spin he wishes he
didn't use a four-letter word ``after every other word.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
