<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5620 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-GENETOWN-USA-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     10-13 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENETOWN-USA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 CAMBRIDGE ,  Mass: ... identified in Massachusetts.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The downside of the gene boom for longtime residents of
Cambridge is that wealthy entrepreneurs and well-paid employees of
pharmaceutical companies are helping drive up rents and house
prices in a difficult real estate market. Young professionals who
snap up houses in East Cambridge to be close to Kendall Square feed
a real estate boom in neighborhoods that once were a key location
for low-cost rental units.
</P>
<P>
   Some Cambridge residents complain the high-tech, biotech boom
has robbed the city of its shabby-chic charm. In the ``new
Cambridge,'' the Blue Room restaurant in Kendall Square is often
packed with MIT scientists or biotech executives who amble over for
roast chicken at $18 a plate.
</P>
<P>
   Money is flowing into Cambridge due to the Human Genome Project,
which has rejuvenated a biotech industry that never fully recovered
from a late-1980s crash, economists and industry executives said.
</P>
<P>
   The formation of firms searching for gene-based drugs has helped
propel New England past San Francisco for the first time, according
to a January study by the accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young. In 1998,
New England had a total of 193 biotech firms; the Bay Area had 185.
</P>
<P>
   No data exists on how many jobs have been generated by the
explosion in private and public gene efforts. Cambridge employers
range from a large company, Millennium Pharmaceuticals, which
employs more than 800, to Harvard University's newly established
Center for Genomics, which expects to employ about 60 people in two
years.
</P>
<P>
   But the gene boom has helped fuel a tripling, to 25,000, in
employees in Massachusetts' biotech industry since 1991. A study on
the state's pharmaceutical industry by Anurag Sharma, business
professor at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, found the
genome project was responsible, directly or indirectly, for a
significant share of a doubling in research jobs, to 12,538,
between 1995 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The genome project is ``attracting a lot of investment and
jobs,'' Sharma said. ``It's going to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic trend has been a sudden influx into Cambridge
of giant pharmaceutical companies, many of them in the past two
years, to set up research facilities. The list is a Who's Who of
German and US companies, including Bayer AG, Hoechst Marion
Roussel, BASF Research Corp., Merck, American Home Products Corp.,
Amgen Inc., and Bristol-Meyers Squibb Co.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmaceutical giants are in a desperate ``land grab'' to secure
patents on genes or drug targets as soon as they are uncovered from
research scientists. These companies sense that gene-based drugs
may change the shape of the entire industry, and they want to be in
on it.
</P>
<P>
   When W. Stephen Faraci is not recruiting employees for Pfizer
Inc.'s new research center in Cambridge, he is courting MIT and
Boston University professors or physicians at Children's Hospital
and Massachusetts General Hospital for research collaborations that
may provide drug targets the parent company's scientists can
pursue.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer's Drug Discovery Center opened a year ago on Memorial
Drive and employs 30. ``We're trying to find the stuff that's brand
new. You have to go to the genome for that,'' said Faraci.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of success pharmaceutical giants are looking for may be
close at hand for tiny Ontogeny Inc. in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Ontogeny's chief executive, Doros Platika, hopes to bring the
firm's treatment for basal cell carcinoma, a skin cancer, into
clinical trials within the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the treatment is the ``hedgehog'' gene, which
controls cell growth in humans _ and zebra fish. To oversimplify,
skin cancer is caused when the switch in the hedgehog gene
malfunctions and won't turn off cell growth, as it should. ``It's
like the accelerator getting stuck,'' Platika said. ``We have a
drug that unsticks the accelerator.''
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by his fish tanks and lab equipment, Ontogeny's
senior scientist, John Shih, explains the advantages of
experimenting on fish: the zebra fish develops from embryo to fully
developed fish in one day. ``You can have a sound set of
experiments in two days,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Shih is typical of the scientists in the gene field who are
drawn from top-drawer universities or research institutions into
private industry. He received a doctorate from the University of
California at Berkeley and completed post-doctoral research at the
California Institute of Technology in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   Dari Shalon straddles both worlds, academia and private
industry. He moved to Harvard Square from the Bay Area this summer
after accepting the job as the first director of Harvard's Center
for Genomics.
</P>
<P>
   Shalon holds a computer chip that reads gene sequences _ a chip
he designed as his dissertation project at Stanford University and
turned into a personal fortune by founding a California company to
make them. He sold the company, Synteni, in December 1997 for $100
million to Incyte Pharmaceuticals Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the best biological science is being done by companies
doing basic R&AMP;D on diseases,'' Shalon argued. ``I feel comfortable
in both.''
</P>
</TEXT>
