<HEADLINE>
FOR COMPANIES, CREDIBILITY COUNTS ABOVE ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, how's the new job going?
</P>
<P>
   If anyone has even an inkling of how Raytheon Co. chief
executive Daniel Burnham feels this morning, it might be Michael
Hawley, the CEO of Gillette Co.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham and Hawley both recently replaced larger-than-life chief
executives at leading Massachusetts companies and soon ran into
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham, a former vice chairman at Allied Signal, took over last
summer for Dennis Picard, who had steered Raytheon to an unlikely
survival in the great defense industry consolidation with a series
of bold deals. This year Hawley succeeded Al Zeien, who boosted
Gillette's stock market value tenfold in eight years with a long
list of consumer products like the Mach 3 razor.
</P>
<P>
   Neither company will remember 1999 as a glory year.
</P>
<P>
   Worse than simple business disappointments, Raytheon and
Gillette dinged their long-standing reputations as financially
dependable and credible producers with unexpected bad-news bombs
this year. Real credibility is a serious asset on Wall Street and
it hurts to chip away a chunk.
</P>
<P>
   The news at Gillette seemed unpleasant enough, failing to make
good on a promised second-half sales rebound, and it has battered
the company's stock by 23 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   But that turned out to be a walk in the park compared with the
truly breathtaking turn of events at Raytheon Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, it did not look as though shares of the nation's
third-largest defense contractor would even open for trading on the
New York Stock Exchange. When they finally did late Tuesday
afternoon, the people who wanted to sell at any price did just
that, and the company's market value plunged by 46 percent, to 24
1/4, in about one hour. Nearly $8 billion in value vaporized.
</P>
<P>
   If pressed to guess, we would expect Raytheon shares will regain
a part of that loss Wednesday. But in some ways, the selloff
Tuesday was even worse than it appeared. After all, this was a
stock that traded for 68 per share just five weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   This may be the common fate of an Internet company that misses
its quarterly forecast, but it is uncharted territory for an
industrial giant like Raytheon.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the financial setbacks alone hurt Raytheon stock. But
the gap between the company's view of business just a month ago
(wary but not bleak) and what it said Tuesday generated a wave of
no-confidence sentiment from analysts who follow the stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the reason, they didn't communicate the problems,''
said analyst Robert Friedman of the Standard &AMP; Poors Equity Group.
``It seriously damages the credibility of management with
investors.''
</P>
<P>
   The company issued a statement about its latest problems Tuesday
morning, and then Burnham participated in what can only be
described as a grueling conference call with stock analysts for
about two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst calls are usually polite and numbingly dull affairs but
the tone Tuesday was distinctly prickly. At one point, Burham said
he was going through the unpleasant exercise to help restore
credibility and emphasized the demand for candor inside the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've told people don't hide behind hope, don't hide behind
commitments to previous leaders. That's the tone here. We hope it's
resonated throughout and we think it has, but nobody can guarantee
anything. We think we have plumbed the depths.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Raytheon is that you can win back investor
confidence. The bad news is that it only happens in a series of
small steps that can take years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The friendly banker?
</P>
<P>
   Richard Chapman has done a lot of things to employ the millions
his Brookline Bancorp raised from its 1998 stock offering, from
repurchasing shares to seeding an Internet bank start-up.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has applied to regulators for permission to buy up to
24.9 percent of Medford Bancorp, viewed by some as a potentially
hostile advance on the holding company that owns the $1.2 billion
Medford Savings Bank.
</P>
<P>
   No way, says the Brookline Bancorp chief exective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been misinterpreted and we're probably going to amend
it,'' said Chapman. ``We're friendly, long-term investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Hostile bids for banks are extremely rare and any takeover of
Medford Bancorp would require a two-thirds majority vote of
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Medford chief executive Arthur Meehan declined to comment about
the Brookline stake in his company.
</P>
<P>
   The request filed with the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston
disclosed that Brookline Bancorp already owned 4.9 percent of the
Medford banking company, the maximum allowed without requiring
disclosure and regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   Practically all of the stock was purchased in a single block on
April 9, according to James Moynihan, the Advest Inc. executive who
brokered the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman said he wanted to buy more stock when Medford shares
fell below 15 per share last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt very frustrated,'' he said. ``The price was in the
basement as far as we were concerned and we couldn't do a darn
thing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chapman noted that a shareholder rights plan at Medford Bancorp
would be triggered if any single investor amassed a 15 percent
interest in the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no intention of going above that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
