<SLUG> BC-EASYRIDERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASY RIDERS ARE HARD TO FIND BACKSTAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the president of downtown Fort Worth's live-music palace, the
Caravan of Dreams, Jerry Thompson has his share of ``rider''
stories to tell.
</P>
<P>
   Like the time metal act Dream Theater requested six pairs of
clean underwear.
</P>
<P>
   Or the time guitar hero Buddy Guy asked for a $175 bottle of
whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Judas Priest's ludicrous request: strippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ask for the world, and we more than take care of them,''
Thompson said. ``But we also draw a line in the sand. I gotta cross
out a lot of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   A ``rider'' is a list of items that a band or artist wants/needs
before, during or after the concert. Band writes it. Management
faxes it. Venue checks off or crosses out items, sends back to
management and band. Band usually frowns.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, venues are not contractually obligated to fulfill
them. Riders, in other words, are simply wish lists, composed of
the usual (food and beverages) and unusual (see above).
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the bigger the act, the bigger the rider. It's
not uncommon for big-name artists to request hotel rooms and
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   In the '70s and '80s, riders rose to ridiculously excessive
heights, a reflection of rock's extravagance and overindulgence.
Venues often wound up spending as much or more money on riders as
on the band.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do a show and pay a band X amount of dollars, and the
rider can be an extra two or three thousand dollars,'' Thompson
said. ``You pay them $100,000, that gets them on stage. But there's
a lot of freight to get them there.''
</P>
<P>
   Area venue owners and promoters say that although the concert
industry has been steadily cracking down on rider expenses, goofy
oddities remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some bands request stuff just to see if they can get
away with it,'' said Kris Youmans, who helps book Rubber Gloves
Rehearsal Studios, a Denton, Texas-based venue that caters to
underground rock bands.
</P>
<P>
   Youmans recalls the time that indie-rock heroes June of 44
played there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted a copy of that day's New York Times and (band
leader) Jeff Mueller wanted a fresh thing of drum tobacco so he
could roll his own cigarettes. Just real obscure stuff that there's
no way we're gonna go out and get for 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Another odd Rubber Gloves request came via punk-pop outfit
Servotron.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted four cans of WD-40 and all these batteries,'' said
Robin Phillips, who also books Rubber Gloves concerts. ``They dress
up like robots and they have all this metal stuff that they have to
oil. I was like, `No way. Batteries not included.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That's nothing compared with the humorous horror stories that
have leaked out of Starplex Amphitheater's backstage area in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   According to a backstage source who refused to be named _ they
need their jobs, after all _ one A-list R&AMP;B star insisted on having
a special toilet seat when she played there last year. ``It was
supposed to be a certain kind, with a certain type of cushion. Took
us forever to find one and apparently, she just used it once, then
threw it away.''
</P>
<P>
   The all-female tour Lilith Fair, the Starplex source says, was
another nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine. They wanted all this specially prepared,
fussy food. Some of the (performers) were hard-core vegetarians, so
they'd be like, `No this, no that. Can't eat that, can't drink
this.' They were real nice, but it was a major pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Big names don't always equal big riders, though.
</P>
<P>
   One of pop and country music's most successful _ and elaborate _
performers is also one of its most low-maintenance: Reba McEntire.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has no rider,'' said Thompson, who has worked on past
McEntire shows. ``She just says, `Please provide a hot meal for me
and my people' and that's it. That's the only thing she asks for.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, McEntire's not the norm. But, Thompson says, a lot of
performers are starting to follow her bare-necessities needs: A
good slice of performers are just asking for nutritious meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a move toward healthier ... food,'' he
said. ``Some of them are strict about it, too. Eric Johnson
requests pasta with no MSGs. And all David Sanborn eats is papayas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old days of rock are still around, just not as much as
they used to be,'' Thompson said. ``We still get acts that request
marijuana, but of course, we don't deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew writes on pop music for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
