<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-SOFTBALL-BOS </SLUG>
 NGES PLANNED IN WOMEN'S SOFTBALL LEAGUE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some big changes are in store for the three-year-old Women's Pro
Softball League in this upcoming Olympic year, and some will last
well beyond 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Next summer, with the US national team's drive to defend its
Olympic gold medal in full swing, the WPSL will reorganize to give
the team someone to play on a national tour. Instead of six teams
in North Carolina, Georgia, Virginia, Florida, and Ohio, the league
will cut back to two teams in the Akron area _ whose Racers enjoyed
the best attendance in the league, averaging 1,200 to 1,500 per
game _ and two near Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, a pair of teams will play each other and a third will
conduct camps and clinics, while the fourth will play the national
team. Tour dates and locations have yet to be announced, although
up to 20 are being considered.
</P>
<P>
   Two league members, Crystl Bustos and Michelle Venturella, are
among the 15 players recently named to the national team.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization will also give the league a chance to
reevaluate itself. Except for Akron, attendance has been
disappointing, and league spokesman Drew Russell said there are no
plans to return to either Gastonia, N.C., or Columbus, Ohio, after
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be seeking new cities on this tour,'' he said,
to be included when the league resumes a normal structure following
the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   Despite attendance so low that the league won't disclose figures
for anywhere but Akron, TV ratings have been more than favorable,
with about 205,000 households tuning in each time a game is shown
on tape delay on ESPN2. That's comparable to the audience for
National Hockey League games shown on the same channel.
</P>
<P>
   In other league action, a national tryout will be held Dec. 5 in
St. Petersburg, Fla., with all women's fastpitch players who have
completed their collegiate softball eligibility invited to
participate. For more information, call Hildred Deese, director of
game operations for the league, at 303-316-7800.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
