<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JIMMY JOHNSON IS STILL IN THE CHASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To Jimmy Johnson, this pursuit is not trivial. He's tired of
trying to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year it seems like we are always chasing somebody,'' the
Dolphins coach said Tuesday. ``The first couple of years it was New
England. Then the Jets last year, now it's New England again. I
would like to see that change.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson knows it will have to start changing Sunday in
Foxborough, where he has not had a lot of good fortune. Johnson has
never beaten the Patriots in New England as the Dolphins coach, and
if he doesn't do it this week he will be chasing them down the
stretch one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at them on film and they are playing very well,'' said
Johnson. ``Bledsoe is doing everything with such a nice rhythm.
There is only a handful of times in the games we've looked at that
you don't see that. And every where you look, you see Terry Glenn.
We know we are going to have to do something to handle Bledsoe and
Glenn to have a chance to win this game up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is very concerned about New England's offense, because
his highly regarded defense was ripped apart by the Colts last
Sunday in Indianapolis. The Colts have the same kind of offense as
the Patriots with a great pitch-and-dash team of Peyton Manning and
Marvin Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really disappointed with the way we played defense in
Indianapolis,'' said Johnson. ``It hurt us that Terrell Buckley,
one of our best cover guys, hurt his ankle and wasn't available.
But our offense came alive in the second half and we came back to
win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami is 3-1 and tied with Buffalo for second place in the AFC
East. New England is at the top at 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``This division is going to be a wild scramble,'' said Johnson.
``The Jets are down, but they will knock off some contending teams
when this is finished. The Colts are the most-improved team, and I
think they will be in it all the way. Buffalo has a great
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami's defense played well in the season's first three games
before giving up 31 points to the Colts. However, their offense
stumbled and staggered in games against Arizona and Buffalo, losing
to the Bills and Doug Flutie at home.
</P>
<P>
   Miami plays much better defense at home than on the road. Last
year the same defensive group fell apart in the second half in
Foxborough, when the Patriots came from 16 points behind to earn a
great victory in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson feels his offense found the answer to scoring points
with its game-winning outburst in the second half against the
Colts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to spread the ball around more in our passing
game,'' said Johnson, who publicly criticized quarterback Dan
Marino after the loss to Buffalo. Johnson pointed out the fact that
wide receiver Tony Martin, signed as a free agent in the offseason
to be a deep threat, caught just two passes against Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony caught 10 passes against the Colts, and many of them were
big plays,'' said Johnson. ``He's very important to what we are
trying to do and we have to get him the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still not running the ball well. This team hasn't run
the ball for 15 years,'' Johnson said with a laugh. ``We thought it
would be better but it hasn't turned out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami has been without Richmond Webb (knee) and Mark Dixon
(groin), two of its best offensive lineman. Johnson says he hopes
to have both back Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose this game, we will be behind the eight-ball the
rest of the way,'' said Johnson, knowing he has already lost to
Buffalo at home and has to try to beat New England in Foxborough
and Buffalo on the road.
</P>
<P>
   New England-Miami games have been special the last two years.
All four have been decided by 3 points or less, and one in
overtime. The teams are very well-matched; both rely on the pass
and can't run. Both are aggressive on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriots are playing much better defense than their stats
indicate,'' said Johnson. ``They have been very physical. I was
impressed when I watched them on film. As a team we know we are
going to have to give it our best shot to win up there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
