<P>
   LAS-VEGAS (Las Vegas) _ When Tom Wolfe wrote about this gambling
oasis in the early 1960s, he reeled: ``Such colors! All the
electrochemical pastels of the Florida littoral.'' Today he would
be struck dumb by ... such details! Las Vegas on the cusp of the
millennium is decked out with all the frills of the Renaissance. By
Frances Anderton.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH-SHOWCASE (New York) _ Colette, the French writer, said
that you shouldn't eat truffles unless you can eat them like
potatoes. She would have loved the 1999 French Designer Showhouse,
which opens Thursday. It would stop a rooting pig. By William L.
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ROCKEFELLER-APARTMENT (New York) _ Sixty-five years ago, a brash
young millionaire named Nelson Aldrich Rockefeller bought the top
floor of 810 Fifth Avenue, at the corner of 62nd Street, then the
southernmost apartment house on upper Fifth Avenue. Last week, a
big chunk of that apartment went on the market; priced at $19.5
million, it may be New York's most expensive fixer-upper. By Tracie
Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA-U.S.-EMBASSY (Ottawa) _ The glassy new mission building
here makes a dramatic statement for an endangered species: the
urban American embassy. By James Brooke.
