Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With how to drawing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CIRCUITS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CYBORGS-FASHION (New York) _ Thad Starner, a 29-year-old
assistant professor at the Georgia Institute of Technology,
considers himself one of the first cyborgs _ an acronym for
cybernetic organism, a being that is part machine, part human.
Cyborgs wear their computers almost continuously. They get e-mail
on their eyeglasses while they're talking to you, and now they've
recruited models to try to make the idea of wearing a computer, all
day every day, the new thing. A series of fashion shows at a
computer trade show last week gave a glimpse into what happens when
the worlds of technology and fashion try to converge instead of
collide. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   With sidebar, CYBORGS-COMPONENTS, Essential components for
cyborgs.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ONLINE-SPIN (Undated) _ When a company's products or
policies come under fire in an outbreak of chat room outrage, one
way to cope is to plant a defender (sometimes incognito) to try to
spin the discussion in a new direction. (``Come on guys, not all of
the gas tanks explode.'') As a result, a small industry is emerging
among consultants who specialize in spinning online discussions to
favor the positions of companies and interest groups. By Rebecca
Fairley Raney.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ With a microscope attached to a
computer, kids now can look at insects, hair, and that strange rash
on a 17-inch monitor, and send digital pictures to friends and
family. By Peter Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-INDIANS-TRADE (Undated) _ Native Americans are using the Web
to revive old trade routes. By Jonathan Lesser.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-SATELLITE-PHOTO (Undated) _ Evolving use of satellite
imaging in law and other areas. By Peter Wayner.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-WORDS-ONLINE (Undated) _ Word sites and dictionaries on the
Web. By Bonnie Rothman Morris.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-FREE-LANCE-HELP (Undated) _ Free-lance is just another word
for nothin' left to lose: sites that offer help to free-lance
workers in various fields. By Deborah Branscum.
