<HEADER>
A5643 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     10-13 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEEL INSTEAD OF WOOD FOR HOMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The vast majority of the houses built in the United States today
are constructed with wood. About 85 percent of that wood is used
for framing. Since wood has been the primary building material
since Colonial times, it might seem that there is no reason for
change, but wood has its drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   In the first place, the supplies of old-growth timber are
diminishing. This has caused the price of construction lumber to
rise dramatically over the last few years. It has also forced the
lumber industry to harvest wood from young trees. This new wood has
a greater tendency to warp and split as it ages. This results in
cracks and warping appearing throughout the house soon after it is
finished.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, some builders are looking for alternatives to
wood as framing. One possible substitute is steel. Steel can be
cold-rolled into pieces that are roughly the same size and shape as
dimensional framing lumber, so they can be used for studs, joists
or rafters. The pieces are rolled into a C cross section _ for that
reason they are called structural-C members, C-members or simply
C's _ and are coated with zinc to make them rust resistant. They
are also available with prepunched slots so electrical wires and
plumbing lines can be run through.
</P>
<P>
   For load-bearing walls, structural members are available in 16-
to 20-gauge thicknesses. Studs for nonbearing walls are available
in thinner 25-gauge steel. These pieces are lighter in weight,
easier to cut and less expensive than the heavier gauge pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike wood, steel is structurally stable and uniformly
straight. That means that walls, floors and ceilings can be
constructed so they are truly flat, plumb and level. Steel is
moisture-resistant, so it will not dry out and warp nor will it
expand in humid weather. Steel framing is also fireproof and free
from rot and insect infestations.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, steel framing is not significantly less expensive
than traditional dimensional lumber, but representatives of the
steel industry point out that prices are relatively stable, while
lumber costs are rising. In the coming years, it may be more
economical to purchase steel framing.
</P>
<P>
   Does all this mean that wood-framed houses are a thing of the
past? Probably not. Right now about 1 percent of the houses
currently being constructed in the United States have steel
framing. The iron and steel industry hopes to entice more builders
into using steel framing, and they predict that by the end of the
next decade, 25 percent of residential homes will be framed with
steel.
</P>
<P>
   Steel framing, however, has a downside. The biggest drawback to
using steel is that steel is a good conductor of heat. A steel stud
will conduct 10 times more heat than its wooden counterpart. This
means that a warm house can quickly lose much of its heat through
the outside walls if they have steel framing. Extra insulation will
not prevent this, because the heat that enters into steel studs
quickly travels laterally through the framing to the outside of the
house.
</P>
<P>
   Builders try to prevent heat loss by sheathing the outside of
the house with high-density foam board instead of the usual plywood
or particle board. This slows the heat transmission through the
walls, but it has little effect on heat loss through the ceiling.
Manufacturers are designing steel structural members with raised
knobs along the edges that minimize the contact between the
wallboard and the studs. This effectively creates a thin barrier of
air that insulates the stud from interior heat. Other manufacturers
are planning to introduce an insulation tape that can be applied to
the stud before the wallboard is installed.
</P>
<P>
   Another drawback to using steel for construction is that most
professional carpenters are not used to working with it. It's true
that working with steel does not require any arcane skills or even
sophisticated tools; still many carpenters make no secret of the
fact that they would rather work with wood.
</P>
<P>
   With a circular saw, a profession carpenter can quickly cut a
dozen wooden studs to length in less time than it would take to
trim six steel studs with a reciprocating saw or a circular saw
with an abrasive wheel. So the amount of money saved by buying
structural steel may be lost in money spent for increased
construction time, although this is not likely to remain a
significant problem as more builders experiment with steel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
