r s BC-BKN-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-13 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILT CHAMBERLAIN: A COLOSSUS IN MORE WAYS THAN ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``Bigger than life''' means whatever the user of
the phrase wants it to mean. For me, it was Wilt Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   His death Tuesday of what is being called a heart attack caught
most people unprepared because he seemed too big to die.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain surely seemed too big to complain about an extensive
dental procedure that most people could endure only with a morphine
drip dispensed from a bicycle pump and a month off from work.
</P>
<P>
   But that was Chamberlain in a nutshell. Nothing he did seemed
real by the normal standards, so his deeds either had to be
dismissed or denied.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the rumor that he didn't actually score 100 points that
night in Hershey, Pa.? Remember the cavalier dismissals of his
sex-with-20,000-women claim (as though anyone would keep track
after, say, 3,500)? Remember how adamantly everyone diminished him
by saying he wasn't better than Bill Russell's Celtics?
</P>
<P>
   Well, he did score 100. How ever many women he bedded, it was a
staggering number. And no, he wasn't better than the best team of
all time.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, who would ask that of a single player? Me, I had my
own standard. A foot and a six-pack of 7-Up.
</P>
<P>
   As a youth, I knew a kid named Brian Joyce whose father had an
in with the Warriors. It wasn't a great in by financial standards,
but it did get Joyce's pals invited to be ball boys when the
Warriors, then based in San Francisco, would play at the Oakland
Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   The plum job was to work the Warriors' bench. Being barely a
raisin at the time, I was shipped off to the visitors' side, often
to sit upon the basket support with a dust mop to take care of any
excess sweat or lint that would touch the floor, and only
occasionally to work the bench, handing out water and towels to the
players.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, I got to see, at roughly rib-cage level, the centers of
the age _ Gene Wiley, Zelmo Beaty, Walt Bellamy, Connie Dierking,
Reggie Harding, Wesley Unseld. Never Bill Russell; the Celtics
always seemed to play in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Ahh, but Chamberlain. Oakland always got Chamberlain, perhaps
because he had been a Warrior once and was traded to Philadelphia
by Franklin Mieuli for a handful of beads of human form.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, I would be on the basket support when the 76ers would come
out for layups _ Hal Greer, Wally Jones, Chet Walker, Lucious
Jackson, Billy Cunningham, Bill Melchionni, and of course,
Chamberlain. The others laid the ball in gently, the way you never
see these days. Chamberlain dunked.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, he dunked so hard that every time, without fail,
the basket support would tilt forward at least a foot from the
force. I know it was a foot in the pregames because once a
photographer carrying a ruler (for reasons I'm still not sure of to
this day), measured the distance between the back of the support
and the floor and told a compatriot, ``Foot and a half ...
da-a-a-a-mn.''
</P>
<P>
   During games, it had to be more, though I have only the
empirical evidence of once rolling forward off the support after a
Chamberlain dunk and onto the floor, nearly at the feet of Warriors
guard Paul Neumann. The 5,000 or so in attendance got a chuckle out
of it, and were I not already 3 1/2 feet tall, I would have felt
about 3 1/2 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   The next year the 76ers came to town, I decided it was safer to
work the bench. It also was much cooler because I got to sit at the
end of the bench and have Larry Costello, later a coach in
Milwaukee, condescend to talk to me during lulls in the action.
</P>
<P>
   On the bench, you made sure there was a 6-ounce Dixie cup of
water for everyone except Chamberlain. Chamberlain got a 14-ounce
beer cup full of 7-Up, poured straight from the can. OK, everyone's
got different dietary needs.
</P>
<P>
   But when the players were done with the water, they gave us the
discarded cups, usually with most of the water still unconsumed.
Chamberlain drained his 7-Up every time, during every timeout. A
full can, in a minute, and back for more every time there was a
stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, he never ran off the floor to go to the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the 100 points; the man had kidneys like a
rhinoceros.
</P>
<P>
   As an aside, he also dominated every game he ever played in
Oakland, and that is said even considering Nate Thurmond's
acknowledged greatness as a defensive center. I didn't need to know
his final stats, and it seems wrong now to look them up and pretend
I remembered them. I just remember him moving Thurmond here, there
and all points in between _ and reading the next day how Thurmond
held his own against the great force of his era.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he did. I don't know. I was 10, and after Chamberlain's
first dunk nearly catapulted me to the free-throw line, I simply
considered myself lucky to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   He must have done this everywhere he played, as well, because he
never said a word in any huddle. He looked at the floor,
occasionally at his coach, and drained that 7-Up.
</P>
<P>
   True, it isn't nearly the grandiose frame of reference some
might have of him, but I know Thurmond never sent me to the floor
in full flail, and I knew he was something else.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain, though, was something other than else, and from
sixth grade on, I made it a point to believe every exploit ever
credited to him, even if he was the only one doing the crediting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
