<SLUG> BC-CIR-FREE-LANCE-HELP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYMENT SITES PUT PROFESSIONAL WORKERS UP FOR AUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Mass., Calif.) (th) 
 By DEBORAH BRANSCUM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Free agents. Free-lancers. Solopreneurs. Whatever they are
called, people working for themselves in American businesses form a
large part of the labor force.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Labor estimates that 7.5 million people,
or roughly one in every 16 workers, are self-employed independent
contractors, hired by companies on a contract basis, often for a
short term.
</P>
<P>
   All those independent contractors have created a booming market
in Web sites that cater to them. Sites like Free Agent
(freeagent.com), Monster Talent Market (www.monster.com) and
Aquent's Talent Finder (talentfinder.aquent.com), and two that will
begin later in the fall, Guru.com and ICPlanet.com, hope to appeal
to self-employed professionals with a mix of job opportunities,
advice and services.
</P>
<P>
   Aquent, Monster.com and ICPlanet.com expect to profit by
charging companies who are seeking short-term talent. Many of the
sites want contractors to pay as well, not for services that match
them with companies, but for additional benefits like group-rate
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American dream is to be your own boss, not necessarily to
run your own business,'' said Carlos Cashman, president of Opus360
Corp., which put Free Agent online in July. The company has taken a
novel approach to attracting customers by offering them the option
of becoming employees of Free Agent.
</P>
<P>
   Contractors who sign up for the $249 monthly plan continue to
accept work from companies, but Free Agent handles the billing,
receives payments, and then pays the contractor after deducting for
taxes, retirement and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Lonier, an author and consultant who runs the Working Solo
site, a resource for independent professionals, predicts that
plenty of contractors will sign up for sites like Free Agent
``because in our Web survey they point out that one of the things
that's most challenging for them is finding new work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially challenging is finding new work while they're doing
the current work,'' Ms. Lonier continued. ``What's going to be
telling is how many people will actually be on the buying side.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far that doesn't appear to be a huge number. In
mid-September, for example, Free Agent appeared to have only 27
listings for companies seeking professional help on projects. Most
were related to technology, although the single listing in the
entertainment category offered one lucky professional the
opportunity to direct the shooting of a feature film in Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Monster's Talent Market has 70,000 registered contractors and
about 5,000 registered employers, according to Jeff Taylor, chief
executive of TMP Interactive, parent company of the Monster.com
career site.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 15, the Talent Market cited the number of its ongoing
auctions at 20,000. No figures were available for the number of
contractors who had actually received bids for their services, but
a search for advertising, public relations and communications
professionals using the keyword ``technology'' found no bids within
the first 100 auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Monster.com, which is based in Maynard, Mass., went online with
Talent Market in July as a kind of Ebay for human beings. There
have been more than 3,000 bids in the system since it began, Taylor
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have enough bids _ I've been pretty open with job
seekers about it _ but there are more bids every day,'' said
Taylor, who added that Monster.com is profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Even though contractors heavily outnumber employers on these
sites, matches do get made. Hani Durzy read about the Monster
Talent Market and went there for public relations help when he was
unable to find a contractor through word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, as director of corporate communications for
Chipshot.com, a online custom golf club business based in
Sunnyvale, Calif., Durzy competes with a slew of other Internet
companies for consultants. But online he found plenty of public
relations professionals in his area, and no competing bidders.
</P>
<P>
   Durzy didn't hire his consultant by completing a Talent Market
auction. Instead he placed an initial bid for services, and then
used e-mail to arrange a job interview with the contractor he
eventually hired, Benita Kenn, of Menlo Park, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this market especially, where it's so hard to hire good,
experienced people, you really don't have any idea what you're
getting unless you meet them,'' said Durzy, who wanted to make sure
the consultant would fit in well at the company.
</P>
<P>
   Such queasiness about hiring contractors sight unseen led
Aquent, which is based in Boston, to try a different approach.
Independent professionals who want to register with the site's
``talent agency'' must submit their resumes and then are
interviewed by Aquent representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only company that can actually meet the talent and
meet the clients and test and screen for skills, so the quality of
matches is much higher,'' said John Chuang, Aquent's co-founder and
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Aquent's strategy is based on its 11-year history as an
international employment service, formerly called Mac Temps, that
places 12,000 professionals annually.
</P>
<P>
   Aquent offers several services for contractors, including free
listing through its Talent Finder search engine, which was unveiled
last month, and Fast Cash, a program in which contractors submit
their invoices to Aquent, which pays them immediately for a 5
percent fee, instead of the workers having to wait for payment
directly from the employers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kenn, the public relations consultant who began working for
Durzy under a part-time contract this summer, isn't willing to
trust Aquent or Free Agent with her invoices just yet. And she
hasn't received any other nibbles from her Monster.com auctions.
Even so, she is upbeat about the sites that cater to people like
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing you've got to lose is the time you spend
putting your information online,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
