<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UP CLOSE AND DIGITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is hardly news when a computer product is released with bugs
in it, but it is rare indeed when the bugs are the cause of so much
delight. The bugs _ in this case a fruit fly and a plant louse,
both long deceased _ come in the box with the new Intel Play QXE
Computer Microscope, along with an assortment of other tiny,
slide-mounted specimens including algae, plant spores, a hair of
the dog and even the bee's knees.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is made by the toy giant Mattel and packaged as a
toy, the QX3 microscope ($99.95) is serious fun. The brains behind
the microscope are provided by the Intel Corp., which knows a thing
or two about computers. Together, Intel and Mattel have created a
new microscope for the digital age, one that goes far beyond the
capabilities of the beginner microscopes through which many of us
first glimpsed the hidden beauty of the microscopic world.
</P>
<P>
   The QX3 attaches to any Windows computer that has a USB
(Universal Serial Bus) peripheral connection port, which includes
almost all PC's made in the last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   With three magnification settings of 10X, 60X and 200X, the QX3
microscope does not have the higher resolution or precision
controls of many classroom microscopes, which typically offer 400X
or higher magnification. It is closer to a toy than to a scientific
instrument, built from plastic _ translucent blue, of course, which
is de rigueur these days _ instead of heavy-duty metal, with a
crude focusing mechanism that lacks the precision of most
microscopes.
</P>
<P>
   But it does things that no ordinary microscope can do, like make
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the traditional eyepiece through which generations of
young scientists have squinted, the QX3 has a small digital video
camera. It transmits what it sees over the USB con to the
computer, and the images are displayed on the computer screen in a
window created by the special software that comes on a CD-ROM disk
with the microscope.
</P>
<P>
   All around the viewing window are simple, one-click software
buttons that let the user control the microscope and manipulate the
images.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing something of interest, the microscopist can simply click
the mouse to capture still images or video clips of whatever is
being examined. The images are stored as standard graphics or video
files on the computer and can be inserted into school reports, sent
to friends as e-mail attachments or even transmitted to a Web page,
depending on the ambitiousness and technical sophistication of the
user.
</P>
<P>
   The user can also detach the microscope from its base and,
within the six-foot range of the USB cable, roam around capturing
close-up images of specimens that might not otherwise fit on the
microscope's stage, like one's own head, a piece of cheese, a
teacher's tattoo or any sort of disgusting, unidentified object one
finds and wants to share with others at 60X or 200X. Even at 10X,
the human body becomes an endless source of amazement: sweating
skin, hair, blinking eyes, scars, teeth, scabs, warts,
fingerprints, tongues and even uvulas.
</P>
<P>
   The software enables children to combine the microscopic images
with scanned artwork and pictures taken with a digital camera. For
example, a student might wish to conduct a scientific experiment to
see what his sister's face would look like attached to the body of
a blood-sucking tick.
</P>
<P>
   The software is exceptionally simple to operate, with built-in
audio help for those of us who have a phobia about software
manuals. The unusual sound effects that are triggered when a button
is highlighted are amusing at first, but grow old quickly.
</P>
<P>
   One important issue that bears close-up examination, however, is
Intel's apparent insensitivity to customer privacy. The CD-ROM
set-up program that Mattel and Intel designed for the QX3
microscope asks for the name, age, sex and e-mail address of the
user. Then it gathers detailed technical information about the
computer and sends it all back to Intel automatically as part of
the online product registration procedure, unless the user clicks a
special box denying Intel the data.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Intel automatically signs the user up for ``special
offers or other information'' unless he or she clicks a small
button instructing Mattel and Intel not to send it. This is called
``opt out'' marketing, and it is disturbing even when aimed at
adults. On a product specifically aimed at children, as this one
is, the only acceptable practice is to make protection of privacy
the default value and ``opt in'' the alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Another gripe: The QX3 comes in a package that is a masterpiece
of vexation. To get the microscope out of its box, I was forced to
hack, shred, tear and mangle the packaging into nearly microscopic
bits. But all was forgiven when the microscope lit up and
displayed, with exquisite intimacy, all of the bugs it came with.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, there is nothing even remotely cute about a
bee's knees at 60X magnification.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there anything cute about the computer I used to test the
QX3 microscope, the new Astro all-in-one computer from Gateway.
</P>
<P>
   The Astro is an Apple iMac wannabe, an all-in-one design that
combines the computer and a 15-inch monitor in one tubby unit. The
$799 Astro, which goes on sale October 14 at www.gateway.com, was
designed for novice PC users and for people with tight budgets. It
is very easy to set up once it is hoisted from its box. Gateway is
also touting the Astro as a second PC for households that already
have one. Unlike the colorful iMac and its other clones, the Astro
is a colorless (well, beige) system that is also about as beige
technologically as one can get these days. It is built around a
400-megahertz Intel Celeron microprocessor and the Microsoft
Windows 98 operating system, with 64 megabytes of RAM, a
4.3-gigabyte hard disk drive, a 56K (V90) modem, a diskette drive
and a CD-ROM drive. It has a pair of built-in speakers and a
microphone, and a pair of USB connection ports.
</P>
<P>
   That is it. The system cannot be upgraded except through the USB
ports. Gateway designed the Astro as a closed box, so there is no
way to open the case to add expansion cards or more memory. To
network the Astro with another computer, for example, you would
have to use a USB connection like Intel's Anypoint USB ($89).
</P>
<P>
   The unit I tested came with Windows 98. Gateway says the Astro
will come with Microsoft Works 99 Suite, Encarta and Money,
although those programs were not included in the unit I tested.
Unlike other Gateway computers, the Astro does not come with a free
year of Internet access through Gateway.net. That costs $14.95 a
month extra, or $129 a year paid in advance. The system comes with
a 12-month warranty, 12 months of free telephone hardware support
and 3 months of software support.
</P>
<P>
   The Astro's direct competitors are the eMachine eOne and the
Apple iMac, and by those measures the new Gateway machine is
something of a dis-Astro. Both the eOne ($799) and the new iMac
($999) have superior technical specifications, and they are better
looking, too.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, some people may appreciate a computer that is not blue.
But the Astro is exceptionally large and ungainly, 45 pounds not
counting the peripherals. That's a full 10 pounds heavier than the
iMac.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Astro is the sort of computer the Klingons would
have built if they had somehow captured the secret blueprints for
the iMac.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
