<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cleaning Up Leftovers
</P>
<P>
   Q. Since I deleted programs I do not use, I get the following
error message every time I turn on the computer: ``Error Starting
Program. A required .DLL file, WBHOOK32.DLL, was not found.'' Is
there anything I can do to get rid of this message permanently?
</P>
<P>
   A. ``.DLL'' designates dynamic-link library files, which contain
data or a collection of functions that are used by Windows
programs. Some D.L.L. files are written just for the system or a
particular application installed on your computer. But some are
used by several different programs. If you delete or overwrite a
D.L.L. file when adding or uninstalling software, other programs on
your machine may not function properly.
</P>
<P>
   When you manually delete a program from your hard drive, pieces
of it are sometimes left behind. These leftovers may cause problems
with your system when they start to look for the parts of the
program that you deleted. Using the -Add/Remove option in your
computer's Control Panel or third-party software designed to
uninstall programs completely can help prevent these types of
problems. Two popular programs that offer to help you safely remove
old programs from your PC are Uninstaller by McAfee and Norton
Cleansweep 2000, made by Symantec.
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft representative confirmed that WBHOOK32.DLL was not
one of the Windows systems files and was probably from one of the
programs you deleted. One way to get rid of the error would be to
reinstall the deleted programs, then remove them with the
-Add/Remove utility.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
