<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
BUSH TO PLAY YANKEE TO CHALLENGERS? (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Yankees made short work of the Texas Rangers in
last week's divisional baseball playoff. Having thereby dispensed
with the formality of eliminating our hometown heroes, New York
Manager Joe Torre revealed that he was rooting for the Boston Red
Sox and Cleveland Indians to wear each other out in the remaining
games of their playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that whoever wins is exhausted,'' Torre said after
mowing down the local team Saturday night at The Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   After sweeping three games from the Rangers without breaking a
sweat, Torre and his Yankees were no doubt thrilled when the
Boston-Cleveland shootout went the full five games. Better yet, the
last two games of the series were slugfests in which the eventual
winner, Boston, scored 35 runs in approximately 27 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Red Sox weren't exhausted after all that base-running,
but there's no way they'll be as fresh as the Yankees when the
archrivals collide in the American League Championship Series
beginning tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The script played out exactly as if Torre had written it.
</P>
<P>
   And as often happens in this sports-crazed country, the baseball
season has provided a fitting analogy for the political season.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, former baseball magnate and current
front-runner for the Republican Party's 2000 presidential
nomination, appears to be benefiting from a campaign story line
that parallels the American League playoffs: While Bush breezes
through the campaign with no serious threat being mounted by any of
his numerous opponents, Democratic front-runner Al Gore finds
himself in a dogfight with ex-basketball star and former New Jersey
Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The upside of a difficult playoff ... er ... primary campaign is
that it can push a candidate to find out what he's made of; it can
toughen the winner for the battle ahead. The downside is that the
primaries can take such a toll in campaign cash and unfavorable
publicity that the survivor is doomed to defeat in the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   The first primaries are months away, of course, and Bush could
hit some bumps in the road en route to the Republican nomination.
But he figures to crush his Republican opponents as easily as the
Yankees crushed the Arlington baseball team that Bush once
commanded as managing general partner.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley figure to fight it out until the final inning.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the new USA Today/CNN/Gallup Poll showing
that Bradley continues to gain ground on Gore and that Bush
continues to thrash them both in head-to-head matchups.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also reaffirmed Bush's runaway front-runner status in
the GOP race. The Texas governor was the choice of 60 percent of
Republicans; runner-up Elizabeth Dole managed just 11 percent.
Other candidates trudged along in single digits.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is on such a roll, in fact, that even his controversial
criticism of his own party and party leaders in Congress worked to
his benefit. According to USA Today, 55 percent of Republicans
polled said that they support Bush vs. Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's suggestion that the GOP needs to show more compassion
apparently touched a chord: USA Today reported that 64 percent of
poll respondents said ``the Republican Party has not been
compassionate enough about the needs of the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Those poll results must be hard to swallow for the anti-Bush
crowd. Rather than stumbling, as his detractors keep predicting (or
rather hoping?), Bush seems to be getting stronger as he goes
along.
</P>
<P>
   Start practicing, Bush-haters. Say it again and again until you
get used to it: ``President Bush, President Bush, President Bush
...''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, need to start choosing sides in the
Gore-Bradley clash. The sooner they make up their minds, the sooner
the potentially destructive contest will be decided _ and the
sooner the Democratic nominee-in-waiting can starting for
the electoral World Series against Bush.
</P>
<P>
   As if all the preparation in the world will make any difference.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1612EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
