of the city _ is a very different place where giant glass
skyscrapers cluster, as if for security, on high ground above a
derelict business district that hasn't seen good times since Harlow
was an ingenue.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the streets are dark and eerily empty at night and it's a
long way to Beverly Hills or Westwood. As a consequence, choosing
from among the many good downtown hotels becomes a little more
personal, since you're more likely to be confined to quarters
longer and dependent on the hotel's individual services and
characteristics. To nut-shell the point, as they say on the other
side of town: here you want to choose your hotel deliberately, and
not on some vague recommendation from a travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   So in making arrangements for a business trip that required a
four-night stay in downtown Los Angeles last week, I tried out
Travelocity. That service is about to surpass Expedia from
Microsoft's as the largest Internet travel-booking service after
its parent, Sabre Group, completes plans to spin it off into a
separate publicly traded company. Sabre is the reservation system
controlled by AMR, which also owns American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The site (travelocity.com) was easy to use, if you paid
attention. I was pretty specific about what I wanted for a stay
during which both my wife and I would be conducting separate
business. No convention hotels. No brassy 1,500-room joints with
soaring atriums and splashing fountains. No venerable old hotels
with elaborate public spaces downstairs and rooms upstairs that
evoke the YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   Within 15 minutes on line at Travelocity, I had evaluated more
than a dozen hotels and booked what turned out to be an excellent
choice, the Wyndham Checkers, a small luxury hotel with gloriously
quiet rooms, large marble bathrooms, impeccable service (you can
specify which newspapers you want left at your door, if you don't
choose to have the ubiquitous USA Today foisted on you first thing
in the morning), and jiffy-fast valet parking. The online price:
$209 a night, slightly below the rack rate and competitive with
other quality hotels in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   While booking it, I felt as if I was in control to a degree that
I'd never been while selecting a hotel in an unfamiliar location.
The Travelocity site provided accurate data and _ this is
important, in the endless galaxy of Web travel hype coming from who
knows where _ credible information, including customer evaluations
from the trusted Zagat survey
</P>
<P>
   Could a travel agent have arranged the same thing to my
specifications? Possibly, but only if I were a preferred customer
deserving of a lot of time and attention. What does this say to the
travel-agent business? It says, stand by for heavy rolls, mates.
</P>
<P>
   After a fitful start, the online travel marketplace is finding
firm footing as people become adept at using the Internet and as
personal computers achieve greater household penetration. They're
in 38.8 percent of United States households this year, three times
the figure of 1995, according to Forrester Research Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer fears about online credit card security have been the
biggest bugaboo for the rapidly expanding Internet travel industry,
but this is changing. In surveys, Forrester Research found that 53
percent of online respondents last July said they felt secure using
credit cards on the Internet, up from 15 percent in early 1998.
Among those who don't use the Internet, however, there is
overwhelming distrust of the idea of online credit card purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials believe that smart customers, including
business travelers who book their own trips, will increasingly take
their business to online booking sites. Within two years, the
industry ``will be generating about $20 billion in sales,'' said
Phillip C. Wolf, president and chief executive of PhoCusWright, an
online travel industry research company.
</P>
<P>
   Travel sites like Travelocity and Expedia that establish
themselves as trusted brands will dominate this new market and
furiously shake the foundations of the traditional travel agency
business, industry experts believe. The competition could become
fierce, too. Earlier this month, one of the most aggressive
American retail giants said that it was developing its own online
travel site for booking airline tickets, rental cars and hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart is the name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
