</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-SENSATION-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SENSATION' FLURRY OBSCURES THE ART 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATRICIA C. JOHNSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Visitors enter the Brooklyn Museum of Art to view
``Sensation`` through an incongruous facade, painted like King
Tutankhamen's famous golden mask.
</P>
<P>
   Yet amusement dissipates quickly when they are required to pass
through metal detectors and have their bags inspected _ safety
measures necessitated by the strident battle over this exhibition
of contemporary British art.
</P>
<P>
   With the possible exception of the museum guards who are
collecting overtime pay, no one wins in the battle of
``Sensation.''
</P>
<P>
   Not New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who, acting like a
petulant Third World dictator, inflamed a controversy over the
exhibit without having seen it.
</P>
<P>
   Not Brooklyn Museum of Art director Arnold Lehman and his
publicity machine, whose deliberately provocative bid for attention
was transparent _ and backfired, terribly.
</P>
<P>
   Not the distinguished museum, with its enviable collection of
Egyptian art and works on paper, as it slides into a legal mud
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Not the artists, at least not in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   The losers also include taxpayers, New Yorkers as well as
tourists. The hundreds of thousands of dollars in legal costs
incurred by both litigants _ the museum asserting its right to
exhibit the art under the First Amendment and the city claiming the
First Amendment does not protect public subsidies of free speech,
even threatening to evict the museum from the city-owned building _
ultimately come from public coffers. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The audience loses too, for the flurry of heated words blurs
the eyes, numbs the ears and the mind. Because it is words, not
art, that provoked this conflagration.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety works by 42 artists compose ``Sensation: Young British
Artists from the Saatchi Collection.'' All belong to Charles
Saatchi, an advertising mogul whose success in business depends on
his talent for using the right combination of words and images to
sell his clients' products to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Without the avalanche of words that preceded and now surround
this exhibit, the art itself, visceral as it is at times, is mostly
self-indulgent. Little of it is new to 20th-century art. Further,
many of the same artists and several of the same pieces were
included in ``Brilliant!,`` a show of young British artists at
Houston's Contemporary Arts Museum three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the unfortunate icon of this exhibition, Chris Ofili's
``The Holy Virgin Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a mixed-media work that includes elephant dung, a material
that has been interpreted as being disrespectful and desecrating to
a holy image. But some African cultures have long used materials
like animal dung and blood to create objects of worship; neither
desecration nor insult was the intent. Further, Ofili, a Catholic
of Nigerian descent living in London, molded and shellacked the
lumpy forms, then applied jewellike beads of paint with the
meticulous care associated with a reverential process.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest, the so-called ``pornographic'' cutouts decorating
the golden background of the Virgin's image don't show a sex act.
It seems they refer instead to the anatomy of fertility and
regeneration.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how we probe, analyze and talk about it, this work
is a lame picture. Divorced from the false heat created around it,
it's not nearly as effectively decorative and texturally
interesting as another Ofili work on view, an abstract
constellation of paint beads and (yes) decorated dung.
</P>
<P>
   Why Damien Hirst's animal sculptures should cause an uproar so
late in the century is puzzling. The dissection and preservation of
animals in formaldehyde are time-honored scientific processes.
Though many critics have defended the sliced cow, halved pig and
the shark, all suspended in formaldehyde-filled tanks, as
commentaries or extensions of minimalist aesthetics and therefore
appropriate in the context of art, the public still expects to
encounter them in a natural history museum, not among the
sculptures and paintings ascribed to the fine arts.
</P>
<P>
   Race, class and sex identify issues at the heart of the exhibit.
How they're expressed ranges from the excruciatingly banal
photographs of Richard Billingham's lower-class family to the
grotesque sexual deformities sculpted by Jake and Dinos Chapman.
(Compared to Henry Darger's &UR;  &LR; disturbing, funny and weirdly
redemptive narrative paintings of the Vivian Girls, though, the
Chapmans are neither original in their vision of weird,
hermaphroditic sexuality, nor subtle.)
</P>
<P>
   How sophomoric the exploration of the themes can be is clear in
an assemblage by Sarah Lucas. ``Au Naturel`` consists of a bucket
and two melons, oranges and an upright cucumber on a mattress, in
obvious representation of sex partners.
</P>
<P>
   Obsession with body parts and their function, or the lack
thereof, is another prominent subject. The installation by Mona
Hatoum, ``Deep Throat,`` consists of a table setting in which the
dinner plate serves as monitor for a video of her throat, in the
process of swallowing .
</P>
<P>
   At its maximum limit is Marc Quinn's bust, made with his own
blood. The sculptor drew 5 quarts _ the approximate total amount of
blood in an average adult _ over several months, froze it and
carved his likeness from it. Now contained in its own special
refrigerated unit, it's like a religious reliquary, shocking in its
egotism but nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   But the loud and sour controversy allows no impartiality, and
has forced us to play devil's advocate, defending works of art that
might otherwise be dismissed as derivative and merely narcissistic.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it also obscures some thoughtful, good work.
Rachel Whiteread's magical, ghostly casts of negative spaces will
alter the way you see a room and small spaces, like those under
chairs, forever more. Ron Mueck's perfectly scaled simulacrum,
``Dead Dad,'' is as attractive formally as it might be repellent in
subject matter. Painter Jenny Saville hybridizes the fierce
brushwork of Francis Bacon and Lucien Freud's unforgiving eye to
render suffocating, fleshy female nudes with compelling
painterliness.
</P>
<P>
   The critical issue of freedom of expression surrounding the
controversial exhibit will be debated in our courts, one hopes on
the principled high ground of constitutional law, not politics.
</P>
<P>
   And the court will eventually determine whether the museum has
the right to exhibit these works at government expense, or if the
mayor, representing civil government, has the power to enforce
his/its definition of what art is appropriate for display. &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
INFORMATION BOX &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sensation: Young British Artists &QL; 
from the Saatchi Collection &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Where: &LR;  Brooklyn Museum of Art, 200 Eastern Parkway, Brooklyn,
N.Y.; 718-638-5000 &QL; 
 &UR; When: &LR;  10 a.m.-5 p.m. Wednesdays-Fridays, 11 a.m.-6 p.m.
Saturdays-Sundays &QL; 
 &UR; Tickets: &LR;  $9.75 adults, $7.75 students and older adults, $6.75
youngsters 13-18, free for age 12 and under. All children 16 and
younger must be accompanied by an adult. Includes general
admission.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
