<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5664 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-KINGBISCUIT-FESTIVAL-     10-13 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGBISCUIT-FESTIVAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUES RECONNECT WITH ROOTS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By   NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELENA, Ark. &UR;  &LR; _ This former plantation town in eastern Arkansas
is not an obvious choice for a festival, with a crumbling downtown,
a shrinking population now at 7,000 and all the economic problems
and racial tensions one would expect in Phillips County, the
poorest county in the state. But back in the 1930s and '40s, when
Helena was a relatively thriving agricultural port on the
Mississippi, it was the blues center of the Delta, with juke joints
lining the streets, now-legendary musicians playing for change on
the piers, and, beginning in 1941, a groundbreaking, highly
influential afternoon blues broadcast called ``King Biscuit Time,''
featuring the harmonica player Sonny Boy Williamson (the former
Rice Miller).
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on this heritage, local officials and blues fans
borrowed a trailer from a traveling evangelist 13 years ago and
used it as a stage for the first King Biscuit Blues Festival, which
has now grown to become the largest free blues gathering in the
South and an extraordinary opportunity for fans of the music to see
a living tradition reconnect with its roots.
</P>
<P>
   The 14th annual festival took place last week, from Thursday to
Saturday, and thus overcame what may have been the greatest odds
ever stacked against it. First came a lawsuit filed by a handful of
local disgruntled black merchants and the regional branch of the
NAACP charging civil rights violations. Naming the city's mayor,
Dr. Robert D. Miller (the first-ever black mayor in this town with
a minority white population), and the City Council as defendants,
the lawsuit alleged that the city favored white merchants and
festival organizers.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, several sponsors (whose support is crucial to
pulling off a free concert that doesn't receive any government
money) threatened to withdraw if the festival didn't change its
logo. That was a replica of the design on packages of Sonny Boy
Cornmeal (an illustration of Sonny Boy Williamson sitting on an ear
of corn with a harmonica in his hands), which were sold in the '40s
by the makers of King Biscuit Flour to exploit the popularity of
the radio show. Although Williamson was said to have been proud of
the package, festival sponsors thought the image could be construed
as racist. And then there was one more threat to the festival, the
weather report: rain, rain and more rain.
</P>
<P>
   But three weeks ago, a federal judge ruled in favor of the
festival. And promoters solved the logo dispute by cropping the
cornmeal image so that it showed just a close-up of Williamson's
face and harmonica.
</P>
<P>
   But they could not stop the rain. It either poured or drizzled
through most of the festival, forcing the cancellation of several
acts, including Little Milton. As loyal locals and blues hounds
from around the world stood in the downpour while Magic Slim and
the Teardrops performed, the electric shocks Magic Slim kept
getting from the microphone didn't help the performance any.
Because of the terrible weather, the festival, which expected
attendance to top last year's 135,000, saw fewer than 100,000
people over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, for those who showed up, the King Biscuit Blues
Festival was a casual and ideal way to experience the music. Fans
sat on railroad tracks or in folding chairs on the grassy levee,
watching performances by Robert Lockwood Jr., Son Seals, Pinetop
Perkins with Bob Margolin, Sam Carr, W.C. Clark, the duo of Cephas
and Wiggins and dozens more. Cherry Street, running behind the
stage, seemed to be in a time warp, with musicians who weren't
booked in the festival playing for change in the street, their
electric guitars plugged into the outlets of obliging stores like
the V.I.P. Beauty Salon. At stalls in the road, the James Alexander
Masonic Lodge sold hog maws, Live Critters offered hermit crabs and
the Lighthouse Assembly of God displayed dolls made out of hymn
books.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage on Saturday night was Son Seals, who has become a road
warrior in recent years despite having had his leg amputated over
the summer because of diabetes complications and the lower half of
his face reconstructed after being shot by his wife two years ago.
For more than an hour he played fast, melting lead guitar lines
that oozed off the stage like syrup. Backstage, sitting with the
pianist Pinetop Perkins, he discussed the letter he had written to
the local newspaper to help defend the festival from accusations of
racism, accusations that festival promoters and most townspeople
say are trumped up. ``I had to do that,'' Seals said. ``I wanted to
tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins, 86, sat slouched in a chair next to him, nodding in
agreement and telling stories about performing in Helena more than
50 years ago. ``I've been playing here since way back, as the King
Biscuit Boys,'' he said, clicking his tongue. ``Ain't but two of us
left.''
</P>
<P>
   The other remaining King Biscuit Time mainstay, Robert Lockwood
Jr., lived around Helena as a teen-ager, playing guitar with his
stepfather, Robert Johnson. Of all the Delta musicians onstage,
Lockwood had deviated most from his roots, playing his own
blues-jazz hybrid on 12-string guitar over the swing and jump of a
brassy backing band.
</P>
<P>
   As if performances by Lockwood and Perkins weren't enough of a
connection to Helena's musical past, a further reminder came from
the fact that not only was there a street named after the bluesman
Frank Frost two blocks away from the main stage, but Frost was
still living on that street. Barely able to play because of ill
health, Frost made a brief appearance during a set by his bandmate
of 45 years, the drummer Sam Carr. Spectators onstage said they saw
Carr crying as he played.
</P>
<P>
   Blues in the Delta has always been an around-the-clock
occupation. After performing on the main stage for tens of
thousands of people, many musicians went straight to nearby
hangouts like Ellie Mae's to perform in dilapidated barrooms for
just a handful of locals and fans.
</P>
<P>
   The best of these impromptu performances was a small picnic at
Carr's shack, which stands in the middle of a picturesque stretch
of farmland across the Mississippi River. Identifying the house and
its occupant is a mailbox that, Carr said, has occasionally been
stolen by blues souvenir hunters. For an audience of about 25
people, Carr beat highly stylized stiff-armed patterns.
Accompanying him from the other side of a picnic table was the
harpist Arthur Williams, who sat under a tree wailing merrily away
with a briefcase full of harmonicas splayed open at his feet.
</P>
<P>
   For those whose tastes ran beyond the blues, the festival had
more to offer. Inside the Malco Theater on Cherry Street local
gospel groups sang and preached for enthusiastic townspeople. Among
them was Mayor Miller, who stood in the lobby buying popcorn. ``I
know it looks a little odd for the mayor of a town with the largest
blues festival in the South to be at the gospel stage,'' he said
sheepishly. ``Especially since I'm a Roman Catholic. But my son is
a Pentecostal minister, and he's my spiritual adviser.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he was thinking of starting a gospel festival,
although he remained a blues fan and played piano with the King
Biscuit Boys in 1945 to fill in for an ailing musician. He stuffed
a handful of popcorn in his mouth and reached to pickeather
medical bag on the counter, explaining that he was also the local
general practitioner and had just attended to an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   As for the lawsuit, he dismissed it. ``As long as I'm mayor, the
festival is not going anywhere,'' he said, adding after a
reflective pause, ``and that's probably why I am mayor here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
