<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SCRIP-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPPING INTO THE FLOW OF WEB DOLLARS TO AID SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.C.)   (bl)  
 By FRANCES DINKELSPIEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   E-commerce is coming to the aid of the PTA, and Debbie Schide is
delighted.
</P>
<P>
   On most school mornings, Ms. Schide and a dedicated group of
volunteers find themselves in the schoolyards and parking lots of
the Menlo-Atherton school district in northern California. They are
selling scrip, a type of gift certificate that has become a
fund-raising mainstay for thousands of schools across the country.
Stores sell the certificates at a discount to schools, which then
sell them at face value to supporters. When the scrip is spent, the
school gets a small rebate, something like a legal kickback.
</P>
<P>
   As a fund-raising tool, scrip is lucrative _ Ms. Schide's school
district alone netted $65,000 from it last year. But it is
labor-intensive. ``It's a major operation, but it's so beneficial
to the school we have to do it,'' Ms. Schide said.
</P>
<P>
   But her workload, and that of thousands of other parent
volunteers, is about to change. In the last year, a number of
online versions of scrip sales have emerged. At Schoolpop
(www.schoolpop.com) and Your School Shop (www.yourschoolshop.com),
parents use the companies' home pages as portals to national
retailers like Amazon.com, J.C. Penney and Officemax. Each online
purchase kicks back a small percentage to the school, and the
merchants also pay a small percentage of each purchase to the scrip
service.
</P>
<P>
   Escrip (www.escripinc.com) also aims to eliminate the hassle of
scrip sales by turning them into electronic transactions. With
Escrip, participants register their credit and debit cards, and a
percentage is sent to a designated charity each time the cards are
used at participating businesses. The merchants that have signed up
with Escrip include Budget Rent-a-Car, American Airlines, Payless
Shoe Source and Eddie Bauer. Escrip transfers the rebates
electronically to schools, or to charities, and sends each family a
detailed list of its monthly purchases, including what percentage
of the sales benefited the charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see schools making a tremendous amount more money on this
program than they could previously on paper,'' said Joanne
Remillard, executive vice president of community groups at
Electronic Scrip Inc., or ESI, in San Mateo, Calif., which operates
the program. ``It is much more convenient.''
</P>
<P>
   Scrip originated about 10 years ago in Petaluma, Calif., when
families there were casting about for a way to rescue a struggling
Catholic school. The school's supporters and the local diocese
approached the local Safeway grocery store and struck a deal to
purchase gift certificates at a 5 percent discount.
</P>
<P>
   Families bought the certificates at face value and raised enough
money to put the school on a sound financial footing.
</P>
<P>
   That program grew into the National Scrip Center, a nonprofit
organization in Santa Rosa, Calif., that sells about $450 million
worth of scrip annually to about 11,000 schools and nonprofit
groups across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations can buy gift certificates from major stores like
Macy's, Gap, Barnes &AMP; Noble and United Artists Theaters at
discounts ranging from 2 percent to 20 percent. Numerous grocery
stores also sell scrip directly to schools.
</P>
<P>
   Paper scrip programs have garnered hundreds of thousands of
dollars for schools, helping them buy computers, hire art and music
teachers and pay for school trips and renovations. But the programs
are not easy to manage. Schools often must float thousands of
dollars up front to pay for the scrip, a requirement that can be
difficult for poorer schools. Paper scrip is essentially cash, so
schools must work out a security system to store it and delivery it
safely. Accounting can be cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   All those problems can be eliminated with electronic versions of
scrip. ``There's a tremendous amount of paper work and the
collecting of cash to purchase scrip,'' said Ian Diary, a former
Apple executive who is the chief executive of ESI. ``All that
disappears with Escrip.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Scrip Center, which controls the bulk of the
nation's scrip business, plans to go on line later this year, said
its chief executive, Edward Phillips. The organization is also
planning to introduce a credit card that can be used in lieu of
paper scrip.
</P>
<P>
   The new electronic programs can extend the purchasing power of a
school beyond its traditional borders. Anyone can sign on to the
Internet, designate a school and make a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``This allows Grandma in Boise and the alumni in Boston to
support the school in Los Angeles,'' said Rea Callender, a former
schoolteacher who is now chief executive of Schoolpop.com, based in
Menlo Park, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Schools seem eager to reduce their administrative overhead for
scrip programs. While Escrip and Schoolpop have been open for only
a few months, they are registering schools in droves. More than
7,500 schools have signed up on Schoolpop; 300 have registered with
Your School Shop, which opened in August. Escrip recently made an
exclusive deal with Safeway, one of the nation's largest grocery
chains, and it is now receiving 90 calls a day from schools, Diary
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always looking for ways to raise funds,'' said Tim Amos,
an assistant superintendent whose district, Asheville City Schools
in North Carolina, has signed up with Schoolpop. ``This seemed like
a safe way to do it. You don't have children knocking on doors,
selling candy or magazines or things like that. I think it's a
growing thing because more and more people are buying things on the
Internet. ``
</P>
<P>
   Escrip promises to simplify accounting for merchants as well.
Participating companies can go on line to look at their accounts
and see the amount of scrip sales at their stores. Many, like
Safeway, are eliminating their paper scrip program in favor of
Escrip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it would be a great way to increase awareness of
the company, build customer loyalty and put money back into
community schools and other nonprofits,'' said Sue Welty, a
spokeswoman for Budget Rent-a-Car, which will give an 8 percent
rebate on the price of a car rental.
</P>
<P>
   The new programs have their drawbacks. Escrip charges each
family $10 annually to register all its credit cards, and some
scrip administrators report that some people are unwilling or
unable to pay those fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our older members, many of whom are on fixed incomes, are
reluctant to plunk out $10,'' said Odette Blachman, who sells scrip
for Temple Beth-El in Berkeley, Calif. For schools in low-income
areas, ESI is considering subsidies for families who cannot afford
the annual fee, Diary said.
</P>
<P>
   Schoolpop, aware that some families do not have access to the
Internet, is recruiting businesses and asking them to adopt
schools, Callender said. The businesses could make their purchases
on line and have the rebates sent to local schools that have large
numbers of students without computers at home.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1632EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
