<HEADLINE>
TRYING ON CLOTHES IN A VIRTUAL DRESSING ROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COSMOPOLITAN FASHION MAKEOVER DELUXE
</P>
<P>
   (Broderbund; $49.95; Windows 95, 98 and NT.)
</P>
<P>
   Buying clothes on line has proved to be a lifesaver for women
who are not quite up to dealing with the rambunctious hassle of
stores, crowds and dressing rooms. Going for convenience rather
than a perfect fit (``it looked great on screen'') has been a major
drawback, though. But now there is hope for women still loath to
f'ht the traffic outside and inside the mall.
</P>
<P>
   In conjunction with Cosmopolitan magazine, Broderbund has
recently released its Cosmopolitan Fashion Makeover program. The
software lets women try on clothes on line before ordering them
from the Macy's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The program uses 3-D rendering technology called My Virtual
Model to create the on-screen figures. Users can pick one of
several cheery voices to guide them as they set things up. ``Think
of your Virtual Model as your electronic second self,'' the voice
urges.
</P>
<P>
   After the shopper types in her measurements (which can be done
to the beat of Muzak-meets-the-Paris-runway music, but it can be
turned off, thank goodness), the program will create and display a
computerized version of the shopper's body in modest undergarments.
A measuring tape is even included with the software, and the model
can be protected with a password for the bashful _ or those with
brothers who might be overly intrigued by the model's Undress
button.
</P>
<P>
   The model can be rotated 360 degrees for viewing at all angles.
For the final dab of personalization, the user can even add a
digital photo of her face to the pixelated paper doll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to look as much like you as I can,'' the chirpy
narrator says at one point in the model-creation process. The head
proportion seemed a bit off on some of the figures after a custom
picture was imported onto a body, however, which might be vaguely
unsettling to some.
</P>
<P>
   Once a woman has a electronic second self, the fashion games
really begin. The program whisks the virtual body to the home page,
which offers several options. The shopper can go into the Flatter
Your Figure area for sartorial tips on what kinds of clothes look
best on her body type. Those users who already have this
information will probably head directly to the Dressing Room.
</P>
<P>
   The Dressing Room is where the goods are. Menus for different
categories of clothes appear on the screen, and the program will
display a selection of items available. Once a woman has settled on
a particular garment, she can drag and drop it onto her digital
body to see how it looks. (If only getting dressed in the morning
was this easy.) If she likes what she sees, she can take a snapshot
of it, save the file on her hard drive and send it as an e-mail
attachment to family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers can mix and match dozens of different items, including
shoes and handbags. The site offers clothing appropriate for every
situation, from business meetings to casual weekends. For those
concerned that the program's fashions will go out of style,
seasonal updates about new merchandise can be downloaded from a
Cosmopolitan Web site (www.fashionmakeover.com).
</P>
<P>
   The shopper can click on each item of clothing for a details box
that gives the size, designer, price and availability. Liz
Claiborne, Esprit, Carole Little and I.N.C. are among the designers
represented.
</P>
<P>
   Since some manufacturers have their own size standards, the
program will convert the shopper's particular measurements into the
appropriate size for each item selected. The Add to Shopping Bag
button is also there, and when the shopping is done, Fashion
Makeover will open the user's Web browser and whisk her to
www.macys.com &UR;  &LR; for nearly instant consumer gratification.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to find the Cosmopolitan content in the program. One
area offers fashion advice from the magazine's staff, and fashion
tips pop up in little boxes on the screen as the shopper browses.
The user-interface colors consist of soft pastels like pink and
purple that dominate women's magazine layouts. (In fact, the
shopper can print a Cosmo cover with her digital self, front and
center.)
</P>
<P>
   Personal empowerment messages abound. ``I'm meant to be your
reflection,'' reads some of the text on the screen that appears
right after the virtual model has been set up. ``And I'm here to
help you look and feel your very best.''
</P>
<P>
   To make Cosmopolitan Fashion Makeover feel its very best, the
shopper needs what is readily available on most current systems: a
minimum of 32 megabytes of RAM (it works better with 64 megabytes),
1 megabyte of VRAM, a SVGA video card that supports 16-bit color
and a CD-ROM drive. The program takes up 150 megabytes of hard
drive space. Cosmopolitan Fashion Makeover also comes in a standard
version that has fewer features than the deluxe edition and costs
$10 less.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmopolitan Fashion Makeover is aimed at women 18 and older, a
demographic group that until now has not been courted by software
makers as assiduously as men have been. Although the program can be
frighteningly perky at times, it is nice to see software that uses
powerful 3-D technology more productively than shoot-'em-up action
games.
</P>
<P>
   And frankly, the virtual women here are much better dressed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
