<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE EYES IN THE SKY GO TO COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ind., Calif., N.C., Va.)   (af)  
 By PETER WAYNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several years ago, David A. Landgrebe, a professor at Purdue
University's School of Electrical and Computer Engineering who
studies satellite imagery, found himself describing his research in
deep technical detail to a local judge when they met socially.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through the whole spiel and wondered what he would ever
do with the information,'' Landgrebe recalled. ``When I asked the
judge, he said: `There's more lying going on in the courtroom, and
I need to make a decision. One lawyer describes some land as
worthless. Another claims it's worth a fortune. I want something to
trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Satellite imagery is beginning to make the jump from being a
secret tool of spies to being a tool of the justice system. New
satellites offering images with significantly better resolution to
the general public will make it possible for experts to reconstruct
the scene of a crime or an accident so the courts can analyze the
event.
</P>
<P>
   A company called Space Imaging released a photograph on
Wednesday from a commercial spy satellite showing objects as small
as three feet wide.
</P>
<P>
   As more precise images become available, satellite photography
is likely to become more useful in the next few years, even as it
opens up a new area for disputes between expert witnesses in court.
</P>
<P>
   A small California company named Visual Forensics demonstrated
the potential of this technology when its team of scientists and
computer graphics experts used satellite data to construct a
computer model of the valley in Italy where a United States
warplane sliced through the cable of an aerial tram in 1998,
killing 20.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors argued that the pilots were showing off, trying to
fly under the cable. A film produced by Visual Forensics tried to
counter this assertion by demonstrating how the shape of the valley
could create an optical illusion that could confuse a pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Johnson, the director of motion graphics at Visual
Forensics, said: ``The optical illusion first became apparent to my
partner when he took a helicopter route along the flight path. The
first thing that struck him was that the river that ran down the
center of the valley appeared to be running uphill. It's the
classic optical illusion that gives you the illusion of gaining
altitude when you're really losing altitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The team at Visual Forensics used the satellite images of the
valley to create a three-dimensional model of the terrain in a
computer. Then they created an animated film showing how even a
conscientious pilot could make mistakes about the altitude.
</P>
<P>
   A military jury in Camp Lejeune, N.C., which saw the film,
ultimately agreed that the pilot, Capt. Richard Ashby, was not
guilty of involuntary homicide and manslaughter and acquitted him
in March; he was later convicted of obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Satellite images can be ideal for recreating the scene of a
crime or an accident. All optical lenses add distortion, but the
amount depends upon the design of the lens and its distance from
the object. Close photographs often show significant bending and
warping in the corners. Satellite photos, on the other hand, are
taken from miles away and are able to map a scene with precision.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, satellite photos have not usually had enough
precision to be useful. The images are ideal for large events like
airplane crashes, but they have generally not had enough detail to
help investigate events like car crashes, which occur on a smaller
scale.
</P>
<P>
   That promises to change in the next several years as several
companies and nations race to launch satellites that can offer
1-meter resolution. In the past, most civilian services offered
10-meter resolution. (The resolution figure is a rough measurement
of the size of the object that can be seen on an image.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be fantastic,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Landgrebe said he was looking forward to the EO1, a new
satellite that will offer about 200 to 300 spectral bands of
information.
</P>
<P>
   Each band is really a number indicating the intensity of a
certain color emanating from a certain spot. Televisions, for
example, use three bands of information _ cyan, magenta and yellow
_ to display images.
</P>
<P>
   More bands give scientists better information to analyze the
plants and minerals being photographed by the airplane. Marijuana
plants, for instance, may reflect distinctive shades of green and
red that show up in 2 of the 300 different spectral bands. The
police might search for illicit crops by looking for locations that
show high amounts of those particular colors.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said his company was excited about this extra spectral
data because it could help in investigating disputes about
pollution and ground water. Information about the type of
vegetation and the temperature of the ground can help track the
flow of water in such cases.
</P>
<P>
   But the extra information could also muddy the water. Dr.
Stefanie Tompkins, a satellite imaging expert who works in northern
Virginia, pointed out that the extra information could be confusing
because one scientist could emphasize certain bands in creating an
image, while a scientific expert for a rival in a legal proceeding
could emphasize different bands. That could lead to strikingly
different images from the same data.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make something look very significant, but in some
cases it could be an instrument artifact,'' Tompkins said. ``In
some cases, it's something real, but it's not as big a deal. You
can stretch or enhance a certain feature.''
</P>
<P>
   While many members of the general public are eager to have
high-resolution information, military and intelligence officials
worry that easy access will promote spying. They have lobbied to
restrict these satellites in the hope of keeping their advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson understands their hesitations but argues that the new
information is too valuable to bottle up. ``I think the compromises
are  in the works,'' he said. ``The advantages of using
satellite information will be too great for the intelligence
community to keep a lid on the technology.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
