</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKEFELLER-APARTMENT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROCKEFELLER FIXER-UPPER: $19.5 MILLION, NEEDS WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sixty-five years ago, a brash young millionaire named
Nelson Aldrich Rockefeller bought the top floor of 810 Fifth Ave.,
at the corner of 62nd Street, then the southernmost apartment house
on upper Fifth Avenue. With its commanding views of Central Park,
it seemed like the perfect place for Rockefeller, then 26, and his
bride, Mary Todhunter Clark, to raise a large family.
</P>
<P>
   It was, and they did. They eventually expanded the property into
a 30-room triplex by buying the floor below and the penthouse
above. Last week, the heirs of Mary Clark Rockefeller _ she was
known as Tod, and died in April at 91 _ put a big chunk of that
apartment on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Priced at $19.5 million, it may be New York's most expensive
fixer-upper. And although the co-op building has a Fifth Avenue
address and prewar prestige, several agents say Mrs. Rockefeller's
apartment, which takes up the 13th floor and the penthouse, is
overpriced.
</P>
<P>
   While praising its full-floor apartments and discreet
side-street entrance, two agents murmured ``A-minus'' when
describing the building, which was constructed in 1926 to the
designs of J.E.R. Carpenter. Another cited a 1993 article in Town &AMP;
Country magazine that trumpeted the co-ops that were ``Tops on
Fifth''; 810 was not among them. It was placed in a second tier:
``Awfully Nice.''
</P>
<P>
   What Mrs. Rockefeller's 17-room, six-bath, four-fireplace home
does have, however, is sweeping views. And the glory of its last
owner's name. And a certain soap opera-style history.
</P>
<P>
   Like his mother, Abby Rockefeller, who fostered the Museum of
Modern Art and lived in rooms decorated by Donald Deskey of Radio
City Music Hall fame, Nelson Rockefeller was a lifelong fan of the
contemporary, in architecture and in art. In 1934, four years after
his marriage, he hired modern architect Wallace K. Harrison to
revamp the apartment at 810 and, later, to remodel the 12th-floor
spaces as well. ( Harrison would go on to design the Metropolitan
Opera House and to oversee the design of the United Nations
headquarters.) Rockefeller then hired Jean-Michel Frank, the hip
Paris or, to decorate via long distance portions of the 12th
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison made a round dining room out of the original square
one, and for its floor, he sank 18th-century parquet de Versailles
into a gray marble border. He also had input into the remodeling of
the penthouse, but its Bauhaus-bare interiors are credited to Jan
Rutenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Frank filled Harrison's spectacular oval living room with
cutting-edge furniture and Rockefeller's edgy art: murals by
Matisse and Fernand Leger, gilded consoles by Diego Giacometti,
candy-colored carpets by Christian Berard, Louis XV-style
furniture, lean ivory tables. The sculptor Hans Arp carved a
squiggle-edge chunk out of a ceiling and back-lighted the resulting
hole for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Rockefeller had residences in Venezuela and at the
family compound at Pocantico Hills in Westchester County, this
modern aerie was the place he considered home, said architectural
historian Andrew Alpern. ``He liked it so much, in fact, that he
did not move out after his divorce,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not entirely.
</P>
<P>
   When Tod and Nelson Rockefeller separated in 1961 _ she divorced
him in Reno, Nev., in 1962 _ they agreed to a Solomonic division of
property. She got the top two floors of the triplex; he got the
building's 12th floor, which included the oval living room. He then
reportedly ordered the connections between the his-and-her spaces
``permanently sealed.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Rockefeller, 55, and the governor of New York,
married Margaretta Fitler Murphy, known as Happy, a 36-year-old
divorced mother of four. The newlyweds proceeded to buy an
apartment in a building going up next door, at 812 Fifth, and
joined it to their portion of the neighboring triplex.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive to what must have been an uncomfortably close living
arrangement, Rockefeller, who died in 1979, and Happy Rockefeller,
as well as their two sons, always used the elevator in 812.
</P>
<P>
   Tod Rockefeller's apartment is one of the highest priced co-ops
to come on the market in several years. It still has the round
dining room. It still has walnut boiseries in the living room: the
circa-1935 ribbon-edge panels are a prime example of Harrison's
``rococo motif,'' as described in Victoria Newhouse's monograph on
the architect.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake. It definitely needs lots of work.
</P>
<P>
   The wall of pear-wood veneer in the foyer still looks good,
although it could do with a coat of wax. Anyone buying the place
would be certain to knock down some walls _ starting with two
built-in bookcases in the front of the apartment. The walls cut off
a third of the original 17-by-26-foot living room to create a
gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller evidently got custody of all the swank 1930s
furnishings, because his first wife _ a witty athlete who never
remarried _ decorated her big slice of the triplex in a mode that
can only be described as Greenwich-in-the-sky.
</P>
<P>
   The living room, as seen in the real-estate brochure, had the
aura of a country club foyer: baby-blue upholstered chairs, limply
pretty floral paintings, wan chintz. A cream carpet covered the
dining room's inset round of parquet de Versailles like a puddle of
evaporated milk.
</P>
<P>
   After the divorce, Tod Rockefeller used the corner library on
the lower floor as her bedroom, said Debby Solomon, the Douglas
Elliman agent who has listed the property. The space is Sensurround
celadon, from wall-to-wall carpet to paint.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Four bedrooms and three maids' rooms are on the main floor. The
kitchen is tiny, 12 by 11 feet, and unmodernized. A smaller kitchen
is in the two-bedroom penthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people would probably want to rip out the walls and make
bigger bedrooms,'' Ms. Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
   Though the $19.5 million price tag struck a number of real
estate agents as high, they couldn't think of anything comparable.
A penthouse at 1060 Fifth Ave. had great views, a great terrace,
good condition and the original floor plan, and it sold this year
for $8 million. But it faced neither Fifth Avenue nor the park.
Another penthouse in an A-plus building on Park Avenue sold last
year for $11.5 million. But the terrace was only 200 square feet:
how dare they call it a penthouse? said one agent. Still, the
Rockefeller apartment needs at least hundreds of thousands of
dollars of work.
</P>
<P>
   The agents conceded that the views from the penthouse's
1,200-square-foot wraparound terrace are one-of-a-kind (when the
building at 800 Fifth Ave. went up in the late 1970s, it was set
back from the street; it didn't block the views of the
Rockefellers). But rooms are not as well laid out as those in the
buildings designed by Rosario Candela, the master of the prewar
apartment house.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Gray, the architectural historian, said 810's
architect, J.E.R. Carpenter, ``designed all the next-best
buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the building was ``next best'' or not, Tod and Nelson
Rockefeller and their five children were in good company during
their three decades at 810 Fifth Ave. William Randolph Hearst Jr.
lived there at one time, as did Richard M. Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Tod Rockefeller's heirs and the real-estate agents arrived at
the price by looking at the prices of other penthouses on Fifth
Avenue, Ms. Solomon said. They also considered the protected
landmark views across the park and down Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Of the people who have seen it, Ms. Solomon said, price wasn't
the issue. ``They're trying to determine if they're at the right
emotional plane in their own lives to undertake a major project
like this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all,'' she added in a whisper, ``it does need an awful
lot of work.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1642EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
