<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5694 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     10-13 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV31-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., OCT. 31, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My house is only a couple of years old and there is a dead
bolt lock installed on the front door. This always closed easily
and lockly when the latch or key was turned, but for the
last few months this dead bolt has become very difficult to close _
in fact my young daughter can't seem to lock it.
</P>
<P>
   When the door is open the key turns easily and the bolt comes
out, but when the door is fully closed the end of the bolt doesn't
want to slide into its opening in the strike plate that is mounted
on the door frame.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the end of the dead bolt no longer lines up wi
opening, but I don't know which way to move the strike plate, or
whether the opening has to be simply enlarged slightly. Can you
tell me how to do this without calling in a professional?
</P>
<P>
   A: First check all the hinge screws on the door to make sure
none have worked loose. If any are loose the hinges may have
allowed the door to sag and this could cause the dead bolt to be
slightly out of alignment with its strike plate.
</P>
<P>
   If this is not the problem you can check the alignment in this
manner: Open the door and turn the dead bolt latch or key. Then
mark the projecting end of the dead bolt by smearing a little wet
paint on it as shown here. Retract the dead bolt and close the
door.
</P>
<P>
   Now turn the dead bolt latch again until it hits the strike
plate. Retract the dead bolt once more, swing the door open, then
look at the strike plate. You will see where the paint mark is and
thus will know where the opening has to be enlarged.
</P>
<P>
   Take off the plate, lock it in a vise, and use a file to remove
the amount required to enlarge the opening.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The aluminum storm door on the front of my house is white and
I want to paint it a different color. What kind of paint should I
use and is there any special preparation required?
</P>
<P>
   A: Scrub the door with a strong detergent, then sand the white
finish with a medium grit sandpaper to remove all gloss. Dust
thoroughly and wipe down with a rag moistened with paint thinner.
Apply a first coat of enamel undercoat or a shellac-based primer,
then finish with two coats of exterior enamel, sanding lightly
between coats.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our 50-year-old house has tongue-and-groove wood paneling in
the living room that is dirty and dull looking. How can we clean
this wood and preserve it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The most effective way to clean old paneling is to dust
thoroughly, then wipe down with a rag moistened with paint thinner
or other cleaning fluid (many of these solvents are flammable and
have an odor, so make sure there is plenty of ventilation and take
all proper precautions).
</P>
<P>
   Preserving the finish is a matter of determining what type of
finish was originally applied. If it was a wax type finish, then
simply applying a fresh coat of wax may be all that is required.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you are not sure, and if the varnish or shellac is
quite dull, then your best bet may be to apply one or two coats of
a wood sealer such as Minwax Tung Oil or Antique Oil Finish. I
would suggest you experiment on an inconspicuous corner first.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The concrete stoop on the front of our house has a corner
broken off on one of the steps. Although I tried filling in this
cavity with a good patching cement, this didn't last for long. Can
you tell me how to make a permanent repair to this concrete stoop?
</P>
<P>
   A: Instead of patching cement you should use a regular concrete
sand mix to build up the corner. However, this will require that
you build a wood form to hold the freshly mixed concrete in place
against the broken corner while it hardens.
</P>
<P>
   Clean off the old concrete thoroughly, making certain there is
no dirt or other foreign material on the surface, then build a
temporary form around the missing corner by using two boards that
are nailed together at right angles to each other, thus forming a
corner form.
</P>
<P>
   To hold this form in position, drive stakes into the ground on
each side, then nail these to the form boards. Or you may be able
to use several bricks or cement blocks propped against the outside
of the form.
</P>
<P>
   Coat the old masonry with a latex masonry bonding liquid, then
mix some of this bonding liquid in with the new concrete before
pouring it into the form. Trowel off at the surface and keep the
new patch slightly damp for at least 24 hours. Don't remove the
form boards for at least two or three days.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``LINING UP A DEAD BOLT LOCK'' goes with
this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Marking end of dead bolt with a little paint will help
determine how bolt end overlaps or misses the strike plate opening.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
