<HEADER>
A5696 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TEEN-SMOKING14-COX     10-13 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-SMOKING14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STATES LARGELY INEFFECTIVE IN HALTING TEEN SMOKING, STUDY SAYS
 &HT;    By Raven Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   States still haven't cracked down on tobacco sales to minors,
despite federal regulations that require them to do so, according
to a study released on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Based on an analysis of 1997 data from 59 states and territories
on their efforts to decrease tobacco sales to minors, the study
concluded that a 1992 federal law banning tobacco sales to minors
has not been adequately enforced by states of the U.S. Department
of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   The study appear in this month's issue of the Archives of
Pediatric and Adolescent Medicine, an American Medical Association
journal.
</P>
<P>
   In an evaluation of Health and Human Services performance, the
study found the department has not ``effectively required states to
enforce their laws, implemented timelines set down by the law, or
sanctioned states that fail to meet federal requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia and Texas, in fact, were found to have laws that
hindered enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few states have implemented effective enforcement
programs, and national surveys confirm that there has been no
measurable reduction in the availability of tobacco to youths,''
said one researcher, Dr. Joseph R. DiFranza, professor of Family
Medicine and Community Health at the University of Massachusetts
Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   This is largely the result of loopholes in various state
regulations and the lack of penalties imposed on merchants who
violate the law, DiFranza said. However, in a letter written to
DiFranza, Department of Human and Health Services Administrator
Linda Chavez expressed concern that the study was not an accurate
depiction of enforcement. Enforcement data over the past few years
has been ``extremely successful'' in achieving its goals, Chavez
wrote, asserting that states continue to improve their laws.
</P>
<P>
   According to Chavez, estimated average retailer sales rates to
minors in 1998 was 25 percent, down from approximately 40 percent
in 1997. The federal goal is for all states to have a 20 percent or
less inspection failure rate by 2003. Almost 20 states have
achieved that goal, Chavez said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, the only state to report a ``significant decline'' in
teenage smoking, has taken numerous steps to address the issue,
DiFranza said. It has increased the number of full-time inspectors
assigned to monitor retailers and imposed penalties on violators,
which have helped to decrease the state's violation rate to 5
percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   DiFranza said the average violation rate should be 10 percent if
states plan to meet the 2003 deadline. He recommended that states
allocate more funds to attacking the problem and encouraged more
aggressive enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to understand how you can enforce a law if
there are no penalties. It defies common sense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
