<HEADLINE>
EDWARD GOREY'S A `MYSTERY' TO MOST, BUT THAT MAY CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Author/illustrator Edward Gorey isn't quite right ... which
probably explains my complete and utter fascination with him.
</P>
<P>
   He fills a corner of a room in my house reserved for what I like
to call my ``darker collections'' with his odd assortment of tiny,
hand-size digest books, little story books, oversized poster books
as well as an assortment of other Gorey tchotchkes, from stuffed
bats to miniature coffins. They seem in perfect company with the
Aurora monster model kits and Day of the Dead knickknacks that
clutter the place.
</P>
<P>
   Gorey has toiled in the business for almost 50 years, producing
as many books and an astounding amount of ephemera, but he still
feels like my own secret discovery. That's nonsense, of course. His
books are phenomenally popular (and pricey for avid collectors),
yet national celebrity seems to have escaped him entirely. The only
identifying connection that most people can make to him comes from
his animated title segment on the PBS series ``Mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of pop-culture obscurity makes him a tough sell for
trend-hungry editors. Thank goodness for Our Endeavors Theater
Company's production of ``Gorey Stories,'' a musical based on 18 of
Gorey's most memorable works. It opens Thursday at Dallas' Deep
Ellum Center for the Arts. Even better, the production will be
accompanied by ``Goreality,'' an exhibit of original Gorey artwork
and rare prints culled from his official archivists at New York's
Gotham Book Mart along with local and San Francisco-area
collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Our Endeavors artisic director and ``Gorey Stories'' director
Scott Osborne recalls discovering Gorey almost six years ago after
receiving a copy of ``The Gashlycrumb Tinies'' from a cast member.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, his discovery of the extent of Gorey's outstanding
career has been ``like peeling an onion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's thematically ideal for this time of year,'' Osborne says,
``both humorous and horrific at the same time. And there's a lot of
room to put our own imprint on the work and still have Edward
Gorey's images filter through. Each story has its own flavor and
style of presentation.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a casual examination of Gorey's cautionary tales of hapless
children, tragic ballerinas, hungry insect gods and loathsome,
murderous couples would lead one to make several assumptions:
</P>
<P>
   1. He's twisted. Although most of Gorey's work appears perfectly
suited to kids, the younger of the species remain his most frequent
victims. One of his most famous works, ``The Gashlycrumb Tinies,''
is a rhyming alphabet of children who meet unfortunate ends.
</P>
<P>
   2. He's British. His figures have the pasty-white, overdressed,
slightly Victorian feel we've come to associate with Brits, and
their speech is achingly proper.
</P>
<P>
   3. He's dead. His works have a dated, antique feel, as if
uncovered among dusty, arcane volumes in a cramped, overstuffed,
forgotten bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you know what they say about assuming. He may very
well be twisted, but his ebony sense of humor has influenced a
generation of artists, from the wickedly funny cartoons of Gahan
Wilson to the mirthfully macabre films of Tim Burton _ whose
``Nightmare Before Christmas'' seems an obvious tribute to Gorey
sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and yes, he is very much alive and still quite prolific. His
next book _ ``The Headless Bust,'' a sequel to last year's
Christmas tale, ``The Haunted Tea Cozy'' _ is due in stores in
early November.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago native claims never to have visited England, and
rarely strays from his weathered 19th-century cottage on Cape Cod.
Apart from his days as an avid patron of the New York City Ballet,
dressed in a floor-length fur coat and sneakers (a look that
frequently appears in his stories), Gorey spends much of his time
at home, reading and, dare I say it, watching television. His
lawyer, Graham Coleman, claims that Gorey maintains a meticulous
library of videotaped programs, though he's unsure whether ``Buffy
the Vampire Slayer'' is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   And now it seems as if Gorey is finding new life among Gen X-ers
and post-Gen X-ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's driving (his popularity) is the under-30s,'' Coleman
says. ``His permanent gallery at the Gotham Book Mart in New York
is like a pilgrimage for them. The folks at Gotham tell me that
every time someone with spiky hair walks in, or someone who looks
like they just got off the train from prep school, you know they're
there on a Gorey pilgrimage.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman says that Gorey Web sites have sprung up like
toadstools, prompting him to politely police sites that get a
little too enthusiastic. Most fans, however, are usually eager to
comply and refrain from reprinting the entire contents of books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them love that they've gotten the notice from someone
who works for the master,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That fan base could grow if Gorey's next project comes to
fruition: an animated film in conjuncture with cartoon legend Chuck
Jones. Coleman says there is currently a deal to produce Gorey's
``The Doubtful Guest'' as either a short or as part of a Gorey
anthology series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That two masters of the line would come together is very
exciting to us,'' Colemen says.
</P>
<P>
   There's a part of me that's excited, too, yet I can't help but
feel a little sad. My secret discovery is soon not to be a secret
any longer.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   INFO BOX
</P>
<P>
   ``Gorey Stories'' opens Thursday and runs through Nov. 7 at the
Deep Ellum Center for the Arts, 2808 Commerce St. in Dallas. Show
times are 8 p.m. Thursdays-Saturdays; 2:30 p.m. Sundays.
``Goreality'' is on display 1-7 p.m. Tuesday-Saturday, as well as
during intermission and before and after performances. Tickets are
$7-$17, call (972) 355-2879.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a pop culture critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1645EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
