r d BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     10-13 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING 'ROUND FOR A SQUARE CAKE PLATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I received an e-mail from Tami Wadlington, who is looking for a
square cake keeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry provides us with square cake pans and recipes,
yet no one seems to have a cake plate that we can keep them fresh
in,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Well, look no more.
</P>
<P>
   The eBay Web site, that Internet source of all things wonderful,
often lists square cake keepers. In fact, I bought a lovely 1950s
chrome one recently for the bargain price of $5. (Shipping, of
course, is extra.) To find eBay, type www.ebay.com and you're in
business.
</P>
<P>
   A READER IN A PICKLE: A reader called looking for a recipe for
okra pickles. She has ``armloads'' of cookbooks but no pickle
recipe.
</P>
<P>
   So, for all you okra lovers out there, here's one from
``Stocking Up III'' by Carol Hupping (MJF Books, $15.95).
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   OKRA PICKLES
</P>
<P>
   Yields 6 pints
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 cups white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   _ 5 cups water
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 teaspoons celery seeds
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 pounds small okra pods, washed, with stems removed
</P>
<P>
   _ 2/3 pound onions, peeled
</P>
<P>
   _ 6 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   _ 6 small hot chile peppers (optional)
</P>
<P>
   _ 6 pieces green pepper, 1-inch square
</P>
<P>
   Make a brine with vinegar, water and celery seeds. Boil in an
enamel or stainless steel pot.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, pack okra firmly in hot, scalded pint jars. In each
jar, put 4 onions, 1 clove garlic, 1 chile pepper and 1 square of
green pepper. Pour boiling brine over okra, leaving 1/4-inch head
space. Seal and process for 15 minutes in a boiling-water bath.
</P>
<P>
   Let ripen several weeks before using.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS FOR 1/4 CUP: 13 calories, 0 fat, 3 grams
carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 0 cholesterol, 2 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   REQUESTS:
</P>
<P>
   _ Donna Green had a recipe for Luby's cucumber salad that
included vinegar, water and pickle juice in the dressing. I've
searched for this recipe in our computer library but can't locate
it. Perhaps a reader has a copy?
</P>
<P>
   _ Beverly Welch ate a chewy chocolate walnut cookie at Fort
Worth's Coffee Haus and says ``it's the best cookie I've ever
eaten.'' Unfortunately, Coffee Haus buys the cookie from an
industrial baker, making the recipe untenable for home bakers. Does
anyone have such a cookie recipe?
</P>
<P>
   _ Nova Seay of Cleburne, Texas, has misplaced her 20-year-old
recipe for strawberry bread. What's unusual about her lost recipe
is that it used strawberry preserves instead of frozen
strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rosa Hubbard of Fort Worth, Texas, would like a recipe for
spinach lasagna.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
