<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5700 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-WORKING-AMERICANS-2ND     10-13 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-AMERICANS-2NDTAKE-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: a master's degree. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Linda Pavlik, owner of the Fort Worth communications firm
Pavlik &AMP; Associates, the nature of the job she loves means
unusually long hours. ``Night meetings, weekend meetings, breakfast
meetings, daylong retreats,'' she says. ``If you're going to
participate in public policy and the making of public policy, that
is when people meet.''
</P>
<P>
   But cultural attitudes toward work may be changing, notes Greg
Stephens, an associate professor of management at Texas Christian
University in Fort Worth. Research examining workers' commitments
to their jobs shows that fewer people are equating long hours at
work with a high level of commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today people say, `I can be very committed for eight hours a
day' '' and still be a valuable employee, Stephens notes.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Gonzalez wasn't consciously looking to change his hectic
pace. As the director of marketing and client relations for a
Dallas graphic-design firm, he was beginning his days with 7 a.m.
networking meetings and proofreading copy until the wee hours of
the night. ``It was a job that was your life,'' the 25-year-old
says.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez recently left the firm and took a temp job that has him
working from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. ``It's like nothing I've ever done,''
he says. ``I get my hour lunch, I don't take (the work) home with
me, and nothing around here is'' a matter of life and death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly will never work that hard again,'' Gonzalez says.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are those people choosing to leave the workplace
altogether. In September, Terri Buggs, a financial analyst for 16
years, quit to stay at home with her 6-year-old. She is expecting
another child in January.
</P>
<P>
   Buggs and her husband, who live in Arlington, Texas, met with a
financial analyst to help them develop a new budget. ``It's going
to be tougher,'' she says. ``But I think all of our needs will be
supplied.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerson and Eurotas admit to pining for saner schedules _ time
to give to their families or other interests. But Weinstein of UNT
sees no alternative but to keep putting in the long days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I complain about my job, my son asks, `Why don't
you retire?' '' Weinstein says, ``And I say, `I wouldn't know what
to do with myself.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
