<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5703 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-WORKING-AMERICANS-120     10-13 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-AMERICANS-1200(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVVING UP THE RAT RACE: AMERICANS ARE WORKING MORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ralph Emerson Jr. makes sure he eats breakfast with his
16-year-old son every morning and checks in with him each afternoon
after school. On the days that son Ralph plays basketball for his
high-school team, Emerson's schedule is uncompromising: He's at the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, his days are defined by his most time-consuming
responsibility by far: work.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson is pastor of Rising Star Missionary Baptist Church in
Fort Worth, and, like those of increasing numbers of Americans, his
workweek easily exceeds the traditional 40 hours.
</P>
<P>
   In September, a study released by the United Nations
International Labour Organization showed that Americans spend more
time on the job than employees in any other industrialized nation:
1,966 hours a year. That's more than the Germans, more than the
French and more than the notoriously workaholic Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   Why this is so, and what the repercussions are _ even whether
the latest statistics are accurate _ are matters of debate among
economists and sociologists. It's probably safe to say, at the very
least, that Americans feel as if they're working more. A minority
are even consciously cutting back.
</P>
<P>
   Not Emerson, who arrives at the office by 8:30 a.m. and often
gets home after 10 p.m. In the evenings, he attends board meetings
and makes house visits. But Emerson is dedicated to his job, he
says, ``so I don't put in those hours and complain.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts attribute the steady rise in American work hours to
numerous things. Women are putting in more hours on the job. In a
booming economy, there's more work to be done. Employees are
attempting to learn and keep up with new technologies, and that
takes time.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate downsizing has left fewer people to do the same amount
of work, notes Dr. Joyce Williams, chairman of the department of
sociology and social work at Texas Woman's University in Denton,
Texas. And, for hourly workers especially, she suggests, keeping up
with the cost of living means working overtime or working more than
one job.
</P>
<P>
   In some sectors, the competition for good jobs puts pressure on
employees to excel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a high level of expectation,'' says a 39-year-old
professional woman who works in Fort Worth, Texas, and asked to
remain anonymous. ``The bar keeps getting raised, and you do
whatever you have to do to get over that bar.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep profits steady, this woman's employer has had to cut
overhead _ i.e. staff _ and now she works her job and someone
else's. She averages 10-hour days and at least one full weekend
day. And when she doesn't go into the office on a Saturday or
Sunday, she feels queasy about it on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, she believes, her hard work will pay off. ``At
a higher level, you can shape your own destiny a little more,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody is convinced that Americans are working more. In
1997, authors John Robinson and Geoffrey Godbey purported in ``Time
for Life'' that Americans have more free time now than they've had
in the past 30 years. Their findings were so controversial that it
took the pair five years to find a publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Economists have generally accepted the ILO statistics, with
differing reactions. When Bernard Weinstein hears about the boost
in American work hours, he sees sunny economic skies. We might be
working more, ``but we're also making more money and we're getting
wealthier,'' says Weinstein, director of the center for economic
development at the University of North Texas in Denton and a
professor of applied economics.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the debate, Juliet Schor sees a potential
maelstrom. The author of 1991's ``The Overworked American,'' Schor
raised a red flag about the effects of longer workplace hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have paid a price for prosperity,'' she wrote then.
``Capitalism has brought a dramatically increased standard of
living, but at the cost of a much more demanding work life.'' This,
she suggested, ``has contributed to a variety of social problems''
_ like stress, sleep deprivation and a perceived breakdown in
family life.
</P>
<P>
   But there may be a whole newer dimension as to why Americans'
workdays are getting longer: It's possible that we like our jobs
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend most of our waking hours working, and for most
people, work is one of the major fulfillments in life,'' Williams
notes. Among sociologists, there is speculation that ``we are less
inclined to look to family and relationships for our only
satisfaction.'' Research, she says, shows that this is especially
true among younger generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the work I do,'' says Gloria Eurotas, assistant
director for the Fort Worth Housing Department. ``I like being in
an executive position and to be challenged, and I don't like to be
stagnant and bored.''
</P>
<P>
   Eurotas, who is single, will work four out of five Saturdays
this month. Since March, she has been doing her job plus the job of
a subordinate whom the department has yet to replace. And she just
started pursuing a master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
