NYT-10-13-99 1646EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5704 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-RUGBY-1014-CO     10-13 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-RUGBY-1014-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. RUGBY TEAM WINNING WORLD CUP FANS ON SYMPATHY, AS WELL AS
GUTSY PLAY
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMERICK, Ireland _ Seamus McGarry took a break Wednesday
morning from scraping the dirt from a roadside gutter to study the
parade of stout young men in navy warm-ups board a large white bus.
</P>
<P>
   The bus waited by a grassy playing field set in a hillside at
Limerick University. ``It's the Americans that's boarding that
coach,'' McGarry remarked to a co-worker, who then paused to lean
on his shovel and have a look. The members of USA Rugby had just
finished their morning practice session in preparation for their
World Cup match Thursday against Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor dears,'' McGarry said, offering his own expert analysis.
``The Aussies will be too much for them, I'm afraid. But its
Limerick that will be for them. Limerick loves the underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   Limerick, meet USA Rugby.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a miracle. No, barring many, many miracles, the U.S.
rugby team will exit the World Cup tournament Thursday after being
drubbed by one of the best teams on Earth. Imagine the Atlanta
Braves playing an amateur team of deeply devoted yet inexperienced
players from, say, Australia. No, it's worse than that. In August,
Team USA was swatted by Team England 106-8.
</P>
<P>
   In their first World Cup match, they were beaten 53-8 by Ireland
_ a fact that may be contributing to the generous spirit in
Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   If the situation doesn't seem sufficiently dire, then let's
strip the underdogs of their best player. Dan Lyle, a former
football standout at Atlanta's Woodward Academy, will be sidelined
with a separated shoulder. A popular professional who plays for the
tough Bath, England, club, Lyle has been the team's captain and
wizened father. He is one of only four professionals on a team that
also includes computer software salesmen, students, teachers, a
miner, chiropractor and a few guys who will be looking for work
when they get home.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle, 29, was forced out of last Saturday's bitter 27-25 loss to
Romania, which was the team's best and so far only opportunity.
Team USA is 1-7 in World Cup competition since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The team also will be without former University of Georgia
football star Richard Tardits, who returned home to Marietta, Ga.,
for personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   If the Americans can manage a score against the Australians it
will be a cause for celebration.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to rugby _ a game that looks like the love
child of American football and soccer _ Limerick celebrates easily.
The town considers itself the sport's spiritual center.
</P>
<P>
   ``What all the people are talking these days is rugby,'' said
John Wallace, a taxi driver who figures the World Cup has flooded
the town of 50,000 with visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Rugby seems the perfect game for this once desperately poor town
that provided author Frank McCourt a childhood miserable enough to
frame his sad and heralded autobiography ``Angela's Ashes.'' (There
is an ``Angela's Ashes'' walking tour.)
</P>
<P>
   While the wounds of poverty still mark the gray old city,
Limerick also sports fresh signs of wealth. The city is capturing
more than its of the boom that President Clinton when he visited
last year called the ``Celtic Tiger.'' All around town there is new
construction. Many of the streets are recently resurfaced and many
main roads are lined by freshly planted trees. For this long
suffering place, the Rugby World Cup means as much as the Olympic
Games to a bigger city. In truth, the rugby championship is No. 3
on the list of the world's most popular televised sporting events
behind the Olympics and soccer's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The aura has infused the Americans. ``Limerick is buzzing,''
said Lyle during a conversation in the lobby of the fancy new
Castletroy Park Hotel, the team's home here. ``Everywhere you go
you're surrounded by knowledgeable rugby people. You wake up in the
morning and read the newspaper and watch TV and you learn something
about the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyle is one of the handful of U.S. players, who look like
throwbacks to gridiron players of the 1940s, with significant
international experience. A massive man at 6-foot-4 and 245 pounds,
Lyle was a college football standout at Virginia Military Institute
who rejected a contract with the Minnesota Vikings to play pro
rugby.
</P>
<P>
   He lives much of the year in tourist mecca Bath, where he is
revered for his unbridled play and All-American style.
</P>
<P>
   His example feeds the notion that you could assemble a
world-beating rugby team from the hundreds of gifted college
athletes who fall just short of professional football standards in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle and others with the team say it's not that easy, however.
The essential framework for recruiting, playing and developing
doesn't now exist in the United States. But it is beginning, and
the exposure given Team USA this year has helped.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Clark, the team's coach, believes just being in the World
Cup is an accomplishment. The team beat Tonga, Fiji and Canada to
get here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States of America is in the world championship of
rugby, and we qualified to get here,'' Clark said in a lightly
attended news conference Wednesday. ``Though boys have played not
always precise rugby, we've left our hearts on the field each time
out. I'm very proud of them and so is America.''
</P>
<P>
   And the future for U.S. rugby is bright, he said. ``For the
first time in our world cup experiences, I think we can identify 10
to 20 players who could see action in the next world cup, and
obviously by that time will have the experience level to make a
mark on the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday is likely to belong to the Australians _ even if
the Irish hearts are with the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even in Limerick, there is a glint of pleasure in watching
the Yanks _ who have come to dominate so much in Europe _ get a
lesson in humility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, you wouldn't think the Americans would be needing to
learn about anything,'' said Damien Duffy, taking a slow frothy sip
from a pint of Guinness in Thady O'Neill's pub on the Ennis Road.
``But I'm thinking it's rugby that still has a few lessons in it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
