<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5707 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-FRAZZLED-PARENT-TEX     10-13 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAZZLED-PARENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRROR, MIRROR, ON THE WALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CARTERINE NEWTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mom's knees were scrunched under a too-small desk and her
torso towered over it, a fact that seemed to add to the intensity
of her voice as she leaned toward her daughter. ``Katherine, don't
be a doormat. Never be a doormat. Don't let people walk all over
you.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a parent-child-teacher conference many years ago, back
when I was on the side representing an organization of learning. I
wasn't a mother yet _ and moms intrigued me. Why was this one so
upset with her daughter? The little girl, Katherine, was a
strong-willed, confident middle-schooler, the kind of student we
all want our daughters to be.
</P>
<P>
   This mom wasn't really talking about her daughter, I thought
smugly. This is all about her and her self-confidence issues
instead.
</P>
<P>
   I won't be like that when I'm a mom, I thought. I won't confuse
my issues with my daughter's. When I'm a mother, it clearly won't
be about me ...
</P>
<P>
   ELEVEN YEARS AND TWO CHILDREN LATER
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's the prettiest girl?'' I ask my daughter. We're on the
way to school,and she looks to me like an American version of
Madeleine with her navy school jumper and Peter Pan-collared white
blouse. ``I am,'' she replies, because she knows this game seems to
make me happy.
</P>
<P>
   And it apparently does make me happy, because I do it all the
time, without thinking. I tell my 6-year-old she's pretty in the
morning when I kiss her to wake her up. I tell her as a consolation
after I torture her by brushing her hair. I tell her when she plays
fairy, when she emerges from a bubbly bath, when she puts on her
Barbie nightgown, or even when she's biting her toenails. ``You're
so pretty, Hadley,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   I guess it makes me happy. It also makes me sick.
</P>
<P>
   I noticed this most recently last week, when Hadley, her older
brother, Jack, and I were engaged in a cutthroat Pretty Pretty
Princess competition. In case you aren't aware of this latest
offering from the masterminds at Milton Bradley, the object of the
game is to acquire all the pieces of jewelry in your special color
_ and the bejeweled crown. If you do so, and avoid the evil black
ring, then you turn the spinner over, look in the mirror and see
just how pretty you, the winner, are.
</P>
<P>
   Jack won, and as he swung his blue, beaded earrings back and
forth, laughing at his own image, it was all fun. But then Hadley
won the second game, and as she gazed at her reflection, serenely
studying her pretty self, suddenly I wasn't smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I thought: I'm raising a girl who cares too much
about what she _ and other people _ look like. I am, in truth,
raising myself. I'm breeding a little ``lookist.'' It wasn't a
pretty thought _ and it wasn't the first time I'd thought it.
</P>
<P>
   Be like me. Be like me. It's a message I've subconciously sent
my kids since the moment they were born. I dress them in Gap capris
and khakis that look like miniature versions of my own. I take
Hadley with me for manicures. I put them both in T-shirts
emblazoned with the name of my alma mater. I play them the songs I
love in the car, encourage them to watch reruns of the Bradys and
make them dance when they're feeling stressed _ just like I do. I
adore these newer, smaller, more perfect mirror images of myself _
these living, breathing conceits over which I believe I have some
control.
</P>
<P>
   Until the illusion shatters. Inevitably, my kids reflect back
something I don't like. Some less pretty side of myself that makes
me wonder, ``What have I wrought?'' And makes me think with fury:
``Don't be like me. Don't be like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't be like me, Hadley, because I know what that's like, and
frankly it isn't easy sometimes. You'll end up buying $100 worth of
makeup from a salesman who tells you that your eyes are beautiful.
You'll have great shoes, but a fence that needs repair. You'll fall
for nice-looking men who tell you that you look good but who in the
end seem to have the self-awareness of a Ziploc bag.
</P>
<P>
   Was it too late for Hadley? I worried about this for days after
the Pretty Pretty Princess episode, obsessing over the matter until
at last I decided to test her, to see how deep my pretty poison had
sunk.
</P>
<P>
   I put the question to my daughter point-blank: ``Is it better to
be pretty or smart?''
</P>
<P>
   Hadley looked at me for a few seconds and then laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, it's better to be snuggly,'' she said. ``And to have a
happy family.''
</P>
<P>
   Whew. At least Hadley hasn't confused my issues with her own.
For now, this love-hate relationship with all things pretty is
clearly all about me. .MDBR/.MDBO/.MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
