<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5711 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-FRENCH-SHOWCASE-ART-N     10-13 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-SHOWCASE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURMURS OF THE WALLET AT THE FRENCH SHOW HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Colette said that you shouldn't eat truffles unless
you can eat them like potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   She would have loved the 1999 French Designer Showhouse, which
opens Thursday at 34 E. 69th St. It would stop a rooting pig. All
the luxuries, both material and ephemeral, that the French hold
dear are there in spades. Walking up through the five floors of
decorated rooms and landings is like spending too much money on a
short holiday in Paris in boutiques, hotels and restaurants.
Soignee as Seyrig, handsome as Deneuve, it's fun, but it's heady.
The house looks like a pile of the best shopping bags at the end of
an exceptionally self-rewarding day. This would not be a cheap
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is not inappropriate to the address of this year's
show: the residence of the consul general of Iran, until it was
seized by the U.S. government in 1980. The State Department rented
it to the show house committee for the month.
</P>
<P>
   If there are fabrics employed, they are silk and velvet in the
most fragile colors, like the tips of Abyssinian-cat hair, or
leather and fur in the most unnatural. If there is ambiance, it is
layer upon layer of wealth, whether subtle or not, coquettish or
unconcealed. For every muted wall treatment, like the two weeks'
worth of gesso-work in Brigitte Saby's quiet-hued, platinum bedroom
or the precious metallic powder mixed into the Benjamin Moore in
Jennifer Ellenberg and Jane Victor's bronze bedroom, there is an
unequivocal cream of pumpkin, like Florence de Dampierre's orange
dressing room for an Anglophilic fetishist.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. de Dampierre's fantasy client has a wardrobe of
caramel-colored bikers' caps that would look good on
St.-Germain-des-Pres, bespoke suits with both trousers and skirts,
high heels and brogues.
</P>
<P>
   Like much of the show house, it has the wit of seduction, which
is decoration practiced at its most professional. Send the bill.
</P>
<P>
   There is much high couture and haute cuisine, all the
dress-fitting and sauce-making expected of the French. Jacques
Garcia's salon has more fabric panels than a Balenciaga, more
braiding and trim than a Lacroix. The warm chestnut browns and
pheasant beiges of Madeleine and Jean-Louis Mellerio's study has
the nuanced richness of a reduced stock.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any much-talked-about globalization or fusion
influence, it is in the roster of designers, from Frenchmen working
in New York, like Garcia, to Italians working in Paris, like the
Mellerios, to Ms. Saby, who has the only decorator's office in
Moscow, period.
</P>
<P>
   As quickly as they are crossing the map, they are also crossing
periods and styles, now as a matter of course. There seems more
fashionable correctness than precociousness or controversy in
Olivier Gelbsmann's dining room table, set with 18th-century French
porcelain and midcentury-modern Italian glass. Or in the Verner
Panton white plastic chairs that sit like Courreges boots across
Paul Mathieu's boiserie-paneled library from a grand piano. A
flat-screen television blocking the marble fireplace mouth projects
a videotape of Alain Resnais' ``Last Year at Marienbad,'' a
cineaste's vision of artificial logs.
</P>
<P>
   Like French couture and cuisine, the show house also has its
ready-to-wear ideas and its recipes for the home cook. Richard
Mishaan's artist's atelier is wallpapered in pool-table felt, at
$11 a yard. Christopher Coleman's contemporary kitchen cabinetry is
standard Ikea and stainless steel restaurant supply, combined for a
custom look. There is hope for the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to know if the news, the direction, the millennial
moment of the French Designer Showhouse is a condemned man's meal
or the start of something great _ they're both parts of a
revolution _ but the message is, clearly, to enjoy, which isn't a
question of money exclusively. It's a question of learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds nice, `the 21st century,''' said Mathieu, unshaven
like Rip Van Winkle, and dressed in brown, sitting on the sofa in
his futuristic library watching the stylish sleepwalkers in
Resnais' film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we are able to manage so much, such a wealth of
choices and technology and information,'' he said, ``now we need
poetry. And peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The French Designer Showhouse, at 34 E. 69th St., is open
through Nov. 14; hours are 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily, until 8 p.m. on
Thursdays. Admission, $20, benefits the American Hospital in Paris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
