<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5712 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SCHOOLS-PESTICIDES14-     10-13 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-PESTICIDES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATORS START DRIVE FOR SCHOOL PESTICIDE LAW
 &HT;    460&AMP;add.
 &HT;    With photos.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Jesse Rifkin was 8 when his grade school in
Annapolis, Md., was sprayed with a pesticide.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse, now 13, said Wednesday that as he left his classroom that
day and went out the door, ``I began to feel red, hot and itchy. My
throat was closing up and I had trouble breathing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesse had been moderately asthmatic since he was exposed four
years earlier in Los Angeles to a similar pesticide sprayed to kill
fruit flies, and his mother recognized the symptoms as he
approached her car. She quickly gave him a pill that kept him from
going into full-fledged anaphylactic shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though I was the only kid who reacted that severely that day,
quite a few students and parents felt pretty ill after that
exposure,'' Jesse said.
</P>
<P>
   His mother brought Jesse to Capitol Hill to join the National
PTA and groups of environmentalists, pediatricians and teachers in
helping Sens. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., and Patty Murray, D-Wash.,
launch a national crusade for uniform pesticide safety rules for
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The School Environment Protection Act proposed by the senators
would ban use of some toxic pesticides in schools and require
schools to first use the safest methods of pest-fighting, such as
filling in cracks or avoiding food spills that attract pests.
</P>
<P>
   If mild methods don't work, schools would have to post signs and
send notices to parents, guardians and teachers one to four days
before applying conventional pesticides. The notice would have to
list potential side effects.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is ``misguided,'' said Allen James, executive
director of RISE, an association of pesticide makers, formulators
and distributors. He said that by making pest control less
effective, the bill would ``put children at risk for a variety of
major diseases and illnesses'' associated with cockroaches, fire
ants, wasps, mosquitoes, poison oak and ivy, rats and mice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main risk would be weeds,'' scoffed Torricelli, who said
risky pesticides often are used to beautify campuses and playing
fields.
</P>
<P>
   To notify each parent or guardian before each application ``is a
little burdensome and cumbersome, and it unnecessarily worries
parents,'' said Gene Harrington, manager of government affairs for
the National Pest Control Association, an alliance of pest control
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing his concern, Murray said, ``It is the right of every
parent to know what their child is exposed to on the playground or
in school.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   Harrington's group prefers laws like those in Texas, which was
the first state to require that schools offer parents or guardians
a chance once a year to sign up to be notified each time a
pesticide is applied.
</P>
<P>
   That wouldn't help parents who don't suspect that their child's
symptoms are related to pesticides, Murray replied.
</P>
<P>
   Laws similar to the Torricelli-Murray bill were adopted in
Maryland last year and in Connecticut this year. In California,
Gov. Gray Davis vetoed a similar bill this week on the grounds that
it had technical flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating a long fight, Torricelli acknowledged that the bill
won't be adopted in this Congress. The U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency has yet to respond to a petition by the National
Coalition Against Misuse of Pesticides to impose similar
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli said that he and Murray hope that their bill will
inspire parents across the land to join their crusade to put
pressure on Congress for a new law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty states have taken leadership, having some form of
protection for children from pesticides,'' he said. ``But they are
almost all different, sometimes contradictory and without any
uniformity.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today, he said, 20 states and most school districts ``have
not addressed this problem and do not even know that it exists.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
