<HEADER>
A5715 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FISHING-BOOK-REVIEW-N     10-13 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHING-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY FELL HOOK, LINE AND SINKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Story was slugged ORVIS-BOOK-REVIEW on the
ENTERTAINMENT-BUDGET.) 
 (DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A jerk on one end of a line waiting for a jerk on the other,''
is the classic folk definition of fishing that explains the title
of Robert Hughes' witty testimonial to the sport, ``A Jerk on One
End: Reflections of a Mediocre Fisherman.''
</P>
<P>
   A jerk is what the author often enough feels like, he implies.
``All in all,'' he writes, ``were I to amortize the market value of
the fish I catch in a year against the expense of catching them, I
would say I was spending about $55 per pound on bluefish, which,
scaled and filleted, can be had in the local store for about
$3.99.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hughes _ who was born in Sydney, Australia, and has lived
and worked in the United States since 1970 as art critic for Time
magazine _ also manages to convey why not only he but also many
other human beings are happy to make jerks of themselves pursuing
fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental experience of fishing consists of dropping a
line into the unknown,'' he writes. ``You can guess at what is down
there; you can make your best estimates based on tide, habitat,
feeding patterns and so forth; but you do not really know. ... It
may be edible or not; thorny, spiny or beautifully sleek; equipped
with gnashing jaws or relatively passive; but there is always,
assuming you aren't sight-fishing, the magic moment when the thing
struggling on your line down there could be anything.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, he plunges himself into many of the mysteries of
fishing and emerges with plausible explanations. He asks, for
instance, why the fishing reel was used in China some four
centuries before it appeared in England, and suggests that
``because fishing in China was a high-class sport as well as common
work, Chinese anglers were far ahead of European techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   He explores how fly fishing for trout came to be regarded as
superior to all other ways of angling, and concludes: ``As the
English countryside was transformed by the Industrial Revolution,
both the old landed gentry and the new mercantile one whose coal
mines and iron works were fouling the streams and blackening the
meadows of an earlier England naturally wanted their own unpolluted
crystal rills, the image of whose purity was the trout.'' To catch
them on a fly became ``a stylistic imperative, a sign of class.''
</P>
<P>
   He inquires why anglers pursue tarpon when that fish has so
little value as food. And answers: ``The jump of a tarpon is
startling and scary. It can go as high as 10 feet. The fish
explodes out of the water, twisting and whipping, a column of
quicksilver in a storm of foam. It is an epiphany.''
</P>
<P>
   One benefit of fishing he disputes is an early English writer's
assertion that angling can make one rich. To the contrary, Hughes
writes, ``the only people who have ever made a buck off amateur
fishing are the makers of fishing gear.'' As if to prove this
point, in ``A Sportsman's Life: How I Built Orvis by Mixing
Business and Sport,'' Leigh Perkins tells how he transformed a
small fishing-equipment company into a $200-million-a-year
mail-order business.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins attributes his success largely to luck: the luck to have
been born wealthy, an heir to the fortune built by the
industrialist Mark Hanna; the luck to have bought Orvis out of a
love for fishing and hunting instilled in him by his devoted
mother; and the luck to have presided over his company in the era
when the computer, the credit card and the overnight
package-delivery system arrived.
</P>
<P>
   But to judge from his lively account, it was more than luck that
led him to prepare himself by working for 12 years in the mining
and welding-equipment businesses; that allowed him to buy Orvis out
of his own earnings rather than his inheritance; that helped him to
overcome the resistance to new ideas in a company that tended to
look down on its customers; and that inspired him to invent the
Orvis zinger, the little reel with the spring-loaded retractable
wire that attaches clippers and other useful small tools to the
vests of virtually every fly fisherman wading a stream these days.
</P>
<P>
   The fun of reading ``A Sportsman's Life'' is watching a company
best known for selling good fly rods grow into an emporium from
which you could order what Perkins proudly refers to as ``a kind of
Americanized version of elegant, English country living,'' or what
Hughes calls ``the whole Victorian-Edwardian Bushido of
fine-tackle, dry-fly fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Less entertaining are Perkins' accounts of fishing and hunting
in exotic places, and his general air of satisfaction with all
things, which embrace even the future of endangered animal species.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes is not so optimistic. He doesn't blame the sport
fisherman, whom he exhorts to embrace moderation. But to save the
world's oceans he calls for an understanding of aquatic otherness
that rather takes away the mystery of the deep. Read ``A
Sportsman's Life'' and you will rejoice in fishing lines that jerk.
But read Hughes' book, where the author concludes that ``as one
gets older one views all death with less indifference,'' and you
will sense that the jerk holding the line has wised up and feels a
little less like fishing.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `A JERK ON ONE END
</P>
<P>
   Reflections of a Mediocre Fisherman'
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Hughes
</P>
<P>
   126 pages. The Library of Contemporary Thought/The Ballantine
Publishing Group . $18.95.
</P>
<P>
   `A SPORTSMAN'S LIFE
</P>
<P>
   How I Built Orvis by Mixing Business and Sport'
</P>
<P>
   By Leigh Perkins
</P>
<P>
   With Geoffrey Norman. Illustrated. 193 pages. Atlantic Monthly
Press. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
