<HEADER>
A5718 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-HISPANIC-NAT     10-13 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-HISPANIC-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        HISPANIC MAGAZINE ACCLAIMS ORTIZ
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Oct.13 -- Rep. Solomon Ortiz, D-Corpus Christi, was
named one of the top 100 ``most influential Hispanics'' of 1999 by
Hispanic Business Magazine, which celebrated the Spanish-speaking
community's impact in the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   The October issue of the magazine lauded the congressman for his
efforts to help increase Hispanic representation in the television,
movie and music businesses, and to address discrimination in that
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm grateful that they think I've been able to do my job
here,'' said Ortiz, now in his 18th year in the House.
</P>
<P>
   From his seat on the Congressional Hispanic Caucus, Ortiz led a
task force last month addressing the discriminatory portrayal of
Hispanics in the movie and on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we've wanted to do is see if the networks
can be more inclusive,'' he said, ``as far as allowing more
Hispanics to play roles, not only in front of the camera, but also
writers and producers.''
</P>
<P>
   The congressman said his Corpus Christi district has plenty of
Spanish-speaking talent, such as San Benito country singer and
actor Freddy Fender, entertainer Johnny Canales, and the father of
late pop singer Selena's, Abraham Quintanilla, who owns a recording
studio.
</P>
<P>
   However, the popularity of acts like these has yet to cross over
to the mainstream, Ortiz said. T.V. advertisers should recognize
their potential and tap into the Hispanic market, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the infrastructure [in Corpus Christi], in the music
or the movie industries, to launch young Hispanics who are capable
of being an actor, a producer, or a guy behind the camera,'' Ortiz
said. ``But it stays within the Hispanic community.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz said he believes the networks would benefit from a more
visible Spanish-speaking community on television because of the
size of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hispanic population is growing by leaps and bounds,'' he
said. ``It's important for the networks to understand that this is
a two-way street.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Ortiz has avoided using federal legislation to increase
Hispanic representation, preferring to get to know media
corporations, and introduce them to Hispanic talent from within and
outside of his district. Taking a ``friendly'' approach toward the
movie business is useful to help Hispanics make job contacts, the
congressman said. ``I hope there isn't a need to introduce any type
of legislation,'' he said. ``Many doors have been opened.''
</P>
<P>
   The congressman's office has collaborated with IMAGEN, a
Hollywood organization aimed at helping Hispanics get into the
movie industry. The group will organize a job fair in January, 2000
to bring Hispanics and entertainment execs together.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll conducted by the magazine, almost all of them agreed
portrayal of Hispanics on T.V. and in the movies was
``stereotypical.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
