<SLUG> BC-CIR-WORDS-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVORING WORDS, PLAIN AND FANCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)   (js) 
 By BONNIE ROTHMAN MORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a recent meeting broke up at Kaufman Patricof Enterprises in
New York, a company that designs Web sites and Internet
advertising, the five co-workers at the session discovered that in
addition to their corporate identification cards, they had another
thing in common. They are all fans of word-a-day Web sites and
e-mail newsletters for word-ophiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, they are entirely impractical, fun words,'' said
Jason Hackett, 28, an account director at the firm, in an e-mail
message. Hackett has been a word lover since high school. The
word-a-day e-mail message he gets from Merriam-Webster Online
(www.m-w.com) does not have much to do with his actual work, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Merriam-Webster offers the plain vanilla version of word-a-day
services. Entries include a definition, a sentence using the word
and a brief discussion of the word's origin.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxford English Dictionary posts a word-a-day feature at its
Web site (www.oed.com/wordofday.htm), but you have to seek it out _
it is not sent via e-mail. Each exhaustive entry is reprinted
directly from the 20-volume Oxford English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   Other word sites offer snippets of English filtered through the
perspectives of various Webmasters, who include at least two
professional lexicographers as well as hobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Anu Garg, who runs the Word a Day site
(www.wordsmith.org/awad &QC; /index.html), is a 32-year-old computer
scientist in Columbus, Ohio, who compares his love of discovering
new words to that of a philatelist finding a rare and beautiful
stamp. He said he had 235,000 subscribers to his word-a-day
service, which sends daily e-mail to subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hobby is words,'' said Garg, who moved to the United States
from India in 1991 and started A Word a Day in 1995 while he was a
graduate student at Case Western Reserve University. Every week
Garg chooses a theme and picks words around it. Recently the theme
was eponyms: Homeric, Molotov cocktail and John Hancock.
Pronunciations, recorded by Garg's wife, Stuti, can be downloaded.
</P>
<P>
   One attitude-infused site is called The Word Detective; the
Webmaster is Evan Morris, who writes a syndicated newspaper column
of the same name and says his site has 3,000 visitors each week
(www.word-detective.com). Morris, whose father, William Morris, was
editor in chief of the first edition of the American Heritage
Dictionary, writes jaunty essays to answer reader's queries. His
favorite work as a word sleuth is to delve into the origins of
phrases from childhood, like ``goody-two-shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris recently snooped for the origins of ``to tie one on,''
``armed to the teeth'' and ``gold-bricking.''
</P>
<P>
   For more academic words, there is the Random House Dictionary's
word-a-day site, written by Jesse Sheidlower, a senior editor
(www.randomhouse.com/jesse). A recent offering explaining the
origin of the word ``spark,'' as it refers to the act of courting,
was introduced by a hearty paragraph exhorting the reader to share
Sheidlower's enthusiasm for Joni Mitchell's pop classic ``Court and
Spark.'' (Yes, he is paid to do this.)
</P>
<P>
   Michael Quinion is a word hobbyist whose approach is similar to
Sheidlower's, though Joni Mitchell has not surfaced in his work.
Quinion runs World Wide Words &UR;  &LR; (www.quinion.com/words), a
commercial-free site where visitors can sign up for his free
newsletter. Quinion is a freelance word sleuth for the Oxford
English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   Quinion's enormous site has more than 100,000 visitors a month,
Quinion said, and he sends his newsletter to 6,000 subscribers each
week. A recent favorite entry of his was ``smouch,'' an
18th-century slang term for imitation tea made from the dried
leaves of trees like hawthorne and ash. Whether the beverage tastes
better with milk or lemon was left to the reader's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Like Morris, Quinion loves puzzling out the origin of phrases
like ``the whole nine yards.'' For the whole nine yards on the
subject, you can check
www.quinion.com/words/articles/nineyards.htm.
</P>
</TEXT>
