<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Growing Backlog For Laptop Computers?
</P>
<P>
   If you are dreaming of a laptop computer under the tree this
holiday season, it may be time to wake up and go shopping. The
recent earthquake in Taiwan, where many PC systems are assembled,
coupled with bad timing in the manufacturing cycles for critical
computer components like liquid crystal displays, means that demand
for popular laptops is outrunning supply, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laptop computers have been in short supply since spring, and
will continue to be in short supply until the middle of next
year,'' said Ross Young, president of Display Search, a flat-panel
display market research company in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to several laptop manufacturers this week revealed an
average delay of several weeks between order and expected delivery.
Depending on the model and its popularity, some laptops are
available immediately, while others are backlogged a week or more.
In general, the larger and sharper the screen, the longer the
delay.
</P>
<P>
   Young said he tried to order a popular Dell laptop recently and
was told the backlog was seven weeks. He shopped around for several
days, he said, before finding a store that had an IBM Thinkpad in
stock.
</P>
<P>
   A salesman taking orders at Dell Wednesday said the company is
encouraging customers to choose the XGA screen option for its
flagship Inspiron 7500 laptop model because those screens are more
readily available than higher-resolution SXGA screens.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen M. Baker, director of hardware analysis at PC Data in
Reston, Va., said that prices are rising for memory chips and other
components, which could affect other PC systems. Baker said that PC
manufacturers probably would not raise prices to consumers for the
holidays but that they might offer less computer for the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chances are they will reduce configurations instead,'' Baker
said. ``If they were planning on shipping a system with 128
megabytes of RAM, it may go out with 96 megabytes at the same
price.''
</P>
<P>
   By Peter H. Lewis
</P>
<P>
   IBM Offering Rainbow of Hues
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long time since IBM stopped requiring employees to
wear dark suits and white shirts, but it is still something of a
shock to see Big Blue producing computers in hues including Mars
Red Metallic, Terra Green Metallic, Eclipse Blue Metallic, Lunar
Gray Metallic, Sirius Red, Andromeda Green and Polaris Blue.
</P>
<P>
   But those are the actual color options for IBM's new Thinkpad
i-series 1400 portable computers, which were introduced this week.
The 1400-series portables come in a traditional IBM black case, but
they have snap-on covers in what IBM calls seven ``bright but
classy'' colors.
</P>
<P>
   The covers cost $29.95 each. One can imagine using the black
Thinkpad Monday through Thursday, and adding Mars Red or Polaris
Blue for dress-down Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   In another design innovation, the new Thinkpad 1460 and 1480
models ($2,199 to $2,399) also have an illuminated keyboard that
makes it easy to type in a dark meeting room or on an airplane at
night.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Peter H. Lewis
</P>
<P>
   A Hazard on the Road, A Hazard at the Pump
</P>
<P>
   By early next year, decals and signs declaring the potential
fire hazard of using a cell phone while pumping gas will be affixed
to gas pumps across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco was the first to issue the warnings, which instruct
people to turn off their cell phones while pumping. BP Amoco has
already placed the warnings on pumps throughout Britain and
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this year, 16,000 BP Amoco service stations in the
United States will have similar warnings. Exxon and Chevron also
plan to put warning labels on their pumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how remote the risk may be, we want to make
customers aware that they are putting themselves at some risk if
they are speaking on a cell phone, or operating a pager or any
other electronic device in the proximity of flammable liquids,''
said Howard Miller, a BP Amoco spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these devices, all consumer devices, rely on batteries
as a source of electrical power,'' said Miller. ``And in many
cases, they hold enough energy to create a spark which could ignite
a flammable liquid like gasoline.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Cellular Telecommunications Industry
Association, the trade association for the cellular industry, were
skeptical of the assertion. ``We have not found an incident
anywhere in the world that indicates that this has ever been a
problem,'' said Lisa Ihde, a spokeswoman for the association.
``We're not aware of any incident that would justify these
concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   What sparked the concern? Said Miller: ``It all started when a
story was widely circulated last May or June of some poor fellow in
Indonesia who was chatting on a cell phone and went up in flames.''
Miller said he had not seen confirmation of that incident.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Katie Hafner
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Getting on the Net Without a Computer
</P>
<P>
   Trying to get on the Internet without using a computer seems to
be the current Holy Grail. The latest device to join the parade is
the I-Opener from Netpliance.
</P>
<P>
   The I-Opener is a kind of portable Web TV. The unit does not
need to be attached to a television. It is portable so that it can
be easily moved to any room with power and a telephone jack. It has
a built-in 10-inch color LCD screen. And it comes with keyboard.
But it does not receive television signals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was to make getting on the Internet as simple as
possible,'' said Kent Savage, president and chief executive of
Netpliance, based in Austin, Texas, during last week's Internet
World trade show in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The I-Opener has joined the trend of providing a colorful array
of choices to match your decor _ Black, Silver, Blue, Green and
Yellow.
</P>
<P>
   There are three pricing plans: $199 to purchase with a two-year
commitment for Internet service at $19.95 per month, $299 with a
one-year commitment and $399 with unlimited email and some free
services _ news headlines, sports, and weather _ a $19.95 per month
charge for full Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Stephen C. Miller
</P>
<P>
   Handspring Developing Programs for the Visor
</P>
<P>
   The Visor, Handspring's new competitor to the Palm Pilot, will
depend on independently developed programs and devices, everything
from MP3 players to exercise monitors, that will fit in the Visor's
expansion slot, called the Springboard.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the modules will not be available until early next year.
However, several should be available during the holiday buying
season.
</P>
<P>
   Concept Kitchen has developed a series of city guides, CitySync,
based on the Lonely Planet series of travel guides. Up to four city
guides can be loaded on to the expansion module, which has 8
megabytes of memory.
</P>
<P>
   The guide will have all the text of the printed guides, but will
also be a searchable database. You can quickly find specific
information such as a good Thai restaurant in the Times Square area
or an inexpensive hotel in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Peanut Press, a publisher that has an extensive list of books
from major publishers that have been formatted for hand-held
devices, has also bundled books for the Springboard, which can hold
up to 40 books on a single module.
</P>
<P>
   Customers can also buy their own 8 MB flash memory modules
($79.95) from Handspring and create a custom library by copying
downloaded Peanut Press books onto the unit. Each book is priced at
a discount from the printed version and cheaper than the discounted
prices at online bookstores. And no shipping and handling fee (just
a personal computer).
</P>
<P>
   _ By Stephen C. Miller
</P>
<P>
   Internet Users Step Into the World of van Gogh
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever been so entranced by a painting that you wished
you could enter its world of light, color, texture and artistic
imagination? The Intel Corp., the giant computer chip maker, is
inviting Internet users to do just that _ virtually, at least.
</P>
<P>
   The company's free art gallery Web site (www.artmuseum.net)
allows users to ``enter'' two of van Gogh's most famous canvases:
``The Yellow House'' and ``The Bedroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Using three-dimensional, computer-generated environments that
are based on the paintings, viewers can look under van Gogh's bed,
or study the paintings on his walls or even walk across the street
from the house on Place Lamartine in Arles and see it as the artist
may have seen it (and imagined it) as he walked home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just some technology stunt,'' said Ralph Bond,
Intel's consumer education manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an educational point of view, it is very compelling,
especially for younger people.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Michel Marriott
</P>
