<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5738 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DICKINSON-REDUX-NYT &LR;      10-13 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DICKINSON-REDUX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: SIGHTS TRAINED YET AGAIN ON AMHERST'S ELUSIVE
BELLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (bl)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few American literary figures are as intensely loved as Emily
Dickinson (1830-1886). But few remain as elusive, which is the
reason waves of fresh interest in her life and work periodically
arise. One seems to be gathering strength now.
</P>
<P>
   A new edition of her complete poems has just been published for
the first time in nearly 40 years, throwing fresh light on her
working methods. A recent controversial selection of her
correspondence with her sister-in-law, Susan Huntington Dickinson,
suggests a potent erotic attraction between the two.
</P>
<P>
   And the poet came under further scrutiny last summer at a
meeting of the Emily Dickinson International Society at Mount
Holyoke College. Nearly 70 scholars presented research which
considered her work in the light of Daoism, Bengali poetry,
contemporary gay and lesbian studies and the domestic culture of
her time.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, this fall the Houghton Library of Harvard University
has put on view for the first time a substantial chunk of Dickinson
manuscripts in an exhibition titled ``Emily Dickinson: A Life in
Writing, 1830-1999'' (through Oct. 29). During the show, the public
also has access to a trove of personal effects usually kept under
lock and key: her tiny bedroom writing table and the chest of
drawers in which she stored her poems, once in the family home in
Amherst, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson was born in that house (which is now a museum) and
died there. She never married; she rarely traveled. Her days were,
on the surface, without incident. Yet, even in her lifetime,
legends began spinning around her.
</P>
<P>
   The writer Thomas Wentworth Higginson, to whom she had sent
poems, visited in 1870. He was mesmerized by ``the little plain
woman'' who entered the parlor ``with two daylilies which she put
in a sort of childlike way into my hand and said, `These are my
introduction' in a soft, frightened, breathless childlike voice.''
Dickinson was then 40.
</P>
<P>
   In 1881 a young Amherst College faculty wife named Mabel Loomis
Todd, new in town, became aware of ``a lady whom people call the
Myth. She has not been outside of her own house in 15 years. She
dresses wholly in white, and her mind is said to be perfectly
wonderful. She writes finely, but no one ever sees her.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did anyone see the extent of her literary output until after
her death, when her sister, Lavinia, discovered more than 800 poems
in the chest. Written on letter paper, undated, untitled and
unsigned, they had been sewn into 40 pamphletlike volumes.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson had instructed that her papers be destroyed, a common
stipulation in Victorian wills. Instead, Lavinia preserved the
booklets _ or fascicles, as they came to be called _ and engineered
the publication of a volume of poems in 1890. Intended as a modest
memorial, it was a huge popular hit.
</P>
<P>
   What, exactly, is Dickinson's appeal? In part it is her
fantastic language: the words with destabilized meanings, the
dissonant hymnbook cadences, the distinctive tone of voice:
defiant, witty, spiritually yearning but skeptical, emotionally
fervent but guarded.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is her personality, the primal, magnetic figure of
the American isolate. She knew her oddity and nurtured it. When
Higginson asked whether she didn't miss going out, seeing friends,
having a normal life, she answered, ``I never thought of conceiving
that I could ever have the slightest approach to such a want in all
future time.'' Then she added, ``I feel that I have not expressed
myself strongly enough.''
</P>
<P>
   She spurned publication (``The auction of the mind,'' she called
it). She turned being unknown into an elect state. She did without
the gratifications that most depend on. In exchange she was able to
give full attention to ideas _ death, divinity _ we barely know how
to think about. She lived a life  &UR; for  &LR;  us that we could never live
ourselves, which is what saints do. No wonder we hunger to know
her.
</P>
<P>
   We look for her in things she knew, like the personal effects at
Harvard. The writing desk, scarcely big enough to hold a lamp,
hints at her physical size. Books from her library _ Emily Bronte,
George Eliot, Shakespeare, the Bible _ reveal some literary
influences. A childhood portrait confirms a description she gave of
her hair as being ``bold, like the chestnut bur.''
</P>
<P>
   But her manuscripts, documenting the movement of her hand and
mind, prove surprisingly slippery. In past editions, her poems have
never been transcribed the same way twice. In fact, Dickinson has
always been to some extent a creation of her editors. This
problematic history is the subject of the Harvard show.
</P>
<P>
   Higginson and Todd prepared the posthumous 1890 book and labored
to make the poetry ``sensible.'' They added titles, normalized
spelling and punctuation and even rewrote poems. Later editors
reversed some of these decisions but made questionable new choices.
Martha Dickinson Bianchi, Lavinia's heir, brought out unpublished
poems in the 1920s and '30s. She left them untitled but, stumped by
the poet's handwriting, got words wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, Thomas H. Johnson issued his scholarly edition, dating
most of the poems and proposing a chronological order for the 40
fascicles. Although he had access to the Harvard material, the
other major group of manuscripts, now at Amherst College, was in
private hands. He was only able to see the group ``live'' on two
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   His monumental work has now been superseded in the variorum
edition by Ralph W. Franklin just issued by Harvard University
Press. Dates have been rethought and myriad textual details
reconsidered. But interpretations drawn from the results raise
still more questions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, while some scholars discern a conceptual logic in
the contents of the individual fascicles, Franklin concludes that
they are random compilations. Both views give potentially
important, though contradictory, readings of how Dickinson intended
her poems to be read.
</P>
<P>
   Editing can also shape a psychological profile, as in the case
of ``Open Me Carefully: Emily Dickinson's Intimate Letters to Susan
Huntington Dickinson,'' published by Paris Press in 1998. The
editors, Ellen Louise Hart and Martha Nell Smith, isolate the poems
and letters that Dickinson exchanged with her sister-in-law and in
them find evidence of both deep emotional ties and literary
collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of locating Dickinson in the manuscripts reverberated
at the Mount Holyoke conference. One historian proposed analyzing
the poet's changing handwriting to gauge her mental and physical
health and her emotional response to her correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   Another warned against turning the manuscripts into
all-answering fetish objects, diverting attention from other ways
of understanding Dickinson. Are the letters to Susan evidence of an
exceptional passion, or are they examplars of how women of a
certain class in a certain era communicated privately?
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to know. Dickinson filtered her life through her art,
which is one of indirection. ``The truth must dazzle gradually,''
she cautioned. So it does. That's why we endlessly recopy and
reread her words, why we revisit relics like those at Harvard, and
why, reversing the ordinary physics of fame, she seems to grow more
luminous the further she retreats in time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FREED-TV-REVIEW-2TAKE     10-13 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREED-TV-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALAN FREED: THE MAN WHO KNEW IT WASN'T ONLY ROCK 'N' ROLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Ask anyone under 30 about Alan Freed, and the
response is probably a blank stare. After all, the legendary disc
jockey died in obscurity and poverty in 1965 after a tumultuous
career in which he introduced ``rock 'n' roll'' to the world and
broke racial barriers.
</P>
<P>
   With his triumphs he also dealt with crushing setbacks and
crises as the center of the great payola scandal of the late 1950s
and a target of J. Edgar Hoover and the FBI, partly because
rock-and-roll seemed so threatening. His world fell apart. He died
at 43 of uremic poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, many young people today aren't aware of who he is
and what he had done,'' said Lindy DeKoven, executive vice
president for movies and mini-series at NBC. ``But the story of his
life _ what he did, the risks he took, the barriers he broke and
his downfall _ is remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour television drama, ``Mr. Rock 'n' Roll: The Alan
Freed Story,'' is to be broadcast on NBC on Sunday at 9 p.m. NBC
has found something of a niche with splashy musical dramas about
the '50s and '60s: in the last few years such shows as ``The
Temptations'' and ``The Sixties,'' have drawn large audiences,
including many teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   The new film, which stars Judd Nelson as the disc jockey, is an
adaptation by Matt Dorff of the 1991 book ``Big Beat Heat: Alan
Freed and the Early Years of Rock and Roll'' by John A. Jackson. It
was directed by Andy Wolk.
</P>
<P>
   The film includes appearances by '50s teen idols like Fabian and
Bobby Rydell (who play fathers outraged at the ``evils'' of
rock-and-roll) and abundant musical sequences that use the original
recordings of such performers as Little Richard, Jerry Lee Lewis,
Buddy Holly and the Crickets, the Moonglows, Jackie Wilson, Bo
Diddley, and Bill Haley and the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This obsession with youth culture we see now is a direct
legacy of Alan Freed,'' said Dorff. ``He believed that teen-agers
needed a culture of their own, and he gave them the kind of music
that they could claim as theirs and theirs alone. He was also
colorblind _ he loved the beat, he loved the people who made the
music, and the fact that they were black made no difference to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Freed _ whose real name was Aldon James Freed _ was a Cleveland
DJ playing mainstream music in 1951 when he eavesdropped on a group
of black and white teen-agers who were dancing to a new music that
made them want to ``jump.'' He played this new black music at
midnight nightly and it became a sensation. Freed soon went on the
air as Moondog at WJW in Cleveland. The next year, at the Moondog
Coronation Ball, considered the first rock concert, 20,000 fans
crashed the 10,000-seat capacity Cleveland Arena. The dance was
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   By 1954 Freed was hired by WINS in New York City, and his career
and fame took off even as he tangled with radio stations,
television networks and the music business over playing the
so-called black music.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really the one that brought black rhythm-and-blues into
mainstream American society, and he made a lot of enemies because
of that,'' said Jackson, a retired elementary school teacher in
Farmingdale, N.Y., who has written other books on rock. ``Here was
this white guy bringing blacks and whites together to dance in the
1950s. It was unheard of.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was also very emotional, outspoken, and said and did what
he felt without considering the consequences,'' said Jackson. ``He
had enemies within the music business establishment, which was
pushed aside by rock. And the FBI had a file on him because of the
power he commanded and because he was so close to black
performers.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the peak of Freed's career, in 1957, ABC gave him a
nationally televised rock 'n' roll show that was canceled after
Frankie Lymon, the black performer, danced with a white girl on the
show and enraged Southern affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   Personal demons shadowed Freed. He was a workaholic, he was a
womanizer, he couldn't hold his marriages (three) together, he was
volatile. He began drinking heavily. ``He ultimately fell because
so many people wanted to see him fall,'' said Jackson. ``He helped
his enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What finally brought down Freed was payola, the practice in
which disc jockeys routinely received cash from song pluggers to
play a record. Jackson noted that, at the time, only New York and
Pennsylvania had laws against payola. The system, he said, was
legal in other states as long as the proceeds were reported to the
IRS.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys lied,'' said Jackson. ``He stood up and told
Congress that everyone took payola. He said that what's payola to
you is the same as lobbying to me. He told Congress that. He didn't
know when to sit down and be quiet.'' In 1962, Freed pleaded guilty
to two counts of commercial bribery and was fined $300. His career
was over, and his personal life slid under the weight of
alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   Freed's career was marred by other practices as well. Like other
music industry insiders, he was accused of taking lucrative
songwriting credits for songs that were actually written by members
of the young groups he championed.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who wrote the Freed biography, said that two members of
the virtuoso group the Moonglows told him that Freed had no
involvement with their big hit ``Sincerely'' yet took a writing
credit for it and received the royalties.
</P>
<P>
   He was listed for years as co-writer with Chuck Berry of another
giant early rock hit, ``Maybelline.'' Berry went to court
eventually and succeeded in having Freed's name removed as
co-writer.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said, however, that unlike other disc jockeys, Freed was
a trained musician who was capable of writing songs and may have
actually done so over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Another expert on vintage rhythm and blues, Ronnie Italiano, the
owner of Clifton Music, in Clifton, N.J., and an expert on the
music, said he had considerable ambivalence about Freed.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, he said, Freed's huge concerts with black
rhythm-and-blues acts led record companies to realize the
potentially huge teen-age audience for those performers. Members of
the great harmony group the Flamingoes told him that they owed
Freed a debt, even though he took credit for some songs that they
wrote. ``Their feeling was, if it wasn't for Freed, they never
would have become popular,'' said Italiano.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, others, like the later Bobby Lester of the
Moonglows, bitterly resented him. Italiano said Lester was
shoveling coal in Chicago to pay his rent while the song
``Sincerely'' was No. 1 on the hit parade.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, the actor, said that after reading the Jackson book,
scouring Web sites and watching documentaries and videotapes about
Freed, he is convinced that what finally crushed Freed was not
payola but the racial breakthrough that the disc jockey almost
unintentionally led. ``He didn't see color, he saw music,'' said
Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other disc jockeys, Freed stuck with black singers and
groups whose songs were often ``covered'' by white acts. ``It was a
common occurrence in the '50s _ Little Richard had a song and then
Pat Boone would redo the song and the radio station would play the
white version,'' said Nelson. ``Alan Freed refused to do that. If
Chuck Berry made it first, he wouldn't play anyone else doing that
song. He made enemies because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Freed made additional enemies at the networks because he
refused to focus his shows on white acts playing before white
audiences as Dick Clark and other disc jockeys did.)
</P>
<P>
   At its inaugural ceremonies in 1986, he was inducted
posthumously into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame, which through no
accident was built in Cleveland. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
