<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5743 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-FLOOD-1014-COX     10-13 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FLOOD-1014-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DISASTER AID TO REMOTE MEXICAN VILLAGES, PEOPLE CUT OFF BY
MUDSLIDES AND CONTINUED RAINFALL
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of as locator map, Chiconcuautla is 15 miles
southeast of Huauchinango in Puebla state.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICONCUAUTLA, Mexico _ After days of torrential rains, the
mountains that gave them life brought them death.
</P>
<P>
   Loosened by water and with no trees left to anchor it, a giant
slab of hillside caved in on a village near this isolated hamlet in
southeastern Mexico last week, burying at least 10 alive in an
avalanche of mud. The poor peasant farmers of Acalama _ casualties
of one of the most disastrous storms in Mexico in a decade _ had
deforested the hills here so they could
</P>
<P>
   plant corn.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday survivors huddled in this neighboring village,
accessible only by helicopter or at least a day's walk from the
nearest city, Huauchinango, Puebla, about 90 miles northeast of
Mexico City. Shivering in the cold, they waited for shipments of
food, candles, batteries and
</P>
<P>
   blankets and word of when their loved ones' bodies might be
pulled from the earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband died trying to save his cousin,'' said a weeping
Maria Juana Campos, who rushed to meet a government helicopter that
landed here in Chiconcuautla. Pulling a dirty frayed red sweater
around her shoulders, Campos said five children were orphaned when
their parents died in the mudslide.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of tiny towns scattered in Puebla state's Sierra Madre
mountains remain cut off from civilization, stranded by swollen
rivers and mud-blocked gravel roads that snake around jagged peaks
here. After more than a week of storms in southeastern Mexico, at
least 329 are confirmed
</P>
<P>
   dead _ 237 in Puebla state _ and almost 300,000 are homeless
here and in the neighboring states of Veracruz, Tabasco and
Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the dead were victims of years of deforestation in these
rugged mountains. Others, including more than 100 people who died
Teziutlan _ a city in Puebla state _ died because their flimsy,
working-class homes were built on precarious urban hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   In Mixun, another village outside Huauchinango, at least 16
people perished, 12 of them children. The children and two teachers
were inside a schoolhouse last Wednesday when torrents of rain
cracked open the soft earth, swallowing the school and washing away
farmers' shacks.
</P>
<P>
   From a helicopter circling the region, Mexican Army troops were
seen picking through a mud-filled ravine that was once Mixun _ a
settlement of 19 wood-slat houses. The next largest town, where
survivors took shelter, is Pantepec, about 50 miles northeast of
Huauchinango and reached only by helicopter or a day's drive over a
battered road.
</P>
<P>
   ``People did not want to evacuate. The teachers said nothing
would happen. Then the earth sank,'' said a shell-shocked Juan Luis
Maria, whose 12-year-old daughter has not been found.
</P>
<P>
   ``The area is still very risky,'' said Army Lt. Col. Jose Ramon
Rojas, whose troops must scatter every time a helicopter passes
overhead. The land around Mixun is still very soft and walls of mud
begin to vibrate and threaten to cave in.
</P>
<P>
   Military helicopters and crafts belonging to Mexican Attorney
General's office are making regular flights to stranded villages
from Huauchinango and other sites throughout the state. From the
air, a bird's-eye view of the devastation reveals giant slabs of
mountainsides that have slid hundreds of feet into the Sierra
Madre's steep ravines. Most of the affected areas had been stripped
of the area's thick tropical vegetation and planted with corn and
other crops.
</P>
<P>
   Swollen waterfalls spill into canyons filled with mud and rocks.
Rivers have cut new paths, also dragging away farmland and homes.
Survivors huddle next to ravaged cornfields on peaks of mountains,
cooking over campfires and waving at helicopters, imploring them to
land and offer help.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main cause of these problems throughout the republic is
land erosion,'' said Jose Luis Flores, an assistant director of
emergencies for the Mexican government's Civil Protection Service.
He was flying over Puebla state's rain-soaked mountains, surveying
damage and emergency needs on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The government says it has reached most isolated townships by
now, but because roads are blocked, getting anything but basic food
supplies to people remains difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Amador Leal, who represents this area in Mexico's
Congress, also said the region has chronic problems with land
erosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional cultivation methods and crops grown here _
corn, chiles peppers and peanuts _ don't help us avoid erosion,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   University researchers, he said, have been trying to identify
vulnerable areas and have begun pilot programs to foster planting
of macadamia trees, blackberry shrubs and ornamental plants that
contribute less to erosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an economic and social problem,'' Amador Leal said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo has made daily trips
to hard-hit areas, his government has been under steady attack for
failing to act more quickly to help survivors. In Veracruz state
last week, he lost patience with a man interrupting his speech and
told him to ``shut up.'' When victims asked Zedillo to request
foreign aid, including American helicopters, he said ``No, we
Mexicans can do it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo later apologized to the man he scolded. And on Tuesday,
he softened his stance on foreign aid, inviting other countries to
contribute to the Mexican Red Cross. Mexico's Senate also issued a
statement inviting foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
