<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Oct. 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Windy and cooler weather will invade the Northeastern states
Thursday as strengthening low pressure quickly moves toward the
Canadian Maritime provinces. The day will begin with clouds near
the Northeast coast, which will rapidly yield to increasing
sunshine. Wind gusts of more than 30 miles per hour will be common,
especially in New England. Most of the region will have plenty of
afternoon sunshine, however, a few showers will linger in the
mountains of northern New England.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Southeast will be sunny and seasonably mild.
Tropical moisture from a large area of disturbed weather over the
Caribbean will stream toward southern Florida bringing clouds and
locally heavy showers.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Storm Irene which formed in the western Caribbean near
Grand Cayman Island on Wednesday is expected to strengthen as it
drifts north. The storm will threaten western Cuba and southern
Florida over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   A frontal system with limited moisture will move quickly across
the northern Plains toward the Great Lakes. Clouds and a few
showers will precede the front, especially near the northern Great
Lakes. Behind the front, breezy and cooler weather will spread into
the northern Rockies and Plains later Thursday and Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny and warm conditions will cover a large area from the
southern and central Plains to the Southwestern states. Meanwhile,
the Northwest will turn cooler, with a few showers along the
west-facing mountain slopes of the Bitterroots.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Garbage In &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The observation from College Station, Texas, reported a
nine-minute snow shower Tuesday despite temperatures in the 80s.
The obviously erroneous report was just one of countless bits of
the weather data that are transmitted around the world each day.
Sometimes, mistaken reports are not filtered from the matrix of
information that is used as the database for complex computer
weather prediction models. Some of the errors present at the
starting point of a computer weather forecast can grow in time
resulting in large errors when the prediction reaches many hours or
days in the future.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
