<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5751 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PRINE-MUSIC-REVIEW-NY     10-13 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINE-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRINE MAKES US LAUGH `IN SPITE OF OURSELVES' 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By PETER COOPER    
 The Spartanburg (S.C.) Herald-Journal    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Prine, ``In Spite of Ourselves,'' Oh Boy Records
</P>
<P>
   John Prine songs aren't the regular kind. They seem birthed not
from a Nashville home but from some other, quirkier place. ``You
come home late and you come home early/ You come on big when you're
feeling small/ You come home straight and you come home curly/
Sometimes you don't come home at all,'' he sang in ``Speed of the
Sound of Loneliness.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as with the finest work of Roger Miller, Prine's humor is
often merely a song's outer layer. Peel the onion and you end up
with a poignant study of a relationship's aftermath (``All the
Best''), or with an affecting vision of a convict's loneliness
(``Christmas in Prison'').
</P>
<P>
   That's a hard trick to perform in a commercial music world where
a line is drawn in the sand between novelty tunes and ``real''
songs. These days, it's either the yucksterism of Weird Al Yankevic
or the cringe-worthy earnestness of Celine Dion.
</P>
<P>
   And that's too bad. Throughout its recorded history, popular
music has woven humor into its mainstream tapestry.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Berry's ``School Days,'' Hank Williams' ``Why Don't You
Love Me Like You Used to Do,'' Phil Ochs' ``Here's to the State of
Mississippi'' and The Byrds' ``So You Wanna Be a Rock 'n' Roll
Star'' are a few of the many songs that sought to make serious
points through amusing lyrical structures.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, John Prine's music may exist in a vacuum, but it
was not born in one.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Spite ofves,'' Prine's just released disc of duets
with his favorite female vocalists, makes this point in spades.
Prine offers takes on such tongue-in-cheek country masterworks as
``(We're Not) The Jet Set,'' which was originally recorded by
George Jones and Tammy Wynette.
</P>
<P>
   Prine also offers an interpretation of Hank Williams' ``Dear
John (I Sent Your Saddle Home),'' and he and Iris DeMent had the
nerve to revive Jones' duet with Melba Montgomery on ``Let's Invite
Them Over,'' the only country hit to tackle a particular type of
swinging:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in love with each other/ We're in love with our best
friends/ So let's invite them over again.''
</P>
<P>
   The album's most intriguing song is the title track, Prine's
only songwriting contribution, which melds Prine's scratchy,
drawling vocals with DeMent's quivering, beautifully anachronistic
voice.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to the song, a husband and wife's evaluations of the
other partner's eccentricities, is like staying too late at a party
and hearing a drunken old couple tell stories on each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``She thinks all my jokes are corny/ Convict movies make her
horny,'' Prine sings. DeMent's retorts, several of them unprintable
in this newspaper, are a mixture of sarcasm, befuddlement and
abiding love as she stands by her fallible man with a touching lack
of judgment.
</P>
<P>
   DeMent, who appears on four songs, is one of nine singing
partners on the album. The others are the legendary and still
wondrous Connie Smith, blues-inflected alternative country singer
Lucinda Williams, hitmakers Patty Loveless and Trisha Yearwood,
angel-voiced Emmylou Harris, Irish alto Delores Keane, Prine's wife
Fiona, and Jones' former duet partner, Melba Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, things work out just fine. Loveless sings
wonderfully on ``Back Street Affair,'' and the acres of echo that
sometimes accompany her more polished studio recordings are excised
here in favor of crisp production from Prine and Jim Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   Harris is great on ``I Know One,'' Smith once again makes a case
for herself as one of the top vocalists in country history on ``So
Sad''(To Watch Good Love Go Bad), and the years since her 1960s
duets with Jones have torn none of the spunk from Montgomery's
voice.
</P>
<P>
   On the downside, Keane fits well on ``It's a Cheating
Situation'' but turns in a curious misreading of Kieran Kane's ``In
a Town This Size.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, Prine sounds rougher and more weathered than before
his recent, successful bout with neck cancer. At times he opts for
singing the melody an octave below his female counterpart rather
than taking a more pleasing harmony line.
</P>
<P>
   But those are small quibbles. Prine has a sly, endearing smile
in his voice that works as well when he sings others' songs as when
he performs his own material. He's not Enrico Caruso, but then
``Milwaukee Here I Come'' is not ``O Sole Mio.''
</P>
<P>
   Heck, I'll take a Prine concert over grand opera any day, and
I'll take ``In Spite of Ourselves'' over most CDs I've heard this
year. As usual, Prine has delivered something special.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Journal in Spartanburg, S.C., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
