<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5759 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-OTTAWA-U.S.-EMBASSY-2     10-13 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OTTAWA-U.S.-EMBASSY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW EMBASSY DESIGN REFLECTS A CAUTIOUS WORLD VIEW  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Cyprus, Jordan, Kuwait, Oman, Thailand, Colombia,
Chile, Venezuela, Peru, Bolivia, Kenya, Tanzania, Germany and El
Salvador.)  By JAMES BROOKE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ One side of the new American Embassy here engages the
town. A wall of warm limestone, generously perforated with windows,
stands across the street from old stone warehouses converted into a
market of upscale shops selling a, books and designer
fashions.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy's other, ceremonial side engages the crown. Sheathed
in tempered glass, it provides a smooth transition from the glass
house that is the National Art Gallery of Canada to the copper
turrets and neo-Gothic gargoyles of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   What is remarkable about this low-profile, steamship-shaped
embassy, inaugurated here last week by President Clinton, is that
it stands in the heart of a city. In a depressing era of truck
bombs and embassies hiding behind high walls in suburban compounds,
the glassy new mission building makes a powerful statement for an
endangered species: the urban American Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being downtown is a wonderful gesture of American openness,''
David M. Childs, the lead architect, said of the embassy, which
cost $40 million to build and opens for business within the next
few weeks. An advocate of cities, Childs, of Skidmore, Owings &AMP;
Merrill, is leading the redesigns of Columbus Circle and
Pennsylvania Station in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, the fate of the embassy, like blueprints for
American embassies the world over, was pushed and pulled by issues
of security. As the United States enters the 21st century as the
only superpower, embassy design has moved from the monumental to
the hunkered down. The design seems to reflect a cautious,
defensive world view that sees the mission of American diplomats as
one of managing resentment.
</P>
<P>
   No one seriously questioned the need for a new American Embassy
in Canada, the largest trading partner of the United States. Sixty
people now work crowded in the old embassy, a neo-Renaissance
structure built in 1932 for a staff of 12. About another 200
American and Canadian employees are scattered around Ottawa,
occupying space under 12 separate commercial leases. The new
embassy will concentrate all the employees under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   Canada had reserved for the United States the last vacant lot on
Parliament Hill, a lot prominent on Sussex Drive, the ceremonial
parade route between Parliament and the prime minister's residence.
In symbolic symmetry, the United States set aside for Canada the
last open lot on Washington's ceremonial thoroughfare, Pennsylvania
Avenue. A decade ago, when Canadian diplomats settled into their
privileged position, the ambassador moved into an office with a
rare and magnificent bay-window view of the United States Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   American diplomats fully intended to occupy a similar position
of honor. The design that emerged and endured is low key _ actually
lower than surrounding buildings and smaller than the Canadian
Embassy in Washington. On Pennsylvania Avenue, the Canadian
Embassy's sharp stone angles, giant aluminum columns and monumental
courtyard speak of a small nation clamoring for attention. In
Ottawa, the reserved U.S. Embassy building, with its modest central
tower, speaks of a nation that knows it accounts for 85 percent of
Canada's foreign trade. The building embodies the calculated
restraint of a dominant nation that sees no gain in throwing its
architectural weight around.
</P>
<P>
   The sober building's one external folie, Joel Shapiro's bronze
building-block sculpture dedicated by Hillary Rodham Clinton, was
greeted two weeks ago by The Ottawa Sun newspaper as ``glaringly
and gratingly American.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, early in the design saga here, the first truck bomb
reverberated through American diplomacy with an explosion at the
U.S. Embassy in Beirut, Lebanon, that killed 63. In 1985, a
commission headed by Bobby Ray Inman, the retired admiral and
former deputy director of the Central Intelligence Agency,
stipulated that new embassies should be set back 100 feet from
public streets and that windows were to be limited to 15 percent of
exterior wall space.
</P>
<P>
   Under these guidelines, the State Department ruled in 1988 that
the downtown site in Ottawa was unsafe. But for the next five
years, there was a lull in major bomb attacks worldwide. In January
1993, after envoys rejected suburban sites, the State Department
decided to waive security standards for Ottawa, allowing 30-foot
setbacks. Ottawa, like New York, was deemed a low security threat.
</P>
<P>
   The next month, a van exploded under the World Trade Center,
killing 6 people and wounding 1,000. That year, the first of the
bunker embassies opened, in Nicosia, Cyprus. Others followed, often
on suburban sites in third world countries: Jordan, Kuwait, Oman,
Thailand, Colombia, Chile, Venezuela, Peru, Bolivia and El
Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   Childs labored quietly against the grain, trying to design an
urban embassy for Ottawa that would not look like the outward
manifestation of a paranoid nation. On April 19, 1995, he briefed
Ottawa's National Capital Commission, which oversaw the
construction of the embassy. A few hours later, he received the
news of the devastating bombing of the Federal Building in Oklahoma
City.
</P>
<P>
   Going back to the design boards, he moved an external corridor
system into the building's core, creating an atrium that now runs
the length of the building, injecting light and a sense of
community into the four floors of offices. In 1997, workers broke
ground on the building. In 1998, truck bombs destroyed two American
embassies in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be in the city and not be a fortress _ that is the real
problem,'' Childs said, talking of the security constraints that
hung over his work.
</P>
<P>
   He has labored to create the illusion of American accessibility
and participation in the urban setting. When the diplomats move in
and the lights go on, passers-by on either side of the building
will be able to see Americans working at their desks, or trotting
up and down glass-enclosed stairwells in the prow and stern of the
boat-shaped building. What they may not know is that that the glass
is three inches thick, bulletproof and bomb resistant.
</P>
<P>
   People strolling past the monumental buildings in Major's Hill
Park, near Parliament, may marvel at the sparkling glass face that
the embassy presents to MacKenzie Avenue, part of the capital
parade route. What they may not know is that this tinted glass
``wall'' has the effect of a 21st century trompe l'oeil _ just
behind it is a concrete wall reinforced with steel and punctuated
with small windows that meet security guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to embassy receptions or passport offices will find
that a security guard is there to push open the doors, leaden
affairs that would fill the bill in a maximum-security prison. Few
visitors will know that the structure is designed to prevent
collapse from horizontal stresses after an earthquake or bomb
blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no security concerns whatsoever,'' Gordon D. Giffin,
the U.S. ambassador here, announced at a news conference last week.
``In Ottawa, it was critical to be part of the vibrant activity
downtown.'' But walking through the building with members of the
press, he refused to allow photographs of the maple wood walls,
citing State Department security rules.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   The opening of this downtown embassy, long advocated by Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., bolsters a school of thought that
says that in some capitals, the combination of risk levels,
prestige and working convenience comes out in favor of the United
States' flying the flag downtown. Although Serbian demonstrators
threw paint bombs at the American Consulate in Toronto last spring,
there is no history of embassy bombings in Ottawa, a well-ordered
city of 1 million people. A month after the end of the Kosovo
bombing, 4,000 Canadians and Americans flocked to a huge Fourth of
July picnic here organized by the American ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   In Singapore, a low-terrorism city-state where real estate
prices are at a premium, the State Department has reduced the
setback guidelines for the newly opened American Embassy from 100
feet to 50 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is trickier in Berlin, where work has stalled on a
new $120 million embassy. Americans and Germans want the United
States to build it near the Reichstag on the prewar embassy site,
at the end of Unter den Linden, with a view of the Brandenburg
Gate. Local zoning laws, drawn up to restore the historical
elegance to the boulevard, require that buildings go close to
sidewalks and have an ample amount of windows on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic problem is the security standards, which require the
embassies to have a 100-foot setback behind a wall,'' said John
Ruble, the principal design architect, whose firm, Moore Ruble
Yudell, is working on the Berlin Embassy in conjunction with Gruen
Associates. ``Of course, in a historic town center that is not that
easy to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Planners have discussed burying streets or moving them into a
park, steps that would violate the historic esthetics of this grand
area. Ruble said of the impasse, ``Imagine trying to move Fifth
Avenue into Central Park to create a setback for a building.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, advocates of a downtown embassy in Berlin were
prevailing. For the work of diplomats, it would be hard to beat the
prestige and efficiency of an embassy located a five-minute walk
from Germany's Parliament and major government buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ready to go in the fall of last year, but in August
those bombings happened, and the whole thing was put on hold,''
Ruble said, recalling the destruction of the American embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   In Ottawa, while American diplomats may feel secure in their new
steel and glass cocoon, their new neighbors are debating their
security. In the African bombings, most of the injuries were to
passers-by and neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred yards to the north stands the National Gallery, an
art greenhouse composed of 5,307 panes of glass. Gallery officials
have decided to forgo covering the windows with a costly coating
that would minimize splintering.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Douglas Kirkland of the Ottawa-Carleton Police Department
thinks that that may be an unwise decision. With a coating, he
said, ``you are not going to have a million shards of glass from
each ones of these panes of glass being driven through people.''
</P>
<P>
   On the east side, merchants in the old stone warehouses of
Byward Market are torn between nervousness over security risks and
the welcome arrival of some 300 embassy employees, their wallets
filled with strong green dollars. For the moment, no one is
investing in coatings on their shop windows. But with the streets
fronting the embassy turned into no-standing zones, shop owners
plan to attend a seminar by Kirkland next month on identifying and
reporting suspicious vehicles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
