<HEADER>
A5762 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-AGE-DISCRIMINAT     10-13 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-AGE-DISCRIMINATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT QUESTIONS FEDERAL AGE-BIAS SUITS AGAINST STATE EMPLOYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court appeared ready Wednesday to deny
state workers who believe they are victims of age discrimination
the right to sue their employers under a federal anti-bias law.
</P>
<P>
   In three cases from Alabama and Florida, the high court, which
in recent years has voted repeatedly to limit Congress' power over
states, heard arguments on whether the state employers have
immunity under the 11th Amendment against the Age Discrimination in
Employment Act (ADEA) of 1967.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment, among other things, bars residents of a state
from suing that state in a federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in the three
cases that states and state agencies have 11th Amendment immunity
from lawsuits under ADEA. Relying on a 1996 Supreme Court decision,
the appeals court said a federal law can override state immunity
only when Congress specifically says that immunity doesn't apply
and when Congress is attempting to stop an unconstitutional
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the arguments, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor noted:
``This statute does not mention the 11th Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy added that in considering the 1967
law Congress never addressed the issue of states' immunity.
``Congress did not have the debate we are having here,'' he said
``It didn't come close to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last eight years, O'Connor and Kennedy have cast key
swing votes in a number of states' rights cases that have curtailed
the power of Congress. In two of those cases, those justices,
joined by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Antonin
Scalia and Clarence Thomas, rejected the idea that Congress can
give the federal government authority over states on issues such as
gun-free school zones and gambling on Indian reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Representing groups of state employees in Florida and Alabama,
Jeremiah A. Collins, a Washington, D.C. attorney, told the court
that Congress did intend to extend the age discrimination law to
the states. ``Congress unequivocally authorized these lawsuits,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Scalia asked whether Congress had the right to ban
discrimination of older workers, who are not protected under the
Constitution. ``Congress just went out on its own and defined a
prejudice that no court had previously pointed out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist quickly asked rhetorically: ``Can Congress deal with a
supposed problem by creating a new constitutional law?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration lawyer Barbara Underwood also urged the
justices to overturn the appeals court ruling and allow state
employers to be sued under the federal law.
</P>
<P>
   But when O'Connor asked why the state employees ``couldn't just
sue their employer in state court since both Florida and Alabama
have their own anti-discrimination laws,'' Underwood acknowledged
that the employees did have that option.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Sutton, a Columbus, Ohio, lawyer representing the state
employers, agreed with O'Connor, arguing that ``instead of
permitting age discrimination, states have overprotected this
group, and there is no need for the federal government's help.''
</P>
<P>
   All 50 states have age discrimination laws.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three cases involved university faculty members and
librarians. In one case, 36 current and former faculty members and
librarians at Florida State University and Florida International
University sued the Florida Board of Regents in federal court,
contending that age bias was the reason they lost out on certain
salary increases given to younger faculty members.
</P>
<P>
   The claims stemmed from a 1991 collective bargaining agreement
that required the state to give annual raises to state university
faculty members. The size of the faculty members' raises was based
on how long they had been with the university.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1993, FSU and FIU refused to give an annual raise to
their faculties, citing a lack of funds. In suing the two
universities, the 36 plaintiffs said that because their raises
would have been larger than those of younger members, the loss of
income would have ``a disproportionate impact'' on them.
</P>
<P>
   In the other Florida case, a Panama City prison guard named
Wellington Dickson sued the state Department of Corrections, saying
he had lost a promotion partly because of age discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   In the Alabama case, two associate professors at the state-run
University of Montevallo in Montevallo, Ala., alleged that they had
been denied promotions to full professor, appointments to committee
assignments, higher salaries and sabbatical leaves because of their
age. They also argued that the university maintained a salary and
evaluation system that worked against older faculty members.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who submitting friend-of-the-court briefs supporting
federal court access for such claims are the American Association
of Retired Persons, the American Association of University
Professors and the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees.
</P>
<P>
   Among those urging the justices to rule out such federal court
access are 23 states _ Connecticut, Delaware, Georgia, Hawaii,
Idaho, Kansas, Louisiana, Maine, Michigan, Mississippi, Montana,
Nebraska, Nevada, New Jersey, Ohio, Oklahoma, Oregon, Pennsylvania,
Rhode Island, Tennessee, Utah, Vermont and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
