<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5768 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX     10-13 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NISSAN USED TO BE DATSUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ When and why did Datsun change its name to Nissan? _
T.E., Euless, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ In 1982, the Nissan Motor Corp. dropped the Datsun name
used in the United States on small pickups, sports cars and sedans
in favor of Nissan, which was being used in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Datsun, a name formed from the initials of company founders, was
used in Japan until the '30s. The change to Nissan was not
well-received by U.S. dealers, costing millions in sign replacement
and lowering the company's name recognition as much as 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took five years for Nissan to get the same level of name
recognition as Datsun,'' Nissan marketing executive Tom Orbe told
``Ward's Auto World'' in 1996. ``From the consumer's point of view,
Datsun went away and Nissan was a new company.''
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ Several years ago, President Zachary Taylor's body was
exhumed because of an author who believed he might have been
murdered. Was the book about this ever written? _ K.B., Ashby,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ No Taylor book appears to have been written by Clara
Rising, the novelist and historian whose research prompted Taylor's
1991 exhumation to look for signs of arsenic poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving permission from some of Taylor's descendants,
Rising sent her research to the coroner of Jefferson County, Ky.,
who approved the exhumation. A medical examiner concluded that
Taylor died of natural causes.
</P>
<P>
   Rising, author of the Civil War novel ``In the Season of the
Wild Rose,'' was doing research on Taylor for a planned book.
Taylor, the 12th president, died on July 9, 1850, after eating iced
cherries and milk during a holiday celebration. Doctors at the time
attributed his death to gastroenteritis.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ Who is the lady with the big glasses in the Old Navy
commercials? _ A.S., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ She's Carrie Donovan, 71, a former fashion writer for
``The New York Times Magazine,'' ``Vogue'' and ``Harper's Bazaar''
who has been wearing those oversize glasses since the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan, who retired from the magazine in 1994, was doing print
ads for Old Navy in 1997 when she joked that she would be ``awfully
good on TV,'' according to ``Entertainment Weekly.''
</P>
<P>
   She soon was hired for a series of commercials with Magic the
dog, Morgan Fairchild, Rob Sporrer and others, wearing a copy of
her glasses with non-reflective lenses.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
