<HEADER>
A5772 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-CANCER-LINKS-TEX     10-13 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-LINKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCH LINKS BREAST, OVARIAN CANCER RISKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women with breast cancer _ especially minority women who have
breast cancer before age 50 _ are much more likely to develop
ovarian cancer than the general female population, research data
show.
</P>
<P>
   Early-breast-cancer survivors have been known to be at higher
risk for second breast cancers and cancers of the digestive tract,
but research on the link between breast and ovarian cancer has only
recently been pursued.
</P>
<P>
   The link is not surprising, because the two cancers share risk
factors, including a higher risk among women who have their first
period earlier and reach menopause later in life, those who have no
children and those who have a family history of breast or ovarian
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   What is surprising is the finding that although Asian and
Hispanic women have a lower risk of breast cancer overall, Asian
women with early breast cancer have a threefold risk of developing
ovarian cancer, and Hispanic women have a fourfold risk, says Dr.
Wendy Brewster, clinical instructor in gynecological oncology at
the University of California at Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   White women, who have the lowest risk of breast cancer, have a
1.79-fold risk of developing ovarian cancer if their breast cancer
is diagnosed before the age of 50, and African-American women have
a twofold risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was very interesting and expected was the highest risk
for ovarian cancer was among those women who were diagnosed with
breast cancer before 50 years, and they had a threefold risk,
overall,'' Brewster says.
</P>
<P>
   She headed a multicenter study looking at 120,000 breast-cancer
patients. She reported initial results at last month's meeting of
the Ovarian Cancer National Alliance in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The study does not distinguish between primary and metastatic
ovarian cancer and does not take genetics or family history into
account, Brewster says.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 120,000 breast-cancer subjects, 16,000 had an additional
malignancy, most commonly in the digestive track or second breast;
however, 478 developed ovarian cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Brewster says the new data point up the fact that minority women
who have had breast cancer should be considered a high-risk group
for ovarian cancer and might well benefit from screening to detect
the development of ovarian cancer early.
</P>
<P>
   Her research is aimed at developing new ways to estimate cancer
risks in particular population bases.
</P>
<P>
   She says she has no definitive answer as to why minority women
with early breast cancer are at increased risk for ovarian cancer,
but identification of high-risks groups becomes more important as
tests are developed for different kinds of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Ovarian cancer is the fifth most common cancer among women and
causes more deaths than any other cancer of the female reproductive
system.
</P>
<P>
   Promising drugs have been developed in recent years, but the
overall five-year survival rate is still only 40 percent to 45
percent. As with most cancers, survival is directly related to the
stage at which it is diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   A nETWORK OF YOUNG SURVIVORS
</P>
<P>
   LaShawn Woodward was only 14 when she developed ovarian cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Leakage from her tumor made her stomach swell, and her doctor
first suspected that she was pregnant. She knew that couldn't be.
</P>
<P>
   Her doctor diagnosed the problem as gastritis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor told me to go home and take Tums,'' recalls
Woodward, now 22.
</P>
<P>
   When neither Tums nor Mylanta brought any relief, the tumor was
discovered and surgically removed, along with her left ovary.
Follow-up radiation damaged the right ovary, and she went through
menopause at 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some young survivors, women who have survived this
disease for many years. I've met women that were 5 (when ovarian
cancer was diagnosed) that survived, that were 10, 14, 15, 16,
17,''says Woodward, founder of Young Survivors of Ovarian Cancer.
She lives in Mitchellville, Md., near Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel ovarian cancer is mainly discussed among older women.
The public, the media, doctors don't really think of younger women
who have survived ovarian cancer or will,'' says Woodward. ``Being
young, African-American, no previous family history of breast
cancer, no ovarian cancer _ I was the only one in my family _ no
one suspected ovarian cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodward spoke at the Ovarian Cancer National Alliance's media
briefing, preceding last month's national advocacy conference in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, she started the support group to help survivors
under the age of 30, especially those experiencing the emotional
and physical changes associated with early menopause.
</P>
<P>
   They talk about things like peer relationships and intimacy and
plans to have kids and hormonal therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Menopause itself can be difficult to handle when you are so
young. Your emotions go up and down, and you don't know which way
is happy, which sad,'' says Woodward, who is a student at Prince
George's Community College. She also works full time as a librarian
and volunteers with the organization she heads. ``You tend to lose
friends. My peers couldn't understand why I don't menstruate. You
tell them you have cancer and they say, `Oh, God, you have what?'
They just don't know how to handle you.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW BLOOD TEST AIMS AT EARLY DETECTION
</P>
<P>
   A promising new blood test that uses a small fat molecule to
identify early-stage ovarian cancer is very near testing in women
at risk for ovarian tumors.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers hope to begin clinical trials on the tumor marker by
the end of this year, says Dr. Gordon Mills, chairman of the
molecular oncology department at M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Mills presented data on the new blood test at last month's
annual meeting of the Ovarian Cancer National Alliance in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The blood test can also be used to monitor patients and help
determine which ovarian tumors are growing quickly, when they
become invasive, when they begin to metastasize, and when they are
not responding to drugs available to treat them, Mills said at a
briefing for medical and science writers preceding the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very exciting time in cancer research. We are
beginning to understand the genetic changes involved in the cancer
process,'' Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   Because cellular ``markers'' identify the different changes,
they can be used to alert doctors that a cancer is developing, to
monitor the disease process and to determine which drugs are most
effective in treating the cancer at various stages of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   In Mills' study of 265 ovarian cancer samples, the new Atairgin
blood test detected 75 percent of early-stage cancer samples with
95 percent accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   The test measures a specific fat molecule in the blood that is
exceedingly high during the development of ovarian tumors and may
therefore provide an early means to detect ovarian cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Early detection is critical because the five-year survival rate
for women with ovarian cancer rises to 95 percent in patients with
early-stage disease. However, with no screening test available,
most ovarian cancer is not detected until later stages, when the
survival rate averages only 28 percent. Overall survival rate is
now 40 percent to 45 percent, according to reports presented at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors also reported that at least eight new drugs are being
developed to fight ovarian cancer, including several that are
already in use against other kinds of cancer, and confirmed earlier
reports that long-term use of the birth control pill cuts the risk
of ovarian cancer in half.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
