<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Having trouble finding it? We did.
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But due to the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It, Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com (please
include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone number);
or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have several copper pans that need to be re-tinned. Do you
know of any place where I can have this done?
</P>
<P>
   _W. P. Smith, Stone Mountain (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   A: We found a ``tin'' man for you in New York: Jamie Gibbons,
owner of Retinning and Copper Repair, 525 W. 26th St., New York, NY
10001 (212-244-4896). For more than 80 years, this waterfront
workshop has been rejuvenating copper cookware. In the early days,
according to Gibbons, steamships would come into port and the cooks
on board would bring their pots and pans via horse and buggy to the
shop. Today, people from all over the country send their wares via
FedEx and express mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Copper cookware is favored by chefs everywhere,'' says
Gibbons. ``It heats evenly, cools quickly and lasts forever.''
However, copper must be lined with tin, to protect the food, and
tin wears out. The cost of re-tinning is $3 an inch. You measure a
pan from the rim, down the side, across the bottom and back up the
other side of the pan. Measure oval and rectangle pans lengthwise.
For example, a 10- to 13-quart mixing bowl is $30, a 20-quart bowl
is $40. Allow three to six weeks for re-tinning an item. You can
read about the company on its Web site, www.retinning.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am experiencing serious withdrawal symptoms from the lack
of Ice Cube chocolate candy _ little squares of milk chocolate
wrapped in a metallic silver-and-blue wrapper. I found them only
once in Atlanta. Will you please help me find a steady supply of
this chocolate candy?
</P>
<P>
   _Michele Bowman, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Another sweet request: I would like to know if Junket Rennet
Custard is available anywhere. It's been a long time since I've
seen any Junket products, which could be used in making homemade
ice cream, cheese, etc.
</P>
<P>
   _Mrs. E.G. Cox, Marietta(Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   And another Junket request: If you could find Junket for me, it
would make a semi-old man so happy. It was a dessert my mother made
for me and my wife made for our son. It was a little like pudding
but much lighter.
</P>
<P>
   _Jerrold Siegal, Roswell(Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   A: Sweets for the sweet. Both of these items, Ice Cube candy and
Junket dessert mixes, are available through Hometown Favorites.
This Florida-based mail-order company specializes in hard-to-find
food, candy and condiments. It has over 400 items on its shelves.
The Ice Cube chocolates are 35 cents apiece. Junket comes as a
custard mix in vanilla, chocolate, strawberry and raspberry; as a
Danish dessert in raspberry or strawberry; and as an ice cream mix
in vanilla, chocolate and strawberry. Each box is $1.25. To order:
1-888-694-2656. Minimum order is $15. Or access the Web site at
www.hometownfavorites.com.
</P>
<P>
   Junket fans can also order their dessert favorites directly from
Redco Foods: 1-800-556-6674.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for ``dulce de leche,'' a marvelous sweet spread
from Argentina that tastes somewhat like a caramel-flavored
sweetened condensed milk. So far, I've located it via the Internet
at several stores in New York, but surely there must be a local
store that carries it.
</P>
<P>
   _Kay Wolfe, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: You're right. Taqueria el Molina carries La Lechera, a
sweetened condensed milk, at its two locations: 3976 Buford Highway
N.E. (404-982-0994) and 2000-A Cheshire Bridge Road N.E.
(404-636-8714). It's $1.89 for a 12-ounce can. Made in Mexico by
Nestle, the milk can be used to make flan or as a spread on bread
for a snack.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you please find Unguentine Plus, an antiseptic cream
made by the Mentholatum Co.? The tube I have was purchased in West
Allis, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   _D.D. Loftin, Rome (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   A: This cream has been a favorite of Dr. Moms for years, as a
first aid for burns, cuts and insect bites. It also prevents
infection and temporarily relieves itching, according to the
manufacturer. A 1-ounce tube is $4.49 at Miller's Rexall, 87 Broad
St. N.W. (404-523-8481). Sandy Springs Pharmacy, 6329 Roswell Road
N.E. (404-252-8165) carries the 1-ounce tube for $3.69. Or you can
order Unguentine Plus from the company at 1-800-688-9046 for $3.70
plus shipping.
</P>
<P>
   _ Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
