<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDWIG-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEEDY AS `HEDWIG': TAKING ON THE GLAM ROCK DIVA (AND GENDER GAP) 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Skedded earlier as HEDWIG-SHEEDY.) 
(th) 
 By PETER MARKS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Deep into the run of an established hit it's time to
take chances, and with the casting of Ally Sheedy in the title
role, ``Hedwig and the Angry Inch'' took a huge one.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sheedy, who has matured in recent years into an intelligent
actress of offbeat charisma _ catch her brooding lesbian
photographer on video in the indie film ``High Art'' _ is to say
the least an unlikely choice for Hedwig, and only partly because
the role of the drag queen in progress, mutilated on an East Berlin
operating table, was written for a man.
</P>
<P>
   Hedwig is also a would-be rock star, in other words, a drag
queen with a set of pipes. And on this fundamental basis Ms.
Sheedy's portrayal lacks the requisite dynamism. She has the will
to play Hedwig, but musically speaking, has not found a compelling
way.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent performance she had pitch and other vocal problems
on a half-dozen songs in Stephen Trask's demanding score; after her
voice took a pummeling in the powerhouse title song ``Angry Inch,''
she had little left for the soulful and softer ``Wig in a Box'' and
``Wicked Little Town,'' two of the 10 numbers she must put over in
the course of an evening in which Hedwig also talks to us virtually
nonstop.
</P>
<P>
   It has become acceptable these days for name actors with merely
passable voices to assume key singing roles in big musicals: both
Natasha Richardson and Jennifer Jason Leigh were cast, for
instance, as Sally Bowles in ``Cabaret.'' One could argue they add
color and emotional dimension in their renditions, but it is
inarguable that in the absence of technique and a natural ease with
music, something vital is lost as well.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sheedy was the choice of John Cameron Mitchell, who
conceived and wrote the book for the show and originated the role
of Hedwig, in which he was spectacular. He has said he saw in Ms.
Sheedy, who had burned out after an early success in Hollywood, a
reflection of his vision of Hedwig, a show-biz survivor who grows
weary of the facade he has chosen and ultimately reinvents himself
before our eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which mocks the conventions of rock stardom, takes us
through Hedwig's downwardly spiraling career and life, from his
botched sex-change operation, to his performances as a drag star in
Midwestern dives, to his sordid entanglement with Tommy Gnosis, the
rock icon Hedwig discovered and tutored on a Kansas Army base.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage at the Jane Street Theater, though, Ms. Sheedy, whose
movie career is once again thriving, seems altogether too
tentative. You can admire the gutsiness of the attempt, but you can
also sense a lack of belief.
</P>
<P>
   Drag is a comic art. Its spirit is in its outrageousness,
attested to in Hedwig's garish get-ups, and its practitioners revel
in the form's ridiculously exaggerated notion of the boundary
between genders. When a man plays a woman, you're always, but
always, aware of something out of kilter under the tresses.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Hedwig,'' Ms. Sheedy is as unambiguously a woman as
Mitchell was a man. In the abstract the idea of this gender
substitution might be playful.
</P>
<P>
   The inescapable reality, however, is that this is a musical
about sexual ambiguity, and when that idea is subverted so
consciously, the show proves a lot less thrilling. The
double-entendres and the myriad jokes at Hedwig's expense simply
don't make as much sense. Even Ms. Sheedy's German accent is
unconvincing.
</P>
<P>
   It is painful to have to report such disappointing results,
especially when they involve a show so inventively theatrical and
an actress so willing to put herself on the line. Sometimes, the
matchmaker can't make a match.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `Hedwig and the Angry Inch'
</P>
<P>
   Book by John Cameron Mitchell; music and lyrics by Stephen
Trask; directed by Peter Askin; sets and projection design by James
Youmans; costumes by Fabio Toblini; lighting by Kevin Adams; sound
by Werner F, musical staging by Jerry Mitchell; hair and makeup by
Mike Potter; production stage manager, Jason Eagan; general
manager, Brent Peek; associate producers, Terry Byrne and Eric
Osbun. Presented by Alice's Enterprises, Samjack and J.B.F
Producing Corp. At the Jane Street Theater, 113 Jane St.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Ally Sheedy, Maggie Moore, Jeremy Chatzky, Joe Pecorino,
Jon Weber and Chris Weilding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
