<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5797 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r b BC-PERABO-REVIEW-TEX     10-13 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERABO-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WOMAN'S VOICE, SOMETIMES CLEAR AND CHARMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY GOLDIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Who I Was Supposed to Be: Stories''
</P>
<P>
   by Susan Perabo
</P>
<P>
   Short fiction
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster, $20
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't deserve this life,'' a mother says, lamenting the role
she's been forced into by her daughter's desultory love life. That
sentiment _ what could have been, what should have been, what yet
might be _ resonates in much of ``Who I Was Supposed to Be:
Stories,'' a quirky and engaging collection by Susan Perabo.
</P>
<P>
   There are well-drawn portraits here of men and women longing to
relive the past or trying to invigorate their humdrum lives.
</P>
<P>
   The stories' real strength, however, is their twists, many of
which catch the reader completely off-guard _ a retired shop owner
who turns to a new kind of business, a divorced man who finds an
unusual way of spending time with his ex-wife, an unhappy woman who
visits her hometown and unexpectedly benefits from her mother's
addiction to lottery tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Perabo displays great range in tone and voice, and she tackles a
variety of subjects, ridiculous and serious. Throughout, Perabo
maintains a light touch. An often ironic humor suffuses each tale,
either in the main focus or in the details.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Perabo approaches the same basic theme from
opposite directions. The absurdity of ``Explaining Death to the
Dog,'' for example, in which the narrator tries to do just that, is
balanced by the devastation of the child who narrates ``Gravity,''
which opens with, ``It rained the morning of the day we killed
Dennis Zeller.'' Both stories examine the aftermath of death, but
in strikingly different ways.
</P>
<P>
   More lighthearted is the aptly titled ``Thick as Thieves,'' a
largely typical narrative of a rich-but-aging man with a faltering
Hollywood career and a failing marriage. He has ``only one
worthwhile story to tell,'' about his father, whom he never knew
well, having left home as a teen-ager. His father comes for a
visit, and the two men get to know each other. Into this tired
scenario Perabo injects an oddity that lifts the tale well clear of
cliche.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the collection comes the only tale with a
fantastic setting and characters, although it's still cast in a
realistic style. ``Retirement'' is told in the third person, from
the perspective of Alfred, butler to Bruce Wayne, aka Batman. The
opening sentence, ``Alfred was out of Pepto-Bismol,'' is the first
clue to how funny and earthy this well-paced story is.
</P>
<P>
   Even the stories that strike false notes are worth reading for
their quirks, sometimes even their settings. In ``The Rocks Over
Kyburz,'' for example, a father who longs for simpler days finds
that his sons are growing up faster than he thought. It's
well-executed up to a point _ the point, long before the final
page, at which the reader guesses what's going on even while the
father exhibits a naivete that's hard to believe.
</P>
<P>
   The ending of ``Measure of Devotion'' also disappoints, but
because it's too pat. The story does gain, however, from its
background action, a tour of the battlefields at Gettysburg.
</P>
<P>
   Even where Perabo achieves her overall aim, smaller problems mar
the effort. ``Counting the Ways,'' for example, is certainly
bizarre enough to hold the reader's interest, using a dress once
owned by Princess Diana to reveal the fault lines in a married
couple's relationship.
</P>
<P>
   However, some of the symbolism is heavy-handed, the psychology
murky (''The magic of the dress had finally worn off, and she had
tunneled back to that place inside her, the place with no name and
no address and no closing time.'') In a first-person narrative,
instances of the second person (''You're probably thinking I kissed
it or something, but I didn't.'') come out of nowhere and quickly
vanish, their purpose, if any, unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Those flaws don't significantly detract from the overall quality
of the stories, however, and the result is amusing and thoughtful
fare.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
