<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5800 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-HURRICANE-RELIEF14-CO     10-13 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-RELIEF14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BLACK CAUCUS RALLIES SUPPORT FOR CAROLINA FLOOD VICTIMS
 &HT;    380&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rallying behind Rep. Eva Clayton, D-N.C., black
lawmakers launched an effort Wednesday to develop a ``Marshall
Plan'' to rebuild flood-ravaged eastern North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy includes reaching out to both parties in Congress,
churches and non-profit groups, private companies and Hollywood
entertainers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take several years and a lot of money,'' Clayton said
at a Capitol Hill press conference. ``Emergency housing is needed,
home repair and replacement is a priority, essential property has
been lost, many are out of jobs. ... Hopelessness is setting in.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., who is co-chairing a task force on
emergency aid for hurricane victims, said the crisis requires
something similar to the Marshall Plan, which provided extensive
aid for post-war reconstruction of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``America has always shown compassion whenever devastation has
hit throughout the world _ especially in Eastern Europe and the
Middle East,'' he said. ``Now we have been struck at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangel said the Congressional Black Caucus is working on several
fronts to help those devastated by flooding. Some members are
assigned to reach out to colleagues in Congress in an effort to
pass emergency aid measures.
</P>
<P>
   One such effort consists of $2.5 billion in emergency aid
included in a larger spending bill. That amount is for hurricane
victims in several states, including North Carolina. The House may
vote on the measure as soon as next week.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Rangel said the Caucus is arranging for members of
Congress to visit hurricane-damaged areas so they can witness the
impact first-hand and bring messages of hope to residents.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the plan involves reaching out to corporations,
such as the Fannie Mae Foundation, which Rangel praised for
contributing $175,000 to non-profit groups working to provide
permanent replacement housing for families who lost their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Caucus members said they will also call on Hollywood to raise
awareness and contribute money to rebuilding efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Maxine Waters, D-N.C., said she would contact members of
the entertainment community, including producer Quincy Jones,
Motown founder Barry Gordy Jr. and actor Denzel Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not called on them much in the past, but now is the
time that we need them,'' she said. ``We've got to help each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   At the press conference, movie actor Bill Duke, whose face is
much more familiar than his name, spoke of the historical
importance of Eastern North Carolina, including Princeville, the
oldest town in the country incorporated by freed slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Businesses have been wiped out there, churches, homes and
people are really, really suffering,'' he said. ``I call on all
Americans, particularly my affluent friends in Los Angeles _
producers, actors, writers _to support this effort one thousand
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Princeville, in Edgecombe County, was submerged in 23 feet of
water for 10 days after Hurricane Floyd. Almost all of the town's
650 homes, 30 businesses and three churches were damaged or
destroyed. The situation is aggravated by the fact that about half
of the residents are senior citizens, who may be too weary and too
poor to start over.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton said that the Caucus wants to help all those hurt by the
floods, including but not limited to disadvantaged communities,
senior citizens and minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not exclusive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the press conference, Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee chairman, said his party will
fully support relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Black Caucus year in and year out has stood behind the
rest of us when we've asked for help on a variety of things, and
the entire Democratic Caucus wants to be involved in this
project,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
