<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5816 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-AFLCIO14-COX     10-13 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFLCIO14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFL-CIO GETS TRADE CONCESSIONS IN EXCHANGE FOR GORE ENDORSEMENT
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The nation's largest union organization threw the
electoral weight of its 13-million membership behind Vice President
Al Gore's presidential campaign Wednesday following days of
backroom political horse-trading on future trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, seeking a crucial victory in what campaign aides
characterized as ``the first primary'' in the Democratic
presidential contest with former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, won
over wavering affiliates of the AFL-CIO by reiterating his pledge
to insist on enforceable labor and environmental rights in future
trade negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade should lift up living standards around the world, not
drag them down in the United States,'' Gore said in a speech to the
700 delegates to the AFL-CIO convention as he celebrated the
endorsement from their 68-union federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe our president needs the authority to reach new trade
agreements and open new markets to our goods and services,'' he
added. ``But as president, I will also insist on and use the
authority to enforce worker rights, human rights and environmental
protections in those agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the labor leaders, Gore sought to paper over trade
differences by touting the economic gains under the Clinton
administration and by promising to veto any ``anti-union bill''
that would come to him as president.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a Reagan-Bush recession. There was a Bush-Quayle
recession, but there's never been a Clinton-Gore recession because
we've been following policies that are good for working families,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   But greater flexibility in trade negotiations is what the more
recalcitrant leaders within the labor federation had hoped for
before extending an endorsement that is pivotal in the vice
president's effort to retool his campaign for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   And that is what they sought in their private meetings with Gore
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president is prepared to be flexible in his search
for a solution to the problems being created by unrestrained
trade,'' George Becker, president of the United Steelworkers of
America, said after the endorsement on a voice vote of the
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Becker had been one of the most vocal critics of the Clinton
administration's free-trade policies, blaming them for some of the
massive loss of U.S. manufacturing jobs over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   But Becker said ``frank and straightforward'' talks with the
vice president convinced him that ``Gore understands the cost in
human terms of unrestrained free trade'' and is committed to
``approach trade so that conditions for workers throughout the
world are leveled up, instead of down.''
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, the vice president's spokesman, confirmed that
Gore has promised to make labor and environmental rights a part of
all trade talks.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's commitments on trade failed, however, to win over the
International Brotherhood of Teamsters or the United Auto Workers,
two of the largest affiliates of the 68-union AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   It also failed to sway some of the rank-and-file union members
who spoke briefly during the floor debate on the endorsement
resolution, which called Gore a ``champion of unions.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Vincent, a Teamsters member from Kentucky, cautioned the
AFL-CIO against endorsing any candidate until it has thoroughly
reviewed their records and commitments. ``Don't wrap that pig;
weigh it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters and the Auto Workers are seeking further
concessions from Gore, particularly as the administration prepares
for upcoming talks in Seattle about possibly expanding the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor opposes any expansion of WTO that would result
in a flood of cheap imports that would put Americans out of work.
Labor also wants tougher environmental protection provisions in
trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope when the vice president leaves here today that he will
take with him our concerns about the future,'' Teamsters President
James P. Hoffa said during the brief floor debate on the resolution
to endorse Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AFL-CIO will endorse today and next month we will go to
Seattle to protest against any possible expansion of the World
Trade Organization,'' Hoffa said. ``Is the vice president going to
listen? We hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hoffa sought to minimize any differences between
himself and AFL-CIO President John Sweeney, Teamsters spokesman
Chip Roth confirmed that Hoffa is seeking a meeting with Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, the Republican presidential front-runner, to
discuss trade issues.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, like Gore and Bradley, is a free-trader. Consquently,
Gore, in his speech to the convention Wednesday, focused on
differences with the governor, most notably, Bush's opposition to a
federally mandated increase in the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Bush would allow states to opt out of any minimum
wage passed by the federal government, Gore said, ``I guess that's
Governor Bush's idea of compassionate conservatism _ states get to
choose one or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Union labors have been furious with the Clinton administration
ever since the president and vice president pushed to pass the
North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA). But throughout the
three-day convention here, they have downplayed their differences
with the administration over trade.
</P>
<P>
   Even the one-page resolution endorsing Gore over Bradley made no
mention of their differences over trade. Instead, it praised Gore
for using the power of his office ``to defend the freedom of
workers to choose a union.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution acknowledged that Bradley ``has the respect of
many and a good record,'' but added that ``there is no question
that Al Gore is the presidential candidate most favored, or that
members support an endorsement of him at this time by an
overwhelming margin.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, who engineered the Gore endorsement, said it was
important to back Gore now rather than later in order to wield as
much influence as possible in a compressed primary season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our leadership recognized that we must move quickly in order
to be full participants in what has become a front-loaded primary
process,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO will not meet again until next spring, and it is
likely that either Gore or Bradley will have nailed down the
nomination by mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement Wednesday will provide Gore with muscle and
money in the primary states, most importantly in Iowa, which will
hold the first presidential voting next January, and in New York,
where Bradley is in a virtual tie with the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   There are 150,000 active and retired AFL-CIO members in Iowa,
and some 400,000 in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement is less of an advantage in New Hampshire, which
will hold the first presidential primary. Only about 27,000
households in New Hampshire have union members.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   But Lehane, Gore's press secretary, said the battle with Bradley
over the AFL-CIO's backing was ``the first primary - and we won.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gore flew from Los Angeles to Seattle to meet with
machinist union members who work on the F-22 fighter jet, which is
threatened by budget cuts. About 1,000 people are employed in
Nashua, N.H., to make parts for the F-22.
</P>
<P>
   .
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
