<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-PRIVACY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT QUESTIONS CALIFORNIA PRIVACY LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Weighing how far a state can go to protect the
privacy of its residents, several members of the Supreme Court on
Wednesday questioned whether a California law that limits access to
individuals' arrest records goes too far.
</P>
<P>
   The statute, which has not been implemented because of a court
challenge, would prevent state law enforcement agencies from
releasing the arrest records to businesses that use them for
pre-employment background checks and other commercial purposes.
</P>
<P>
   However, the law would allow the release of the records when the
information is used for a ``scholarly, journalistic, political or
governmental purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   The law, which would have gone into effect in June 1996, was
challenged by United Reporting Publishing Corporation, a Los
Angeles-based company that compiled and sold the arrest records to
attorneys, insurance companies, alcohol and drug counselors and
other businesses. The company argued that the law violated its
First Amendment right to free speech.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1996, a U.S. District Court judge agreed, blocking the
law from going into effect. The Los Angeles Police Department
appealed the ruling, but in 1998, the U.S. 9th Circuit Court of
Appeals decided against the California law, saying that it violated
United Reporting's commercial free-speech rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's decision, expected by June, could provide
guidance for lower courts on how to deal with the growing number of
companies known as ``look-up'' services that take advantage of
computer technology to gather and sell public records to lawyers
and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Alan F. Westin, a Columbia University political science
professor and publisher of a newsletter called Privacy &AMP; American
Business, said ``look-up'' businesses have proliferated in the last
few years as employers, prompted by concerns ranging from workplace
violence to embezzlement, dig ever deeper into the personal
histories of job applicants.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent survey of 500 large companies, the American
Management Association found that 42 percent check whether job
candidates have criminal convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Representing United Reporting Publishing Corp., Bruce Ennis, a
Washington, D.C. attorney, told the high court that the California
law violated his client's free-speech rights because it made the
same information available to journalists, private investigators
and others but not to United Reporting.
</P>
<P>
   He added that by releasing the records to the press, the law did
nothing to protect the privacy of individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having one's name, crime, and address printed in the local
paper is a far greater affront to privacy than receiving a letter
from an attorney, substance-abuse counselor, or driving school,''
Ennis said.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas Goldstein, a Washington, D.C. lawyer representing the
Los Angeles Police Department, said the statute was needed to
prevent improper use of the arrest records.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country's desire for the free flow of information has
been hijacked by people who only want to use the information to
make money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Representing the Clinton administration, Justice Department
lawyer Edward DuMont argued that the arrest records should not
become a ``commodity that can be bought and sold.''
</P>
<P>
   But several justices appeared unconvinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information is a commodity for the New York Times and every
other newspaper,'' Justice David Souter said. ``I don't see how
this company's use of the records is any different from a newspaper
writing a story about a person who runs a red light and gets
pinched by the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia said: ``Just because newspapers sell a
greater variety of information than this company doesn't mean
they're in a different business.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
