<HEADER>
A5819 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEB-CLASS-NOTES-NYTR &LR;      10-13 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-CLASS-NOTES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFESSORS GIVE LOW SCORE TO WEB SITE'S CLASS NOTES  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALISSON CLARK   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ University of Florida professor Jonathan
Reiskind has used the Internet to post his lecture notes for years,
so the availability of free online course notes doesn't bother him.
What does bother him about StudentU.com's new notes service is the
potential for misinformation.
</P>
<P>
   StudentU's Web site, www. studentu.com, offers free notes for
classes at 60 major universities, including 57 courses at the
University of Florida ranging from business finance to theater
appreciation. Reiskind said StudentU's notes for his Integrated
Principles of Biology course are less than perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a variety of misspellings in here of things that
are actual questions on the exam,'' he said. ``The notes are not up
to date _ they seem to be quite behind the time. This won't do
anyone much good.''
</P>
<P>
   The notes are posted by students, most of whom are enrolled in
the classes, who earn $300 a semester. StudentU founder Oran Wolf
said the only qualification necessary to be a notetaker is signing
up for a class that's not already covered on the site. For the
first few weeks, Wolf's seven quality-control readers scan the
notes, but without attending the classes themselves, they can't
guarantee that the notes are accurate or complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make sure they enter the notes on time and that they look
complete, but we don't know the actual content,'' Wolf said. ``We
can look and see pages of beautiful notes, but for all we know,
it's only 50 percent of the lecture.''
</P>
<P>
   To deal with the problem, Wolf has started a rating system that
allows students to score the notes _ five stars for ``outstanding''
to half a star for ``flush 'em.'' If students are unreliable or
take shoddy notes, Wolf gives them a pep talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like firing people,'' he said. ``I'll talk to them
about the quality of the notes or give them a few notetaking
techniques, then give them another week and see if the quality
improves.''
</P>
<P>
   While he's concerned about accuracy, Wolf said StudentU's notes
are not intended as a substitute for attending lectures.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a student, I would recommend going to class on your own and
using our notes as a supplement,'' he said. ``You can't go in and
just read the notes and think you're going to get a good background
in organic chemistry. Students are smarter than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reiskind's experience supports Wolf's theory. He said that in
the three years he has posted notes online, attendance hasn't
changed. ``I've thought about not posting the notes, but I don't
think that will make them come to class more regularly,'' Reiskind
said.
</P>
<P>
   History professor Geoffrey Giles, whose History of the Holocaust
lectures are summarized at StudentU.com, said the threat posed by
StudentU's notes goes beyond attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the important lessons we teach is how to distill
information,'' he said. ``That's precisely the information that
they're going to need in careers later on. I think it does a real
disservice to our students that they should be able to get notes
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Giles shares Reiskind's concerns about inaccuracy. Take this
passage from the anonymous notetaker's summary of Giles' lecture on
the Krakow Ghetto, with spelling and grammatical errors intact:
</P>
<P>
   ``A family of five was living in an 8ft by 10 Ft with one
kitchen and one bathroon. A great deal of smuggling took place in
the ghettos. It was used to find food (kids came in and out). It
was also dangerous and people did try to go in and out even though
they were not allowed ... The Nazis were fooled by the physical
apperance of the Jews. If the Nazi's suspected that you were
missing, the results were devestated for the family. Part of the
family could be tortured or held hostage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm absolutely appalled,'' Giles said. ``It's absolutely
wretched. It's written by someone who is virtually illiterate and
who's obviously going to have trouble passing the class.''
</P>
<P>
   Giles fears the garbled notes will have an impact on some
students' performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger here is that undergraduates have the tendency to
assume that if something's on the printed page, it's true,'' he
said. ``Having these notes on the Internet like this, especially
having it for free, lends a kind of authority to it that it doesn't
deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf's solution? ``I have a lot of professors who send me their
notes directly,'' he said. ``That way they know they're accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   No thanks, said Giles. ``My whole stand on this is that it's
inappropriate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Graduate teaching assistant Kristen Conway posts her notes for
World Geography on the department's Web site. But, like Reiskind,
she leaves out some information that students can only get in
class. Even if the StudentU notes include the omitted information,
students who don't attend class miss key slides, photos and maps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that students won't come to class if they think
they can just wait and do this when it's convenient for them,'' she
said. ``It's nice if it is used as a supplement, but I think
students have too much of a tendency to use it as more than that.
This is not a distance-learning class.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
