 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, Oct. 14,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TREATY _ WASHINGTON _ The nuclear test ban treaty is headed for
a Senate defeat late Wednesday unless President Clinton and his
Democratic allies can craft an agreement to postpone the vote.
(Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   w/TREATY-IMPACT _ WASHINGTON _ Will U.S. rejection of the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty make the world a more dangerous
place? The answer depends on how you view the world. In the debate
leading up to the vote, some senators argued that past treaties had
reduced the nuclear threat from the Soviet Union and its allies,
while others claim that the CTBT and similar arms pacts are
worthless, or may actually put Americans in greater peril. (Deans,
Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-HEARINGS _ Preview of the House Commerce committee
subcommittee hearing into the Atlanta Olympic bid process. Bily
Payne and Andy Young are scheduled to speak about Atlanta's
lobbying excesses and the Olympic bid process in general. (Turner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   UPTON-PROFILE _ A profile of the man heading up the
congressional investigation of the Atlanta Olympics, Rep. Fred
Upton. (Carr, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-AGE _ WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court heard arguments
Wednesday in a Florida case on the issue of whether Congress can
make a law allowing people claiming age discrimination to sue
employers in federal courts as well as state courts. (Lipman, Cox
News Service). 12.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-RELIEF _ WASHINGTON _ Members of the Congressional
Black Caucus hold a news conference to discuss initiatives designed
to address the damage caused by hurricanes Dennis and Floyd in
eastern North Carolina. (Moscoso, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-PESTICIDES _ WASHINGTON _Jesse Rifkin was 8 when his
grade school was sprayed with pesticides while he and other
children were present. Five years later, he tells what it felt like
as his whole body got red hot and itchy, his throat swelled and he
went into anaphylactic shock. Jesse and others, like the National
PTA, are supporters of a national crusade being launched Wednesday
by Sens. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., and Patty Murray, D-Wash., for
a law to require federal safety standard sfor the use of ``toxic
pesticides in and around public schools.'' (Mollison, Cox News
Service). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-SMOKING _ WASHINGTON _ The main federal law restricting the
sale of tobacco to minors is not working, the Substance Abuse
Policy Research Program reported Wednesday. (Hill, Cox News
Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RAMSEY _ BOULDER, Colo. _ Awaiting developments from the grand
jury investigating the death of JonBenet Ramsey. (Schneider,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   KKK-TERRORISTS _ CHARLESTON _ The city council has declared the
Ku Klux Klan a terrorist group and condemned other hate groups as
well in a resolution approved after an emotional debate. Mark
Potok, a spokesman for the Southern Poverty Law Center in
Montgomery, Ala., said this may be the first municipality to
designate the Klan a terrorist group. The resolution only expresses
the opinion of council and doesn't create law, city attorneys said.
If the Klan wants to march, they may apply for a permit. Sponsor
Wendell Gilliard had said when he first proposed the resolution
that he wanted to prevent the Klan from holding rallies in the
city. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-LOTTERY _ Does the rejection of a lottery in Alabama give
pause to gambling proponents in South Carolina, North Carolina and
Tennessee? (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-GROUPHOME _ TROTWOOD, Ohio _ Margaret Gerkin has been an
outspoken advocate for the mentally ill since her son was diagnosed
with paranoid schizophrenia 13 years ago. Now she's taking her
activism to another level: She and her husband, Jim, have ``hocked
everything we own'' to purchase an 1860s farmhouse on 40 acres, and
plan to use it for a special kind of group home for the severely
mentally ill and handicapped. (Beyerlin, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-FLOOD _ XICOCAUTLA, Mexico _ As the crow flies, some
villages are just a ridge or two away from this city in Mexico's
southeastern Sierra Madre Mountains. But after a week of killer
rains they might as well as be a million miles from civilization.
Mexico has been overwhelmed by this disaster, and rescuers still
cannot reach isolated hamlets stranded by mudslides and swollen
rivers. When aid does arrive in some rural areas it sometimes
consists of things that are not really needed, angry officials
complained at a meeting here Tuesday night. Even in a city like
this one _ difficult to reach because of mudslides _ poor people
who were evacuated from their homes feel forgotten. (Ferriss,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   AIDWORKER _ Before the NATO bombing campaign and just after
CARE's Bob MacPherson was in Kosovo. This week he returned from
duty that was equally dicey: a stint in both East Timor and West
Timor. With the shooting of UGA grad in Pristina and attack on two
other workers in Burundi, we talk to MacPherson about the
increasing danger to humanitarian aid workers. (Graham, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-RUGBY _ LIMERICK, Ireland _ The U.S. rugby team has been
the punching bag in the World Cup, the third most popular televised
sporting event on Earth behind the Olympics and World Cup of
soccer. The team is readying for their final likely inglorious
match Thursday and we spend a day with them. Focusing on team
captain Dan Lyle, who was a football star at Atlanta's Woodward
Academy. (Roughton, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO _ LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore is expected to
address the annual convention of the AFL-CIO labor confederation
after winning its endorsement for the Democratic presidential
nomination. (Shepard, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
