<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF RELIGIOUS BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   ``When Christ Comes''
</P>
<P>
   By Max Lucado
</P>
<P>
   Word, $21.99
</P>
<P>
   About the only rapture in ``When Christ Comes'' is in Max
Lucado's voice.
</P>
<P>
   That is, unlike a lot of those writing about the end of the
world, Lucado isn't discussing theories about the Antichrist, the
millennium or the idea that believers will be snatched away _ aka
the Rapture _ before (or maybe during) the great tribulation. He is
discussing why Christians should not be indulging discomfort,
denial, disappointment or panic when it comes to the Second Coming.
</P>
<P>
   Lucado sees Judgment Day as a time of reunion, rejuvenation and
rewards for believers. But for many people, it will be a day of
tragic reckoning: ``Can we scissor (hell) out of our Bibles? Only
at the expense of a just God and a reliable Bible. Hell is a very
real part of the economy of heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Christ Comes'' is a sweet-tempered and relatively short
study of a topic whose darker and more complex side sometimes seems
to dominate the discussion. ``Could you use some comforting words
regarding the return of Christ?'' Lucado asks. The San Antonio
author does provide some.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   ``The Slow Way Back''
</P>
<P>
   By Judy Goldman
</P>
<P>
   William Morrow &AMP; Co., $24
</P>
<P>
   This novel is not about faith, but rather ethnicity and
identity. A Southern Jewish woman, uncomfortable with her religious
heritage, seems happily married to a non-Jew. But her psyche rages
with nagging issues. Why doesn't she embrace the legacy of her
forefathers? Why is she impatient rather than passionate toward
Judaism? Why is she exasperated when people allude to Jewish
practices, assuming her familiarity rather than her indifference?
Why does she suffer the same headaches, emanating from the right
side of her face, as her mother did? The discovery of eight
handwritten letters, scrawled a generation earlier in
hard-to-decipher Yiddish, leads to clues that help piece together a
troubled family history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Slow Way Back'' is a compelling novel interlaced with
Southern idioms and Yiddish rhythms. The writer, a National Public
Radio commentator in Charlotte, N.C., tells a story of Jewish
immigration and assimilation into the life of the South. She
borrows from life to enhance her art. The protagonist is a radio
commentator, a psychologist akin to Dr. Laura, a glib expert who
analyzes listeners' problems in split seconds. Simultaneously, the
radio star ponders her own dilemmas, unresolved issues that have
lingered from generation to generation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Hollace Weiner
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
