u a BC-CIR-VIRTUAL-FACE-LIFT     10-13 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VIRTUAL-FACE-LIFT-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRAMS THAT CAN REDECORATE YOUR COMPUTER SCREEN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE HUTSKO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Look into the reflection on your darkened computer monitor _ the
face staring back could be lifted, tweaked, tightened, uncreased or
flat-out overhauled, with the help (and high cost) of cosmetic
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Flick on the monitor, and what you're facing, your computer's
user interface, can also be nipped and tucked with a virtual face
lift. Find those plain gray windows tiresome? Then paint on a coat
of rusted metal. Envy that futuristic (albeit make-believe) Web
browser in the movie thriller ``The Net''? Now you can download
something like it, complete with shiny 3-D edges and voice
feedback.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike real cosmetic surgery, these changes, minor or major, run
little risk of permanent damage and can be undone with the click of
the mouse. Performing an interface face lift on your own computer
is a virtually painless procedure and, unlike real surgery, costs
little or no money.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the user interface enhancement programs _ available for
both Mac and Windows computers _ are referred to as ``themes'' and
``skins'' (or ``skinz''). Themes change the appearance of your
entire desktop, from the icons and the cursor to the wallpaper and
screen saver.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these custom file sets can be found already loaded on
your computer; others can be downloaded from the Web as trial
versions, which let you try out a pretty new interface before
paying a low shareware fee for the complete, registered version.
Skins are a more limited form of customization. They often dress up
a single program, like an MP3 player or a browser.
</P>
<P>
   Themes and skins are contributed by artistic computer users and
designers. Many of the contributors earn reputations on the various
themes and skins sites, building a sort of cult following with
downloading counts that run into many thousands.
</P>
<P>
   But before putting your computer under the virtual knife, it's a
good idea to get acquainted with the interface makeup kit built
into your computer. Beginning with Macintosh OS 8.5, Apple tucked a
program called Appearance Manager into the Control Panels folder.
With it, you can easily get a new look _ from sleek platinum to the
spring's-in-the-air golden poppy, with an orange flower in full
desktop bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Besides changing the desktop background and highlight colors
(which appear when selecting text or icons), users may also choose
different fonts, font sizes and sound effects. While sound effects
may seem annoying at first, they become familiar and welcome,
providing a subtle audible feedback when clicking or dragging
icons, pressing the Web browser's Back button, opening and closing
windows and opening programs. Anyone who ever doubted the firmness
of a double-click on a program, only to do it again and run the
program a second time, will appreciate sound effect feedback.
</P>
<P>
   On the PC front, Microsoft's Windows 95 and 98 offer various
``scheme'' selections in the Control Panel under Display
Properties. Choices include predefined, color-coordinated schemes
that transform the usual plain-gray appearance to colorful
combinations with names like eggplant, slate and lilac. Windows 98
also includes a glitzy program called Themes, also hidden away in
the Control Panel.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond colors and fonts, Themes changes the desktop wallpaper
and icons, screen saver and sounds. The Baseball theme, for
instance, pastes onto the desktop a batter with a catcher and an
umpire at the ready, changes the My Computer icon to a home plate
and the Recycle Bin to an arena (a pennant indicates that there is
trash to be emptied) and replaces the boring old hourglass ``wait''
cursor with a baseball bat that ticks off the seconds with animated
swings.
</P>
<P>
   Other themes include Travel, with a vintage train station on the
desktop; Jungle, complete with drum and animal sound effects, and a
theme celebrating the work of Leonardo da Vinci.
</P>
<P>
   A boatload of themes celebrating such cult favorites as ``The
X-Files,'' Pokemon and the Dallas Cowboys are available for
downloading at various Web sites, including Winfiles.com
(www.winfiles.com) from CNet, Dream Theme
(www.mountvalley.com/dreamtheme) and Tucows Free Themes
(freethemes.eunet.fi). The sites organize themes by categories like
Animals, Cartoons, Movies, Nature and Sports. Microsoft's Windows
Update Web site also offers Windows 98 Themes
(windowsupdate.microsoft.com).
</P>
<P>
   While Mac and PC Control Panel programs change the overall look
of the desktop, they do not modify the windows' underlying
architecture: familiar details like where a window's title and
close box appear, and how the scrollbar looks. Changing those
aspects calls for a separate interface-enhancement program that
burrows a bit deeper beneath the window's top-layer skin, modifying
the way window frames are drawn on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Mac users appear to have the advantage when it comes to options
for better-looking windows. The top tool for tweaking the Mac user
interface is Kaleidoscope, a shareware program that can be
downloaded and used for a trial period; it costs $25 to register
(www.kaleidoscope.net).
</P>
<P>
   The site features hundreds of downloadable themes, including the
sparkling, gilded String of Stars and the distressed-metal,
post-industrial Boilerplate. There is also the remarkably
tactile-looking Notepaper, which turns the Mac desktop into an
architect's worktable, right down to papery, torn-edge windows and
superbly pencil-smudged lettering for icons and window titles. The
site also features seasonal themes for holidays like Valentine's
Day and Christmas, holly berries and all.
</P>
<P>
   Another choice for Mac users is DSG Themes, free for downloading
from the DS Group (www.dsgroupinc.com). The company is also working
on a Windows version.
</P>
<P>
   A popular Windows interface enhancement program is
Window-blinds, by Stardock (www.stardock.com). This shareware
program is fully functional, and principled users who take a real
shine to it can register for $19.95. The site offers hundreds of
downloadable skins that, like Kaleidoscope's, range in style from
sleek and smooth to giddy and glittery.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Besides the customizing programs, there are add-on programs that
enhance only the computer's Web browser without altering the rest
of the user interface. The front-runner is Neoplanet
(www.neoplanet.com), which layers itself on top of Internet
Explorer's ordinary look with shiny, extraordinarily rendered
metallic-looking buttons and a female voice that welcomes users
aboard every time the program is opened. The site offers a large
gallery of additional Neoplanet themes, like ones simulating the
texture of wood grain or titanium. A single click downloads and
installs the theme. The latest version of Neoplanet's browser also
includes a chat program, for sending instant messages to other
Neoplanet users.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who want to enliven younger users' Web experiences while
cleverly blocking them from the Net's pornography can download the
child-friendly Surf Monkey helpers (www.surfmonkey.com). Animated
with the Surf Monkey character, which looks like a ``Jetsons''
version of Curious George, the Surf Monkey Bar binds itself to
Internet Explorer and offers controls for adjusting where children
can go on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   The Surf Monkey Browser one-ups the bar by completely
transforming Internet Explorer into a candy-colored window on the
Web, complete with the monkey's own home page and virtual gadgets
with sound effects that let kids squirt green slime on Web pages or
shatter the page with bolts of animated lightning that create
make-believe cracks.
</P>
<P>
   While the maker suggests that Surf Monkey is designed for ``kids
ages 6 and up,'' the slime and shatter features may also be brought
into play by news-surfing grown-ups who wish to protest a rival
baseball team's late-breaking victory or just another piece of
spam.
</P>
</TEXT>
