<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-AGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES TO DECIDE AGE-BIAS CASES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An intensely skeptical Supreme Court on Wednesday
considered whether the Constitution prohibits states from
discriminating against older Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, hearing arguments in a case involving the federal
Age Discrimination in Employment Act, noted that they have never
given older people much constitutional protection. The court has
ruled that the Constitution's Equal Protection Clause requires only
that states have a ``rational basis'' for treating older Americans
differently than their fellow citizens.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the high court has allowed states to impose
mandatory retirement ages on judges, concluding that a state can
rationally conclude that health and judgment decline with age.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the court's record in age-bias cases, an attorney for
Florida and Alabama state workers pressed the justices to give
greater constitutional protection to older employees. Jeremiah
Collins argued that older workers suffer from the same ``invidious
discrimination'' faced by blacks and women, who are
constitutionally protected against discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was pressing the case of older workers at Florida and
Alabama state universities who claim that because of their age they
were paid less than their younger colleagues. The workers sued the
states.
</P>
<P>
   Federal courts, however, threw out their cases, ruling that the
Constitution protects states from being sued for money damages
unless Congress expressly says that states can be sued.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said Congress had not
made clear its intention to override the states' constitutional
immunity from suits. It also said the Constitution does not
prohibit age discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   In his appeal to the Supreme Court, Collins argued that Congress
``unequivocally authorized'' states to be sued under the
anti-age-bias law. In addition, the Washington, D.C., lawyer said
the Constitution's Equal Protection Clause gave Congress the
authority to prohibit states from discriminating against people
based on their age.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before the Supreme Court, Collins said that Congress
in 1974 amended the age-bias law to make clear that state agencies
are subject to the law's anti-discrimination provisions. He also
said older Americans warrant Constitutional protection because they
are victimized by the same nefarious stereotypes that plague
minorities and women in the workforce.
</P>
<P>
   But Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist apparently was not
convinced, saying that older workers do not face the same
``invidious discrimination'' that blacks often endure at work.
States also could rationally conclude that people start ``going
downhill at a particular age,'' the 75-year-old chief justice said,
adding that ''a lot of us can testify`` to the relationship between
age and decline.
</P>
<P>
   But Deputy Solicitor General Barbara Underwood, pressing the
Clinton administration's support for the employees, said states
have no rational basis to discriminate against older workers. Older
people have just as strong a desire to work as their younger
colleagues, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia, however, noted that a state could
rationally conclude that it would be better off hiring a younger
worker, who could reasonably be expected to be in the workforce
longer than an older employee.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia also drew a distinction between age discrimination and
bias against minorities and women, saying that age affects
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all going to be old,'' Scalia said. ``It's unlike ...
race and sex. Some of us don't have to worry about that (type of
discrimination).''
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to render their decision in the case
by July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
