<P>
   &UR; TAKING THE CELEBRITY ROUTE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gary Loffredo &LR;  of the Neptune Society, which claims to be ``the
hottest e-commerce Web site of the year, told the New York Times
that ``sales'' of cremations were up in September. That was due, he
said, to publicity about the memorial services for  &UR; John F. &LR; 
 &UR; Kennedy Jr. &LR; ,  &UR; Carolyn Bessette Kennedy &LR;  and  &UR; Lauren Bessette &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``With 76 million Baby Boomers starting to age and pass away and
with Baby Boomers being one of the fastest-growing demographics on
the Internet, the Web is just a perfect place for us to be,'' said
Loffredo. ``... What better product to offer online than the
prepayment of the cremation service?''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh2,10p10  &LR; Tina's Talk Troubles
</P>
<P>
   &LR; rt,10p10  &LR; Writer  &UR; Stephen Dubner &LR;  pulled his interview with
 &UR; Ted &LR; 
 &UR; Kaczynski &LR;  from Talk magazine because of edits mandated by  &UR; Tina &LR; 
 &UR; Brown, &LR;  and is negotiating to sell it to Time. MSNBC says Brown
wanted the story to be less nuanced and more about good versus evil
because she thought it would more likely be turned into a movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tina is tearing out her hair,'' a source told New York
magazine. But there's more to be upset about:
</P>
<P>
   Features editor  &UR; Lisa Chase &LR; , who assigned the story, quit,
adding to the many staff members _ among them the chief financial
officer, managing editor, production editor, special editor and
contributing writer _ who have departed recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magazine has been a work in progress for a year now,'' a
Talk spokeswoman told the Hollywood Reporter. ``When it's a
startup, you're going to see change.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE STREETS OF CLINTON-LAND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Traditionalists who opposed the renaming of Markham Street in
Little Rock, Ark., to President Clinton Avenue found allies in
anti-Clintonites. ``With the Lewinsky scandal you had reasonable
people wondering why Little Rock would want to honor the guy,''
said political columnist  &UR; John Brummett &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   At a public meeting in July where the issue was decided, reports
Metropolis magazine, some naysayers carried signs saying that the
street, which is near the planned Clinton Presidential Library,
should be called Lewinsky Lane.
</P>
<P>
   A compromise was reached after debate: Only the section of the
street nearest the library would be renamed for the president.
Mayor  &UR; Jim Dailey &LR;  said he realized the wisdom of the compromise
after asking himself, ``What would Jesus do?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - The Australian Olympic Committee has announced that  &UR; Nicole &LR; 
 &UR; Kidman &LR; , who looked great in her underwear in ``Eyes Wide Shut,''
will run through the streets of Sydney with the Olympic torch
before next year's games.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Edwin Heaven &LR;  forwards  &UR; Garry Shandling &LR; 's advice to possible
presidential candidate  &UR; Warren Beatty &LR; : ``Warren, listen, if you
run and get elected, make sure that you get your name above the
title of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Alex Leyton &LR;  got a manicure in Reno last week from a woman
who said she had done  &UR; Tony Bennett &LR; 's nails.
</P>
<P>
   - Along with her Marin County water bill,  &UR; Connie Thorpe &LR;  has
received notice from the pessimistic County of Marin Y2K Task Force
that her household guide is on the way: ``Preparing for the Year
2000 ... and Other Disasters.''
</P>
<P>
   - A survey of 2,000 people who signed on to an online wedding
resource, theknot.com, found that 60 percent wanted the macarena
and the chicken dance banned. And a survey of 400 new college
students, taken by campuscruiser.com asked what they feared most.
The answers, in descending order: freshman English, nuclear war,
becoming a victim of terrorism, not making friends at school,
parents' death.
</P>
<P>
   - Are dogs becoming more macho? Bernie's Pet Supply on Valencia
Street is selling the 99-cent Power Bark energy bar, and Bow Wow
Bistro of Orlando, Fla., is selling Gourmet Cigar Treats for Dogs,
each cigar-shaped biscuit packed in cellophane with one end
``hand-dipped in creamy yogurt to create its white `ash' tip.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; ``The thing about having been around as long as I have is
that you can't fit your hearing aid over your earring.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Quincy Jones  &LR; to the New York Post.
