r a BC-WOMEN-SUPERINTENDENTS     10-13 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-SUPERINTENDENTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SCHOOLS DOMINATED BY WOMEN, FEW BECOME SUPERINTENDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBs grafs 4 thru 6 to add attribution; pickup 7thgraf:
``Superintendents are)  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Ore., Tenn., Texas, Wash.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Although women make up nearly 80 percent of the
nation's teachers, they account for just 10 percent of the
superintendents leading public school systems, virtually the same
percentage as at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   The glass ceiling between women and the top job in school
systems is proving one of the most difficult to shatter. In
corporate America, women account for 46 percent of the work force
and hold 40 percent of top management jobs. In the female-dominated
field of education, women hold 35 percent of all management jobs,
from superintendent down to school principal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society still wants women _ the teachers _ to take care of
children, nurture them and make sure they're safe,'' said C. Cryss
Brunner, a University of Wisconsin professor and author of two
books exploring the role of women superintendents. ``Men are there
to be top administrators who step in and oversee the `school
families.'''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Urban Superintendents Program at Harvard
University, women comprised 10 percent of superintendents at the
dawn of 1900; their ranks dropped to a mere 1 percent during the
1920s, rose to 3 percent in 1990, and have reached 10 percent on
the eve of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For educators such as Lonnie K. Chin, principal at Spring Valley
Elementary School in San Francisco, the bias is far more personal,
and can change a career.
</P>
<P>
   Chin said she once thought of becoming a district
superintendent. She was even recruited into Urban Superintendents
Program. But after seeing the national trend and frankly assessing
her management style, she decided she is happy being a principal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Superintendents are supposed to charge all over like the Lone
Ranger. My style is more collaborative and cooperative. That's
something that's seen as less decisive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the superintendents these school districts have hired:
</P>
<P>
   _ Seattle picked retired Army Maj. Gen. John Stanford in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chicago recently chose former city Budget Director Paul
Vallas.
</P>
<P>
   _ The school board in San Diego this year hired Alan Bersin, a
former U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Women who have cracked the top job often encounter reactions
they never imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was Chicago's superintendent in the early '80s, I had
reporters asking me who I was dating,'' recalled Ruth Love, a
former superintendent in Oakland, Calif., and in Chicago. ``They
wrote about what I wore or (about) my hair style. There was this
expectation that I, as a woman, would wither up under criticism or
just say, `I'm getting out of here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Yvonne Katz, the first woman to head school districts in
Beaverton, Ore., and San Antonio, had similar experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Now overseeing Beaverton's 32,000 public school children, she
said she hopes younger women will not have to struggle as hard to
be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   In schools, just as in business, there are myriad reasons women
have not advanced to the superintendent's office. Some women
teachers put their careers on hold to raise families. Some search
firms aggressively push male candidates for top jobs. But educators
say perhaps the most critical reason is the perception of what type
of personality it takes to manage teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of superintendents who came up through the ranks
were high school principals. And ``in education, people believe
it's OK for women to be elementary school principals, but at high
school and beyond, a man is needed to maintain order and rally the
troops,'' said N. Gerry House, the female superintendent in
Memphis, Tenn., one of the 20 largest districts in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, women account for 35 percent of elementary school
principals and 17 percent of high school principals.
</P>
<P>
   Delaine Eastin, California's first female superintendent of
public instruction, predicts the glass ceiling will break only
after women fill more high school principal jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, 85 percent of teachers were women and 85 percent
of principals were men. Now, as more women become principals, more
will become superintendents.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not having more women among the ranks of superintendents is
hurting schools, some educators say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're looking for leadership in education _ and we are
desperate for strong leaders _ we're eliminating some of our best
candidates,'' said Bob Peterkin, director of Harvard's Urban
Superintendents Program, founded in 1990 to encourage women and
minorities to become superintendents.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose Unified Superintendent Linda Murray said women are
well-suited for the job because: ``It's the women who have an
understanding of what teaching and learning is about. ... You'd
hope that expertise would come through at the highest levels of
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   For House, the most compelling reason is this: ``In all of our
teaching, we tell kids they can be whatever they want in life and
that gender should not be a discriminating factor. If we aren't
conscious of practicing gender equity, we become a mockery of what
we teach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5844 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      10-13 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS BUS IS HEADED FOR RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ How do you turn a bus around on a city
street?
</P>
<P>
   Deliberately and skillfully.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fitting analogy for ``corporate culture'' changes being
attempted at the Kansas City Area Transportation Authority.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Metro bus company had to get its operators past the
notion that you can't turn the bus around, that it's just not done.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen years of budget cuts and downsizing had traumatized the
largely unionized work force. And years of less-than-amiable
negotiations had created a rift between supervisors and drivers.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996 a breakthrough contract agreement allowed the
authority to work more efficiently by using part-time drivers and
smaller buses where routes called for them. Federal funding also
has stabilized in the last couple of years, and the ridership
decline leveled off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally got to the point where we had a mutual appreciation
of our serious problems,'' said Dick Davis, ATA general manager.
</P>
<P>
   After the financial emergencies were handled, though, some
workplace relationships remained troubled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ATA unfortunately had become too oriented to dealing with
the problem operator,'' Davis said. ``We'd become a disciplinarian.
We needed to move more to a culture that spent a lot more time
supporting and recognizing the good ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The authority found what most organizations have learned in the
1990s: Workers want to be included in the thought process. They
want to be asked for their suggestions. They want to share their
experiences from the front line. They don't want to just take
orders.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that evolution, the ATA board authorized a
consulting contract. Jerry Haney was hired to work with a ``culture
change team'' of supervisors and union members, people handpicked
to lead the transformation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked for respected employees who were thinkers or natural
leaders, not just yes men or complainers,'' said Fern Koehler, ATA
deputy general manager. ``We've held long meetings and training
sessions. We wanted to agree on values, react to each other's
concerns and treat each other with respect.''
</P>
<P>
   They're working on such issues as conflict management, rudeness
and personal safety. A major goal is to have a work force that
works well without supervision, that makes the ``right'' decision
because it's the right thing to do based on the circumstance _ not
because a company rule or schedule says so.
</P>
<P>
   My limited recent experiences riding ATA buses indicates that
the goal isn't universally met yet. It will take time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying for open, two-way communication, not
order-giving,'' Davis said. ``When we opened one of our first
change meetings to questions and comments, we got remarkable
feedback. We heard customer and employee issues that had never been
raised in union talks.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an amazing thing when organizations finally get to a place
of mutual respect and common purpose. Everybody at the ATA isn't
there yet, but the organization is en route. Let's see when and if
riders appreciate the change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
