<HEADER>
A5853 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MALAYSIA-JOURNALIST-N     10-13 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-JOURNALIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN JOURNALIST SAYS MALAYSIAN JUDICIARY IS FLAWED 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Murray Hiebert finished his assignment as a foreign
correspondent in Malaysia last week on a jarring note: stripped to
the waist and sitting on a bare floor as a prison guard called the
roll.
</P>
<P>
   Hiebert, a Canadian reporter for The Far Eastern Economic
Review, was released from a prison near Kuala Lumpur on Monday
after serving four weeks for contempt of court for an article he
wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hiebert, who was released two weeks early for good behavior,
left Malaysia on Tuesday for the first time in more than two years.
Wednesday, as he made the rounds at the Hong Kong headquarters of
his magazine, he was savoring the small things, like the panoramic
view of Victoria Harbor from the Review's offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry if I seem distracted,'' Hiebert said with a wry smile.
``I haven't seen views like this for a little while.''
</P>
<P>
   His home for the last month was a windowless room he shared with
35 other inmates. Given the high profile of his case, Hiebert said
he believed that he had been treated better than a typical
Malaysian prisoner. He slept on a cot with a thin mattress rather
than on a concrete floor, as is customary for new arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was treated as well as the prison rules would allow,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty days in prison is not a draconian penalty by Malaysian
standards. Anwar Ibrahim, the former deputy prime minister and
rival of Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, was sentenced to six
years on corruption charges that his defenders insist are
politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the experience has shaken Hiebert, 50, a soft-spoken man
known among his colleagues for his ascetic way of life and
unflappable demeanor. And it could have lingering impact in a
country where critics say the government uses the courts as a club
to bully news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my freedom, which is a rather shocking thing to have
happen, for writing about a debating team,'' Hiebert said. ``I
wasn't Bob Woodward trying to bring down a presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble started in January 1997, after Hiebert wrote about
the wife of a prominent judge who sued the Kuala Lumpur
International School when her 17-year-old son was dropped from the
debating team.
</P>
<P>
   Hiebert suggested that the case moved through the legal system
unusually quickly because the boy's father was a judge. He quoted
an unnamed Malaysian lawyer as saying such cases normally took at
least five years to reach a court. The court heard this one just
seven months after it was filed.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's wife, Chandra Sri Ram, agreed to a settlement of her
case. But in an affidavit, she accused Hiebert of contempt of
court. A judge agreed, finding Hiebert guilty of ``scandalizing the
judiciary.''
</P>
<P>
   In imposing a three-month prison sentence, Judge Low Hop Bing
wrote, ``In my view, for far too long there appears to be unabated
contemptuous attacks by and through the media on our judiciary.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiebert is appealing the verdict. But last month he decided to
serve a reduced sentence rather than seek a delay, because he
wanted to retrieve his passport. The government was holding it
while the case was pending, preventing him from leaving the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Hiebert's case was complicated by the fact that shortly before
the article appeared, his wife had been named deputy headmistress
of the school. Even Hiebert's friends acknowledge that this was a
potential conflict of interest. Hiebert declined to discuss the
issue, citing his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the anguish it caused him, Hiebert said he had no
regrets about the article. He said it had been vindicated by
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made some critical comments about the judiciary, and I stand
by them,'' he said. ``Most of what I said in that article has been
shown over and over again in all the various cases we've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Malaysia was galvanized earlier this year by the trial
of Anwar, the protege-turned-rival of Mahathir. Soon after Anwar
was dismissed by the prime minister, he was charged with corruption
and sex-related crimes.
</P>
<P>
   After a trial marked by questionable rulings, Anwar was found
guilty and sentenced to six years. He is now fighting sodomy
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's defenders say it was a convenient way to dispose of
Mahathir's most potent political rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a judiciary that is at the beck and call of the
executive,'' said Chandra Muzaffar, an academic who is helping
Anwar's wife, Azizah Ismail, mount a challenge to Mahathir.
</P>
<P>
   In an odd twist, Hiebert was sent to the same prison where Anwar
is serving his sentence. As he leaves Malaysia's roiling political
drama for a new job as Washington correspondent of the Review, one
might expect Hiebert to express bitterness about his experience.
But he is remarkably generous about the country that turned him
into a legal precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lovely country,'' he said. ``The people are very
friendly. My problem isn't with the 22 million people who occupy
most of the country. My problem is with the judiciary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
