<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5854 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-BEER-NUT-TEX     10-13 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-NUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEFFE ABBEY ALE _ PROOF THAT BLONDES DO HAVE MORE FUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN MELTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regular readers of The Beer Nut may be tired of my infatuation
with Belgian brews, and I'm truly sorry if I sound like a broken
record about how wonderful they are. So here's my advice: Get over
it. Or get your own column.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, indulge me, please, as I sing the praises of
yet another masterful Belgian Abbey-style Ale: Leffe (LEF-fay)
Blonde.
</P>
<P>
   Brewed, not coincidentally, in the tiny town of Leffe, Blonde
hits the tongue with a tart, fruity sharpness, but goes down with
the traditional big, bitter and yeasty finish. Indeed, the
murkiness of the brew puts off many first-time tasters, but don't
flee. It's just the yeast that the brew masters add right before
stoppering to condition the beer. And as with most top-fermented
brews, Leffe is best served at the same temperature at which it
comes into the world: roughly between 60 and 68 degrees. In fact,
the change of seasons right now is a perfect time to sit back and
enjoy a Leffe with a big ol' bowl of chili.
</P>
<P>
   But Beer Nut, you ask _ why the passion for Belgians? Allow me
to offer a bit of explanation about my obsession.
</P>
<P>
   It all goes back to how beer is made. Top-fermentation, an
ancient brewing method, allows yeast to rise to the top of the
brewing vessel during naturally occurring fermentation. This yields
stouts, ales, porters and wheat beers, all of which have distinct
fruity notes. In contrast, bottom-fermentation is a relatively new
Bavarian innovation from the 19th century, wherein yeasts stay at
the bottom of the brewing vessel, resulting in lighter,
cleaner-tasting lagers and their subset, even cleaner-tasting
pilsners.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, mass production of beer began with the advent of
bottom-fermentation, because it allowed brewers to do their thing
year-round. With top-fermentation, the yeasts tended to interbreed
with airborne yeasts, rendering brewing impossible during summer
months. Nowadays, with refrigeration and sealed brew kettles, both
methods are used year-round. But bottom-fermentation came out on
top, which is why so many different lagers now hail from all over
the world. Which is a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   But it also brings me back to my infatuation with Belgian beers.
It's a personal thing: After years of swilling lagers, I'm ready
for a change. And no other country in the world offers more
varieties of beers (except possibly Engthan Belgium.
Pilsners, lambics (gueuze, kriek and faro), abbey, white, red,
brown ....
</P>
<P>
   All this wonderfully strong beer to taste, yet so little time.
Truly a dirty job, but hey, somebody's gotta do it. So hey, this
one's for you.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5856 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-EUROPE-NYT &LR;      10-13 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-EUROPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORY STANCE ON EUROPE TIES IS CRITICIZED BY FORMER PARTY
OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The decision at the Conservative annual convention
distancing the party further from Europe was attacked by past Tory
leaders Wednesday as unthinking and suicidal for the party's
chances of ever getting back into power.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's relationship with Europe is the most divisive issue in
the party that long dominated British politics, and a vexing
internal dispute over it contributed to the Tories' overwhelming
loss to Labor two years ago and to their continued low standing in
opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Party leader William Hague declared the hard-line policy at the
party conference in Blackpool last week in an effort to end the
debate, but the action seems instead to have renewed it.
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister John Major called the new stance ``absurd
and crazy.'' Former Prime Minister Edward Heath termed it ``very
sad.'' Former party chairman Chris Patten said the party was
``making no sense'' anymore and risked losing mainstream support.
</P>
<P>
   Former Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd called the party's
deepening skepticism toward the Continent ``frivolous'' and said,
``Judging from last week's speeches in Blackpool, Conservative
policy on Europe is increasingly based on the caricature, not on
the reality.'' The party will cease to be taken seriously, he
added, ``if it's busy throwing abuse at the caricature.''
</P>
<P>
   Patten, who served as the last governor-general of Hong Kong and
is now taking up the job of European external affairs commissioner,
signaled that Hague was mistaken if he thought the party would
unite uncomplainingly behind the tough new attitude. He was
breaking his own pledge of silence, he told The Times of London
from his Brussels office, ``because if the result of keeping quiet
is that things keep on being dragged in a direction which plainly
raises question marks about the national interest, is one still
obliged to take a vow of omerta?
</P>
<P>
   Patten said disenchanted Tories were obliged to take public
issue with the new policy now ``because we're in danger of crossing
a river and it's very difficult to get back from the other side
unless people like me speak out at this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Heseltine, who was the deputy prime minister in Major's
government, and Kenneth Clarke, who was chancellor of the
Exchequer, assailed the new policy during the Blackpool conference
and will be speaking out against it Thursday when they join Prime
Minister Tony Blair in the launching of a cross-party ``Britain in
Europe'' public education campaign in London.
</P>
<P>
   Blair has staked out a position of establishing a more
cooperative atmosphere between Britain and the rest of Europe while
keeping the country for the present out of the monetary union, the
agreement under which 11 nations are converting their national
money into euros.
</P>
<P>
   Blair is starting to prepare public opinion for entry at a later
date when, he argues, joining the common currency will make more
economic sense for Britain than it does now. He has promised a
public referendum on the decision, and the expectation is that it
will occur soon after the next election, which must take place by
May 2002.
</P>
<P>
   In the two years of Hague's leadership, the Conservatives have
adopted an absolute position that there will be no consideration of
Britain's joining a common currency for seven years at the very
least. They have cast the argument as one of giving up the pound, a
powerful national symbol.
</P>
<P>
   At their conference in Blackpool, they stiffened this position,
suggesting that Britain should renegotiate the founding treaty of
the European Union and saying Britain must not agree to any new
arrangements with continental nations that do not give it
permission to escape requirements it does not like.
</P>
<P>
   A move among hard-liners in the party to take Britain out of the
European Union altogether was given impetus by the rapturous
reception accorded former Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, who is
known to favor that action. ``In my lifetime, all the problems have
come from mainland Europe,'' she said on arrival in Blackpool in a
much-commented-upon statement, ``and all the solutions have come
from the English-speaking nations across the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Major told The Daily Telegraph on Wednesday that ``to say
nothing good comes out of Europe is just plain silly.'' He said he
feared for Hague and the party's future. ``He is being pushed too
far to the right,'' he said. ``We cannot possibly win an election
from there.''
</P>
<P>
   A hard-line attitude toward Europe has held more allure for the
Conservatives in Parliament who run the party than it has for
Conservative voters. Surveys show that while opposition to
Britain's participation in the European common currency remains
widespread, it has been diluted by the conclusion of a majority of
Britons that the country's eventual entry is inevitable and by
growing fears among businessmen of the bottom-line risks of staying
out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
