<HEADLINE>
WHERE SHOULD SLEEPING BABY LIE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday, Oct. 20.)  
(lh) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The parent and baby co-sleeping debate has risen again, with
valid arguments on both sides of the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say it's dangerous: the baby might roll between the
mattress and the headboard or wall and smother, or a deep-sleeping
parent might accidentally roll over on the infant and injure him.
Another camp says it's indulgent, and will spoil the child, making
him clingy and unable to sleep alone.
</P>
<P>
   But pro-family bed researchers say it's largely safe, and an
important bonding time.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Western cultures have allowed technology to be
substituted for mother and baby contact, biology is the same as it
was 10,000 years ago,'' says James McKenna, an anthropologist and
mother/baby sleep researcher at the University of Notre Dame.
``Babies still need that contact and comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   McKenna studied 110 pairs of breast-feeding mothers and their
babies 2 months to 5 months old. He find that co-sleeping babies
are placed in safer positions, breast feed more, cry less and sleep
more.
</P>
<P>
   I've studied only two babies _ my own.
</P>
<P>
   And, to be honest, I tried whatever worked. At various times
I've shared a double bed with them; let them cry themselves to
sleep in their crib; rocked them until they fell asleep; and, as
they grew older, let them crawl in bed between my husband and me
after they had nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   Our son slept well in his own crib until he was ill for a few
weeks when he was about a year old. We brought him into our bed and
didn't get him completely out again for the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   To be honest, I loved snuggling with him at night, since I was
working full time and didn't have much body contact with him during
the day.
</P>
<P>
   He grudgingly started sleeping alone in his twin bed at just
over 3, but even now, at 8, he will sometimes ask us to lie down
with him or at least let the cat stay in his room ``so I can sleep
with something warm.''
</P>
<P>
   With my daughter, I set up a bed and cradle in the guestroom so
we could nap together frequently. She gladly nursed next to me
until sated. Then she wiggled restlessly until I placed her in her
bumper-lined cradle.
</P>
<P>
   Just when things had settled into a routine, my son got his bunk
bed, and his sister inherited his twin bed. She was so happy to be
in a ``big girl'' bed, with Winnie-the-Pooh sheets.
</P>
<P>
   She played on the bed, read on the bed, snuggled with us on the
bed. And then, after lights were out, she'd promptly climb out of
bed and wander the house at all hours of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Short of locking her in her dark room (which we actually tried a
few times, to hysterical screaming) we had to battle each night to
make her stay in bed.
</P>
<P>
   In short order, we were back to a family bed again.
</P>
<P>
   Through trial and error over the years, we have tried to
maximize sleep time while recognizing that we don't rule out
co-sleeping in the first few years. Now that my children are 3 and
8, they sleep alone most nights unless they are sick or have a bad
dream ... about once a month for each.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few purists'' when it comes to family sleeping
arrangements, says McKenna. ``Parents try about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus has master's and specialist degrees in marriage
and family counseling. The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the
New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
