<SLUG> BC-TV-NYPDBLUE-ABC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NYPD BLUE' TO LOSE ITS TIME SLOT ON ABC, PRODUCER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Steven Bochco, co-creator of the Emmy-award winning
television series ``NYPD Blue,'' said Wednesday that ABC had told
him the show would be moved from its Tuesday night time slot after
six years. The network declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   An angry Bochco said that Stuart Bloomberg, co-chairman of ABC
Entertainment Group, told him Wednesday morning that the network
was considering replacing the show with ``Once and Again,'' a
series about two single parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know where we're going; they won't tell us,'' Bochco
said. ``Basically they're kissing us off. If you look at the
schedule, there's no place that makes any sense at all.'' He added:
``It's disrespectful, it's disloyal. I told them that if you want
to shoot yourself in the foot, be my guest. Except my foot's under
your foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ABC declined to comment officially, executives there
said that no final decision had been made. ``NYPD Blue'' was ranked
13th last year among regular series for viewers 18 to 49. The
audience for the police drama dropped 7 percent last year from the
previous year, a normal rate of attrition for a popular show that
has been on the air for years.
</P>
<P>
   Bochco said Bloomberg told him that ``Once and Again'' was being
considered for the time slot because of its appeal to women. That
show, created by Edward Zwick and Marshall Herskovitz, is in the
``NYPD Blue'' time slot at 10 p.m. Eastern time on Tuesdays. It was
scheduled to go off the air when ``NYPD Blue'' returned on Nov. 9
and come back later in another time slot.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Bochco, Bloomberg told him that if ``Once and
Again'' were removed, its substantial number of women viewers would
turn to a rival show on CBS, ``Judging Amy,'' and turn it into a
hit. ``They're doing this to us in order to prevent that possible
scenario,'' Bochco said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once and Again,'' which began showing in September, is the
highest-rated new drama on any network among viewers 18 to 49.
</P>
<P>
   Bochco, the creator or co-creator of shows like ``L.A. Law'' and
``Hill Street Blues,'' said he was convinced that one reason his
show was being shifted was that Walt Disney Co., which produces
``Once and Again'' and owns ABC, was protecting its investment.
``NYPD Blue'' is produced by Bochco's company, Steven Bochco
Productions, and distributed by 20th Century Fox television, a
division of News Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
