<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHERNY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS INVESTIGATE RUSSIAN BUSINESSMAN FOR POSSIBLE BANK FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The police in Switzerland have said investigations into
possible money laundering and crimes by Russian executives and
politicians have expanded to include Lev Cherny, a Russian emigrant
businessman with extensive interests in the metals industry.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Swiss Federal Office of Police Matters,
Juerg Pulver, confirmed a report in the weekly Sonntagsblick that
an inquiry had started.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Cherny have denied his involvement in
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss law-enforcement agencies have for several months been
looking into major cases involving Swiss organizations doing
business in Russia or Russian companies with accounts in
Switzerland. One prominent investigation involves reported
kickbacks from the Mabetex Group of Lugano, the global engineering
and construction company, to officials in President Boris N.
Yeltsin's administration in exchange for contracts here.
</P>
<P>
   Another inquiry focuses on Swiss companies that may be tied to a
Russian financier, Boris Berezovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Cherny made a name for himself years ago through his involvement
with a metals trading company, the Trans-World Group, which gained
control of the vast smelters at the heart of the Russian aluminum
industry. Trans-World has repeatedly denied that Cherny is involved
in running the company, which has offices in London, Geneva and
elsewhere. But past discussions with Trans-World executives have
shown that Cherny had a role in establishing relations between the
company, once a small-time player in the metals market, and Russian
smelters.
</P>
<P>
   Those relationships helped increase Trans-World sales, generated
the income that the company needed to buy major stakes in the
smelters during the privatization of large factories, and made
Trans-World into a leading aluminum producer.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1990s, investigators with the Interior Ministry
have been looking into whether Cherny and his two brothers were
part of a sweeping bank fraud that the police say the Chernys used
to finance their first deals with the smelters.
</P>
<P>
   In written testimony at a May 1995 parliamentary hearing, a
senior investigator with the Interior Ministry, Sergei Glushenkov,
said preliminary investigations showed that foreign companies ``set
up by a group of former citizens of the Soviet Union led by the
brothers Cherny'' signed contracts with aluminum plants. ``Payment
by the above-mentioned foreign firms for the majority of these
contracts,'' Glushenkov wrote, ``was made through fictitious
companies that used resources obtained as a result of fraudulent
operations with bank documents.''
</P>
<P>
   Trans-World and Cherny's lawyers have said that if the company's
name did arise in connection with bank fraud, that was because
Trans-World had fallen victim to shady companies during the chaos
of the early days of market reforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
