<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-STRAWBERRY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INDEFATIGABLE STRAWBERRY IS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They'd prefer not to dwell on it, but they remember.
They remember it well.
</P>
<P>
   They remember somberly assembling in front of the ESPN cameras
to send a live get-well card to an ailing teammate. They remember
having the No. 39 stitched into their New York Yankees caps. They
remember his wife leaving his side at the hospital long enough to
throw out the first pitch before the first game of the American
League Championship Series. They remember the World Series
champagne celebration in San Diego, the wishing that he could have
been there.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry _ last October's cancer patient, this past
spring's lapsed drug addict _ is this fall's monument to recovery.
Strawberry has been back with the Yankees barely a month, and he's
already making himself indispensable. Even the Yankees wouldn't be
in the ALCS against the Boston Red Sox with pitching alone.
</P>
<P>
   A three-run home run by Strawberry accounted for the only runs
of Game 3 of the AL Division Series. With one cobra strike of his
bat, Strawberry provided the offense they needed to sweep the Texas
Rangers out of the way. The effortless swing that drove an Esteban
Loaiza fastball 415 feet underscores why people like Strawberry get
second and third and fourth and fifth chances. At 37, Straw still
can stir a drink with as much of a flourish as any Yankee this side
of Reggie Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's his style,'' Yankees designated hitter Chili Davis said
admiringly. ``That's why he's Darryl Strawberry.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry missed almost the entire regular season. He got just
enough September at-bats to fine-tune a swing that somehow has
stayed with him through all the years of drinks and drugs, of
falling down and picking himself back up. And it just so happened
that Yankees manager Joe Torre was keeping his DH options open,
because Davis was feeling the wear and tear of being 39.
</P>
<P>
   Just last year, Davis missed almost the entire regular season
because of a bum ankle. Davis got just enough September at-bats to
fine-tune his switch-hitting stroke. And it just so happened that
Torre was exploring his DH options, because Strawberry was in no
condition to play in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry hit 24 homers last season before his diagnosis of
colon cancer came down between Games 2 and 3 of the ALDS. Two days
later, doctors removed 16 inches of Strawberry's large intestine.
Strawberry had hopes of making the season-opening roster, but the
Yankees left him in Tampa, Fla., for extended spring training. He
nearly gave himself a permanent vacation April 14 by getting
arrested on charges of cocaine possession and solicitation of a
prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice if the likes of Torre wouldn't try to soften
Strawberry's succession of problems as ``hiccups.'' Aside from the
cancer, Strawberry has brought his problems on himself and his
teams. Here's a professed born-again Christian whose dossier
includes multiple drug suspensions, charges of spousal abuse and a
plea-bargain for tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, Strawberry definitely isn't a quitter. On the
other hand, he had Hall-of-Fame talent and frittered away most of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who spends any time around Strawberry would be
hard-pressed not to like him. He has a soothing, upbeat clubhouse
presence. He doesn't complain about playing time. He says the right
things. Of course, he has had a lot of practice at figuring out
what people want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   The cycle keeps repeating itself nevertheless. Regression.
Redemption. Regression. Redemption. Regression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever Straw's back is against the wall, that's when he's at
his best,'' Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter said. ``He saves his best
for last, in prime-time, when the spotlight's on.''
</P>
<P>
   That undoubtedly contributed to Torre's decision to use
Strawberry over Davis when the ALDS began. Strawberry did what he
could to make his case in 49 regular-season at-bats with the
Yankees, hitting .327 with six homers and 17 walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love him,'' Davis said. ``I love what he does for us. ...
Whoever plays, the other guy will be pulling for him.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees prefer not to dwell on it, but they remember pulling
for Darryl Strawberry last October just to recover from cancer.
They remember it _ and his other troubles _ well. They made it a
point to have non-alcholic champagne on hand Saturday night when
they celebrated their sweep of the Rangers. He has been in recovery
from one thing or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having this again _ a postseason _ to me that says I didn't
give up when I really could have given up,'' Strawberry said. ``I
look in the mirror and I know whose fault it is. And I look in the
mirror and see the guy who is going to try and keep fighting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
