<HEADER>
A5870 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-''DUTCH''-REVIEW-TEX     10-13 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-''DUTCH''-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACT, FICTION, WHO CARES?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A note to our readers: Former first lady Nancy Reagan did not
write this review; books editor Jeff Guinn did. But since Edmund
Morris, the author of ``Dutch,'' inserted himself as a fictional
character in his book about Ronald Reagan, we thought, hey, why not
give it a try?
</P>
<P>
   ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan''
</P>
<P>
   By Edmund Morris
</P>
<P>
   Biography
</P>
<P>
   Random House, $35
</P>
<P>
   By ``Nancy Reagan''
</P>
<P>
   I remember when someone on my husband's staff, that roly-poly
Michael Deaver, probably, said we needed to bring in a historian to
observe firsthand some of Ronnie's time in office and write a book
about it afterward. A ``good'' book, not one of those tell-all
things. A few weeks later, I noticed this slovenly, bearded man
hanging around the Oval Office. He was introduced to me as Edmund
Morris, an author who won the Pulitzer Prize for his biography of
Theodore Roosevelt. Everybody else seemed to like him, and Ronnie
didn't care one way or the other, so he stayed and later on kept us
waiting for years and years before he finally got that book
written.
</P>
<P>
   All that waiting, and the dreary little man has let us down. He
made up parts, if you can believe that, and he says he did it
because he couldn't figure out any other way to write about Ronnie.
Thousands of other writers and journalists and press people
certainly were able to during our years in office, so I can't
understand why the supposedly wonderful Mr. Morris couldn't manage
such a simple thing. Maybe his vocabulary is as limited as his
wardrobe. (He wears the same suit three days in a row! I think he
only has two or three).
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people are criticizing this so-called memoir without
even reading it, since biographers are supposed to stick to the
facts. Even though people warned me, I decided to read it before
offering my opinion, and I have and now I am: It's dreadful. Awful.
Edmund Morris has such a pleasant way of writing about the tackiest
things that I'm very much afraid people will read ``Dutch'' from
cover to cover. Comparing my eyes to ``two large, pale,
accompanying jellyfish?'' Really! Though that's not the worst part.
Mr. Morris sort of invents himself as a character and pretends he
was in different places seeing things with his own eyes. I know, I
know, he claims he's just using some new way of writing a
biography, but how can you feel like you're reading actual history
when you're never really certain which parts are true and which are
made up? It's like those terrible old days when Patti broke curfew
and would have all kinds of excuses when she finally got home. Once
or twice, I nearly woke Ronnie up so he could hear that drivel for
himself.
</P>
<P>
   And, frankly, I don't think this so-called new technique of Mr.
Morris' gets many results, although there are a few good insights.
For instance, Mr. Morris says Ronnie, like all actors, remembers
the future rather than the past _ it comes from memorizing scripts,
he thinks. You know, an actor has to know the lines being shot
today while, at the same time, he's trying to memorize his lines
for the next day's shooting. This is why Ronnie occasionally got
facts about his past wrong, Mr. Morris says _ little things like
his children's names.
</P>
<P>
   There is entirely too much space devoted to Ronnie's supposed
love affairs, which no one cares about anyway, or at least they
shouldn't. And there's a lot about that first woman he married,
which I suppose is inevitable, although I must admit the book
brightens considerably when I come into the story. Mr. Morris calls
Ronnie's and my romance a love story for the ages. At least he got
that right.
</P>
<P>
   I expect people will be most critical of the last third of the
book. That's when Mr. Morris stops making things up and pretty much
concentrates on Ronnie in the White House. He actually was there
watching and taking notes, of course, so he didn't have to resort
to make-believe. Yet this part is, frankly, pretty boring. Instead
of chat about Hollywood, there are pages and pages about
legislation and things. There are also some unnecessary comments
about my astrologer; I should have asked her about Mr. Morris
before I agreed to let him write the book about Ronnie! We'd have
saved ourselves grief, believe me!
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Morris sums things up by saying Ronnie was simply
unknowable, that while he seemed friendly he really was sort of
distant, aloof. Even his immediate staff aren't supposed to have
ever felt entirely comfortable with him, and that one part about
the Bushes, and Ronnie never thanking them for their 75th birthday
gift to him! I just know George would never have said such a thing,
although I wouldn't put it past Barbara. People with weight
problems are like that, you know.
</P>
<P>
   Like most other unfair criticism of my husband _ that
Iran-Contra thing is a good example, although Mr. Morris does point
out Ronnie had just had surgery when he more or less approved it _
I think ``Dutch'' will eventually be forgotten, thank goodness. It
is obviously a book written for the money; I've heard for as much
as $3 million. I wouldn't pay a penny for it; if I want to read
made-up things about my husband, I'll try Jane Wyman's diary. Come
to think of it, I'll bet she put Mr. Morris up to the whole thing.
Her or Barbara Bush.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
