<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5881 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-ME-BOS &LR;      10-13 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BRIDGET JONES FANS, `A LITTLE MORE' ABOUT HER DIARIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE DANIEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A LITTLE MORE ABOUT ME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Pam Houston &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Norton, 288 pp., $23.95 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I recently lent a young male friend ``Bridget Jones's Diary,''
the comic novel about an over-the-top neurotic single woman. After
reading some of it, he e-mailed me: ``Women are not really that
completely without confidence and desperate as that Bridget Jones
girl, or are they?''
</P>
<P>
   My friend, bless his heart, hasn't yet learned that many of the
strongest-seeming women have their own bits of Bridget _ a
character consumed by worry about her weight, men, and being at
peace with herself.
</P>
<P>
   These shared self-doubts are part of the bond among women, and a
large part of the reason writer Pam Houston has so many fans. Here
is a woman who has scaled mountains, guided numerous white-water
rafting trips, and led hunters through the Alaskan wilderness. Her
20s were spent ticking off, and writing about, one adventure after
the other, on five continents. All the while, she fretted about her
weight almost constantly, was largely motivated by men and romance,
and endlessly struggled to find peace with herself. In short, she's
Indiana Jones meets Bridget Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Little More About Me,'' a collection of personal essays, is
her first nonfiction work, though her previous books, the very
popular ``Cowboys Are My Weakness'' and ``Waltzing the Cat,''
clearly had their roots in autobiography, as Houston has readily
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of the book's offerings are new; most were either
published in women's and outdoors magazines or appeared in
anthologies. In ``The Long Way to Safety,'' an introduction of
sorts, Houston has finally (her summation) settled down, at a ranch
she bought in Creede, Colo., elevation 9,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Says the typically conflicted Houston: ``The road I've taken
these five years has been a long and twisted one. . . .Through the
windshield I can see everything I want to take with me: horses and
men and mountains and rivers. But in the rearview mirror, damned if
I don't see horses and men and mountains and rivers, everything I
need to leave behind.''
</P>
<P>
   In her late 30s, Houston has determined that ``the edge,''
though it still beckons, has lost much appeal. ``How many times can
you walk to the same edge and find it interesting? . . .I see new,
more interesting edges everywhere I look: artistic, spiritual,
emotional, even physical edges that don't necessarily involve
risking my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Because these essays were composed during a five-year span, some
relate more to the Indiana Jones, some to the Bridget; in others
the two meet and duke it out, or perhaps wind up in couples
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's writing is at its sparkling best when chronicling
trips, while gazing more at the stars than at herself. ``Soul of
the Andes'' brings together what is beautiful, maddening, and great
fun about South American travel. And she pays moving homage to the
people and the land of Bhutan in ``In Bhutan,There is No Way to be
Famous,'' based on her rugged Himalayan trek there.
</P>
<P>
   It's in the grouping of essays titled ``One Long Look in the
Mirror'' that the author's self-doubt, even self-loathing, becomes
almost too painful too bear. But one can understand the source of
her emptiness and confusion. Houston's father, a natural athlete,
wanted her to rival Chris Evert in tennis. She didn't come close.
Her mother, a former actress, wanted Houston to be beautiful, which
to her mind meant thin, with well-applied makeup and good hair. She
failed again. Her home was cold, violent, and unsafe, and Houston
believes that is why she went after danger, to find the
``comforts'' of home.
</P>
<P>
   While men come and men go, her dogs remain by her side. Her deep
connection with them is chronicled in several pieces, including the
final essay, ``Home is Where Your Dogs Are,'' a sweet eulogy for
her canine companion Jackson and a homecoming for herself. Though
she will always mourn her longtime sidekick, ``I no longer feel
like I won't be able to live without him. He saw me through the
loneliest years . . . years that I needed to live through, before I
could find my way home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
