<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Oct. 14 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please contact
Susan Leh at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   BRUSHFIRES-HEAT (Los Angeles) _ Two wildfires broke out along
Mulholland, which firefighters hoped to contain quickly, despite
temperatures near 100 and multiple fronts. By Dominic Berbeo and
Phillip W. Browne. (Will move in the ``n'' California and ``a''
national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD-SHAKEUP (Los Angeles) _ Los Angeles Unified Superintendent
Ruben Zacarias met Wednesday with the district's new chief
executive officer, the lawyer who has wrested away control of the
nation's second largest school district from the career educator.
While the mayor praised the installation of Howard Miller as CEO,
Zacarias supporters clamored the move by the school board is
nothing less than a coup, designed to immediately undermine and
eventually topple the superintendent. By Greg Gittrich and David
Baker. (Will move in the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news
files.)
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-VICTORY (Los Angeles) _ Southland union leaders declared
victory Wednesday even before the last delegate left the floor of
the 23rd Biennial AFL-CIO Convention. The convention's
unprecedented blend of languages and politics reflected an overdue
change in the labor movement, officials said. By Jason Takenouchi.
(Will move in the ``n'' California, ``a'' national and ``f''
financial news files.)
</P>
<P>
   FOX-ADS (Los Angeles) _ 20th Century Fox has pulled all of its
ads from The Hollywood Reporter after the trade journal's editor
wrote a scathing commentary about the studio's ``The Fight Club.''
The decision is just the latest controversy leading up to Friday's
release of ``The Fight Club,'' which critics and industry insiders
alike have panned as being too violent. By Dave McNary. (Will move
in the ``f'' financial and ``e'' entertainment news files.)
</P>
