A5893 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-RECORDS-HNS &LR;      10-13 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-RECORDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES QUESTION LAW'S VALIDITY IN POLICE RECORDS CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Wednesday considered the
constitutionality of a California law that prohibits police
departments from releasing arrest records to companies and people
who want to sell the information.
</P>
<P>
   Several justices questioned the law's validity, saying the
prohibition might unconstitutionally restrict the free-speech
rights of companies seeking to publish the information. But others
indicated that the statute might be a constitutional way to protect
the privacy of arrestees and ensure they are not inundated with
unwelcome solicitations from lawyers and social workers.
</P>
<P>
   The case before the justices arose when United Reporting
Publishing Corp., which provides names and addresses to law firms
and other businesses, sued the Los Angeles Police Department in
1996 to gain access to arrest records. The police had refused to
release the information to the company, citing the California
Public Records Act, which limits release of the records to
organizations with a scholarly, journalistic, political or
governmental purpose.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. district court and then the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals ruled for the publishing company. In its decision, the 9th
Circuit rejected the state's argument that it sought to protect the
privacy of arrestees, noting that the information is made available
to newspapers that can publish the information at will.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Thomas Goldstein, pressing the police department's
appeal, conceded that the controversial law restricts corporate
access to the records but added that the restriction is necessary
to protect the privacy of arrestees. He said companies like United
Reporting indiscriminately sell the information to professional
service agencies.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Antonin Scalia appeared unswayed, noting that the
law allows newspapers to have unrestricted access to the records.
Newspapers, just like United Reporting, are in the business of
selling information, Scalia said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, of Washington, D.C., responded that the
``constitutional tradition'' of freedom of the press entitles
newspapers to the information. No such constitutional protection
exists for companies seeking to sell information to solicitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are massive wholesale invasions of privacy'' when
companies like United Reporting sell the information to attorneys
and social workers, Goldstein said. The data in the arrest records
is a mere ``commodity'' to United Reporting, he added, drawing a
stinging rebuke from Justice David H. Souter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information is a commodity to the New York Times,'' Souter
said, indicating that no legal difference exists between United
Reporting and newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Solicitor General Edward DuMont, pressing the Clinton
administration's support for the California law, conceded that
newspapers are free to publish information they get from police and
other state agencies. But states should remain free to dictate that
the information it releases will not be used for commercial gain,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   For example, DuMont said the Los Angeles Times can publish the
names and addresses of arrestees, but it cannot use the information
for the commercial purpose of soliciting subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   But Scalia objected, saying the Constitution prohibits states
from providing information to one industry _ newspapers _ while
keeping it from others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Sixpack should be able to do anything with the information
that the press can do,'' Scalia said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, DuMont said United Reporting is just as free as
newspapers to publish any information it acquires. However, the
Constitution does not require that the state help the company
gather the data.
</P>
<P>
   United Reporting's attorney, Bruce Ennis, countered that the
California law violates the First Amendment by permitting police to
discriminate between speakers, giving information to newspapers but
not to other companies. Ennis said the law violates constitutional
protections for commercial speech by keeping information from
companies involved in solicitation.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state is not saying, `We don't like solicitors,''' she
said. Instead, California is trying to protect the privacy of
arrestees by restricting public access to their home addresses.
</P>
<P>
   The high court is expected to render its decision in the case,
Los Angeles Police Department vs. United Reporting Publishing
Corp., by July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
