<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5913 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-YEN-NYT &LR;      10-13 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-YEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEN RECOVERS FROM NEWS THAT JAPAN MIGHT INCREASE MONEY SUPPLY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Bank of Japan moved Wednesday to expand the range of
tools it could use to increase the supply of money in the economy
to help weaken the resurgent yen.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's currency initially tumbled more than 1 percent in
response to the action, taken by the central bank after an
unusually long monthly meeting of its policy board.
</P>
<P>
   But there was considerable confusion in the financial markets
about whether the bank's action marked a policy change or something
less significant.
</P>
<P>
   In a reflection of skepticism about the effectiveness of the
action, the yen recovered from a low of 107.96 per dollar
immediately after the bank's meeting in Tokyo to 106.60 per dollar
by the end of trading in New York _ only slightly weaker than its
106.31 per dollar exchange rate a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Japan has been under increasing pressure from the
government and its global economic partners, notably the United
States, to take steps that would weaken the yen, which has risen to
the highest levels in more than three years against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The yen's strength is threatening to undermine Japan's slow
recovery from its worst recession in a half-century by hurting the
sales and profits of Japanese exporters.
</P>
<P>
   In a display of independence, the Bank of Japan has shown little
sign of capitulation to the domestic and foreign pressure to weaken
the yen. Rather, the central bank has been insisting that its
monetary policy of keeping interest rates extremely low and keeping
1 trillion in excess cash sloshing around in the system is
sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   But the action Tuesday seemed to at least mark an enhancement of
that policy. The bank said that it would expand the maturity range
of government securities it purchases from time to time, which
theoretically could put even more yen into circulation and dilute
the currency's value.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Gittler, an economist at the Bank of America in Hong
Kong, said the bank's decision could even lead to purchases of
long-term government bonds, something the bank has staunchly
resisted in the past.
</P>
<P>
   But most analysts seemed to be concluding that while the bank's
decision might be a more effective way of increasing the supply of
yen in the system, it was not an about-face by the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they have done is open another channel for their money
market operations,'' said Robert Alan Feldman, chief economist at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in Tokyo. ``It doesn't mean they'll use
it, and it doesn't mean a change of policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Feldman said, he read it as an effort by the bank to
demonstrate concern about the impact of the yen's strength.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey D. Young, an economist at Nikko Salomon Smith Barney who
has written about the possibility of the bank adding treasury note
purchases to its tool chest, agreed. ``People inside the bank are
not convinced the economy is in a self-sustaining recovery, and
they're worried about the rise of the yen and bond yields,'' he
said. ``They're looking for a way of boosting the impact their
policy has, and this is one way of doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior bank official confirmed the economists' analysis.
``Nothing has changed,'' he said. ``The essence of the bank's
policy has not changed, but it has tried to make the appearance
more attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the bank had made no commitment to increasing the amount
of the yen in the system and that he did not expect it to do so.
``Unless you see the bank put more than 1 trillion yen of surplus
money into the market tomorrow morning, it has not changed its
policy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time the Bank of Japan has sent confusing
messages about its monetary policy. At a meeting of finance
ministers from the Group of Seven industrialized nations in
Washington last month, the Bank of Japan similarly perplexed
reporters and others with an opaque statement about its stance,
leading some to report that it had succumbed to the prodding of the
ministry of finance and the U.S. Treasury Department to print money
and take other measures to further ease monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   So alarmed was the bank by what it perceived as a severe
misunderstanding of its position that Masaru Hayami, the bank's
governor, held a hastily called news conference a day later to deny
that the bank had signaled a major departure from its policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5915 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-FREE-ON-INTERNET-930(     10-13 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREE-ON-INTERNET-930(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET OFFERING MORE ITEMS FOR FREE, BUT AT A PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, marketers have known that one word, more than any
other, can spur people to action.
</P>
<P>
   The magic word, of course, is ``free.'' And the wheels of
commerce havereased with free samples, free trial issues,
free toasters at the bank, or free tote bags with every bottle of
perfume.
</P>
<P>
   But those are nothing more than Cracker Jack prizes compared
with what's happening these days on the Internet, where the slogan
is quickly becoming: buy nothing, get everything free.
</P>
<P>
   ``You name it, and there is a start-up somewhere that wants to
give it away free,'' said James Breyer, the managing partner of
Accel Partners, a big Silicon Valley venture-capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   The World Wide Web, after all, took off because free browser
software enabled access to an ever-wider range of free information,
including all sorts of things like magazine articles and stock
quotes, that people had been accustomed to paying for.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with hundreds of Internet start-ups hellbent on immediate
visibility and rapid growth, the giveaways have moved beyond
information into products and services that sometimes cost hundreds
of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with nothing more than a computer hooked up to the
Internet, you can download a word-processing program or a recording
of a hit single, sign up for a new phone number to receive faxes
and voice mail, and organize your Rolodex and expense-account forms
_ all without paying a penny.
</P>
<P>
   You can even find a site that will set you up in business with
your own online store free, if you can think of something to sell
that people will pay for.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to take advantage of this costless cornucopia but
are not yet wired to the Web, don't despair. A bunch of companies
want to provide free Internet access. FreePC.com hopes to give away
a computer too. And if you need to communicate with your militantly
unwired Uncle Waldo, postage4free.com will send you a stack of
stamped envelopes, gratis.
</P>
<P>
   All this free stuff comes at a price, of course. Those free
envelopes are covered with advertising, and so are most of the
other free offers. To get freebies, customers often must also
disclose a dossier's worth of personal information for use by
marketers and put up with minimal customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone wants to listen to 30 seconds of commercials to
make a free two-minute long-distance call, as offered by
mytalk.com. But enough of these deals are attracting enough
customers that the free offers keep coming, despite questions about
whether there will be enough advertising to support many more such
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   MyTalk is hardly striking fear in the heart of AT&AMP;T, but other
giveaways are already roiling certain markets.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in Internet service providers are scared by the
prospect of free competitors. And relatively few companies are
developing new software programs because so many functions can now
be performed on the Web free.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are markets that could be spoiled,'' said Gill Cogan, a
general partner with the venture-capital arm of Weiss, Peck &AMP;
Greer. ``After you give something away free, it is very difficult
to start charging for it, or even for other things.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend is being driven by the ever-plummeting prices on
computers and communications, which make it so inexpensive to offer
many of these services that it makes as much sense to give them
away covered in ads as it does to try to sell them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general rule is that anything that has a potential for a
broad audience will eventually be free,'' said Joe Kraus, a
co-founder of the Excite service, which searches the Web free and
now also offers free e-mail, voice mail, auctions, classified ads,
chat rooms and a small library's worth of information. Ultimately,
he said, companies would rather have consumers' time than their
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are shifting from a retail economy to what I call an
attention economy,'' Kraus said. ``You are willing to give away
services or even pay people to use services, if you can get a lot
of people listening to your message.''
</P>
<P>
   Marketers have always looked to place ads in new and prominent
locations, but the popularity of the Internet has given rise to
hundreds of new companies with rich backers, desperately racing to
get lots of new customers right away, even if they do not know
exactly how they will make money from them.
</P>
<P>
   Many newer start-ups look to the example of Hotmail, the first
big Web site offering free e-mail with advertising. In 18 months,
Hotmail signed up 11 million customers. And even though it never
made much selling advertising, Microsoft bought it for some $400
million.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Draper, of the venture-capital firm of Draper Fisher
Jervetson, Hotmail's early backer, said he is so convinced that
free services are the way to build really big businesses that he
has invested in a variety of others, including free Web sites, free
disk space and free Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe that the Web is opening up a whole new world
economy where there will be a lot of winners, what you want to do
is back one of the 30 companies that ends up being worth a trillion
dollars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is so sure that the way to make a trillion dollars
is to give away the most stuff free.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an unwarranted frenzy around the free model on the
internet,'' said Breyer of Accel Partners, who argues that there
just isn't enough money to be made in advertising to justify most
of these companies. ``In most cases, if one does the math, the
business assumptions simply will not hold up and the companies are
pursuing suicidal strategies.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One site challenging that premise is Free-PC.com, which has to
sell about $30 a month in advertising to cover the costs of a
computer and Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Donald S. La Vigne, its chief executive, maintains that the
prominent placement of the ads, in strips along two sides of the
screen, and the data the company collects observing how its
customers use the machine, will help increase sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone goes to E-Loan and four other housing sites in one
week, it's a good bet they're shopping for a mortgage,'' he said.
``Banks will pay a lot of money to find someone in the market for a
home loan.'' Still, the company will wait to see how this idea
works on 30,000 computers before it gives away more.
</P>
<P>
   The hurdle for NetZero and other companies that want to offer
free Internet service is almost as high. It costs about $10 a month
to cover the telecommunications cost of Internet access. So far the
biggest Internet service, America Online, takes in only about $5
monthly per user from ads, on top of its $22 monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street appears to have fewer doubts. With 900,000 active
accounts, NetZero is now worth $3.2 billion, after its public
offering earlier this month. That compares to Earthlink, a big
internet servce provider with 1.5 million paying customers, that
investors value at $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Implicit in Wall Street's thinking is that millions of consumers
are willing to make their homes, or at least their computers, look
like the logo-covered outfield wall of a major league ballpark. So
far they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average consumer gets 3,000 marketing messages a day,'' La
Vigne. ``That doesn't mean they like it, but they are used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, these Internet sites are riding a cultural shift, in
which more people embrace rather than fight commercialism.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in this generation are not as concerned with
advertising as older people,'' said Bo Peabody, 28, the founder of
Tripod, an online gathering place for Generation X now owned by
Lycos. ``We feel that everybody has an agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the sales pitch is very subtle. Onebox is a start-up
that is offering free voice mail with no visible advertising. It
hopes to profit ultimately selling a premium service linked to
people's home telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   ``It costs long distance companies $100 to $300 to get a new
customer,'' said Bill Nguyen (pronounced win), the company's
founder. ``Our free service costs less than $2 to provide. If one
person in 50 ever pays us, we will make a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   There are already myriad examples where free services on the
Internet are eating into lucrative markets. Five years ago, for
example, 40 percent of the revenue of Dow Jones &AMP; Co.'s online unit
came from news headlines and stock quotes it sold for 25 cents per
quote. Now hundreds of sites give those away free.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, it took two years for a company called Jfax to
attract 35,000 customers to its nifty $12-a-month service that
forwards faxes to an e-mail address. Earlier this year, a rival
called Efax introduced a service that is similar, but free, and to
date has a million customers. Jfax was forced to respond with its
own free service.
</P>
<P>
   An even higher stakes battle is occurring over Internet
auctions. EBay, the auction leader, charges a fee of 2 to 5
percent. But Yahoo is gaining ground with totally free auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo is getting the same treatment in reverse in its business
that charges $100 a month and up for a business to set up a store
on the Internet. Now services like BigStep.com and FreeMerchant.com
will do all that without charge.
</P>
<P>
   Another free scheme meant to bite into Yahoo and the other
popular Internet sites is Rocketboard, acompany that hopes to give
free keyboards, with 18 extra buttons that send the user to certain
online stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The portals now have the ocean front views, but with
Rocketboard, we are putting up a building that is closer to the
water,'' said Scott Heiferman, the company's founder.
</P>
<P>
   Where does the free frenzy end? Venture capitalists say that
entrepreneurs are now trying to raise money for everything from
free cell phones to free movies to free stock trades. But so far,
there is little inclination to give away such basic, nondigital
commodities or services as food, shelter and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, someone has to sell something, or its all a shell
game,'' Kraus of Excite said. ``The car companies are never go to
give away free cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Or will they? Draper, the venture capitalist, said the idea may
not be as crazy as it sounds. ``It's a captive audience,'' he
remarked. ``If you control my radio while I'm driving, keep track
of where I go with a global positioning system, and maybe do
something with my cell phone, there's a possibility you might be
willing to pay $50,000 to own me for two hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   And yes, someone has already registered the Internet address
free-cars.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
