<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOBEL-ECON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMBIA UNIVERSITY ECONOMIST WINS NOBEL PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Mundell of Columbia University on Wednesday won the Nobel
Memorial Prize in economics for bringing the international economy
into Keynesian economics and vice versa in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   A decade before they became everyday (and sometimes
overwhelming) facts of economic life, he introduced foreign trade,
capital movements, and currency swings into formal analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Mundell's long years during the 1970s and 1980s as a shadowy
expositor of ``supply-side'' economics and an enthusiast of the
gold standard, were overlooked by the prize committee _ or ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``His work on monetary dynamics and optimum currency areas has
inspired generations of researchers,'' the Royal Swedish Academy of
Sciences said. ``Although dating back several decades, Mundell's
contributions remain outstanding and constitute the core of
teaching in internatioroeconomics.''
</P>
<P>
   In London on Wednesday, Mundell told the Associated Press,
``It's a measure of the respect that colleagues around the world
have for me, and I'm very pleased with that recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1932 in Kingston, Ontario, Mundell received his
undergraduate education at the University of British Columbia and
the University of Washington. He began his graduate studies at the
London school of Economics and completed them at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, where he received his PhD in 1956. From
1961 to 1963, he served as chief economist for the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the early 1960s that he published the two seminal
papers cited by the academy. In ``A Theory of Optimum Currency
Areas'' in 1961, he argued that under certain circumstances it
might not make sense for a nation to maintain its own currency. He
boldly anticipated the arguments for the European Monetary Union
and the ``dollarization'' of smaller economies around the world,
and created a framework for analyzing such decisions.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Capital Mobility and Stabilization Policy Under Fixed and
Flexible Exchange Rates'' _ published in 1963 in the relatively
obscure Canadian Journal of Economics _ he tied together a number
of previously confusing factors in an elegant but not overly formal
analysis that became known in time as the Mundell-Fleming model
(IMF economist Marcus Fleming, who developed a similar approach,
died in 1976).
</P>
<P>
   It became the workhorse for policy analysis, relating currency
swings and interest rates to fiscal and monetary policies.
</P>
<P>
   Mundell then became a key figure in the debates between the
University of Chicago and MIT. In ``Man and Economics,'' a primer
published in 1968, he began with characteristic unpredictability,
brilliance, and charm:
</P>
<P>
   ``Economics in the science of choice. It began with Aristotle
but got mixed up with ethics in the Middle Ages. Adam Smith
seperated it from ethics, and Walras mathematized it. Alfred
Marshall tried to narrow it, and Keynes made it fashionable.
Robbins widened it, and Samuelson dynamized it. But modern science
made it statistical and tried to confine it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the science won't stay put. It keeps cropping up all over
the place. There is an economics of money and trade, of production
and consumption, of distribution and development. There is also an
economics of welfare, of manners, language, industry, music, and
art. There is an economics of war and an economics of power. There
is even an economics of love.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1966 until 1971, Mundell was a professor at the University
of Chicago. There he matched wits with Harry Johnson, another
expositor of the monetary approach to the balance of payments, and
taught many of the best of the next generation of international
economists, including Rudiger Dornbusch, Stanley Fischer, and Jacob
Frenkel.
</P>
<P>
   At a certain point, however, he lost interest in university
life. He left Chicago for a summer job teaching in Italy. He bought
a ruined castle near Siena. He grew his hair long and rarely spoke
above a whisper.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago he had struck up a friendship with a young assistant
professor named Arthur Laffer. They shared a fascination with the
tax cuts of President John F. Kennedy that Mundell had witnessed
during his years in Washington. Before long, they were propounding
a global view on economics in an inceasingly integrated world and a
recipe of tax cuts and tight money for stimulating economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of systematically publishing their views in scholarly
journals, however, the pair sought out policy makers and gave
newspaper interviews. Laffer took a job as chief economist at the
Office of Management and Budget in the Nixon administration.
Mundell returned to the United States and a professorship at
Columbia in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   A young newspaper editorialist for the Wall Street Journal named
Jude Wanniski ecountered the pair. The technical virtuosity of a
decade earlier was diluted until it became a curve written on a
cocktail napkin describing ``supply-side economics.''.
</P>
<P>
   After Ronald Reagan was elected president in 1980, Mundell
remained aloof from Washington, relying mainly on his friendship
with Federal Reserve chairman Paul Volcker (who had been his
opposite number at the Treasury Department during his IMF years) to
stay in touch. The ``supply-siders'' were quickly replaced by a new
generation of internationally oriented conservative economists led
by Harvard's Martin Feldstein and trained, for the most part, by
Mundell's students.
</P>
<P>
   In an early example of ``country-doctoring,'' Mundell consulted
to the Central Bank of Uruguay for a time. And in a clear signal
that he was returning to his professional responsibilities in the
early 1990s, he helped organize the American Economic Association
meetings after his old and out-of-touch Columbia colleague (and
fellow Canadian) William Vickrey was elected president. (Vickrey
died a few days after he shared the Nobel Prize a few years later.)
</P>
<P>
   Wanniski, now a political consultant and adviser to presidential
aspirant Steve Forbes, Wednesday exulted in an open letter to
Laffer, ``What great news, Art, that our boy is finally recognized
. . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Mundell told reporters he planned to use some of the prize money
(it comes to $960,000) to repair his Italian castle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
