u e BC-BOOK-AWARDS-NYT &LR;      10-13 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK AWARD FINALISTS ANNOUNCED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Finalists were announced Wednesday for the 50th
annual National Book Awards, with the list an unusually diverse one
featuring books on subjects as varied as postwar Japan and an
American Indian girl on a remote island in Lake Superior.
</P>
<P>
   The awards will be given at a dinner on Nov. 17 at the Marriott
Marquis Hotel in Manhattan celebrating the 50th anniversary of the
prizes' sponsor, the National Book Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Among the nominees are Ha Jin, a former member of the People's
Liberation Army in China, for his novel ``Waiting'' (Pantheon),
about a man caught between the demands of two women and two worlds,
and Ai (whose real name is Florence Anthony), a poet of urban life
who is part African-American, Asian-American and Native American,
for her book ``Vice: New and Selected Poems'' (W.W. Norton).
</P>
<P>
   As is often the case, the list was as notable for the books not
included as for those that were. Not nominated was ``Dutch,'' a
highly publicized biography of Ronald Reagan by Edmund Morris that
has been criticized for mingling fact and fiction, and `` 'Tis,''
the sequel to Frank McCourt's Pulitzer Prize-winning memoir,
``Angela's Ashes.'' `` 'Tis'' has been received by critics with
less enthusiasm than the first book.
</P>
<P>
   The nominees included a winner from a previous year, Judith
Thurman, who was cited this year for her biography ``Secrets of the
Flesh: A Life of Colette'' (Alfred A. Knopf). The poet Louise
Gluck, who was a finalist in 1992, was nominated this year for
``Vita Nova: Poems'' (The Ecco Press).
</P>
<P>
   The foundation said that this year it had considered the authors
of 881 books from a record 207 publishing imprints, despite
consolidations in the book industry. Each finalist will receive a
bronze medallion and $1,000. Winners get $10,000 each and a crystal
sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Martin will be the master of ceremonies at the
foundation's 50th-anniversary gala on Nov. 17. Oprah Winfrey is
also scheduled to receive a gold medal for her contributions to
reading and to books.
</P>
<P>
   The full list of nominees follows.
</P>
<P>
   FICTION
</P>
<P>
   ``House of Sand and Fog'' (W.W. Norton) by Andre Dubus 3d
</P>
<P>
   ``Waiting'' (Pantheon) by Ha Jin
</P>
<P>
   ``Plainsong'' (Alfred A. Knopf) byaruf
</P>
<P>
   ``Hummingbird House'' (MacMurray &AMP; Beck) by Patricia Henley
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Do You Love?'' (Harcourt Brace &AMP; Co.), a short-story
collection by Jean Thompson
</P>
<P>
   POETRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Vita Nova: Poems'' (Ecco Press) by Louise Gluck
</P>
<P>
   ``Vice: New and Selected Poems'' (W.W. Norton) by Ai
</P>
<P>
   ``Configurations: New &AMP; Selected Poems 1958-1998'' (Copper
Canyon Press) by Clarence Major
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pilot Star Elegies'' (W.W. Norton &AMP; Co.) by Sherod Santos
</P>
<P>
   ``Repair'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux) by C.K. Williams
</P>
<P>
   NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   ``Secrets of the Flesh: A Life of Colette'' by Judith Thurman
</P>
<P>
   ``Woman: an Intimate Geography'' (A Peter Davison Book/Houghton
Mifflin) by Natalie Angier, a science writer for The New York Times
</P>
