<SLUG> BC-CELLPHONE-INTERNET-VENTURE-490&AMP;ADD(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALM ANNOUNCES PARTNERSHIP TO DEVELOP CELLPHONE INTERNET STANDARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Forging an ambitious alliance to create a de facto
standard for wireless Internet access, the Palm Computing unit of
3Com Corp. on Wednesday announced a partnership with Symbian, a
joint venture of the wireless phone makers Nokia, Motorola,
Ericsson, Psion and Matsushita.
</P>
<P>
   The move is a serious blow to Microsoft Corp., whose Windows CE
operating system for hand-held devices has failed to make headway
against Palm Computing's Palm operating system in the United States
or Psion's Epoc operating system in Europe. Microsoft has sought to
gain support for Windows CE from cellular phone manufacturers, but
Wednesday's announcement makes it very unlikely that Windows CE
will be widely used in mobile phones anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Nokia, the world's largest manufacturer of wireless phones, said
it would be the first to make a model combining the Palm and
Symbian operating systems. The phone is to be introduced in 2001,
first in the United States. Nokia said it would be ``pen-based,''
meaning that users would enter text by writing on its screen
surface with a stylus.
</P>
<P>
   While the new Nokia phone will use an interface similar to that
of Palm's successful hand-held digital assistants, Symbian's Epoc
operating system, originally created by Psion for its hand-held
devices, will run the phone's data communication functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Combining Nokia's undisputed expertise in the wireless
industry and Symbian's robust and effective platform with Palm
Computing's industry-leading application environment and
user-interface strengths gives the customers the best solution in
this new product category,'' said Nokia chief executive Jorma
Ollila. .
</P>
<P>
   The alliance is Palm's first major licensing agreement since
3Com said in September it would spin off the company early next
year. Palm has already made a major foray into mobile Internet
access with its Palm VII, which offers electronic mail and limited
World Wide Web services. It also has a licensing agreement with
Qualcomm, which makes a mobile phone that doubles as a digital day
planner.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Palm said in September that it was licensing its operating
system to Handspring, a start-up company that recently released its
first Palm-based device, and to TRG, which is expected to introduce
its first product next week. Palm is increasingly looking to
license its operating system as a way to protect its market share,
especially in devices that do not compete directly with its own
products.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the alliance was a major victory for Palm in its
market war against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great for Palm because it gives it a good footprint into
Europe and expands their licensees,'' said Michael Kleeman, an
independent telecommunications consultant in San Francisco.
Referring to Windows CE, he added: ``Any time an emerging standard
loses a potential customer, it becomes a problem. I'd be
concerned.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Reacting to news of the alliance, Jonathan Roberts, general
manager for Windows CE market development, defended the Microsoft
product at the Geneva telecommunication trade fair. ``We are
gaining greater expertise in this space,'' Roberts told Reuters.
``As you get to a richer set of services, we become more
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   The joint venture is also a major achievement for Epoc, which
has been desperate to fend off competition from Palm and Microsoft
as it seeks to become the standard operating system for wireless
phones. The Palm alliance makes it almost certain that Epoc will be
running the underlying operations of most next-generation cellular
phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adding Palm computing functionality to Symbian's robust and
scalable wireless platform will result in new types of devices,
providing both Symbian and Palm developers with a compelling new
opportunity,'' said Symbian chief executive Colly Myers. .
</P>
</TEXT>
