<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERFECTSTORM-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERFECT JOB ON A CHILLING SUBJECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This month's celebrity author: Patricia Cornwell
</P>
<P>
   Her selection: ``The Perfect Storm'' by Sebastian Junger
</P>
<P>
   ``The Perfect Storm''
</P>
<P>
   By Sebastian Junger
</P>
<P>
   Nonfiction
</P>
<P>
   HarperPaperbacks, $6.99
</P>
<P>
   Given her emphasis on research and her detailed explanations of
complicated subjects, it's no surprise that Patricia Cornwell chose
Sebastian Junger's ``The Perfect Storm'' as the featured title for
October in the ``Star-Telegram's'' monthly book club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junger's book is nonfiction, of course, but he does such a
wonderful job of taking the reader right into the middle of it,''
says Cornwell, whose novels featuring coroner Kay Scarpetta
consistently top national bestseller lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It,'' of course, is the so-called Halloween Gale, a murderous
storm that, in late October 1991, blew a New England fishing boat
called the Andrea Gail into a watery grave somewhere off the coast
of Sable Island in the Atlantic Ocean. All six members of the crew
were lost.
</P>
<P>
   Many other ships and crews have died tragically at sea; books
have been written about those storms and sinkings, too, but none
has had reader and sales impact like ``The Perfect Storm.'' This is
because Junger, a frequent contributing writer to several
outdoor-oriented magazines, does such a superb job of teaching
readers, in a compelling way, just how storms at sea occur and why
the Halloween Gale in particular grew into terrifying proportions
seldom experienced anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Junger acknowledges in his book's introduction that no one can
be certain when the Andrea Gail went down, and how its captain and
crew may have tried to get through the storm that eventually killed
them. But Junger pieces things together through extensive
interviews with the crew's relatives and friends, and by relating
the experiences of other ships and crews that endured the Halloween
Gale without being relegated to the depths of the Atlantic. We end
up caring about the captain and his crew, even when Junger makes it
obvious that no saints were on board. Combined with the author's
masterful explanation of how wind and current can join into a
killer storm, his description of how the Andrea Gail's final
moments must have been spent is both horrifying and riveting; as
Cornwell says, you really can't put the book down.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Junger gets down to what had to have happened at the
end: how people drown.
</P>
<P>
   His descriptions of lungs full of seawater, of how the brain
fights to keep the body alive even when the mind has accepted
imminent death, are terrifyingly classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an easy way to die, not as painful as we might think it
is,'' says Cornwell, who worked in a coroner's office before
embarking on a full-time writing career. ``Junger captures that so
well; it's one of the most brilliant passages I've ever read.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the massive success of ``The Perfect Storm'' _ the book
spent six months on various bestseller lists _ publishers have
flocked to follow it with other titles about natural disasters.
Readers, it seems, are fascinated by the power of nature.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how many eminently readable copycat titles follow
it, Sebastian Junger's ``The Perfect Storm'' will probably be
remembered as the perfect book describing how the sea can overcome
human technology. We can invent all the wonderful boats and
superior onboard equipment we like; the sea is still all-powerful.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
