<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-MONSOON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Monsoon was a gorilla inside the ring, pussycat outside
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When it comes to old-school wrestling, very few names
are more recognizable than that of Gorilla Monsoon. On Oct. 6,
Gorilla Monsoon, 62, died at his home in Willingboro, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of wrestling, few have done more for longer than
Monsoon _ real name Bob Marella. He was a wrestler, announcer and
president of wrestling organizations for nearly 40 years. For
generations of wrestling fans Monsoon was either a scary wrestler,
or a bumbling announcer, or a legendary figure in pro wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   When Monsoon was Marella, he was a Rochester, N.Y., high school
star in football, wrestling and track and field. He went to Ithaca
(N.Y.) College, where he placed second in the 1959 NCAA national
wrestling championship. He still holds the school record for
fastest pin by a heavyweight. After school he was thinking of
joining the NFL but was approached by western New York promoter
Pedro Martinez. Marella made his in-ring debut at the Rochester War
Memorial in 1959 and won. But it wasn't until 1963 that Marella
became Gorilla Monsoon.
</P>
<P>
   Monsoon's story line was that he was being raised by a gypsy in
Manchuria. After years of hard work and being forced to wrestle
bears for other people's entertainment, he left for America, where
he ate raw meat and drank the blood of his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The gimmick worked as Monsoon was one of the most feared and
hated heels of the '60s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   But for many he was the prototypical gentle giant.
</P>
<P>
   I had the opportunity to meet Marella twice while attending
Ithaca College. He would stop by whenever he was in the area and
was very different from his in-ring persona. He was always smiling
and made people around him feel important.
</P>
<P>
   Pro athletes today could learn a lot from Marella. He performed
in pain, gave the fans a show and was extremely approachable, which
probably came from the fact he didn't take his job as seriously as
the fans in the stands did.
</P>
<P>
   After his in-ring career, Monsoon became an announcer famous for
making up body parts while describing wrestling moves. Eventually
he stepped away from the traveling grind and was semi-retired.
</P>
<P>
   Heart problems plagued Marella, who weighed around 400 pounds
during his wrestling career. A second heart attack eventually sent
him home, where he died with his family by his side.
</P>
<P>
   A quiet ending for a Monsoon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
