<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-WWF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Monday show proves why fans kept organization at the top of the
wrestling pile
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Popcorn, profanity, and flop sweat ruled the night as
35,000 wrestling fans packed the Georgia Dome for a ringside seat
at the biggest and baddest show on cable television _ the World
Wrestling Federation's ``Raw is War.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's live show and telecast took on added significance
because it was staged in the hometown of World Championship
Wrestling, the rival organization whose prime-time show ``Monday
Nitro'' on TNT has been getting a drubbing from WWF in the Nielsen
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Just moments after Monday night's shunder way, it became
clear that ``Raw'' would live up to its name.
</P>
<P>
   Bald-headed anti-hero ``Stone Cold'' Steve Austin entered the
ring, grabbed a microphone and explained to his screaming fans how
he planned to defeat his WWF nemesis, Triple H. His description and
the crowd's reaction involved several unprintable derivations
involving the human posterior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love Steve Austin,'' yelled Maria Walker, a warehouse
supervisor who was so excited by the show that she left her two
sons sitting alone two rows back. ``I'm not even sure what he said,
but it doesn't matter because he's Stone Cold.''
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd roared its approval, Austin showed his affection by
leaping on the ring ropes and flashing his patented two-fisted,
middle-finger salute, which made his fans cheer even louder.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Anderson, a 17-year-old high school student, said WWF has
been a hit with wrestling fans because their performers are younger
and their story lines are more outrageous and unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``WWF makes you feel what's in the wrestlers' hearts,'' said
Anderson, who added he never watches the WCW show on television.
``They're more fun to watch than WCW. If you don't like violence
and cursing, you shouldn't come and you shouldn't watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, WWF started whipping WCW in the ratings race, and
their dominance has continued unabated. WWF's Monday night show
``Raw is War'' has been the top-rated cable show on television
since January.
</P>
<P>
   While WWF has become the gold standard for professional
wrestling lately, it has had its share of triumphs and tragedies.
The WWF's profile got a boost after former grappler Jesse ``The
Body'' Ventura was elected governor of Minnesota. Since then
Ventura has participated in WWF bouts, serving as a referee during
one pay-per-view event.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the WWF announced it would issue an initial public
offering that is expected to raise $172 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the WWF took a serious body blow in May when wrestler Owen
Hart fell 78 feet to his death as he was being lowered into the
ring at an event at the Kemper Arena in Kansas City. Hart's family
is suing the organization in connection with the incident.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to cut into their competitor's ratings edge, WCW
recently hired Vince Russo and Ed Ferrara, writers who are credited
with creating the outrageous characters and story lines that have
been a hit with viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give us a little time and we will be back on top,'' says Alan
Sharp, a WCW spokesman. ``We will do that by depending on more
creative stories, superior athleticism and better TV production.
You can be creative without resorting to shock TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Russo and Ferrara were unavailable for comment, but during a
chat session last Tuesday on the WCW web site, they hinted at some
of the changes they had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that controversy is our middle name,''
Russo told a caller. ``If there's not controversy, we ain't happy.
We're going to get away with whatever they allow us to get away
with.'' Russo added that one of the innovations they are
considering is a ``Jell-O battle royal'' involving the WCW Nitro
Girls, a group of scantily clad dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Schwarz, a spokesman for the USA Network in New York,
downplayed the significance of Russo and Ferrara jumping ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys worked with Vince McMahon; he's the guy,'' Schwarz
said. ``We're confident that he will bring on more folks who will
continue to come up with new stories and characters that wrestling
viewers will want to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Doster, 35, didn't care about the behind-the-scenes
wrangling between the WCW and the WWF. And as she sat demurely in
the crowd Monday night, she didn't seem fazed by the bulging
spandex, foul language and testosterone-stoked fans. In her line of
work, it comes with the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no big deal _ people are just having a good time,''
said Doster, who works as a dancer for an Atlanta strip club.
``People sometimes get a little adrenaline rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
