<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-CANCER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS RACIAL GAP IN LUNG CANCER OPERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. surgeons operate less often on African-Americans with
early-stage lung cancer than on comparable white patients, a
disparity that mostly explains higher death rates among blacks with
potentially curable lung tumors.
</P>
<P>
   A new study documents the treatment gap, providing the most
compelling evidence so far that widespread and inexplicable racial
differences in medical care result in thousands of avoidable
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies had pointed to racial disparities in treatment,
but many of them involved procedures with debatable effects on
survival, such as coronary bypass surgery. However, nobody
disagrees that surgery to remove early-stage lung cancers offers
the only chance at a cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If black patients were to undergo surgery at a rate equal to
that of white patients, their survival rate would probably be
substantially improved and would approach that of white patients,''
the study's authors said in their report, which appears in this
week's New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the study may understate racial inequalities in lung
cancer treatment because it involved only patients who had enough
access to health care to receive an early diagnosis. Other data
show that blacks are more likely to get lung cancer and less likely
to be diagnosed at an early stage.
</P>
<P>
   The findings elicited strong reactions.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of bias among physicians, subconscious or not, is
``disheartening because we all believe that if our loved ones get
cancer, they will receive the best care possible,'' wrote Dr.
Talmadge E. King Jr. and Dr. Paul Brunetta of the University of
California at San Francisco, in an editorial accompanying the
study.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies showed that black Medicare beneficiaries,
compared to whites, undergo fewer than half as many heart bypass
operations or artery-opening angioplasty procedures. Black women
have 25 percent fewer mammograms than white women, and
African-American Medicare recipients overall have 16 percent higher
mortality rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data is coming from so many sources that it is hard even
with the best of conscience not to think that race is the factor,
be it conscious or unconscious,'' Dr. Walter W. Shervington of New
Orleans told the Associated Press. Shervington is president of the
National Medical Association, an organization of 20,000 black
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   However, a separate study, by the California-based Kaiser Family
Foundation, found that two-thirds of white Americans believe that
African-Americans are ``just as well or better off than the average
white person when it comes to getting routine medical care when
they need it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kaiser survey, based on a national poll of nearly 3,400
Americans, found that 51 percent of African-Americans believe
blacks are worse off when it comes to medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Bach of Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New
York, who led the new cancer study, was careful not to accuse
doctors of racism. ``I'm not convinced that I understand what's
going on,'' Bach said, saying further research is needed on such
questions as whether doctors are offering blacks surgery less
often, how they present patients' options, and whether black
patients have undue pessimism or cultural beliefs that incline them
against surgery for lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Bach and his colleagues at Sloan-Kettering and the National
Cancer Institute extracted their conclusion from nearly 11,000 lung
cancer patients over age 65 with potentially curable stage I and II
disease in five metropolitan areas and five entire states. All the
patients had so-called nonsmall cell cancer, which accounts for 70
percent of lung malignancies.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 170,000 Americans who receive lung cancer diagnoses
each year _ more than for any other malignancy _ about 34,000 are
diagnosed with nonsmall cell lung cancer early enough for surgeons
to aim for cure. Among those who get surgery at such a stage, 40
percent will be alive and free of disease five years later.
</P>
<P>
   If the new results were applied to two groups of 1,000 patients
with early-stage lung cancer _ one white and one black _ the
researchers said that 767 white patients would get surgery compared
to 640 blacks. At the end of five years, 341 white patients would
be alive versus 264 blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these 77 additional black deaths can be blamed on the
decision not to operate, according to Bach. ``We think we have
identified more than half of the explanation for why there's a
gap,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors besides lower surgical rates contributing to
higher mortality among African-Americans with lung cancer, Bach
said, include a generally lower life expectancy among blacks and
``other things that are probably not related to lung cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   One implication of the findings is that large improvements in
blacks' lung cancer survival rates could be made by applying
existing treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason for optimism here,'' Bach said. ``We think
we've identified a group of patients who could substantially
benefit with a treatment of known efficacy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
