A5928 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE-C     10-13 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 -GRAPEVINE-COX &HT;    Wrestling grapevine
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Biggest rumor this week is that Hulk Hogan is quitting WCW. All
week leading up to Monday's ``Nitro'' in Biloxi, Miss., rumors
circulated that Hogan had exercised his 90-day release clause.
After the ``Nitro'' show, in which Hogan hinted that he wasn't
going to be leaving right away but he wasn't happy with the current
situation, WCW Live reporters Bob Ryder and Mark Madden said Hogan
gave his notice two weeks ago and exercised his out clause. The
reason for Hogan's decision could stem from WCW's decision to hire
the main creative team behind the WWF's raunchy story lines _ Vince
Russo and Ed Ferrara. The duo joined the struggling WCW and have
been given free rein to set the organization on its ear, which
presumably means less of the older wrestlers like Hogan and more of
the younger wrestlers like Chris Benoit. That does not sit well
with Hogan, who has forced his way to be the main event since
joining the WCW after being out of wrestling for a year. While
battling the WCW for ratings, Russo and Ferrara have taken less
well-known talent and made stars such as Steve Austin, Triple H and
The Rock. They hope to do the same in the WCW with wrestlers like
Benoit, Kidman, Disco Inferno, Eddy Guerrero and Buff Bagwell. That
could change the product and leave less of a role for
headed-over-the-hill stars such as Hogan, Ric Flair, Bret Hart and
Macho Man Randy Savage. The duo will take over creative control the
day after the Oct. 24 ``Halloween Havoc'' pay-per-view. It's
interesting to note that while WCW has pushed Goldberg since Eric
Bischoff's ouster, Russo and Ferrara have not mentioned Goldberg as
one of the top young talents in the WCW.
</P>
<P>
   _ The WWF had another tragedy last week when Droz broke his neck
and was paralyzed after falling the wrong way after a move by
wrestler D'Lo Brown. A week later, the 30-year-old former NFL
player was still in the hospital and getting feeling back in
different parts of his body.
</P>
<P>
   _ It looks like Ken Shamrock's wrestling career is over. He will
not need surgery on his neck, but he has been advised to stay out
of the ring.
</P>
<P>
   _ WCW had a return to ``Old School'' on the Oct. 4 ``Nitro.''
Bret Hart's return to Kemper Arena, where his brother Owen was
killed this year, was highlighted by the longest match in ``Nitro''
history (over 27 minutes). Hart vs. Benoit was Bret's idea, even
though WCW offered him the chance not to even have to show at
Kemper. But Bret wanted it and wanted an old-style NWA match and
originally wanted Benoit to win. Creative forces changed the
ending, thinking the fans would rather see a Hart victory.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaking of Owen Hart, A&AMP;E expects to air a special biography
on the wrestler Nov. 16 at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ WCW's woes at the gate continue. Last week's ``Saturday
Night'' taping drew only 500 paying fans. Meanwhile, buy rate for
the ``Fall Brawl'' pay-per-view was a dismal .23, which is less
than 100,000 purchases. ECW's recent ``Anarchy Rulz'' topped that.
Last year's ``Fall Brawl'' had over 250,000 purchases.
</P>
<P>
   _ The main event is set for the WCW ``Mayhem'' pay-per-view Nov.
21 in Toronto. Bret Hart will take on the winner of the Sting-Hulk
Hogan match from ``Halloween Havoc.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The WWF has not been happy with the performances of two former
WCW wrestlers _ The Big Show and Chris Jericho. Both may continue
their fall down the low-to-mid-card status until they get more over
with the fans.
</P>
<P>
   _ Announcer Mean Gene Okerlund has re-signed with the WCW for
three more years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sting is asking WCW officials to let him turn face. He doesn't
feel the fans are buying him as a heel.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
