<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5929 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-HONDURAS-HURRICANE-AR     10-13 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDURAS-HURRICANE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGACY HURRICANE MITCH: POOR MUST WALK ACROSS BRIDGES IN   HONDURAS
CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras _ The bus from Boulevard Suyapa had barely
pulled to a stop when Heriberto Herrera jumped off and began his
way to work through a wearying and familiar maze. First he walked a
block to La Isla bridge, which crosses the Rio Chiquito, a slender
river whose churning currents are the color of milk chocolate. Then
he squeezed past dozens of sidewalk vendors selling everything from
toothpaste to lottery tickets, sometimes stepping out onto the road
and gingerly dodging a steady caravan of cabs and sedans. Then he
walked some more. Uphill.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, after winds and floods from Hurricane Mitch damaged
scores of bridges throughout Honduras, buses were banned from
crossing the spans linking Tegucigalpa's outlying neighborhoods to
its historic center and thousands of people were forced to make
walking part of their daily and extended commute. People who had to
go from one end of the city to another suddenly confronted the
vexing reality of two-fare zones, since they had to get off one
bus, walk through downtown, then pay to board another bus. Nearly a
year later, the bus ban and the ensuing frustrating routine remain
in effect.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera, a typographer, said he resents the fact that after a
nation-battering catastrophe like ``El Mitch,'' the government has
created more hardships for the throngs of poor and working-class
bus riders while continuing to cater to the relatively fortunate
few with the time or money for cabs or cars that carry only a
handful of passengers each.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say the bridges are no good, but that's a lie,'' Herrera
said, watching as taxis and private cars crept over the bridge at
La Isla. ``Even before Hurricane Mitch they wanted to stop the
routes at the edge to protect the millionaires. The millionaires
have their own cars. But those of us who work in the center have to
walk.''
</P>
<P>
   His gripes were not off base, because although the capital's
bridges have been deemed largely safe, city officials have no
intentions of letting the buses back in. In fact, the emergency
measures taken after the hurricane allowed city officials to carry
out long-standing plans to bar buses from the central district's
incredibly congested and narrow streets, which were laid out during
the horse and buggy era.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stop in the center of the capital at any hour, even
without the buses the traffic cannot move,'' said Nany de Flores, a
spokeswoman for the mayor of Tegucigalpa. ``The fleet of taxis has
grown from 2,500 to 6,000 since Mitch. It is a total block without
the buses. The day the buses enter the center, the city would be
paralyzed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Adrian Matamoros, an electrician who now spends twice as
much time and money for his commute, wonders about another kind of
paralysis, namely the fear that old people or women with children
must face as they walk through packed streets by day or darkened
sidewalks at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``A neighbor of mine was walking in the street with her child
and she was almost hit by a car,'' he said. ``I heard of other
people having their earrings or watches stolen. Before, when the
buses went through the center of the city you did not have that
problem. You could go from one side of the city to the other
without getting off.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many people, he has to leave an hour earlier if he wants to
get anywhere on time. Some take it, well, in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it's good,'' said Ruben Martinez, a retired translator.
``I'm old and I need the exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   He then lighted a cigarette and began his walk into town.
</P>
<P>
   However, there's nothing good about paying double, which is what
Idalia Euraque has to do to get to her job at a downtown archive.
She's usually late getting to work and coming home. Still, she
agreed that the buses should not cross the bridges.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say the pavement is weak,'' she said, pointing to the
Puente Mallol, which connects the market area in Comayaguela with
Tegucigalpa. ``Look at this pavement, the asphalt is almost gone.
It is pure stone.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the capital has fared better than other parts of the
country, where public works officials say 128 bridges were knocked
out by the hurricane, affecting some 70 percent of the road
network. With the cost of rebuilding estimated at more than $450
million, most places will have to make do with temporary metal or
culvert bridges. In some parts of the country, people have to walk
over trees that have been laid across rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Several new bridges are planned for Tegucigalpa, as well as yet
another rerouting of buses. Yet despite the numbers and needs of
commuters, no officials are suggesting what mass transportation
advocates have long urged in other countries: banning private cars
from downtown rather than buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we cannot go into the city, why should private cars?'' said
Jose Maldonado, a bus driver taking a break. ``The buses are for
the poor. I have been in 10 countries and that's how it is. They
leave the cars outside of the center and let the buses pass. Here,
it's the reverse.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they were planning a campaign to encourage people
to park their cars near the downtown bridges. Already, heavy trucks
are limited to making deliveries only between 6 p.m. and 7 a.m.
Officials are also collaborating with French consultants on
building bus stops closer to the bridges, on land reclaimed from
the riverbanks with stairs leading up to the bridge entrances _
from which they would walk into town.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with street vendors like Jorge Anaribe, who sells
shorts and shirts from a blanket he spreads on the sidewalk leading
to La Isla bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Since the ban on bus crossings took effect, he said, his sales
have increased tenfold.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it's good because everybody has to get off the bus,''
he said. ``Before, the buses passed by on their way to the center
and that hurt my sales.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing that hurts him now is the rain. Farther
down the street, Romulo Isaias was ready for anything. On hot days
he sells water. On rainy days he sells umbrellas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have everything,'' he said. ``You are born to die. So while
you live, you work.''
</P>
<P>
   And watch the people walk on by.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
