u w BC-CONGRESS-MEDICARE-810     10-13 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-MEDICARE-810(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESCRIPTION DRUG COVERAGE NOT AMONG MEDICARE INCREASES PROPOSED BY
REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senior Republicans in Congress proposed Wednesday
to restore some of the money they cut from Medicare in 1997, but
they said they had no plans to provide prescription drug benefits
to the elderly this year.
</P>
<P>
   Under immense pressure from the health care industry, the
Republican lawmakers said they would soon pass legislation to
increase Medicare payments to hospitals, nursing homes, outpatient
clinics, home health care agencies, doctors and health maintenance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But they said they did not have enough time this year to address
the top priority of many elderly people: Medicare coverage of
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   On June 29, Clinton unveiled an ambitious plan to redesign
Medicare. Drug benefits for the elderly were the keystone of that
plan. Overall, the plan was the most significant health care
proposal advanced by the president since Congress rejected his plan
to guarantee health insurance for all Americans in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Jennings, the health policy coordinator at the White
House, said Wednesday night: ``The president certainly would have
preferred to do broader reforms in the Medicare program, including
prescription drug benefits, this year. He is not giving up. He will
continue to work with Congress to achieve that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., who is chairman of the House Ways
and Means Subcommittee on Health, said he had ruled out new
initiatives this year and was trying only to solve problems created
by the last big budget-cutting law, the Balanced Budget Act of
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our basic principles was `no new starts,''' Thomas said
in announcing his proposals Wednesday. ``Pretty obviously
prescription drugs are an important benefit that needs to be added
in the context of overall reform of Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, such changes will have to wait till next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare proposals were unveiled separately by Thomas and
Sen. William Roth Jr., R-Del., who is chairman of the Senate
Finance Committee. Neither man said how he would pay for his
proposals, other than by using some of the federal budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists for nursing homes and home health agencies said they
liked the House proposals better than the Senate proposals. But
teaching hospitals strongly prefer the Senate proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, the ranking Democrat
on the Finance Committee, was a co-author of the Senate proposals.
Moynihan's concerns were reflected in a proposal to provide
teaching hospitals with a big infusion of Medicare money.
</P>
<P>
   In restoring money cut from Medicare in 1997, the House and
Senate bills both go further than Clinton has proposed.
Administration officials have been clear on the question of whether
the 1997 cuts are harming hospitals and other health care
providers, as the industry contends.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on July 21, Clinton said, ``The cuts in
Medicare were far more severe'' than he or Congress expected.
``That's why you've got all these hospitals all over America, every
place I go, talking about how they are threatened with
bankruptcy,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But the president's comments have not been translated into
action by his administration. Officials at the White House Office
of Management and Budget and the Federal Health Care Financing
Administration, which runs Medicare, say that the financial
problems of hospitals and nursing homes have been caused by many
factors other than Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 law cut the growth of Medicare by $115 billion over
five years. Thomas' proposals would restore $15 billion over five
years. Roth's plan would restore $12 billion to $14 billion over 10
years. The Clinton administration has proposed restoring $7.5
billion over 10 years. Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the
Democratic floor leader, has introduced a bill to restore $20
billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said the president could take action on his own to soften
the impact of the 1997 cuts. House Republicans are prodding Clinton
to restore $5.6 billion to Medicare through more generous
interpretations of the law, without action by Congress. That sum
accounts for more than one-third of the $15 billion that House
Republicans want to see restored to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth E. Raske, president of the Greater New York Hospital
Association, welcomed the Senate proposal. Congressional aides said
Thomas' plan would provide teaching hospitals with $300 million to
$500 million over five years, while the Roth-Moynihan proposal
would provide $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that the hue and cry from teaching hospitals is
being heard by the Senate Finance Committee,'' Raske said. ``The
Roth-Moynihan proposal could hold off the pain and bloodletting
that would otherwise occur as a result of the Balanced Budget Act.
Under the Senate proposal, there would be no further erosion of
medical education payments over the next four years.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Medicare beneficiaries say that one of the most troublesome
features of the 1997 law is a set of limits on the therapy services
they can receive under Medicare. The government will pay no more
than $1,500 a year for physical therapy and $1,500 for occupational
and speech therapy combined.
</P>
<P>
   Roth would replace these limits with a ceiling of $3,500 a year
for all three types of therapy. Thomas would allow a combined total
of $4,500 a year in therapy services, with $1,500 for each of the
three categories. In addition, under Thomas' proposal, 1 percent of
patients receiving therapy _ the sickest patients with the most
severe needs _ would be exempted from the limits.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Keegan, vice president of the American Health Care
Association, which represents 12,000 nursing homes, said the Thomas
proposals were more helpful than the Roth proposals, which she
described as ``wholly inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Balanced Budget Act, Medicare payments to home health
agencies will be cut by 15 percent in October next year, just as
the government is scheduled to adopt a new reimbursement formula.
Thomas would re-examine the need for the cut and would delay it by
at least one year. Under Roth's proposal, the 15 percent cut would
take effect gradually over three years.
</P>
<P>
   Mara Benner, executive director of a trade group, the Home
Health Services and Staffing Association, said Thomas' proposal was
much better than Roth's proposal, which she said would provide only
``minimal help'' to home health agencies. Her group represents
1,500 such agencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
