<HEADER>
A5932 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-13 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: GORE HAS IT MADE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The thing is, Al Gore should be _ even now, even with
all the trouble he's seen, the jokes he's spawned, the missteps
he's made _ unbeatable in the race for the Democratic nomination
for president. Even with his campaign limping embarrassingly along,
he should be able to beat Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   He's got Big Labor behind him. He's got hundreds of
superdelegates _ party chieftains and other assorted big shots _
already committed to him, with hundreds more ready to get on board.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have scrapped the winner-take-all primaries and
gone to a system of proportional representation. So even if Gore
loses some key states to Bradley, the vice president would still
pick up a substantial number of delegates from those states.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has the advantage in California at the moment, and he'll
certainly do well in the South. So it would seem virtually
impossible for Bradley to prevent Gore from accumulating the 2,167
delegates he needs to secure the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the smart money will tell you that Bill Bradley is
peaking too soon, that he was better off as the stealth candidate,
hoarding his money and keeping expectations as low as possible for
as long as possible. The spotlight found him three or four months
too early. The barbarians in the media are ready to pounce.
</P>
<P>
   But if all of this is such bad news for Bradley, why are so many
Gore supporters so ill at ease?
</P>
<P>
   There is a very dangerous divide developing for the Democrats as
the primary season approaches. Al Gore has just about locked up the
official support. He's been endorsed by more than 100 members of
Congress and by Democratic officeholders from coast to coast. He is
the candidate of the Democratic establishment. He's already won
that primary.
</P>
<P>
   But the voters are another matter. Gore is not connecting with
the people and time is running out.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's supporters insist it will be awfully tough,
no matter what happens, for Bradley to steal the nomination. But
they are speaking openly, if not always for attribution, about
their dismay at seeing Gore struggling day after day to establish a
reasonably comfortable relationship with potential voters, the kind
of ordinary rapport that is second nature to most politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's painful to watch,'' said one aide. ``It's like he was
born without the ability to be spontaneous. He's trying so hard,
but it's not working.''
</P>
<P>
   More bad news came Wednesday when a poll in Connecticut, thought
by Gore's people to be friendly turf, showed Bradley leading the
vice president by 51 to 34 percent. The poll was conducted by
Quinnipiac College. A similar poll in June showed the vice
president ahead of Bradley by 47 to 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In private conversations, several top Gore supporters said they
didn't think Bradley would win the nomination, but they could
imagine a scenario in which he might. One key aide put Bradley's
chances at 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley would have to use the early primaries, concentrated in
the Northeast, as a springboard. New Hampshire's primary is Feb. 1.
Then, on March 7, come New York, California, Maine, Vermont,
Massachusetts, Rhode Island, Connecticut, Maryland, Georgia, Ohio
and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's people say they expect the vice president to do well in
those primaries, but even if he doesn't they are building a
``firewall'' in the South. On March 14 there are primaries in
Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi, Gore's home state of Tennessee,
Texas, Oklahoma and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   The danger for Gore is that if he does not find a way to begin
connecting with voters, Bradley may change the whole dynamic of the
race before the Southern primaries come into play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say Bradley does well in the Northeast,'' said Lee Miringoff,
director of the Marist College Institute for Public Opinion in
Poughkeepsie. ``And say the bookends topple, with Gore losing both
New York and California. That would be a cataclysmic, defining
event. The question on the news would be, `How can Gore win the
nomination?'''
</P>
<P>
   That's the best-case scenario for Bradley. The worst-case
scenario for Democrats is that Gore hangs on and wins the
nomination, but never finds that real connection with the voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1944EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5934 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-13 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE YEAR OF DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the coming year, with no White House incumbent
to vote for or against, we'll be basing our nomination and election
decisions largely on how candidates impress us in the televised
debates.
</P>
<P>
   The first match-up will be the Democrats Gore vs. Bradley.
Front-runners are usually reluctant to debate, for good reason: It
gives challengers an audience. Because the front-runner, Al Gore,
now knows he is in a scrap and is eager to appear the underdog, the
newly energized vice president has already challenged Bill Bradley
to a series of debates.
</P>
<P>
   The cool former senator is in no hurry to engage. He runs by his
own internal clock and pays no mind to either the importuning of
the press for specific positions or the call from Gore to respond
to his revitalization needs. In a month, however, after his
necessary foreign policy address to some New York forum, ducking
debate would make him appear weak or arrogant, and Bradley will
accede to popular demand for a series of televised confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will enter as the favorite, because he is famed for
trouncing Ross Perot and Jack Kemp in past debates (though he was
fought to a standstill by Dan Quayle). He will carry the fight to
Bradley, taunting him for ``quitting'' the progressive cause in its
hour of need to combat the Gingrich Congress; for timorously voting
against the war to contain Saddam Hussein, and for being nowhere
near the bridge during the ``Clinton-Gore'' prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley will surprise : noncombative but giving no quarter, he
will project a gentle strength and present a low-key disdain for
the usual political point-making. He will keep changing the subject
to race relations (seeking out a Clinton source of strength) and to
a need for the rebirth of decency (offering Democrats escape from
Clinton guilt).
</P>
<P>
   Who will win? First, the Democratic Party will. These are two
serious, experienced and intelligent candidates, neither of whom
wants to appear personally to be out to clobber the other and
thereby sow division in the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   In debate, Gore is likely to win on points; he not only knows
his stuff but is trained in how to slam it home. Bradley is likely
to win on general impression; he's a new face to most viewers,
good-humored and likable, talks dull but hangs loose, and fits in
his skin. In a nomination fight, points count; in a general
election, impression is all. Victory in the Gore-Bradley debates
will be measured by who gains most against the Republican
front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, with the most now to lose, can be expected to
resist pre-nomination debate as long as possible. Lest this make
him seem fearful or unprepared, he will agree to a single debate
early next year with as many other Republican candidates as can be
rounded up. He would be the moderate, gamely suffering the arrows
of Steve Forbes and Gary Bauer, free in that format from the need
to expound in detail, stressing winnability.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain has now broken out of the pack in New
Hampshire polls to become the viable Bush alternative. He has found
his villain _ ``the special interests'' in both parties trading
campaign money for legislative favor _ and is winning independents.
If McCain shakes up Bush in New Hampshire, the public pressure will
be intense for a one-on-one debate before the March 7 New York and
California primaries.
</P>
<P>
   With Bush in Clintonesque triangulation and McCain in
Trumanesque populism, that would be fun: two guys running against
their party for its nomination. Who'd win that debate? Despite
having done well debating Ann Richards in Texas (and let's see that
on C-Span), Bush would have the advantage of low expectations
against the feisty McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In the general election, neither major party will repeat the
1992 mistake of giving a huge audience to a third candidate,
especially from a party now giving ``lunatic fringe'' a bad name.
</P>
<P>
   So: Which Democrat, hard-hitting Gore or intellectual Bradley,
would be more likely to savage Bush in debate if he is still ahead?
Put another way: Which Republican, maverick McCain or moderate
Bush, would be more effective in stopping the momentum of the
victor of the exciting Democratic debates?
</P>
<P>
   For a guide to the Main Event, we have to watch the prelims.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
