<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5935 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-COURT-BOS &LR;      10-13 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-COURT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FIRST, WOMAN TO HEAD TOP COURT IN MASS. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL REZENDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Margaret H. Marshall was confirmed yesterday as chief
justice of the Massachusetts Supreme Judical Court, making her the
first woman to lead the state's judiciary or any of the three
branches of Massachusetts government.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci, who has stood by his nominee in the face
of criticism from Cardinal Bernard F. Law and abortion-rights
opponents, Wednesday hailed Marshall as a leader of ``great
character'' and repeated his contention that her opponents on the
Governor's Council were motivated by sexism.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in the history of Massachusetts we have a
woman leading one of the branches of state government,'' Cellucci
said. ``Margaret Marshall has a great intellect, she's a woman of
great character, and she will be a great Supreme Court chief
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The eight members of the council and Lieutenant Governor Jane
Swift voted 6-3 to confirm Marshall. One councilor said she was not
sufficiently qualified for the post, and another said she had been
unfairly attacked by abortion rights opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The Council also voted 9-0 to confirm Superior Court Judge
Judith A. Cowin as an associate justice of the high court. Law had
also raised questions about Cowin's nomination, but councilors who
reviewed her ruling in a discrimination case against the
Catholic-affiliated Carney Hospital in Boston, said they were
convinced she did not exhibit an anti-Catholic bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on her record as a whole, I am persuaded that the text
of one decision called into question did not reflect a bigoted
mindset that would disqualify her from confirmation,'' said
Councilor Edward M. O'Brien, an Easthampton Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien led the opposition to Marshall's nomination as chief
justice, asserting that her comparatively short tenure of two years
and nine months on the high court, coupled with a lack of previous
judicial experience, should disqualify her from the position.
</P>
<P>
   The chief justice manages the activities of the SJC, assigning
judges to write opinions on specific cases, serving as the liaison
to the governor and Legislature, and helping to oversee operation
of the lower courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``At no time in the history of the court has any governor named
a chief justice who has had less experience as a member of the
court system,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   Councilor Michael J. Callahan, a Medford Democrat, said he voted
against Marshall's confirmation because of her relatively brief
tenure as a judge, while Councilor David Francis Constantine, a New
Bedford Democrat, said he opposed Marshall in part because she did
not recuse herself from an abortion-related lawsuit after serving
on the board of a home for unwed mothers that performs the
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can tell me this is the best candidate for the
position,'' said Constantine, who cast the sole vote against
Marshall's confirmation as an associate justice three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Marshall nor Cowin was on hand to witness Wednesday's
confirmation vote. In a prepared statement, Marshall said: ``I am
honored, deeply honored, by the vote of confirmation of my
nomination as Chief Justice. . . . I follow in the footsteps of
giants. I do so with humility and with a deep commitment to the
rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, 55, the wife of New York Times columnist Anthony
Lewis, was a student leader who opposed apartheid in her South
African homeland before immigrating to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her beliefs were tested when it was a dangerous thing to stand
up,'' said Cellucci. ``I think that kind of person leading one of
our branches of state government is a wonderful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cellucci, Wednesday's confirmation votes helped define the
extradinary role he is playing in reshaping the high court. With
Supreme Court justices Ruth I. Abrams and Neil L. Lynch facing
mandatory retirement next year, Cellucci is on a course to have
appointed four of the high court's seven judges and named its chief
justice in a single gubernatorial term.
</P>
<P>
   In addition elevating Marshall and naming Cowin, Celluci
recently named Judge Francis X. Spina to the high court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for judges who have a respect for our democratic
system, respect for the legislature and respect for the people,''
Cellucci said, adding that judges in his view should uphold the
law, not make the law.
</P>
<P>
   The Marshall and Cowin nominations erupted in controversy last
month when Law said in a letter to Cellucci that each of the
nominees had taken actions that showed ``a certain mindset which at
times is open to the serious charge of anti-Catholicism.''
</P>
<P>
   In Marshall's case, Law objected to an action she had taken as
chief legal counsel at Harvard University, when she admonished
noted Catholic intellectural Mary Ann Glendon for using Harvard Law
School stationery for a letter to Catholic priests that discussed
opposition to federal abortion-rights legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Law, after speaking directly with Marshall, dropped his
objections to her nomination but abortion rights opponents
continued to oppose her elevaton to chief justice.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Citizens For Life, the largest organization in the
state opposing abortion rights, charged Marshall violated the
judicial code of ethics by taking part in a unanimous ruling of the
high court that allowed a Brookline reproductive health clinic to
keep longtime anti-abortion protestor Barbara Bell from its doors.
</P>
<P>
   The group based its assertion on Marshall's tenure as a member
of the board of trustees of Crittenton Hastings House, a Brighton
home for unwed mothers that performs more than 1,500 abortions a
year. MCFL president Ray Neary said Marshall's role as a board
member at Crittenton Hastings, which ended in 1995, the year before
she was confirmed as a judge, means that Marshall's impartiality as
a judge is compromised.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Councilor Marilyn Petitto Devaney, a Democrat of
Watertown, Mass., said Marshall was the victim of a ``witch hunt''
perpetrated by abortion rights opponents, declaring that, of the
hundreds of letters and calls she received for and againt
Marshall's nomination, none had mentioned the abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   But MCFL executive director Maryclare Flynn said she personally
spoke with Devaney and lobbied her to vote against Marshall's
confirmation because of her former affiliation with Crittenton
Hastings. ``I personally called Devaney and mentioned abortion,''
Flynn said. ``And I know others who called her and mentioned
abortion because that was the reason for their calls.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cowin's case, Law's concern about possible anti-Catholic bias
arose from a post-trial ruling in which she increased the standard
payment to attorneys representing a Carney Hospital employee who
successfully sued the Catholic-affiliated institution, claiming he
was wrongfully fired because his superiors believed he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   In her ruling, Cowin cited the difficulty that hospital employee
John Walsh had in finding attorneys willing to take a case in which
they would have to go up against ``the strength of the Catholic
Church.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowin's critics said that because the Church was not
specifically mentioned as a defendant in the case, the wording of
the ruling may have evinced prejudice against Catholics. But at her
confirmation hearing, Cowin, after allowing that she could have
written her ruling ``more artfully,'' said she harbors no
anti-Catholic bias and councilors believed her, resulting in the
unanimous vote for her confirmation as an associate justice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
