<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5937 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-OLY-HEARINGS14-COX     10-13 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HEARINGS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Players in Atlanta Olympic bid to testify
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Billy Payne certainly never believed Atlanta's
extraordinary Olympic adventure would end up here _ with the city's
heroes called before a Congressional panel bent on ferreting out
possible bribery and skulduggery that brought Atlanta its greatest
glory.
</P>
<P>
   Payne and former Mayor Andrew Young, the two men primarily
responsible for winning the 1996 Games for the city, will testify
this morning before a House Congressional subcommittee
investigating the Olympic site selection process.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Fred Upton (R-Mich.), the committee's chair, has labeled
the system corrupt because gifts and favors were exchanged for
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Payne and Young are not likely to disagree. But they probably
will portray themselves as victims caught up in an anything-goes
environment of currying favor in the hopes of landing the world's
biggest prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will describe the environment in which the bid was
conducted,'' said Lee Echols, the bid committee's spokesman, ``and
also discuss the fact that although we jumped over the line from
time to time, the ultimate reward of winning the Games was
Atlanta's most positive experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Upton, chairman of the House Commerce oversight and
investigations subcommittee, may not be persuaded by ``the end
justifies the means'' argument.
</P>
<P>
   A report submitted by former Attorney General Griffin Bell
portrayed the Atlanta bid team members as being tangled in a
pattern of excessive gift-giving and offers of scholarships and job
assistance, athletic training and free health care for IOC members
and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Upton said the report proved ``votes were for sale'' and accused
the IOC of fostering a corrupt bid culture.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the picture Payne painted when the first hint of
vote-buying emerged from Salt Lake City late last year.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, he assured Atlantans that such impropriety didn't
happen on his watch. But as the scandal unfolded over the next 10
months, it became clear it had.
</P>
<P>
   Now Upton wants to publicly air the sordid details as Congress
considers legislation that would limit the IOC's fund-raising in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch declined Upton's request to
appear, saying he was too busy enacting reforms aimed at restoring
the organization's image and credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Anita DeFrantz, a delegate from Los Angeles, is expected to
testify on behalf of the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch had similarly snubbed Sen. John McCain's Senate
Commerce Committee hearing into the Salt Lake City Olympic scandal
last April.
</P>
<P>
   Ten IOC members already have been purged, but congressional
leaders are skeptical of the IOC's promise to enact lasting reforms
to make the Lausanne, Switzerland, organization more accountable
and less open to corruption.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech this summer aimed at his critics in Congress,
Samaranch said the IOC, which has bristled under Congress'
spotlight, would enact reforms at its own pace and on its own
terms.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC's own ethics commission would investigate any misconduct
by members related to the Atlanta bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say `no' to hasty reforms to please our critics,'' he said.
``No to reforms which defend the interests of some at the expense
of others. No to reforms based on personal and conflicting
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Other speakers expected to testify: former secretary of state
Henry Kissinger, who serves on an IOC reform commission, and former
Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, whose independent ethics
committee suggested that the IOC undergo major reforms.
</P>
<P>
   DeFrantz said earlier that Congress should take into account
that the IOC has embarked on major reforms, expelling members and
opening its financial books.
</P>
<P>
   Her pleas are falling on deaf ears. McCain (R-Ariz.) plans to
hold hearings next week on the issue of performance-enhancing drugs
in sports.
</P>
<P>
   Barry McCaffrey, the White House drug policy chief, recently
launched a series of scathing attacks on the IOC and its plans to
set up an international anti-drug agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sometimes get the impression that our attentions are not
entirely welcome,'' the Arizona Republican said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
