<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5960 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-UPTON-PROFILE14-COX     10-13 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPTON-PROFILE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olympics investigator known for dogged style
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the morning that he took hi presidential
fitness test, a skinny boy named Fred Upton got some bad news: one
of the lowest scores in the class.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Upton arrived at school before any other student
with one thing in mind _ mastering the push-up. By the end of the
year, he had set the school's push-up record and aced the fitness
test.
</P>
<P>
   The story shows the tenacity of a 13-year-old who would later
become a U.S. congressman against improbable odds.
</P>
<P>
   It also sheds light on the way the moderate Michigan Republican
might conduct a wide-ranging inquiry into what he calls the
``culture of corruption'' surrounding Atlanta's bid for the 1996
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to clean it up,'' said Upton, who at 46 still looks a
little like the Boy Scout he once was. ``The discovery period is
over. We've identified the mistakes. My charge is to restore the
integrity of the Olympic Games. We're going to demand that things
are changed.''
</P>
<P>
   As the chairman of the House Commerce Committee's panel on
investigations, Upton is determined that those demands will be
heard.
</P>
<P>
   If what friends, colleagues and his own family have to say about
him is any indication, Upton won't stop until he has uncovered
every misspent dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't know the words `give up,''' said Bruce Laing, a
longtime friend from Michigan who has chased him down ski slopes
and worked closely on his re-election efforts. ``He's his own
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's skiing, playing hearts or talking policy, Upton
goes to the limit. When he wanted to propose, for example, he hired
a plane to fly over a Baltimore Orioles game with a banner
emblazoned with: ``Amey, this is the inning to say yes.''
</P>
<P>
   She did, and they now have two children, ages 8 and 11.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, Upton constantly urges reporters, aides and
elevator attendants to ``call me Fred'' before they can even utter
the words ``Congressman Upton.''
</P>
<P>
   But Upton's relationship with his own party hasn't always been
so easygoing.
</P>
<P>
   Upton resigned the highly coveted post of deputy whip in 1993
because he did not agree with former House Speaker Newt Gingrich's
confrontational style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to vote the party line,'' Upton said at the
time. ``I'm going to vote on the merits.''
</P>
<P>
   While he is a staunch fiscal conservative, he has stood against
his party on key social policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   During this summer's gun control debate, for example, Upton
sounded almost Democratic in his support for stricter regulations
on gun sales. He was one of the first Republicans to attack tobacco
companies for trying to sell discounted cigarettes through the mail
to minors. He also supported President Clinton's plans to deter
violent crime with social programs, which resulted in Michigan
Republicans booing him at the state party convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very fair and thorough,'' said Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.),
who visited Upton's district last year to help him address some
bitter racial divisions between two communities there. ``He's a
great believer in doing what is right and trying to hear all
sides.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has high moral standards, but he's not a goody-two-shoes;
he knows how the world works,'' said Mike Garey, the owner of a
roofing company in Benton Harbor, Mich., who has known Upton for
most of his life.
</P>
<P>
   The only bias that Upton has is for the Chicago Cubs or the
University of Michigan's football team, Garey said.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Michigan in 1975 with a degree in
journalism, Upton returned home to St. Joseph to pursue his
lifelong dream of becoming a sports reporter.
</P>
<P>
   But a political speech made by a Republican candidate named
David Stockman changed all that.
</P>
<P>
   Upton was so inspired by Stockman's economic policies that he
signed up to work on his campaign. Soon he was a convert, following
Stockman to Washington to work in his congressional office.
</P>
<P>
   When President Ronald Reagan tapped Stockman to be the director
of the Office of Management and Budget, Upton followed him again.
</P>
<P>
   And when Stockman resigned, Upton went back home, a place where
his grandfather helped found the Whirlpool Corp., to run for
Stockman's former congressional seat.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the job was held by a Republican Christian conservative
named Mark Siljander.
</P>
<P>
   The primary race was tight until a few days before the election
when Siljander told the members of a church they should ``pray and
fast to break the back of Satan.'' The obvious comparison of Upton
to Satan won Upton votes, his father recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does hone in,'' Steve Upton said. ``When he gets
militaristic, he'll hang on until satisfied that he has all the
facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0366 </DOCNO>
