<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MASS-BUDGET-580&AMP;ADD(T     10-13 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-BUDGET-580&AMP;ADD(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS IS LAST OF 50 STATES TO PASS BUDGET THIS FISCAL
YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Wis.)  (bl) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts on Wednesday effectively claimed the
budgetary booby prize for 1999 when legislative leaders announced a
long-awaited agreement that will finally let the state pass its
annual financial plan _ 104 days after the fiscal year began July 1
and dead last among all 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Thomas Birmingham and House Speaker Thomas
Finneran _ both Democrats, both powerful figures, and lumped
together by some as ``the Toms'' _ announced their breakthrough
Wednesday with relief after weeks of one-on-one wrangling, often on
a secluded State House balcony high on Beacon Hill.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When white smoke wafts up from the Vatican, Birmingham told
reporters, people say, ```Habemus papam' _ `We have a pope.' So
perhaps today it would be appropriate to say, `Habemus rationem
pecuniae' _ `We have a financial plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Amen!'' responded Finneran with enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Both said the wait had been worthwhile because it had allowed
them to hash out compromises on moves of long-term importance to
the state, from reforming the finances of the subway system to
salting away 70 percent of the hundreds of millions of dollars the
state will receive from the tobacco settlement. The two also
managed after long debates to agree on increasing prescription drug
coverage for low-income elderly patients, proposing that old people
with incomes up to 188 percent of the federal poverty level be
covered by the state for up to $1,250 a year.
</P>
<P>
   But critics remained unmoved by their post-game back-patting and
bonhomie, saying the weeks of tardiness, during which monthly
interim budgets were passed and no new programs could be financed,
had hurt the state, including many poor people and underpaid state
employees who were waiting for promised state money.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also derided the two leaders as chamber chieftains whose
tete-a-tete talks bespoke an autocratic style typical of a
traditional, troubling Massachusetts style of back-room politics.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislature has accomplished next to nothing this year,
and I think it's embarrassing,'' said Brian Cresta, chairman of the
state's Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Along the way, a lot of issues languished and almost died on
the vine,'' he said. ``You expect to see this during bad economic
times,'' he said, but in good times like these, ``It just doesn't
make sense to me.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Actually, say some experts on state budgets, it does make sense
that financial plans become much harder to pass when times are good
_ just as family budgets are harder to agree upon when parents'
incomes are up and a ``no'' to a child's request for a new bike or
sound system is harder to justify.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to be more difficult in times of plenty for states
to pass a budget compared to relatively lean years, because in
those years, at least legislators understand that there is a limit
to how much they can ask for special projects in districts or for
special programs they favor,'' said Arturo Perez, a senior policy
specialist who follows state budgets at the National Conference of
State Legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   Coming at the end of a record spell of peacetime prosperity,
this year's budgets have been especially slow, Perez said: In
Wisconsin, the next-to-last state, the legislature passed its
budget only last week, and perennially tardy New York, whose fiscal
year starts in April, was four months late as well.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wisconsin Assembly Speaker Scott Jensen said Wednesday that he
was ``glad to tell the legislative leaders of Massachusetts, ``Tag,
you're it!'' Wisconsin lawmakers mainly got hung up over how much
of the state's $1.1 billion surplus to devote to tax cuts and how
much to spend on new social and education programs, he said. It
ended up cutting about $900 million in taxes and spending about
$200 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, disagreement in the overwhelmingly Democratic
legislature was not so much over tax cuts, though the two leaders
did wrestle to an agreement over phasing the income tax down from
5.95 percent to 5.75 percent. Rather, it was an intra-Democrat
tussle focused more on how much windfall money to squirrel away
versus how much to spend now on social programs. Birmingham
appeared to be more for spending, Finneran more for squirreling.
</P>
<P>
   Prosperity also contributes to slow state budgets in the
complacency it engenders among voters, some lawmakers noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, if we didn't have a budget this late in the
year, legislators didn't dare go out in public for fear of bodily
harm,'' said Jim Marzilli, a Democratic state representative from
Arlington. ``Now, when I meet my constituents on the street, there
is a mix of befuddlement and contempt for government _ they ask,
`What's wrong with us?' _ but nobody calls me going, `Make the
budget move!' Even while literally hundreds of thousands of people
are harmed by the failure of the legislature to act.''
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, the Boston Globe has been carrying a ``Budget Watch''
noting how many days the budget was late and naming a different set
of victims each day, from parents awaiting daycare subsidies to
school districts crippled in their hiring to elderly patients
skimping on their medications.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, officials in the Republican administration of Gov.
Argeo Paul Cellucci and some columnists in the more conservative
Boston Herald emphasized the positive side of the budget stalemate:
that it saved millions of dollars by holding back planned new
spending. (And the wait is not over yet: Finneran estimates it will
be another two weeks or so before final details can be worked out
and the budget can be passed.)
</P>
<P>
   But critics like Marzilli called the delay outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   ``As our economy creates two huge classes - one of winners and
one of losers -the folks who were most hurt by the budget stalemate
were the ones left behind,'' he said. ``They are not the people who
elect us. And most legislators know that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
