<SLUG> BC-HISPANICS-MISSING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC WRITERS ARE FEW IN CURRENT CATALOGS
</HEADLINE>
 
Accompanied by HISPANICS-SUCCESSES (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifteen out of 1,871.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers _ gleaned from the 1999 fall and winter catalogs
from 25 of the most prestigious U.S. publishing houses _ confirm
what any casual trip to a bookstore makes obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Very few Hispanic authors are getting books published _ at least
by mainstream publishers, which is the same thing as saying that
very few Hispanic authors are getting the chance to have their work
read by a wide audience. In the final quarter of this year, 15 of
1,871 books from major publishers, or fewer than 1 percent, were
written by Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow, I'm not sure why, it's slumped off a bit,'' says Ash
Green, a senior editor at Knopf. ``The numbers have been better.
We, for instance, publish Sandra Cisneros. I don't think American
publishers shy away from Hispanics. It may just  despite the
growing Hispanic population, the writing tradition there isn't
being developed much.''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic educators and community leaders agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where kids are concerned, they want to become what they see,''
says Anita Quinones, who coordinates the Fort Worth school
district's school-to-work program and who has been an educator for
more than 20 years. ``Our kids aren't exposed to careers in
writing. Historically, they haven't had lots of books in their
homes, which perhaps is connected with economics. For economically
disadvantaged families, owning books may not be a priority compared
to buying other necessities.''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic youngsters she talks to, Quinones notes, are often
interested in the arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that means acting, drawing and painting, but not
writing,'' she says. ``They get those ideas from watching TV and
going to movies. So they think about acting in that movie, but not
writing the book that movie is based on.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fernandez, who serves on multiple local and state
community boards, including the state Board of Higher Education,
faults Hispanic families and public-school curriculums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, our kids aren't growing up in family environments where
literary individuals are highly regarded,'' he says. ``That's my
opinion, unfortunately. But it's also true that, in school, I was
not exposed to Hispanic authors until I took some courses in
college. Public schools do not expose us to Hispanic authors as we
are growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Quinones says, ``very few Hispanic kids I have
worked with _ very, very few _ have even mentioned the possibility
of becoming writers. I think some of them are probably writing on
their own at home without anybody saying to them, `Hey, that's a
good thing to be doing.' I think they have to get their support
outside the home.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet area support groups for developing writers report minuscule
Hispanic membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any Hispanics out of about 60 members,'' says
Lucile Davis, who founded Fort Worth's Freelance Writers Network
five years ago. ``I've had inquiries about the group from two
Hispanics. I also teach a continuing-education writing class at
TCU, and in three semesters, only one Hispanic has enrolled. Now,
the African-American community seems to be encouraging writers.
There are several African-American writers' groups around now. But
there isn't one especially for Hispanic writers.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman says the 85-member D/FW Writers Workshop has no
Hispanic members.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the most, we had maybe six or seven,'' says longtime member
Jack Ballas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think many publishers are getting manuscripts from
Hispanics,'' says Kenneth Kirkland, an independent publishing
industry analyst based in New York. ``You can't print their books
if they're not being offered to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if more Hispanic writers were submitting manuscripts to
publishers, odds are not in favor of them selling their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the same as it is for almost any writers in 1999,''
says Judy Alter, director of Fort Worth's Texas Christian
University Press and the author of many fiction and nonfiction
titles. ``Right now, publishers are cutting back their publishing
lists, so there are fewer chances for Hispanic writers, black
writers, any kind of writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirkland says Hispanic writer-wannabes might also be hampered
``by not knowing how the publishing industry works. For instance,
they may not know you need an agent to sell a book to a major house
like Knopf or Putnam. Or, if they do, they may not know anyone who
can tell them how to find an agent.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the U.S. Hispanic population grows, many literary agents
are beginning to believe that Hispanic authors could eventually tap
into a new, gigantic market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying hard to develop our Hispanic client list,'' says
Jan Miller, of Dupree/Miller Literary Agency in Dallas. ``I think
it's going to explode in very much the same way the
African-American market did 10 years ago.'' (About 8 percent of
this fall's 1,871 books are by black writers.)
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rosenberg, owner of the Rosenberg Group in Fort Worth,
says he has recently attended ``four Southwest writers' conferences
looking for Hispanic writers. We think there is going to be an
opportunity for them in the publishing industry. They are difficult
to find; we're looking in the academic community and now we're
talking to one, a professor of sociology. We're waiting for him to
send us his book proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, publishers haven't beaten the bushes for
Hispanic authors, Miller says, ``because sales of books by Hispanic
writers haven't warranted it.''
</P>
<P>
   That opinion is seconded by Alter.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any financially based business, the product offered to the
public is determined by what's going to sell best,'' Alter says.
``I think we've published one book by a Hispanic author, published
it both in English and Spanish, and we had a hard time marketing
it. The feeling was that there weren't enough Hispanic readers to
support Hispanic authors.''
</P>
<P>
   That is going to change, Miller predicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to find the right writing talent, like you have to
find the right talent in anything,'' she says. ``So we're out
looking hard, even looking on the Internet, and it's going to be
fun. What we've seen with the African-American market is crossover.
It's not a case anymore that only black readers read black writers.
Now for the next 10 years, I think we'll see that for Hispanics and
Hispanic writers, too.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
