<HEADLINE>
JURY CLEARS COUNTRY SINGER OF MURDER CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RALPH WININGHAM  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UVALDE, Texas _ Country singer Johnny Rodriguez lowered his head
in relief and his supporters cheered Wednesday as a Uvalde County
jury found him innocent of murder.
</P>
<P>
   The six-man, six-woman jury returned its verdict after two hours
of deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez had been charged with murder in the Aug. 29, 1998,
shooting death of Israel ``Bosco'' Borrego, 26, at the Rodriguez
family home in Sabinal. The singer, who did not testify during the
trial, said he shot Borrego in self-defense after Borrego broke
into the house.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Borrego family, including Borrego's widow, Anita,
began softly crying when the verdict was read.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors were immediately ushered from the courthouse under
heavy security after the decision was announced, and Rodriguez was
quickly hustled to the judge's chamber. More than a dozen law
enforcement officers were in the courtroom for security when the
verdict was read.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that went through my mind was that I could be
a father to my baby,'' Rodriguez said later in a courtroom news
conference. He said his daughter, Aubrey Rae, is 18 months old.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said he was relieved to be acquitted, adding that he
is embarrassed and sorry about the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank my wife, my family and the jury, and everybody
who has been so nice,'' he said. ``I know a lot of people have been
praying for me, and I've been doing some extra praying myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Relatives and friends of both families have maintained a
constant vigil inside and outside the courthouse throughout the
six-day trial in Uvalde, 50 miles west of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   There had been no incidents during the trial, but witnesses
testified there had been threats by the Borregos against anyone who
supported Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the Borrego family, Baltazar Borrego, is in the
Uvalde County Jail on a charge of making a threat that reportedly
included a promise ``to kill Johnny, if he walks.''
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Tony Hackebeil said ``the jury has spoken''
and that he was satisfied with the way he presented the case.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Brown, the lawyer who represented Rodriguez, said he
believed the jury was sending a message with its verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've heard clearly that citizens should have the right to
defend themselves,'' Brown said. ``We could have tried this case
anywhere, and we would have the same result.''
</P>
</TEXT>
