<HEADER>
A5977 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-KKK-TERRORISTS14-COX     10-13 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KKK-TERRORISTS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S.C. city declares Klan terrorists
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ A Charleston, S.C., councilman who sponsored
a city resolution to declare the Ku Klux Klan a terrorist
organization said Wednesday he will now push for state legislation
condemning hate groups.
</P>
<P>
   First-term Councilman Wendell Gilliard said if he can find a
sponsor for a resolution denouncing hate groups, he would expect
``rigorous debate'' among South Carolina legislators.
</P>
<P>
   He likened it to the debate over the Confederate battle flag
flying atop the state capitol in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not different topics,'' said Gilliard, 45. ``The Ku
Klux Klan, since its inception in the 1800s, has taken the
Confederate flag and used it as a symbol for their organization.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the flag protest, the South Carolina NAACP will hold
its annual meeting next week in North Carolina, beginning Thursday
in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Charleston's city council Tuesday approved by voice vote the
resolution stating that ``the Ku Klux Klan is a terrorist
organization.'' It said Charleston ``welcomes diverse opinion,''
but added that the city ``does not tolerate speech, actions, or
activities that incite violence in our community.'' ``What council
did was exercise its freedom of speech,'' city attorney Bill Regan
said, ``but it was not an enactment of any law.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Klan wants to march, it may apply for a permit.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing a concern raised by some council members, Regan said
publicity from the resolution ``might prompt the Klan to march
again in Charleston, something that has not happened for 10
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Potok, of the Southern Poverty Law Center in Montgomery,
Ala., said he believes Charleston may be the first municipality to
declare the Klan a terrorist group. But he questioned whether the
resolution would have much impact aside from symbolic rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the aim is in some way to ban the Klan or prevent them from
rallying or publishing, I think it is quite pointless,'' Potok
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gilliard, a Charleston native who recalls rural cross
burnings as a teen-ager, said he intended the resolution as a
warning that the Klan and other hate groups are still active in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
