<SLUG> BC-FBN-BC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLES' BACKUP QUARTERBACK IS READY, JUST IN CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Brian St. Pierre, quite naturally, was shocked. The
Boston College redshirt freshman quarterback had no idea starter
Tim Hasselbeck had been injured in last Saturday's 24-14 loss at
Temple until Hasselbeck gingerly boarded the team bus, his right
(throwing) arm in a sling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him what had happened,'' St. Pierre said Wednesday,
``and he said, `They think I might have separated my shoulder.' It
was a total shock to me. Since then, I haven't really talked with
Tim much about it. I know I don't like it when I'm injured and
people come up to me and ask about it, but I know Tim's done
everything this week to get himself ready like he should.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the starter and if he can play, he should play.''
</P>
<P>
   But, St. Pierre admitted, when he first saw Hasselbeck's wing in
a sling, another thought crossed his mind. ``This could be a week
where I need to be even more prepared, if that's possible,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While St. Pierre got a majority of the repetitions in Tuesday's
practice, Hasselbeck proclaimed Wednesday he was ready to return to
work and expressed every confidence that he would be ready to play
in BC's huge Big East home game Saturday against Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw some (Tuesday), but not a whole lot,'' Hasselbeck
said. ``But I felt a whole better and it wasn't bothering me, so
I'm ready to get back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasselbeck did not report the mild shoulder separation until
after he completed 14 of 22 passes for 146 yards and a 3-yard
touchdown pass to fullback Ryan Burch. He threw one interception
and was sacked three times. But Hasselbeck said that at no time
during the Temple game did he feel his injury hindered his
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I watched the tape and I know what play it happened on,
and I had a touchdown pass after that,'' Hasselbeck said. ``I hurt
it on an option play in the first quarter. The first one we ran was
when we were down on the goal line and next one we ran was when we
hurt it.''
</P>
<P>
   When told he appeared to be the latest casualty among Big East
quarterbacks, given the injuries to West Virginia's Marc Bulger
(broken index finger) and Rutgers's Mike McMahon (separated
shoulder), Hasselbeck shrugged and said, ``It's the fifth game and
really it's the first bump I've had. Playing this game, you've got
to expect it. You're not going to finish the season completely
healthy, so I'm not discouraged about this at all.''
</P>
<P>
   That certainly wasn't the case with Hasselbeck's older brother,
Matt, whose first year as a starter in 1996 was truncated by a
shoulder injury against Temple, forcing him to sit out the finale
at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``He separated his left shoulder against Temple, which is
obviously different from when you're a righthanded quarterback,''
Tim said. ``But like I said I was able to throw (Tuesday) and I
feel better today. They wanted to see how it would feel today after
throwing (Tuesday) and it doesn't feel worse, so that was
encouraging. I'm approaching this like a normal week with the way I
feel right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Which meant, of course, that Hasselbeck went back to working
with the first-team offense and St. Pierre went back to work as
Hasselbeck's backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to lie you. I don't like backing up. I don't
like not being on the field,'' said St. Pierre, who had hoped to
earn the starting job in preseason camp. ``I understand the
situation and I understand my role right now, as far as they
wanting to get me a series or two in the second quarter. I think
that's good and it benefits me. I think it'll benefit the team
because if something were to happen to Tim, then I'd have some
experience. At the same time, it's hard coming out of the game or
coming in cold off the bench, but I'll just take it week to week.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Pierre has made second-quarter appearances in all five games
so far this season, completing 14 of 20 passes for 175 yards. He
has been intercepted twice, once in the Navy game, where he tried
to force a ball into quadruple coverage, and again at Temple, where
he made the right decision and the right throw, but wound up
getting intercepted in the end zone when redshirt freshman Jamal
Burke was outleaped by cornerback Fulton Fryar.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that situation, you couldn't have drawn up a better play,''
St. Pierre said. ``We had man-to-man, bump and run. It was an
all-go play with four verticals and that's where my read took me. I
put the ball there and Jamal made a great effort for it and the
(Fryar) kid did, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Navy pick? ``That was just a bad play on my part,''
he said. ``I was trying to force it and make something happen. I
think it was just a product of me pressing a little bit because I
want to play so badly. It was just inexperience on my part, but in
the past few weeks I think I've come so far since the Navy game.''
</P>
<P>
   While he is unsure of Hasselbeck's status, St. Pierre knows
he'll have to remain on ready-alert status against Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wednesday was great getting those reps, because I feel like I
know more about the game plan this week than I have in any other
week,'' St. Pierre said. ``I don't know what to expect today and I
don't know what to expect Saturday, so I'll just go about soaking
up everything I can. You try to take every rep you can and just be
ready to play, because you're one play away just like you are on
every Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC athletic director Gene DeFilippo indicated the ticket office
had been besieged with calls from angry fans who complained about
the switch of Saturday's starting time from noon to 5 p.m. to
accommodate the ESPN2 telecast. The Eagles, as a result, will go
head-to-head with Game 3 of the ALCS between the Red Sox and
Yankees. ``If we had our druthers, we'd prefer to have it at
noon,'' DeFilippo said. ``But we have no control over it. Our hands
are tied because of TV, and so are the Red Sox.'' . . . Senior free
safety Pedro Cirino, a Yankees fan at heart, said he doesn't mind
if Game 3 is the biggest game in town Saturday. ``That's fine,'' he
said. ``I don't mind the Yankees coming up here and spanking some
butt.'' Cirino, however, failed to mention he was a Yankees fan
when, during preseason camp, he happened upon Red Sox ace Pedro
Martinez, who was sitting on the steps outside the North entrance
of Conte Forum waiting on a friend. ``I introduced myself and we
talked in Spanish a little bit,'' Cirino said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
