NYT-10-13-99 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-UTILITIES-MERGER-NYT &LR;      10-13 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTILITIES-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILITIES MERGER: BOLD MOVE FROM A METHODICAL COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Northeast points)  (lh) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Five years ago, when deregulation of the utility
industry was just beginning in the Northeast, including New York
state, Eugene R. McGrath, the chairman and chief executive of
Consolidated Edison Inc. proudly showed off a large plan that
covered a wall in a room at its downtown Manhattan headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   It outlined in detail the steps the utility would take to
prepare for competition.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, McGrath said he wanted a gradual approach in which
the utility was able to adapt to change but still keep its system
reliable; continue paying its steadily increasing dividend to many
of its mostly older stockholders, and strengthen its balance sheet
to be able take advantage when opportunity knocked.
</P>
<P>
   It was not an approach that excited Wall Street. His methodical
approach seemed out of step with the fast pace taken by other
utilities, many of which hunted for merger partners and had big
ambitions to become national sellers of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, McGrath put Con Edison on the national stage with a
deal that holds the promise of cheaper power for its customers. At
a news conference in Berlin, Conn., McGrath announced the
acquisition of New England Utilities in deal worth $25 a share in
cash or stock, or $3.29 billion. The transaction also includes the
assumption of $4.2 billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Under this bold move, Con Edison will become the dominant force
in the Northeast in the rapidly changing industry and will become
one of the largest utilities in the country with a customer base of
4.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   But McGrath took care in an interview to point out that he was
staying on his straight and narrow path. ``Our core strategy is to
be a wires and pipes company,'' he said, meaning the company will
primarily deliver electricity and other services and no longer be a
large generator of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not deviating from our business.'' he added. ``It has be
very close to what we know.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he has kept the door open to becoming a dominant
player in the Northeast in the selling of electricity, natural gas
and eventually other services like security systems and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   The two utilities have both set up marketing groups backed by
subsidiaries that have kept a core of power plants that are low
cost and will be a source of cheap electricity. Thus Con Edison is
in a strong position as states in the Northeast allow customers to
choose their electricity provider.
</P>
<P>
   A subsidiary called ConEdison Solutions has been marketing power
and other services, mostly in the New York metropolitan area, and a
unit of Northeast Utilities called Select Energy Inc. has been
doing the same in an 11-state area.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath said that the two units would most likely be combined to
save money, avoid duplication and bring together expertise.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the two marketing groups are concentrating on signing
up large customers like retail chains, businesses and institutions
that buy large amounts of electricity and natural gas, which are
more profitable than residential customers.
</P>
<P>
   The sales force also offers other services like upgrading
heating systems, balancing out the use of power to take advantage
of lower off-peak rates and programs to manage energy use.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, little attention has been paid to individual retail
customers because the cost of persuading them to switch and then
billing them is high.
</P>
<P>
   In the near future, smaller customers will see few marketers
offering them alternatives in states like New York, Connecticut and
Massachusetts, which have begun to deregulate.
</P>
<P>
   As markets are opened wider, however, smaller customers will be
able to buy cheaper power.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are seeing benefits already. Con Edison customers,
for example, will see their rates decrease by 10 percent by 2001
under New York's order to deregulate. And states served by
Northeast Utilities, like Connecticut and Massachusetts, plan to
require rate cuts under deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   Michael G. Morris, the chairman, president and chief executive
of Northeast Utilities, said in an interview Wednesday, that his
group had gained experience in selling to small customers and could
make money.
</P>
<P>
   John Boyd, the president of ConEdison Solutions, said in an
interview Wednesday that it was difficult to bring significant
savings on electricity because utilities had already been providing
power inexpensively. He said that perhaps 5 percent to 10 percent
could be cut form the power portion of the bill, which is about 25
percent of customers' total bills. The rest is for delivery of
electricity, which will not be opened to competition.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, he said, technological innovations will allow
even smaller customers to get bigger savings.
</P>
<P>
   Even in bringing together the marketing units of the two
companies, McGrath remained cautious. ``We're going to be very
careful about the way we do things'' he said. ``We want to start
out on the right foot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
