<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC LITERARY LUMINARIES _ AND NEWCOMERS TO WATCH
</HEADLINE>
 
Accompanies HISPANICS-MISSING (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three Hispanic writers have earned special renown, certainly
achieving the so-called crossover audience that guarantees
six-figure book advances and regular visits to bestseller lists. In
approximate order of literary importance, they are:
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR HIJUELOS, a Cuban-American who became the first Hispanic
writer to win the Pulitzer Prize for fiction. ``The Mambo Kings
Play Songs of Love'' remains his best-known novel, but any Hijuelos
novel is exceptional. ``The Fourteen Sisters of Emilio Montez
O'Brien'' is equally full-spirited, whereas ``Empress of the
Splendid Season'' is a darker tale of dreams thwarted and a
middle-aged woman's determination not to give in to life's
disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   ISABEL ALLENDE is Chilean, and, unlike Hijuelos, is a Hispanic
whose major works were first published in Spanish and translated
into English. ``The House of the Spirits'' is her most popular
work, thanks partly to its movie version. But there is also
``Cuentos de Eva Luna'' (''Tales of Eva Luna,'' ``El Plan
Infinito'' (''The Infinite Plan'') ``Hija de la Fortuna''
(''Daughter of Fortune'') and, most recently, the sensual
``Aphrodite: A Memoir of the Senses.''
</P>
<P>
   Texan SANDRA CISNEROS is the most eclectic of the trio: She
seems equally at home writing for children (''The House on Mango
Street);'' and adults (''Woman Hollering Creek and Other Stories;''
``My Wicked, Wicked Ways),'' a collection of poems. Cisneros'
emergence a half-dozen years ago was considered a sign that more
talented Hispanic writers would come to national literary
attention, but that didn't prove to be the case.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even in today's sparse Hispanic market, there are a
number of gifted authors whose books are readily available in local
stores. These writers include:
</P>
<P>
   YXTA MAYA MURRAY, whose gritty barrio tales (''What It Takes to
Get to Vegas'' and ``Locas)'' have either captivated readers or
elicited accusations of stereotype-ng. Maya Murray has the
kind of writing style that invites strong emotional reaction, both
pro and con. She's someone to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ERIC GARCIA, a screenwriter-turned-author whose first novel,
``Anonymous Rex,'' is a quirky farce starring a race of dinosaurs
who masquerade as humans, hiding their reptilian identity from
``Homo sapiens.'' ``Anonymous Rex'' is solid proof that Garcia is
one of those rare authors who can combine good writing chops with
colorful, if somewhat warped, characters and story lines (think
Christopher Moore and ``The Lust Lizard of Melancholy Cove'').
</P>
<P>
   ANA CASTILLO, author of ``Peel My Love Like an Onion,'' a novel
destined to be short-listed for many major literary awards. Carmen
Santoas, its protagonist, is a flamenco dancer hampered by
childhood polio. Other notable Castillo titles include ``So Far
From God,'' ``Loverboys'' and ``Massacre of the Dreamers.''
</P>
<P>
   ANDRES Martinez, a journalist of note (''The Wall Street
Journal,'' among other papers), offers as his first book
``24//7:Living It Up and Doubling Down in the New Las Vegas.''
Because his book isn't limited to Hispanic experience, Martinez may
be the first of the New Wave to gain the attention of mainstream
readers.
</P>
<P>
   FELIPE FERNANDEZ-ARMESTO is anything but a struggling author; he
is on the faculty of Britain's Oxford University. Some of his
previous books (''Millennium,'' ``Reformations'') have received
considerable attention in academic circles. But ``Truth: A History
and a Guide for the Perplexed'' is being published by mainstream
St. Martin's Press, and its chatty, informal tone
(Fernandez-Armesto's first example of semitruth is the Santa Claus
legend) makes it a definite contender for bestsellerdom.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
