<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5990 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-JOE-THE-KING-FILM-ART     10-13 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOE-THE-KING-FILM-ART-2TAKES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICTURING A LOST BOY, DRAWING ON MEMORY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating, adding art note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17)  
 (Eds: Use this version. Includes author I.D.)  
 (af)  
 Karen Durbin is the film critic for Mirabella magazine.  
 By KAREN DURBIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some addiction counselors classify the children of alcoholics
into behavioral types: the hero child, who tries to save the family
by doing everything right; the scapegoat, who constantly fails and
gets into trouble; and the lost child, who goes AWOL from the
family dynamic and develops a private solution, sometimes with
disastrous results.
</P>
<P>
   With the ironically titled ``Joe the King,'' which opened on
Friday, Frank Whaley has made an intensely affecting yet
unsentimental movie about a lost child. That the film contains a
large dollop of autobiography _ it is dedicated to his parents _
only makes this 36-year-old actor's achievement more striking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe the King'' is Whaley's first outing as a writer and
director, and if this is what's considered a small film, it's an
exceptionally rich one. The movie won the screenwriting award at
this year's Sundance Festival, and it opens with a beautifully
composed pan of schoolchildren on the lawn at recess that feels
like a tour of childhood itself.
</P>
<P>
   We see children playing, reading, chatting, roughhousing and, in
a few lonely instances, wistfully looking on. Finally, beyond a
dense barrier of leafy shrubs, the camera finds Joe. He's slumped
against the side of the building, his hands in his pockets and his
back to the world.
</P>
<P>
   His hair is so short you wonder if his head has been shaved.
When the bell goes off, he jerks around to reveal a gaunt face and
hard, fearful eyes; a half-smoked cigarette droops from his mouth.
He can't be more than 9 or 10.
</P>
<P>
   The first 20 minutes of ``Joe the King'' are background,
sketching in the misery of Joe's early childhood before moving on.
His father (played without a scrap of vanity by a bloated,
bleary-looking Val Kilmer) is a surly drunk who does some of his
drinking at Joe's school, where he's the janitor.
</P>
<P>
   This makes him all but ubiquitous in his son's life. It also
makes Joe the target of cruelty by other children, and by a
sadistic teacher, who gives him a bare-bottom spanking in front of
the class after he throws an eraser at a child who has razzed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it happened today,'' Whaley says, ``she'd be arrested. She
pulled down my pants, and it was mortifying. It's like a dream _
you know how you remember moments of it? I remember the kids in the
class looked like they were in shock. They were as traumatized as I
was.''
</P>
<P>
   This scene points up the perils of autobiographical art. The
teacher, played with monstrous relish by Camryn Manheim _ it's one
of the movie's more piquant pleasures that we get to see some
high-profile actors in down-and-dirty roles _ is a villain of
near-Dickensian dimensions. Whaley says this is one incident that
was drawn from life, but reality has a way of pushing realism into
melodrama. What saves the scene is the way it's shot, with just the
faintest touch of Grand Guignol wit.
</P>
<P>
   Whaley likes to hear that his film is unsentimental. ``When
you're dealing with something of a personal nature, it's easy to
become precious with it,'' he says. ``Something you might sit at
home and cry about may not be important to the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   His clipped speech and flattened vowels make Whaley, who grew up
in inner-city Syracuse, sound a little like a character out of a
1940s movie; with his pale, serious face, small features and thick
shock of brown hair, he looks like one, too. He could be a Dead End
Kid grown up or John Garfield's younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   He has had a busy 12-year film career, mostly with leading roles
in small films (``Swimming with Sharks,'' ``Homage'') and
supporting roles in big ones (``The Doors,'' ``Hoffa,'' ``Field of
Dreams.'')
</P>
<P>
   We meet at a French cafe in Chelsea, where Whaley lives. The
cafe, which specializes in crepes and coffee, isn't chic, exactly,
but it's very '90s. The young women who work there tend to be slim
and leggy, the men incline to fashionable, convict-cropped hair or
retro-hippie locks.
</P>
<P>
   In this setting, maybe what makes Whaley stand out most is his
complete lack of self-absorption. He seems far more interested in
what's going on around him than in himself, and he enjoys a joke.
When a thunderous pounding erupts in the kitchen, he deadpans,
``They're beating up a couple of Belgians back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Whaley's sense of humor works like yeast in ``Joe the King.''
But what really saves the movie from sinking into simple pathos is
his decision to focus on his protagonist in adolescence. At 9, Joe
is inescapably a victim. At 14, he has begun to contend with his
lousy circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   His tactics are hustle and evasion. This is a boy navigating in
a sea of adults who, with few exceptions, either ignore or injure
him. His teachers get on him about the money they've been dumb
enough to lend his endlessly cadging father.
</P>
<P>
   As played by Karen Young (in a performance so beautifully
contained that Whaley instructed his child actors to make her their
model), his mother is a once tender woman cauterized by abuse and
disappointment. She takes the brunt of her husband's violence,
partly to deflect it from her children. But suffering deforms more
than it ennobles.
</P>
<P>
   Whaley expresses gratitude for his own mother, Josephine
Timilione, who he thinks married his father because ``she wanted a
little danger.'' But ``the pain and the pleasure kind of mangled
her,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Joe's mother bullies the boy but occasionally gives
him a treat, when she's not altogether withdrawn. So he does his
best to duck his tormentors and look after himself. He has a decent
older brother, but Joe is essentially a loner.
</P>
<P>
   He works long nights washing dishes in a greasy spoon. He's also
an opportunistic thief, well-acquainted with the local pawnbroker.
Sometimes he's an impulsive thief as well, stealing things he can't
use or sell, like the tampon he nabs from a classmate's locker. He
squirrels it away in his secret hideout under the family's shabby
house, to take apart and examine later. (He really is raising
himself; nobody's teaching him anything.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
