<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSIVE END   HAS TAKEN LONG AND WINDING ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The song ``Long and Winding Road'' may have
been a hit for the Beatles, but it also describes Ferric Collons's
NFL career.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots defensive end has endured many twists and turns in
his five-year NFL career and at one time left New England for
another team, but somehow hasn't played an NFL game for anyone
other than the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Collons was released after last season by the Patriots because
his salary was scheduled to increase from $525,000 to $2.1 million.
The Patriots had given Collons a two-year contract after the
Philadelphia Eagles signed him to an offer sheet as a restricted
free agent after the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   In order to retain Collons's services, the Patriots had to match
the Eagles' offer, even though the second-year salary was
prohibitive, given salary cap restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots and Collons's agent, Angelo Wright, engaged in
bitter negotiations before the Eagles tendered their offer.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Patriots elected not to pick up the second year, an
angry Wright said he failed to understand why the team didn't try
to negotiate a decreased salary rather than a release.
</P>
<P>
   Wright even began to file a suit against the Patriots because
Collons was injured at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But when Collons went on the free agent market, the Oakland
Raiders signed him to a two-year deal. Collons was pleased, since
he calls the Bay Area home and his wife is an orthopedic surgeon at
a San Francisco hospital.
</P>
<P>
   While feeling he did a good job in Raiders camp, Collons did not
survive the final cut. The road was about to take another turn.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Patriots' defensive line was as thin as it
could be. Henry Thomas had missed training camp with a torn
shoulder tendon, Chad Eaton had missed some time with sore knees,
Willie McGinest was still trying to come back from groin injuries,
and Brandon Mitchell had broken his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be perfectly honest, the phone rang two hours after I got
cut and I didn't entertain (going) anywhere else,'' said Collons.
``I was sitting around my house with my family. I was surprised
they called, but as I've found out, it's a business. Personal
feeling and emotions can't enter into it on my part or theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this is where I wanted to be anyway. I never wanted to
leave. It wasn't my choice. I had no control over that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots definitely adhered to the adage ``in confusion
there is profit,'' for they made out like bandits in a situation
they appeared to botch, lopping $2.1 million off their 1999 payroll
and re-signing Collons for the $400,000 veteran minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Does Collons harbor any hard feelings about being let go
originally?
</P>
<P>
   ``You would not be human if you weren't upset about that. But
sometimes you put yourself second for other people,'' Collons said.
</P>
<P>
   Collons was happy to return to the team that had originally
acquired him Aug. 25, 1995 for ``past considerations,'' which meant
dinner at then Patriots general manager-coach Bill Parcells's
favorite restaurant. It's one of the trades that Parcells and Green
Bay Packers GM Ron Wolf make.
</P>
<P>
   Usually the two star executives try to help improve the other's
team _ though the last trade, when Green Bay sent quarterback irer to the Jets _ hasn't worked out yet. Parcells needed a run
stopper, and Wolf had just the guy. Collons wasn't needed in Green
Bay line.
</P>
<P>
   It was a perfect fit for the Patriots. Parcells came to like
Collons's attitude and his obvious abilities to contain the run.
</P>
<P>
   Collons has been both a front-line player, when he made 13
starts last season, and a role player, such as this year. But
what's becoming obvious is that Collons will have to play more, for
he is an impact player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he makes such a difference to our defense,'' said
Eaton, one of Collons's biggest fans whose constant boosting of
Collons to coach Pete Carroll and the front office helped get him
another deal with the Patriots. ``He's a force on the edge, and
having him do what he does helps us control the other team's
running game. He just does it so well.''
</P>
<P>
   Collons admits his name doesn't show up much in the statistics.
He won't have many sacks. Though the Patriots have typecast him as
a run stopper, the 6-foot-7-inch, 300-pound Collons would like
nothing more than to be unleashed toward the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when it gets fun, but there are a lot of people on this
team who play roles,'' said Collons. ``That's the way they set this
team up. You have to deal with those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last four years I've been here, I just do what they ask
me. I give them everything I have on the field and take it from
there. I can't control my playing time or when they play me and
when they don't play me. I'm trying to progress in a positive
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look at the stats and you'll see I don't get a lot of
sacks, but that's not what they ask me to do. They ask me to go out
there and shut down the running game and I do that to the best of
my ability. Five years ago when I got here I never played on
running downs. I always played on third down. Now, I never see a
third down. I do what they ask me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Collons has heard all the questions about the
Patriots' AFC East showdown Sunday against Miami in Foxborough.
He's been asked whether his team has exceeded expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't exceeded anything,'' he said. ``This team will go as
far as we allow ourselves to go. Strange things happen in this
game. We won't go far if we shoot ourselves in the foot. I don't
see why you wouldn't expect a lot from this team. The core guys
have been together a long time. We're not going to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Collons never did. That's why the long, winding road has led
him, again, to New England.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
