u a BC-SOUTH-LOTTERY14-COX     10-13 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-LOTTERY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S.C. next to face lottery question
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ Gambling opponents can cross Alabama off
their list of lottery-friendly states. Next in their cross hairs is
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   There, voters not only are expected to decide whether to start a
lottery but also whether to keep an unregulated, undertaxed video
poker industry. The state Supreme Court was expected to rule today
on whether to allow next month's video poker vote to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite more than a year of campaigning, Alabama Gov. Don
Siegelman couldn't persuade voters Tuesday to approve a
Georgia-style education lottery he projected would raise $150
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no plans to come back with a lottery proposal,''
Siegelman said during an office news conference Wednesday. ``Never
say never, but I have no plans. I think the people spoke pretty
clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Zeb Little, who sponsored the legislation that would
have set up the lottery, said the issue is dead ``at least for
several generations. I don't see that changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, South Carolina voters will consider a similar
referendum. Anti-gambling forces are hopeful voters will take a cue
from Alabama, where the issue lost in 47 of 66 counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells me people in the Deep South are taking a long, hard
look at gambling and not just stepping in line to do what everyone
else is doing,'' said Scott Vaughan, director of marketing for the
state Baptist Convention in South Carolina. The group represents
750,000 members in 2,000 churches.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama's Baptist Convention united clergy from all religions to
kill a lottery proposal that looked like a sure bet just two months
ago. Despite polls throughout the decade that gauged statewide
lottery approval at nearly 65 percent, more than 54 percent of
Tuesday's voters rejected the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   A similar scenario could play out in South Carolina. Like
Alabama, South Carolina is mostly rural with few urban centers,
said Brooks Holifield, a professor of American religion at Emory
University.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina and Tennessee, where state legislatures have
debated the lottery for years without resolution, are less
susceptible to the political sway of Southern Baptists because of
larger cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of a factor in Southern states than any other part
of the U.S.,'' Holifield said. ``They set the tone. But when you
have large urban centers, you have more religious diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Current polls show lottery support in South Carolina at 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Alabama's lottery rejection is an isolated incident or
the first sign of a gambling backlash may become clearer next
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``In conjunction with what could be the defeat of video poker in
South Carolina, it sends a signal that some states are rethinking
the rush to gambling of one form or another. That would be a
significant trend nationally,'' said Whit Ayres, a Roswell,
Ga.-based Republican pollster who once worked for former South
Carolina Gov. David Beasley.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show voters favor banning the video poker machines, which
pervade gas stations, restaurants, bowling alleys, hair salons and
hotels throughout the state. However, representatives of the $2.8
billion industry went to court to try to stop a referendum on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Carolina voters are smart enough to know the differences
between a lottery and video poker,'' said Kevin Geddings, who will
lead the pro-lottery campaign on behalf of Gov. Jim Hodges.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Hodges was elected on the promise of an education
lottery, just like Siegelman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
