<HEADER>
A5996 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-BABBITT-INVESTIGATE-4     10-13 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABBITT-INVESTIGATE-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT COUNSEL CLEARS BABBITT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Wis.) (rk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ending an investigation that had haunted Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt for 19 months, an independent counsel
announced Wednesday that she had uncovered insufficient evidence to
warrant charges against Babbitt or anyone else involved in his
agency's handling of a American Indian gambling project.
</P>
<P>
   The statement by the prosecutor, Carol Elder Bruce, represented
a decisive dismissal of the allegations against Babbitt after an
investigation that centered on whether the secretary lied in
congressional testimony in 1997 about an Interior Department
decision to deny an application by three Indian tribes to operate a
casino in Hudson, Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   In her statement, Ms. Bruce said that her investigation, which
included interviews with 450 witnesses and examination of more than
630,000 pages of documents also found no evidence of criminal
conduct in connection with the Interior Department's rejection of
the casino project. The investigation of Babbitt also focused on
allegations that political contributions to the Democratic party
influenced the department's decision.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Bruce said in her statement that the evidence ``would
not support a finding of a criminal `quid pro quo,' an explicit
agreement between any opponent of the casino application and any
government official involved in the Hudson decision to perform an
official act in exchange for a political contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Ms. Bruce said that she and her staff concluded that
``the evidence was insufficient to prove that Babbitt violated the
statutes prohibiting perjury and false statements in his Senate
testimony.'' Ms. Bruce said she would present a more detailed
discussion of the evidence and her findings in a report that she
will submit to the three-judge panel that appointed her.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor's statement represented a powerful vindication
for the 61-year-old Babbitt. But the long investigation had been an
unexpectedly painful test of political survival for a former
two-term Arizona governor from one of the state's oldest and best
known merchant and ranching families who arrived in Washington in
1993 with greater star power than almost anyone else in the
Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Babbitt said he was pleased by the outcome. ``I
am, of course, gratified that the grand jury and independent
counsel have determined after an exhaustive investigation that no
charges are justified in this matter,'' Babbitt said. ``That is not
surprising, as I have said from the beginning, all the employees of
the Department of Interior who participated in the Hudson casino
decision acted with complete integrity,''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With the appointment of Ms. Bruce in February 1998, Babbitt
became one of five Clinton cabinet officers to undergo criminal
investigation by an independent counsel, in addition to Kenneth
Starr's inquiry of Clinton. Together, the cases fed a furious
congressional debate over the independent counsel law that ended
when the statute expired in June without being renewed.
</P>
<P>
   Only one independent counsel inquiry involving a Cabinet
official remains unfinished. That investigation of Labor Secretary
Alexis Herman, which was unaffected by the law's expiration, is
focused on allegations that she engaged in a plan involving
kickbacks and illegal campaign contributions _ although Attorney
General Janet Reno in seeking an outside investigation said she had
uncovered no direct evidence of a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Clinton expressed satisfaction with the outcome of
the Babbitt investigation. ``I am very pleased by today's
announcement concerning Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt,'' Clinton
said. ``As I said at the beginning of this inquiry, Bruce Babbitt
is a man of the highest integrity, and I was convinced that he
would be vindicated. Secretary Babbitt's record of superb
stewardship of our nation's lands speaks for itself, and I look
forward to his continuing service to our country, its people and
its extraordinary God-given resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt had been under scrutiny since Janet Reno referred the
case, after intense debate among her circle of advisers, to a
three-judge independent counsel panel that selected Ms. Bruce, a
former federal prosecutor, to investigate the allegations against
the interior secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The Babbitt inquiry, coming at a time when the White House was
already buffeted by multiple investigations into Clinton's
relationship with a former intern, into campaign finance and into
other Cabinet officers sharpened the impression of serious ethical
laxity within the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, from the start, Babbitt said he had played no role
in the Interior Department's decision to deny the casino permit and
said that the deliberations reflected the Interior Department's
policies on Indian gambling operations.
</P>
<P>
   But Babbitt's account was challenged by Paul F. Eckstein, a
lawyer, former classmate and law partner of the interior secretary,
who lobbied in favor of the permit. Eckstein said that Babbitt told
him of a White House lobbying effort to kill the casino deal. After
the decision, victorious tribes who opposed the casino permit gave
$230,000 to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 30, 1997, Babbitt told the Senate governmental Affairs
Committee that the decision to reject the casino was made by a
senior career civil servant at the Interior Department and said
that political considerations had not influenced the permit denial.
</P>
<P>
   But Eckstein said that he spoke with Babbitt two or three times
on the telephone and met with him in the secretary's office on the
day the decision was announced. Eckstein said that Babbitt had told
him that Harold Ickes, then deputy White House chief of staff,
wanted a quick decision on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Eckstein, who was chairman of Babbitt's gubernatorial campaign
in 1982, said that the secretary also asked him whether he realized
how much money the Indians were contributing to the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said that he did not remember mentioning campaign
donations, but he did not deny that he mentioned Ickes. Babbitt
said that he had mentioned the name of the powerful presidential
aide as a way to usher Eckstein out of his office. In his
congressional testimony, Babbitt said, ``It was just an awkward
effort to terminate an uncomfortable meeting on a personally
sympathetic note.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
