<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHEAST-UTILITIES?-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CON ED PURCHASE OF NORTHEAST UTILITIEPROVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as the Red Sox-Yankees pennant playoff whips thousands of
New Englanders into a frenzy of hating all things New York, the Big
Apple's hometown utility announced a $3.5 billion deal to take over
the parent of three New England electric utilities.
</P>
<P>
   ConsolEdison Inc. Wednesday approved a $25-a-share,
cash-and-stock purchase of Northeast Utilities, based in Berlin,
Conn. Northeast is the parent of Western Massachusetts Electric,
Public Service of New Hampshire and Connecticut Light &AMP; Power and
is taking over gas utility Yankee Energy in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which is not expected to close until the end of next
year, would create one of the country's biggest utilities, with 5
million electric customers and 1.4 million gas customers from
Pennsylvania to New Hampshire and annual revenues of about $11
billion. Customers would continue to get bills and service from
operating companies such as WMECO.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast takeover accelerates a trend of rapidly
consolidating ownership of New England utilities, including last
month's combination of Boston Edison and Commonwealth Electric into
NStar.
</P>
<P>
   British utility giant National Grid plc, which is in the process
of acquiring New England Electric System and Eastern Utilities, had
been rumored earlier this week to be interested in Northeast
Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   A National Grid spokeswoman said Wednesday the company does want
to pick up more northeastern utilities to build on the NEES
footprint, but only after it has digested the NEES and Eastern
deals, indicating it may not be ready for a bidding war with Con Ed
for Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg Business News reported that Northeast must pay Con Ed
a $130 million termination fee if it breaks off the merger, so a
rival bidder such as National Grid would have to pay $1 a share
more than Con Ed to beat its offer.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Maloney, president of Devonrue Ltd. in Hingham and a
consultant on electric and telecommunications deregulation, said
the Northeast-Con Ed deal ``is one of those combinations that is
just inevitable, and I know we haven't seen the last of these
deals.''
</P>
<P>
   By 2002, New York will introduced competition for electric
supply to its market as Massachusetts did last year. That could
push Con Ed to look for merger partners in New Jersey, Pennsylvania
or elsewhere to get big and efficient enough to cope with
deregulation, Maloney said.
</P>
<P>
   Con Ed chief executive Eugene McGrath said his company and
Northeast ``are natural partners.'' Company officials expect to
save $150 million a year by merging the companies, but said they
will take steps to minimize layoffs and focus on retraining
employees, reducing hiring and leaving vacancies unfilled.
</P>
<P>
   Con Ed said it would pay $25 a share for Northeast, a 17.6
percent premium to the 21 1/4 Tuesday closing price of Northeast
shares on the New York Stock Exchange and up nearly one-third since
the beginning of this month as rumors of a Con Ed or National Grid
takeover began circulating on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Northeast shares had cratered in 1996 and 1997, dropping below
$10 for a time, during protracted problems restarting its Millstone
nuclear units in Connecticut. The Millstone outage cost the company
$1.5 billion and forced it to stop paying dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Northeast, which recently put two Millstone units up for sale,
is scheduled to pay its first dividend in nearly three years, of 10
cents a share, on Dec. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Con Ed said it will add $1 a share to its bid if Northeast is
able to unload the troubled Millstone 2 and 3 units and also add to
its purchase price for every day the transaction's closing is
delayed past next August.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath will remain chairman and chief executive of the combined
company. Northeast president and chief executive officer Michael G.
Morris will become president of the Con Ed holding company, which
will remain based in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The merger needs approval from the Federal Energy Regulatory
Commission, Securities and Exchange Commission, Nuclear Regulatory
Commission and some state regulators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
