<SLUG> BC-DELTA14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta ends alliance with Swissair to concentrate on Air France
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The divorce is final.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines said Wednesday it is ending its long-standing
marketing alliance with Swissair, Sabena and Austrian Airlines to
concentrate on closer ties with Air France.
</P>
<P>
   Delta marketing chief Fred Reid diplomatically called the move a
``difficult decision,'' but it was one that had been widely
expected since Delta and Air France said last spring they would
form a new global alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement immediately strained Delta's ties with
Swissair, which views Air France as a competitor for the
trans-Atlantic passengers it has shared with the Atlanta-based
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Both Swissair and Delta in recent months sold their stock
holdings in each other, and Swissair has made preliminary moves
toward new ties with American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of the Delta-Swissair alliance ends a long and tight
relationship that was among the first of its kind. Over the years,
many thousands of passengers booked by Delta have flown Swissair
flights under their ``code share'' pact.
</P>
<P>
   But Delta in 1997 established ties with Air France and last year
decided to make a major push to build those links into a new
branded alliance.
</P>
<P>
   That alliance, which has not yet been named, also includes
AeroMexico and is expected to include an Asian partner.
</P>
<P>
   Delta hopes to be able to generate more code-share business with
Air France, whose hub at Charles de Gaulle Airport in Paris is much
bigger than Swissair's in Zurich.
</P>
<P>
   Delta and Air France hope to build a multicarrier alliance that
will rival other pacts such as the Star Alliance, which includes
United, Lufthansa, Thai Airways and Brazil's Varig, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Delta said it will continue to book passengers on code-share
flights with Swissair, Sabena and Austrian through the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Swissair, Sabena and Austrian all fly to Atlanta, with Delta
filling some seats on their planes. It remains to be seen whether
the end of the alliance will affect those flights.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Delta is expected to gradually expand the number of
Air France flights on which it sells seats, but no specific
announcements have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
