A6003 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CLINTON-FORESTS-ART-2     10-13 0272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FORESTS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 REDDISH KNOB, Va.: harvest timber. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since early this year the Forest Service has enforced an
18-month moratorium on road-building and other development in most
of the areas covered by Clinton's action Wednesday. If all goes
according to the White House plan, the new, permanent ban would be
put in place just as the moratorium runs out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tight, but we're going to make it,'' Podesta
said, clearly enjoying an outdoor break from his duties in the West
Wing. Clinton flew into the area Wednesday on a helicopter, and
then drove up the mountain _ in a sport utility instead of his
limousine _ along a Forest Service road of the kind he wants to
outlaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already seen a lot of people saying a lot of terrible
things about what I'm doing, saying the world will come to an
end,'' Clinton said, referring to the reaction to news last week
that a permanent ban was on the way. He argued that only 5 percent
of the timber harvested in the United States each year comes from
the national forests, and only 5 percent of that timber comes from
the land protected by his directive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can replace 5 percent of 5 percent of the timber,'' he
said. ``We can't replace these 40 million acres.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also vowed to veto an interior department bill, now
making its way through Congress, that he said was ``loaded up with
special-interest riders that permit overlogging in national forests
and a windfall to major companies that produce oil on federal
lands.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that if the bill stays in its current form, ``I'll send
it straight to the recycling bin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
