<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6004 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PALESTINE-TV-HOST-NYT     10-13 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINE-TV-HOST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALK SHOW HOST SPEAKS OUT ABOUT PALESTINIANS TORTURING
PALESTINIANS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank _ Maher Dasuki, a popular talk show host on
a local television station in this Palestinian-ruled town, became
the topic of his own program last week.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested and jailed for 20 days by the Palestinian security
forces after a guest on his program denounced Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, Dasuki was back in the studio to tell the tale
of his incarceration.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed by a colleague for more than an hour, Dasuki, 38,
pulled no punches, and the echoes of his remarks are still
reverberating.
</P>
<P>
   He accused his jailers, some of whom had served time with him in
Israeli prisons, of torture. He described how they had blindfolded
and shackled him in a painful position, how they had called him a
collaborator with Israel and abused other prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing at the camera as he named his interrogators, he defied
them to arrest him again, and received a steady stream of
supportive telephone calls from viewers. There was no disruption of
the broadcast by the Palestinian authorities, nor any official
denial of his account.
</P>
<P>
   Dasuki's imprisonment and forceful television appearance
reflected the contradictions of life under the Palestinian
Authority: arbitrary intimidation on one hand and freedom to
criticize it on the other.
</P>
<P>
   The unpredictable responses of the security forces showed the
peculiar nature of Arafat's authority in the areas he controls,
which often swings from autocratic repression to tolerance of
dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Dasuki's program, on which guests and viewers debate political,
social and economic topics, is broadcast twice a week on two
Ramallah-based television stations. He was arrested at his office
on Sept. 15, several days after guests on the program criticized
the Palestinian Authority for failing to secure the release of
their sons from Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of one prisoner, an Israeli Arab sentenced to life
imprisonment, went so far as to wish Arafat a speedy death. The
object of her anger was Arafat's assent to the exclusion of Arabs
from East Jerusalem and Israel from the lists of prisoners released
under the latest Israeli-Palestinian accord.
</P>
<P>
   The personal attack on Arafat appears to have been too much for
the security forces and the likely cause of Dasuki's arrest, which
Jibril Rajoub, the Palestinian security chief in the West Bank,
attributed to ``security reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Dasouki's interrogators accused him of ``incitement and
possession of inciteful materials,'' he recalled in the televised
interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The words that recurred in every interrogation session were,
`You insult us,' '' Dasuki said during the interview, which was
conducted by Daoud Kuttab, a prominent Palestinian journalist who
heads the Institute of Modern Media at Al Quds University, which
owns one of the two stations that broadcast Dasuki's show.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Palestinian tortures you as a Palestinian, that's the big
problem,'' Dasuki continued. ``I never imagined that at 2 o'clock
in the morning I would hear screaming and beating of prisoners. The
Islamic Club in thr of town has become a center of torture,
a center of degradation. How does that happen? It should be the
opposite, prisons should be turned into clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Callers, some of whom declined to identify themselves, praised
Dasuki as courageous, and expressed revulsion at his treatment in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows these things are going on,'' said one caller,
Abu Muhammad. ``The authority must put a stop to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Another caller said: ``We want respectable people to govern us,
we don't want to be ruled by security agencies. The Palestinians
reject government by the security forces. We want institutions,
democratic institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   The unhindered interview with Dasuki and the strong viewer
response it evoked showed the ``strengths and weaknesses of the
Palestinian Authority,'' Kuttab said. ``It allows terrible things
like torture, but it also allows people the freedom to say
something about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
