<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia fertile territory for private companies
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia has a ``peachy'' small-business economy, Inc.
(Dec. 19) says in a special edition on the nation's 500
fastest-growing private companies.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia and New York have 24 firms each, but Georgia led the
nation in growth by adding seven since last year. California had
the most with 75, followed b with 38, and Virginia and
Massachusetts with 27 firms each.
</P>
<P>
   The 500 companies posted average 1998 sales of $22.1 million and
five-year average sales gains of 1,715 percent. Inc. says 46
percent are computer-related businesses, 15 percent provide
business services and 10 percent offer consumer goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   The five fastest-growing Georgia companies on the list are CFC
Refimax, a Marietta refrigerant recycler at 55th place; IntelliNet,
an Atlanta software company, 76th; Datamatics Consultants, Duluth
computer consultants, 81st; CodeSoft International, an Atlanta
software and consulting firm, 85th; and Lockwood Sign, a Marietta
manufacturer and installer of electric signs, 98th.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER REVOLUTION
</P>
<P>
   Management guru Peter F. Drucker, writing in The Atlantic
Monthly (October), looks at the computer-driven information
revolution and concludes that its impact ``is just beginning to be
felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Industrial Revolution altered our mental maps and
gave rise to industries nobody predicted, e-commerce _ or business
by Internet _ will do the same thing, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the new mental geography created by the railroad, humanity
mastered distance,'' he writes. ``In the mental geography of
e-commerce, distance has been eliminated. There is only one economy
and only one market. The competition is not local any more _ it has
no boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   The new knowledge-based industries will depend on attracting,
holding and motivating ``knowledge workers'' _ a term Drucker
coined.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this can no longer be done by satisfying the knowledge
workers' greed, it will have to be done by ... turning them from
subordinates into fellow executives, and from employees, however
well-paid, into partners,'' writes Drucker.
</P>
<P>
   FUTILE CRACKDOWNS
</P>
<P>
   Periodic waves of puritanism inspire politicians to ban alcohol
or tobacco or other drugs. But, says Forbes (Oct. 18), ``history
shows that legislating sobriety achieves nothing _ and may
aggravate the excesses it is aimed at.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes cites research by Indiana University Professor Ruth C.
Engs showing that temperance and similar movements follow
predictable cycles of early success, restrictive laws and eventual
failure. When enough time has passed to forget the failures, the
next cycle begins, leading to new laws.
</P>
<P>
   The irony, says Forbes, is that in each temperance campaign,
``most of the decline in consumption came before the laws took
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
