<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6008 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NISSAN-CEO-PROFILE-AR     10-13 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-CEO-PROFILE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
TOKYO: I expected.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the deal was announced in March, Hanawa was clearly under
pressure. Nissan was closer to being broke than most imagined, with
its banks pushing it to find a new source of cash fast and talks
with Daimler Chrysler AG ending abruptly, in an embarrassingly
public way. The company had no mid- to long-term strategy at that
point; it was simply trying to stay alive day to day.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, however, an alliance with DaimlerChrysler, roiled
now by its own dramatic management changes and the
take-no-prisoners style of its chief executive, no doubt seems far
less appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Even though some changes at Nissan are uncomfortable _ Hanawa
himself said it was somewhat unsettling how fast decisions were
being made _ he is pleased with the deal he made.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were totally the same, there would not be stimulus and
inspiration between us,'' he added. ``Sometimes that stimulus is
comfortable, and sometimes it's painful.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men speak with each other often _ ``Between my broken
English and Ghosn-san's Japanese, the gap is getting closer,''
Hanawa said _ but Ghosn is clearly calling the shots now. He has
startled workers by showing up to stroll the assembly lines and ask
questions, not only of senior engineers and managers but also of
workers themselves. He has encouraged the use of e-mail, rarely
used in the past at Nissan, although language has proven to be
somewhat of a barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Sakanoshita, the labor representative, said Nissan's senior
executives had previously visited production lines only for formal
celebrations of new-car introductions. He could recall only one
other time when someone of Ghosn's stature visited the plant at
Musashimurayama, when Takashi Ishihara, Nissan's legendary chairman
in the early 1980s, paid a call.
</P>
<P>
   `` Hanawa seems more Japanese in that when he collects
information, it is after it has worked its way up from the factory
floor through the plant managers to the section chiefs and division
chiefs,'' Sakanoshita said. `` Ghosn skips the process and goes
directly to the factory floor.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sakanoshita is not at all certain he likes Ghosn's common
touch, even he recognizes that Nissan must change. ``It would be
hard for Nissan to avoid,'' he said. ``I'm not sure Renault should
have been the partner we chose, but it is clear that Nissan could
not survive on its own.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite doubters like Sakanoshita, Ghosn is confident he will
have an easier time selling the plan to Nissan than to outsiders.
``Hundreds of people have had a chance to contribute to this inside
the company,'' he said. ``I've met no resistance and had a lot of
good cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Has he had any fun in the last six months? He burst into
laughter, then said it was a difficult question. ``It's an intense
job, and I like intense jobs,'' Ghosn said. ``I'll put it this way:
it takes up all your intelligence, all your skill, your capacity to
listen, your humor, your patience. You are fully used in this
job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
