u f BC-DELPHI14-COX     10-13 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELPHI14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quarter results buoy Delphi
 &HT;    By Lynn Hulsey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, Mich. _ Delphi Automotive Systems' run of good news
continued Wednesday with the company announcing strong
third-quarter earnings and continued growth in orders from
companies other than former parent General Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Delphi also announced the creation of a new division, Delphi
Aftermarket, to bolster sales of replacement auto parts. The
company had focused on the warranty-related aftermarket parts, but
now will push into the broader aftermarket parts industry, said
Alan Dawes, chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Dawes said Delphi also continues to look for companies to
acquire, including businesses that now serve the aftermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Delphi employs about 13,000 people in the Dayton area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our acquisition strategy is truly what I would call
opportunistic,'' Dawes said. Delphi has made inquiries but no
formal bids on other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Delphi is looking for companies that introduce new customers,
bring synergistic technology, or expand the geographic footprint,
Dawes said.
</P>
<P>
   Auto industry analyst Gary Lapidus of Goldman Sachs said he is
encouraged by that stance and by the third-quarter results, which
show strong sales growth and good cash flows.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest auto parts maker said it earned $136
million, or 24 cents a share, compared with a loss of $214 million,
or 38 cents a share, in the same period last year that was blamed
on a strike at GM plants in Flint.
</P>
<P>
   The results were a penny a share higher than Wall Street
predictions, according to a survey of analysts by First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Sales totaled $6.8 billion, up 18 percent over 1998 levels. The
company also generated $484 million in operating cash flow during
the quarter, allowing Delphi to make a $300 million pension
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The third quarter is typically a challenging period for us,''
said J.T. Battenberg III, Delphi's chairman, president and chief
executive. ``This year, despite the usual production changes for
the new model year and the seasonality of (customer) schedules, we
were able to post very solid results.''
</P>
<P>
   Lapidus said he was particularly encouraged by the company's
growth in non-GM business.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, Delphi booked $2 billion in business with
non-GM customers, including a deal with Caterpillar that
significantly expands the company beyond its traditional auto
industry base. Delphi also booked $8 billion of new business with
GM.
</P>
<P>
   Dawes said this year's non-GM business bookings total $7
billion, topping 1998's $6.2 billion in total non-GM bookings.
</P>
<P>
   Delphi (NYSE:DPH) stock closed at 15 13/16, down 5/16. The
52-week range was 15 1/16 to 22 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Dawes and Lapidus both said the company's recent soft stock
market performance is due to overall lack of interest in auto
components businesses. Dawes said the possible spin-off of Ford's
Visteon parts maker could help stock prices by generating interest
in the components sector. Lapidus also said it will create an
opportunity for Delphi to grab some Ford business now done by
Visteon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
