<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6012 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ARTISTS-RETREATS-2TAK     10-13 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTISTS-RETREATS-2TAKES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME OFF TO DIVE INTO REALITY RATHER THAN RETREAT FROM IT  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Mo., N.C., N.Y.)  (af) 
 By ANN WILSON LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a late 20th-century version of J.M.W. Turner's search for the
untrammeled landscape, a small band of contemporary artists is
spending this month trekking in the Himalayas, seeking fresh vision
as well as fresh scenery.
</P>
<P>
   In Salvador, Brazil, artists are working with street children to
bring them back into society. In Kansas City, Mo., artists have set
up shop in a converted downtown garage, while in San Antonio, a
former automobile showroom functions as a high-tech studio.
</P>
<P>
   All are new versions of the artist residency program in which,
traditionally, artists retreat for sabbaticals in bucolic,
cloistered settings like Yaddo or the MacDowell Colony. Now artists
may convene in gritty urban environments, participate in group
living experiments or join far-flung adventures resembling Outward
Bound.
</P>
<P>
   The Himalayan trek, for example, initiated by the Kiasma Museum
of Contemporary Art in Helsinki, Finland, is theoretically about
perception and how new experience rets formation, according
to Maaretta Jaukkuri, the museum's chief curator. Artists may work
while walking, or during a monthlong residency at the museum next
spring. An exhibition will be held in the summer of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Liisa Roberts, a trekker and New York-based artist who is half
Finnish, said before leaving that combining nature, art and
expeditions is not so strange in Finland. Jussi Heikkila, a Finnish
artist who has previously used mountain hiking in his work, came up
with the idea. Ms. Roberts was excited but a little nervous. ``I am
not much of an outdoor person,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Xu Bing, a Chinese artist living in New York and another
trekker, may be more prepared, at least ideologically. The trip
echoes his student days in China during the Cultural Revolution,
when he was sent to live with farmers. Long conditioning marches
were also prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project is an avant-garde idea in Western contemporary
art,'' he said, ``but it's something they were doing 20 years ago
in China. The project addresses a lot of problems in contemporary
art, where things are missing between the artist and the audience.
A more social-minded approach is needed.'' Perhaps a response to
withdrawal of funds by the National Endowment for the Arts, these
new-style artists' residencies are cropping up everywhere, said
Tricia Snell, executive director of the Alliance of Artist
Communities. The alliance, which started in 1990, has a membership
of 60 nonprofit programs, but there are close to 80 in the field at
large.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twelve have recently opened, 11 more are in planning stages,
40 or 50 people have contacted us about startups,'' Ms. Snell said.
``Here is a grassroots movement much as there was in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ArtPace, the new program in San Antonio, is where Ms. Roberts
was contacted to discuss the Himalayan trek. ArtPace was founded in
1993 by Linda Pace, a San Antonio artist, benefactor and collector,
whose father developed Pace Picante Sauce. ArtPace residencies,
awarded by nomination, are considered the cream.
</P>
<P>
   A local-global mix of residents is chosen by a panel of
international art professionals or a curator. This year, Okwui
Enwezor, director of the next Documenta, tapped Ms. Roberts, Chris
Sauter from Texas and Oladl Ajiboy Bamgboy from London.
</P>
<P>
   Artists live and work for two months in a sleek new facility
carved from a vintage car showroom, are given private apartment and
studio space, technical support and facilities, a $500 weekly
stipend and an $8,000 budget for supplies. Exhibitions cap the
residency.
</P>
<P>
   ArtPace prides itself on underwriting costly new works. ``The
demise of NEA grants to individual artists and the aftermath of the
early '90s economy diminished opportunities for artists to make
significant, expensive works,'' says Ms. Pace.
</P>
<P>
   It was here that in 1997 Cornelia Parker, a British artist, made
``Mass (Colder Darker Matter),'' an installation of charred remains
from a burned Texas church that was later exhibited in the Turner
Prize show at the Tate Gallery in London. Consequently, San Antonio
has become a preview site for the art world, staff members claim.
</P>
<P>
   In a collaborative first, Isaac Julien, a British filmmaker, is
splitting his residency this fall between ArtPace and a somewhat
similar program, Grand Arts, in Kansas City. It, too, is financed
by a private foundation established by Margaret Hall Silva, a
member of the Hall family of Hallmark Cards. Ms. Silva is also an
artist, though like Ms. Pace, she has found her program eclipsing
personal artmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Arts is in a former garage in downtown Kansas City that
has also undergone an upscale architectural makeover, setting it
apart from nearby pawn shops and parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Arts is slightly smaller in scope and more fluid than
ArtPace. ``We have no program the artist has to plug into, Ms.
Silva said. ``Each residency is individual.'' The stipend and
budget are customized. Recently Jim Leedy, a local artist, used
Grand Arts state-of-the-art sculpture studio to prepare a large
installation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the staff was also mapping logistics for Julien's
film project and a project with the New York artist Dennis
Oppenheimer.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Arts residents come from solicited applications, with
final selection made by a revolving panel of national arts
professionals. The center offers, in addition to the sculpture
studio, an elegant on-site apartment and two galleries. As at
ArtPace, Grand Arts' staff says art-world traffic has enlivened the
scene in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Evolving from sources exactly opposite from Grand Arts and
ArtPace, the new Tryon Center for Visual Art, in Charlotte, N.C.,
may be the first residency program to be generated by civic leaders
rather than art ponals. Opening its doors last month with
six artists ranging from local to international, the Tryon Center
has a $7 million endowment given by the Bank of America, which has
its headquarters in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Tryon Center was inity Hugh McColl, the CEO of Bank of
America who has been behind much of the rebirth of downtown
Charlotte. But the new arts center is not necessarily an urban
renewal project, says Barbara Spradling, chairman of the Tryon
board and a Bank of America senior vice president. ``Culture and
visual arts are what make cities great,'' she said. ``We would like
more artists to live here, to help build audience and collectors,
and to fill a gap in Charlotte.''
</P>
<P>
   Tryon Center also filled a gap in the urban landscape _ a
burned-out shell of a neo-Gothic church just blocks from the bank's
downtown corporate tower. The spectacular renovation created 15us studios (almost too handsome for messy art making),
lavishly equipped workshops and high-tech labs for everything from
digital media to printmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Such grand scale corporate largesse stems partly from the fact
that McColl's mother was a painter. ``I like art and want to
support artists,'' he explained. ``I thought of painters living on
the south side of the rebuilt church and painting in north-facing
studios, so it's not exactly as I envisioned it. But my philosophy
is to do something and then be happy with it. And part of the deal
is that artists will give back in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   Tryon's residents are chosen half by nomination and half by the
staff. Residencies are for three months and artists receive
housing, studios, up to $2,500 for materials plus a monthly stipend
of $1,500 to $4,000. In return, community involvement is strongly
encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, everyday life is the leitmotif of the Quiet in the
Land, a series of ad hoc residency projects created by France
Morin, an independent curator. The first, in 1996 at the Sabbathday
Lake, Maine., Shaker colony, included 10 artists she personally
selected. Now Ms. Morin is in Salvador, Brazil, overseeing the last
of 16 staggered residencies in her second project.
</P>
<P>
   In Salvador, completely removed from the typical pampered
residency and from the art world, artists work with Projeto Axe, a
philanthropic organization that uses the arts to seduce street
children back into society.
</P>
<P>
   ``By sharing powerful histories, first the Shakers and now
children of Axe help artists re-examine relationships of life and
work to the world beyond the narrow confines of the art world,''
Ms. Morin says. ``I cannot say all the artists have had the same
level of experience, but most of them are leaving troubled and
rethinking these relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Nari Ward, who has participated in both Ms. Morin's projects,
found Brazil incredibly challenging. ``I think artists came on
board thinking they were tired of the old model residency, to flex
themselves a little more,'' he said. ``The Shaker project was a
personal introspection. Brazil is much more a social project, but
both had the same premise _ to take everyday situations and regard
them the way you would art in a museum or gallery. It has
intensified my desire to work more with communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was completely comfortable with the Salvadoran
experience. Kara Walker, who worked with teen-age girls, cited
frustrations with language barriers as well as living close
together in one house with other participants. She recalls vigorous
discussions about why they were there; whether they were artists or
missionaries. ``I wasn't really sure what we were working toward,''
she said, ``but there were moments when something a little bit
magical would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The art generated from her collaboration with the young women
had a little bit of a high school feel to it, Ms. Walker said
(which may be one reason Ms. Morin and the artists decided not to
show the project's exhibition outside of Salvador as originally
planned). Ms. Walker, who spent four weeks in Salvador, added, ``It
affected my real life more than my working life; it made me
question all that I do.''
</P>
<P>
   These projects stem from Ms. Morin's general dissatisfaction
with the gallery and museum circuit (she was formerly the head
curator at the New Museum of Contemporary Art in New York) and her
desire to work in more intuitive and personal ways. Two more
phases, one at the Parrish Museum on Long Island and another
long-term project in Southeast Asia, for which the artist Chen Zhen
is teaching himself to become a Chinese doctor, are planned.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of their quixotic nature, Ms. Morin is passionate
about their necessity. ``I know these projects are like throwing
pebbles in the water,'' she said. ``But they have an amazing
capacity to ripple outward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
