<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6016 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TREATY14-COX     10-13 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREATY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE VOTES TO REJECT NUCLEAR TEST BAN TREATY
 &HT;    750&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A deeply divided Senate voted Wednesday to reject
an international ban on nuclear test explosions, derailing the
centerpiece of the global non-proliferation agenda and dealing
President Clinton a bitter foreign policy defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-48 vote, split along party lines, plunged the treaty into
a sort of legislative purgatory, ending any near-term prospects for
an objective that has eluded the world diplomatic community since
the dawn of the nuclear age.
</P>
<P>
   Treaty proponents pledged to try to resurrect it after the
current Congress adjourns in January 2001, with some expressing
hope that the accord might be strengthened in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   With polls suggesting that eight in 10 Americans support the
treaty, Democrats also signaled they would use the vote as a
political weapon in next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect that this should be, and will be, a national issue
next year in the presidential elections,'' Senate Minority Leader
Tom Daschle, D-S.D., told reporters. ``And we certainly don't want
to preclude the opportunity from speaking out on the issue on the
Senate floor.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the treaty's Republican opponents carried the day by
rallying around the view that the 154-nation pact would risk
undermining the U.S. nuclear arsenal without sufficiently deterring
the efforts of outlaw states and others to build and test atomic
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dangerous treaty,'' said Senate Foreign Relations
Committee Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C. Perhaps the treaty's most
vociferous opponent in the Senate, Helms assailed the accord as
unverifiable and called it ``the most egregious arms control treaty
ever presented to this body.''
</P>
<P>
   The treaty's proponents, however, said the Senate missed an
historic chance to add an important tool, however imperfect, to
global efforts to limit the spread of the most dangerous weapons on
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart aches,'' said Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., who led the
floor debate on behalf of the treaty's proponents. ``This is the
most serious mistake the U.S. Senate has ever made.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., ``With this fateful vote tonight,
the world becomes a more dangerous place.''
</P>
<P>
   In an immediate effort to head off such criticism, Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., ordered a Senate survey of the
global spread of nuclear weapons on Clinton's watch, ``from North
Korea to Iran to Iraq, from China to Russia and from India to
Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   Brushing aside critics who said the treaty's rejection gives a
green light to nations wanting to acquire or expand nuclear weapons
capabilities, Lott said Wednesday's vote sent a more important
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will defeat bad treaties,'' Lott said. ``We did the right
thing for America.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Clinton was the first head of state to sign the accord,
formally called the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty. Since then,
another 153 nations have signed on to the treaty. It cannot take
force, however, without the ratification of 44 nuclear-capable
states, including the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Senate ratification would have required a two-thirds majority
vote. The treaty failed to garner a simple majority, however, as 51
Republicans voted against the measure and only four Republicans _
John Chafee, of Rhode Island, James Jeffords of Vermont, Gordon
Smith of Oregon and Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania _ voted for it.
</P>
<P>
   All Democrats voted in favor of the treaty except Sen. Robert
Byrd, of West Virginia, who simply voted ``present,'' as a protest
against what he regarded as insufficient deliberation and
consideration of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents levied serious substantive charges against the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Tex., objected to the
treaty's ban on test explosions so small that the U.S. intelligence
community cannot detect them. Previous presidents, dating to Dwight
D. Eisenhower, had favored a ban on tests of larger bombs that
would have allowed the United States to conduct test blasts of its
smaller and more sophisticated weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton gave that up,'' Hutchison said. ``No other
president gave in on that issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., said the treaty ``relies more on
hope than fact,'' and would actually raise the danger of atomic
attack by undermining the U.S. nuclear deterrent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children deserve to live in a world free from the threat
of nuclear war,'' Coverdell said in a prepared statement.
``However, the ratification of this treaty would have increased our
nation's vulnerability to such an attack.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Near the heart of the debate, however, also lay a fundamental
difference of world view between those senators, mostly Democrats,
who touted the necessity of collective diplomacy and international
agreements and those lawmakers, chiefly Republican, who vest far
less faith in global institutions and treaties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't know, unfortunately, for another 10 years or so, the
real negative effects of turning down this treaty,'' said Sen. Max
Cleland, D-Ga. ``It's a terrible, terrible, terrifying message to
send.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms, though, scoffed at such talk, saying the key to U.S.
security and influence in a dangerous world is to maintain the
might to command ``a credibility not based on scraps of paper but
on clear American resolve.'''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond any substantive or ideological arguments, the treaty was
undoubtedly roiled by the enmity between Clinton and his Republican
foes at a time of heightened political posturing in the run-up to
next year's presidential and congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   Helms, for his part, even managed to inject into Wednesday's
debate a dig at Clinton over the sex scandal that nearly toppled
his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Belittling a plea for treaty passage by Prime Minister Tony
Blair of Britain, Helms suggested that Blair weighed in only in
deference to Clinton's request.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he (Blair) will say 'Oh I'll do that, I'll do that _ and
give Monica my regards,' '' Helms said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky led to his impeachment by the House last year and
subsequent acquittal by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
