<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6017 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PAKISTAN-COUP-1100&AMP;AD     10-13 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-COUP-1100&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTANIS APPEAR TO ACCEPT COUP BUT WONDER WHAT WILL HAPPEN NEXT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ A day after Pakistan's armed forces seized
power and dismissed the elected government of Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif, the people of Pakistan waited expectantly on Wednesday to
find out who will rule them.
</P>
<P>
   Bureaucrats reported for work, but were left in limbo, as some
ministers had been detained by the army. Traders milled about
outside the Karachi Stock Exchange when it failed to open. So didlers at the country's airports, which remained closed on
Wednesday. Pakistani embassies were paralyzed as staff members were
left to wonder exactly what government they would represent.
</P>
<P>
   The army chief, Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf, said in a nationally
televised speech to the nation early Wednesday morning that he
would soon lay out the army's plans, but by late evening he still
had not revealed whether he would impose martial law, call new
elections or install a civilian government controlled by the
military.
</P>
<P>
   During the day, he met for more than an hour with President
Muhammad Rafiq Tarar and with constitutional law experts,
apparently searching for a way to give a veneer of legitimacy to a
naked coup d'etat. In the hours after the prime minister, Sharif,
announced Tuesday that he was firing Musharraf, the army moved to
take power.
</P>
<P>
   It was still not clear on Wednesday exactly where Sharif, his
brother Shabaz and Lt. Gen. Ziauddin Butt, the intelligence agency
head whom Sharif had named to serve as the new army chief, were
being held.
</P>
<P>
   A senior army officer who spoke on condition of anonymity said
they were still under house arrest at the prime minister's
residence. Other reports suggested they had been shifted to an army
mess.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers on Wednesday arrested key figures in the dismissed
Sharif government, including Brig. Javed Malik, military secretary
to the prime minister, and Mushtaq Tahir, Sharif's political
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   And troops continued to maintain a presence _ albeit a smaller
one _ at Parliament House, the cabinet block, the state-run
television station and the residences of influential ministers of
the dismissed government. They also took over key provincial
government offices.
</P>
<P>
   But there were virtually no signs of public grief on Wednesday
at this latest blow to democracy in a nation that has been ruled by
the military for 25 of its 52 years of independence. Nor were many
shedding tears at the downfall of Sharif, who won in a landslide
electoral victory two-and-a-half years ago but disappointed the
voters' hopes for a stronger economy and an end to public
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, children went to school and adults went to work. There
were no big public protests against the military's actions. In
fact, the only people demonstrating seemed to be those happy about
the coup.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Pakistan was wondering what kind of government its
military will select, India was celebrating the rituals of the
world's biggest democracy: the swearing in of Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee as head of a newly elected government.
   The chasm of distrust between India and Pakistan, which have
both tested nuclear weapons and nuclear-capable missiles in the
last year-and-a-half, has yawned wider since this summer when a
conflict over the Himalayan territory of Kashmir nearly turned into
their fourth war. But Vajpayee, a man with a temperate style,
seemed in a magnanimous mood on Wednesday about Pakistan, not an
alarmist one.
</P>
<P>
   He did not rule out restarting talks with Pakistan, even though
India would now have to negotiate with a government controlled by
Pakistani army leaders who many Indians blame for the
Pakistan-supported occupation of portions of Indian-held Kashmir.
More than 400 Indians died this summer battling to drive those
forces out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish the people of Pakistan well,'' Vajpayee said on
Wednesday. ``We remain committed to developing friendly relations
and cooperative ties with Pakistan based on mutual trust and
confidence for which the government of Pakistan needs to create the
right environment.''
</P>
<P>
   More than any other issue, the Kashmir conflict damaged Sharif's
relationship with the military. Some analysts say army leaders were
angered when the Sharif bowed to American pressure and called for
withdrawal of the Pakistan-supported forces. Others say military
leaders were upset that the prime minister gave the impression that
rogue army officers were to blame for the misadventure, rather than
accepting responsibility himself.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the baldness of Tuesday's power grab by the military,
many Pakistani intellectuals _ people who advocate democracy _ do
not seem outraged about what has happened. As rumors of a possible
coup swirled in recent weeks, scholars, journalists and opposition
politicians have talked about what form a post-coup government
might take.
</P>
<P>
   Ijaz Hussain, chairman of the international relations department
at Quaid-I-Azam University in Islamabad, said one option might be a
government of technocrats whom he described as ``nonpolitical
people who don't have a suspicious past indulging in wrong doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's own authoritarian impulses _ his government's crack
down on critics in the press and its decision to curtail public
demonstrations _ badly undermined his credibility, as did his
failure to deliver good government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the demise of democracy,'' said Najam Sethi,
editor of the Lahore-based weekly, The Friday Times, who was
himself dragged from his home in the middle of the night and
interrogated for over a month before being released. ``It died a
year or two ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Statements from opposition groups, however, betrayed deeper
indignation, even though they have called on the prime minister to
step down for months, alleging he had misruled the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistan People's Party, led by former Prime Minister
Benazir Bhutto, whose own political life has been shrouded by
corruption allegations, demanded new elections under an interim
government. Ms. Bhutto herself remains in London in a kind of
self-imposed exile.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike previous military coups, Musharraf has so far not
declared martial law, which would dissolve parliament and abrogate
or suspend the constitution. He has thus left the country, for the
time being at least, suspended in a kind of legal and political
limbo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can very well understand that this is not something that
one expects to happen every day,'' one officer, Brig. Rashid
Qureshi, told the BBC on Wednesday. ``And whatever was done, it was
a spontaneous reaction actually by the army to what actions, and
wrong action, Mr. Nawaz Sharif had taken.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Whatever its motivations, it is nearly certain to place at risk
billions of dollars in loans and assistance from international
lenders and Western governments that Pakistan cannot afford to
alientate.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Paris, the head of the International Monetary Fund,
Michel Camdessus, said he was ``not certain'' whether the fund
could ofistance to Pakistan after Tuesday's events.
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said in London that he
would meet with the representatives of Commonwealth nations, which
would consider a ``collective response'' to the coup. ``Any country
under military rule qualifies itself for suspension,'' Cook said.
``As for other steps, it is too early to say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
