<HEADLINE>
TEXAS JURY ACQUITS COUNTRY SINGER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UVALDE, Texas _ Country singer Johnny Rodriguez was acquitted of
murder Wednesday in the shooting death of a drunken acquaintance
who he found in his mother's house in the pre-dawn hours after a
drinking party nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, whose voice propelled him to country music stardom in
the 1970s, was charged with killing 26-year-old Israel ``Bosco''
Borrego, on Aug. 29, 1998, in the ranching community of Sabinal. If
convicted, he could have been sentenced to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   A jury of six men and six women deliberated two hours before
delivering a verdict that left Borrego's widow and other relatives
in tears and prompted cheers from Rodriguez supporters and extended
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just sorry that the whole incident took place,'' Rodriguez
said later. ``I don't want to go through anything like this
again.''
</P>
<P>
   He later went up to Uvalde County District Attorney Tony
Hackebeil, hugged him, called him a ``peckerwood,'' and said he had
no hard feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reflection of the conscience of the community,'' the
prosecutor said of the verdict. ``Obviously the jury feels Johnny
was justified in taking the actions he did, even though it resulted
in taking the life of Israel Borrego.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's lawyers had argued that he was justified under Texas
law to defend himself and his property. The singer's mother was not
living in the house at the time of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the verdict, local residents had said an acquittal
wouldn't surprise them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around here if you find somebody in your house at night,
they're toast,'' said a Uvalde gun dealer.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, the jury learned that Borrego was on felony
probation for four separate burglaries in Sabinal. He also had an
extensive criminal history of arrests for drunk driving, public
intoxication, assault and criminal trespass.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Rodriguez's testified that Borrego was suspected of
breaking into Rodriguez's home two weeks before the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hackebeil sought to portray Rodriguez as drunken and
angry _ not fearful _ when he discovered Borrego preparing
breakfast in the kitchen of his mother's home.
</P>
<P>
   And a police officer testified that when he arrived on the scene
after Borrego was shot, Rodriguez was viciously kicking the wounded
man, as he lay moaning on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez is best known for his 1970s hits such as ``Pass Me
By'' (If You're Only Passing Through) and ``Ridin' My Thumb to
Mexico,'' which soared into the Top 10 on the country charts. His
career took a downturn by the 1990s, but he still plays weekend
gigs in South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my mind will be a little more clear now. I think I'm
going to cut back on the drinking, too. I've learned a little about
that,'' he told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez has struggled over the years with drug and alcohol
addiction. In 1994, he was jailed for public intoxication after he
and a Nashville guitarist got into a fight in a Weslaco lounge.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said Wednesday that he had booked a singing date this
weekend in the Houston suburb of Rosenberg ``just in case,'' but he
didn't have definite plans beyond that other than trying to write
some new songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think that far ahead right now,'' he said. ``I think
I'm going to go barbecue me some little ribs or something.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
