<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> no timestamp </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FED-MARKETPLACE-(TRIM     10-13 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-MARKETPLACE-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: THE FED LEANS IN, AND THE MARKETS PULL BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Federal Reserve policy makers want to, they
can still stir the pot on Wall Street. Their Oct. 5 decision to
leave their interest rate target unchanged at 5.25 percent but to
hint at a future increase in rates has left investors uncertain,
tripped up stocks and pushed long-term interest rates near a
two-year high.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks tumbled Wednesday after Intel Corp. announced
disappointing third quarter earnings late Tuesday and interest
rates moved higher. The Nasdaq composite index dropped 2.48 percent
while the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks dropped 2.09
percent. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 1.77 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the yield on the 30-year bond jumped to 6.27
percent, its high since Aug. 12 and just below 6.28 percent in
October 1997. The yield on the two-year note, which is more
sensitive to the threat of Fed interest rate increases, jumped to
5.83 percent, its highest since October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed policy-makers did not say this was their intent when
they released their statement explaining what they decided after
the policy-making session earlier this month. They would not do
that. But the members of the Federal Open Market Committee are
savvy and had to know that the uncertainty about the next rate
increase would have an impact on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Fed policy-makers have been worrying about the rally in the
stock market all year because the gains are spurring consumer
spending through what is called the wealth effect. Even after
Wednesday's declines, the Dow is up 11.44 percent so far this year,
and the Nasdaq has jumped 27.58 percent this year. Consumer
spending has been the driving force of an economy that is growing
at a 4 percent pace, much faster than the Fed would like.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Governor Laurence H. Meyer has been talking
about the problem of the stock market and how it effects the
central bank's interest rate policy for some time. He realizes that
the danger of a rate increase to cool the stock market is that
investors could overreact, setting off a big sell-off that could
damage the economy rather than slow it.
</P>
<P>
   Policy-makers, he said in a speech last month, ``should be alert
to the potential that a tightening of policy could have a
disproportionate effect on demand, if it induces a reassessment of
market fundamentals.''
</P>
<P>
   So maybe no rate increase but a lean toward higher rates is a
step in between.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Fed is disappointed in seeing the stock
market stabilizing or moving lower,'' said Joseph Abate, senior
economist at Lehman Brothers. ``A little bit of uncertainty about
the outlook for monetary policy is not necessarily a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   With the sell-off this week, the Dow has given back the 4.3
percent rally that started at the end of September. Equity
investors are jittery, although third quarter earnings overall are
supposed to be strong followed by a good fourth quarter. But if the
interest rate worries subside, the earnings outlook _ backed by
some important companies beating expectations _ could give stocks a
lift again.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Louis Crandall, chief economist at R.H. Wrightson &AMP; Associates,
said that if the Fed had increased its short-term interest rate
target a quarter of a percentage point to 5.50 percent Oct. 5, many
investors would have taken that as a all-clear signal for the year.
And that could have opened the door for stocks to move higher.
</P>
<P>
   What is adding to the negative environment now is the
anticipation of reports of rising inflation in September at both
the producer and consumer levels. Although analysts argue that the
jumps are caused by the recent increases in tobacco prices, in oil
prices last month to just under $25 a barrel, and the subsequent
jump in gasoline prices, they are still disturbing investors.
</P>
<P>
   The core rate for the September producer price index of finished
goods, which excludes food and energy, is forecast to rise 0.5
percent, well above the trend for the year. For the Consumer Price
Index, the core rate is forecast to jump 0.3 percent, the biggest
move since April and well above the trend for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Although economists are telling Wall Street traders that these
jumps in September inflation gauges are not signaling a trend, they
do not want to make you buy bonds a week after Fed policy-makers
said they were leaning toward a rate increase, Crandall said. ``If
buyers see reasons to sit on their hands for a period of time,'' he
added, ``the market suffers for it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, although September retail sales, which will be
reported Thursday, are expected to slow to an increase of 0.2
percent, that is coming after two months of 1 percent or more
growth. And that means the economy may not be slowing fast enough
to satisfy the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Crandall said that the threat of a weakening dollar is also
worrying investors. The dollar is down sharply against the yen this
year but has leveled off recently. But it is not yet clear if steps
taken by the Bank of Japan Wednesday will really lead to an easier
monetary policy there that could end the dollar's decline.
</P>
<P>
   But the dollar, which has rallied for most of the year against
the euro, could turn around, especially if growth here slows while
it is picking up in Europe. A steady dollar decline against the
euro, Crandall said, would make investment by Europeans in the
United States less attractive because the weaker dollar would
reduce their returns when translated back into euros. That would
slow foreign investment in both stocks and bonds here, taking away
an important prop for both markets.
</P>
<P>
   However, a rise in interest rates _ home mortgage rates are
still near their highs foyear _ and a modest slump in the
stock market could help change the mood of investors by slowing
economic growth enough to get Fed policy makers less worried about
the tight labor market and rises in wages and commodity prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
