<SLUG> BC-TEST-BAN-TREATY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REJECTS NUCLEAR TEST BAN TREATY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET; see also
TREATY-ASSESS) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT26 is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Wednesday rejected a treaty banning
all underground nuclear testing in a 51-48 vote that crushed one of
the major arms initiatives of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, largely along
party lines, followed a weeklong power play among Senate
Republicans, Democrats and the White House to forestall the defeat
of the treaty by delaying action until after President Clinton
leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   In a last-ditch effort to save the treaty, Clinton called the
Republican leader, Trent Lott, two hours before the vote and asked
that he delay action for national security reasons. In a blunt
rebuff, Lott told the president that what he offered was too
little, too late, and he pushed ahead with an action he knew would
humiliate Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The vote marked the first time that the Senate defeated a major
international security pact since the Treaty of Versailles,
creating the League of Nations, failed to win Senate approval in
1920. While the Senate and White House often joust on legislation
governing domestic issues, in matters of national security senators
of both parties have usually deferred to the president.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the treaty to clear the Senate raised serious
questions about its survival. Supporters of the treaty, in
Washington and abroad, had argued that if it was not adopted by the
United States, other nuclear nations, ranging from Pakistan and
India to Russia and China, would follow suit, denying the 1996
treaty the 44 ratifications it needs to go into force. The leaders
of Britain, France and Germany had urged the Senate to postpone the
vote.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6026 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-AIR-POLLUTION-ART-     10-13 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AIR-POLLUTION-ART-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI WILL ORDER POWER PLANTS TO CUT EMISSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds. note: budgeted on one advisory as NY-ACID-RAIN) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gov. George Pataki will order power plants in the
state to make sharp cuts in the smokestack emissions that cause
acid rain and smog, his aides said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The move will raise the state's electricity rates by 1 percent
to 2 percent, they said, but it will put New York substantially
ahead of the rest of the country in the cleanup schedule set by the
federal Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, who is expected to outline the plan at a news conference
Thursday, will order cuts in two kinds of pollution: sulfur
dioxide, the main cause of acid rain, and nitrogen oxides, which
cause smog and also contribute to acid rain, administration
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   While an impending federal rule would require cuts in nitrogen
oxides only in the summer, when smog is at its worst, the new New
York state regulations would require the same reductions all year,
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Word of Pataki's plans pleased both environmental groups seeking
cleaner air and power companies with proposals to build new
natural-gas power plants in the state. These plants are costly to
build but produce much less pollution than the old coal-burning
plants that dominate in western New York. Under the new rules, the
gas-fired plants will be able to compete against coal plants,
energy experts say, because the coal plants will have to invest in
expensive systems to filter pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very exciting and bold move by the governor,'' said
Ned Sullivan, the executive director of Scenic Hudson, a private
environmental group. ``No other state has mandated this level of
reduction for acid rain control.''
</P>
<P>
   The slight increase in electric rates would be more than offset
by the environmental benefits, said John Cahill, the state
commissioner of environmental conservation. ``No one could dispute
now that New York has done more than any other state in the country
to control emissions from its sources,'' Cahill said Wednesday,
after describing the plan. In addition, he said, the New York plan
could add momentum to efforts in Congress to pass federal
legislation that would require similar reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of some of the state's coal-fired plants, which sit
mainly in western New York and the upper Hudson Valley, said they
could not comment on specifics until after the Pataki
administration released details Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But some said they planned to comply with whatever new standards
emerged once the new regulations were written. ``Our goal is always
to meet or exceed environmental standards,'' said Frank Rapley, a
spokesman for NRG Energy Inc., a Minneapolis company that recently
bought two of the biggest power plants in the state, Dunkirk and
C.R. Huntley, near Buffalo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Starting next year, a provision of the Clean Air Act will
require a 35 percent reduction in nitrogen oxide emissions from
power plants, but only from May through September. The state would
require the same reduction throughout the year. As a result, annual
emissions would drop from levels like those seen in 1998 _ 102,000
tons _ to 62,000 tons a year, according to state environmental
officials. That level is 20,000 tons less than the federal rule
would allow, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The planned reductions in sulfur dioxide emissions would be even
sharper, dropping from more than 300,000 tons a year _ the level in
1998 _ to less than 130,000 tons a year, with the reduction being
phased in from 2003 to 2007, Cahill said. Under the Clean Air Act,
New York would only be required to cut its sulfur dioxide pollution
to 262,000 tons a year, according to state officials.
</P>
<P>
   A spate of recent studies has shown that pollution cuts called
for under the Clean Air Act will not be sufficient to repair damage
to forests, streams and lakes around the Northeast from acidic rain
and snow.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, New York environmental officials calculate, only 17 to
20 percent of the acid rain problem in the Adirondacks and other
areas upstate comes from pollution produced by New York's own power
plants. The rest comes from coal-fired power plants in the Middle
West and South, Cahill said.
</P>
<P>
   New York has been locked in a dispute for a decade with those
states.
</P>
<P>
   By moving to cut its own pollution, Cahill said, the state can
increase the pressure on them to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the federal Environmental Protection Agency said
that some of Pataki's planned cuts in power-plant pollution would
have been required anyway. Some states downwind of New York have
petitioned the EPA to force some of New York's old coal-fired
plants to cut pollution that drifts east and contributes to
problems.
</P>
<P>
   But they conceded that some of New York's moves, particularly
the cut in nitrogen oxides throughout the year, went beyond
anything done by any other states.
</P>
<P>
   Many private environmental groups were delighted by the Pataki
plan. ``It sets a new tone, and increases New York's commitment to
putting more pressure on Washington to make it all happen,'' said
Ashok Gupta, an economist at the Natural Resources Defense Council.
But, he said that if Congress did not quickly follow suit with
stronger federal laws, it might still be possible in several years
for New York to retreat.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate development, state Attorney General L. Spitzer,
who is investigating eight of New York's older power plants for
possible violations of federal and state pollution rules, sent
letters Tuesday to their owners requesting hundreds of pages of
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer announced in September that he planned to sue the owners
of power plants in upwind states, on the ground that their
pollution harmed New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Larry Shapiro, a lawyer for the New York Public
Interest Research Group, a lobbying and environmental organization,
the moves by Pataki and Spitzer show that New York is finally
getting serious about stanching the flow of air pollution, whether
its source is smokestacks in upwind states or in New York itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to lead by example,'' Shapiro said, ``and
that's what the governor's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many air pollution experts said that the maneuvers implied a
significant amount of political competition for credit as New York
moved toward cutting pollution, with the Republican governor and
Democratic attorney general eager to be perceived as a leader on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But Darren Dopp, a spokesman for Spitzer, said the end result
was a good one. ``The bottom line is that a little competition
between us and them is good for the air,'' he said Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
