<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6028 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-RAYTHEON-TROUBLES-BOS     10-13 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-TROUBLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPECTED COST SAVINGS, PROFITS ELUDE RAYTHEON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A round of consolidation in the defense industry in recent years
was supposed to produce big cost savings and profits for the
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   But things haven't worked out that way for Raytheon Co., the
nation's third-largest defense contractor, whose class B shares
tumbled 44 percent on Tuesday to close at 24 1/4 after it outlined
big revenue and earnings shortfalls; shares lost another 1 5/8 in
trading Wednesday to close at 22 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosures included a confession by Raytheon chief
executive Daniel Burnham that the company had blown its attempts to
integrate operations it purchased in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, we tried to do too much too fast,'' he told
analysts and reporters in a marathon three-hour teleconference,
reviewing a plethora of cases where profits had fallen below
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham vowed to do better, but the news left analysts
struggling to comprehend the outlook for the company, based in
Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The disappointing earnings news also served as a reminder that
despite modest growth in defense spending, contractors such as
Raytheon and its troubled rival, Lockheed Martin Corp., must find
ways to build sales, particularly in often-lucrative overseas
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The lower costs Raytheon had hoped to obtain from its
acquisitions _ the declared rationale for many mergers _ ``clearly
appear to have been over-estimated,'' said Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette analyst Joe Nadol. He downgraded Raytheon's stock from
``buy'' to ``market perform'' despite its lower price.
</P>
<P>
   Nadol said he worries whether Raytheon can achieve the
additional foreign sales it needs to drive earnings growth. ``I'm
not convinced we have a full grip on what the ongoing profitability
in their defense business is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense industry consolidation moved into high gear in 1995 with
the merger of Lockheed Corp. and Martin Marietta Corp. Over the
next two years Boeing Corp. purchased Rockwell International and
McDonnell Douglas. The Pentagon blessed all these deals, mindful of
a procurement budget that had fallen to $43.1 billion in 1995 from
its 1985 peak of $90 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon didn't join the merger-and-acquisitions game until
1997, however, and when it did, it set the ambitious goals of
integrating simultaneously two giant defense units purchased from
Texas Instruments Inc. and Hughes Electronics Corp. for a total of
$12.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Those purchases doubled Raytheon's annual revenue to about $20
billion and brought it control of many new products such as the
Hughes' Tomahawk cruise missile.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts expected that Raytheon's reputation for good
management meant the company would assimiliate the new units
straightaway, said Jon Kutler, president of Quarterdeck Investment
Partners, a Los Angeles-based investment bank that has worked for
Raytheon on other deals.
</P>
<P>
   But the company now admits it had difficulty keeping track of
finances made more complex by the acquisitions that added dozens of
new facilities and thousands more employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``By trying to do it all at once they basically upped the bar,''
Kutler said in a telephone interview Wednesday. ``Raytheon had the
reputation of being great managers, and people thought they could
pull it off. In hindsight, maybe there was a happy medium in terms
of the speed they could have attempted.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Raytheon must prove it can boost overseas sales of products
like its Patriot ground-to-air missile, which command higher profit
margins than do sales to the Pentagon. Overseas revenue accounted
for 26 percent of Raytheon's business last year, down from 29
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Along with its gloomy earnings forecast, Raytheon on Tuesday
said it would cut 2,380 jobs, including 340 positions in
Massachusetts and New Hampshire, for which it would take a charge
of about $92 million this year. The figures include 140 workers who
will lose their jobs at Raytheon's Lexington headquarters, but the
company hasn't specified which other facilities will be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Raytheon spokesman David Polk said the company is
continuing to hire software engineers and other white-collar
employees, and that total Massachusetts employment at the end of
the year will be about 13,700, or the same as last summer.
Worldwide, Raytheon now has 108,000 employees, although the company
was unable to say how many workers it will have after the current
round of layoffs is complete.
</P>
<P>
   One group of workers whose jobs appear safe are the 1,000
workers at a Portsmouth, R.I., facility where Raytheon builds naval
electronics systems.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of positions already have been shed at Portsmouth in
recent years, but a spokesman for US Representative Patrick
Kennedy, a Democrat whose congressional district includes
Portsmouth, said Wednesday Raytheon executives told them recently
no further cuts are planned there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
