<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-INQUIRE-ART-38     10-13 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-INQUIRE-ART-385(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATORS AGAIN BLOCK YELTSIN'S BID TO FIRE GADFLY PROSECUTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT40 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN and MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Three times now, President Boris Yeltsin has tried to
get rid of a troublesome prosecutor general whose investigations
into corruption have crept inside the Kremlin itself.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday, Yeltsin failed for the third time. Russia's
increasingly rebellious Federation Council, the upper house of
parliament, rebuffed yet another attempt to fire Yuri Skuratov, who
sealed his political fate in Russia one year ago by signing a
secret order initiating a criminal investigation into links between
top Kremlin officials and a Swiss construction company, Mabetex
Project Engineering.
</P>
<P>
   That investigation, given new life recently by a stream of leaks
in both Russia and Switzerland, has offered evidence suggesting,
among other things, that Mabetex, which did considerable work in
Russia, bankrolled shopping sprees by Yeltsin's two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, after eight months of limbo since the first attempt
to oust him, and with eight months to go before Russia is scheduled
to elect a president, Skuratov again put his case to the Federation
Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``The masks have been cast off and the situation has become as
simple as it can be,'' he said. ``Either we all try to stem the
tide of corruption and salvage whatever authority our country still
has in the world community _ and I am prepared to work with your
support _ or the Federation Council will follow the path indicated
for it by the corrupt Kremlin officials.''
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 98-52, the council _ made up of regional leaders
now at the focus of Russia's intense and vicious power struggle _
again took Skuratov's side.
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov's next battle to win back his old job will be in
Russia's Constitutional Court, which is scheduled this week to
examine Yeltsin's order to suspend him pending a criminal
investigation hurriedly prepared against him last April. The heart
of that case is a video, broadcast March 18 on a state-owned
television channel, that showed Skuratov in bed with two
prostitutes allegedly provided by businessmen under investigation
by the prosecutor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Turned out of his office, Skuratov has continued to occupy an
ample government dacha on the outskirts of Moscow provided,
paradoxically, by the Kremlin property administration headed by
Yeltsin's friend Pavel Borodin, who is the principal target of the
Mabetex inquiry.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   His armored Mercedes has been replaced by a Russian-made Volga
sedan, and his salary has shriveled to about $60 a month.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, his dacha, his Moscow apartment and even his
mother-in-law's apartment have been searched by government
investigators. He said they had confiscated videos of family
birthday parties, as well as 13 of 14 suits made by a
Kremlin-favored tailor, which his enemies say were actually a gift
from Mabetex.
</P>
<P>
   But Skuratov has refused to stay silent. And his periodic salvos
against the Yeltsin administration, delivered to a steady stream of
visiting journalists, have become part of the background noise for
the political battle to control who succeeds the president, and
what Yeltsin's legacy will be.
</P>
<P>
   In all this, Skuratov remains a curious figure. Not everyone
accepts his portrayal of himself as a lonely crusader against
corruption. Some point to his friendly relations with some of the
most hard-line members of the Communist opposition. Others say he
is no better than the people he investigates.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, however, Skuratov comes back to the tale of the
Mabetex investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attempts are being made to destroy the Mabetex case, to show
that it is all politics,'' Skuratov said recently in a lengthy
interview in his dacha dining room. ``But I won't allow it to
happen because I paid for it with my own career. I simply won't
allow the case to be destroyed. It is a method of self-defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The secret order initiating the Mabetex case was the key that
unleashed a Swiss-Russian investigation that is still in progress.
Documents seized in a search of the Mabetex offices in Lugano,
Switzerland, and brought to Moscow last spring contained evidence
that Mabetex had provided credit cards to Yeltsin and his two
daughters, Tatyana Dyachenko and Yelena Okulova, Skuratov said. The
documents also indicated that Mabetex paid for purchases made on
those cards, which amounted to tens of thousands of dollars, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone conversation in September with President Clinton,
Yeltsin denied the allegations against him and his daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov is fighting his suspensions in the courts, but
acknowledges that he is unlikely to get his job back _ at least not
until there is a change in Russia's leadership. And he plays a
prominent part in the power tussles preceding the elections for
Parliament in December and for president next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closer we get to a change in power, now less than a year
away, the more those who know things feel on firmer ground,'' said
Pavel Voshchanov, a former press secretary to Yeltsin. ``And
corruption in Russia is a tree that has its roots at the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov denies that his pursuit of the Mabetex investigation is
politically motivated. But he makes no secret of his admiration for
Yevgeny Primakov, the former prime minister who was also fired by
Yelt-sin for failing to pass the Kremlin's increasingly pointed
loyalty tests, and who is now a leading candidate to become the
next president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pin great hopes on Primakov,'' Skuratov said. He said
Primakov allowed him to investigate Russia's oligarchs and the
Yeltsin family.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov, 47, the son of a police officer, began his career as a
law professor in Sverdlovsk, now renamed Yekaterinburg, which is
also Yeltsin's hometown. He wathusiastic supporter of
Yelt-sin, first as the local Communist Party boss and later as the
leader of the democratic reform movement.
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov came to Moscow in 1989 to join the staff of the law
department of the Communist Party's Central Committee. By 1991 he
was a member of the Yeltsin team, as adviser to the Se
Ministry _ the old KGB _ and later as one of the drafters of the
1993 Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   When he was named chief prosecutor in October 1995, the
opposition welcomed him as someone who was politically unengaged.
</P>
<P>
   His first break with the Yeltsin team, he said, came in the 1996
elections when he opened an investigation into two top Yeltsin
campaign aides who were caught leaving the Kremlin with a box
containing $550,000 in cash. Skuratov said he soon learned that
Kremlin denials of the event were false, and top Kremlin aides
pressed him to drop the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since then the president has held me in distrust,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks before his suspension, Skuratov said, he tried to
reach Yeltsin to inform him that evidence of his daughters'
shopping sprees had turned up in the Swiss investigation. When he
failed to get a meeting with the President, Skuratov said, he
reported it to Primakov, who told him it was his duty to carry on
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that when Yeltsin called him last March to tell him
he was being ousted, Primakov, who was present along with Vladimir
Putin, now prime minister, did not object.
</P>
<P>
   He said the original investigation into Mabetex was begun by the
German and Italian tax police, who were investigating the ``huge
turnover'' in Mabetex-related bank accounts. Carla del Ponte, then
the Swiss federal prosecutor, asked Skuratov whether he was
interested in pursuing it at his end.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could I say I was not interested in that?'' he asked.
``She would say that Skuratov is not interested in corruption in
the top echelons of power in Russia, that he is a prosecutor who is
afraid of everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also understood one more thing,'' he said. ``Sooner or
later, these materials would come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his suspension, the tempo of the Mabetex investigation in
Russia has slowed. But Skuratov, helped by television stations and
newspapers whose owners have also broken with the Kremlin, has kept
up the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   This month he gave an interview to NTV, a private television
channel, in which he said for the first time that Mabetex had paid
$10 million to $15 million in bribes to Russian officials, a figure
he said came from the Swiss prosecutors. He also called on
Yeltsin's daughters to make a public accounting of the reported
credit card charges.
</P>
<P>
   Within days officials raided Skuratov's dacha and his apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course the family is afraid,'' he said. ``Now they control
the situation, but it may get out of hand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6040 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      10-13 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILT CHAMBERLAIN: GIANT CONTRADICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ To the generation of basketball fans who have grown up
since Wilt Chamberlain retired: You have no idea.
</P>
<P>
   Not just about the the enormity of the man, who was then dwarfed
by his staggering accomplishments. But about the contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   The only player to lead the NBA in scoring, rebounds and assists
could not execute consistently a basketball action often mastered
by 12-year-olds: The free throw.
</P>
<P>
   When the nation in 1968 was shaken by a civil rights movement
seeking long-denied justice, Chamberlain,who along with Muhammad
Ali may have been the world's most prominent black athletes,
endorsed Richard Nixon for president.
</P>
<P>
   The man who once averaged 48.5 minutes in a season for a
48-minute game (he played overtimes too) was sometimes criticized
for lacking competitive heart.
</P>
<P>
   For a player who remade basketball for all future big men, who
forced the rules writers to rejigger the game, who was the
7-foot-1, 275-pound acme of basketball's majestic power, his most
frequent contact with the game in his retirement was as a spectator
at Los Angeles Clippers' contests, where he was a pal of the club's
vile owner, Donald Sterling.
</P>
<P>
   For all his imagery as an invincible titan, he was probably too
soft, fearful of his power to injure. Said longtime rival and
friend Bill Russell of Chamberlain's famous 1970 Finals showdown
with gimpy-legged Willis Reed, who led the Knicks to victory over
the Lakers partly because Chamberlain seemed to back off:
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm the one playing Willis when he comes out limping, it
would only have emphasized my goal to beat them that much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the behemoth Lothario who claimed to have bedded 20,000
women died Tuesday at home in bed, alone, never married.
</P>
<P>
   A man bigger than nearly all men and nearly all description,
Chamberlain's contradictions make him that much richer a character,
and so much more than a great ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his ballplaying greatness has somehow been warped, not only
with time but through the green filter of Russell, his nemesis,
rival and friend whose unmatched career seemed fated to compromise
the game's most powerful, agile giant.
</P>
<P>
   As the pair locked up in a goateed grind in the low post
throughout the 1960s, it was Russell's Celtics who almost always
were superior to Chamberlain's Warriors, 76ers and Lakers teams.
Watching the NBA evolve on fuzzy black-and-white TVs, it seemed
that every winter Sunday was incomplete without at least a few
minutes spent watching Russell barely outmaneuver his formidable
adversary.
</P>
<P>
   Sports theater was rarely better. To witness two such skilled,
intelligent, dramatic rivals directly pitted against each other for
most of a decade was a national privilege, made all the more rare
by sports' failure to produce its like again.
</P>
<P>
   Russell's teams won 11 championships in 13 years, and he was
recently selected Sports Illustrated's greatest team player of all
time. Chamberlain's Philadelphia team of 1966-67 and his Laker team
of 1971-72 won titles, but it was never enough, even though those
teams may have been the best in league history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all judged by the championships we win,'' said forlorn
Laker president Jerry West Tuesday, talking about his former
teammate and fellow 40-year hoop icon. ``Unfortunately, he only won
two.''
</P>
<P>
   Only won two.
</P>
<P>
   Think about that. Consider how many NBA greats, particularly in
the Michael Jordan era, never won a single one. But Chamberlain
seems forever consigned to secondary status because his foil had so
many more.
</P>
<P>
   The heat of their battle long since faded to cold embers,
Russell articulated, during the NBA All-Star game in 1997 that
featured the selection of its 50 greatest players, the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody seems to appreciate what an incredible player Wilt
was,'' he said. ``He was the best player of all time because he
dominated the floor like nobody else ever could. To be that big and
athletic was special.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be blasphemous in the recently concluded era of Jordan.
Comparisons between eras are always murky, as well as comparisons
between different positions. But there is one fact that usually
escapes consideration in the argument.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA of Chamberlain's time had about 100 players. The NBA
when Jordan dominated swelled to more than 300, meaning he came up
against nowhere near the caliber of competition Chamberlain took on
every night. Whether it was Russell or Reed, or Nate Thurmond, Walt
Bellamy or Wes Unseld, Chamberlain almost always ran into a quality
foe.
</P>
<P>
   He crushed 'em all.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the freakish, 100-point game. Those 50-point, 28-rebound
games that he (begin italic) averaged (end italic) didn't come
against Jim McIlvaine or Greg Ostertag. While 30 years of gene-pool
splashings may have improved the caliber of the average NBA
athlete, 30 years of expansion have spread those athletes around
much more broadly.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain in his prime today would be even more dominant than
in his day, because of the flatness of the surrounding territory.
And owing to growth of the NBA's popularity and the increase in
media coverage, his blunt, sometimes reckless personality would be
even more immense.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a Dennis Rodman with brains, sophistication and
multidimensional talent.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1983 biography ``Giant Steps,'' Kareem Abdul-Jabbar wrote
about his hero worship as a kid of Chamberlain, his brief playing
rivalry as their careers crossed in the early 1970s, and of his
later contempt for his personal politics.
</P>
<P>
   But the game's giants eventually patched things up. And although
the book is filled with Abdul-Jabbar's belief of his superiority
over Chamberlain, he knew that in psychological as well as physical
stature, there was no one in the public mind quite like
Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Jabbar wrote: ``In airplanes and subways, on movie lines
or in the street, all big black guys were asked not, `Are you Bill
Russell?' but `Are you Wilt?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In his greatness, his contradictions and his foibles,
Chamberlain was a magnificent American original _ outsized, all
ways.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
