<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6044 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-LUNGCANCER-BLACKS     10-13 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LUNGCANCER-BLACKS-ART-(TRIMS) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKS LESS LIKELY TO HAVE LUNG CANCER SURGERY, SAYS STUDY  
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Black patients with early-stage lung cancer are less
likely than whites to undergo life-saving surgery, and as a result
are more likely to die of their disease, doctors are reporting
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter B. Bach, a lung specialist at Memorial Sloan-Kettering
Cancer Center in Manhattan and an author of the report, said the
for the disparity was unknown. But Bach said it was not
because of the differences between the races in socioeconomic
status, insurance, general health or access to medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Among the possible causes, the researchers said, are that
doctors do not recommend surgery to blacks as often as to whites,
or that blacks more often refuse surgery, perhaps because of poor
doctor-patient communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad situation where patients with potentially curable
disease are not having surgical treatment and therefore are
dying,'' Bach said. He and his co-authors said it was imperative
that doctors acted to make sure that black patients got the lung
surgery they needed. ``It's extremely important that we figure out
what's happening,'' Bach said. ``We're talking about saving a lot
of lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The study by Bach and three other researchers is being published
Thursday in the New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hugh Stallworth, a national vice president of the American
Cancer Society, said, ``This study suggests that, possibly,
physicians are treating cancer patients not just based upon their
illness and recommended treatment, but on the basis of their
race.'' Stallworth said other studies had also suggested that the
providers of health care treated patients differently on the basis
of race or ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   ``So this is not new,'' Stallworth said. ``But each time we hear
it, it's surprising and rather shocking, specifically as it relates
to cancer. It's quite concerning.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Bach said that the findings come at a critical period in
lung cancer research in the United States. A study published in
July suggested that a test called spiral C.T., or computed
tomography, could detect lung cancers at an earlier stage than
standard methods, and increase the rate of cure for the disease. If
that test fulfills its promise, and nothing is done to eliminate
the racial disparity, the gap in the lung cancer death rate might
even increase.
</P>
<P>
   Lung cancer is the leading cause of cancer death in the United
States, killing more than 150,000 people a year. The people in
Bach's study all had the most common form of the disease,
non-small-cell lung cancer. The study was based on the medical
records of 10,984 patients (860 black and 10,124 white) 65 years
old and over who were found to have an early stage of the disease
from 1985 to 1993. Surgery is the treatment of choice for such
patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without surgery, half the patients are dead in a year,'' Bach
said. ``With surgery, it takes more than four years for half to
die.''
</P>
<P>
   Among whites, 76.7 percent had surgery. But only 64 percent of
the blacks did.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every five whites that had surgery, only four blacks
did,'' Bach said.
</P>
<P>
   Survival differed as well: five years after the diagnosis, 34.1
percent of whites, but only 26.4 percent of blacks, were still
alive. But when patients who had surgery were compared, five-year
survival rates were similar: 42.9 percent for whites, 39.1 percent
for blacks; the difference was not meaningful statistically, and
may have been due in part to the fact the overall longevity is
lower for blacks than for whites.
</P>
<P>
   The authors studied people 65 and over because medical
information on them was available through the Medicare program.
They cautioned that it is not known if the findings applied to
younger patients.
</P>
<P>
   The records did not disclose why some patients did not have
surgery. But Bach said they provided enough information to prove
that the unequal surgery rates could not be blamed on differences
between the races in socioeconomic status, insurance, sex,
complicating illnesses or access to care. Rather, the disparity
appeared to depend entirely on race itself, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   But the researchers could not say if doctors were less likely to
recommend surgery to black patients, or if black patients
themselves were more likely to refuse surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But Stallworth said, ``I can't believe that number of people
would not avail themselves of the recommended treatment, if the
information is presented in the right way, in a sensitive and
knowledgeable way.''
</P>
<P>
   But there may be communication gaps, he said. If doctor and
patient cannot establish a rapport, the patient may be reluctant to
take the doctor's advice, and the doctor may give up, feeling he or
she has made a good-faith effort to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that patients, black and white, feel more comfortable
with physicians that are like them, look like them and sound like
them,'' Stallworth said. ``And physicians relate better to patients
who are more like them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, 12 percent of the population is black, but
only 4 percent of doctors are.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``What has been suggested is that we may need to look at our
medical training programs and begin to introduce some type of
cultural sensitivity,'' Stallworth said. ``Some would even go
further and say we need to introduce some human sensitivity. This
transcends culture. It's one human being talking to another human
being.''
</P>
<P>
   It has also been suggested that more minority doctors are
needed, but Stallworth said that while he agreed, that was no way
to solve cultural misunderstandings. If doctor and patient cannot
communicate, regardless of racial background, ``you have a serious,
serious problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial accompanying the study, Dr. Talmadge E. King
Jr., chief of Medical Services at San Francisco General Hospital,
said racial differences could be a barrier to effective
communication. ``I think there's a very, very complex interaction
we need to understand better so that we can partner with patients
who may not feel comfortable interacting with us,'' King said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   King said that at his hospital, more than half the patients were
black or Hispanic, and 20 percent were Chinese. Each group, he
said, has slightly different attitudes about medical care.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge issue we deal with,'' King said. ``We are
acutely aware of it, and trying to do better.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   King, who is black, said that some black patients tended to be a
bit more fatalistic and religious than whites, and to believe that
God would take care of them.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Because of those beliefs, he said, it can be harder to convince
them that treatment is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``If a patient is talking to a majority physician who is not
familiar with the background and and doesn't think through how to
approach this patient, there can be delays in care,'' King said.
``And the patient moves from being an operable candidate to
becoming inoperable during this period of miscommunication. This is
a ticking time bomb.''
</P>
</TEXT>
