<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUCHANAN-REFORM-ART-N     10-13 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-REFORM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN APPEARS TO MOVE CLOSER TO SEEKING REFORM PARTY'S
NOMINATION
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT33 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the clearest indication yet that he is planning
to break with the Republican Party, Pat Buchanan has begun
notifying supporters that he will make a major speech on Oct. 25 in
Falls Church, Va., where he is widely expected to announce that he
will seek the Reform Party's nomination for president.
</P>
<P>
   Though Buchanan, the conservative commentator and former adviser
to Presidents Reagan and Nixon, has been signaling for weeks that
he would try to run on a third-party line, his campaign said on
Wednesday night that Buchanan had still not made a final decision
about his political future.
</P>
<P>
   But a close adviser to Buchanan said it was all but certain that
he would bolt the Republican Party and try to win a place on the
Reform Party ballot. ``I think it would be very unusual to schedule
a major room to not announce it,'' the adviser said. ``You can
count on it happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Much to Buchanan's apparent delight, talk of his running on an
independent line has roiled the Republican Party for weeks. Top
Republican officials, including Jim Nicholson, chairman of the
Republican National Committee, and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas,
the frontrunner for the party's presidential nomination, have
appealed to Buchanan to stay within the party and not play the
spoiler with a third-party candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   But his potential candidacy has also revealed deep fractures
within the Reform Party itself. Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota,
the party's highest ranking elected official, has said he would
support a more moderate alternative to Buchanan. But Ross Perot,
the Texas billionaire who founded the party, has signaled through
intermediaries that Buchanan has his tacit support.
</P>
<P>
   Donald J. Trump, the developer, has formed an exploratory
committee to investigate a Reform Party candidacy. Trump, who calls
himself a fiscal conservative but a liberal on social issues, has
been mentioned by Ventura as a possible standard bearer for the
party.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, an ardent isolationist, has fueled the media buzz
around his potential campaign by publishing a book earlier this
year, ``A Republic, Not an Empire,'' in which he questioned whether
Hitler had hostile intentions toward the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Russell J. Verney, chairman of the Reform Party, said on
Wednesday that Buchanan has not told him whether he plans to seek
the party's nomination. But if he does, Verney said, Buchanan will
have to explain his theories on World War II more clearly to party
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the first things he should do is address these
charges that have been made against him in the commentary class
about his writings and views, so members of the Reform party can
have an understanding of his position,'' Verney said.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Reform Party has never been large _ just 50,000
people voted in its nominating contest in 1996 _ its impact on the
presidential race could be significant, political analysts say.
Because of Perot's presidential campaigns of 1992 and 1996, the
party has automatic slots on the ballot in 21 states and is
eligible to receive $12.6 million in federal funds. Perot won 19
million votes in 1992 and may have played a crucial role in helping
Bill Clinton win the general election by siphoning votes from
President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   With his staunchly conservative credentials, Buchanan would
probably draw more votes from the Republican candidate, and for
that reason the campaign of George W. Bush has not wanted him to
mount a third-party candidacy. Bush has tried to avoid the
appearance of banishing Buchanan from the party, which might
increase Buchanan's credibility among disaffected conservatives. At
the same time, Bush has been criticized for not taking a stronger
stand against Buchanan's contention that American involvement in
World War II might not have been necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Tucker, a spokeswoman for Bush's campaign, said on
Wednesday that she would not comment on Buchanan's Reform Party
campaign until he makes it official.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who is also running for the
Republican nomination and has been sharply critical of Buchanan's
views on World War II, bid Buchanan good riddance from the
Republican Party. ``As I have said all along, I believe that Pat
Buchanan has already left the Republican Party,'' McCain said
through a spokesman. ``Today's news comes as no surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party does not use the traditional primary process to
select its presidential nominees, but rather relies on a
complicated process under which party members will cast ballots
during the party's national convention next August. Candidates are
also expected to try to get on the ballot via petitions in the 29
states where the Reform Party does not have automatic ballot lines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
