<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0420 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6049 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-AIDWORKER14-COX     10-13 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDWORKER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Risks of delivering aid are rising worldwide
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Without doubt, this has been a bad week for the good
guys, the humanitarian workers who risk their own lives to make
others' lives safer, healthier and happier.
</P>
<P>
   Monday: In Kosovo, a U.N. worker was beaten by a mob, then shot
in the head. Valentin Krumov, fresh from completing a doctoral
program at the University of Georgia, had arrived in the troubled
Serbian province only that day. He had hoped to help re-establish
civilian government.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday: In Burundi, Hutu rebels attacked a U.N. humanitarian
convoy. They robbed everyone and killed nine people. Shot at
point-blank range were Burundi's UNICEF representative, Luis
Zuniga, and Saskia von Meijenfeldt, a logistics officer for the
World Food Program. Zuniga had devoted his career to helping
children. Von Meijenfeldt fed the hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday: In Georgia's breakaway republic of Abkhazia, six U.N.
military observers and their translator were taken hostage. Part of
a force monitoring a truce in the region, the neutral observers
were in the process of delivering aid to refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing about such incidents ``is very painful,'' said Kathleen
Egan, director of UNICEF Atlanta. ``And it's just happening too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Is the world becoming a more dangerous place for humanitarian
workers? ``Absolutely,'' said Bob MacPherson, assistant director of
the emergency group for Atlanta-based CARE USA.
</P>
<P>
   MacPherson is CARE's leading expert on land mines and security
issues and does strategic assessments of security issues around the
world for CARE International.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, while helping CARE re-establish operations in
Kosovo, he became very familiar with the neighborhood where Krumov
died. This week, he returned to Atlanta from 16 days in East Timor,
which is attempting to assert its independence from Indonesia.
There, as in Kosovo, humanitarian workers are pouring in at the
same time U.N. peace-keeping troops are struggling to re-establish
a safe environment.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, relief agencies have legitimate worries about the
security of their staffs. In neither case does MacPherson, a
retired Marine colonel, see aid workers as special targets.
</P>
<P>
   In East Timor, he said, he never felt especially threatened,
although concerns continue about the re-organization _ just across
the border in West Timor _ of militia groups that could re-ignite
violence. ``But I was very cautious,'' MacPherson said. He
generally worked in secure areas. When he asked about the safety of
an area and peacekeepers began their responses with the conditional
word ``Well ... ,'' he took note.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I heard the word `Well,' I said we should keep our
people out of there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, for the last decade, humanitarian workers have
needed to act with extra caution, MacPherson said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that aid workers are increasingly sent into areas
where violent clashes have been led by ragtag militias and
paramilitary forces. ``Dealing with ill-trained or untrained
militias is definitely far worse than dealing with regular
armies,'' MacPherson said. Not only relief workers but also
civilians have been far more vulnerable to violent attacks in those
scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, humanitarian groups _ once universally accepted
as neutral _ have been actively targeted because they are seen
merely as representatives of Western society.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to violent attacks, kidnappings also have become
more common, MacPherson said. Some seem designed mainly to attract
publicity and make a point. In those cases, the victim may be
treated well. Other times, kidnappers are prepared to slice a
victim's throat.
</P>
<P>
   But some attacks occur simply because humanitarian workers, just
like anyone else, happen to be at the wrong place at the wrong
time: Someone wants to rip off a warehouse or steal a vehicle, or a
worker gets caught in cross fire.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the motives for attacks may have less to do with politics
than the fact that relief organizations of necessity move large
amounts of cash into chaotic situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you tell what makes someone pull the trigger even if
they just want to steal your watch?'' MacPherson said. ``I spend a
lot of time while I'm in some of these godforsaken places coming up
with ways to ensure that both the CARE workers and the funds we're
entrusted with are safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenges have made basic security training one of the
paramount concerns for many humanitarian agencies. ``There are
certain baseline skills we have to ensure our people have,''
MacPherson said.
</P>
<P>
   But dying in a violent attack is far from the only risk aid
workers face, he added quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When everything is said and done, automobile accidents
absolutely lead the list of what causes death and injury in the
humanitarian community,'' MacPherson said.
</P>
<P>
   His best advice for workers abroad applies equally at home:
``Wear your seat belts, and drive sanely and safely.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
