<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6050 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-ALA-GAMBLING-NYT &LR;      10-13 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-GAMBLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCHGOERS REJOICE IN DEFEATING A STATE LOTTERY IN ALABAMA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Fla., Miss., La., Ga., N.D., Ark. and Okla.)   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ Wednesday was a day of jubilation for the
churchgoers of Alabama. To the dismay of a clearly shaken Gov.
Donald Siegelman, religious leaders led his plan for a state
lottery to firm defeat in a referendum on Tuesday, and there was
widespread rejoicing at their display of political force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glory,'' said one woman who called in to a Christian radio
station in Opelika this morning. ``The Lord was with us in the
voting booth.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, in the words of Bob Russell, chairman of the Alabama chapter
of the Christian Coalition, ``The Red Sea just parted.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, gambling's once-improbable march through the Bible
Belt had seemed inexorable. There were casinos in Louisiana and
Mississippi, lotteries in Georgia and Florida, and video poker
machines in almost every gas station in South Carolina. Alabama had
only dog racing and bingo, but after Siegelman was decisively
elected last year on a platform consisting almost entirely of his
proposal for a lottery, the state seemed ready to join its
neighbors in the search for easy money.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed on Tuesday, when the driving force behind the
success of government-sponsored gambling _ the region's hostility
to taxes _ ran directly into a rock that may be even stronger here:
the power of the pulpit. There was barely a pastor in the state, of
any denomination, who did not issue fiery instructions to defeat
gambling as a moral corruption and an injustice to the poor. When
54 percent of the voters did just that on Tuesday, both sides
agreed that the church's role had been decisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an interfaith effort, people from all over, churches
that probably hadn't spoken to each other in years,'' said Tom
Blackerby, president of the American Family Association of Alabama,
a group of religious conservatives that campaigned against the
proposal. ``But this was a common cause that brought the churches
together.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Siegelman proposal envisioned it, a lottery would have
raised $150 million a year for education. With its defeat,
Alabamians will still find themselves with one of the worst
educational systems in the country. Other states are finding ways
to pay for preschool programs and guaranteed college scholarships,
but neither the governor nor his opponents have put forward a clear
plan to do so now that the lottery has been killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no Plan B,'' a chagrined the governor said at a news
conference in his office at the State Capitol Wednesday. ``My plan
was on the table yesterday. Now my door is open, my mind is open,
my arms are open, for any of those people who want to come in and
offer suggestions on how we can improve education for our
children.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as those plans do not include raising taxes, he added.
Alabama, with the lowest per-capita spending on education in the
country, also has the lowest per-capita state and local tax burden,
$100 a person less than the states ranked next-lowest, Mississippi
and Tennessee. But the governor said he would not consider a tax
increase to improve education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I speak for the people of Alabama,'' he said. ``They
don't want their taxes raised, and I'm not going to do it. Can I
find the money? I don't know, but we're going to look. We're going
to do everything we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the governor said he would not put a revised lottery
proposal on the table, he vowed not to give up his hopes for
improved education, adding, ``I didn't get my black belt in karate
some years ago, I might add, by being a wuss.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegelman, a Democrat, run for governor in 1990 on a tax reform
platform, and his loss that year purged the idea from his playbook.
Similarly, for all its political strength, the anti-lottery
religious coalition has been criticized for being an essentially
negative force, knowing what it is against but not what it is for.
</P>
<P>
   ``The religious groups are outraged by private sins, but they
don't seem as concerned about social sins, like a third of the kids
in Alabama's public schools being poor,'' said Wayne Flint, a
prominent history professor at Auburn University. ``I haven't seen
them mobilize to this extent in favor of anything that might
actually improve education.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Steve Windom, a Republican, and Jim Cooper, chairman of
the state's largest anti-lottery group, Citizens Against Legalized
Lottery, spoke without detail Wednesday of using existing education
funds to pay for college scholarships. That could mean cutting
current programs, which the governor said was pointless, but they
said they believed the money could be found. ``If the scholarship
program was a high priority yesterday with the lottery, it should
still be today without it,'' said Windom, a vocal lottery opponent.
``I think we can pay for it with the growth in our budget, or with
pork spending.''
</P>
<P>
   D.L. Ireland, executive director of another leading anti-lottery
group, the Alabama Citizens Action Program, said voters might
consider a tax increase for education, but only after they were
convinced that current funds are being properly spent.
</P>
<P>
   That general mistrust of government is another important force
behind Tuesday's defeat, in which Alabama joined North Dakota,
Arkansas and Oklahoma as the only states to turn down a lottery.
Cooper's group focused its advertising on the lottery's potential
for corruption, and many voters said they did not believe that
officials of Alabama, never known for governmental efficiency,
could be trusted to use the money as promised. A recent
ticket-fixing scandal, in which it was revealed that high-ranking
Siegelman aides had traffic tickets dismissed, only contributed to
that sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a good while, you know, we were a dry county here,'' said
Bob D. Plunket, pastor of the Tuscumbia Church of Christ, in the
northwest corner of the state. ``And they told us if we'd just have
liquor, which was voted in, that it would solve our tax problems
and our school problems and we'd have plenty of money, and it was
never a reality. And I think people remembered that, for one
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the only areas of support for the lottery was the belt of
historically black counties through the lower middle of the state,
as well as the area around Birmingham, similar to areas where the
lottery is the most popular in other Southern states. Those
counties tend to be the poorest, with the largest percentage of
students in public school. The lottery failed in suburban and rural
areas, precisely the places where the idea of higher taxes for
schools is often the most repugnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``As strong as the religious opposition is to gambling, that's
where there's even stronger opposition to tax reform,'' said Flint,
of Auburn. suggesting that the anti-lottery vote might have a
silver lining. ``Maybe that's a sign of the maturing of the
culture, if people recognize that there's not going to be any magic
bullet to the problems that have plagued this region. But that's
only if this crisis winds up producing a solution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
