<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6051 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-AFLCIO-GORE-ART-1000(     10-13 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFLCIO-GORE-ART-1000(TRIMS)-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE WINS ENDORSEMENT OF AFL-CIO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT13 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE and STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; Winning the biggest prize so far in the
presidential campaign, Vice President Al Gore on Wednesday gained
the AFL-CIO's endorsement and vowed to battle for working families,
although labor leaders urged him to work harder to win the hearts
and minds of union members.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement came without the support of two of the nation's
most powerful unions, the International Brotherhood of Teamsters
and the United Auto Workers, and only after Gore had met privately
this week with several union leaders and promised more attention to
their concerns, like job losses caused by trade.
</P>
<P>
   After an extended entrance to the jaunty beat of blaring salsa
music, Gore thanked the AFL-CIO convention here for its support and
spoke to the heart of the argument that had prevailed earlier in
the debate whether to endorse now or later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work of labor is to lead and not to follow,'' the vice
president said. The endorsement was made by voice vote among 700
delegates representing the labor federation's 13 million union
members.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO endorsement is a boon to candidates because the
federation includes 68 unions, prints millions of leaflets and,
perhaps better than any other group in society, can mobilize tens
of thousands of volunteers for phone banks, registration drives and
get-out-the-vote drives.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's rival for the Democratic
nomination, conceded in an interview Wednesday that he did not
believe he himself could win the endorsement of therkers or
the Teamsters, but he added, ``I think it's a significant gap in
(Gore's) support given the size of both unions.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speech Wednesday to the organization underlined many of
the commitments that he made in private meetings with union leaders
in the last few days. With regard to one of labor's most pressing
issues, Gore pledged that any agreements he negotiated to expand
trade would not undercut American workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our president needs the authority to reach new trade
agreements to open new markets to our goods and services,'' he
said. ``But as president, I will also insist on the authority to
enforce worker rights, human rights and environmental protections
in those agreements. Trade should lift up living standards around
the world, not drag them down in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   He also indicated that he would take to heart union leaders'
advice that he should meet personally with members of local unions
across the nation. The Teamsters president, James P. Hoffa, told
Gore's campaign manager, Tony Coelho, that Gore could not win the
Teamsters support without doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Heeding the advice, Gore said in his speech, ``I want to work
alongside all of you in Iowa, in New Hampshire, in every state and
from every member of this AFL-CIO. I want to take this message
right to the grassroots. I need everyone of you to be with me, and
I am not taking a single vote for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 20 minutes of debate before the vote, Hoffa said his
1.4-million member union was not ready to endorse, and in speaking
out so forcefully, he indicated he would be a power to reckon with
within organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We disagree not necessarily with the candidate but with the
process,'' he said. ``I understand the need to lead, but I also
understand the need to listen. Now is the time to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa said a crucial test would be how the Clinton
administration performs at a December meeting of the World Trade
Organization in Seattle, where some pro-business trade proposals
that worry labor unions are on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the vice president going to listen?'' Hoffa asked. ``We
hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was pressed on his trade views in the private meetings
here. George Becker, president of the United Steelworkers of
America, which was sitting on the fence, said he would back the
federation's endorsement of Gore but only after the vice president
promised to address the union's biggest concern, the loss of
manufacturing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa, who said his position should not be construed as
anti-Gore, added: ``Our members have made it clear they don't want
to be told how to vote. They want voting information, not
instruction. They want to know how the candidates we endorse will
affect their lives, and at this time, we still don't know that,
between these two candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   One teamsters delegate from Kentucky, Jerry Vincent, seconded
Hoffa's views about wanting to know more. ``In the South, we always
say, `Don't wrap that pig. Weigh it.' And we'd like to have it
weighed before it's wrapped,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After promising to ``work my heart out to earn this
nomination,'' Gore concluded his speech with his new battle cry
that he will ``stay and fight.'' The reference was a thinly veiled
swipe at Bradley for quitting the Senate when many Democrats dug in
to fight what Gore described as an anti-union offensive by the
Republican Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also took some swipes at the Republican Congress and at
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas for not supporting an increase in the
minimum wage. He said they should ``stop paying off their special
interest friends on the backs of the working poor.''
</P>
<P>
   He vowed as president to buck any anti-union action. ``If they
send any anti-union bill to my desk, I'll ink up that veto pen, and
I'll hit them right between the eyes with a veto,'' he declared.
``You can count on that.''
</P>
<P>
   The delegates reacted enthusiastically, but not rapturously
during Gore's 37-minute speech in which he often ran right over his
applause lines.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional plea before the endorsement vote, John Sweeney,
the AFL-CIO's president, said: ``Ours is a movement with an
extraordinary gift for hope. We must make it a movement with an
uncommon ability to act. In this compressed election season, I
believe that this endorsement at this time represents our best
ability to act and to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   In an admonition to those holding out, Sweeney added: ``When we
are unified we can move mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution acknowledged that Bradley ``has the respect of
many and a good record,'' but added: ``there is no question that Al
Gore is the presidential candidate most favored.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The resolution said that during Gore's seven years in the
Senate, he voted the pro-union position 88 percent of the time. It
did not note that Bradley voted with unions 86 percent of the time.
Gore had the second most pro-union voting record in the Senate,
after Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass..
</P>
<P>
   ``More than any other national leader,'' the resolution said,
``Al Gore has used the power of his office to defend the freedom of
workers to choose a union, free from interference by their
employers, and he has repeatedly urged other elected officials to
do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking forcefully for Gore's endorsement was Gerald McEntee,
president of the American Federation of State, County and Municipal
Employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many unions in this hall who have called upon him
for help and assistance,'' he said. ``He has been there for us, he
has been there I think for most unions in this room, if not all
unions in this room.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
