<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DUQUETTE HAS THE RED SOX IN HIS BLOOD
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Most baseball general managers are strangers in town.
Most are hired to assemble a team for a franchise they know only
from the standings. To them, one city is not that much different
from any other. They sit at their office desk or in the ballpark.
It's their job, but no fan emotion is involved, no attachment to
the franchise history. No blood, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Duquette is different.
</P>
<P>
   As the general manager of the Red Sox watched Wednesday night's
opener of the American League Championship Series, his team was
doing what he had been hoping to do since he was growing up in the
Berkshires near Pittsfield, Mass., where the Red Sox had a farm
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wanted to play the Yankees for the pennant ever since I
was 10,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now 41, he remembered going to Fenway Park with his father and
his older brother Dennis in 1967, the year the Red Sox lost the
World Series to the St. Louis Cardinals. He remembered players he
had seen in Wahconah Park in Pittsfield who went on to play for the
Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Scott was the first,'' he said. ``Billy Conigliaro,
Sparky Lyle, Carlton Fisk.''
</P>
<P>
   And in 1978, while an English literature major at Amherst, where
he caught Jeff Reardon, he was in Fenway Park when Bucky Dent hit
the home run that will always haunt Red Sox fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting behind home plate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, when it appeared that the Red Sox were about to win the
World Series against the Mets at Shea Stadium, he was the Milwaukee
Brewers' scouting director.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother called late that Saturday night,'' he remembered,
``and told me, `All we need is two more outs from Schiraldi.'''
</P>
<P>
   To him and his brother, ``we'' meant the Red Sox, but Calvin
Schiraldi never got those two outs. Mookie Wilson's grounder rolled
through first baseman Bill Buckner's legs; the Mets won that sixth
game and the seventh game. Another haunting memory for the Red Sox
and Dan Duquette, but he continued to climb baseball's front-office
ladder.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 he was hired as the Montreal Expos' general manager, the
major leagues' youngest at the time. Early in 1994 he moved to the
Red Sox in the job he had always wanted.
</P>
<P>
   His autocratic style could be alienating. He kicked the Red Sox
icon and longtime coach Johnny Pesky upstairs. He talked to beat
writers only in a weekly conference call. After the 1996 season, he
described Roger Clemens as being ``in the twilight of his career.''
Clemens departed as a free agent to Toronto, where he earned two Cy
Young Awards. Before the 1997 season, Duquette hired Jimy Williams,
who has now managed the Red Sox to their first consecutive
postseason appearances since 1914-1915 when Babe Ruth was a
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Jimy from when he was Bobby Cox's first lieutenant with
the Braves, who shared a spring training facility with the Expos,''
he said. ``He knows how to bring young players along. When we lost
our closer, Tom Gordon, he did a great job of stabilizing this
team. And he had been a good manager in Toronto.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 1997 season, Duquette startled baseball by signing
free agent Pedro Martinez to a six-year, $75 million contract. He
knew all about the Dominican right-hander. As the Expos' boss, he
had obtained Martinez from Los Angeles in a trade for second
baseman Delino DeShields after the 1993 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1997 Pedro had a Cy Young year with the Expos that was
almost unparalleled,'' Duquette said. ``He was the first
right-hander since Walter Johnson in 1912 to have an ERA under two
and to strike out over 300.''
</P>
<P>
   With a 19-7 record, Martinez led the Red Sox to the 1998 wild
card, but after they lost to Cleveland in the division series, Mo
Vaughn, their popular slugger, departed as a free agent to the
Anaheim Angels. Without him, the Red Sox were not considered a
contender this season. But they earned the wild card, then stunned
the Indians in the division series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question for the Red Sox,'' Duquette said, ``is not
whether we can put a good team out there, but whether the team can
withstand the movement of star players. We can do it. We've done
it.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anybody else, Pedro Martinez has helped them do it.
With a 23-4 record, a 2.40 ERA and 313 strikeouts, he will be voted
another Cy Young Award, if not the most valuable player award.
Monday night in Cleveland, his six no-hit innings in relief put the
Red Sox into this best-of-7 showdown with the Yankees for the AL
pennant.
</P>
<P>
   And ever since Dan Duquette was 10, that's all he has wanted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
