<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Ferraro, the goal is to get going
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Players who score 108 goals in one year in the
juniors don't take slumps well. Players who twice record 40-goal
seasons in the NHL and average more than 25 a year don't smile a
lot when their statistics after three games read: 0 goals, 0
assists, 5 penalties. Especially when the player was signed
specifically for his goal-scoring ability.
</P>
<P>
   When the Thrashers open a three-game trip tonight against the
New York Islanders, no player on the team will be looking to alter
the recent course of events more than Ray Ferraro.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran center said he has been plagued by bad starts most
of his career, but the situation this year has been magnified by
the Thrashers' lack of proven goal scorers and Ferraro's
determination that he can bounce back from two injury-plagued
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I'm not happy with the way I've played,'' Ferraro
said. ``I know I was being counted on to score and I haven't done
it yet. I've been frustrated and I know that's the worst thing I
can do to myself. But it's only three games out of 82, so there's
still time.''
</P>
<P>
   The surroundings tonight could help. Ferraro had some of his
best career moments in his nearly five seasons with the Islanders
(1990-95); he scored 40 goals and had a career-high 80 points in
1991-92. The next year, he led the team in the playoffs with 13
goals in 18 games, and New York eliminated Pittsburgh and Mario
Lemieux before losing to Montreal in the league semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always like going back to places where I played before,''
Ferraro said. ``When we went to the semifinals in '93, that was the
most fun I've had in hockey. I don't like to see what's happened to
the franchise. Hopefully, (coach) Butch (Goring) can turn it
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, Ferraro wants to turn himself around. His frustrations
were evident Saturday against Buffalo when he drew consecutive
minor penalties in the second period, including elbowing the
Sabres' Rob Ray. According to Ferraro, Ray ``gave me a whack'' as
both exited the penalty box moments earlier. The penalty led to a
power-play goal that closed Atlanta's lead to 4-3 in the game that
wound up 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   In the opener Ferraro was slowed by a sore back, the result of a
check in the final exhibition e says the back is at 95
percent now. In the second game, a 7-1 loss to Detroit, Ferraro
missed three great scoring chances _ two breakaways and a
redirected pass from Mike Stapleton in the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers assistant general manager Les Jackson was the general
manager of Ferraro's junior team in Brandon, Manitoba, in 1983-84,
the season he scored 108 goals. Jackson also saw Ferraro bounce
back from knee injuries last season to play well down the stretch
for Los Angeles, leading Atlanta to sign him as an unrestricted
free agent. ``He's got some goals in him that he hasn't shown us
yet,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he scores that first goal,'' coach Curt Fraser said,
``we'll see a different Ray Ferraro in the confidence department.
He's taking the load on his shoulders right now and he can't do
that. Instead of putting all this pressure on himself, he needs to
just go out and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro acknowledges that he hasn't had fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to play a simple game, move the puck and go to the
net,'' he said. ``I need to get myself into position to score.''
</P>
<P>
   With his stick, not his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
