<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Huge purses not a draw for everyone
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Something is missing from the Tour Championship this
year. And it won't be any different when the event returns to
Atlanta's East Lake Golf Club in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 PGA Tour money champion might not be determined in the
$5million Tour Championship with its $900,000 first prize, Oct.
28-31, at Champions Golf Club in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Odd as it might seem, no longer does the Tour Championship end
the official PGA Tour money season. It isn't over until the next
week's $5 million American Express Championship, Nov. 4-7 at the
Valderrama Golf Club in Sotogrande, Spain. It is the third World
Golf Championship event of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The WGC event will count for all the applicable money lists. It
is open to the top 50 players on the Official World Golf Rankings,
the top 30 from the PGA Tour money list, the top 20 from Europe and
top three from Japan, Australasia and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   When PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem and the other pooh-bahs
of the world tours created the WGC events, they envisioned the Tour
Championship and the American Express Championship as a two-week,
worldwide money showdown. If a world money list evolves, perhaps
then the two events will blend. But as things stand, both the PGA
Tour and European Tour players seemed to think everything was fine
before.
</P>
<P>
   American Justin Leonard joins the majority of PGA Tour players
who would rather see the WGC event played the week before the Tour
Championship, if the former has to be played.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably so,'' Leonard said. ``It's strange, and I think David
Duval put it very well, that a European player could decide who
wins our money list (and vice versa). That would be my only
criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   A few prominent names might be no-shows, Duval, in particular.
In early spring, Duval half-seriously hoped for a money lead of
$1,000,001 in order to bag the Spain event and still guarantee the
title. But even though he trails Tiger Woods by nearly $800,000,
Duval apparently does not have Spain on his schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing in Houston in our Tour Championship and I've got a
couple of opportunities after that, all in the States,'' Duval said
last week at Kingsmill.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the PGA Tour should have reduced the price on the $6,200
charter it has organized from Houston to Malaga, Spain, Oct. 31. A
few million bucks in earnings just doesn't reach as far as it used
to.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard plans to attend, but he said, ``I don't think I would be
too harsh on a player who doesn't go.''
</P>
<P>
   It says something about the financial explosion in golf when a
player can bypass a field of approximately 60 players that pays a
minimum of $25,000 and $1 million to the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can play well those two weeks and pass a lot of guys on
the money list,'' Leonard said. ``It's something to get excited
for. The public wants to see the best in the world playing against
each other as much as possible, and we have two weeks like that
back to back.''
</P>
<P>
   It might not be a reason for skipping Spain, but some U.S. Ryder
Cup players are bracing for some post-Brookline celebration
reaction at the site of the 1997 matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll catch some flak,'' Leonard said. ``I'm hoping
that people start to put that behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
