<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons try to solve slyness of the Rams
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On Sept. 26 in St. Louis, confusion reigned in the
Falcons' secondary.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams ``flat-out looked All-World,'' free safety Eugene
Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Falcons (1-4) are going to win the rematch Sunday in the
Georgia Dome, they must slow down the 4-0 Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, St. Louis bolted to a 21-0 lead before the Falcons
ran their fifth offensive play. They led 28-0 at the half and won
35-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons didn't slow the running game, either, but they were
done in mostly by the Rams' passing attack. Kurt Warner completed
12 of 17 passes for 190 yards and three touchdowns in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis coach Dick Vermeil's offense made it happen mainly by
moving backs and receivers around. In turn, the Falcons tried to
counter by moving defenders around, sometimes before the snap,
trying to preserve matchups.
</P>
<P>
   It was a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really got us on our heels because we were moving,''
Robinson said. ``Hopefully, we can alleviate that problem by
getting set up and not worrying about who's at the `X' spot and
who's at the `Y' spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons won't be running around as much in the secondary
Sunday, although defenses usually have to follow a man in motion.
</P>
<P>
   One option might be to double-team wide receiver Isaac Bruce and
put one man on rookie Torry Holt, depending on alignment.
Sometimes, however, they are on the same side.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulty is they move around in so many formations,''
Falcons coach Dan Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Ray Buchanan, on the wrong end of touchdown
receptions by Holt and Bruce that day, concedes it might be time to
simplify matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they did pretty good was game-plan us,'' he said. ``They
knew what we were in, but a lot of times we didn't know what they
were going to be in. A lot of what they did we didn't see in
film.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' defensive pressure has to start with the pass rush.
Warner was not sacked and rarely was pressured in the first
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're sitting back there massaging the ball, I don't care
what quarterback it is, any quarterback can look good,'' Buchanan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Lester Archambeau agreed. ``You can't lay a
measure on it,'' he said. ``It is immensely important (to pressure
the passer). You can't let a guy who is that accurate have time to
throw the ball ... and the DBs (must) bump those (wide receivers)
and disrupt their routes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons failed to jam the receivers at the line, Robinson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their receivers got off the ball. It was free access,'' he
said. ``We didn't do a good job of getting in their faces. That has
to stick in your craw. If it doesn't, something is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked like we were in high school and they were world
champions,'' Robinson said. ``I anticipate this go-around is going
to be starkly different.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
