<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BARNHART-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Midseason report has some A's and F's
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here at the halfway point of the season, we present
the highlights and lowlights of the season to date:
</P>
<P>
   _ Biggest surprise: Michigan State, which was barely on the
radar screen when the season began and is 6-0 and ranked No. 5. The
Spartans still have a lot of work to do, but a Nov. 20 game at home
with Penn State could be a blockbuster. The Spartans had better be
careful Saturday at Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   _ Biggest disappointment: The behavior of Florida State wide
receiver Peter Warrick, whose suspension on charges of felony theft
could cost him the Heisman Trophy. Warrick passed up NFL millions
to come back to school and gets done in by Tommy Hilfiger.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best game: Florida State 41, Georgia Tech 35. It gave the
whole country a chance to find out what we already knew _ Tech QB
Joe Hamilton is a great football player. Honorable mention: Army
59, Louisville 52, in double overtime.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best conference: No debate this season. With Penn State,
Michigan State, and Michigan in the top 10, and with Wisconsin,
Ohio State, and Purdue not far behind, it's the Big Ten in a
walkover.
</P>
<P>
   _ Worst conference: Another easy choice. The Pac-10 has a
combined record of 28-26 and no team ranked in this week's Top 25.
Halfway through the season, every team in the conference has at
least two losses. The Rose Bowl must be excited.
</P>
<P>
   _ Teams to watch in the second half: Mississippi State (6-0),
Syracuse (5-1), Texas (5-2), Tennessee (4-1).
</P>
<P>
   _ Biggest upset: East Carolina 27, Miami 23. The Pirates rallied
from a 20-0 deficit to post one of the biggest wins in school
history.
</P>
<P>
   MIDSEASON COACHES OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   ACC: George O'Leary, Georgia Tech
</P>
<P>
   SEC: Jackie Sherrill, Mississippi State
</P>
<P>
   Big Ten: Nick Saban, Michigan State
</P>
<P>
   Big East: Frank Beamer, Virginia Tech
</P>
<P>
   Big 12: Bill Snyder, Kansas State
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10: No winner.
</P>
<P>
   MIDSEASON PLAYERS OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   ACC: QB Joe Hamilton, Georgia Tech
</P>
<P>
   SEC: QB Tee Martin, Tennessee
</P>
<P>
   Big Ten: WR Plaxico Burress, Michigan State
</P>
<P>
   Big East: DE Corey Moore, Virginia Tech
</P>
<P>
   Big 12: QB Major Applewhite, Texas
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10: No winner
</P>
<P>
   WORTH NOTING
</P>
<P>
   _ For the seventh time in the history of the series, but for the
second time in three seasons, neither Notre Dame nor Southern
California will be ranked when they meet on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Virginia Tech plays Syracuse on Saturday for homecoming. In
the Hokies' past two homecoming games, they have lost to Temple
(28-24) and Miami of Ohio (24-7). Both times, Virginia Tech was
undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   _ Former Kentucky football player Jeremy Streck, a starter at
offensive guard last season, died Saturday after he was struck by a
car. He was 23.
</P>
<P>
   WORTH QUOTING
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's a fair assessment, because, if that's the
case, then we don't need to play the gam   Reggie Germany, Ohio State receiver on comments from coach John
Cooper that the Buckeyes would have to play a perfect game to beat
Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   JUST THINKING
</P>
<P>
   _ SMU was passed over for membership in Conference USA this week
for several reasons. But the main reason is that the football
program is 0-5 and is in the middle of a new investigation into
possible wrongdoing. The ``death penalty'' placed on the Mustangs
in the 1980s is still affecting the program.
</P>
<P>
   _ Penn State coach Joe Paterno has put all but three of his
players off limits to the media in the days leading up to
Saturday's game with Ohio State. Could be that Joe Pa is more
worried about the Buckeyes than the media. Ohio State has won four
of the past six meetings.
</P>
<P>
   _ When it comes to the Heisman Trophy, let's not forget about
Ron Dayne just yet. The Wisconsin running back needs to average
172.8 yards in his final five games to break the NCAA rushing
record.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   1-9: Combined record of Rutgers and West Virginia, who play
Saturday in Morgantown.
</P>
<P>
   269: Rushing yards for Army's Michael Wallace last week against
Louisville, for an academy record.
</P>
<P>
   36.7: Yards rushing per game allowed by Michigan State, best in
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   14-3: Combined record of the three Division I teams from the
state of Mississippi _ Mississippi State, 6-0; Mississippi 5-1;
Southern Miss 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
