In a cramped kitchen at the 1999 French Designer Showhouse,
Christopher Coleman solved the problem of a large window and an
ugly view by using extraordinary illumination: he commissioned a
12-panel fused-glass inset from Dorothy Hafner, a New York glass
artist. The radiator cover beneath is plywood lacquered with 10
coats of polyester sanded to an automotive finish. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NY37) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1999 -- FRENCH-SHOWCASE-2, 10-13 --
Appropriately for a bedroom, Brigitte Saby started with the softest
possible touch at the 1999 French Designer Showhouse: an
atmospheric palette of colors that shade and blush and wake like
morning light. The silvered-taupe wall surfaces were built like
paintings with layers of gesso and pigment, creating a narrow
pattern of vertical texture that is like an abstract of groves of
bamboo. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1999 -- FRENCH-SHOWCASE-1, 10-13 --
Florence de Dampierre's orange dressing room for a fashionable
fetishist exemplies the luxury goods and adult sophistication
evident at the 1999 French Designer Showhouse, which opens
Thursday. Like much of the show house, it has the wit of seduction,
which is decoration practiced at its most professional. Send the
bill. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
