<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-NOTES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Remlinger rewarded with deal
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the first time in his life, Mike Remlinger has
some long-term security.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves signed the 33-year-old reliever to a two-year
contract extension Wednesday worth $3.2 million with a club option
for a third year. It was the first multiyear deal for Remlinger, a
first-round draft pick by the Giants in 1987 who didn't spent his
first full season in the majors for another 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger, traded to the Braves from the Reds last winter, along
with Bret Boone for Denny Neagle, Michael Tucker and Rob Bell, has
emerged as the Braves' primary left-handed reliever. He had a
career year, going 10-1 with a 2.37 ERA and appearing in 73 games.
His 10 wins were the most by a Braves reliever since Cecil Upshaw
had 11 in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``With everything I've been through, to be in a place I'd pick
over everywhere else, to get to stay here and to be financially
secure is great,'' Remlinger said. ``It's a great cap to what to
this point has been a great year.''
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger had a one-year deal for this season worth $1.1
million. With his new contract, he will make $1.4million in 2000
and $1.6million in 2001, with a club option worth $2million in 2002
with a $200,000 buyout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's done a remarkable job, as his statistics attest,''
Braves general manager John Schuerholz said. ``He's been an
important linchpin performer for our bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   NOW PITCHING ...
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz's excellent adventures continued with the first
relief appearance of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Just as nearly everything Smoltz has tried this season has come
out golden _ from a new arm angle to a knuckleball _ so did the
ninth inning. Smoltz retired the side to add his first career save
to his record of 12 postseason wins.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz was greeted by a roar from the Turner Field crowd as he
jogged out of the bullpen in right-center field.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz needed only 11 pitches, eight of which were strikes, to
retire the side. He finished by striking out Bobby Bonilla on a
fastball clocked at 97 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to smile now,'' said Smoltz, who said he'll have no
problem being ready for his start in Game 4 Saturday. ``It gives me
a far greater appreciation for what those guys do.''
</P>
<P>
   LEARNING THE HARD WAY
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had discussed Kenny Rogers' capacity to pick off
runners at first base during a team meeting before the series. They
even listened to longtime American Leaguer Ozzie Guillen say not
only was Rogers' move good, it was great.
</P>
<P>
   But Gerald Williams and Andruw Jones got picked off first base _
neither was trying to steal on the plays _ in the first two innings
to spoil offensive opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we learned to glue our feet to first base,'' Cox said.
``I told Gerald and the guys when you get up there, you're not
running, his move is good. It's borderline (to a balk), but we
weren't stealing.'' WEISS BACK IN
</P>
<P>
   Cox had originally planned to start Jose Hernandez in Game 2
against Rogers, but changed his mind after the night Walt Weiss had
in Game 1, going 3-for-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked good at short and he swung the bat well ... so we're
going to go ahead and go with the hot hand right now,'' Cox said.
``It's not demeaning Hernandez in any way. It's a great situation
having two right-handers on the bench (along with Howard Battle)
instead of one.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
