<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6093 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-HISPANIC-FILMFEST-TEX     10-13 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-FILMFEST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS FILM FEST MAKES INROADS FOR HISPANICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a lot of micro-budget independent films, Bob's Video _ ``a
romantic comedy about a hostage situation in a video store'' _ is a
mixture of problems and promise. Although it's a bit ragged, it has
flashes of bright wit that have inspired comparisons with
``Clerks,'' and moments of stylistic dash that echo the raucous
work of the Coen brothers.
</P>
<P>
   It almost didn't get made, though, because director Dino Andrade
wanted to cast a Latino actor in a nonethnic role _ a decision that
ultimately cost him his financing. Eventually, he and his wife
maxed out four credit cards and put their business up as collateral
to get the movie made.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made a lot of distributors crazy,'' says Andrade, whose
movie will show this weekend at the Vistas Film Festival, Dallas'
first Hispanic-oriented film fest. ``I would say what I had to say,
and they'd look at me and nod, and then they'd say, `Do you think
Michael J. Fox could play Hispanic?' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's frustrations such as Andrade's that helped lead to Vistas,
an ambitious fest that opens Thursday (Oct. 14) on three screens at
the Medallion 5 theater in east Dallas. The festival has an
impressive lineup ranging from hard-to-find films by surrealistic
director Luis Bunuel to regional premieres of more than a
half-dozen movies. Some of the movies, such as ``Bob's Video,'' are
not ethnocentric; others speak specifically to Hispanic culture and
issues. In some way, however, all involve Latinos, either onscreen
or behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Vistas is the latest in a growing number of Hispanic-oriented
festivals, including those in Corpus Christi, San Antonio, San
Francisco and New York. The fest was the brainchild of Frank P.
Hernandez, a Dallas lawyer and activist who is the founder of the
Herculano y Elida Hernandez Foundation, which is presenting the
festival. Hernandez enlisted Rita Meno, a 1998 graduate of Southern
Methodist University's film school, as the executive director for
the festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this huge audience,'' Meno, 23, says of the Hispanic
population. ``And yes, they go see the blockbusters. But I think
that it's important that there's a place that can provide the films
that show reflections of themselves. And I don't even mean ... it
has to be about Hispanic culture, it has to be about Latinos, it
has to be about that. Just to see a Hispanic, regardless.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, though, seeing a Hispanic character in a movie means
seeing a stereotype. Even in successful Hispanic-themed movies such
as ``American Me, Stand and Deliver'' and ``Mi Familia,'' a
Hispanic actor was just as likely to play a gang member or maid as
to portray a positive role model. For every success story such as
Jimmy Smits, Jennifer Lopez or Salma Hayek, scores of actors
struggle against the typecasting mind-set. And just because a
character is Hispanic doesn't mean that a Hispanic will be cast in
the role.
</P>
<P>
   Andrade tells stories of having agents send him Italian and
Greek actors for ``Bob's Video'' when he specifically requested a
Mexican-American, or of having Latino hopefuls show up in gang
regalia because that's the kind of part they expected to play.
Besides Fox, distributors also suggested John Cusack for the role
of a timid video-store clerk _ an adopted young man who's unsure of
his heritage. Andrade eventually cast Mexican-American actor
Richard Coca, a veteran of such movies as ``The Truth About Cats
and Dogs'' and ``Lone Star,'' in the lead role.
</P>
<P>
   Similar casting woes led Evelina Fernandez, an actress who has
had parts in such movies as ``American Me,'' to write
``Luminarias,'' a romantic comedy about four Latinas and their
search for love. Unlike Andrade, who simply wants to see more
opportunities for Hispanic actors, Fernandez wants to make films
with Hispanic themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our film is maybe the first film that features four
professional Latina women in the lead roles,'' says Fernandez, who
also stars in ``Luminarias,'' which has played festivals in San
Francisco and Europe. ``We've been to so many different cities, and
it seems as though the Latino audience is just dying to see visions
of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Meno _ who emphasizes that she is not Hispanic _ is
trying to remedy that with her programming, she hopes to attract
non-Latino audiences to the festival as well. Her mixture of
classics by Bunuel and Carlos Saura, '80s and '90s films such as
``The Milagro Beanfield War'' and ``American Me,'' and new material
should be of interest to any film fan. So should the festival's
half-dozen workshops, as well as the guest appearances by
filmmakers and actors, including Andrade, Fernandez and Coca (who
is in ``Luminarias'' as well as ``Bob's Video'').
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the new films are all in English,'' Meno says. ``Just
because it involves Hispanic people, and because it's about the
Hispanic culture, it doesn't have to be scary. It doesn't have to
be completely different and completely nonrelated to everything
else. I think they're all pretty mainstream, as far as the story
goes.''
</P>
<P>
   And although ``Bob's Video'' falls into that mainstream category
_ it's as influenced by the '60s slapstick comedies of Blake
Edwards as by the hipster shenanigans of the Coens _ Andrade's
biggest hope is that the fest will eventually lead distributors to
see the film through colorblind eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a possibility that we'll have a premiere at
CineVegas,'' he says, referring to Las Vegas' film festival,
scheduled for December. ``That kind of thing, to be recognized by a
nonethnic festival, happens because of festivals like Vistas.
That's one of the most important things _ to put us on the map.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
