<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6096 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CLINTON-FORESTS-1STLD     10-13 1391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FORESTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OUTLINES PLAN TO PROTECT FEDERAL FOREST LANDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to correct location in 2nd graf, to Shenandoah Valley, sted
Park; deletes photo note)  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Calif., Colo., Idaho, Va., Wash.)  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER with SAM HOWE VERHOVEK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDDISH KNOB, Va. _ President Clinton said Wednesday that he
would permanently protect at least 40 million acres of federal
forest land from road building, logging and mining, using
administrative actions meant to outmaneuver powerful opponents in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in front of a spectacular fall vista here on the edge
of the Shenandoah Valley _ and next to the grandson of Gifford
Pinchot, who mapped out the first protected forests under President
Theodore Roosevelt _ Clinton said, ``We're going to have a big
fight on this for about a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he said, ``In the end, we're going to protect all this
before it's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the strategy described Wednesday by Clinton's top aides,
the Forest Service will speed through hearings and issue
regulations by the end of next year that will prevent any type of
development in the remote sections of national forests that have
never had roads, and in other underdeveloped areas of the 192
million acres the agency manages.
</P>
<P>
   They would include the North Fork of the American River in
California, the Pagoda Peak Roadless Area in Colorado, and the
South Quinault Ridge in Olympic National Forest in Washington. Most
of the newly set aside land would be in tracts of 5,000 acres or
more that are undeveloped, but not protected by formal wilderness
designation.
</P>
<P>
   The protection of so much land would be one of the most
significant conservation actions taken by the administration, which
has fought bitter battles over the use of public lands. The
directive Clinton issued Wednesday affects far more acreage, for
example, than the preservation of 1.7 million acres of the
mineral-rich Grand Staircase Escalante in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which has been pressed by Vice President Al Gore and
Clinton's chief of staff, John Podesta, has been debated heatedly
since the administration first floated the idea early in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton went out of his way to credit Gore, who was in Los
Angeles, seeking an endorsement from the AFL-CIO. At one point,
Clinton referred to conservation efforts ``taken under the
administration of Vice President Gore _ and me.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's action was applauded by conservation groups, which
the White House had invited to this remote peak overlooking the
Little River Roadless Area, another of the forests that would be
protected under the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   But the action was denounced by the timber and paper industries
and legislators from states, mostly in the West, where logging in
the national forests is big business.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, the Alaska Republican who chairs the Senate
Appropriations Committee, has opposed including the 17-million-acre
Tongass National Forest in the declaration. So have Sen. Frank H.
Murkowski and Rep. Don Young, both Alaska Republicans who chair the
House and Senate committees that oversee the Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a grand slam,'' said Ken Rait, the director of the
Heritage Forests Campaign, a conservation group financed by the Pew
Charitable Trusts. ``Future presidents would have to go through the
same type of review process to undo this, and we think that's
politically impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   But other environmental groups were far more cautious in their
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simply premature to say that this is a great thing,''
said Carl Ross, executive director of Save America's Forests, a
coalition of environmental groups based in Washington, D.C. ``All
he's doing is setting in motion a study, which may or may not lead
to more protection in the end. It's preservation, with a big
asterisk, and maybe with loopholes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross said the protections also fell short of those in a bill
sponsored by Sen. Robert Torricelli, the New Jersey Democrat, which
would essentially ban clear-cut logging on the nation's public
forests altogether.
</P>
<P>
   And the environmentalists were also concerned that Wednesday's
announcement left open the fate of the Tongass National Forest. It
is one of the world's largest remaining temperate old-growth rain
forests and has long been at the heart of a legal battle zone
pitting conservationists against logging companies, both seeing
immense value in the forest's vast stands of cedar, hemlock and
spruce.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be one of the greatest environmental protection
measures in the country's history, but it has to include the
Tongass,'' said Matt Zencey, campaign manager for the Alaska
Rainforest Campaign, an environmental group. ``It is the largest
national forest, and it is the poster child for everything that
could be right or could be wrong with the country's forests.''
</P>
<P>
   But if environmentalists expressed some mixed feelings about
Clinton's announcement, logging industry representatives and many
Western Republicans were unshaking in their disdain for the whole
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous state of frustration in our industry _ I
mean, who is going to argue with the idea of protecting national
forests?'' said W. Henson Moore, president of the American Forest &AMP;
Paper Association and a former congressman from Louisiana. ``You
can give a beautifully crafted speech, which President Clinton is
very good at doing, and make the American people feel very good
that we're going to stop these evil people from cutting trees down,
but that's not what's going on here at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore said the protections outlined by Clinton amounted to ``an
extremist form of preservation'' that could lead to the loss of
thousands of jobs and that would subject the forests to fire and
disease hazards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason roads are built is to keep the forests
healthy,'' he said, ``to get out dead and dying trees that can
build a fuel load and cause a catastrophic fire, which happened on
5 million acres in the past year alone. Now the extreme
environmentalists will say, that's right, a forest burning down is
all a part of the natural cycle and that's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Larry Craig, a Republican from Idaho, was equally caustic
in his criticism, and said Clinton was wrong to try to impose
unilaterally a decision that should have been up to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an attitude in this administration that not only does
King William want to reign, he appears at this moment to be setting
up a monarchy for Prince Albert,'' Craig told reporters Tuesday,
criticizing the president in advance of his public announcement.
``These are not the king's lands, these are the people's lands, and
we think he ought to come to the people's bodies to form and shape
this kind of policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan outlined by the president, however controversial, could
well amount to one of the most sweeping land-preservation measures
in the nation's history. Roosevelt added more t million
acres to the national forest system in his tenure, and the National
Park System, created under a single agency in 1916, started with
about 7 million acres and has grown over subsequent decades to
around 80 million acres in all.
</P>
<P>
   Under Forest Service rules, most national forests can be used
for logging and some types of mining, although much of the property
is not suitable for these uses. About 34 million acres of the
forests _ roughly 18 percent _ have been designated ``wilderness
areas'' by Congress, and are off limits for development.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cannot expand wilderness areas without congressional
approval, which would be virtually impossible to obtain. So
instead, starting with a notification that is expected to be
published Thursday in the Federal Register, the White House is
creating a another class of Forest Service lands, only slightly
less protected than wilderness areas. That category of roadless
areas would restrict a wide variety of activities, chiefly the
construction of new roads. And without roads, it is extraordinarily
difficult to harvest timber.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
