<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6099 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-TESTBAN-VOTE-BOS &LR;      10-13 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTBAN-VOTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTES DOWN NUCLEAR TEST BAN PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a blistering slap at President Clinton, the
Senate on Wednesday rejected a treaty banning nuclear weapons
testing worldwide. It refused to delay the vote even after an
11th-hour personal plea from the president.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and the White House attributed the treaty defeat to
unbridled partisanship and personal animosity toward Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The 48-for, 51-against vote was historic both in its
implications for global nuclliferation and for its impact on
Clinton's presidency. The vote marked the first time since the
League of Nations was killed during the Woodrow Wilson
administration that a foreign policy treaty had been defeated on
the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to ratify the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty also
robs Clinton of his hope, amid the scandals that have marred his
presidency, to earn a line in history as the president who ushered
in a new era of nuclear stability.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary move, European heads of state had pleaded
with the Senate to ratify the treaty, noting that other nations
would follow the lead of the world's last superpower. Many world
leaders have voiced the concerned that some rogue regimes might
take a U.S. defeat of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty as a green
light to develop and test nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate, after struggling and failing to find a graceful
way out of voting on the treaty, went ahead with a vote, falling
well short of the 67-count, two-thirds majority needed to ratify
the document.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a moment that will long be remembered for the failure
of the U.S. Senate to act responsibly,'' said Senator John F. Kerry
of Massachusetts. The Senate acted ``without even the veneer of
statesmanship. Politics and spite are what are directing this
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Four Republicans, including Senator James M. Jeffords of
Vermont, sided with the Democratic minority; veteran Senator Robert
C. Byrd, Democrat of West Virginia, voted ``present.''
</P>
<P>
   In a late attempt to stop the vote, Clinton called the Senate
majority leader, Trent Lott of Mississippi, at 5:15 p.m. to ask
what could be done, said a Lott spokesman, John Czwartacki.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lott basically said, `Well, thank you, Mr. President, for
calling for the first time since this started, but we have a vote
in a few minutes,''' Czwartacki said of the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The unsuccessful call demonstrated Clinton's diminishing
personal clout, and gave weight to complaints from both Republicans
and Democrats that the president had not spent enough time lobbying
for the treaty's ratification since he signed it at the United
Nations in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, under parliamentary rules, Senate leaders said,
that the treaty could be reconsidered. But with support for the
treaty weak, a new vote is not expected soon.
</P>
<P>
   A disappointed Clinton called the rejection of the treaty
``reckless, and ultimately partisan,'' and said the United States
would continue to refrain from nuclear testing, treaty or no
treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assure you, the fight is far from over'' to get the treaty
ratified, Clinton told reporters Wednesday night. ``We have to
press on and do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican legislators, replying to the partisanship assertions,
insisted that they objected to the treaty on its merits. Some
senators say believe that any kind of arms control compromises the
U.S. ability to protect itself.
</P>
<P>
   Others said they were unconvinced that the compliance of other
signers could be verified.
</P>
<P>
   But the underlying issue, Democrats on Capitol Hill and in the
White House argued, had less to do with honest, philosophical
disagreement on arms control and more to do with a lingering,
post-impeachment bitterness toward Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen partisanship as bad as it is here now. It
started with impeachment, and it's gotten worse since,'' said
Senator Patrick J. Leahy, Democrat of Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   There is ``a major disconnect between the White House and the
Congress,'' Leahy said. ``For some members, it's as though having
failed to convict the president, they want to convict him every day
on something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans on Capitol Hill have shown astonishment and
anger at the president's repeated ability to bounce back from
adversity, be it a poor showing in a poll or an impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   It is that frustration and irritation, Democrats say, that has
led the Republicans in Congress to try to thwart Clinton at every
turn.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, for instance, has refused to confirm many of
Clinton's judicial nominees.
</P>
<P>
   The test ban vote was especially embarassing for the President,
analysts say, because it makes him appear weak internationally, out
of control of foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad thing here is that Trent Lott's hatred of Bill Clinton
is stronger than his love of country,'' said Mark Mellman, a
Democratic pollster who is an unofficial adviser to Vice President
Al Gore's presidential campaign. ``I never thought I'd see this,
but that's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The irritation with Clinton surfaced during Wednesday's debate.
Senator Jesse Helms, Republican of North Carolina, dismissed an
article written by the leaders of France, Britain and Germany
urging ratification of the treaty, suggesting that Clinton had
ordered it up from Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain, with whom
Clinton shares a strong relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Voicing an imaginary conversation between Clinton and Blair,
Helms said Blair might have responded to Clinton's alleged request
by saying, ``Yes, I can do that. And give my regards to Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   Senators spent much of the last week trying to find a way to
delay the vote, in negotiations that focused mainly on couching the
right rhetoric to give political cover to both Democrats and
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side wanted to appear to have caved in, and the
Republicans were worried that a ``no'' vote on the treaty, which
polls said 80 percent of the American public supported, would hurt
them in their 2000 campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans had insisted on, and got, a formal request from
Clinton to delay the treaty vote. They had demanded a promise that
the Democrats would not bring the treaty up again for the remainder
of Clinton's term, a condition Lott refused to give absolutely,
arguing that international events might warrant a reconsideration.
</P>
<P>
   The demand was meaningless, since it is the Republican Senate
leadership, not the Senate Democrats or the White House _ that
schedules items for votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
