<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6103 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-INDEPENDENT-BROKERS14     10-13 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDEPENDENT-BROKERS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Independent brokers making big gains
 &HT;    By Jim Dillon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CENTERVILLE, Ohio _ Dwayne Adams, Bob Gossett and Cory Crozier
share more than adjoining office space at 7990 Clyo Road. They
share careers as independent securities brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who runs the Adams Financial Group, and Gossett and
Crozier, who run a separate firm that bears their names, are among
the thousands of securities dealers nationwide who have left major
brokerage houses in recent years to start their own businesses as
so-called ``independents.''
</P>
<P>
   As of 1998, there were 96,000 independents nationwide. That
constituted about 20 percent of all financial intermediaries in the
country, according to Edwin Barkel, senior vice president for Sky
Investments, a division of the Sky Financial Group based in Bowling
Green, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1992 and 1997, the number of independents grew at a rate
of 23 percent annually, Barkel said. That rate has dropped to about
20 percent as the ``Merrill Lynches and Smith Barneys of the world
realized they were losing good, quality producers. They have
changed some strategies'' to retain good brokers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams Financial and Gossett and Crozier sell securities offered
by Sky Investments. About 80 percent of Sky Investments' sales are
made through independents, said Sky Investments President and Chief
Executive Robert Gioia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pride ourselves on products that vary from insurance to
financial planning to fee-based accounts,'' Gioia said. ``We offer
everything because we truly are a conduit for a broker to do
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Independents must adhere to the same rules and regulations
issued by the National Association of Securities Dealers and the
Securities and Exchange Commission as their brokerage house
counterparts. But independents say they are freer to offer a wider
variety of products and services to their clients because they are
not locked into offering only what their employer wants them to
sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not representing any one company or product,'' said Adams,
who started working with Sky Investments about three years ago. ``I
can sit next to my client and look at all of the products available
and make a recommendation on what best fits his needs. That's how I
explain it to prospective clients, and most of them really like the
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he has about 200 clients. Gossett said he and Crozier
have about 150 clients. Like Adams, they focus largely on financial
planning, mutual funds and annuities.
</P>
<P>
   Gossett said he much prefers being an independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``After running your own business, it's hard to imagine going to
work for somebody else again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gioia said his ultimate goal is to sign up 400 independent
brokers in Sky Investments' 20-state sales territory.
</P>
<P>
   Prospective brokers go through a series of background checks
that include reviews of their credit and regulatory records.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, established independents with Sky Investments
undergo yearly physical audits of their offices and compliance
reviews designed to make sure they are following NASD and Sulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found some reps who have fallen out of compliance and
we have asked them to leave,'' Gioia said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
