<HEADER>
A6104 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MFUME-SCHOOLS14-COX     10-13 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MFUME-SCHOOLS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NAACP leader urges progress in education
 &HT;    By Scott Elliott
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ NAACP President Kweisi Mfume rallied urban
educators from around the country in a speech in Dayton on
Wednesday, telling them to keep faith in their struggle to improve
the lives of children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of you think what you do goes unnoticed by others,'' he
said. ``That is not the case at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Mfume spoke at a kick-off reception at the Crown Plaza Hotel for
the annual convention of the Council of the Great City Schools, an
organization that represents the 58 largest urban school districts
in the United States. More than 500 educational leaders are
expected to attend the five-day convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real andawesome challenges face all of us,'' Mfume said.
``It's not a matter of having come a long way, but of having a
long, long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The disparity between the high level of spending per student in
the wealthiest suburban public schools and the low level in the
poorest urban public schools in the U.S. is ``immoral,'' Mfume
said.
</P>
<P>
   He assailed voucher programs that use public dollars to pay for
children to attend private schools, saying they benefit only a few
poor children while taking money from public schools that must
educate the disadvantaged students left behind.
</P>
<P>
   `not want to leave any child behind,'' Mfume said.
``Vouchers leave 98 percent of them behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress has enacted a ``reverse Robin Hood'' economic plan, he
said, so that ``the haves have more and the have-nots have nothing
at all,'' and race still is an issue in the U.S. and in education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of skin color dominates too many aspects of American
life,'' Mfume said.
</P>
<P>
   The convention continues today and includes a luncheon speech by
civil rights leader the Rev. Jesse Jackson. Speeches and programs
are open only to those registered to attend the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
