<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6108 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-DAIRY-COMPACT-BOS &LR;      10-13 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIRY-COMPACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE FARM BILL LEAVES OUT NEW ENGLAND DAIRY COMPACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New England farmers suffered two costly defeats
Wednesday, as the Senate passed a $69 billion farm bill that the
region's senators say shortchanges the region's dairy and crop
producers.
</P>
<P>
   The farm bill, which passed the Senate 74-26 and has already
been approved by the House, did not reauthorize a regional dairy
compact that had guaranteed farmers in the New England states a
base price for milk above that set by the US government. The bill
also shuts out the region from the bulk of disaster relief funds.
</P>
<P>
   All New England senators voted against the Agriculture
Appropriations bill except for Massachusetts Democrats Edward M.
Kennedy and John F. Kerry.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy and Kerry favored the package because they were able to
tack on a provision giving $15 million to New England fishermen,
aides to the senators said. The $15 million in research grants is
meant to alleviate the losses fishermen incurred from conservation
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast Dairy Compact, which has brought $75 million to
the region's dairy farmers since it was set in place in 1996, was
designed to pNew England's dairy farmers _ who are at a
climatic disadvantage to their counterparts in the Midwest _ from
fluctuations in milk prices.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the compact say it artificially inflates dairy
prices. But Kenneth Becker, executive director of the compact,
based in Montpelier, Vt., said the system has provided ``a safety
net for farmers.'' Now the region's dairy farmers may face
increased competition from Wisconsin and other states, and lower
prices for their products, New England lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   If raw market forces push Northeastern dairy producers out of
business, Becker and other supporters of the compact said,
consumers in the region might not have enough milk. Since dairy
products are perishable, farmers cannot store them in time of
excess, nor move them across the country in time to fill shortages.
</P>
<P>
   The farm bill also shortchanges the Northeast of federal aid for
farmers hit by this summer's drought, the area's lawmakers
complained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never considered votes for people'' struck by disasters ``a
regional vote,'' said Senator Christopher Dodd, Democrat of
Connecticut. ``I'm just disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   The dairy industry in the Northeast ``gets a double-hit,''
because it loses out on both the dairy compact and on disaster aid,
Dodd said. ``It's grossly unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is expected to sign the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate fight over the agriculture bill was sharply divided
along regional lines, with Midwestern senators, whose states tend
to benefit more from the $8.7 billion in disaster relief,
squelching the cries of Northeastern lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The way the relief portion of the bill is structured, New
England will have no shot at all at $5.5 billion of the disaster
relief pool, and will only be able to compete with dozens of other
states for $1.2 billion in aid to cover losses from the drought,
the New England senators said.
</P>
<P>
   New England governors estimate that the need in their region
alone is $1.5 billion to $2 billion. Senate Minority Leader Thomas
Daschle, Democrat of South Dakota, said he would try to get an
additional $1 billion for disaster relief later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the dairy compact is unclear. Both the dairy compact
and analysts like the Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group
say the system has not substantially raised milk prices, because
farmers are able to do better financial planning with the price
supports.
</P>
<P>
   But companies that buy dairy products to produce other foods
called the compact a ``price-fixing cartel'' that costs both milk
drinkers and food companies money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need a dairy farm in every backyard in New England,''
said Kathleen Nelson, spokeswoman for the International Dairy Foods
Association. ``New England has way more milk than it needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Midwestern farmers, Nelson said, should not be punished because
New England cannot produce milk as ``efficiently.''
</P>
<P>
   Milk prices have been propped up by the federal government for
60 years on the theory that milk producers have extraordinary risks
_ such as weather, natural disasters, and the short shelf-life of
dairy products.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration decided it was time to bring a more
market-oriented approach to dairy farming, and ordered an overhaul
of the price-support program.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-member Northeast Dairy Compact has had a brief reprieve
from dissolution as supporters and opponents of the new Clinton
policy battle in court over the overall dairy policy. But Becker
said that when the fight over the Clinton agriculture policy is
resolved, the compact _ whose authorization has expired _ will die
unless Congress acts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
