<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6109 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-TREATY-ASSESS-655&AMP;ADD     10-13 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREATY-ASSESS-655&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: THE MOST SIGNIFICANT TREATY REJECTION SINCE VERSAILLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With TEST-BAN-TREATY) 
(bl) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate's decisive rejection of the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty on Wednesday night was the most
explicit U.S. repudiation of a major international agreement in
almost 80 years, and it further weakened the already shaky standing
of the United States as a global moral leader.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the Versailles Treaty was voted down in November 1919,
an action that was repeated in March 1920, has so far-reaching an
accord been turned down. In the entire history of the Republic, the
Senate has rejected only 20 treaties negotiated by U.S. presidents
or other officials, while it has approved 1,523.
</P>
<P>
   By torpedoing a face-saving compromise that had been tentatively
agreed upon by the White House and the Republican leadership,
conservative Republicans made a vote inevitable. And by denying the
treaty not only the requisite two-third majority but even a simple
majority, the conservatives and their allies made good on a promise
by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., to give the agreement a Capitol Hill
``funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   The control of nuclear weapons, perfected in the final days of
World War II, has been a central goal of U.S. foreign policy since
President Dwight D. Eisenhower proposed a ban on all nuclear
testing in 1958. All eight presidents in the four decades since _
Republicans and Democrats, liberals and conservatives _ have sought
in some way to limit testing and weapons development.
</P>
<P>
   In rejecting the test ban treaty, which President Clinton signed
on Sept. 24, 1996, at a ceremony at the United Nations, the Senate
halted the momentum built up over the years. No modern arms-control
treaty had ever been rejected, although President Jimmy Carter, who
had a hard time winning passage of the Panama Canal treaties,
withdrew the SALT II agreement with the Soviet Union from
consideration after the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in late
1979.
</P>
<P>
   The SALT agreement was finally ratified in 1996, when memories
of Afghanistan had faded, but the Russian Duma has never acted upon
it.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty rejected Wednesday night was to have been the
capstone of arms-control efforts, banning even nuclear tests
conducted underground.
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, an international conference in Vienna urged the
United States, Russia and China, all of which had signed the global
agreement without formally ratifying it, to accelerate approval as
a means of bringing renewed pressure on North Korea, India and
Pakistan. They are the only three of the world's 44 nuclear-capable
nations that have not signed the pact.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday of this week, a spokesman for the Chinese foreign
ministry urged U.S. ratification, arguing that it would ``serve as
an example and promote the ratification of the treaty by other
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has not stated its intentions clearly. India and
Pakistan have said they would ultimately sign, although the
military coup in Pakistan this week has raised doubts.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 nations that have signed but not ratified the accord now
have far less incentive to ratify. In addition to Russia and China,
Egypt and Israel are on that list. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said in a speech in Maine on Wednesday that the United
States would continue to observe the terms of the treaty,
conducting no nuclear testing, and urge other nations to do the
same.
</P>
<P>
   But the whole point of the treaty was to make such undertakings
legally binding, not voluntary, and that now seems unachievable.
Ratification by all 44 countries is required for the agreement to
take effect.
</P>
<P>
   So the United States finds itself in the position of the
spoiler, at a time when it is already stigmatized as a nation that
refuses to pay its dues to the United Nations and, in some
quarters, as a nation that takes part in international
peace-keeping and other such efforts only reluctantly, only in some
parts of the world and only when its own ox is being gored.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For Clinton, whose influence abroad is waning, perhaps more than
that of the typical president approaching his final year in office,
the treaty's rejection was the latest in a series of difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   It took place against a backdrop of intense partisan and
ideological polarization between the White House and Congress,
which Clinton was unable to neutralize with the finesse he often
displays on domestic issues. Such polarization also played a key
role in the defeat of the Versailles Treaty, which came after t the
end of World War I, the most popular war the United States had ever
fought up to then.
</P>
<P>
   President Woodrow Wilson, a Democrat, invited neither Republican
leaders nor important senators to Paris for the peace talks,
telling associates that the Republicans, who had taken control of
both houses of Congress in the 1918 elections, would never dare to
refuse ratification. Compounding his error, Wilson refused to
compromise with Sen. Henry Cabot Lodge, R-Mass., chairman of the
Foreign Relations Committee and leader of the opposition to the
Versailles Treaty and the League of Nations, which was set up by a
covenant within the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Lodge and many other Republicans intensely disliked Wilson, and
that contributed to the defeat, just as the enmity of Helms, the
current chairman of the Foreign Relations Committee, and others
towards Clinton contributed to the rejection of the test ban
treaty. But in 1919 and 1920, unlike today, there was a passionate,
detailed debate about the treaty on both sides of the Atlantic,
with leading thinkers joining in attacks on the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the great British economist John Maynard Keynes
condemned Wilson as ``a blind and deaf Don Quixote'' who had been
``bamboozled'' by the more sophisticated Europeans. But the debate
on the test ban treaty has been brief and muted, with opponents
relying on generalized assertions that the accord would harm U.S.
national security by unwisely limiting sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Because it never joined the League of Nations, the United States
was unable to play a role in the League's attempts to head off the
approach of World War II in places like Ethiopia, then called
Abyssinia, and that inevitably weakened the League's peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   After the defeat of the Versailles Treaty and before Wednesday,
only five other treaty agreements had been rejected by the Senate.
U.S. adherence to the World Court, an arm of the League of Nations,
was one of the most important of the issues involved; it was turned
aside in January 1935, with 20 Democrats forsaking President
Franklin D. Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Described as a historic setback at the time, it proved to be
much less than that, as the influence of the World Court crumbled
in Europe's rush towards war. U.S. adherence would have made little
difference.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Lawrence Seaway project was blocked a year earlier, but
it was of course built after World War II. A commercial rights
treaty with Turkey was voted down in 1927. More recently, a
protocol of the Law of the Sea treaty regarding the compulsory
settlement of disputes was rejected (though not the treaty itself),
as was an obscure Montreal aviation protocol.
</P>
<P>
   But none of those actions had anything approaching the gravity
of Wednesday night's rejection, which went to the very heart of thes by the victorious allies to build a safer world in the wake
of World War II.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
