</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: VALENTINE FINESSED AND FLUMMOXED BY COX 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Think of it. The manager who gets no credit for his
team's eight consecutive division championships has outmanaged,
outmaneuvered, outfoxed the self-proclaimed smartest manager in
baseball. It's Bobby Cox 2, Bobby Valentine 0, and counting. Two
more games like the two here, and the Mets will be counted out.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets lost the second game of the National League
Championship Series Wednesday because Brian Jordan and Eddie Perez
clouted two-run home runs for the Braves in the space of five Kenny
Rogers pitches. Rogers, Valentine freely admitted afterward, should
not have been allowed to throw the fifth pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no reason to keep him in,'' Valentine said when asked
about the sixth-inning meltdown. ``I left him in, and it was
absolutely the wrong move.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Valentine makes comments because he thinks that's what
his listeners want to hear, not necessarily because he means them.
So he was asked a few minutes later why he kept Rogers in to pitch
to Perez after Andruw Jones followed Jordan's game-tying home run
with a single.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just what I said,'' he responded. ``I had no reason for that.
It was just not the right move to do. It was just the wrong
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Why was it the wrong decision?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the guy hit a home run, and we got down by two.''
</P>
<P>
   But the failure to remove Rogers at what turned out to be a
critical juncture of the game was unprovoked by anything Cox did or
did not do. Just as he did the night before in Game 1, the Braves'
manager conned Valentine into making a pinch-hitting move that
would backfire. The Game 1 incident was not as meaty as
Wednesday's, but it worked for the Braves and against the Mets
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, Greg Maddux went to the mound to warm up for the
eighth inning, the Braves ahead, 3-1. Dennis Cook, the Mets' relief
pitcher, was scheduled to be the first batter in the inning, but
Valentine sent up Matt Franco, his premier pinch-hitter, to bat for
him. Sorry, Bobby, bad move.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the left-handed-hitting Franco was announced as being
in the game, Cox went to the mound and summoned a left-handed
pitcher, Mike Remlinger, from the bullpen. Gotcha. Valentine had
just wasted his best pinch-hitter. ``He fell for it,'' a member of
the Braves' staff chortled. Playing the right-left game, Valentine
had Melvin Mora, a right-handed hitter, bat instead of Franco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was done; I had stiffened up a little bit,'' Maddux said
later. ``We were just trying to get Franco out of the game. I
wasn't going to make a pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to the ninth inning of Wednesday's game. John
Rocker, the Braves' closer whom the Mets can't hit, had relieved in
the eighth inning after securing the last four outs of the first
game and, with a runner at second base, maintained the one-run lead
by striking out John Olerud and Robin Ventura. When the Braves ran
onto the field for the ninth inning, the left-handed Rocker went
with them, taking his place on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine reacted accordingly, telling the right-handed hitting
Shawon Dunston to bat for the left-handed Darryl Hamilton. But as
soon as Dunston was officially in the game, Rocker was out. The
right-handed John Smoltz entered, and Dunston was left to face him.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bonilla, who would face Smoltz later in the inning, used
the word brilliant in discussing Cox's decision to use Smoltz in
the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, who has taken teams to more postseasons than any other
manager in baseball history, declined to take credit for outfoxing
his foe. He acknowledged that he had no intention to have Maddux
and Rocker pitch any longer, but he said of Valentine, ``He doesn't
know that. What was he going to do? I've had to do the same thing
before.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was not Cox who said in a recent magazine interview: ``I
don't need my competition to like me. But a lot of them just
absolutely fear that someday they're going to have to be on a panel
with me or something, and they'll just be exposed. That's a bad
statement. I know that. But I think it's absolutely true.''
</P>
<P>
   The Franco and Dunston moves weren't the only ones that
backfired for the Mets' Bobby.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth inning of Game 1, the Mets, down a run, had a
runner at first, two out and Rey Ordonez the next hitter. Valentine
let Ordonez, the weakest hitter in the starting lineup, bat while
he had Benny Agbayani in the on-deck circle to bat for Turk
Wendell. Agbayani might not have had much of a chance against
Rocker, but maybe he would have gotten lucky and tied the game with
a home run. Such a possibility did not exist with Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   But Valentine regretted that he had had Bonilla bat for Ordonez
with the bases loaded in a game here three weeks ago _ Bonilla
struck out _ and apparently had resolved not to make that move
again.
</P>
<P>
   Asked before the game Wednesday if there might be a time he
would hit for Ordonez, Valentine said: ``I don't think so. I don't
have a reason to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, he added: ``He's giving really good at-bats. That was the
best at-bat we had all day yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant the one against Rocker when Ordonez fouled off a
succession of pitches before grounding out sharply. But with two
out in the ninth inning Wednesday, Valentine did hit for Ordonez,
calling on Bonilla again. Again Bonilla struck out.
</P>
<P>
   At least the bunt that Ordonez foolishly tried in the second
inning wasn't Valentine's doing. With one run in, runners at first
and third and no one out, Ordonez pushed a bunt toward first base,
and Brian Hunter caught it in the air. The shortstop had bunted on
his own, the manager said. ``I was surprised by it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The part of the baseball world that listens to Valentine is
undoubtedly surprised at the turn of managerial events in this
series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
