<SLUG> BC-DELL14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report critical of Dell customer service
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a surprising turnabout for a company that
consistently garners awards for customer service, Dell Computer
Corp. has been placed on a ``watch list'' for alleged
customer-service failings by a company that advises corporate and
government clients about their computer purchases.
</P>
<P>
   A report by Giga Information Group cites seven customers,
ranging from an author to a large Atlanta mortgage lender, who
complained of problems and poor customer service.
</P>
<P>
   The six-page report follows a sharply critical one-page
``Alert'' from Giga on Sept. 27 that accused Dell of shipping wrong
equipment, missing promised delivery dates, failing to fulfill
terms of agreements and ``arrogant disregard'' for customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the problems largely appear to be new accounts, this
does not reflect a broad quality problem with Dell,'' wrote Giga
Vice President Rob Enderle on Sept. 27. ``But (it) does reflect a
risk for accounts that are choosing to move to Dell from another
vendor _ a move that we believe is unreasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   In both reports, Enderle claims that Dell employees are covering
up mistakes, which is a pattern he said he saw previously in
fast-growing companies such as Apple Computer Inc., Microsoft Corp.
and Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Enderle, a 26-year veteran of the industry, also has been
critical of other computer makers. Earlier this year, he put
Houston-based Compaq Computer Corp. on a watch after Chief
Executive Eckhard Pfeiffer was fired. Compaq has since been removed
from the watch.
</P>
<P>
   Dell executives readily acknowledge problems with some orders,
noting that mistakes are inevitable for a company that is expected
to ship 12 million PCs this year. But the company disputes
Enderle's assertion that employees routinely conceal
customer-service problems from senior management.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think that customer-support issues do not get raised to
senior executive level is ... ridiculous,'' Dell spokesman David
Frink said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Frink said Dell officials will meet with Giga, a 4-year-old
Cambridge, Mass., company with more than 1,000 clients in business
and government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't reiterate enough that we are continuing to talk
to Giga to resolve these customer issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reports are surprising in light of Dell's reputation for
being sharply focused on customer service. Last year, Fortune
magazine's Technology Buyer's Guide gave Dell its ``Readers'
Choice'' award for overall service and reliability. Another
publication, PC Magazine, named Dell its ``Readers' Choice'' winner
for service and reliability for desktops and notebooks.
</P>
<P>
   Other industry research companies said they have not noticed
recent customer-service problems at Dell. Nonetheless, complaints
about Dell _ or any computer maker _ aren't hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   Geri Roberts, a 62-year-old Austin resident, said she tried
recently to buy a Dell Dimension with the help of her sister in
West Virginia, who planned to charge the machine on her credit
card. Excited to learn Web page design as a source of income,
Roberts tried to order a custom-built machine on the phone with a
Dell saleswoman. But for the next several days, Roberts and her
sister were unable to reach salespeople at Dell to complete the
purchase. Frustrated, they bought a PC from Micron Electronics
Inc., Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think that somewhere along the line they (Dell
officials) need to find out that customers are not being treated as
they ought to be,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Oppenheim chose Dell in June for a server, workstations
and notebooks when she started her Dallas-area business, Grapevine
Medical Systems Inc., which sells software programs for physicians.
</P>
<P>
   But because of problems with several notebooks she ordered _
ranging from shipping delays to missing software and two computers
with pinholes in screens _ she had employees sitting idle for weeks
while waiting for new equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was paying five people for two months to sit there because
we didn't have computers,'' Oppenheim said.
</P>
<P>
   Oppenheim said she bought notebooks from Compaq. This week, Dell
told her it would credit her account for the $25,000 order.
</P>
<P>
   The experience of Atlanta-based HomeBanc Mortgage Corp., the
leading residential lender in Georgia, was more serious. The
company estimates its five-month problem with Dell notebooks cost
it $350,000 in lost business.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, HomeBanc bought 100 Latitude notebooks from Dell
for loan officers in South Georgia and Florida. Almost immediately
they started failing because the motherboards were loose, said
Robert Bennett, HomeBanc's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Warranty work with Dell's partner, GetronicsWang, that was
supposed to arrive within a day didn't come for five days, he said.
He said Dell resisted accepting responsibility for the defects.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put the burden back on us to prove their hardware had a
problem,'' said Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said things improved once he reached Dell Senior Vice
President Joe Marengi, who flew to Atlanta this summer to meet with
him. The faulty notebooks will be replaced with faster machines and
the company has agreed to buy an additional 175 Latitudes, Bennett
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad news is it took quite a long time to get here,'' he
said, adding that Dell salespeople pleaded with him not to go over
their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
