<SLUG> BC-BBA-CURRY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ENJOY THE SHOW AT SHORTSTOP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The statements uttered as facts begin with one or two people
when Derek Jeter ambles out of the team hotel in Boston. The words
turn into verbal abuse when he emerges from the dugout for batting
practice at Fenway Park. The noise escalates to a deafening level
when he saunters toward the on-deck circle in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   There are thousands of fans booing Jeter, but there are always a
few who are a little louder and a little more proud of their own
slick shortstop. So they let Jeter know that, in their opinion, he
cannot lift Nomar Garciaparra's batting gloves. Not today, not next
week, never.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, when I go to Boston, that's all I hear,'' Jeter
said. ``How bad I am. How I'm no Nomar. I'm sure when he comes
here, he hears the same things.''
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative. Garciaparra grinned when he heard about Jeter's
ears buzzing in Boston and confirmed that his ears buzz whenever he
visits the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear the same thing here about Derek being great and stuff
like that,'' Garciaparra said. ``I think it's all in good fun. I
have the utmost respect for all the fans here.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra is obviously not as loose with his opinions about
New York fans as the Braves' Chipper Jones was, but his gracious
sentiments will not prevent them from treating him like an imposter
who is invading Jeter's hallowed ground between second and third
base. This is the way it should be. Baseball should be about
debating who is better, team versus team, player versus player and,
of course, Nomar versus Derek.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter and Garciaparra are talented, respectful, team-oriented
players who symbolize their teams; the businesslike Yankees and the
resilient Red Sox, and, therefore, the two shortstops symbolize
this rivalry. It is a different rivalry now, not built on hatred so
much anymore. That could change during this century-concluding
American League Championship Series. Even Roger Clemens said,
``This might rekindle it a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   It should. The rivalry between the Yankees and the Red Sox will
always be intense because they have a history, because they are in
the American League East, because they are so close geographically
and because, for the next decade, it will continue to be
embellished by Jeter and Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only enhances it,'' Yankee pitcher David Cone said. ``It's
already a good matchup and then you add two good, young players to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra has more power (27 homers to Jeter's 24), but Jeter
has more range and is better defensively (14 errors to Nomar's 17).
Garciaparra won the batting title with a .357 average, with Jeter
second at .350. Garciaparra has helped a pesky team reach the
post-season for the last two years, but Jeter has helped the
Yankees win two World Series titles in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Who is better? Who cares? Enjoy the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have thought they were going to be putting up the
numbers they do?'' asked John Valentin, who was supplanted by
Garciaparra and now plays third for Boston. ``It's like Nintendo. I
still think they're going to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the way it should be. Fans stillabout whether Ted
Williams or Joe DiMaggio was the superior hitter. Don Zimmer said
on Tuesday that Carlton Fisk hated Thurman Munson and vice versa.
Don Mattingly was perturbed when Wade Boggs sat out the last three
games of the 1986 season against the Yankees with a phantom
hamstring injury and won the batting title over Mattingly, .357 to
.352. Mike Torrez helped the Yankees win the World Series in 1977
and helped the Red Sox lose a playoff game and so much more to
Bucky Dent in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know if you're a Yankee fan, you hate the Red Sox,'' Jeter
said. ``If you're a Red Sox fan, you hate the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is apparently no animosity between Jeter and
Garciaparra, just respect. When Jeter jogged onto the field to
replace Garciaparra during the All-Star Game in Fenway Park last
July, they hugged. When Jeter batted, he tapped his left foot and
imitated Garciaparra's constant fidgeting in the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said I didn't do it right,'' Jeter said. ``I struck out.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter is perfect for New York and Garciaparra is perfect for
Boston and neither team would trade one for the other. Boston is a
conservative town and Garciaparra mixes seamlessly into this
attitude with his no-nonsense style. He dislikes talking about
himself and someone who has been around the Red Sox said that
Garciaparra looks weird wearing sunglasses. Even that seems too
flashy for him.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter, who has a white mother and an African-American father,
thrives in the multicultural melting pot of New York. He once said
that fans are not sure what nationality he is so everyone embraces
him, which is being modest about his skills. Jeter is not too
flashy, but he has been on the cover of GQ, he endorses clothing by
Michael Jordan and he has more pizazz than Garciaparra. Argue about
which shortstop is better, but, more important, watch and enjoy
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I hear my name in the same sentence as his, I think
that's an honor,'' Garciaparra said. ``I think he's absolutely
tremendous. Put my name with his and I'm saying, `Wow, that's an
honor.''' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
