<SLUG> BC-SENATE-FARM-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPROVES $8.7 BILLION FOR EMERGENCY AID TO FARMERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Pa., Vt., Iowa, N.C., Cuba)   By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Driven by low crop prices, bad weather in many
parts of the country and arcane farm-state politics, the Senate
gave final legislative approval Wednesday to an $8.7 billion
package of emergency aid to farmers.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second straight year Congress has spent billions to
bail farmers out of financial trouble, raising doubt about the
political practicality of applying free-market principles to
American farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency assistance is part of a $69 billion spending bill
to finance agriculture and food programs in the current fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved the final version by a vote of 74-26. The
opponents were almost all Easterners from both parties who opposed
the way the bill dealt with milk prices.
</P>
<P>
   The House gave its final approval to the measure on Oct. 1.
President Clinton is expected to sign the measure quickly. The
Agriculture Department said checks should begin going out to
farmers within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The new fiscal year began on Oct. 1, but the agriculture bill is
only the sixth of 13 spending bills for the federal departments and
agencies to clear Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The government has been running on stop-gap legislation that
will expire on Oct. 21 and will almost certainly have to be
extended to keep federal offices open while the politicians work
out their differences.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the money in the bill approved Wednesday will go
for food stamps and other nutrition programs. Much of the rest is
earmarked for uncontested agriculture and rural development
programs.
</P>
<P>
   To get the final version through Congress, several potentially
controversial items were left out by the conferees who reconciled
the bills passed by the House and Senate. One would have allowed
food and medicine to be shipped to Cuba. Another would have
prohibited the Food and Drug Administration from approving abortion
drugs like RU-486.
</P>
<P>
   But senators from the East balked when the conferees excluded
provisions that would have blocked a new milk-pricing system
favored by the Clinton administration and would have allowed the
continuation of an arrangement that keeps a floor on milk prices in
New England. Several other Eastern states hoped to join the New
England compact.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the Senate voted, 79-20, to cut off a filibuster by
the Easterners and bring the bill to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   The dairy question led to strange political bedfellows. Liberal
Democrats like Patrick J. Leahy of Vermont and Frank R. Lautenberg
of New Jersey voted alongside conservatives like Rick Santorum,
R-Pa., and Robert C. Smith, a Republican-turned-Independent from
New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency assistance itself had no opposition, though many
senators argued that $8.7 billion was inadequate in the face of
Midwestern grain prices that are the lowest in decades and the
large crop losses from the drought this summer in the East, floods
in the South and crop disease in the upper Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Harkin, an Iowa Democrat who voted for the bill,
c it to ``throwing a leaking life raft to a drowning
person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps a little bit,'' he added, ``but it's not a long-term
solution to the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The consensus in Congress is that additional emergency
assistance will be needed when the farm losses in North Carolina
from Hurricane Floyd are tallied.
</P>
<P>
   Farm politics is guided much more by regional interests than
partisan ones. But Democrats used the bill Wednesday to renew their
attack on the Freedom to Farm Act of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The law was one of the central elements of Republican dogma that
party leaders got enacted after they won control of Congress in the
1994 election. It abolished most of the government price-support
programs, in place since the 1930s, on the theory that farmers
would fare better in an unfettered marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers were happy in 1996 and 1997, when commodity prices were
high and they were entitled to what were called transition payments
from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But when grain prices began to plunge last year, farmers turned
to the government for help, and the politicians who represent them,
regardless of party, obliged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transition turned out to be more difficult than we
anticipated,'' said Sen. Charles E. Grassley of Iowa, a leading
Republican supporter of the Freedom to Farm Act.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Grassley said, was not the principle of the law but
the fact that its authors did not anticipate such events as the
devaluation of Brazilian currency and the crash in Asian economies,
which had a devastating effect on American farm exports.
</P>
</TEXT>
