<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-REAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS EXPANDS CHOICES ON PUNISHING PAKISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (With PAKISTAN-COUP) 
(lh) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress moved Wednesday to give President Clinton
greater flexibility in deciding whether to impose sanctions against
the Pakistani military a day after the overthrow of the elected
government there.
</P>
<P>
   The change, which was embedded in a $268 billion defense
appropriations bill approved by the House, technically eases
sanctions that have prohibited U.S. military assistance and arms
sales to Pakistan since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted Wednesday to approve the bill, which House and
Senate negotiators worked out last week, 372-55. It now goes to the
Senate, where approval is also expected.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Wednesday's House vote was a coincidence, but the
change in sanctions underscored the complexities of the U.S.
response to the coup and other events in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has endorsed the change in the
sanctions, but officials emphasized Wednesday that the United
States would not now begin providing military assistance or
economic aid to Pakistan in light of the coup on Tuesday, led by
Pakistan's army chief, Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf. The bill stops short
of repealing the sanctions outright, which the Senate originally
included in its version of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it gives the president the authority to waive a raft of
sanctions that, by law, are now imposed automatically against
Pakistan, as well as India, because of their development of nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Wednesday that the changes would
give the president greater flexibility in offering incentives and
disincentives to the Pakistanis, rather than tying his hands with
blanket restrictions on aid. At the same time, officials said, the
coup had sorely undercut any Pakistani hopes of receiving aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no intention of pursuing military sales at this
time,'' the State Department's spokesman, James Rubin, said. ``What
we intend to do is seek from Pakistan the earliest possible
restoration of civilian government.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Wednesday night, President Clinton
announced that he had ordered the U.S. ambassador, William B.
Mylam, back to Pakistan's capital, Islamabad, to push the
administration's call for a return to civilian rule. ``Pakistan's
interests would be served by a prompt return to civilian rule and
restoration of the democratic process,'' Clinton said. ``I urge
that Pakistan move quickly in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation to ease sanctions had been part of a bipartisan
congressional effort, supported by the administration, to try to
deepen its engagement with Pakistan following years of tensions
over its development of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The United States cut off all arms sales and military assistance
in 1990 after concluding that Pakistan possessed nuclear weapons.
Pakistan, like India, faced even more sweeping sanctions on trade
and food assistance last year after detonating nuclear weapons in
May 1998. But members of Congress, worried that those sanctions
could hurt farmers and manufacturers, gave Clinton the authority to
waive some of those.
</P>
<P>
   The new bill would make that waiver authority permanent and
expand it to include the prohibitions on military assistance, as
well as those on sales of products that have both civilian and
military uses. The United States would still prohibit sales of
military items that could be used to develop missiles or nuclear
weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
