<SLUG> BC-TEST-BAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTES NOT TO RATIFY NUCLEAR TEST BAN TREATY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican-controlled Senate voted Wednesday
not to ratify the landmark global test ban treaty, rejecting a
last-minute appeal by Democrats and allied leaders to set aside the
accord aimed at preventing the proliferation of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-48 vote against it was an unprecedented and stunning
rebuke for President Clinton, who has worked hard to have it
ratified by other nations and to win support for it from U.S.
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance at the White House, Clinton vowed to revive the
treaty again and suggested that he would use it against Republicans
in next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is well-worth fighting for, and I assure you the fight is
far from over,'' the president said, calling the vote ``reckless''
and ``partisan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a political deal and I hope it will get the treatment
from the American people it richly deserves,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said his administration would continue to abide by the
terms of the treaty anyway and continue with a 7-year-old U.S.
moratorium on nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton needed the backing of two-thirds of the senators, or 67
votes, to win ratification. But only four Republicans joined with
44 Democrats to support it. Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., voted
present.
</P>
<P>
   The vote marked the first time since the Treaty of Versailles
following World War I was defeated that the Senate had rejected an
arms-related pact intended to stop the spread of weapons and the
expansionist ambitions of rogue nations.
</P>
<P>
   It also endede time being decades of bipartisan
cooperation on arms control matters that have helped guide U.S.
foreign policy down a consistent path through both Democratic and
Republican administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Trent Lott, R-Miss., said Republicans had acted
``with great pride'' in rejecting the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty, which was negotiated by 154 countries between 1994 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Insisting the treaty was ``fatally flawed,'' Lott said
Republicans would not be ``a rubberstamp'' for Clinton's foreign
policy. ``We did the right thing for America,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, however, said rejection of the treaty would only
contribute to instability in areas of the world, such as South
Asia, where nuclear proliferation problems are nearing a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this fateful vote tonight, the world becomes a more
dangerous place,'' said Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Condemnation of the Republican-led effort rejecting the test ban
treaty also came from U.S. allies who have already ratified the
pact signed by 154 countries. British Prime Minister Tony Blair and
other leaders took the unprecedented step of appealing directly to
Republican leaders by letter and phone before the vote, saying that
rejection of the treaty would send a message to emerging nuclear
nations that it's all right to pursue weapons development programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats vowed to use the treaty's rejection to portray
Republicans in next year's elections as opponents of global
anti-proliferation efforts designed to prevent the buildup of
nuclear arsenals. Democratic leaders said they would also resubmit
the treaty again next year in hopes of persuading more Republicans
to back it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect this will be an issue in the national elections next
year,'' declared Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.
</P>
<P>
   In a floor speech prior to the vote, Daschle accused Lott of
choosing partisanship over statesmanship in moving ahead with the
vote on the controversial treaty, which would prohibit all nuclear
test explosions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican response was cynical. It was a partisan attempt
to embarrass the president and embarrass the Democrats,'' he
charged.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was a major defeat for Clinton, who had made the
initiative a cornerstone of his foreign policy. He and Daschle had
sought to head off a vote by forging a compromise agreement with
Lott on Tuesday that would have shelved the pact in return for
Daschle's written pledge that the Democrats would not try to revive
it until 2001 after Clinton leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   But that tentative deal was ultimately scrapped by four
conservative opponents of the treaty _ Sens. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,
Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., James Inhofe, R-Okla., and Bob Smith, I-N.H. _
who insisted that Lott not compromise.
</P>
<P>
   As further evidence of just how highly-politicized the test ban
treaty had become, the Republicans beat back an 11th-hour attempt
by Democrats to withdraw it by voting 55-45 strictly along party
lines in favor of holding the final vote.
</P>
<P>
   In the subsequent debate, Helms and other treaty opponents
scoffed at Democrat charges that they were playing politics with
the nation's national security just to ``get even'' with Clinton
for besting them on a host of other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me a break,'' said Helms, who also rejected what he
called ``the Chicken Little argument'' asserted by Democrats and
allied leaders such as Blair that the United States would no longer
be able to object when other countries conduct nuclear test
explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Helms stressed that the treaty would hinder U.S. efforts to
modernize its own nuclear arsenal. He also expressed concerns that
the treaty could not be verified because monitoring technology does
not yet exist that can distinguish between low-level nuclear
explosions and naturally occurring phenomena, such as earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must have a clean break (on the treaty) so that the next
president can establish American credibility on nonproliferation,''
Helms said.
</P>
<P>
   Helms was able to keep more than enough Republicans from siding
with the Democrats. Only four Republicans senators _ Arlen Specter
of Pennsylvania, John Chafee of Rhode Island, Gordon Smith of
Oregon and James Jeffords of Vermont _ voted in favor of the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Specter agreed with the Democrats that rejection of the pact
would be ``an open invitation for other nations to test.'' In hopes
of winning more GOP support, he also pointed to an ``escape
clause'' in the treaty that would allow the United States to
withdraw its support if U.S. nuclear officials conclude at any time
that the safety and reliability of the U.S. arsenal cannot be
certified without further testing.
</P>
<P>
   The raw politization of the issue was apparent from the first
moment debate began Wednesday. Tempers flared, for example, when
Lott rejected a request by Byrd to speak for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd eventually got his time and he used it to blast Lott for
engaging in partisan politics and running roughshod over the
minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in this body for 41 years ... and as a (former)
majority leader and minority leader I never once objected to a
senator's request to speak,'' a red-faced Byrd snapped at Lott.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to have better comity in this Senate. The American
people are watching,'' Byrd said.
</P>
<P>
   Responding, Lott offered no apologies for his handling of the
treaty or his treatment of the senior senator. Instead he simply
summed up the attitude on both sides of the aisle by observing that
``passions do run high.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
