<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRBUS-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRBUS IS SAID TO WIN ORDER FROM FRONTIER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo.)  (af) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frontier Airlines has decided to buy 20 new narrow-body jets
from Airbus Industrie, two people close to the negotiations said,
becoming the latest airline to choose the European consortium over
its archrival, Boeing Co.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier, a low-cost carrier that flies to 19 cities from its
base in Denver, Colo., plans to replace its current fleet of 19
Boeing 737s, beginning in 2001. The two people said that the
airline is in the final stages of negotiating a letter of intent
with Airbus that includes a firm order for 10 Airbus A319 and A318
jets, as well as options for another 10 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   At list prices, the deal is worth about $1 billion, though
airlines often pay much less than list.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel D. Addoms, Frontier's president and chief executive, said
in a telephone interview Wednesday that the airline had been
negotiating with Airbus and Boeing for six months, but he declined
to say whether a final decision had been made. Spokesmen for Airbus
and Boeing also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Frontier is yet another blow to Boeing, which has
lost several longtime customers to Airbus in recent years. Last
week, British Airways, which bought its first Airbus planes last
year, said it had placed an additional order for the 100-seat A318
to replace its fleet of 44 Boeing 757s.
</P>
<P>
   Since its resurrection under new management in 1994, Frontier
has struggled to compete against UAL Corp.'s United Airlines, which
dominates Denver's airport.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier turned a profit for the first time last year, making
owning rather than leasing planes more cost-efficient, Addoms said.
</P>
<P>
   One person close to Frontier said that the airline, which only
offers economy service, chose Airbus in part because the fuselage
of its narrow-body jets is slightly wider than the 737s, giving
Frontier the ability to offer slightly wider seats or a wider
center aisle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
