<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OTHER MARTINEZ HEADS FOR THE SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He is the Martinez brother who pitched a no-hitter.
He is the one who struck out 18 batters in one game. He is the one
who will take the mound at Yankee Stadium Thursday night in Game 2
of the American League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   He is Ramon Martinez, the older brother of Pedro. That Ramon
Martinez would pitch in a meaningful October game against David
Cone is quite improbable after a rotator cuff injury threatened to
end his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great,'' Ramon said of the prospect of the two
brothers starting for the same team in the postseason, a baseball
rarity that until now has been identified with Dizzy and Paul
``Daffy'' Dean, who won two games each as they led the St. Louis
Cardinals over the Detroit Tigers in the 1934 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the beginning, I've enjoyed being with my brother this
year, and we've got a chance to make it to the World Series,'' the
31-year-old right-hander said. ``I mean, I don't think anybody
could ask for anything more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox could ask for Ramon to pitch the way he did before
the surgery, when his production with Los Angeles placed him among
the league's elite pitchers. At the time, Ramon, who was 123-77
with the Los Angeles Dodgers, was the prominent Martinez brother,
and Pedro was trying to establish himself with the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   But the elder Martinez cannot be what he was then. Clearly,
Ramon is still finding his way back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any difference,'' Ramon said. ``My velocity maybe,
but everything else is there. I can throw all my pitches. I don't
have any kind of problem with my arm. And I feel better and
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Cone, who has had to endure his own shoulder problems,
understood what it feels like to step back on the mound filled with
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure in his own mind he didn't know what to expect when he
went out there,'' Cone said. ``It sort of came on in a hurry for
him. It's a remarkable comeback. I don't think anyone was counting
on him pitching in the postseason for Boston. Not only has he
pitched, he seems to be back. It's a real emotional story, sort of
a tough thing to deal with, that you're back, that your arm
strength is back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox took a gamble on him, signing him last March 11
after he had undergone the surgery on his right shoulder on June
30, 1998. There was some hesitance on the part of Pedro to bring
his older brother, a more quiet and sensitive man, to Boston. But
the team discussed its plans with Pedro and the two sides agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of whether we were going to sign him or make him an
offer was discussed with Pedro prior to us extending an offer to
Ramon,'' Dan Duquette, the Red Sox general manager, said. ``It was
discussed, and Pedro thought about it. We talked about it a couple
of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Pedro came around, Duquette smiled and said, ``Ramon
signed with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon made his first rehabilitation start last June 21, throwing
two innings in the New York Penn League for the Lowell Red Sox.
After 10 rehabilitation assignments, while working his way through
the Red Sox chain, he finally found his way to a major-league mound
on Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Four starts during the regular season totaling 20 2/3 innings
was all he had pitched when he took the mound in Game 3 of the
division series against Cleveland. But he limited the Indians to
two runs in 5 2/3 innings in Boston's 9-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put a lot of air miles on this year, bus miles too,''
Boston Manager Jimy Williams said. ``When he joined us, he started
a game, and then I brought him in and said, `Listen, maybe it is
just asking too much of you.' But the kid kept working, and he
never stopped one day from doing his exercises. He was just trying
to come back and help our club win.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still felt in his mind he could pitch and help us. We had a
situation later on during the trip, in Cleveland, when Pat Rapp had
to leave our club and was supposed to start a game. In my mind,
flying at 35,000 feet, I said, `I'll pitch Ramon.' He pitched very
good there. He got better with each of his starts.''
</P>
<P>
   While Ramon once struck out 18 in a game and the best Pedro has
done is 17, Pedro did strike out 15 or more batters six times this
season, and the 17 strikeouts were against the Yankees in a
one-hitter he pitched last month. So being ranked second in the
Martinez family is hardly shameful. But Ramon is happy just to be
back, pitching in a crucial situation, even if he has to resort
more to craft than to raw talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started my rehab, that was the hardest part because
there was a lot of pain,'' he said. ``There was a lot of soreness,
but I never stopped. I never gave up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
