<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6143 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS-HNS &LR;      10-13 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ Their backup catcher is playing like Carlton Fisk, their
baby-faced closer looks like he has been here a million times, and
their starting pitching has been everything you might expect from
the best collection of starters in baseball.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And, oh, yeah: The Atlanta Braves' manager is batting close to
1.000 when it comes to making key decisions in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets are in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves extended their postseason winning streak to five
games with a come-from-behind 4-3 victory Wednesday in Game 2 of
the National League Championship Series. If you thought it was only
the Astros who had trouble solving the complexities of the Braves,
think again.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are two victories away from another trip to the World
Series. And from the looks of things, there's not much the Mets can
do about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd better do something soon,'' Mets third baseman Robin
Ventura said. ``We're running out of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Time might as well be on the Braves' side; everything else is.
</P>
<P>
   In the 29-year history of the NLCS, only two teams _ the 1984
Cubs and the 1985 Dodgers _ have failed to reach the World Series
after winning the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   Today is a travel day in the best-of-seven series, which resumes
Friday at New York's Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to New York up 2-0 gives us a lot of confidence, and
maybe it puts a little pressure on them, too,'' said Braves starter
Kevin Millwood, who won his second playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood outdueled Mets starter Kenny Rogers, who was cruising
along until the Braves exploded for four runs in a sixth-inning
outburst keyed by a pair of two-run homers _ one by Brian Jordan
and the other by Eddie Perez.
</P>
<P>
   The little-known catcher is 4-for-7 with two homers and three
RBIs in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the key,'' said Mets manager Bobby Valentine, who
second-guessed himself for allowing Rogers to pitch to Perez.
``That was absolutely the wrong move. I had no reason for it; it
was just not the right move to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of things that went through my mind. It was
just the wrong decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox wouldn't know about that. Every move he
made turned to gold.
</P>
<P>
   If it were possible to credit two pitchers with a save in the
same game, John Rocker and John Smoltz each would have received one
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz got the save in his first career postseason appearance
out of the bullpen. Smoltz pitched the ninth inning, but you could
argue that Rocker actually saved the game in the eighth when he
struck out John Olerud and Robin Ventura to bail Millwood out of a
jam.
</P>
<P>
   Because Rocker pitched 1 innings in Game 1 and had worked past
the Mets' two dangerous lefthanded hitters, Cox wisely used the
hard-throwing Smoltz to close Wednesday's game. Smoltz, who is
scheduled to start Game 4 on Saturday, would have done his
between-starts throwing Wednesday anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had him in my hip pocket,'' Cox said of Smoltz, who
reached 96 mph on the radar gun.
</P>
<P>
   It's the third time Cox has used a starting pitcher in relief
during this postseason. Millwood and Greg Maddux worked out of the
bullpen against the Astros in Game 3 of the Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have good makeup, and you have to be kind of
special,'' Cox said. ``I'm sure a lot of pitchers could do it, and
these guys have pretty good stuff, too. You kind of want to get
them in there; it's not a desperate-type thing.''
</P>
<P>
   If the move had backfired, Cox would have opened himself to
second-guessing for using his closer, Rocker, too soon. But when
Rocker entered the game, the Mets had a runner on second base with
one out.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Olerud and Ventura are a combined 0-for-11 with
seven career strikeouts against Rocker, Cox picked a good time to
use his closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you have an opportunity to win, you'd better grab
ahold of it,'' Cox said. ``It was a critical part of the
ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored first on Roger Cedeno's RBI single in the second
and stretched the lead to 2-0 when former Astros farmhand Melvin
Mora homered in the fifth. It was the first home run of Mora's
brief big-league career.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves killed the Mets' early momentum with two swings in
the sixth inning. Not surprisingly, Chipper Jones walked prior to
Jordan's home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it when people challenge me, and if the Mets want to
continue to walk Chipper to get to me, then I'm just going to
continue to take advantage of those opportunities,'' Jordan said.
``So far, I've been pretty fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said: ``They've been pitching me carefully, and now
they're going to have to pitch B.J. carefully. He did this to
Houston, too. I think people are going to start looking at our
lineup and see that I'm the only sure out.''
</P>
<P>
   The way things are going, the Braves might be able to wrap up
the series in New York even without much of a contribution from
Chip-pah.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
