<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6150 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-TREATY-MISSTEPS-ART-2     10-13 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREATY-MISSTEPS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS' SUBTERFUGE AND DEMOCRATS' MISSTEPS DOOMED TREATY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.D., Ariz., Mich., N.C., N.Y., Del., Va.)  (See also TEST-BAN-TREATY, TREATY-ASSESS, TREATY-CLINTON) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Byron Dorgan reached the limit of his patience
on Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Dorgan, a Democrat from North Dakota, took to the Senate floor
that day to denounce the Republican leadership for refusing to
permit debate on the worldwide treaty to ban nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I am not here to cast aspersions on any member of the
Senate,'' said Dorgan, doing just that with an attack on Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott. Dorgan said Lott had failed in his duty
_ to the Senate and to the world _ to allow consideration of the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty. Until Lott relented, Dorgan said,
``I intend to plant myself on the floor like a potted plant'' and
block any routine business from coming before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a tough place to run if you do not decide
to bring this issue to the floor of the Senate,'' Dorgan threatened
Lott.
</P>
<P>
   It was a foolish and empty threat, Clinton administration
officials and some of Dorgan's Democratic colleagues now say. Not
only did it offend Lott's sense of his role as master of the
Senate, it precipitated Wednesday night's vote that defeated the
treaty and humiliated President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   What Dorgan and other advocates of the test ban treaty did notwhen he issued his threat in September was that the
Republicans already had more than enough votes to decisively reject
the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a sharp stick in the eye of the Republicans,'' said a
chagrined senior administration official. ``They called our
bluff.''
</P>
<P>
   The demise of the test ban treaty is a tale of fatal
miscalculation by Senate Democrats, benign neglect by the White
House and sleight of hand by Senate Republicans and other opponents
of the agreement. The result pleased Lott and his associates, but
it shined a harsh light on the institution of the Senate and left
U.S. allies bewildered yet again by the nation's strange way of
doing public business.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate action was a particularly sharp repudiation of
Clinton because he had sold the treaty as a national security
imperative for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Since last winter, a handful of Republicans led by Sen. Jon Kyl
of Arizona had been secretly proselytizing their fellow members
about the treaty and accumulating committed votes against it. They
enlisted several former top U.S. officials who opposed the treaty,
including former Defense Secretary James Schlesinger and retired
Gen. Brent Scowcroft, a former national security adviser, to help
sway their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Kyl told Lott he had 34 firm Republican votes against
the treaty, meaning that advocates of the treaty could not reach
the two-thirds majority needed to approve it.
</P>
<P>
   Lott reported the news to Sen. Jesse Helms, chairman of the
Foreign Relations Committee, an ardent foe of the nuclear testing
agreement, and suggested that Helms could safely release the treaty
for a quick rejection on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Helms said, ``Get me more,'' according to an aide. He wanted the
treaty finished, dead, with no chance of revival, the aide said.
Kyl continued quietly rounding up opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats did not see the opposition to the treaty hardening in
large part because relations between the parties are so bad that
Democrats and Republicans often do not talk to each other about
pending business. The White House's legislative affairs operation
likewise did not detect the looming disaster for the president,
according to a senior administration official.
</P>
<P>
   Although President Clinton and Senate Democrats had periodically
issued calls for consideration of the treaty since Clinton
submitted it to the Senate in September 1997, they began their
agitation in earnest this summer.
</P>
<P>
   All 45 Democratic senators signed a letter to Helms on July 20
urging him to hold hearings on the treaty and report it to the
Senate for debate by September, so that the United States could
attend a conference of countries that had signed the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Helms responded a week later with a scornful letter, saying he
would not consider the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty until after he
had disposed of two other international agreements the
administration cared about, amendments to the Anti-Ballistic
Missile treaty and the Kyoto global-warming pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I note your distress at my floccinaucinihilipilification of
the CTBT,'' Helms wrote, using a word meaning ``considering as
worthless.'' ``I do not share your enthusiasm for this treaty for a
variety of reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   The matter lay dormant through the Congress' August recess, but
when lawmakers returned in early September, some Democrats were
determined to press the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a frustration with the failure to get this treaty
considered, a legitimate frustration,'' said Sen. Carl Levin,
D-Mich. He acknowledged that Democratic impatience gave Lott all
the excuse he needed to call for a quick vote on the treaty, a vote
he was certain he would win.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put us in a position of looking like we didn't want the
treaty to come up if we opposed that kind of extremely rapid
consideration,'' Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 22, Senate Democratic Minority Leader Thomas Daschle
and Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., the senior Democrat on the Foreign
Relations Committee, assembled other Democratic supporters of the
treaty to meet with White House National Security Adviser Samuel
Berger to plot their next move.
</P>
<P>
   Biden told Berger that he intended to try to make good on
Dorgan's threat to disrupt other Senate business in a bid to speed
consideration of the weapons testing treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Biden and other Democrats, ignorant of the deeply rooted
Republican opposition to the treaty, thought at that point that as
many as 25 Republicans could be persuaded to vote to approve the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, we felt we needed to bring this to a head, any
way we could,'' Biden recalled. He told Berger that unless the
Democrats acted, the treaty would remain bottled up by Helms in the
Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Berger asked, presciently, ``What if they call for up or down
vote?'' Biden recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the best way,'' Biden replied, ``but it's better than
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later, in a private conversation on the Senate floor,
Lott told Biden that he would bring up the test ban treaty if
Democrats lifted their threat to obstruct the Senate calendar.
</P>
<P>
   It sounded like a good-faith offer, but in fact it was a trap.
Lott intended an accelerated schedule of treaty hearings,
culminating in a vote less than two weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, only partly aware of what was happening behind the
scenes in the Republican caucus, gave their unanimous consent to
Lott's timetable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became difficult for the Democrats to say we can't do this,
we would have looked stupid demanding hearings, demanding a vote
and then complaining about the process. There's no moral victory in
that,'' said a Democratic legislative aide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lott thought we'd turn down his offer,'' the aide continued,
``and so we were both locked into essentially a fight to the death,
like scorpions in a bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration quickly recognized the noose Lott had slipped
around the president's neck. Privately, officials were furious with
Senate Democrats for putting the treaty at risk by baiting the
Republicans into calling a quick vote without adequate time to
gauge the sentiment of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is the White House didn't see this coming,'' said a
senior administration official enlisted in the belated effort to
salvage the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question the administration wanted the treaty and
wanted it done right, but the precipitous rule giving us only 12
days to do it was based on taunting by the Senate Democrats and
they were free-lancing,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The president and his top foreign policy advisers went all out
to try to win votes for the treaty. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, Defense Secretary William Cohen and Gen. Henry Shelton,
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, all appeared on Capitol Hill
to lobby for the agreement. Clinton assembled former officials and
Nobel laureates at a White House pep rally to try to build support.
White House chief of staff John Podesta and Berger made dozens of
calls to Senators trying to find a face-saving way to delay the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a losing battle, and all seemed to know it.
</P>
<P>
   Albright on Tuesday telephoned Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
D-N.Y., and Sen. John Warner, R-Va., who together were trying to
fashion a compromise that would defer consideration of the treaty
indefinitely. The administration had grasped at that solution as
preferable to the treaty's being permanently rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling kind of helpless here,'' Albright told Moynihan,
according to an official who was privy to the conversation. ``What
can I do?''
</P>
<P>
   Not much, Moynihan replied, the Republicans have made up their
minds to take this thing down.
</P>
<P>
   The question was echoed by Clinton himself in a series of
belated phone calls to Republican senators as late as two hours
before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   And the answer was the same: It's too late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
