</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROCKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKER HELPS GET ATLANTA OUT OF ANOTHER TIGHT SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Rocker is a man of habit. And during the
postseason, he has made a habit of getting batters out.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 minutes after Wednesday's sparkling relief
performance, Rocker finally appeared in the Atlanta Braves'
clubhouse, having followed his ritual of working out after games.
Why should Rocker change his routine? He has been baseball's best
reliever during the postseason, a hard-throwing, highly emotional
left-hander who attacks batters and dares them to hit his best
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Rocker is winning the battles. During the eighth inning
of Wednesday's 4-3 victory in Game 2 of the division series against
the Mets, Rocker pitched his way out of another crucial jam.
</P>
<P>
   He entered the top of the eighth with one out, with the Braves
protecting their one-run lead and with Edgardo Alfonzo on second
base after a run-scoring double. The heart of the Mets' order was
coming up _ John Olerud, Mike Piazza and Robin Ventura _ and
Rocker's difficult mission was to keep Alfonzo from scoring, to
protect Atlanta's lead.
</P>
<P>
   Mission accomplished. First Rocker struck out Olerud, a fine
left-handed hitter who usually makes contact, even against
left-handers. Then after walking Piazza intentionally, Rocker
struck out Ventura, another left-hander, with a nasty slider,
ending the inning and bringing the partisan crowd at Turner Field
to its feet.
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz retired the Mets in the ninth inning to earn the
save, but Rocker earned congratulations on another job well done.
He has saved both games as the Braves have taken a 2-0 lead over
the Mets in the best-of-7-game championship series, and in the
division series against the Houston Astros he escaped a
bases-loaded, nobody-out situation in the 10th inning of Game 3
without allowing a run, which proved to be the turning point of
that series.
</P>
<P>
   It has become an impressive formula for the Braves: get to the
late innings with a lead, then get Rocker in the game. Rocker has
made it look easy. But when it was over, Rocker, the star reliever,
admitted that he was relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys like Olerud and Ventura are veteran hitters who keep
making adjustments, and you never know what adjustments they'll
make,'' Rocker said. ``I'm playing a cat-and-mouse game with them,
changing my patterns. If Olerud guesses right and gets the pitch
he's looking for, it's almost a guaranteed base hit. But so far,
I've been fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker has also been good, and his emergence as a dominant
pitcher could not have come at a better time for Atlanta. The
Braves lost their ace reliever, Kerry Ligtenberg, for the season
with an arm injury in spring training, opening the door for Rocker
to fill the void.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker responded by saving 38 games, one short of the team
record. And being a left-hander gives him an advantage in many
situations, such as Wednesday, when he overmatched the left-handers
Olerud and Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   ``Left-handed closers are rare, because if you have a
left-hander with that kind of stuff, you usually make a starter out
of him,'' said John Schuerholz, Atlanta's general manager. ``But we
don't need starting pitching. We needed a closer. When John was a
starter earlier in his career, there was nothing very special about
him. But he was a closer walking around in a starter's body. He not
only has the stuff to be a closer, he has the aggressive
mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rocker runs hard from Atlanta's outfield bullpen to the
mound, the crowd explodes. And after Rocker ends a game, or escapes
a jam, he often celebrates outwardly, pumping his fist or
screaming. But his actions were subdued by his standards after
saving Game 1 on Tuesday and after Wednesday's eighth inning. What
gives?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to act like not quite such an idiot,'' Rocker
explained. ``And the game wasn't over. It would've looked silly to
do that, then see them come back and win 5-4 in the ninth.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker wanted to pitch the ninth inning Wednesday, but he lost
his dugout debate with Manager Bobby Cox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I argued, but it's kind of pointless to argue with a manager
with his credentials,'' Rocker said.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Mazzone, Atlanta's respected pitching coach, sided with Cox.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Rocker to pitch another 10 years,'' Mazzone said. ``We
protect arms around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker warmed up before the ninth inning, then yielded to
Smoltz, leaving the game to a warm ovation. But when the series
resumes Friday at Shea Stadium, Mets fans will not be nearly as
friendly to Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   Was Rocker worried? What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tired act,'' he said of the Mets fans. ``I'd rather
pitch in front of a crowd that jeers than a crowd that cheers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker will get his wish this weekend. But so far in the
postseason, both home and away, Rocker has been having his way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
