<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6153 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-TREATY-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      10-13 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREATY-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DISAPPOINTED CLINTON SAYS THE FIGHT IS `FAR FROM OVER'
</HEADLINE>
   (With TEST-BAN-TREATY, TREATY-MISSTEPS, TREATY-ASSESS) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A grim-faced President Clinton said Wednesday night
that he was ``very disappointed'' over the Senate's rejection of
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty but said the fight was ``far from
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on the White House lawn, the president attributed the
treaty's defeat to ``politics, pure and simple.'' He said the
treaty was critically important in preserving world peace, and that
it was ``well worth fighting for _ and I assure you, the fight is
far from over.''
</P>
<P>
   Many politicians involved in the battle have said that the
Senate's action Wednesday dooms any chances for the treaty to be
considered again for the rest of the Clinton presidency, and the
president did not elaborate on his promise that the fight would
continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never before has a serious treaty involving nuclear weapons
been handled in such a reckless and ultimately partisan way,'' the
president said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we could have had a responsible alternative,'' he told
reporters. ``I worked until the 11th hour to achieve it,'' adding:
``I also encourage strongly countries that have not yet signed or
ratified this treaty to do so. And I will continue to press the
case that this treaty is in the interest of the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Several countries had planned to follow the lead of the United
States in taking action on the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   He said the senators who rejected the treaty ``turned aside the
best advice of our top military leaders,'' and ``ignored the
conclusion of 32 Nobel Prize winners in physics, and many other
leading scientists.''
</P>
<P>
   The president went on to call the vote ``a political deal _ and
I hope it will get the treatment from the American people it richly
deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   And speaking thousands of miles away, Vice President Al Gore
pledged that if he was elected president, his first act would be to
work toward ratifying the treaty. Gore called the Senate's
rejection the fruit of ``right-wing extremists'' and said it was
``breathtakingly irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to make this a campaign issue,'' he said in an
interview with National Public Radio shortly after he landed in
Seattle, on a flight from Los Angeles. ``And with the support of
the American people, I will make this pledge: My very first act as
president, if I have the support of the American people to become
president, my very first act will be to resubmit this treaty to the
Senate for ratification. And during this campaign, I want to do
everything I can to cultivate support for ratification.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore added: ``For somebody in the rest of the world who thinks
`Oh, gee, the United States has just gone off its rocker here and
come out in favor of opening up nuclear tests again,' no, that's
not what happened. A small, willful group of Republicans listened
to a tiny minority of right-wing extremists and took an action thatis contrary to what the American people feel.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``So stay tuned, world. We are going to ratify a
treaty banning nuclear tests. It is only a matter of time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
