<HEADER>
A6155 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LEAD-LAWSUIT-1STLD-WR     10-13 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAD-LAWSUIT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-585(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RHODE ISLAND SUES PAINT MAKERS OVER LEAD-POISONING HEALTH COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 7th graf to give full DuPont name; adds insert after 89th
graf to give companies' response)  (bl) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rhode Island attorney general sued eight paint manufacturers
and a lead industry trade group in state court Tuesday in an effort
to make them pay for treating children poisoned by lead paint and
removing lead paint from buildings.
</P>
<P>
   At least a dozen other states, counties and cities are
considering filing similar suits, as governments did earlier
against the tobacco and gun industries, and others are considering
suits, lawyers involved in the cases said.
</P>
<P>
   And as in the suits against cigarette makers, which led to
settlements with the states totaling $240 billion, lawyers for
Rhode Island are accusing paint manufacturers of knowing lead paint
was dangerous, especially to children, and of covering up the risk.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government banned lead paint in 1978 because of
health concerns, but studies this decade have found that two-thirds
of the nation's housing still contains lead paint, and that 890,000
children between 1 and 5 years old have elevated lead levels in
their blood. Ingesting paint chips or dust containing lead can
cause severe mental, developmental and behavioral problems,
including lowered intelligence, in children.
</P>
<P>
   High lead levels are more common in the older Northeast, where
many homes and buildings were constructed more than a generation
ago, when lead was a standard ingredient in paint. According to
Rhode Island officials, 20 percent of kindergarten students there
have elevated blood-lead levels.
</P>
<P>
   The Rhode Island suit accuses the eight companies, or companies
that they now own, of promoting the use of lead paint while
covering up the dangers it posed to children. The suit, filed by
Attorney General Sheldon Whitehouse, also names as a defendant the
Lead Industries Association, an industry trade group.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants are Atlantic Richfield Co. of Los Angeles; E.I.
duPont De Nemours &AMP; Co. of Wilmington, Del.; -Williams Co.
of Cleveland; and NL Industries Inc. of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Also named were Glidden Co., a unit of Imperial Chemical
Industries PLC in England; O'Brien Corp., which was bought by ICI;
and SCM Chemicals Inc. and American Cyanamid Co., whose paint
liabilities were assumed by Cytec Industries Inc. of West Paterson,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of some of those companies said the lawsuit was
meritless and that they had always manufactured paint in a safe and
appropriate manner. Some compa- nies also said they had not
manufac- tured paint in years. Cytec Indus- tries Inc., which
acquired certain as- sets of American Cyanamid six years ago, said
it did not believe the company was ever a maker of made lead paint.
</P>
<P>
   A number of lawsuits against lead manufacturers by individual
plaintiffs have failed in the past. But the Rhode Island lawsuit
seeks a different remedy, following the path of state lawsuits
against the tobacco industry, which ended in settlements totaling
more than $240 billion.
</P>
<P>
   As in those cases, which sought to recoup the costs of treating
smoking-related illnesses, Rhode Island is seeking reimbursement of
money spent on the health costs of lead paint, not money to
compensate individual victims.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers pressing the new cases also plan to harness the same
financial resources used to pay for the tobacco litigation, as at
least three lawyers who played major roles and won huge fee awards
in suits against tobacco will be involved in lead-paint cases. The
Rhode Island attorney general said the plaintiffs' lawyers would
receive about 17 percent of any verdict or settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Lead industry officials called the lawsuit a ``groundless and
wasteful action'' and said that past lawsuits alleging industrywide
conspiracies have failed. ``This is litigation that is trying to
make a scapegoat of responsible companies,'' said Timothy Hardy, a
lawyer representing NL Industries, one of the defendants in the
Rhode Island suit. ``The story the plaintiff lawyers are trying to
tell is wrong.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jeff Miller, executive director of the Lead Industries
Association, said he had not seen the lawsuit and could not comment
on its specifics. But he said blood-lead levels have been falling
for years, in part because the industry quit selling lead paint in
the early 1960s. ``Most kids are way below any medical level of
concern,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Motley, a key lawyer in the state tobacco lawsuits, whose
firm filed the Rhode Island lead-paint suit, said he believed that
documents he has show that the industry covered up the dangers of
lead paint, much as tobacco executives hid the dangers of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were as omnipresent and evil as the tobacco industry ever
hoped to be,'' Motley said. ``This is not a teenage problem. This
is a toddler problem. The tobacco industry targeted teenagers, but
at least teenagers could read. You're talking about poisoning
children with an odorless, colorless but tasty thing. It's
insidious.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for New York City Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani said
the city is looking at possibly suing lead paint manufacturers but
that no decision has been made. A spokesman for New York State
Attorney General Eliot Spitzer said he was not aware of any
imminent plans to file a suit against the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Rhode Island lawyers will seek to contrast advertisements
and statements by manufacturers that lead is not harmful with
internal and other documents that they contend demonstrate the
industry knew of serious health risks but lied about them and
sought to delay increased labeling and disclosure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Subpoenas to the defendants will begin going out this week,
lawyers said. But they already have obtained some documents that
they say support their accusations, with industry officials
dismissing concerns about poisoning as a problem faced largely by
``slum children,'' while also showing that they knew more than 50
years ago that lead was toxic and lead paint dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   One document, from the Lead Industries Association's 1959 annual
report, comments that lead poisoning, or the threat of it, ``means
thousands of items of unfavorable publicity every year. This is
particularly true since most cases of lead poisoning today are in
children, and anything sad that happens to a child is meat for
newspaper editors and is gobbled up by the public. It makes no
difference that it is essentially a problem of slums, a public
welfare problem. Just the same, the publicity hits us where it
hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   And, according to the lawsuit, the association's director of
health and safety informed members in 1955 that ``childhood lead
poisoning is common enough to constitute perhaps my major
`headache,' this being in part due to the very poor prognosis in
many such cases, and also to the fact that the only real remedy
lies in educating a relatively ineducable category of parents. It
is mainly a slum problem with us,'' the lawsuits quotes document as
stating, adding that ``we have no monopoly on either substandard
housing or substandard mentalities in the U.S.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy, the lawyer for NL Industries, said these documents have
been introduced into courts before, and yet no judge or jury has
ruled against the manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Don Ryan, executive director of the Alliance to End Childhood
Lead Poisoning, a public interest group in Washington, said lead
poisoning has long been a more severe problem in lower-income
areas. But he said it also afflicts affluent areas, especially when
renovations cause the release of lead-paint dust.
</P>
<P>
   Some problems happen because of ``the inadvertent creation of
hazards at the other end of the economic spectrum, yuppies fixing
up the grand old Victorian,'' Ryan said. He estimates it would cost
$500 billion to remove all the paint in the nation's dwellings.
</P>
<P>
   The lead-paint lawsuits will be a reunion of sorts for some of
the most important lawyers involved in the state tobacco
settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Motley, whose Charleston, S.C., firm, Ness, Motley,
Loadholdt Richardson &AMP; Poole, represented 28 states in the tobacco
litigation, Baltimore Orioles owner Peter Angelos, another
prominent anti-tobacco plaintiff lawyer, filed two cases against
lead paint manufacturers in September in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   And Richard Scruggs, a Pascagoula, Miss., lawyer who also was
instrumental in the tobacco litigation, is expected to play a part
in at least a few lead paint lawsuits in the Southeast. Scruggs
said Wednesday he may not become involved at the same national
scope as he was with tobacco, due to the press of other cases,
including recent litigation against HMOs. But he said ``in some
selected cases, I'm sure we'll be with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
