<HEADLINE>
APPLE REPORTS POSITIVE FOURTH QUARTER RESULTS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After warning last month of an earnings
shortfall, Apple Computer Inc. Wednesday reported results for its
fourth quarter that exceeded Wall Street analysts' revised
estimates. Apple executives also predicted strong sales for the
December quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Apple said it had been able to ship only 6,000 of its new iBook
laptops, which were announced in July, because of production delays
caused by the Taiwan earthquake. Apple executives said they
expected no material impact from the earthquake in the December
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Apple also said that IBM Corp. would begin manufacturing its
high-end G4 microprocessor next year, alleviating supply problems
that held back sales during the quarter. Motorola, which has been
the sole supplier of the chip, was not able to raise production
rapidly enough to meet the demand for Apple's new G4 Power
Macintosh. The G4 is the latest version of the Power PC
microprocessor co-developed by Apple, IBM and Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   Apple reported its results after the market's close. In Nasdaq
trading, Apple shares closed at $64.03125, down $3.65625, but they
gained as much as $4 in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they squeaked out of the quarter pretty well, and have
set themselves up for just tremendous performance now through the
end of the year,'' said Lou Mazzucchelli, an analyst with Gerard
Klauer Mattison. Noting that growth in orders was accelerating, he
added: ``The company's profile has been elevating, and people feel
safer buying these things. That's a very powerful long-term
trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Motorola has been unable to supply the fastest versions
of the G4, Apple said it had rered the Power Mac computers
using the chip. They will now ship in speeds of 350, 400 and 450
megahertz, each 50 megahertz slower than originally announced, but
with no reduction in prices. The 500-megahertz version will now not
be available until after the first of the year.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended Sept. 25, Apple reported earnings of $111
million, or 63 cents a diluted share, up 5 percent from $106
million, or 68 cents a share, in the period a year earlier. Sales
fell 14 percent, to $1.35 billion, from $1.56 billion in the fourth
quarter of fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-quarter 1999 earnings include a $21 million positive
impact from nonrecurring items, including an after-tax gain of $37
million from the sale of approximately three million shares of ARM
Holdings PLC, and a reorganization charge of $16 million for
contract cancellation charges related to previously outsourced
services and a discontinued business. Without these nonrecurring
items, Apple's earnings for the quarter would have been $90
million,cents a diluted share.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Apple to earn 45 cents a share, according
to First Call/Thomson Financial. Before Apple's warning last month,
the consensus estimate was 76 cents.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been reachable but for the limited availability
of microprocessors, Steven P. Jobs, Apple's interim chief
executive, said in a telephone interview. ``If we'd have gotten the
G4 chips that had been promised us, we'd have been fine,'' he said.
``We're back on track now. We have no production constraints on
Powerbooks, G4s or the new iMac, and we're coming up to speed very
quickly on iBooks.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with securities analysts, Fred Anderson,
Apple's chief financial officer, said Apple had orders for 200,000
iBooks but had only been able to ship 6,000 units in the quarter.
He said it had orders for 150,000 G4 PowerMac's, but had only
shipped 64,000. The company ended the quarter with a backlog of
400,000 units, equivalent to $700 million in unrealized revenue, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Apple announced three new versions of its popular
iMac, including two with the ability to edit digital movies, and it
has already received more than 250,000 orders, Anderson said. These
machines are not included in the backlog number.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to catch up on G4 Power Macs by the end of the
December quarter, but will remain constrained on iBooks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With all four product lines shipping in the December quarter,
Anderson said he expected sales to exceed the fourth fiscal quarter
and the corresponding quarter a year earlier. But he said gross
profit margins would probably drop a point or two from the 28.7
percent reported in the fourth quarter, primarily because a greater
percentage of total sales would be lower-margin consumer machines
and because of higher costs for memory chips. These negative
impacts will be partly offset by the release of Mac OS9, the latest
version of Apple's operating system, which begins shipping this
month.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, Apple reported earnings of $601 million, or $3.61
a diluted share, nearly twice the $309 million, or $2.10 a diluted
share, it reported in fiscal 1998. Revenues rose 3 percent, to $6.1
billion, from $5.9 billion in the prior year.
</P>
</TEXT>
