<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: FORBIDDEN TO LEAVE
</P>
<P>
   A woman from a religious-oriented party was forbidden to leave
the country while a prosecutor draws up charges of subversion
against her. The politician, Merve Kavakci, was elected to
Parliament this year but forbidden to take the oath of office
because she insisted on wearing her Muslim head scarf. Later, after
it was discovered she had failed to disclose that she held a U.S.
passport, she was stripped of her Turkish citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: ULSTER TALKS IN LONDON
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of Northern Ireland's political parties taking part
in the peace settlement review under former Sen.r George J.
Mitchell are meeting for two days at an undisclosed location in the
London area under an agreement not to speak with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: `BLOODY SUNDAY' ANONYMITY
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry into the Bloody Sunday killing of 14 civil rights
protesters by paratroopers in Londonderry 27 years ago granted
anonymity to all soldiers present at the shootings. Relatives of
the dead deplored the decision, but a Ministry of Defense spokesman
said, ``It provides a crucial measure of protection for all
military witnesses who could have been subjected to the threat of
terrorist reprisal.''
</P>
<P>
   BELGIUM: 6 MORE APPLY TO EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   In a move to accelerate expansion of the 15-nation European
Union, the executive commission in Brussels proposed that six more
nations be allowed to start membership negotiations. Talks are
under way with Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Estonia,
Slovenia and Malta. The commission has now agreed to consider
eventual membership for Slovakia, Latvia, Lithuania, Bulgaria,
Romania and Malta.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE: DEPORTED CHRISTIANS WELCOMED
</P>
<P>
   The government announced that it would welcome a group of 25
Christian pilgrims, 18 of them Irish, who were deported from Israel
as a doomsday cult and then refused entry to Cyprus. A spokesman
for the group denied they planned a mass suicide attempt in
Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA: PESSIMISM ON TALKS
</P>
<P>
   An official newspaper voiced pessimism over the prospects of an
Israeli-Syrian peace, accusing the Israeli prime minister, Ehud
Barak, of having ``blocked all the routes'' that might lead to the
resumption of talks. The Syrian government welcomed Barak's
election last May, but that mood has turned much darker as Barak
has refused to endorse what Syria says was a previous Israeli
commitment to withdraw fully from the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: FISHERMEN STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   More than 5,000 west coast fisherman and fishery workers have
gone on strike, forcing factories to halt processing of pilchards
and anchovies and threatening export supplies. Workers have been
locked in a dispute over a wage increase, with management offering
7.5 percent and the Food and Allied Workers Union demanding 10.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: PERONIST PICKS UP
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll of 1,537 people suggests that Gov. Eduardo Duhalde
of Buenos Aires, the presidential candidate of the governing
Justicialist Party, is gaining strength before the Oct. 24 election
but remains far behind the Buenos Aires mayor, Fernando de la Rua.
De la Rua, of the Alianza coalition, leads by 12 points compared
with 19 points a month ago. De la Rua has 43 percent support,
Duhalde 31 percent and former Economy Minister Domingo Cavallo 10
percent. The poll had a margin of error of 3-4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   5 U.N. WORKERS SEIZED IN GEORGIA
</P>
<P>
   A day after two U.N. relief officials were killed in Burundi by
an armed gang that raided a refugee camp, five U.N. military
observers and two other employees accompanying them were taken
hostage in Abkhazia, a province trying to secede from Georgia.
</P>
</TEXT>
