<SLUG> BC-TIME-WARNER-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER SAYS RESULTS SHOW STRONG REBOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Time Warner Inc. said Wednesday that it earned $369
million in the third quarter, with the cable, cable networks and
publishing divisions posting substantial gains while the music and
filmed entertainment divisions showed losses.
</P>
<P>
   Net income per diluted share was 27 cents, in contrast to a loss
of 3 cents a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's combined cash flow _ earnings before interest,
taxes and amortization _ for the period was $1.6 billion, up 49
percent from $1.08 billion a year earlier. Revenue grew 3 percent,
to $6.71 billion, from $6.59 billion for the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Leibowitz, a senior vice president at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, said that the report had no surprises. ``The expectations
had been lowered because of a recent downturn in the music
business, which showed a pretty big decline,'' he said. ``But
everything else was pretty much in line with their expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's stock closed Wednesday at $62.625, down $1.25, on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner chairman and chief executive Gerald Levin said
Wednesday in meetings with analysts and reporters that he expected
the company's overall growth rate for 1999 to be similar to that of
1998, about 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings at the cable networks grew 21 percent, to $328
million, in the third quarter; part of that growth was driven by
double-digit growth at Turner Cable Networks and HBO. Time Warner
Cable posted record earnings of $894 million, up from $417 million
a year earlier, reflecting an increase in basic cable, advertising
and pay-per-view revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Levin cited the People group as the most dynamic producer of new
products at Time Inc., the company's publishing division, where
earnings rose 15 percent to $129 million. He said Teen People, a
magazine founded in early 1998, will be profitable by the beginning
of the new year.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting with reporters, Levin said he was disappointed in
the music division, the Warner Music Group, which posted
third-quarter earnings of $76 million before interest, taxes and
amortization, down from $99 million in the third quarter the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music was off and will be down for the year,'' Levin said, but
he added that the replacement of the former management team, Robert
Daly and Terry Semel _ whose primary duties included overseeing the
Warner Brothers film studio _ with Roger Ames would bolster the
division's productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner president Richard Parsons said the music industry
had been affected by adverse economic conditions in Japan, Germany
and Brazil, three of the five major international music markets.
Levin said that the music division experienced ``some slippage''
this year, but that was also partly because the division's major
performers _ among them Madonna, Alanis Morrissette and Jewel _ did
not produce any albums this year. ``Not enough of our big horses
were out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Third-quarter earnings for the filmed entertainment division
were down slightly, to $228 million, from $233 million in the third
quarter of 1998. But earnings for the first nine months of 1999
were up to $806 million, versus $497 a year earlier. Revenue at the
Turner Broadcast Networks filmed entertainment division declined
because of the absence of revenue included in the previous year
from the syndication of ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   Theatrical revenue benefited from the domestic box-office
results of New Line Cinema's ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged
Me'' which earned $205 million, and the worldwide box-office
revenue for ``The Matrix,'' which has earned $418 million.
</P>
<P>
   The WB Television Network lost $24 million in the third quarter,
which compared with a loss of $17 million for the third quarter in
1998. The network has lost $95 million in 1999, large part because
of the cost of expanded programming; analysts said that was to be
expected. ``The WB added another night of programming and the
ratings have been pretty good,'' Leibowitz of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the WB is losing money now, if you are trying to
reach the teen-age demographic, there is no better place to be,''
Levin said, adding that he expected to see advertising revenue rise
in the next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
