<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6173 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BROOKLYN-FILM-STUDIOS     10-13 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYN-FILM-SNYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE NIRO GROUP REPLACED AS DEVELOPERS OF FILM STUDIO IN BROOKLYN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., Calif.)   By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Five months after it was announced with fanfare, a
tentative deal calling for the actor Robert De Niro and Miramax
Films to develop a $150-million Hollywood-style sound stage complex
at the Brooklyn Navy Yard has collapsed, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the mayor said the project would go forward, with the
sound stages to be built by a group headed by Douglas C. Steiner,
the son of David S. Steiner, a New Jersey financier who is
prominent in political and Jewish causes. Their company, Steiner
Equities, will provide much of the financial backing for two
entrepreneurs, Louis Madigan and Cary Dean Hart, who signed a
contract with the city in 1998 to build the sound stages but were
brushed aside when De Niro and his partners became involved.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Douglas Steiner and his partners signed a 70-year
lease with Brooklyn Navy Yard Development Corp.,asi-public
agency that manages the former shipbuilding site, Marc H.
Rosenbaum, the agency's president, said Wednesday. Their team, New
York Studios, has $90 million in financing, enough to begin
construction, Rosenbaum and Steiner said. Steiner Equities is
putting up $35 million of that, Rosenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the New York Studios proposal ``a much better deal for
the city,'' Giuliani said that the plans with De Niro's company,
TriBeCa Productions, and his partner, Steven Roth, the chairman of
Vornado Realty Trust, were abandoned for legal, financial and
practical reasons. The city's decision was first d Wednesday
by Bloomberg News Service and New York 1 News.
</P>
<P>
   New York Studios had threatened to sue the city if De Niro's
team prevailed, and that could have tied up the project for a long
time, even if the city ultimately won, officials said. While the
TriBeCa deal would have required the city to put up $25 million,
the rival group has not asked for a similar subsidy. Under the
Steiner proposal, the city would get at least $63 million more in
revenue during the first 40 years of the contract, Rosenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by reporters why the plans with De Niro had been unveiled
with so much hoopla, including the actor's presence, Giuliani said
that the press release for that event had emphasized that the idea
was being explored.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press release says `explore' at least three times, so it
was explored,'' the mayor said. ``That's what the word means. It
doesn't mean `agreement.' It doesn't mean `deal.'''
</P>
<P>
   But the press release also quoted Giuliani as saying, ``This is
great news for New York City's booming film and television
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed deal with De Niro and his partners was greeted with
skepticism in some quarters because the team had yet to raise $80
million at a time when there was a surplus of sound stages in
Hollywood and the movie industry itself _ including the Walt Disney
Co., Miramax's parent _ was not in good financial shape. Even
people who operate sound stages say it is tough to make money
because production companies cannot usually make long-term
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the entertainment industry said that it might be even
tougher for inexperienced entrepreneurs. Madigan is a computer
consultant and Hart is a set designer.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosenbaum, of the Brooklyn Navy Yard, dismissed those
concerns, saying that film companies using the site for location
shooting routinely complained about a shortage of modern sound
stages. He said the city wanted to meet the demand without
incurring any further delays.
</P>
<P>
   Steiner said his team planned to build 11 sound stages _ one
fewer than the rival group had proposed _ ranging in size from
12,000 to 40,000 square feet. He estimated the cost of the project
at $90 million to $120 million and said he hoped that TriBeCa
Productions, Miramax and Vornado would eventually agree to join
forces with New York Studios venture. ``But we're prepared to go it
alone,'' he said. He said construction could begin in six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   TriBeCa and its partners declined to comment on the city's
decision. But one associate of the partners with intimate knowledge
of the negotiations said that De Niro and Harvey Weinstein, the
co-chairman of Miramax, had been committed to the Navy Yard project
and were baffled by the way the city had treated them. He said
there was no chance that the De Niro-Weinstein group would join the
rival team.
</P>
<P>
   There was some speculation Wednesday that politics had played a
role in the city's decision. This summer, Weinstein, a staunch
supporter of Hillary Rodham Clinton, Giuliani's potential rival in
next year's Senate race, had to hold the celebratory party for his
new magazine, Talk, at the Statue of Liberty after the city refused
to allow him the use of the Navy Yard.
</P>
<P>
   David Steiner and his wife, Sylvia, have contributed thousands
of dollars to Giuliani's campaigns. But over the last five years,
Steiner has contributed more than $700,000 to the Democratic Party
and many Democratic candidates. In July, he attended a White House
dinner for Ehud Barak, the prime minister of Israel, and sMrs. Clinton's table.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
