<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON TAKES MIDDLE GROUND: SHE ROOTS FOR SUBWAY SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARMONK, N.Y. _ The New York Mets were battling for the National
League pennant in Atlanta. The New York Yankees were going up
against the Boston Red Sox in the Bronx. And Hillary Rodham Clinton
was here in Westchester County Wednesday for a news conference
devoted to epidemiology, when what is arguably the most difficult
question any candidate in New York could confront this fall whizzed
toward her head:
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees or the Mets?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, it seems, is both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am for a Subway Series!'' the first lady, who is a probable
candidate for the U.S. Senate, declared. ``I can state that without
fear of any contradiction. I think it would be great for New York
and hope it comes to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Mrs. Clinton's press secretary, Howard Wolfson,
stepped in with a polite, if firm, `'Thank you,'' and drew the news
conference to a hasty close.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, whose hometown is Chicago, had been asked the
question back in July, when the notion of a Mets-Yankees World
Series senciful. At the time, Mrs. Clinton sidestepped it,
saying that _ no matter her inexperience in running for office _
she was smart enough not to take sides in such a hypothetical
dispute. This took place after she had plopped a Yankee cap on her
head during a White House ceremony, which struck even her friends
as politically inartful.
</P>
<P>
   But baseball times have changed. Mrs. Clinton's likely
Republican opponent, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, is a vigorous Yankee
fan, and, inevitably, was headed to Yankee Stadium for Wednesday
night's game. And with her answer, it seems safe to say that Mrs.
Clinton may be the only New Yorker _ or more precisely,
soon-to-be-New-Yorker _ who has not chosen sides in the
Mets-Yankees faceoff.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's nonrevealing response was in keeping with the
generally risk-averse nature of these early days of her presumed
campaign for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, for example, she came to a biological field
station of Fordham University to denounce Republicans in Congress
for failing to finance a $65 million network for tracking emerging
epidemics. The context was the outbreak of West Nile-like
encephalitis in New York, but she declined to suggest the network
would have made any difference in how the matter was handled, nor
did she find fault with Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue,'' she said, ``is will we be prepared next
time, because I think all of us agree there will be a next time.''
</P>
<P>
   From here, Mrs. Clinton headed back to New York City for another
fund-raiser, arranged by the Rap impresario Russell Simmons. The
first lady had no plans to drop in on any ball games that might be
taking place in the Bronx, said Wolfson (who is, he revealed
without hesitation, a Yankees fan.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
