<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS READY FOR WEST RIVALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After three games against Eastern Conference teams
and four days off, the Kings fly to Calgary this afternoon for the
first of two games against Western Conference opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The Flames and Oilers have one victory between them, but as
teams from the West, the Kings will play them a little differently
than they did the Washington Capitals last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings blew a two-goal lead to tie the Caps 2-2. Under a new
system, teams each receive a point for a tie game after regulation
and another point if they win in the five-minute, sudden-death
overtime period.
</P>
<P>
   Against nonconference opponents on the road, the Kings said they
didn't mind playing for the tie. But against teams that could
impact the Kings season-long battle to make the playoffs, the team
is expected to be more aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly didn't want to tie a game that we were leading
2-0,'' coach Andy Murray said. ``But to go home after starting the
season 3-1-1 on the road is pretty good in my book.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules, teams use four skaters in the extra session
to promote more scoring. So far the Kings are tied for second in
the conference with 14 goals, including seven by league leader Luc
Robitaille, who was named NHL Player of the Week.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille actually was in the penalty box for more than 1{
minutes to begin the overtime against Washington, putting the Caps
at a 4-3 advantage. Robitaille returned to the ice and swatted away
a last-second shot in front of the goal to preserve the tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little too exciting,'' Murray said. ``But I like the
new setup. It will be wide open and we need that. You can gain a
point in your conference if you tie and another if you win. If you
lose, you still get a point.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flames will take anything they can get these days. The NHL's
second-youngest team behind the New York Islanders earned its first
point Monday afternoon with a tie against Carolina. The Hurricanes
play in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Playing time: Forward Dan Bylsma and defenseman Jaroslav Modry,
who were scratched from each of the Kings' first five games, were
sent to the Kings' minor-league affiliate, the Long Beach Ice Dogs,
to play Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Murray wanted to keep both sharp and the players will accompany
the team to Calgary and Edmonton this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Modry had an outstanding training camp, playing in place of
Mattias Norstrom, who missed the entire preseason in a contract
dispute. Murray told Modry two days before the season opener in
Nashville that Norstrom was close to signing and that Modry would
lose playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Modry played 64 games last season at Long Beach with six goals
and 29 assists. Bylsma played most of the 1998-99 season with the
Ice Dogs but appeared in eight games with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Storr ready: With back-to-back games in Calgary on Friday and
Edmonton on Saturday, the Kings wanted to make sure goalie Jamie
Storr was ready. He started the second of back-to-back games last
Thursday but left after one period with a strained right groin.
</P>
<P>
   Stephane Fiset, who has started four of the first five games,
entered the game Thursday against Tampa Bay and turned away all 17
shots he faced. Storr, who missed 16 games last season with astrained left groin, participated in workouts this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
