u k BC-EDIT-TESTBAN-TREATY-N     10-13 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TESTBAN-TREATY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A DAMAGING ARMS CONTROL DEFEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Oct. 14:
</P>
<P>
   In a narrow and misguided show of partisanship, the
Republican-led Senate on Wednesday forced a vote on the nuclear
test ban treaty and defeated it by a margin of 48-51.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's action _ its bluntest rebuff of a president on a
major international agreement since it voted down Woodrow Wilson's
Treaty of Versailles in 1919 _ is a destructive abdication of U.S.
leadership on arms control and other international issues. The harm
done to U.S. foreign policy and national security could be
considerable. President Clinton must now do what he can to limit
the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Tactical blunders were made on all sides of the treaty debacle.
Democratic senators insisted that the issue be included on the
Senate calendar though they were well short of the 67 votes needed
for ratification. The White House belatedly launched its campaign
for the treaty and seemed unprepared for opposition testimony. But
by far the greatest blame belongs to Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott and the Republican caucus, which allowed itself to become
captive to some of the party's most parochial senators.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days Lott stubbornly rejected efforts by Senate
Democratic leaders to avoid the international embarrassment of a
rejection vote even when they were prepared to offer him firm
assurances that the treaty would not be reintroduced without his
approval during the life of the present Congress. Those guarantees
amounted to a painful concession by treaty supporters. But they
were right to make the offer. Regrettably, Lott turned them down.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, Senate Democrats now intend to make an issue of
the Republicans' unstatesmanlike handling of the test ban treaty.
They are entitled to do so, and the American people may choose to
register their unhappiness over this Senate vote in next year's
elections. But the Democrats should remember that any future
attempt to ratify the treaty, which must presumably wait until
after those elections, will require bipartisan support, since the
Constitution requires a two-thirds Senate majority for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, some of the worst fears expressed by treaty
opponents may now be more likely to come about as a result of
Wednesday's vote. These include nuclear weapons development by
countries that have not yet signed the treaty, erosion of America's
current lead in weapons technology and secret low-yield testing by
Russia or other nuclear powers.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest dangers lie in South Asia, especially after this
week's military coup in Pakistan. It will be much harder now for
the United States to persuade both India and Pakistan to sign a
test ban trea the Senate has refused to ratify. Washington
must also keep working to prevent such potential nuclear powers as
Iran, Iraq and North Korea from moving ahead toward their own
nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate vote will also complicate America's nuclear diplomacy
with China, which has signed the treaty and is observing a
voluntary moratorium on testing. Beijing has recently acquired
improved bomb designs, possibly through espionage at U.S. nuclear
labs. China may be tempted to test those designs if it begins to
seem as if the treaty will never be ratified.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a greater risk that a future Russian government
might feel tempted to conduct secret underground nuclear tests now
that plans for establishing the treaty's worldwide network of
monitoring stations and its provisions for on-site inspections have
been indefinitely postponed.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for Clinton will be to do his best to discourage
such dangerous developments by keeping alive some realistic hope of
eventual U.S. ratification. After 40 years of bipartisan efo
make the world safer through arms control treaties, dating back to
the Eisenhower administration, it is dismaying that a small band of
Republican opponents could abruptly upend U.S. policy.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
