<SLUG> BC-BROKER-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
146 PERCENT RISE IN EARNINGS AT BEAR STEARNS FALLS BELOW ESTIMATES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bear Stearns Cos. posted first-quarter earnings
Wednesday that fell short of expectations, a trend-breaking
disappointment that the securities firm attributed to weaker
markets for the stocks and bonds it underwrites and trades.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended Sept. 24, Bear Stearns, the sixth-largest
Wall Street securities firm, had net income of $157.on, or
$1 a diluted share, up 146 percent from $64.1 million, or 38 cents
a share, in the unusually bleak period a year earlier. Revenue rose
to $1.05 billion from $740.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the results fell well short of analysts' expectations, which
were for $1.15 a share, according to First Call/Thomson Financial,
which tracks company earnings. Bear Stearns was the only large
securities firm that did not report better-than-expected earnings
in the latest quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Investors reacted by pushing shares of Bear Stearns down $3.50,
or 8.7 percent, to $36.75.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been crushing the numbers for three quarters in a row,
but this time they came up short,'' said Chuck Hill, director of
research at First Call. ``No matter how you slice it, they missed
the number.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend among securities firms has been to post profits much
higher than those in the period a year earlier, when a global
economic crisis sent financial markets into a tailspin, but down
from a revved-up first half of 1999. Still, the magnitude of the
dropoff in some of Bear Stearns' businesses, especially its trading
operations, caught most analysts off-guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is that, relative to other firms, their declines
business by business were greater,'' said Joan Solotar, an analyst
at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, analysts pointed to the firm's 20 percent drop in
investment banking revenue, to $262.5 million from $324.9 million,
despite a big increase in gains from the sale of merchant-banking
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Solotar said Bear Stearns suffered by comparison in Europe,
where some of its competitors have raked in big fees for advising
companies on a spree of mergers and acquisitions. ``Even
domestically, you're continuing to see the tiering effect where the
top firms are separating from the rest,'' she said. ``That has to
hurt the tier-two company.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the investor unrest, Bear Stearns executives said they
were pleased by the results. ``This quarter, while it was not
spectacular, was very solid,'' said Samuel L. Molinaro, the chief
financial officer. He said revenue rose for the firm's clearing
business, which processes trades for smaller brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   That operation landed the firm in legal trouble when one of its
clearing clients, the now-defunct brokerage firm A.R. Baron &AMP; Co.,
was charged with defrauding investors in thinly traded stocks. Last
summer, Bear Stearns agreed to pay $38.5 million to settle charges
filed against it for its role in clearing Baron's fraudulent
trades.
</P>
<P>
   Molinaro said the cost of that settlement did not significantly
affect Bear Stearns' first-quarter earnings because the firm had
previously set aside money for that purpose. He said much of the 30
percent increase in ``other expenses'' for the period, to $96
million, went toward the firm's restricted-stock plan for
employees.
</P>
<P>
   That amount came on top of $516.4 million in employee
compensation and benefits, which ate up about 49 percent of the
firm's net revenue for the quarter. Bear Stearns traditionally
gives its executives some of the fattest pay packages on Wall
Street. Last week, it disclosed that it had paid $76 million to its
top five executive officers for the fiscal year 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's proxy statement also disclosed another change: Bear
Stearns is reviving the practice of using stock options to pay key
employees. Those options would grant holders the right to buy the
stock for as little as half of its market price at the time the
options are granted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
