<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-SHOOTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMBUSH LEAVES 3 LAW OFFICERS DEAD IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLEASANTON, Texas _ A man who made a phony 911 call lay in wait
with an assault rifle and killed three law enforcement officers,
including a deputy who earlier had arrested him for beating his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   Before his fury played out three hours later Tuesday night,
21-year-old Jeremiah Engleton shot two more officers and held off
75 more officers. Then he spun around in a circle, spraying gunfire
in every direction in a last attempt to hit anyone within range
before he killed himself.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators could only speculate that Engleton's anger was
connected to his arrest less than 24 hours earlier for beating his
wife, who fled their mobile home before he was released from jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he felt the police had caused his wife to
leave him or what,'' said Atascosa County Sheriff Tommy Williams.
``He had to blame somebody, and I would say he took it out on us.''
</P>
<P>
   The shooting outside this ranch town south of San Antonio was
the deadliest assault on law enforcement officers in Texas since
the Branch Davidians killed four federal agents outside Waco in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   The officers slain Tuesday were Atascosa County sheriff's
Deputies Thomas Monse Jr., 31, and Mark Stephenson, who would have
turned 32 Friday, and Texas Department of Public Safety Trooper
Terry Miller, 37.
</P>
<P>
   It was Monse who had arrested Engleton on assault charges around
1 a.m. Tuesday for beating his 35-year-old wife, Violet.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff said Engleton had also been arrested in April for
hitting her, although not as violently.
</P>
<P>
   While Engleton was locked up, a sheriff's department's family
violence officer advised his wife to leave. By the time Engleton
posted his $2,000 bond Tuesday afternoon, she and their
15-month-old daughter were gone.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Deputy David Soward said that immediately after Engleton
got out of the county jail in Jourdanton, he headed to Pleasanton,
went to a gun store and bought $200 worth of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   He called 911 shortly after 8 that evening, telling the
operator, ``need someone ... right way,'' giving his address and
hanging up.
</P>
<P>
   Monse was the first to arrive. He was shot immediately with
Engleton's SKS Chinese-made semiautomatic assault rifle, then
apparently was hit again as he got out of his car.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Stephenson drove up. The same thing
happened to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both were probably shot in the car, got out of the car,''
the sheriff said, ``and he probably shot them again.''
</P>
<P>
   And it appeared that Engleton had taken each officer's Glock
automatic pistol and shot each man in the back of the head with his
own gun, Williams said. Investigators did not know if the deputies
were still alive or conscious when those last shots were fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``These officers, as far as I'm concerned, they done everything
right,'' the sheriff said. ``There's no way to prepare for
something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes later, Trooper Miller arrived after a dispatcher
reported no contact with the two deputies. Miller radioed in,
saying, ``Two officers down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We surmise that in the next three or four seconds after he did
that, he took on fire and he tried to back out of there, back down
the road, but he was shot while he was trying to back out,'' Soward
said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's car rolled into a ditch across the road. He died with
his seat belt still fastened.
</P>
<P>
   Living nearby was U.S. Marshal Carl Fisher, who either heard the
police radio or was curious about the gunfire. The shots were so
near that his wife hid in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher arrived on the scene, and so did Pleasanton police
Officer Louis Tudyk.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff's office got a call from Fisher on his cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``911? This is Carl and Louis,'' he said. ``We're both here with
gunshots.'' On the tape of the call, gunfire is clearly heard in
the background.
</P>
<P>
   Next on the scene was Wendell Munson, owner of a local cattle
company who also lives nearby. Munson drove up in his truck and
hastily rescued Fisher and Tudyk, braving the gunfire. As he drove
away, Engleton sprayed his truck with shots, puncturing the tires.
</P>
<P>
   But Munson was able to get the two men to a waiting ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   As more officers swarmed the area, Soward said, ``we couldn't
move very much'' because of the darkness and because no one knew
exactly where the gunman was.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a San Antonio police helicopter with infrared cameras
arrived. ``It was real tense until the helicopter got him
pinpointed, and then we knew where he was and we could take
cover,'' Soward said.
</P>
<P>
   Little is known about Engleton. Residents said he moved to the
area from San Antonio less than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared to be unemployed, and authorities said he had no
criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he used the pistol of one of the officers he had
killed to shoot himself in the head. He also was shot by
approaching officers who saw he was still moving. Nearby, police
found a shotgun and three pistols in addition to the deputies' guns
and assault rifle.
</P>
<P>
   As signs and billboards expressing grief sprouted up around
Pleasanton, Jim Daughtry, an oil and gas company executive, spoke
of the tragedy and the loss of innocence in another small town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atascosa County, in the last 10 years, we've gotten a lot of
the rough stuff out of San Antonio. But we've never had nothing
like this,'' he said. ``We don't have murders here, especially law
officers.''
</P>
<P>
   In a strange postscript, the gunman's two grief-stricken
brothers from San Antonio were arrested just hours after he died.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Engleton, 25, was arrested around 2 a.m. Wednesday on a
charge of public intoxication and unlawful possession of a weapon
after a friend drove him to Pleasanton and he tried to get to his
dead brother's home.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio early Wednesday, Jonnell Engleton, 20, was
arrested after neighbors reported hearing gunshots. He was sitting
alone and distraught in a car. He was charged with unlawful
carrying of a weapon and resisting arrest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
