<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-LABOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PICKS UP LABOR ENDORSEMENT, SLAMS RECORD OF BUSH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore, claiming his long-sought
endorsement by the AFL-CIO, on Wednesday slammed the labor record
of Texas Gov. George W. Bush and stiffened a pledge to veto
anti-union legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake, there is a battle,'' Gore told cheering
delegates at the labor confederation's convention. ``I stand with
you. I will fight with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore faulted Bush's support of a proposal to require specific
authorization from workers before their union dues can be used in
political campaigns and the governor's call to allow states to opt
out of future increases in the federal minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore addressed AFL-CIO convention delegates shortly after they
shouted approval of a resolution endorsing his quest for the
Democratic presidential nomination and brushed aside Teamsters'
calls to delay a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work of labor is to lead and not to follow,'' an exuberant
Gore declared. He entered the Los Angeles Convention Center to
pulsating salsa music, grasping outstretched hands and giving some
delegates high-fives.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke in a vast exhibition hall across the street from the
new arena where the Democratic National Convention next August will
select the party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been focusing recently on the increasingly potent
nomination challenge from former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
But because of Bradley's strong labor record, Gore trained his
rhetorical guns on Bush, even mentioning the Republican
front-runner by name, which he usually avoids.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current Republican front-runner believes we should pass
what's called `paycheck deception' tobust up unions and silence
working families,'' Gore said of the dues-authorization proposal,
which advocates refer to as a ``payroll protection'' measure. Gore,
along with most leading Democrats, opposes the idea, which has made
its way to the ballot in several states only to be defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Bush ``also believes there should be a lower minimum
wage for millions of struggling workers,'' a reference to the
Republican proposal for a so-called training wage for young people
entering the work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now he says let's refuse to raise the minimum wage unless
individual states can opt out of the minimum-wage increase,'' Gore
said. ``I guess that's Governor Bush's idea of 'compassionate
conservatism.' States get to choose one or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm for a minimum wage increase in every state including the
state of Texas, because people can't get by on what it is today,''
Gore said. ``It ought to be raised $1 an hour and be phased in over
the next couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said ``it is compassionate to
protect the paychecks of union members'' so they are not forced to
contribute to political campaigns or parties through dues
checkoffs. Tucker also said ``it's compassionate to make sure we
protect jobs by allowing states where jobs would be eliminated by
raising the minimum wage to opt out.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's rhetorical assertiveness masked the fact that he
solicited the union endorsement as a lifeline for his sluggish
campaign. Labor's official move into Gore's camp comes as polling
indicates Bradley is gaining on Gore nationally. The former senator
already leads Gore in several large or early-voting states, such as
New Hampshire, traditionally the site of the first primary, and New
York, which with California is among a mass of states scheduled to
hold primaries March 7. The latest CNN-USA Today national survey by
the Gallup Organization showed Gore leading Bradley 51 percent to
39 percent, down from 63 percent to 30 percent in mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   Both polls showed Bradley and Gore trailing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Brown, a vice president of the International
Longshoremen's Association, urged delegates to back Gore so that
Bush ``not be given aid and comfort by our failure to act.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had urged the AFL-CIO, with 13 million members in its
dozens of unions, to withhold an endorsement until the campaign
takes firmer shape.
</P>
<P>
   Similar caution had been advocated by the Teamsters and United
Auto Workers, two major AFL-CIO component unions. Teamsters leaders
spoke against the endorsement and voiced scattered 'nays' in an
anti-climactic voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   FL-CIO President John J. Sweeney said the quickly
approaching primary season _ the first caucus will be in Iowa in
January _ dictated action.
</P>
<P>
   The union move cuts off one more avenue for Bradley to the heart
of the Democratic Party, but he issued a statement thanking Sweeney
and union members who supported him and added: ``My commitment to
working men and women and the role that labor can play in their
lives is unwavering.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign's high command declared the labor vote was
``the first primary,'' a phrase used by campaign chairman Tony
Coelho and campaign manager Donna Brazile. Union representatives
have made up about one quarter of the delegates to recent
Democratic National Conventions and claim about the same proportion
of specially appointed ``super delegates.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore fought for the endorsement because it is considered yet one
more testimonial that the candidate favored by the Democrat
establishment needs to have. It can also be an organizational plus
because of the unions' contact with its members.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
