<HEADLINE>
WARNING ABOUT HOT DOGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Pa., N.C., Ga., Fla.) (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal and state health officials told grocers
Wednesday to remove from their shelves Sabrett hot dogs that carry
an Oct. 22 sell-by date, because two packages from a Saratoga
Springs, N.Y., market were contaminated with listeria bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Listeria usually causes mild flu-like symptoms in healthy
people, but can be serious or even fatal in children, the elderly,
pregnant women and people with depressed immune systems, said Pete
Gregg, a spokesman for the State Department of Agriculture and
Markets.
</P>
<P>
   The warning refers only to 1-pound packages of Sabrett's
Skinless Beef Frankfurters, Gregg said. The hot dogs were
distributed to stores in New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, North
Carolina, George and Florida, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
