A6324 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-SERENA-WILLIAMS-N     10-13 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-SERENA-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS RETURNS, WITHOUT A RACKET
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A buoyant Serena Williams ventured back to New York
Wednesday for the first time since she captured her first Grand
Slam title, and became the first black woman since Althea Gibson to
win a major title, at the U.S. Open last month.
</P>
<P>
   In a generous mood, Williams praised Gibson, as well as her
older sister Venus for paving her way toward tennis posterity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like Althea gave me this opportunity,'' said Williams,
who has interviewed the reclusive Gibson, by fax, for the monthly
newsletter she and her sister publish from their home in Palm Beach
Gardens, Fla. ``I hope I can inspire other young kids to get into
tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said she felt blessed to have her sister for a
trailblazer, but insisted that she felt no additional pressure to
become an African-American role model after her Grand Slam victory.
She also expressed no regrets about dedicating her childhood to
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the opportunity of a lifetime,'' she said. ``People
would give their left arm to have this opportunity. And I'm going
to take my opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what Williams did at the Open, said Brandi
Williams, her mother, coach and chaperone. Unlike Venus, who lost
in the 1997 Open final, Serena maintained a carpe diem attitude
through all seven rounds this year. Within the family, Brandi
Williams said, there are no hard feelings that Serena, the younger
sister, collected a Grand Slam title before Venus. ``If anything,
Serena is setting a good example for Venus now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Serena Williams came to New York, she was a player
in search of her first major championship. This time she came as a
full-fledged celebrity, right down to the lap dog she cuddled like
a furry life preserver.
</P>
<P>
   One of the perks of making your first million before turning 18,
said Williams _ whose two latest singles titles were worth $1.5
million _ is being able to support your own dog. But she no longer
plans to become a veterinarian after her retirement from tennis;
she has enrolled at a Florida art institute to pursue a degree in
fashion design between tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, clad in black leather and traveling in a black
limousine, passed a tennis-free day in Manhattan Wednesday that
included a motivational visit to Public School 129 in Harlem,
appearances on talk shows with Barbara Walters and Conan O'Brien
and a shopping spree at Saks Fifth Avenue, where she rated the VIP
fitting room.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said her next goal in tennis, the No. 1 ranking, could
wait until next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can be the best player out there if I work hard, but
I'm definitely ready for a wind-down,'' said Williams, who just
turned 18. Her next and last 1999 event is the invitational Chase
Championships at Madison Square Garden, beginning Nov. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Williams followed her breakthrough at the Open
with one on a more personal front _ she defeated Venus for the
first time, dethroning her sister as champion of the Grand Slam Cup
in Munich, Germany. The victory ended a three-match losing streak,
and although Serena did not pretend to be sorry it happened, she
did memorize her sister's reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came over to my side of the net and she said, `Sometimes
little sisters can be very mean,''' said Williams, whose older
sister is competing alone in Zurich this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
