<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-AGENDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGER ON AGENDA FOR WTO SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA, Switzerland _ A dispute over the agenda that appears to
pit developing nations against the United States has injected a
tense atmosphere into preparations for the World Trade
Organization's summit next month.
</P>
<P>
   Non-industrialized countries in the 134-member group that makes
the rules for global commerce had drafted a detailed list of
priorities for the Seattle meeting agenda, determined to rectify
what they see as bias in current trade rules that have benefited
larger economic powers at their expense.
</P>
<P>
   But their two-page list was mysteriously deleted from the first
formal draft of the agenda that circulated at the organization's
Geneva headquarters earlier this week. Representatives of
developing nations expressed outrage, particularly because the
coming summit has been publicly extolled by the group's new
director general, Mike Moore, as a forum meant for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was totally, totally unfair. It shocks us, frankly,'' said
India's trade envoy to Geneva, Srinivasan Narayanan.
</P>
<P>
   While no names were publicly mentioned, the United States was
blamed and accused of bullying tactics. ``It was too convenient.
Every single item developing countries wanted was eliminated,''
said one aggrieved trade envoy.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. representatives to the trade group declined to comment on
these accusations Wednesday, saying only that the agenda remains
subject to negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   But a subsequent version of the agenda draft restored much of
what developing nations had proposed earlier. Whether all or even
some of those issues survive the final draft remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are a proposal to weaken anti-dumping measures, an
important U.S. trade tool used to protect U.S. manufacturers from
low-priced imports. Developing countries want a one-year waiting
period between inquiries into a product that has flooded the
market. The United States would likely reject such a change.
</P>
<P>
   Another agenda item sought by developing countries would
reintroduce subsidies to protect domestic manufacturers, made
illegal in previous trade agreements. Countries such as India argue
that subsidies are necessary to protect their native businesses
from foreign competition.
</P>
<P>
   Modifying rules for the textile trade is also on the developing
countries' list. They want to shorten the 10-year schedule for
lifting restrictions on imports. The Americans want to keep the
schedule unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Developing nations also want the agenda to include proposed
changes that would delay enforcement of intellectual property
rights, postpone a tightening of trade-related investment rules and
force pharmaceutical companies to sell essential drugs at
affordable prices.
</P>
<P>
   In recent congressional testimony, the U.S. Trade
Representative, Charlene Barshefsky, gave little support for such a
wish list, saying implementation of existing agreements is
necessary to the credibility of future negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   But comments by a top Commerce Department official this week
indicate that the United States may offer some room to compromise,
partly because it wants the trade summit to include negotiations on
raising labor standards among all member nations. This is an
important issue to American and European unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we could get a trade deal though Congress
without some kind of concessions,'' said Deputy Commerce Secretary
Robert Mallett. He indicated that U.S. negotiators may have to put
``some incentives on the table ... perhaps a more protracted
timetable for the implementation of some issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0500 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6332 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-RUDY-WILT-HNS &LR;      10-13 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RUDY-WILT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SEATTLE _ Rudy Tomjanovich had one hero, one favorite player who
stood as far above all other choices as he did opponents.
Tomjanovich tied paper around his knees to mimic Wilt Chamberlain's
kneepads. He finger-rolled trash into the garbage.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And when Tomjanovich reached the NBA, he played as if to show
his hero that he belonged on the same court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a dream playing against the guy,'' Tomjanovich
said.
</P>
<P>
   But there was one part of the fantasy Tomjanovich had never
concocted back in Hamtramck, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hated me,'' Tomjanovich recalled Wednesday, a day after
Chamberlain died in Bel-Air, Calif. ``I was this young guy going
after rebounds, sometimes on shots that would go in. I'd end up on
his back, and he got pretty irritated. He tried to intimidate me
when I'd come into games.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain never got over his feelings about Tomjanovich. But
Tomjanovich had an accomplice in getting under Chamberlain's skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing down at the Dome,'' said Calvin Murphy,
Tomjanovich's teammate then and eventually a friend of Chamberlain.
``Rudy dunked on Wilt, and I'm talking a hellacious tomahawk. I
started talking . I said, `Damn, Wilt, he just busted you.' Wilt
came into our huddle and said, `From now on, nobody gets nothing.'
</P>
<P>
   ``From that point on, Wilt wanted to fight Rudy. Out in LA, Rudy
was on the foul line. I was on the bench, and Wilt was talking .
And I'm talking back. I'm on the bench anyway, (saying) `Rudy, I've
got your back.'''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, when traveling with Chamberlain, Murphy said he
asked Chamberlain why he maintained his obvious distaste for
Tomjanovich during the three seasons both were in the league.
Chamberlain told Murphy then that he never got over the dunk.
</P>
<P>
   But at least Tomjanovich's hero never forgot him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would always attack the boards and wind up on his back,''
Tomjanovich said. ``It used to aggravate the hell out of him. He
was being dubbed the strongest basketball player in the league. He
had really bulked up by then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Why the hell do I have to have him be my hero, No. 1,
and the strongest guy in the league mad at me, No. 2?' He used to
tell me, `Get your butt out of here.' But I told him, `Look, I've
got to do my job.' But he came after me a couple of times.
</P>
<P>
   ``You start realizing sometimes your expectations aren't what
you wanted. Calvin used to always rip me about that. When we were
going to play the Lakers, he'd tell me I was going to aggravate the
guy. He'd be under the basket, and I'd come in looking for
offensive rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   When Tomjanovich finally got his chance to see his hero up
close, Chamberlain did not disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I got in the league, he used a fadeaway bank shot in
the left corner that was unstoppable,'' Tomjanovich said. ``He was
the most dominating force there was. He was still a really, really
good force if he played today. The 100 points probably would never
have happened. They didn't do all the double-down stuff, the
rotations then. But he was very athletic before he bulked himself
up. He could pass, rebound, block shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a guy that really could do just about anything. When he
set up his mind to score, he was going to score; to rebound, he
would rebound. His stats will never be broken.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0501 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6333 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE     10-13 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW RISK FOR CAMPAIGN LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Oct. 14:
</P>
<P>
   An important but little-noticed boost was given to campaign
finance reform in the Senate this week. Sam Brownback of Kansas
became the eighth Republican to break with his party's leadership
and support the McCain-Feingold soft-money ban, scheduled for
debate Thursday. There are now 53 votes to choke off a
Republican-led filibuster and pass the bill, only seven votes short
of what is needed. The pressure is mounting on other Republicans to
support reform. But amid these favorable developments, a move by
Robert Torricelli and some other Democratic supporters of reform
could undercut the cause.
</P>
<P>
   The risk is posed by a Democratic attempt to block Sens. John
McCain and Russell Feingold from advancing a stripped-down 
of their reform legislation. The new McCain-Feingold bill would
omit a section preventing independent groups from raising unlimited
money for sham campaign ads two months before an election. Some
Republicans say that because that section threatens free speech,
they cannot go along with the central objective of reform, which is
to ban unlimited donations to campaigns waged by political parties.
Shrinking the bill to a simple soft-money ban for parties has paid
off. Brownback is on board and other Senate Republicans may follow.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli and the Democratic Senate leader, Tom Daschle, are
nonetheless determined to scrap the new McCain-Feingold bill and
substitute the original bill, with the limits on independent
groups. This is a serious tactical mistake that raises questions
about the Democrats' commitment to campaign finance reform. They
ought to know that the bill they are pushing does not have the
votes to break a filibuster, whereas the revised McCain-Feingold
bill has a chance of getting them.
</P>
<P>
   It would be especially grievous if their move played into the
destructive tactics of Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky and other
Republican foes of reform. McConnell might even try to deliver
enough votes for the Democratic move, allowing it to pass because
in the end the bill in that form will surely die.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats, noting that the House passed its broader
Shays-Meehan reform bill last month, warn that a narrower bill in
the Senate will not survive either. But Brownback's courageous move
makes it worth a try.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate development, Rep. Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas, an
influential Republican in the House, also announced his backing of
the stripped-down version. His brother, Sen. Tim Hutchinson of
Arkansas, could follow suit. Sens. Pete Fitzgerald of Pennsylvania,
William Roth of Delaware, Chuck Hagel of Nebraska and George
Voinovich and Mike DeWine of Ohio are known to be looking at this
new version of reform. They need to liberate themselves from
McConnell and from the ring of their party's cash machines. If they
do, a campaign cleanup can actually happen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
