u k BC-EDIT-TOBACCO-NYT &LR;      10-13 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE TRUTH ABOUT TOBACCO
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Oct. 14:
</P>
<P>
   After denying the truth for decades, Philip Morris now admits
that cigarettes cause cancer and other fatal diseases and are
addictive. In what appears to be a calculated turnabout, the
tobacco company says on its new Internet Web site that ``there is
overwhelming medical and scientific consensus that cigarette
smoking causes cancer, heart disease, emphysema and other serious
diseases.'' It also now admits that ``cigarette smoking is
addictive, as that term is most commonly used today.''
</P>
<P>
   These admissions might have helped save American lives had they
been made 30 years ago when the tobacco industry's own researchers
found cigarettes to be addictive dispensers of nicotine. But as
late as 1994, top executives of the seven largest American tobacco
companies, including Philip Morris' president, testified in
Congress that they did not believe tobacco was addictive.
</P>
<P>
   Denial no longer works with the public or with government
officials who have been forced to deal with smoking-related health
costs. The $246 billion settlements in state lawsuits for Medicaid
expenses against the industry, and greater willingness by juries to
award large damages to addicted smokers, are forcing the industry
to modify its tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris' new stance is an effort, according to a company
spokesman, to begin a new public dialogue about tobacco. It may
also be a savvy way to limit liability in future lawsuits by
allowing the company to assert that it has given smokers full
warning. For the more than 35 million smokers who are addicted, the
company's new position will not make ending their addiction easier.
</P>
<P>
   But truth-telling should have consequences. In admitting that
its business is sustained by addiction, Philip Morris should now
voluntarily agree to regulation of its product by the Food and Drug
Administration. In 1996 the FDA asserted power to regulate nicotine
and tobacco as a drug and a device ``intended to affect the
structure or any function of the body.'' The tobacco industry
promptly challenged that authority, arguing that the FDA lacked
jurisdiction to impose new restrictions on the sale of cigarettes
to teenagers and new limits on tobacco marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court will take up the question of the FDAs
authority this term. The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled
last year that the FDA had no right to regulate tobacco. If upheld,
that odd decision would make tobacco the only addictive drug that
is not subject to government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   More than 400,000 Americans die annually from smoking-related
diseases, and the average smoker cuts his life short by 15 years.
Tobacco kills more people than alcohol, homicides, suicides, car
accidents, illegal drugs, AIDS and fires combined. For years,
industry leaders told the public that they would not knowingly sell
a dangerous product. Philip Morris, for one, is no longer hiding
behind that cover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 2322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
