<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REGENTS-EXAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEARLY 80 PERCENT HAVE PASSED STATEWIDE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In the first high school class that is required
to pass the Regents English exam to graduate, nearly four in five
students have so far succeeded, state education officials announced
Wednesday. They hailed the results as evidence that raising
standards has raised performance. But the data were open to other
interpretations as well, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, 55 percent of the class has passed thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers, for students who entered high school three years
ago and took the test in January or June, are expected to rise as
students who failed the test or have not yet taken it are able to
try next year.
</P>
<P>
   But there are ominous ambiguities buried in the numbers released
Wednesday. During a four-year transition period, the Board of
Regents has lowered the minimum passing grade for the exams from 65
percent, to 55. For those who begin ninth grade next year, the
class of 2004, the standard will rise to 65 again.
</P>
<P>
   What concerns some educators is that of the students who entered
high school three years ago, only 66 percent statewide have scored
65 or better, and just 40 percent of those in New York City have
done so.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, only an elite group of students have taken the
Regents exams, while most students have taken less stringent
competency exams to graduate. But beginnh those who entered
ninth grade in September 1996, all students must pass the Regents
exam in English to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   The city's schools chancellor, Rudy Crew, said he was encouraged
by the results. ``I am pleased to report that our students showed
steady improvement this year, which confirms my belief that with
the proper support from the system, all students can achieve at
higher levels,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
