<HEADER>
A6340 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-SCHOOL-FUNDING-NYT     10-13 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SCHOOL-FUNDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES FAULT PACE OF EFFORT FOR PRESCHOOL IN NEW JERSEY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MARIA NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ State Supreme Court justices criticized state
Education Department officials Wednesday over their slow pace in
putting into effect a court order to provide preschool for 3- and
4-year-olds in the state's 30 poorest districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court believed the preschool program would be the
foundation for reform of the entire school system for these
districts,'' said Justice Gary S. Stein, noting that fewer than
half of the 49,000 eligible children in those districts had access
to preschool so far. ``The result has been chaotic. My question is,
how did this happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen months after the court ordered broad changes in
financing and programming to help the districts overcome the
disadvantages of poverty, the case was back in court Wednesday,
with the plaintiff, the Education Law Center of Newark, contending
that the preschool program provided by the state so far fell far
short of what the court intended.
</P>
<P>
   David Sciarra, the Law Center lawyer who is representing the
students in the districts, has said the Education Department and
Gov. Christie Whitman are engaging in ``consumer fraud'' and ``bait
and switch'' by providing a preschool program that does not have
properly trained teachers.
</P>
<P>
   He said Wednesday that to keep its costs down, the state had not
made the program available to all children who would be eligible.
He also said the state has tried to impose programs on districts _
and financing levels _ without taking into account their own
opinion on how best to serve their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be that the districts at the ground level get to
make these decisions, at least initially,'' Sciarra told the court
Friday . The Law Center is asking the court to appoint a judge to
oversee the making of the changes outlined in the court's decision
on Abbott vs. Burke, the nation's longest-running court battle to
improve the quality of education for urban schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The state justices, who will not announce a decision on the
matter for some time, appeared to agree with the Law Center, at
least on some points.
</P>
<P>
   Stein pointed out that in September 1998, the state gave the
districts _ from large systems like Newark's to small ones like
Phillipsburg's _ one month to come up with their own plans for a
preschool program, and that it had received many creative plans.
</P>
<P>
   But in February, the Education Department sent letters to all of
the districts rejecting those plans, saying in large part that the
districts had not explored the possibility of working with existing
day care centers to provide such programs, something the court
order allows.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection letters arrived less than a month before the
districts had to make their budget requests to the state on how
much money they would need for their programs, Stein said, not long
enough for them to come up with another plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the classic Catch-22,'' Stein said. ``The effect of
that process has been so disillusioning to many of the
superintendents.''
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general, John J. Farmer Jr., who represented
the Education Department in the hearings, acknowledged that there
had been several problems in the first year. But he attributed most
of it to the difficulties of trying to start such a huge program in
such a short time _ from May 1998 to September 1999 _ a task that
has involved coming up with new standards for the preschool
programs, training new teachers, recruiting students who were not
yet in the school system and finding space for the additional
students in districts that were often already overcrowded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state has acted in good faith to implement preschool in
the Abbott districts,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
