u a BC-NY-GUN-CONTROL-NYT &LR;      10-13 0290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GUN-CONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL REQUIRING TRIGGER LOCKS ON ALL HANDGUNS IS PASSED BY CITY
COUNCIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The City Council voted Wednesday to approve
legislation requiring all gun owners to use safety devices designed
to prevent accidental shootings by locking a weapon's trigger.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which passed unanimously at a meeting of the full
Council Wednesday, was sponsored by Councilman Sheldon Leffler of
Queens and is supported by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The new law would broaden existing legislation that requires
that safety devices be installed on all pistols that are sold or
otherwise change hands in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new legislation, the devices would be required for all
weapons, and gun owners would be required to lock the triggers of
all firearms whenever they are not in use. The locks can cost as
little as $2 to $3, and are available from licensed gun dealers,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A commission appointed by Giuliani to change the City Charter
has put forth a proposal that is virtually identical to the Council
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Leffler said the law would make the Charter change unnecessary.
``We have the legislative authority to do just what the Charter
proposal wants,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the mayor said he had urged Leffler to introduce the
legislation and would most likely sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Leffler, the chairman of the Council's Public Safety Committee,
said the new law would provide ``additional protection from
accidental discharges.'' He said the law was aimed primarily at
protecting children but might save adults lives, too. ``Others, as
well, can sometimes set off a gun accidentally,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991013.0507 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-13 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6344 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AUSTRALIA-BALLET-REVI     10-13 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRALIA-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SPIRIT OF THE ANCIENTS AND A CLASSICAL PURITY IN THE AUSTRALIAN
BALLET  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Australian Ballet may usually be down under, but
it was absolutely tops on Tuesday night when it opened a weeklong
season at City Center with a brash and contemporary triple bill
brimming with energy and fresh ideas.
</P>
<P>
   With sexy men and good-humored women, all ablaze in the
perfection of classical style introduced by their current artistic
director, Ross Stretton, it was a very different Australian Ballet
from the past.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. premiere of ``Rites,'' a company collaboration with
Bangarra Dance Theater, a modern-dance troupe that focuses on the
heritage of Australia's Aborigines, added to the distinctly
Australian flavor of this first of three different programs.
</P>
<P>
   Discarding the scenario of Stravinsky's all-too-familiar ballet
score for ``The Rite of Spring,'' Stephen Page's choreography
nonetheless has something of the pantheistic inspiration of the
original. It also offers a singular Australian perspective:
``Rites'' is a story of Creation, referring directly to spirits
that in Aboriginal beliefs have inhabited the landscape of
Australia since the beginning of time.
</P>
<P>
   Centered on the charismatic Djakapurra Munyarryun, who dances in
the work with the Australian Ballet and fellow members of Bangarra,
``Rites'' is a fascinating and successful experiment. But it does
not mean that the Australian Ballet must seek Australian subject
matter to define itself.
</P>
<P>
   It there is to be an Australian style in ballet, it is most
likbe found in works by Stanton Welch, including his
``Divergence,'' which received a rousing reception after it opened
the program in a packed house filled with, among others, many
members of American Ballet Theater. Stretton, an Australian who
returned to Melbourne to succeed Maina Gielgud as artistic director
in 1997, was a Ballet Theater star for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gielgud fostered the development of Welch and Stephen Baynes
as young choreographers in the company. ``Divergence'' was seen in
1994 when the Australian Ballet appeared at the John F. Kennedy
Center for the Performing Arts in Washington, and it was clear then
that the company was reaching a new level of technique.
</P>
<P>
   Stretton has now given it a greater classical purity, especially
impressive in the perfect body placement that recalls his own noble
style as a dancer. Yet this is not an old-fashioned style, and it
is used with a contemporary attack that literally stretches the
dancers' silhouettes withou losing form.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Divergence'' and in William Forsythe's ``In the Middle,
Somewhat Elevated,'' the two neo-classical pieces on the program,
the company has a sleekness, clarity and modern spirit that is a
far cry from how it looked on its first U.S. tour in 1970-71 with
Rudolf Nureyev, and even on its last visit to New York in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that Stretton has not included any 19th-century
classics, and one has to pay tribute to the company's early stars,
who excelled in those works: among them, Marilyn Jones and Garth
Welch, the parents of Stanton and Damien Welch, a principal in
``Divergence'' whose bravura comes with heartthrob appeal.
</P>
<P>
   If the original style in the company owed much to the British
view of classical ballet, Stretton and his new artistic staff
(Danilo Radojevic and Wendy Walker from Ballet Theater and Noelle
Shader, formerly of New York City Ballet) have streamlined the
dancers' classical silhouette and cleaned up the details in
technique.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Forsythe's way with classical technique (daring
images of acceleration and off-balance arabesques with something
always askew) looks perfectly at home in the Australian company.
``In the Middle, Somewhat Elevated,'' was seen here originally with
Sylvie Guillem, Isabel Guerin and other stars of the Paris Opera
Ballet, for which it was created.
</P>
<P>
   The larger-than-life dimension of the French cast is missing
here but the Australians, just plain excellent dancers, go at
Forsythe's sashaying and convoluted encounters in a bare-bones
setting with apt vim and vigor.
</P>
<P>
   Welch has a similar interest in subverting neo-classical
choreography, and his approach is more playful and sardonic. Now
bereft of the set it had in 1994, the piece is clearer on its
various levels, commenting on life in ballet and life in general.
</P>
<P>
   The women in pleated flat tutus throw these tutus into the wings
in the end, liberated to pursue most of the activities they have
been pursuing anyway until then to incidental music from Bizet's
``Arlesienne.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some images of women entering crablike in deep plies
and going through some programmed sex. There is plenty of kissing
amid the conventional ballet steps used unconventionally.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all is the astounding duet in which Damien Welch keeps
wrapping the s Justine Summers around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Rites'' Munyarryun dominates the stage, his large frame not
at odds with the spring in his t as he presides over the
joining of earth, water, fire and wind.
</P>
<P>
   Page's choreography is not always at one with Stravinsky's
music. But more important, he succeeds in suggesting the essence of
these elements through the ensemble. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-99 2327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
