<HEADER>
A6357 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      10-13 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAPPLING WITH DEATH OF A LEGEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
(UNDATED) - One of the all-time greats, a sports legend in his 60s,
died quietly in his home recently. He deserved in death all the
testimonials he'd earned in life, but I had no plans to produce
one.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least, not until Wilt Chamberlain, also in his 60s, died
quietly in his home, and every keyboard puncher in the West ern
Hemisphere filed a teary-eyed tribute.
</P>
<P>
   In our house, Wilt the Stilt wasn't nearly as big as Gorilla
Monsoon.
</P>
<P>
   Just over a week ago, the Associated Press reported that Robert
``Gorilla Mon soon'' Marella, died at age 62. The news came. The
news went. A paragraph bur ied in the sports section, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain made front pages every where.
</P>
<P>
   Almost always, when reporters mourn the passing of a great
athlete, they're only rewriting a eulogy to their own youth.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, when I was a boy, we didn't know a Celtic
from a Laker from a Warrior. Basketball was hardly ever on
television. I don't remember see ing a game.
</P>
<P>
   But every week, my friends, my neigh bors, my parents, my
grandparents gath ered around to watch a show called Studio
Wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   It was produced at a television station in downtown Pittsburgh
and featured a ring, an announcer, a few rows of folding chairs
(always with a heavyset woman called Ringside Rosie sitting closest
to the ropes), a camera and, on its best days, the great Bruno
Sammartino.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno immigrated to western Pennsyl vania from the Abruzzi
region of Italy, where my mother's people lived. At the time, he
was the World Wrestling Federa tion champion. &QL; 
A MODEL `VILLAIN'
</P>
<P>
   Because he was a good Pittsburgh boy, he appeared often on
Studio Wrestling. And because the show's producers wanted to
capitalize on Bruno's hometown appeal while keeping the show fresh,
they'd bring in a series of ``evil'' opponents for him to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   There was 600-pound Haystacks Cal houn. And George ``The
Animal'' Steele. And Killer Kowalski. And Dick the Bruiser. And The
Crusher.
</P>
<P>
   And Gorilla Monsoon, who, in an exhi bition, once body-slammed
Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the ring, Robert ``Gorilla Monsoon'' Marella had a wife
and four children and, like Sammartino, was a friendly fellow who
spent most of his time with his family.
</P>
<P>
   You couldn't tell that from Studio Wrestling, though, which
played out like an old-fashioned Western staged in tight trunks.
</P>
<P>
   During the wrestling re-enactments performed in the bedroom I
shared with my older brother, I always played the bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   Gorilla Montini.
</P>
<P>
   This was not by choice. My brother's name is Sam, and, through
size and brute force, he claimed the champion's identity of Bruno
Sam Montini, eventually caus ing his smaller, weaker, but
surprisingly nefarious opponent to cry for his mommy. &QL; 
HERO OUT OF RING
</P>
<P>
   The real Gorilla Monsoon never did such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   This was before pay-per-view, steroids and face paint.
</P>
<P>
   Before heroes went out of fashion.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring from the ring, Gorilla Monsoon became a
commentator for wrestling matches, where he worked with the future
governor of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Ventura issued a statement last week saying, ``The loss of
Gorilla Mon soon saddens me deeply. He was both a friend and a
colleague.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Marella's sons, Joey, died in an auto accident in 1994,
and the Gorilla character seldom appeared on television after that.
He is survived by his wife, Maureen, another son and two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Wilt Chamberlain's sport is considered to be more legitimate
than Robert Marel la's, his accomplishments more profound.
Chamberlain claimed in his autobiogra phy to have slept with 20,000
women.
</P>
<P>
   These days, off-the-court accomplish ments like that will earn
you more more front-page eulogies than anything in the life of
Gorilla Monsoon, a loving father who, neighbors said, prided
himself on his lasagna. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
